1. d4 {Welcome to my course on the Queen's Gambit Declined: Tartakover! This is my third course for Chessable. The first was another Lifetime Repertoire, on the Symmetrical English for Black. The second was a much smaller course on the fascinating Dzindzi-Indian. Creating a course on a defense against 1.d4 (along with 1.Nf3 and 1.c4) was a bigger undertaking than I expected. It seems I never learn, as I have written several books, and they also ended up bigger than expected. So why the Queen's Gambit Declined? Isn't it 'boring'? Well, I used to think so. For a long time, the King's Indian was my only defense to 1.d4. It's very interesting and fun to play, but of course it entails certain strategic risks. I also liked that it was pretty 'move order proof' against anything other than 1.e4. At some point I decided I needed to be able to play something a bit more solid on occasion, and I incorporated the Slav and Semi-Slav into my repertoire. In fact I have written books on all three of these openings! I have spent a good thirty years or so playing the closed openings with White. Of course I faced the Queen's Gambit Declined ('QGD') many times, and it has always been a tough nut to crack. This is not surprising, as it must be a totally correct opening. Let's take a look...} ({I will also cover various Reti/English lines with} 1. Nf3) ({(} 1. c4 e6 {will soon transpose somewhere.)}) 1... d5 2. c4 {(White can also forsake this move with 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 e6 4.O-O Be7 5.d3 aiming for e2-e4 - the King's Indian Attack.)} e6 3. g3 {(Here 3.e3 is not so harmless, and it became more popular when GM Axel Smith released the book 'e3 Poison'.)} Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 {O-O O-O and now} 5. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. Quite dangerous for the unprepared!} ({One reason I shifted from the Slav to the QGD is that the 'Anti-Slavs' with} 5. Nf3 {d5} dxc4 {c6 g3 Nf6 Bg2 always annoyed me. If Black grabs on c4 with dxc4 White always seemed to get interesting play. I have played this lines with White many times. While bringing out the bishop with 4...Bf5 or 4...Bg4 always seems to lead to some harassment of this piece, and often White's Qb1-b3, hitting the b7-pawn, was a serious annoyance. In the QGD we just play ...Be7 and castle, so we rarely face an early crisis.}) {d5} 5... dxc4 {[%mdl 32768] Of course we cover all the fun stuff like: e6 Fundamentally, the difference between the Slav and the QGD is this: in the Slav, Black wants to keep the option open to bring the c8-bishop out, while in the QGD it gets locked in right away. It makes the Slav sound better, right? Well, we see that it's not always so easy to actually bring the bishop out without some price, and often we get dragged back into the complications we sought to avoid with 1...d5. In the QGD we say, ok, I am going to get castled, and then I can deal with the problem bishop on c8. It's not as passive as it may seem - after all, Black is developing very quickly with ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...O-O. Because of this, Black can often strike in the center quickly with ...c5. In the Slav, this is more difficult, because if we prioritize this c-bishop, it will take several more tempi to get castled. Also, the c-pawn has already moved to c6, so pushing it again will cost another tempo.} ({* The London Bf4 * The Veresov Nc3 Nf6 Bg5 * The Jobava Nc3 Nf6 Bf4 * The Torre Nf3 Nf6 Bg5 * The Colle Nf3 Nf6 e3 * The Pseudo-Trompowsky Bg5 * And the Blackmar-Diemer e4 . Ok, now I have some explaining to do. Yes, I have both played and written about the Slav extensively. So why the switch? After} 5... c6 {I started to get annoyed with just about everything.} 6. Nf3 {Of course everyone worries about 3.cxd5 cxd5 as the Exchange Slav has a drawish reputation. I was actually quite happy with the symmetrical lines arising after 4.Bf4 Nc6 5.e3 Nf6 6.Nc3 Bf5 7.Nf3 e6 in my 'Play the Semi-Slav', I tried to show that Black often gets good counterplay here. I am less enthused with Black's position after 7.Qb3 Na5 8.Qa4+ Bd7 9.Qc2 however. I first learned of this line when I lost a few blitz games on the Internet Chess Club to some GM. I think this was back in the late 1990's. I started playing it with White with good success. Then Kramnik and others joined the party. Now it's quite well known, but I still find it to be a bit annoying... There is also the move order 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e3 which I have also employed with White. Now I believe that 4...e6 is the best move, but the Meran complex is quite a lot to learn, especially if you want to play the Classical Slav. 3...Nf6 4.Nc3 Main line. 4.e3 the 'Slow Slav' is another potential issue. I thought I would like these positions, but I have actually done poorly - with both colors! Again if we bring out the c8-bishop, it will get pestered by the white pieces. 4...dxc4 The Classical Slav. I've played this many times with both colors. 5.a4 Bf5 Now I was happy enough with the 6.e3 e6 7.Bxc4 Bb4 lines. But if White went for 6.Ne5 everything become very sharp again, and I was never totally happy with any of Black's lines here. The peculiar 6...e6 7.f3 Bb4 8.Nxc4 O-O 9.Kf2! was especially difficult (White scores over 70%!), and I never found anything I liked here. I often played the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 After 5.Bg5 I went for the Botvinnik with 5...dxc4 6.e4 b5 Very sharp and fun, but I thought I was trying to play solidly! Another big issue is that today's engines have worked out the lines so deeply. I found that I had to remember everything, but it wasn't worth it as I didn't get to play these lines much. If someone did go for the sharp stuff, then usually knew it quite well. Even though Black is doing fine theoretically, it seemed like I was trying to remember an awful lot to just make a draw at the end of some long computer variations. The Anti-Moscow lines with 5...h6 6.Bh4 dxc4 7.e4 g5 8.Bg3 b5 did not seem like much of an alternative.}) 6. Nc3 ({A principled move. Really} 6. Nf3 {is just as good. It depends what White wants to do. Often with this move order White signals his desire to play the Catalan with Nf6 g3 This is very popular. Black has many ways to play here, but we will go with the very classical Be7 Bg2} O-O 7. O-O {dxc4 as favored by Karpov and Anand. There is a lot to know here, but it's actually fun to play I think. Again, Black is developing very quickly.}) ({Be7 This is the 'Alatortsev' move order, which was favored by both Karpov and Kasparov. The idea is to avoid the Exchange Variation with Nf6 cxd5 exd5} 6. Bg5 {This is hugely popular, as it's always been considered both objectively strong and straightforward to play. In recent years it's been shorn of some terrors, and I do not think it is so easy for White to play. Black has all kinds of systems here. The main ones for a long time were} c6 7. e3 {Be7 Bd3} Nbd7 {when Black could either castle or play ...Nh5 next. Nowadays there are all kinds of little systems. Sometimes Black plays the formerly forbidden ...h6 at an early stage, and there are also some lines with a quick ...Bd6. So White aficionados have a lot more homework to do.}) ({Nf3 In the Alatortsev chapter, we look at cxd5 exd5} 6. Bf4 {Both} c6 7. e3 {Bf5 and 5...Nf6 6.e3 Bf5 are interesting lines. We will go with the former.}) ({Nf6 Bg5 This was always the main move, but nowadays it's considered that Black has multiple solutions. Today} 6. Bf4 {definitely looks more dangerous.} O-O 7. e3 {We will play} b6 {which fits well with the Tartakover. I really wanted to go for 6...c5 as it's the real 'classical' move. I think it's rather difficult for Black though. We will see why in the relevant chapter. 6...Nbd7 is a good move, preparing ...c5. This can lead to an isolated d5-pawn, while White can also play for a space advantage with 7.c5}) 6... h6 {A good move to throw in. Black can castle first, but this is more accurate I think. Bh4 O-O} {White can also play Bxf6 Bxf6 This is another line I played many times with White. I don't think it's too dangerous though.} 7. e3 {Now that Black has castled, it's time to figure out what to do with the c8-bishop.} b6 $1 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) *

