1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c6 ({We will keep the tension with this flexible move.} 11... Nd7 12. Qb3 c6 {is likely to transpose}) 12. Rb1 Nd7 (12... Re8 13. Qb3 Nd7 {transposes.}) 13. Qb3 Re8 {Both sides have just about completed development, and White just has to decide when to play e3-e4.} 14. Bd3 ({Or} 14. Rbd1 {White brings all of the pieces into play before breaking in the center.} Nf8 {is a typical complex Tartakower middlegame. Black has the bishop pair and while they are not active, if the position opens up they may show their teeth. White still generally plays to break in the center, hoping that his central buildup will mean more than Black's potential.}) 14... c5 {Let's do it. If White does not capture, both ...c4 and ...cxd4 look like good options.} ({The prophylactic} 14... g6 {is good too, as} 15. e4 $6 {is well met with} c5 $1) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Qc2 g6 {We have an IQP, but our pieces are good. White's pieces on the other hand, look a bit awkward as he went searching for a phantom mate.} 17. Nd4 {Khalifman claimed that White was better here, but this is rather optimistic.} Rc8 {Today's engines clearly prefer Black. His position is active and White lacks a good plan.} *

