1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {This natural move is the most common overall, but not by much. White intends to develop smoothly with O-O and Qe2, and then he will be free to deploy his rooks however he likes. Often White will play Bh4-g3 to avoid certain exchanges as well. Black can develop his minor pieces easily enough, but then there's the old question - what do do with the queen? Black needs to trade at least one set of minor pieces. This will be attempted with ...Ne4, or perhaps ...Nh5. Pawn exchanges in the center may help too for example, if White plays cxd5 we react with ...Nxd5, as always. Black just has to be careful that in his eagerness to trade pieces, he does not give White a big lead in development, which may turn into a tangible initiative.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {This plan seems more appropriate with White's light-squared bishop on e2, where it does not block the d-file.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {Black will generally play ...c5 here, as the d3-bishop blocks White's queen from putting any pressure on the d5-pawn.} 11. b4 {We have seen this idea in the 8.Be2 chapter. Here we react differently.} (11. Rc1 c5 {transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 11... c5 $1 ({We reacted differently with the bishop on e2. Here} 11... c6 {is playable, although} 12. O-O {leaves White a bit ahead on e3-e4 plans compared to some other lines.}) 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 {White plays along the lines of a main line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.b4 c5 we go for 12...c6 there 12.bxc5 bxc5 . Here White's d3-bishop interferes with his control of d4.} Bc6 {This keeps some play in the position, but we have to make sure we do not get pulled into an unfamiliar and unpleasant line.} 14. Bb5 $146 {Untried, but a tricky move.} a6 $1 15. Ba4 $5 (15. Bxc6 Nxc6 {is easy for Black. The d4-pawn is still pinned.}) 15... cxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxa4 17. Qxa4 {Now we have a funny trick.} Nc6 $1 {A remarkable move!} 18. Nce2 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Rc8 $1 20. O-O {The white king wisely evacuates.} (20. Qxa6 $2 Bxd4 21. exd4 Re8+ {is clearly no good for White.}) 20... Rc4 {Not the only move, but the most forcing.} 21. Qxa6 Bxd4 22. exd4 Rxd4 {White has survived the complications and a draw is likely.} *

