1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768] Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 ({There is a little trick here but it's easy enough to avoid. White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with} 10. Qe2 {, is a more serious try for an edge.}) 10... c5 ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. cxd5 ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nc5 {We simply hit the bishop and consider ...Ne4.} ({Another solid choice is} 14... Bf6 15. Rfd1 Bxd4 16. exd4 Nb8 $1 17. Rac1 Nc6 {as played in the high-level games Ivanchuk-Kasimdzhanov, Tripoli 2004 and Nakamura-So, Saint Louis 2015.}) 15. Bc2 Ne4 {Continuing with the plan.} (15... Bd6 $6 {has been played quite a few times, but I do not like it.} 16. e4 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Bb7 18. Rfd1 Qe7 19. e5 {with a nice space advantage.}) 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Rfd1 {We have the usual concerns with our queen, but the problems are not so difficult.} Qe8 {Sidestep.} (17... Qd5 {seems fine too. We can always retreat our bishop to g6.}) 18. Nb5 {This looks like the only move that could possibly cause us any concern.} Rd8 19. Nd6 {We cannot take it or we lose the exchange.} Qc6 20. Rac1 Qa8 21. Rc7 {Now it's safe.} Bxd6 22. Bxd6 Rc8 {This is even simplest. We have no problems at all.} (22... Rfe8 {is also possible, when} 23. Qg4 {is a little uncomfortable, but still ok after} e5 $1) *

