1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Bg3 ({Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now} 11. Rfd1 {and}) (11. Bg3 {are clearly the main moves.}) {A bit of a prophylactic move. White wants to keep pieces on the board.} 11... cxd4 ({Reversing the captures with} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 cxd4 {is valid and would transpose if White took with the pawn, but this White has an extra option with} 13. Nxd4) ({The main alternative is} 11... Ne4 12. cxd5 exd5 {, but I don't like this structure as much. After 12...Nxc3 13.bxc3 Bxd5 14.e4 is not a good version of this kind of structure for Black - the queen has no good square.} 13. Rad1 Qc8 {is a well-known idea of Nigel Short. Black intends ...Nf6 and ...Qe6.}) 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 {This looks like a typical IQP position, but there are some notable details. Usually White's rooks are ideally placed on the e1- and d1-squares. He can aim for this setup, but the white queen has committed rather early to e2. The most dangerous setup is with Qd3, often combined with a3, Bb3 and Bc2, setting up a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal. One issue Black faces is that his knights are kind of tripping on each other. If he could 'teleport' the d7-knight to d5, all would be fine. As it is, the minor pieces are cramped, and this helps to understand what follows.} Nh5 {Black wants to eat the bishop and bring his other knight to f6. Generally the biggest concern Black faces is the advance d4-d5 blasting things open. Even if Black has the bishop pair, this is dangerous - White's rook are connected and Black's are not, so the central pressure can be difficult to deal with.} ({Another idea is} 13... a6 {Ideally Black would play ...b5 and then ...Nb6! solving the problem he has with his knights. White should certainly respond with} 14. a4 {It would seem that this favors Black - the b5-square is covered and White has weakened b4. But it's not that simple. For one thing, Black cannot play ...Rc8 without hanging his a6-pawn.}) ({There is also} 13... Bb4 {White's bishop voluntarily retreated to g3, so there is no pin on the f6-knight now.} 14. Nb5 $5 {with some complications.}) 14. d5 ({The only really critical move. Instead} 14. Rad1 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Nf6 {transposes to 11.Rad1. Here Black has played ... Nh5xg3 rather than ...Ne4xg3, but the position is the same!}) 14... Nxg3 15. hxg3 exd5 16. Bxd5 {White immediately 'halves' Black's bishop pair, hoping that his knights will be superior in the center.} Bxd5 17. Nxd5 Bd6 $5 ({Keeping the bishop. Black could also play} 17... Re8 {.}) 18. Rad1 Nf6 {Black has no problems here. If White does not trade knights, Black can just play ...Qe7. It's equal, but the bishop always keeps some prospetcs in the endgame. In fact Black won both of the GM matchups that reached this position.} *

