1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 {A natural move, lining up with the black queen and keeping c1 open for the other rook.} Ne4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4) ({Or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bxe7 {Black certainly will not end up with the bishop pair now, but we are happy to have a good square for our queen.} Qxe7 13. cxd5 exd5 ({Now our bishop is blocked, but we keep good control of the center. Instead} 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxd5 15. e4 Bb7 {is a typical response, but} 16. d5 $5 {works tactically and looks a bit better for White.}) 14. Rac1 Nxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Rxc3 $6 {is even worse, as after} c4 {and ...b5, our queenside play rolls along easily.}) 15... c4 $132 {A typical idea. We have a bad bishop but our play is clear on the queenside. White's only pawn break with e3-e4 will bring our bishop right back to life!} *

