1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. O-O-O $6 {This may look natural and aggressive, but it's just bad. White's king is much less safe than Black's.} ({We can understand from previous chapters that} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {cannot be dangerous for Black. Why is the white queen on c2?!}) 9... Nbd7 {The engines already have this as  ! Black's king is safer and he leads in development.} 10. Kb1 {Getting off the c-file.} c5 11. dxc5 Rc8 $1 {Everything is rolling for Black. White cannot hold onto the extra pawn. For example:} 12. cxb6 Nxb6 13. cxd5 $2 Nfxd5 (13... Nbxd5 {is winning too.}) 14. Bxe7 Nxc3+ 15. bxc3 Qxe7 {White will not last long.} *

