1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but is Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} c5 $1 {Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center! Now White should really get going with his kingside demonstration, but he can also take on c5.} 12. dxc5 $6 {White switches his attention to the apparently vulnerable d5-pawn. This is the main alternative to the pawn advances, but it's not very good. It's been played a lot and was used successfully by a young Kasparov, so it's important to know how to react.} Bxc3 $1 ({Black must avoid} 12... bxc5 $6 13. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 14. Bc4) ({The traditional move is} 12... Nd7 {, and this is also good.} 13. c6 $1 {( 13.cxb6 Bxc3 14.bxc3 axb6 ) ( 13.Nxd5 Nxc5 14.Bc4 b5! Kasparov-I.Zaitsev, Baku 1980).} Bxc6 14. Nd4 Bb7 {both practice and the engines show that Black is a little better, but White is more solid here compared to 12...Bxc3!}) 13. Qxc3 Nd7 $1 {This is a highly thematic idea.} ({After} 13... bxc5 {White can grab the pawn with} 14. Qxc5 {.}) 14. c6 {Practically forced.} ({If} 14. Kb1 bxc5 {Black's king is much safer.}) 14... Bxc6 15. Kb1 {It's best to leave the c-file. This position looks pretty solid for White, as the powerful f6-bishop is gone and White has d4 for his knight, but Black's initiative is still quite strong.} Rc8 {Threatening ...Ba4.} 16. Qd2 Nc5 17. Nd4 ({Instead} 17. Bd3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 {transposes to StartFEN2rq1rk1/p2n1pp1/1pb4p/3p4/8/2Q1PN2/PP3PPP/1K1R1B1R w - - 2 16EndFEN 16.Qd4 Nc5 17.Bd3 Nxd3 18.Qxd3 which we'll check too.}) 17... Ne4 {It turns out that f2 is another vulnerable spot in White's camp.} 18. Qe1 Ba4 $1 {This simple attack is rather annoying for White.} 19. Rc1 {White hopes that exchanges will relieve the pressure.} Rxc1+ 20. Kxc1 Qh4 {Black is well ahead in development and White is given no time to rest.} (20... Qf6 21. f3 Nc5 {and then ...Re8, is also good.}) 21. g3 Rc8+ 22. Kb1 Nxg3 $1 {[%csl Rb1,Rh1][%cal Gh4e4] Black wins a pawn.} *

