1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qb3 {This is a funny looking move. White waits for the bishop to go to b7 before fixing the center.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {White embarks on a familiar plan. If White does not do this, Black can play normally as there's no reason for White's queen to be on b3.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {The main line. White looks to discourage the ...c5 advance.} (11. Bd3 $6 {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Qb3?!}) (11. Be2 c6 12. O-O Re8 {is likely to transpose to a line from 8.Be2. For example} 13. Rfe1 Nd7 {is a line that usually arises from StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.O-O}) 11... Re8 $1 {Black does not commit the c-pawn yet, preferring to line up his rook against White's uncastled king.} (11... c5 {is premature because of} 12. dxc5 {After}) (11... c6 12. Bd3 {White has his ideal setup in this structure - the bishop going to d3 in one move. He intends to castle and play for a quick e3-e4. Nevertheless, after} Na6 13. O-O {the rare} c5 {!? still seems satisfactory for Black despite the lost tempo.}) 12. Bd3 {White is still going for the ideal setup, but Black is very quick with counterplay here.} ({Instead} 12. Be2 c6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfe1 {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.O-O .}) 12... c5 $1 {This thematic pawn sacrifice is completely sound.} (12... c6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfe1 Nf8 15. e4 {is ideal for White, although the position is still complex after} Ne6 16. e5 Be7) (12... Nc6 {!? intending ...Na5 and then ...c5, is another idea, but I prefer the immediate strike.}) 13. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {The point - the knight is coming to c5 no matter what.} 14. c6 $1 {This is the safest.} Bxc6 15. O-O Nc5 16. Qc2 Rc8 {This is a typical Tartakover position where both sides have their advantages. We will see a nice example of Black's play in Beliavsky-Kramnik, Beograd 1997.} *

