1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent lines as well.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {Now that Black has brought the bishop to b7, White fixes the pawn structure. We saw this in the main lines of 8.Be2.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 ({Now White can go in two completely different directions - he can continue to develop with} 11. Bd3 {, hoping to be better placed to break with e3-e4 than he was in the lines with the bishop on e2; or he can play}) (11. b4 {, looking to restrain Black's queenside pawns. According the engines, Black can play} c5 {against either move here. There is certain logic to that approach, as White is not castled yet. Indeed, it would be simpler to consider that approach, but I don't think Black is bound to it, and we will attempt to keep things a bit more complicated.}) ({According to Ivan Sokolov White's idea with this line is to force an exchange on d4 and obtain a position with the d-pawns fixed, and then rely upon the superiority of his d3-bishop to the one on b7. Sokolov says that 'if White's idea is well executed, he will have a small but lasting advantage'. Well, nowadays computers can help us neutralize just about anything, but we have some idea what we'll up against now. Instead} 11. Be2 c6 12. O-O Re8 13. b4 {will bring us to the 11.b4 line.}) 11... c5 $1 ({After} 11... c6 {White doesn't have to bother with b4 now.} 12. O-O {and White will play e3-e4 at some point. It's not fatal for Black, but White has a better version of the StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.O-O line, as his bishop is already on d3.}) 12. O-O {Now we have a position that could have also arisen from StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Rc1 . Black has many reasonable moves here. This is always nice if you forget something!} Nd7 {Simplest. One of our Tartakover heroes, Nigel Short, once tried} (12... Re8 {here. Then} 13. dxc5 {is the most challenging. If} bxc5 14. Qb3 {!}) (12... Na6 {!? is an interesting move. The idea is to bring the knight to c7 and e6 - often a nice centralization that pressures d4.}) (12... cxd4 {is common - 'satisfactory, but lacking complexity' - Short.} 13. Nxd4 {13.exd4 Nc6 14.Bb1 Re8 looks fine to me. This is the structure that 'is supposed to favors White' but not sure I believe it. After 15.Qd3 g6 I like the bishop pair.} Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Ne2 Qd6 {was Yermolinsky-Short, Tallinn/Parnu 1998. Fine for Black, but very solid for White.}) 13. Bf5 {This is a typical idea which puts pressure on both the d5- and c5-pawns indirectly. The white queen's path to d5 is opened, and there is the possibility of capturing the d7-knight, which helps protect the c5-pawn.} g6 {Asking the bishop a question. I find} (13... cxd4 {to be too panicky. After} 14. exd4 g6 15. Bh3 {The d7-knight has no squares, and} Re8 {?} 16. Nb5 {! would be a big problem.}) (13... Re8 {is a valid alternative however.}) 14. Bxd7 {Consistent.} cxd4 $1 {An important in-between move! The hasty} (14... Qxd7 {? runs into} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Ne4 {! and Black is basically lost.}) 15. Bc6 $5 {This gains a tempo.} (15. Nxd4 Qxd7 {is similar.}) 15... Bxc6 16. Nxd4 Bb7 {Knights vs. bishops! Play is about equal.} *

