1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent lines as well.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Now that Black has brought the bishop to b7, White fixes the pawn structure. We saw this in the main lines of 8.Be2.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Now White can go in two completely different directions - he can continue to develop with} 11. Bd3 {, hoping to be better placed to break with e3-e4 than he was in the lines with the bishop on e2; or he can play}) (11. b4 {, looking to restrain Black's queenside pawns. According the engines, Black can play} c5 {against either move here. There is certain logic to that approach, as White is not castled yet. Indeed, it would be simpler to consider that approach, but I don't think Black is bound to it, and we will attempt to keep things a bit more complicated.}) 11... c6 {[%mdl 32768] With this move Black keeps the game interesting.} 12. Bd3 {This at least looks productive. The bishop is more active and Black has committed to ...c6, so e3-e4 becomes more attractive. But with b4 played, Black also has ready made counterplay on the queenside.} a5 $5 {This is the most direct, and it limits White's options. With the bishop on e2, all of White's moves have some point here a3, b5, bxa5, but here pushing is best. White has also spent a move on Rc1 instead of castling, so it makes sense to keep the position relatively closed. As always, White has a few ways to react.} ({Black has a lot of choice:} 12... Re8 {,}) (12... Nd7 {,}) (12... Qd6 {,}) (12... Be7 $5 {are all playable.}) 13. a3 Be7 {Taking aim at the b4-pawn.} 14. Rb1 axb4 15. axb4 b5 $5 {Fixing the b4-pawn. Instead of going for ... Nd7-b6-c4, which would be met with a quick e3-e4, Black plans to lay siege to the b4-pawn with ...Na6, ...Bd6, and ...Qe7.} *

