{Black will castle and double rooks on the d-file with good play.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves whether on move 6 or 7, we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach.} 7. e4 $6 {This looks aggressive, but it exposes the d4-pawn.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nc6 $1 {This is one variation where the tempo saves on not castling can be put to good use, as White does not have time to castle long. White already has to be careful.} ({Instead} 8... O-O 9. Qd2 {gives White time to castle, adding protection to the d4-pawn.}) 9. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {This is very comfortable for Black. White is close to equality, which is not much of an accomplishment for him nine moves into the game!} 10. Qd3 ({This is less common than} 10. Qd2 {, but it is probably a better chance for White to equalize.}) ({After a quiet move like} 10. Be2 {simply} O-O {intending ...Rd8 will cause White problems.}) 10... b6 $1 {This is still good, but White can stay within the bounds of near-equality.} 11. O-O-O Bb7 12. Be2 Rd8 $15 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd8d7,Ge8g8,Gf8d8]} ({I like this even better than} 12... O-O-O) *

