1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves whether on move 6 or 7, we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Qxc4 O-O {The position actually resembles a Grunfeld, Russian Variation, but White's dark-squared bishop has been traded off. Black has some similar ideas here - taking advantage of the exposed white queen to play on the queenside aiming for ...b5 and ...c5.} 9. e3 {This is definitely the safest try.} b6 ({After} 9... a6 10. Ne4 {now makes some sense.} Be7 11. Rc1 {and e3 is more useful than ...a6.}) ({Instead} 9... Nd7 {is possible, but we have lost the possibility of ...Ba6.}) 10. Be2 {This has been played with success by Bu Xiangzhi.} c5 $146 {An idea of Kornev, which is again in the spirit of the Grunfeld.} ({Alternatives are} 10... Nd7 11. O-O c5 {-Colovic}) ({And} 10... Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 12. Rfd1 a6 13. a4 c5 14. d5 {Black is probably ok here with some care, but White has achieved what he wants - a slight pull - and Bu Xiangzhi has shown that it's not completely harmless.}) 11. dxc5 Ba6 $1 12. Qe4 ({Instead} 12. Qa4 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Bxe2 14. Kxe2 Nd7 15. cxb6 axb6 {is similar.}) 12... Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Bxe2 14. Kxe2 ({White avoids the greedy} 14. Qxa8 Qd3 {.}) 14... Nd7 15. cxb6 ({After} 15. c6 $2 Nc5 {the advanced c-pawn won't last.}) 15... axb6 $13 {This looks a lot like some lines of the Grunfeld. The open a- and c-file give Black excellent compensation against White's split pawns.} *

