1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves whether on move 6 or 7, we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach.} 7. e3 O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 8. cxd5 {White switches to a Carlsbad structure. This is not especially dangerous, but it's reasonable enough.} exd5 {Strangely enough, the position is almost identical to a line of the Grunfeld: StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bg5 Ne4 6.cxd5 Nxg5 7.Nxg5 e6 8.Nf3 exd5 9.e3 O-O . The only difference is that Black has a pawn on h6 instead of g6! Of course in the Grunfeld line they'll tell you it looks like a QGD... White has many moves here, but the positions are not exactly 'move by move' critical - an understanding of the structures is more important than remembering anything. Black enjoys the bishop pair, and he will typically develop with ...Be6 and ...Nd7, while rerouting the f6-bishop to d6 is also common. We will check a few moves to see some typical ideas. The most common is the minority attack with b4-b5.} 9. Bd3 {This natural move is White's most common choice.} c6 ({The direct} 9... c5 {is also fine, with the idea} 10. dxc5 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nd7 {.}) 10. O-O ({Sometimes White plays} 10. h3 {if he wants to avoid ...Bg4 , but we'd just continue with} Nd7 {anyway.}) 10... Nd7 {This looks the most flexible in view of White's coming minority attack.} (10... Be6 {should be fine too though.}) ({I do not see any reason to part with a bishop with} 10... Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {.}) 11. b4 {White's standard plan in the Carlsbad.} Nb6 $1 {The knight is well placed here, as Black has various 'counter plans' to deal with White's queenside play.} 12. Rc1 {White clears the long diagonal.} a6 $5 (12... Be6 {looks fine too.}) 13. a4 Be7 14. b5 $6 {Now we will see a nice idea that is well worth knowing.} cxb5 15. axb5 a5 $1 {Black was doing well in L.B.Hansen - Nielsen, Aalborg 2000. The a5-pawn is strong and we have the bishop pair of course.} *

