1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves whether on move 6 or 7, we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 {After all the queen dances, we come to the main line, and probably the most challenging move.} dxc4 $5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({A bit of a revelation, as} 8... c6 {is by far the main move. There was a time when this immediate capture, just allowing Bxc4 in one move, would have been unheard of. But with today's engines, we can see that a lot of moves which apparently violate certain principles are quite playable. Considering that in the Queen's Gambit Accepted White takes on c4 in one move, we can see that it is not unreasonable to play this way. We will consider 8...c6 as an informational line, where I will show that both moves may even transpose!}) 9. Bxc4 ({White should not get fancy. Black is already better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6 {.}) 9... Nd7 10. O-O {The most natural move.} c5 {Now there is a big split. White can play classical with Qe2 , intending Rd1 with quick development, or he can play Ne4 , aiming for further simplifications.} 11. Qe2 {This was the choice of none other than Kasparov, which of course gives the move a certain stamp of approval. 'The Boss' won a rather clean game, but maybe this is because he is Kasparov, and not because of any faultiness in Black's setup?!} cxd4 {Black seeks clarity.} ({Kasparov faced} 11... a6 {This is a typical QGA-type move and it is not bad, but Black is lagging in development.} 12. Rfd1 cxd4 {(Kasparov gave no comment to this move, but 12...b5 looks more consistent. I imagine everyone assumed that 13.dxc5!? would be very strong for White, but after 13...bxc4 14.c6 Qe7 15.cxd7 Bxd7 16.Qxc4 Rfc8 Black has a fair amount of play for the pawn, and the engines think it's equal).} 13. Nxd4 $1 {Here ...a6 does look too slow, as Black has trouble getting his pieces out.} Qe7 14. Ne4 Be5 15. Qh5 $1 {and Kasparov relentlessly kept up the pressure in Kasparov - Olafsson, Dubai 1986.}) 12. exd4 Nb6 ({Black must maintain some control over the d5-square. If Black had all the time in the world,} 12... b6 $6 {would be desirable, but both} 13. Rfd1 Bb7 14. d5 $1 {and the immediate 14.d5! are quite problematic.}) 13. Bb3 {Not dangerous. The b1-h7 diagonal is more important.} Bd7 {This is fine for Black. It's important to understand that the following pawn structure is satisfactory:} 14. Ne5 Bc6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 $132 {We have a well-known structure where the c6-pawn is no more weak than the target on d4.} *

