1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves whether on move 6 or 7, we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 {After all the queen dances, we come to the main line, and probably the most challenging move.} dxc4 ({A bit of a revelation, as} 8... c6 {is by far the main move. There was a time when this immediate capture, just allowing Bxc4 in one move, would have been unheard of. But with today's engines, we can see that a lot of moves which apparently violate certain principles are quite playable. Considering that in the Queen's Gambit Accepted White takes on c4 in one move, we can see that it is not unreasonable to play this way. We will consider 8...c6 as an informational line, where I will show that both moves may even transpose!}) 9. Bxc4 ({White should not get fancy. Black is already better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6 {.}) 9... Nd7 10. O-O c5 {Now there is a big split. White can play classical with Qe2 , intending Rd1 with quick development, or he can play Ne4 , aiming for further simplifications.} 11. Ne4 {White goes for simplifications. Usually this is welcomed by Black, and Colovic was not concerned here, but this line was recommended by Papaioannou via a different move order considered in our informational line on 8...c6 in his course on modern-chess, so we must take it seriously.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. Qxd4 {Papaioannou's recommendation. White's chances for a pull are in the endgame.} b6 $146 {This simple move was not considered by Papaioannou. I do not see any problems here.} (13... Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Bd7 {is given by Colovic. Papaioannou goes quite a bit further, and White's play is not as harmless as it may seem. Some care is still required by Black:} 15. Be2 $5 Rac8 16. f4 $1 {White intends Bf3 and e4-e5. I think that Black is ok with careful play, but our move looks easier.}) (13... Bd7 {is also quite solid, if Black meets} 14. Ne5 {with the clever} Ba4 $1 {acquiescing to the queen trade under somewhat better circumstances.}) ({After} 13... b6 {the engines show simple equality. A couple of little lines:} 14. Bb5 {( 14.Rfd1 Bb7 15.Qe5 Qe7 ) ( 14.Be2 Bb7 15.Qxd8 Rfxd8 16.Rc7 Rab8 )} Bb7 15. Bc6 Qe7 {.}) *

