1. d4 d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O {Now e3 is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.} 6. Rc1 {A typical move in the QGD. Here the rook combines with the f4-bishop to cast a glance at the c7-pawn. So Black's options are a bit limited, but White is also restricted - castling long is certainly no longer an option. There are also some positions where queens will be exchanged, and White will lose a tempo by playing Ra1-c1xd1.} c5 $1 {We will meet 6.Qc2 this way as well, so it will all be easier to remember.} ({First of all,} 6... b6 {is now less appealing.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. a3 $1 {saves the pawn, covers the b4-square, and renews the threat to c7 . After} c5 10. dxc5 {give White a small but safe edge. Really White's sixth move is directed against the popular setups with ...Nbd7, or e3 Nd5 Bxc4 Nxf4 exf4 Nc6 ! ( 10.e3 is a 'clean' edge for white). The immediate 9...dxc4!? is rather thematic 10.e4} b5 {! Nxb5 Bb4+ Nc3 Ba6 is possible, but it's needlessly complicated and I am not so sure Black will equalize here in any case.}) 7. dxc5 dxc4 {Again, simplicity. As mentioned before we do not mind the queen exchange. The alternative} (7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 {is also quite playable. This usually arises from the 6...c5 line, but Black has avoided the most dangerous setup with Qc2 and Rd1.}) 8. e4 {This looks ambitious, but the e-pawn can quickly become a target.} Qxd1+ {White does not want to take with the king, so it's good to make him move the rook again.} 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Bxc4 Bb4 $1 {A typical idea - this not only threatens to win the e4-pawn, it prepares to split White's queenside pawns.} 11. Bd6 ({If} 11. Bd3 {Black can either split the pawns with} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Bd7) ({Or develop simply with Nc6} 11. O-O Bd7 {.}) 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rd8 {The e4-pawn is now attacked.} 13. O-O {Connecting the rooks.} (13. e5 Ne4 {hitting d6 and c3 looks good for Black.}) 13... Bd7 ({We cannot take} 13... Nxe4 $4 14. Bxb8 {and we lose because of the back rank.}) 14. Rfe1 Bc6 {White has the bishops, but Black has the better pawn structure and good squares for the pieces, Aronian-Radjabov, Porto Carras 2011.} *

