1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O {Now e3 is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.} 6. Qc2 {Another typical QGD move if White insists on delaying e3. White does not commit his rook and maintains the options of castling queenside, but the queen is a bit exposed here and Black can often take advantage of this.} c5 $1 {We will meet this the same way as we did with 6.Rc1.} ({A) Once again,} 6... b6 {is inferior, this time because of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {the thematic move, but it doesn't work well here. ( 7...exd5 8.e3 is a nice edge for White).} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. e4 $1 {makes 6.Qc2 look quite clever. One point is that} Bb4+ {does not cause the trouble it seems to, as} 10. Kd1 $1 {is good for White - Black will waste a lot of time retreating his pieces.}) ({B) Black should also skip} 6... Nbd7 {because} 7. cxd5 {forces} exd5 8. e3 {with another good exchange variation for White.}) ({C) Finally,} 6... dxc4 {can be met with} 7. e3 $1 {rather than 7.e4 Nc6!}) 7. dxc5 Na6 $1 {A good flexible move. We may recapture on c5, while ...Nb4 is also a possibility. If} (7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Rd1 {we have been tricked into White's best line in the 6.e3 c5 complex. The less common}) (7... Qa5 {is given by Ntirlis. This seems fine as well, but White has a lot of choice here and it can be a bit complicated after} 8. Nd2 {!?} Qxc5 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. Bg5) 8. e3 {The safest choice. White needs to get developed.} Nxc5 {[%mdl 32768] This transposes to a line that is often reached via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 6 6EndFEN 6.e3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5 Nxc5 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. Be2 {The only good move. Again, White needs to develop his pieces.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 $1 {I like this line for Black a lot. White should really play a4 to avoid being worse.} 11. a4 {By restricting the b7-pawn, Black is limited to ... b6, and it's harder to find a comfortable square for the black queen. Harder, but not impossible!} b6 {Black has also done well with} (11... Qa5 12. O-O b6 {but I find the position of the queen on a5 to be a bit awkward.}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 {Black is ready to play ...Rd8 and ...Qc6, creating pressure on the long diagonal. White has been unable to present Black with any problems in practice. I will give a couple of lines though, as there are a couple of small pitfalls to avoid.} 14. Qe2 {This is the most common, but it allows Black to execute his plan.} (14. Ne5 {prevents ...Qc6, but Black can just play} Rd8) 14... Qc6 {Black is ready to bring the rooks into play, and White must be wary of the long diagonal.} 15. Qf1 {Covering the g2-pawn to free up the f3-knight.} Rfc8 $1 {This is the right square.} (15... Rac8 16. Nd4 {forces the queen back to e8, blocking in the f8-rook.}) ({While} 15... Rfd8 16. Nd4 Qc8 {(if 16...Qe8 17.Bc7 wins a pawn).} 17. b4 Ncd7 18. Rac1 {is very uncomfortable for Black.}) 16. Ne5 Qe8 {Black coordinated his pieces and had nothing to worry about in Karjakin-Kramnik, Nice blindfold 2009.} *

