1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bxc7 {We will start with this move, as grabbing the pawn is both obvious and critical.} Bb4+ {First we create a little disruption in the white camp.} 10. Nd2 Nc6 $1 {White is tied up and Black has a rather large lead in development. Black may bring the bishop to b7 or d7, depending on what follows. Either rook may come to c8.} ({Practice has show that this is more flexible than} 10... Bb7 {while}) (10... Ba6 {is well met by} 11. Bxb8 {.}) 11. a3 {This is a natural move but it shows an advantage to Black's move order.} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5 ({An untried idea which looks interesting is} 12... Bd7 $5 13. b4 {(If 13.f3 Rac8 14.e4 Qxd4 15.Bd6 Qxd2+ 16.Kxd2 Nd4 is fine for Black)} Rac8 14. Bg3 Ne7 {looks like decent compensation.}) 13. Qd3 {This looks critical. White avoids the fork and the queen is less vulnerable here.} Bd7 {This bishop has better prospects here than on the long diagonal.} ({After} 13... Bb7 14. f3 {it's not clear how to continue.}) 14. b4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Ba4 {Securing the knight in the enemy camp and preparing to take the c-file.} 16. Qc4 {White wants to exchange queens and go after our knight.} Qxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxd4 $1 {We grab a pawn and then we will win back the piece with ...Rfc8.} ({For example} 17... Rfc8 18. Bxb6 {(Or 18.Bxe6 Rxc7 )} axb6 {In both cases Black is well ahead in development and should easily win back the pawn.}) *

