{A few little lines: exd4 or Rxc8 ? dxe3+ and if e4 d3} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bxc7 {We will start with this move, as grabbing the pawn is both obvious and critical.} Bb4+ {First we cause a little disruption in the white camp.} 10. Nd2 Nc6 $1 {White is tied up and Black has a rather large lead in development. Black may bring the bishop to b7 or d7, depending on what follows. Either rook may come to c8.} ({Practice has show that this is more flexible than} 10... Bb7 {while}) (10... Ba6 {is well met by} 11. Bxb8 {.}) 11. f3 {A logical looking move, but it does weaken White's position a bit too.} Bd7 {[%mdl 32768] White's last move blocked the h1-a8 diagonal, so Black goes a different way. Often ...Ba4 is a resource. The natural} (11... Bb7 {is untried, but does not look bad. One possibility is} 12. a3 Bxd2+ {or even 12...Rac8 first} 13. Qxd2 Rac8 14. Bg3 Na5 {with typical compensation.}) 12. Kf2 {This looks like the best choice. Now a brief flurry of tactics will follow.} Nxd4 $1 (12... Rac8 {allows White to consolidate with} 13. Bf4 {! but not 13.Bg3 Nxd4 !}) 13. Ne4 $1 {White is not up a pawn any more, but he hopes to have a little something in the endgame that will soon arise. If} (13. exd4 {?} Qxd4+ 14. Ke1 {and now everything wins, but the most straightforward is} Ba4 15. b3 Bxd2+) 13... Rac8 {This looks the most straightforward to me.} (13... Rfc8 {is also possible. Let's see what's different.} 14. Rc1 Nb5 15. Bxb5 Bxb5 16. Nd6 Bxd6 {another possibility is 16...Qxd1 17.Rhxd1 Bxd6 18.Rxd6 Re8 , but Black is more passively placed here than in our line.} 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Bxd6 f6 {with the idea ...Kf7-e6 was given by Ntirlis in his excellent Playing 1.d4 d5 book. White is definitely 'better' after} 19. g4 {gaining some space. It's still a draw - especially in a correspondence game - but I'd keep playing if I were White here.}) 14. Rc1 Nb5 15. Bxb5 {Or} (15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Bxb5 Bxb5 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. Bxd6 Rfe8 {transposing to the 16.Qxd5 note.}) 15... Bxb5 16. a3 {White can have this move for free, or do without it with the immediate} (16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. Bxd6 Rfe8 {is the same, but without a2-a3 Instead}) (16. Nd6 Qxd1 17. Rhxd1 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 f6 {! with the idea ...Rf7 shows the virtue of keeping a rook on f8.}) 16... Be7 {We are going to allow the isolated pawn. If} (16... Qxd1 {?} 17. Rhxd1 Be7 18. Bd6 {suddenly gives White a winning position.}) 17. Qxd5 ({Again} 17. Nd6 Qxd1 18. Rhxd1 Bxd6 19. Rxd6 f6 {is nothing.}) 17... exd5 18. Nd6 Bxd6 19. Bxd6 {An apparent downside to Black's choice of rook on move 13, but there is a point...} Rfe8 {Now if White wants to gain space, we will have counterplay.} 20. g4 ({If} 20. Bb4 h5 $5 {prevents g4, and Black really has nothing to worry about.}) 20... d4 $1 {Black has chances too. Rcd8 !} *

