1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {This is much less popular than 5.Bf4. It's less flexible, and the tempo spent here means that Black can usually develop the c8-bishop more easily.} Nf6 {It is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.} 6. Bg5 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Qc2 {Preventing ...Bf5, but only for a moment.} g6 $1 ({After} 7... O-O 8. e3 {Black will not get the c8-bishop out, and must revert to the older lines of the QGD where White can hope for an edge.}) 8. e4 {This is White's only attempt to 'make something happen'. Karpov defeated Yusupov once this way, but he never played it again. Nowadays it is well-known and not considered dangerous.} (8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {is very similar to 7.e3.}) 8... dxe4 {This looks like the best response.} ({Likely caught by surprise, Yusupov went for} 8... Nxe4 9. Bxe7 Kxe7 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4+ Be6 {which is still not bad. But after} 12. Bc4 {he erred with} Qa5+ $2 {12...Re8! would have been fine for Black.} 13. Kf1 Qf5 14. Qe3 Nd7 15. Re1 {which by now was rather uncomfortable for Black in Karpov-Yusupov, USSR ch 1988.}) 9. Bxf6 ({If} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Be6 {Black has no issues at all and enjoys a superior pawn structure.}) 9... Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7 {Already the engines slightly prefer Black.} (10... Kf8 {is fine too.}) 11. Bc4 ({The best move order. If} 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. Bc4 {Black can simply transpose with} Bf5 {while 12...Rd8!? is a decent choice as well.}) 11... Bf5 {Forcing matters.} 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 ({We could play} 12... Bxe7 {but the bishop is more active on f6 , and with the queens off the board, we should not face any problems with our king.}) 13. O-O-O (13. h3 {would be met with} h5 {.}) 13... Kf8 $5 {A novelty in a well-known position!} (13... Rd8 {is played a lot, but after} 14. h3 {the desirable} h5 {is not so good.} 15. g4 $1 {and if} hxg4 16. hxg4 Bxg4 $2 17. Rh7 $1 {is crushing.}) (13... Nd7 {is very solid, and similar.} 14. h3 h5 15. Rhe1+ Kf8 {.}) 14. h3 h5 15. Rhe1 (15. Ne5 $4 {loses to} Bg5+ {.}) (15. d5 $6 {is tempting but premature.} Kg7 16. d6 {(Or 16.dxc6 Nxc6 ) .} Nd7) (15. Rhg1 {dreams of g2-g4, but Black has} h4 {and here I like having the rook on the h-file for the time being.}) 15... Kg7 {Black is ready to complete his development.} 16. Ne4 {White seeks to eliminate of one Black's bishops.} Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Nd7 {Black is clearly fine, and things are 'trending' his way. If White is tempted to eliminate his isolated pawn, he can easily get in more trouble.} 18. Z0 ({For example} 18. d5 $2 Nc5 19. Ree1 b5 $1 20. Bf1 cxd5 21. Rxd5 Rac8 22. Kb1 a6 $17 {and in this symmetrical structure, Black is much more active - just compare the activity of the bishops! Already ...Na4 looks very dangerous for White.}) *

