1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 6. Qc2 {[%cal Rc8f5]} Nf6 7. e3 ({White does not want to spend time on} 7. h3 {, but he can't have everything.}) 7... Nh5 $1 {A very important move. We cannot just let White play h3, Bd3, Nf3 with a secure edge.} 8. Be5 Nd7 (8... f6 {is not fatal, but it is clearly weakening. Both} 9. Bg3 {and 9.Bxb8 Rxb8 Be2 are better for White.}) 9. Be2 {If White does not do this, Black will take on e5 and play ...g6, rerouting the knight to g7.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 g6 {No choice.} 11. Bxh5 gxh5 {This may look ugly, but it's quite an interesting line for Black. The pawns are not as weak as they seem, and the bishop pair has a ton of potential. A quick ...f6 will open the position. White must try to make something of his slight development lead and in fact he will also generally seek to open things up with an e4 break. Both sides will have to make decisions regarding where to put their king.} 12. O-O-O {This is by far the main move. White brings his rook to the d-file, while getting his king to safety. But the king may not be so safe on the queenside.} f6 13. exf6 $6 {An obvious move, but it's a poor choice.} Bxf6 {This is like the line StartFENr1bqk2r/pp2bp1p/2p5/3pP2p/8/2N1P3/PPQ2PPP/R3K1NR w KQkq - 0 12EndFEN 12.Nge2 f5 13.exf6 Bxf6 14.O-O-O?! The engine already considers White to be in big trouble.} 14. e4 O-O $1 {Black can just ignore White's central aggression.} ({Instead} 14... d4 {would forgive White and transpose to 13.e4.}) ({But} 14... Bg7 {is good too. For example} 15. exd5 O-O {! with ...Bf5 coming.} 16. dxc6 {?} Qg5+ {.}) 15. exd5 $2 {This loses, but it illustrates how things may go.} Bg5+ $1 16. Kb1 Bf5 17. Ne4 cxd5 {Black is winning, for example:} 18. f3 Qe7 $1 19. Rxd5 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 (20. fxe4 Rac8 {is even worse.}) 20... Qxe4+ 21. fxe4 Rf1+ 22. Kc2 Be3 {Black wins.} *

