1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qc2 {[%cal Rc8f5]} Nf6 7. e3 ({White does not want to spend time on} 7. h3 {, but he can't have everything.}) 7... Nh5 $1 {A very important move. We cannot just let White play h3, Bd3, Nf3 with a secure edge.} 8. Be5 Nd7 (8... f6 {is not fatal, but it is clearly weakening. Both} 9. Bg3 {and 9.Bxb8 Rxb8 Be2 are better for White.}) 9. Be2 {If White does not do this, Black will take on e5 and play ...g6, rerouting the knight to g7.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 g6 {No choice.} 11. Bxh5 gxh5 {This may look ugly, but it's quite an interesting line for Black. The pawns are not as weak as they seem, and the bishop pair has a ton of potential. A quick ...f6 will open the position. White must try to make something of his slight development lead and in fact he will also generally seek to open things up with an e4 break. Both sides will have to make decisions regarding where to put their king.} 12. O-O-O {This is by far the main move. White brings his rook to the d-file, while getting his king to safety. But the king may not be so safe on the queenside.} f6 13. e4 {This is White's only good move.} d4 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. exf6 {Another possibility.} Bxf6 15. Nge2 {This is rare but not bad.} O-O 16. Qd3 {A familiar idea. We can't take the knight.} Be6 $1 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 {The move order matters!} (17... Qxd4 {??} 18. Qg3+ {would be embarrassing.}) 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Rxf2 {Black has regained the pawn and has little to fear in the endgame.} *

