1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 {This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} (7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 {!} h5 10. Bd3 {!} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. Ng3 {This is the main move by a very wide margin.} Bg6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Instead} 8... Be6 {is playable threatening ...g5 , but} 9. Nh5 {is a bit of a nuisance.}) 9. Be2 {The main line.} Ngf6 (9... Nb6 {preventing h2-h4 for the moment, was Colovic's choice. This should also equalize. A well-known high level game went} 10. Be5 $5 Nf6 11. h4 h6 12. h5 Bh7 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kh8 16. Nf5 Nc4 {when Black has decent play, despite White's eventual victory in Nakamura-Aronian, London 2011.}) (9... Qb6 $5 10. Qd2 h5 {was played a couple of times by Geller, and this also looks sufficient; the play is just a bit murky.}) 10. h4 {This must be critical.} ({Of course both sides can castle too} 10. O-O O-O {with normal ideas like ... Re8 and ...Nb6. Black will generally meet f3 with ...c5.}) 10... h5 {So here we have a kind of 'tabiya' that can be reached in various ways. White has tried all kinds of semi-waiting moves here.} ({Instead} 10... h6 {is generally regarded as a concession, because} 11. h5 Bh7 12. Bd3 {gains the f5-square for White's knight.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O 14. Nf5 Re8 {is similar to Nakamura-Aronian mentioned above. Probably White is a little better, but it's not so clear. In practice White has gone for} 15. O-O-O {But 15.f3 looks more flexible to me, as the white king may be better on f2.}) 11. Bd3 {White embarks on a straightforward plan which has come up before. Here it has cost him a tempo though, as the bishop has moved twice.} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 g6 {Covering the f5-square, but} (12... O-O 13. Nf5 Re8 {looks quite playable too. We've come across positions like this on our way here, but with Black a tempo down here White lost a move with Be2-d3. We are very solid, and the h4-pawn could prove weak. If White goes for the typical f3, e4 plan, sometimes Black can play ...dxe4 and if White takes back with the pawn, we have ...Ng4. Black may also be able to ignore the central advance.}) 13. O-O-O (13. O-O O-O {intending ...Re8 and ... Nb6, hardly looks dangerous for Black.}) (13. Nge2 O-O {does not change much.}) (13. f3 {can also be met with} O-O {.}) 13... O-O 14. Kb1 ({Similar play could result after} 14. f3 b5 {.}) 14... Re8 15. f3 b5 $1 {Black has various ways to proceed on the queenside, and his play looks easier to me.} ({We avoid the passive} 15... Nf8 $6 16. e4 Ne6 {( 16...dxe4 17.Ngxe4! 17...Nd5 18.Be5 also looks dangerous.)} 17. Be5 {gave White the initiative in Kasimdzhanov-Grabarczyk, Germany 2013.}) ({After} 15... b5 $1 16. e4 b4 17. Nce2 dxe4 18. Nxe4 {(or 18.fxe4 Ng4 ) .} Rc8 {with the idea ...c5 and ...Qa5, Black has sufficient play.}) *

