1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. h3 {White is satisfied with chasing off Black's bishop and now looks to consolidate his space advantage and develop normally with Bd3, Qc2, Nge2, O-O-O and so on.} (8. Bd3 {This will generally transpose to the 8.h3 line.} Nd7 9. h3 {and we are in the 8.h3 line. White can vary with a couple of questionable moves: A) 9.Qf3?! g5 10.Bg3 Ngf6 11.h3 h5 is already favoring Black. B) 9.Bf5?! is another strange move. 9...Bxf5 10.gxf5 Ngf6 Black develops normally.}) 8... Nd7 {We develop a piece and await White's next move. Black will not be idle - the thematic ...h5 and ...g5 strikes are the source of counterplay.} 9. Bd3 {The main line. White can bring the knight to either f3 or e2 if we are idle, but we won't be.} g5 $5 (9... h5 {is a big alternative, which was Colovic's choice. We will consider this as an informational line. I decided to go with 9...g5, both for variety and because I slightly prefer it. It is also consisitent with our necessary answer to 9. Nf3.}) 10. Bg3 h5 {Now White can either try to hold his ground on g4, or release the tension.} 11. gxh5 {White chooses to open the position. I think this is more critical.} Ngf6 12. Be2 $6 {This looks too greedy. White holds the pawn, but is he going to ever develop the g1-knight? Now Qb6 has been seen in practice and it's good, but I still prefer:} (12. h4 {can be met with} g4 {.}) 12... Ne4 $146 {With ideas like ...Bb4, ...Qa5, and even ...f5. Black just looks better to me.} *

