1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 9. h5 ({This is the most popular move by far. The line goes} 9. Qb3 g5 10. Be5 f6 11. Bh2 Bxg4 {when} 12. Qxb7 {should ultimately leads to a perpetual check which is fine theoretically if you remember it all while Be2 which I consider to be more critical leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure. Colovic gives 8...Bxh4 and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw.}) {This is the older way of playing. White simply gains space.} 9... Nh6 $1 {A very original idea which is considered standard now. Karpov played in against Kasparov in their 1985 match, and its value was upheld in many games by QGD experts Vaganian and Lputian.} ({After} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 {Black is very cramped on the kingside.}) 10. Be2 {This is by far the main move. White protects the g4-pawn without further weakening his structure.} Nb6 {[%mdl 32768] The main line. White has to figure out how to develop. He would rather not play f3, but the g4-pawn requires attention.} 11. Nh3 {White develops and supports g4-g5 if Black goes for ...f5. This is the main line.} {(Instead 11.gxf5 was played in Fier-Bacrot, Tbilisi 2017. Bacrot took with the bishop and won, but I think 11...Nxf5 is stronger.) gxh6 gxf5 Bxf5 Bg4! Bxg4 Qxg4 when White has a small edge at best, but it's much less interesting for Black. We will see a similar, but improved version of this in our line.} g5 $1 ({Black cannot play} 11... f5 $2 12. g5 Nf7 13. Rg1 {when he is really suffering for lack of space.}) 12. hxg6 {White really must take.} hxg6 {Black has clear counterplay and has done very well in practice.} 13. Bg3 $2 {This was played in Nakamura - Aronian, Sao Paulo/Bilbao 2011. White won, but the move is actually a peculiar blunder!} Nxg4 $1 14. Bxg4 Qd7 $17 15. Z0 ({Very unusual! The h3-knight is essentially trapped. Black wins back the piece and remains up material. note that} 15. f3 f5 {does not really help.}) *

