1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {[%mdl 32768] This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked kind of, as we shall see, and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance. The most obvious move is} (10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 {?! is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went Nd7 Rfd1}) (10... Bxf3 {?!} 11. Bxf3 {Rb8 e3 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless,}) (10... Nc6 {!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. a3 $6 {White wants to prevent ...Nb4 for good, but he cannot completely ignore the attack on the d4-pawn.} Nxd4 $1 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Nxe6 {White is too clever for his own good.} Qd5 $146 {This is even stronger than} (13... fxe6 14. Kxg2 Nd5 15. Bd2 c5) 14. Nc3 Qxe6 15. Kxg2 c5 $15 {I really like the queen on e6, and Black has an active queenside pawn majority. He may already consider kicking the c3-knight with ...b4, grabbing control of the center squares.} *

