1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked kind of, as we shall see, and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance. The most obvious move is} (10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 {?! is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went Nd7 Rfd1}) (10... Bxf3 {?!} 11. Bxf3 {Rb8 e3 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless,}) (10... Nc6 {!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. Rd1 {The main move. White protects the d4-pawn and tries to discourage ...c5.} Nb4 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Qc1 {This is the only good square, but if White loses control the queen is not well placed and the a1-rook may have trouble getting into the game. White loses material after} (12. Qxc7 {?} Qxc7 13. Bxc7 Nc2 {and}) (12. Qd2 c5 {is too easy.}) 12... Rc8 (12... Nbd5 {is also possible, but we may as well wait to see if White wants to spend a tempo kicking us away.}) 13. Nc3 {It is important to shield the c-file.} Nbd5 {Black is ready for ...c5. White can only aspire for something if he can hold off this advance.} ({If you want to get off the beaten track,} 13... Qe8 $5 {is an idea, getting off of the d-file to prepare ...c5.}) 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Be3 {The only move to hold up ...c5.} (15. Ne5 c5 {and}) (15. Bg5 c5 {transposes to 14.Ne5 and 15.Bg5, respectively.}) (15. Be5 c5 16. dxc5 Rxc5 {with ...Qb6 coming, is comfortable for Black.}) 15... Ng4 {Black has also had success with} (15... c6 {I guess the idea is to continue with ...Qb6, but I think White is a little more comfortable after} 16. Ne1 {intending Nd3.}) 16. Ne1 {Sticking with the aforementioned plan.} Bxg2 17. Nxg2 {Instead} (17. Kxg2 Qd5+ 18. Nf3 Qe4 {actually transposes to the line 16.Ne5.}) 17... Qd5 $1 {We've seen this move before.} 18. h3 {Instead} (18. Nf4 {looks nice to gain a tempo, but after} Qe4 {...Nxe3 and ...c5 are coming. Black is doing well. Anand once faced}) (18. f3 {?!} Nxe3 19. Nxe3 Qb7 20. Kg2 c5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 {in Bruzon-Anand, Turin 2006. This is similar to our main line.}) 18... Nxe3 19. Qxe3 (19. Nxe3 $2 Qh5 {hits the h3- and e2-pawns.}) 19... c5 20. Nf4 Qf5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 $15 {Black is a bit better and managed to win in the illustrative game Carlsen-Anand, Mainz 2008, where the Indian great beat his opponent before the 'changing of the guard'.} *

