1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 ({This is by far the most popular move, with well over 3000 games in my filtered database, compared to under 1000 for both} 10. Bg5 {and}) (10. Bf4 {. I must say though, as a Catalan player myself, I never really cared for this line I always preferred StartFENrnbq1rk1/1pp1bppp/p3pn2/8/2pP4/5NP1/PPQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 0 8EndFEN 8.a4 to 8.Qxc4 .}) ({The big Idea is to play the bishop to a5 to both attack and pin the c7-pawn, but I always found this to be rather artificial looking. Also, at least compared to} 10. Bg5 {and}) (10. Bf4 {, Black has a great many choices here, and I think most of them are quite playable! We will focus on a modern solution, but one good thing about classical openings for Black is that it is easy to expand your lines, whether it be because of some small theoretical problem, or simply for variety's sake.}) 10... Be4 {This is the main move, but we will have a little twist. Here is a brief summary of some other lines:} (10... Nbd7 {is the only move I really do not like, as it really plays into White's hands.} 11. Ba5 Rc8 12. Nbd2 {with Nb3 in mind.}) (10... Nc6 11. e3 Nb4 12. Bxb4 Bxb4 13. a3 Bd6 14. Nbd2 {and White has both the e4- and b4-advances in hand.}) (10... Bd6 $5 {was Hammer's recommendation in his Chess24 course. This is a decent line, but White has about six different moves here to analyze, with different types of play...}) (10... Ra7 $5 {is a funny move, and this would be my second choice. The rook laterally supports the c7-pawn and there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ... Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course.} ({The engine also considers} 11... Nc6 {, as well as the unusual}) (11... Bd5 {, and even}) (11... h6 {as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking}) (11... Nbd7 {.}) ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Bg5 {With Ba5 prevented, White reverts to a Bg5 setup, where the thematic Bxf6 is always a possibility.} Nbd7 $146 {[%mdl 32768] In practice Black has grabbed the pawn with} (12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 {This is probably fine too, although White maintains some pressure after} 14. a4) 13. Nbd2 (13. Rd1 {would transpose to 12.Rd1.}) 13... Bd5 {As long as e2-e4 is not a threat, this is usually a good way of meeting Nb1-d2. With the knight on c3, it may take our bishop!} 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nb3 {This is consistent at least. We are not getting in ...c5 yet, but there is another typical way to react.} a5 $1 {White cannot play a4 himself, so we get ready to torment the knight. Right now the threat is ...a4, and if Nc5 we can take on f3 and d4.} 16. Rd1 a4 17. Nc5 Ne4 {Not the only move, but the play is clear.} 18. Nd3 {White tries to keep control of the important squares. Instead} (18. Nxe4 Bxe4 {is easy enough. Black will follow up with ...Qd5 and achieve the ...c5-break easily.}) 18... Rc8 19. Qe3 (19. a3 {? is too slow after} c5 {with the initiative.}) 19... a3 $1 {A nice move which disrupts White's position. Play is unclear, but Black has the initiative. Note that} (19... c5 {is not good:} 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Nf4 {and the pin is quite annoying.}) 20. b4 ({This looks the most logical. If instead} 20. b3 $2 Nc3 $1 {and the knight, which can be supported with ...b4, is a monster.}) 20... Nc3 21. Rd2 ({Similar, but worse for White, is} 21. Re1 Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Bg5 23. Nf4 Nd5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 25. Qxa3 Bxf4 26. gxf4 Qf6 27. Qe3 Rc4) 21... Bxf3 $1 22. Bxf3 Bg5 $1 {Suddenly White's queen is feeling some heat!} 23. Nf4 Nd5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 {Black has all the positional trumps, so White grabs a pawn.} 25. Qxa3 Bxf4 26. gxf4 Rc4 {White has so many weak pawns that Black can hardly have any problems here.} *

