 and this would be my second choice. The rook laterally supports the c7-pawn and there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ... Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course.} ({The engine also considers} 11... Nc6 {, as well as the unusual}) (11... Bd5 {, and even}) (11... h6 {as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking}) (11... Nbd7 {.}) ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any .. .Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768] Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} (12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Nc3 Bg6 {By now we have seen that this is often Black's best move. Avrukh only considered} (13... Bd5 14. Qc2 b4 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {and here he gave} 16. Bf4 {I am more discouraged by 16.Rdc1 although in either case, Black remains quite solid and White only has a small edge.}) 14. Bg5 {Again we have this typical move, but there's no knight coming to b3 to clamp down on the c5-square. Kramnik played this move however, so we must pay attention.} Rc8 15. a3 {The immediate} (15. Bxf6 {essentially loses a tempo.} Bxf6 {here 15...Nxf6 16.Ne5 Qb6 is also fine.} 16. Ne5 Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qc7 {and Black has no worries.}) 15... h6 {This looks the simplest to me. Black can also play} (15... a5 16. h4 h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 {. See the game Kramnik-So, Wijk aan Zee 2018.}) 16. Bxf6 (16. Bh4 {is possible, but after} Qc7 {There is no Bf4 to worry about and I am not sure what White has achieved. The bishop looks weird on h4.}) 16... Bxf6 {But not} (16... Nxf6 {? , as} 17. Ne5 {would be a big problem.}) 17. b4 {White prevents our ...c5 advance, but he had to part with his dark-squared bishop.} Qe7 {If we can get in ...e5 to remove the d4-pawn, then ...c5 may follow.} (17... Qb6 {is of similar value, but I wanted to show a nice tactical idea.}) 18. Qb2 $6 {This looks sensible as it connects the rooks.} c5 $1 (18... e5 {is good too, but this works!}) 19. bxc5 Nxc5 $1 {With the idea:} 20. dxc5 $2 Qxc5 {We win the c3-knight.} *

