1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 {This has been more popular than} (8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {[%mdl 32768] This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6 {and}) (8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qc2 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... Be4 {The c2-square is a good spot for White's queen so we continue the chase.} 12. Qd1 $5 {This has been tried by some very strong players. White allows ...c5 straight away, as the endgames that may arise are not so easy for Black.} h6 {Black forces matters.} (12... c5 {is more common, but I am not a big fan. This is covered as an informational line.}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nc3 {This looks more direct, but the d4-pawn will be loose.} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 {Here Black can play in typical fashion with 15...c6, but there are some little problems there. Instead we will focus on a more direct solution.} Qxd4 $1 {The cleanest equalizer} (15... c6 {is an almost automatic move, but I am going to recommend something else as our main choice.} 16. e3 a5 17. Qb3 Qc7 18. Rac1 {White is well developed and intends d4-d5 with the initiative.}) 16. Qxd4 (16. Bxb7 Ra7 {does not change much. After} 17. Bg2 Nd7 18. Ne4 c5 19. Rb1 Qxd1 20. Rfxd1 Rb8 21. b3 Be7 22. e3 c4 23. bxc4 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 Rc7 25. c5 Nxc5 26. Rc1 f5 27. Nxc5 Rxc5 {the game Aronian-So, Stavanger 2018 was soon drawn.}) 16... Bxd4 17. Bxb7 Ra7 18. Bf3 Nd7 19. Rfd1 c5 {Black's active pieces and play on the b-file make up for his split queenside pawns.} *

