1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 {This has been more popular than} (8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6 {and}) (8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} (11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 {! This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main but not only choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly. The typical}) (11... h6 {?! is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. dxc5 {This has been played a lot but it is quite harmless.} Nbd7 {We want to take on c5 with the knight.} 13. Nc3 (13. b4 {?! is not a good idea. White's structure is unstable, and this is easily exploited with} a5 {when Black easily regains the pawn while taking over the initiative.}) 13... Nxc5 14. Qe3 {Now the positional threat of Bxf6 is easy enough to deal with.} Qa5 {This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives.} ({The natural} 14... Rc8 {also looks fine.} 15. Rfd1 {(Or 15.Nxd5 Nxd5 16.Bxe7 Qxe7 17.Qa3 a5 ) .} h6 {when Black does not have to fear the isolated pawn after} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxd5 exd5 {This is similar to 15.Bxf6.}) ({Even the rare} 14... Bxf3 $5 15. Bxf3 Qa5 {is very solid. White has the bishop pair, but Black's minor pieces are all good.}) 15. Nxd5 {White usually plays this, hoping for a tiny edge, but with today's tools it's pretty easy to neutralize.} Nxd5 16. Qa3 {The point of White's play. The c5-knight is under pressure and Black must watch for b2-b4.} Bxg5 17. Nxg5 h6 18. Rfc1 {This is the main move} Nd7 {Around here the engine chills out and realizes that White has nothing.} 19. Ne4 {There are other moves too, but nothing to be too concenred with.} (19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Rd1 Qxg5 21. Rxd7 b5 {is easy.}) (19. Qd6 N7f6 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Rac8 {and White's pressure dries up. We are not so worried about an isolated d-pawn because White's e-, b-, and a-pawns are all similarly weak.}) 19... Rac8 {Black is fine here and actually has a plus score in practice.} *

