ge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} Qa5 {The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} 14. Ne5 {Very direct.} Bxg2 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Kxg2 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 $5 {This is a natural enough move, although the play will become surprisingly complex. Instead} (16... h6 {may be simpler, but it's less interesting.} 17. Bf4 {or 17.Bxf6 Bxf6 18.Qe4 Qc7} Nc6 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Qc4 c5 {has seen all draws.}) 17. Qc4 $5 {A piece sacrifice. We must take, as there is not a good way to develop now.} Qxe5 18. Rxd8+ Bxd8 19. Bf4 ({A necessity. The immediate} 19. Qc8 {?} Qc7 {just leaves us a piece up.}) 19... Qa5 20. Qc8 {This is the point of White's play. The queen ties down everything on our first rank.} Qb6 {Threatening ... Qc6+} 21. f3 $1 {Now Rd1 is a huge threat. alternative:} e5 $5 {Various analysts have considered this to be bad, but it's not clear at all. Black can also play} (21... g5 22. a5 {!} Nc6 {!} 23. Qxa8 Qxb2 {as in the game Leko-Karjakin, Dortmund 2012.}) 22. Bxe5 Nc6 23. Qxa8 Nxe5 24. Rd1 Nc6 {Black is ready to consolidate with ...g6. The defenses are stretched too thin after} (24... Ned7 {?} 25. Rxd7 Nxd7 26. Nd5 Qa5 27. b4 {!}) 25. b4 $1 {White must keep some momentum going.} g6 $1 {Anyway. We must avoid} (25... Qxb4 {when} 26. Rxd8+ Nxd8 27. Qxd8+ Qf8 28. Qc7 {is highly unpleasant.}) 26. b5 axb5 27. axb5 Nd4 28. Na4 Qd6 {Everything is holding together, and there does not seem to be a way to make Black fall over.} 29. Nc5 {White is trying to be tricky, but we have a good answer.} Qe7 $1 {Hitting the e2-pawn.} 30. Rxd4 $6 Qxe2+ 31. Kg1 ({If} 31. Kh3 Qf1+ 32. Kh4 {and Black keeps checking:} g5+ 33. Kxg5 Qc1+ {picking up the c5-knight and leading to mate.}) 31... Qe3+ 32. Kg2 Qxd4 {We got the rook but White can regain a piece.} 33. Nxb7 Qd2+ 34. Kg1 $2 (34. Kh3 {is also met with} Kg7 {!}) 34... Kg7 $1 35. Nxd8 {After} (35. Qxd8 Nd5 {White has to deal with mate threats and discovered attacks.}) 35... Nd5 {Despite the extra pawn, White will have to play well to survive.} *

