ge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is fairly simple and safe alternative to our main line with} 13... Qa5 {.}) 14. Nxd4 {This has been played in the most games, by far.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {Instead} (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Kxg2 {transpose to the last line.}) 15... Nbd7 16. Qf3 {White has done pretty well with this move, but I do not see any real problems for Black here. Other moves are easier to deal with:} (16. f4 {?!} Rc8 17. e4 h6 {or}) (16. e4 Bb4) 16... h6 $5 {A rare move. Black not only ignores the attack on the b7-pawn, but he appears to just lose a tempo.} ({Black has also tried} 16... Qb8 17. Bf4 Qe8) ({And} 16... Qb6 17. a5 Qa7 {but I find these queen wiggles to be awkward.}) ({The most common move is} 16... Rb8 17. Bxf6 $5 {The flashy 17.Nf5 leads to nothing after 17...exf5 18.Bxf6 Bxf6 19.Qxf5 Bxc3 20.bxc3 Qf6 21.Qxd7 Qxc3} Bxf6 18. Ne4 Be7 {is almost the same thing as our main line, but after} 19. Nf5 $5 Rc8 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qa3 Qxa3 22. Rxa3 {the lack of ...h6 could lead to bank rank problems, and thus the computer sees chances for White in the endgame.}) 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 Be7 19. Nf5 Rc8 $1 {Black has used the extra tempo by playing ...Rc8 in one move instead of ...Rb8-c8 on ...h6, which prove to be of some use. Here} (19... exf5 {?} 20. Qxf5 {just wins back the piece leaving White with a good extra pawn.}) 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qa3 Qxa3 22. Rxa3 {So it's the same as the line above in the note to Black's 16th, but here we have that beautiful move ...h6 played.} Ne5 {No back rank stuff so Black should be fine here.} *

