1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges. The natural} (10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 {and White will prepare e2-e4. A thematic idea is}) (10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces. A popular alternative is}) (10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Qc1 {This was recommended by Avrukh in his second edition of his Grandmaster Repertoire book on the Catalan, so not surprisingly it became the most popular choice for White.} a5 {[%mdl 32768] Following the typical script. A solid yet rather passive alternative is} (11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 {intending ...e5.}) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Rd1 Nb4 14. Bg5 {Avrukh's recommendation is the most interesting try.} h6 15. Bh4 {An important point in White's play. The pin is maintained for the moment.} (15. Bxf6 Qxf6 {is no problem at all. If} 16. e4 e5 {.}) 15... Be7 $5 {Now ...g5 is on. Of course Black cannot play} (15... g5 {??} 16. Nxg5) 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. e4 {It was considered worse for Black to have the pawn on h6 here - he cannot play ...g6, and White's h4, g4-g5 could be dangerous. It seems that Black is ok here however, and in more than one way. As is often the case, White comes up with some ideas, but given enough time, Black will solve the problems.} Qe8 $5 {This is odd-looking, but Black intends ...Rd8 and this move has held firm in correspondence games. One point is that White's typical move is not very good.} 18. Qf4 $6 {This runs into difficulties.} Nc2 19. Rac1 $2 {This is bad, but what else?!} Nxd4 $1 20. Nxd4 Bxd4 {when White cannot play} 21. Rxd4 $2 e5 {and Black wins.} *

