1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Nc3 {Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different. After the natural developing move} (10... Nbd7 {? White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. Bg5 {The future of White's bishop is unclear, so White looks for further exchanges, hoping that his apparently better pawn structure will give him some chances.} Rb8 {Grabbing the half-open file. Now White has some choice.} 14. a5 {This can also arise after 13.a5 Rb8 14.Bg5.} Rb4 {An active move.} 15. Na2 {A typical idea to hit the rook.} (15. Ra4 $6 Qb8 {does not help White.}) (15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Na2 Rb5 {transposes.}) 15... Rb5 {Hitting both the bishop and the a5-pawn.} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxc4 ({If White plays} 17. Nc3 Rb4 18. Na2 {we can repeat moves or play} Rb8 $5 {with the idea} 19. Qxc4 Qd5 $1) 17... Qd5 $1 {I like this immediate centralization. Black is already fine here, but in practice White has gone for:} 18. Qxd5 $6 {Correcting Black's pawn structure is not always a bad idea if White can make something of the half-open c-file, but here it does not work out well.} cxd5 19. b4 {Saving the b2-pawn while trying to clamp down on c5, but the b4-pawn will prove to be weaker than Black's c7-pawn. The a2-knight has seen better days.} Be7 {Black is clearly better here. There is a clear plan to play ...Bd6, ... Rfb8 or ...Ra8 to protect the a6-pawn in the event of Rc1-c6, and then he can bring the king to d7.} *

