1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is} (7... c5 {which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. dxc5 Qc7 9. Nxc4 Qxc5 {Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b3 {This move is uncommon and it scores poorly, but it is not bad at all. It was recommended by Ipatov in his book Unconventional Approaches to Modern Chess.} cxb3 {[%mdl 32768] This is the most ambitious.} (11... Rd8 {is also good. It is probably less to learn, but leads to a lot of simplifications. We will check this as an informational line.}) 12. Qxb3 {The main line. White gets his queen off of the d-file.} Rd8 {Black has also done well with} (12... Qd7 13. Ba3 Rd8 {rather than 13...Re8 14.Rd1 Ba6 15.Nc3 Nd5 16.Rd2 Rab8 17.Qc2 Nxc3 18.Qxc3 with an edge for White in Banusz-Nisipeanu, Austria 2018.} 14. Nc3 Ba6 {transposing to the next note.}) 13. Ba3 Qe8 $1 {My preference. The d8-rook stays active, and ... e5 is a possibility.} (13... Qd7 14. Nc3 Ba6 {intending ...Nd5 should also be ok.}) 14. Rd1 Ba6 {We develop and attack the e2-pawn. White should play d5 when e4 is unclear.} (14... e5 {is also possible. If} 15. dxe5 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 Bh3 {! with the idea} 17. exf6 {?} Qe4 18. f3 Qe3+ 19. Kh1 Qf2 20. Qg1 Qxe2 {and White is in trouble.}) 15. Nc3 Nd5 {It's very typical in all of these 8. Bxc6 lines for Black to seek an exchange of knights. The slightly worse pawn structure is less troublesome without a blockading knight, and the opposite colored bishops will favor the side with the initiative - hopefully us - while also providing some drawing margin in the endgame.} 16. e4 {After} (16. Nxd5 {?} exd5 {our pawn structure is optically worse, but our king is safer and our bishop is much more active - White's bishop has little to do.}) 16... Rab8 {We may as well gain a tempo. Instead} (16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 {may favor White a bit, as the only real imbalance is the pawn structure.}) 17. Qc2 Nb4 {Always played, but I think here} (17... Nxc3 {makes more sense as we gained ... Rb8 for free. After} 18. Qxc3 Qa4 {either ...e5 or ...f5 offer opportunities for counterplay.}) 18. Bxb4 Rxb4 19. d5 {Ipatov gave this as unclear. Fair enough, but let's look a little more.} e5 {This fixes the structure which seems to help White, but the knight does not have a great square. The engine also likes the non-committal} (19... h6 {!?}) 20. Qc1 {White tries to improve the position of his queen.} Rc4 {The immediate} (20... Rd6 {is also reasonable.} 21. Qe3 Qb8 22. Rab1 h6 {was unclear in Hilby-Brown, Las Vegas 2017.}) 21. Qa3 Rd6 {Black combines attack and defence.} 22. Rab1 h5 $1 {Black has his weaknesses covered and creates counterplay on the kingside. Blocking with h4 is possible, but White will have to watch out for ...g5 at some point.} 23. Rb4 h4 {Black had good counterplay in Duda - Deac, Chennai 2022.} *

