1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is} (7... c5 {which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. dxc5 Qc7 9. Nxc4 Qxc5 {Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8. Nxc6 {This is almost as popular as} (8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {[%mdl 32768] Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 {This is the main line. We get quite the unusual pawn structure.} Bxa3 10. bxa3 {Lovely, isn't it? The play is quite interesting. White has the bishop pair, but Black is often very active. We must always keep in mind the pawn break ... c5, and sometimes ...e5 as well.} Ba6 {Black protects his frontal c-pawn, which is an asset now. There is also latent pressure on the f1-a6 diagonal.} 11. Bg5 $6 {White willingly parts with his greatest long-term asset: the bishop pair.} h6 {I will give this as the main line as it's direct and it was play by Karpov in a game that made an impression on me long ago. I confess that according to the engine, 11...Rb8 is at least as strong.} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Bxc6 {Levelling the material, but White's double a-pawns are worse than Black's c-pawns.} Rab8 14. Qa4 Rb6 {This was Antunes-Karpov, Tilburg 1994. Black is much better. Eventually Black got in ...c5, and the strong c4-pawn was essentially an extra pawn.} *

