1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is} (7... c5 {which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. dxc5 Qc7 9. Nxc4 Qxc5 {Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8. Nxc6 {This is almost as popular as} (8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active. Moves other than Na3 are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.} 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 {The modern treatment. It looks funny to block in the c1-bishop, but the queen is headed to a5. Although the move was not new, it was revived in 2016 and then interest in 8.Nxc6 heated up.} Rb8 {[%mdl 32768] We grab the open file. Black should avoid the rash} (11... c3 {?!} 12. Qxc3 Bxe2 13. Re1 Bb5 14. a4 {!} Bxa4 15. Qb4 Bb5 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 {and White wins an exchange, as seen in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ... Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6. We will also consider} (12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 {?! is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 {Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} (14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Rfb1 {This is supposed to be rather clever compared to 15.Rab1, but ultimately it may not matter much.} Rxb1+ $5 {This is simplest, but} (15... Rb6 {is good as well. We'll consider it as an alternative line.}) 16. Rxb1 {Watch out for Qxa6!} h6 $5 {Luft.} 17. Bc5 {This move is always played, but it's probably not very good.} Rd5 $1 18. Qb4 {Relatively best. For e4 ?! Rd3 see the game Nisipeanu-Huschenbeth, Austria 2019. The c-pawn is ready to roll. After} (18. Bxd5 {?!} cxd5 19. Bxa7 Nd7 {Black is only down one exchange! What a luxury. 20.Bc5 e5}) 18... e5 {Black intends ...Qf5 and maybe ...e4.} (18... Rd8 {!? with the idea ...Nd5 and ...c3 looks good too.}) *

