1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {[%mdl 32768] We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. Ne5 {This has always been the main line of 7.Na3, and it's always been considered to be just fine for Black.} Bc6 10. Nxc6 {White has to go for this, but it helps us develop.} Nxc6 11. Bb2 {The main line.} Nd5 {The knight is strong here, and it can go to b6 to protect the c4-pawn. White will also have to watch for ...c3 now.} ({Originally I planned to recommend} 11... Qd6 $5 {which worked well in the old game Alburt-Geller, New York 1990, but after some digging I ultimately decided to go with the most popular continuation.}) 12. Rc1 Nb6 {Black clings to the pawn and is ready to connect his rooks. After} (12... c3 13. Ba1 {! White will play e3 or e4 and soon eat the pawn. The immediate}) (12... b5 {is untried, but playable. The engines say it's about equal after} 13. e4 Nb6 14. d5 exd5 15. exd5 Ne7 16. Qg4 Ng6 {or} 17. Qd4 f6 {but White's activity concerns me.}) 13. e3 Qe7 {Honestly I think that various queen moves here are about about equivalent. This was Wesley So's choice, but he questioned whether} (13... Qd7 {could have been more accurate because it allows for ...Ne7. I think it's also useful to have the d-file open for the rooks.}) (13... Qd6 {is also totally legitimate. Both this square and e7 allow the queen to keep an eye on the queenside a bit too.}) 14. Qc2 Rfe8 {So said that this was a mouse slip! But it's a good move...} (14... Rfd8 {is also good, intending to double rooks on the d-file.}) 15. Rfd1 Rad8 {I like this natural, centralized setup. Black still may double rooks, control the light squares with ...f5, and the ...e5 break will be a strong possibility. It's not easy for White to do anything constructive that does not create weaknesses.} (15... h6 {!? and there's still not much for White to do, while Black will double his rooks on the d-file soon.}) ({We will win back the pawn, but} 15... e5 $1 16. Qxc4 exd4 {is certainly fine for Black.}) (15... h6 16. Rd2 Red8 17. Rcd1 f5 {was very comfortable for Black in Dubov-So, chess24 rapid 2021.}) *

