1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nc3 {This move has always been around, but in 2018 Fabiano revived an uncommon interpretation of White's play against Hikaru Nakamura. This started a revolution of sorts, and White scored heavily. Nowadays it is one more main line to deal with, rather than a 'harmless sideline'.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768] We will not be scared of of our normal plans. From White's perspective,} (6... c6 {has to be considered, with an early committal to Nc3 in a Closed Catalan.}) 7. Ne5 {The point of White's play. It looks similar to the 6.0-0 dxc4 7.Ne5 line, but the switch of 6.0-0 for 6.Nc3 greatly changes things. This was not appreciated for a long time.} (7. O-O {StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN transposes the to 6.O-O dxc4 7.Nc3 line.}) (7. Qa4 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 {leaves the c3-knight misplaced. Black will play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5 with an easy game.}) 7... Nc6 $1 {Perhaps this is what white players want to see, but I am stubborn.} ({Theoretically,} 7... c5 {holds up just fine, but after} 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White has played six! moves here with some success. Although Black is ok, he must play precisely while White is generally playing for two results.}) ({A curious idea is} 7... Qd6 {The queen may head to a6, while ...Rd8 is facilitated. It still looks a bit artificial to me, and you can look up the game Nisipeanu-Nakamura, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 for further discouragement.}) 8. Bxc6 {The best move.} ({Instead} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. O-O {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.0-0 dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3 .}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Nxd5 {It certainly looks questionable to open the e-file.} exd5 14. Qc5 {The sober move, but Black's game still looks easier.} Qe6 $1 {Of course we avoid the exchange of queens.} 15. Be3 Ba6 {Now White can't castle without dropping the e2-pawn.} 16. Rc1 a4 (16... Rfb8 {looks good too.}) 17. Qc6 {Taking on c7 would be too much, as Black would take control of the c-file.} Qe4 18. O-O {White didn't have much choice at this point.} Bxe2 19. Rfe1 Bg4 20. Bd2 Qxd4 21. Bc3 Qc4 22. Qxc4 dxc4 {By now Black is up a pawn. It's still just level though, and the game Piorun-Van Foreest, Paris 2022 was soon drawn.} *

