{So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3 .}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Bd2 {The most popular, the choice of the engines, and the most complicated.} Ba6 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Qc5 $1 {The only challenging move. Both} (14. Qb3 Rfb8 15. Qc2 c5 {and}) (14. Qa4 Rfb8 {hitting the b2-pawn and planning ...c5, give Black great play.}) 14... Qd7 {Dodging the queen trade and planning ...Rfb8, activating everything. We still have a comfortable lead in development, and White's queen position is a bit sketchy. In his Chess24 course, Jon Ludvig Hammer points out that Black should really be able to draw after} (14... Qxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 a4 {intending ...Bb5 and ...f6, but White can certainly play on for a long time, and there's no upside for us here.}) 15. f3 {White tries to control some light squares and makes an escape for his king.} Rfb8 {Black is very active and we start with hitting the b2-pawn.} 16. Rb1 {White protects the b-pawn without commiting his pawn structure.} Rb6 $1 {The same idea as we saw before.} 17. Qa3 {The immediate retreat is easy to deal with.} Nb4 {Black is winning back the pawn immediately.} 18. Kf2 {Best, under the circumstances.} Qxd4+ 19. Be3 {Did we blunder?} Qxe3+ $1 {A small combination.} 20. Kxe3 Nc2+ {We regain the queen and secure at least equality, as White's pawn will be doubled.} *

