1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. White has three ways to play here, but really only 7.0-0 and 7.dxc5 have any bite. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on the type of position Black prefers. One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.0-0 dxc4, here} (6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because White has} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, 6.Qc2 does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play}) (6... c6 {but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. O-O {The main line.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Nxd4 {Now Black has some choice in the direction of play.} Na6 $5 {This rare move looks like a good practical solution. It was played by Wei Yi against Carlsen, and also recommended by Hammer in his Chess24 course. The main line is} (8... Nc6 {, but after} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {it's like a reversed Grunfeld. One discouraging possibility is} 10. Rd1 Ba6 11. b3 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd2 {intending a3 and b4. I prefer White here. Black can also play}) (8... e5 9. Nf5 d4 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with a reversed Benoni of sorts. After} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd2 Nc6 {Black is totally fine, but White's play is straightforward starting with} 14. c5 {which scores a very healthy 65%. With 8. ..Na6 Black eyes ...Nb4 while maintaining the possibility of ...e5.}) 9. cxd5 Nb4 $1 {After the compliant} (9... Nxd5 10. Rd1 {gives White the typical Catalan position that he was hoping for.}) 10. Qb3 {The most logical.} e5 $1 {The point of Black's play. We are actually making room for ...Be6.} 11. Nb5 Nbxd5 12. Rd1 {Pinning the knight certainly looks critical, but Black has enough resources, as we shall see.} Be6 13. e4 {White has little choice, as he is behind in development and the b5-knight is misplaced.} Nf4 {With this move we can force equality. We will also consider Hammer's suggestion} (13... Nc7 $5 {as an alternative.}) 14. Rxd8 Ne2+ 15. Kf1 Bxb3 16. Rxa8 (16. Rxf8+ Kxf8 17. Kxe2 Bc4+ {doesn't really change anything.}) 16... Rxa8 {White can't take everything, and his own bishop is hanging on c1.} 17. Kxe2 (17. axb3 Nxc1 18. Rxa7 Rxa7 19. Nxa7 Nxb3 {is also equal.}) 17... Bc4+ {The point - Black wins back the piece with total equality.} *

