1. Nf3 {Here we have White's most flexible first move. I have played it myself hundreds of times. White may transpose to mainstream 1.d4 openings, and English Opening, or maintain a Reti flavor. Black has to be aware and ready for all kinds of transpositions. We don't want to get tricked!} ({White can also start with} 1. c4 {when for this repertoire we will play} e6 {and 2...d5 against anything. There is also a great course on Chessable 1...c5 :} 2. Nf3 {(Or 2.g3 d5 3.Bg2 Nf6 4.Nf3 )} d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {when} 6. b3 {reaches our main positions in the Neo-Catalan.}) 1... d5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({We will use this first move. There is nothing wrong with} 1... Nf6 {first though.} 2. g3 d5 {or} 3. c4 e6 {and we will be on track.}) 2. c4 ({Another move order is} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 {( 5.d3 is the King's Indian Attack).} O-O 6. b3 {.}) 2... e6 ({This is what fits in our repertoire. I think that objectively,} 2... d4 {should be quite strong, but it leads to a totally different kind of game, has a lot of theory, and perhaps most importantly, does not help us if White plays 1.c4.}) 3. g3 {Of course if White plays d4 at any point in the next few moves, we will just be in a normal Catalan.} ({White could also start with} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2) ({Instead} 3. e3 {is the 'e3 Poison' which we will get to later.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {The Neo-Catalan. It looks like a quiet system, but it has a lot of venom. White is quite flexible, and he may take on d5 at any point or meet ...c5 with d4, in both cases opening the position. We have to be ready.} b6 {This fits well with our repertoire.} ({This is not the same as the Catalan} 6... dxc4 7. bxc4 {just strengthens White's center and leaves us with a problematic c8-bishop.}) ({The immediate} 6... c5 {is well met with} 7. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {( 7...exd5 8.d4 is a Tarrasch QGD - not so easy for Black).} 8. Bb2 {with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. d4 $5 {Shankland's suggestion in Lifetime Repertoires: Neo-Catalan - Part 1. This is an unusual and dangerous move order.} (7. Bb2 {is the main line.}) (7. Nc3 {has no important independent significance.} Bb7 {when} 8. d4 {is back into the 7.d4 line. And 8.e3 c5 9.Bb2 just reaches the other main lines.}) (7. cxd5 {will also transpose elsewhere after} Nxd5 8. Bb2 {(Or 8.d4 Bb7 9.Bb2 )} Bb7 {is the 8.cxd5 line.}) 7... Bb7 8. Nc3 ({Here} 8. Bb2 {is not very good. This will be considered via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2P5/1P3NP1/P2PPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7EndFEN 7.Bb2 Bb7 8.d4 , which we will see later.}) ({While} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bb2 {is the 8.cxd5 line.}) 8... Nbd7 {Now we are ready for ...c5.} ({We would like to play} 8... dxc4 $6 9. bxc4 c5 {to give White the hanging pawns, but} 10. d5 exd5 11. Nh4 {is good for White. This is a well-known idea in the Queen's Indian Defense.}) ({If} 8... c5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Ne1 {we will end up with an isolated d-pawn. It's not so bad but I prefer to avoid this with the bishop on b7 .}) 9. Bb2 Rc8 $5 {A bit of a waiting move. This should always be useful. We may still play ...c5 but we are not committed to it yet.} ({Not} 9... dxc4 10. bxc4 c5 11. d5 {with a huge advantage for White.}) ({White's novel idea is to meet the typical} 9... c5 {with} 10. Ne1 $5 {This is an idea of Ding Liren, which is recommended by Shankland. This pins the d5-pawn and thus it's hard to avoid getting a worse structure. The engines think Black is fine but it's not so easy.}) 10. Ne1 {White can still play this way, but we have not played ...c5 yet.} ({If} 10. Rc1 {Black can still wait with} Re8 $5) 10... Re8 $5 {Another flexible move.} 11. Nd3 {This lessens White's control of d4.} c5 $1 12. cxd5 $6 cxd4 13. Nb5 Nxd5 {Now White should bail out and equalize.} 14. Nxd4 (14. Nxa7 $6 {is too adventurous} Ra8 15. Nb5 e5 {.}) 14... Nc5 {Black has clearly equalized.} *

