{with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces usually our knights, avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. cxd5 {We always have to consder this capture.} Nxd5 {We will take with a piece when there's no reason not to. Certainly} (8... exd5 {is playable. After} 9. d4 {it's a Queen's Indian of some sort.}) 9. Nc3 {White defers the central advance, but it does not change much.} c5 10. d4 (10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. d4 {transposes, as does}) (10. Rc1 Nd7 11. d4 Rc8 12. Nxd5 Bxd5) 10... Nd7 {We want to recapture with the knight.} 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Rc1 (12. dxc5 Nxc5 {is obviously fine for Black.}) 12... Rc8 13. Qd3 {Playing for e4, but this is usually not anything to worry about.} (13. dxc5 {can be met with the obvious} Nxc5 {While 13...Rxc5!? clearing a path for the queen to a8*, is also good.}) 13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 ({Other moves are also harmless:} 14. Nxd4 Nc5 {or}) (14. Qxd4 Bf6) 14... Nc5 15. Qc3 $5 ({After} 15. Qe3 Nd7 $1 {we start trading pieces on the c-file.}) 15... Nxb3 $5 ({I like this forcing continuation, but} 15... Ne4 16. Qb2 f6 {is also fine.}) 16. Qxc8 Nxc1 17. Qxc1 {Did we miscount pieces?} Bxf3 $1 {We regain the piece!} *

