1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!? If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6 {and Colovic's suggestion}) (6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. e5 Nd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Nf1 Bb7 {We checked the traditional move} (10... a5 {as an informational line.}) 11. h4 {This is the main line. White has various attacking ideas on the kingside. We will seek our fortune on other parts of the board.} Qc7 12. Bf4 Rfc8 13. N1h2 {This square is more flexible as the knight can be in the way on e3.} Qd8 14. Ng4 (14. h5 h6 {will be considered via the move order 13.h5.}) 14... Bf8 {This may not be strictly necessary, but it allows us to meet h5 with ...h6 without fearing any sacrifices on h6.} 15. c4 {This was play by Karjakin. White can still play} (15. h5 {when} h6 {again reaches lines covered via the 13.h3 move order.}) 15... Ne7 $5 {This looks preferable to} (15... bxc4 16. dxc4 d4 17. Ng5 {! , heading for e4.}) 16. b3 {After} (16. cxb5 a6 {!} 17. bxa6 Bxa6 {the d3-pawn is weak and Black has open lines on the queenside.}) 16... Bc6 17. h5 h6 {This was Karjakin-Dominguez Perez, Khanty-Mansiysk 2015. White's pawn moves have given Black clear targets for counterplay.} *

