1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!) but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bb5+ (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7. This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like 5...Bd6 and 6.dxc5 , but there are four main ways White can play: StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Nbd2 will be met with 6...Bxf4 with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6. StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Ne5 will be met with 6...Qc7 , delaying ...O-O StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Bb5+ will be met with 6...Nc6}) {A logical move, as we have no choice.} 6... Nc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Bxc6+ {This is the only move that causes Black any concern. Other moves are either harmless or very risky.} bxc6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Qa4 {Rather than pawn hunting, White seeks a positional edge. The main idea of this move is to play Qa3, pinning the c5-pawn. If the pin holds, White will conquer the important c5-square.} Nd7 $5 {Overprotecting the critical ...c5 square.} (9... cxd4 {avoiding the pin.} 10. cxd4 O-O 11. Qa3 Qxa3 12. Nxa3 {White's knight is not well placed, but Black has trouble achieving ...c5.} Rb8 13. b3 a5 {with the idea ...a4 is equal according to the engine, but I don't like it.}) 10. Qa3 {( 10.Qa3 Ne4 11.Nfd2 e5 is Black's point.) 10...cxd4 11.cxd4 c5 12.Qa3 and now Black has to play 12...Qa6! 13.Qxa6 Bxa6 This is holding for Black, but it requires further accuracy. The pin is White's main plan. He could also delay it with} (10. O-O a5 $1 11. Qa3 Ke7 $1 {with similar play.}) 10... Ke7 $146 ({I like this move, protecting the queen and welcoming an endgame.} 10... Qe7 {has a similar idea, but I want to connect the rooks quickly. The immediate}) (10... a5 {is also possible, likely with ...Ke7 next.}) 11. Ne5 ({Logical, but not too much trouble. Black's idea is well illustrated after} 11. O-O $6 cxd4 {when Black's king will soon be well placed for the endgame on d6.}) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. O-O ({Black is again doing well after} 13. Qxc5+ Qd6 {.}) 13... a5 {Black is active here and welcomes the endgame now. If White could get his knight to c5, he'd be doing well, but that's not happening.} *

