1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!) but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7. This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like 5...Bd6 and 6.dxc5 , but there are four main ways White can play: StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Nbd2 will be met with 6...Bxf4 with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6. StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Ne5 will be met with 6...Qc7 , delaying ...O-O StartFENrnbqk2r/pp3ppp/3bpn2/2pp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 1 6EndFEN 6.Bb5+ will be met with 6...Nc6}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 {Another move order is} (7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it! Again,} (7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 {!}) 8. Bd3 {This is White's most common choice. It does not strike me as being very dangerous though.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Black can play ...e5 at will, or completely development with ...b6. Black cannot play} 8... Nc6 {?} 9. dxc5 $1 {stealing a pawn.}) 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {This is still equal, but Black scores around 70%! Although the London can be a serious weapon, many players still employ it 'to be safe'. Black's score shows that these relatively simple positions still offer plenty of scope to outplay an unambitious opponent!} *

