1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3. Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} (3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ...h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({A) Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 . If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5 .}) ({B) Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and c6 are both very solid.}) ({C) Jones gives the King's Indian style with} 3... g6) ({D) Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd2 {A natural, but rather poor move. The engines already give Black an edge - and in more than one way! And it's only move four.} e6 ({Black can also play} 4... h6 5. Bh4 {and then} e6 {In most of the lines Black can throw in ...h6. We will avoid doing this on move four just to be consistent, but it's rarely going to be a mistake.}) 5. f3 {This is White's most common move, but it doesn't look very good. It just weakens the position too much, and Black is the one getting ther initiative.} c5 $1 {Black is already better.} 6. dxc5 ({A)} 6. e3 {is very meek. Why is the pawn on f3?} Be7 {with typical ideas like ...h6 and ...a6, ...b5.}) ({B)} 6. e4 {transposes to the main line after} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bc5 8. Qd2) 6... Bxc5 ({Flinging in} 6... h6 {immediately is good too.}) 7. e4 h6 $1 8. Bxf6 {The only move to be concerned with. If this was problematic, it would be a good argument for playing ...h6 earlier, but Black is doing great. White is going to be suffering on the dark squares. A common theme whenever White plays f2-f3.} ({A)} 8. Bh4 {walks into a typical tactic:} Nxe4) ({B)} 8. Be3 dxe4 {leaves White with a bad pawn structure.}) 8... Nxf6 9. Bb5+ {This check is the reason some will play ...a6 early. Here it's no problem.} Bd7 ({Even} 9... Kf8 {intending ...a6, is good.}) 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. exd5 {Again aiming to play against an isolated pawn.} O-O $1 {We have been denied the bishop pair, but our development is even faster now as our rooks are connected.} ({The immediate} 11... Rd8 {is also strong.}) 12. dxe6 $2 Qxe6+ 13. Qe2 {Blocking with a knight would be met the same way.} Be3 $1 {What a bishop! White won't be able to castle anywhere. Black's rooks will just come to the center.} 14. Nd1 {Hoping to evict the intruder.} Nd5 $1 {Another will take its place. White is totally busted.} *

