1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3. Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} (3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves. Here} (3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5. Shankland's suggestion}) (3... Bf5 {and c6 are both very solid. Jones gives the King's Indian style}) (3... g6 {Finally there is the direct}) (3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. e3 {This is solid, but passive.} e6 {[%mdl 32768]} 5. Nf3 c5 {White has to play well to equalize. Black can throw in} (5... h6 {but there's no hurry. Svidler likes}) (5... a6 {!? preparing ... c5. Later we'll see why, but it's not strictly necessary.}) 6. Be2 {The main move. This is White's most solid choice, but clearly Black is not under any pressure. We don't really have to analyze} (6. dxc5 Bxc5 {as this just helps our development and we can play normal moves.}) 6... Be7 7. O-O O-O {It's not so easy for White to find a plan here. He cannot play e4 or c4.} 8. Qd2 {White connects the rooks before making his move. The immediate} (8. Ne5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. f4 f6 {! is similar. Here White has not completed his development either, so we can hit back immediately.}) 8... a6 {We want to gain space on the queenside.} 9. a4 b6 {It looks a little like some of our London setups, but White's knight on c3 limits his options.} 10. Ne5 {The only real plan.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. f4 Bb7 {We will complete our development before opening the position. We want our rooks connected.} (13... f6 {?} 14. Nxd5 {would be embarrassing.}) 14. Bf3 Rad8 {It's useful to oppose the queen, but we really want to keep our d5-pawn well covered.} 15. Qf2 f6 $1 16. Qh4 {The pin is only a temporary inconvenience.} Rde8 $132 {When things open up, I like having the rooks on the e- and f-files.} (16... Rf7 17. exf6 Nxf6 {was also ok in Chernyshov-Jumabayev, Khanty-Mansiysk 2008, but the rook looks weird on f7 .}) (16... Rfe8 {is perhaps the most natural, and of similar value to 16...Rde8.}) 17. exf6 Nxf6 {We will play ...e5. Note that 17.Rad1 does not prevent our break because of the position of White's queen 17...e5 18.Nxd5 Bxd5 19.Bxd5+ Nxd5 wins material.} *

