1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3. Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} (3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves. Here} (3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5. Shankland's suggestion}) (3... Bf5 {and c6 are both very solid. Jones gives the King's Indian style}) (3... g6 {Finally there is the direct}) (3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd3 {This move, which prepares queenside castling, has had some bouts of popularity. Like other sharper lines in the Veresov, the mighty engine is quick to cool down White's enthusiasm.} c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] We're four moves in and White must search for equality. This is less common than} (4... h6 5. Bh4 c5 {but both moves score tremendously for Black. Our favorite}) (4... e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. dxc5 {It looks strange to invite a knight to c5 to hit the queen, but White has a check on b5.} Nxc5 $1 {A simple, yet tremendous move. We hit the queen and also threaten ...d4, so White has little choice.} 6. Qb5+ Nfd7 $1 {A very rare move, but it is quickly indicated by the computer with the assessment  Indeed, White is in big trouble here. White's queen is rather short of squares, and other pieces are going to get kicked around as well.} 7. Nxd5 {White may at least have a pawn. This also gives his queen one more square on c4.} a6 $1 8. Qc4 {If} (8. Qb4 f6 {followed by ...e6 will win material.}) 8... b5 $1 9. Qh4 (9. Qf4 Ne6 {gains more time.} 10. Qg3 Bb7) 9... Bb7 {It may not look like much is happening, but White would do well to survive for a few more moves. We'll look at a couple of lines.} 10. O-O-O {Natural, but this gets destroyed.} Bxd5 $1 11. Rxd5 Qa5 $1 {White's king is alone.} 12. a3 Qe1+ 13. Rd1 Nb3+ $1 {The point.} 14. cxb3 Rc8+ {And White can resign.} *

