1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 {[%mdl 32768] White should certainly go for the disruptive Nb5 now to justify White's second and third moves.} 4. e3 {This looks highly questionable.} Bb4 {This puts a lot of pressure on White. Black is already fighting for an advantage here and his score is close to 60%! It looks a bit like a Winawer French, but White does not have the space advantage or attacking chances that he'll find there. Now the only sensible moves are Nge2 to avoid doubled pawns, and Bd3 to get developed.} 5. Bd3 c5 $1 {Just like in the French.} 6. dxc5 {After} (6. a3 {?} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5 {White will find it rather difficult to avoid losing a pawn.}) 6... Nbd7 {This is the most flexible move, but} (6... O-O {is good too.}) 7. Nge2 {This avoids doubled pawns.} a6 $1 {A clever move which threatens to play ...e4-e5, winning a piece. White's bishop will not be able to go to b5 now.} 8. a3 {I was familiar with Shankland's analysis when I was faced with this unfamiliar move. It didn't take me long to goof it up.} Bxc5 {Again White has to watch out for ...e5-e4.} 9. Bg3 {If} (9. e4 {?!} e5 10. Bg3 {not 10.Bg5 Bxf2+ !} d4 {is great for Black. For example} 11. Nd5 {or 11.Nb1 Nh5} Nxd5 12. exd5 O-O {Bakalchuk-Postny, Tiberias 2016. Now I was trying to decide between}) (9. O-O {,} Nh5 {, and e5 Ultimately I made the worst choice possible along with a good choice - a draw offer.}) 9... O-O $15 {Black keeps all options open and has a great position.} (9... e5 {? was agreed drawn here in Canty-Vigorito, Charlotte 2022.} 10. Bf5 {! wins a pawn though. It was near the end of a long event and we were both done for the day.}) (9... Nh5 {is fine though.} 10. Nd4 Nxg3 11. hxg3 {White does have the open h-file. The engine still prefers Black slightly after} Nb6) *

