{Stockfish comes up with the following amusing line: 17...g5 18.Bg3 ( hxg5 h6 g6 h7+ ) 18...Kh8 19.Qd7! Wait, what?! 19...Qxd7 20.Be5+ f6 21.Bxf6+ Qg7 22.Bxg7+ Kxg7 ( 23.h8=Q+ ! White has to force the pace, or Black's bishops will be strong. 23...Rxh8 24.Rxh8 Kxh8 ) 23.Rd1 Bc6 24.Rd8 Rc8 25.Bd5 Rc7+ 26.Kf6 Rxa7 with equality!?} 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 4. Nb5 {This is much more critical as it forces Black to misplace his knight.} Na6 {[%mdl 32768]} 5. e3 Be7 {I just want to get on with development. We can kick White's knight later. The immediate} (5... c6 {is more popular.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {Black's main plan is to kick the knight with ... c6, and then play ...c5. The a6-knight will often reroute to c6, via b4 or b8.} 7. h4 $5 {A thoroughly modern idea. In the London we avoided some similar stuff.} c6 8. Nc3 c5 {White's center is not as stable as it is in the proper London with a pawn on c3 and knight on d2.} 9. h5 {Consistent.} h6 {I'd rather the pawn not advance to h6.} 10. g4 $5 {Instead} (10. Ne5 Nb4 {transposes back to 9.Ne5.}) 10... Ne4 $5 {An active move. We want to avoid} (10... Nb4 11. g5 {opening lines. Grabbing the pawn with}) (10... Nxg4 {is possible, when} 11. Rg1 {forces} f5 {Playable, but White has compensation.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 b6 $5 {A simple move really. White can't play g4-g5, so we just want to develop the bishop and cover the e4-pawn. We can reroute the a6-knight later. Instead} (12... Nb4 13. c3 Nd5 14. Bg3 {was played in Matlakov-Azarov, Tornelo internet rapid 2021. The e4-pawn is vulnerable here.}) 13. Bb5 {This looks critical.} Bb7 14. Nd7 Re8 15. dxc5 {Here too White can repeat with} (15. Ne5 Rf8 16. Nd7) 15... Nxc5 $1 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. Bxe8 Qxe8 $13 {Black is down a whole exchange, but I like his compensation. The engines says 0.00. There is no forced draw in sight, but I think that two points worth of compensation will give excellent practical chances. Black intends to play ... e5 and ...Qe6.} 18. Z0 ({White's king will have trouble finding a safe haven, and his rooks do not come into the game very easily. For example} 18. Qe2 e5 19. Bg3 {with Qe6 eyeing the g4- and a2-pawns.}) *

