1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. e3 {The main line.} Qb6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({The most ambitious. Both} 5... Nc6 {and}) (5... cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 {are fine for Black as well.}) 6. Qc1 {By far the most common move, but White has to walk a tightrope.} Nc6 {It's best to maintain the tension. Black is playing for an advantage here.} (6... cxd4 7. exd4 Nc6 8. c3 {is fine too after} Bf5 {or 8...Bg4}) 7. c3 {Giving up the center with} (7. dxc5 {is obviously a concession.} Qxc5 8. Nbd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 f6 {is a familiar story.}) 7... f6 $5 {Now ...g5 followed by ...h5 is a real threat, while White also has to be wary of ...e5.} (7... Bf5 {is simple enough, but we can play for more.}) 8. h3 {This looks like the best try to me. White removes the sting of ...g5 by providing a retreat to the bishop. Black thus strikes from the other direction.} cxd4 $1 {White will have to open either the e1-a5 or g1-a7 diagonal.} 9. exd4 e5 $1 10. Be3 {Everything else loses material.} exd4 11. Nxd4 ({Opening the c-file with} 11. cxd4 {leads to trouble after} Bf5 {and ...Rc8 is coming.}) 11... Bc5 {Many writers have considered this position to be disastrous for White. It's true that it's not very good, but White is more alive than has been indicated.} ({I'll mention that} 11... Nxd4 {is good too, but after} 12. Bxd4 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Qe3 {Black is merely comfortable - there is no knockout.}) 12. Nd2 $1 {In practice White has capitulated in most games, but this move keeps White alive. Of course this is not such a tremendous accomplishment with the white pieces in twelve moves.} Bxd4 {This keeps the game going.} ({Black can also grab the pawn, but it all fizzles out soon} 12... Nxd4 13. Nxe4 $1 {(Worse is 13.cxd4? 13...Bb4! followed by ...Bd7 and ...Rc8 with a strong initiative.)} dxe4 14. cxd4 Bxd4 {(Or 14...Bb4+ 15.Bd2 Qxd4 16.Bb5+ Kf8 17.a3! 17...Bxd2+ 18.Qxd2 Qxd2+ 19.Kxd2 and with a rook coming to c1, White is fine.)} 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 16. Bb5+ Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {The position is equal now. For example} 18. O-O {when Black should really just play} O-O {allowing} 19. Qc4+ {winning back the pawn.}) 13. cxd4 Bf5 14. Be2 $1 Rc8 ({There is nothing concrete after} 14... Nb4 15. O-O Rc8 16. Qd1) ({And if we take the pawn now with} 14... Nxd4 {White has} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 $1 Nc2+ 17. Qxc2 Bxc2 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Rc1 {.}) 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. O-O O-O {White has the bishops, but Black is active and White has to keep an eye on the d4- and b2-pawns. So, we do not win by force, but White has to avoid a lot of trouble and we have the option to steer the game to a draw in a couple of places.} *

