1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. e3 {The main line.} Qb6 ({The most ambitious. Both} 5... Nc6 {and}) (5... cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 {are fine for Black as well.}) 6. Nc3 {Shankland considers this to be dubious, but I think it may be White's best chance to equalize.} Qa5 {[%mdl 32768] The most ambitious.} (6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qa5 8. Qd2 {is less convincing.}) 7. Bb5+ {White's safest choice. At least he can evacuate his king from the center quickly.} Bd7 {This is the simplest. I also checked the sharper} (7... Nc6 {and there are lots of possibilities.} 8. O-O Nxc3 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. bxc3 {I looked at this quite a bit as it's good with White's bishop on h4. Black can still play} Qxc3 {but with no pieces out it's all a bit risky, and doesn't seem practical in such a rare line.} 11. Ne5) 8. Bxd7+ Nxd7 9. O-O cxd4 {Black can also play} (9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Rc8 {as indicated by Gledura in his QGA course.}) 10. exd4 (10. Nxd4 $2 {is incomprehensible.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 e5 12. Re1 {( 12.Nb3 Qxc3 13.Bg3 Qc6 )} O-O-O 13. Nb3 Qxc3 {Stocek - Svane, Teplice 2023.}) 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Rc8 {Preventing c4. This looks quite safe for Black despite his lagging development and White's structure is bad.} ({We should avoid} 11... Qxc3 12. Rb1 Qc6 13. c4 $1 {with great play for White.}) *

