1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {[%mdl 32768] I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ... Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 without hanging our queen, then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. Nf3 Qb6 5. b3 {White has avoided various little tactical ideas, but this softens up the queenside a bit.} Bf5 {We just follow the development plan.} 6. e3 e6 7. Bd3 {White generally wants to eliminate our strong bishop.} (7. Be2 {is rather passive. We can play} Nd7 {and then either ...Be7 or ...Ngf6.}) 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Be7 ({Following Kramnik. Black could play} 8... Nd7 {first too. Now White can either exchange bishops, helping us develop, or keep the bishop, which costs a tempo.}) 9. Bg3 {White keeps the bishops on the board.} Nf6 10. O-O Nbd7 ({The immediate} 10... Ne4 {is also possible.}) 11. c4 O-O ({Again,} 11... Ne4 {is possible, but it's good to see how Black can deal with White queenside ambitions.}) 12. c5 ({The immediate} 12. Nc3 {could be met with} Qa6 $5 {a la Kramnik.}) 12... Qa5 ({This is more active than the immediate} 12... Qd8 13. Nc3) 13. a3 ({If} 13. Nc3 b6 $1 {and we immediately break up the pawns.}) 13... Ne4 14. b4 Qd8 15. Nc3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Qc7 {Black can play ...e5 at any time. It's also possible to play ...b5 and ...a5, but White's queenside play is not so dangerous that we have to do that.} 17. Z0 ({Note that the immediate} 17. a4 {could even be met with} a5 18. b5 b6 $1 {when Black is not even worse on the queenside.}) *

