1. d4 d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. cxd5 {This is White's most straightforward response, but I think we should be happy to face it.} Nxd5 $1 {Very often we will recapture this way, as Black has less space and wants to trade some pieces.} 9. Bg3 {This is a typical idea, avoiding the trade of bishops, but it does not combine well with the non-developing 8.cxd5.} Bb7 {This is just easy for Black. Achieving ...c5 is no problem, and we can always trade a set of knights. Depending on what White does next, the position could transpose to another line like 8.Be2 or 8. Bd3.} 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 c5 11. O-O Nd7 {will reach the 8.Be2 lines.}) 10... c5 11. O-O {Black can go for a transposition to some common lines, but he does not have to.} cxd4 $5 {This is probably even better than heading to other lines.} (11... Nd7 {would transpose to the 8.Bd3 line.}) 12. exd4 (12. Nxd4 {just allow Black to split White's pawns with} Nxc3 $17) 12... Nc6 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ga8c8] Black has a normal IQP position, where White's bishop is curiously placed on g3.} *

