1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. cxd5 {This is White's most straightforward response, but I think we should be happy to face it.} Nxd5 $1 {Very often we will recapture this way, as Black has less space and wants to trade some pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Nxd5 {The main move by far. Other moves will transpose to rather harmless lines:} ({A)} 10. Be2 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 is a harmless note in the 8.Be2 chapter. [/course/93560/21]}) ({B)} 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.O-O Nbd7 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Bxe7 Qxe7}) ({C)} 10. Rc1 Bb7 {brings us to StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Rc1 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 .}) 10... exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8e6] This is the main position for 8.cxd5. Compared to a normal QGD Exchange, Black's pawn is on b6, not c6, which changes a lot. Black cannot just play ...c6 and ...Bf5 for example, as the c6-pawn would be a serious weakness. If the bishop goes to b7, it would be very passive, and compared to other positions that we will see later, Black does not have the bishop pair to compensate for this. So the right plan is the active ...c5, combined with ... Be6! instead of the more passive ...Bb7.} 11. Rc1 {This is the main line. White hopes to create pressure down the c-file. White can hardly achieve anything without this. There are other moves, but they will generally transpose.} (11. Qb3 {does not have real independent significance.} Be6 12. Rc1 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes to the main lines.}) (11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc1 {transposes to 12.Bd3.}) (11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 {14.Rc1 transposes to 12.Be2} Nd7 {for 14...Qb7!? see Bertok-Fischer, Stockholm} 15. Rac1 {again transposes to 15.Be2.}) 11... Be6 $1 12. Qc2 ({Now} 12. Qa4 {with the idea} c5 13. Qa3 {, is the main line.}) {There's this queen move too, which rather naively attacks the c7-pawn.} 12... Rc8 {The ...c5 break is coming anyway and White's queen is exposed.} 13. Bd3 c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Nd4 $5 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc2c8,Gd3h7] Otherwise Black plays ...Nd7 and is very comfortable.} c4 $5 {[%cal Gc4d3]} ({Black could also keep the bishop with} 15... Bd7) ({or simply develop with} 15... Nd7 {as} 16. Nxe6 fxe6 {is not worse for Black.}) 16. Be2 Qb4+ 17. Qc3 ({If} 17. Qd2 a5 $1 {favorably maintains the tension.}) 17... Nc6 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black will create counterplay on the b-file.} *

