 to 12.Bd3.}) (11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 {14.Rc1 transposes to 12.Be2} Nd7 {for 14...Qb7!? see Bertok-Fischer, Stockholm} 15. Rac1 {again transposes to 15.Be2.}) 11... Be6 $1 12. Bd3 ({Now} 12. Qa4 {with the idea} c5 13. Qa3 {, is the main line.}) {More active than 12.Be2, but any ...c4 advance will come with tempo.} 12... c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. O-O Nd7 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gf8b8]} 15. e4 $6 {Played often, but not very good. White looks to change the course of the game. Other moves would lead to similar play as we saw in the 12. Be2 line.} d4 $1 {[%cal Gf8b8,Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Ga7a5]} (15... dxe4 16. Bxe4 Rad8 {has also done well for Black in practice, but let's avoid splitting the pawns and be ambitious.}) 16. Nd2 $2 {[%cal Gd2c4] This natural move has been played a lot, but now Black get the upper hand.} Ne5 17. Bb1 $6 c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4]} 18. h3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} (18. f4 $2 Ng4 {is even worse.}) 18... g5 $17 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge5] Black's strong knight and powerful pawns gave him a clear advantage in Sasikiran-Bruzon Batista, Yerevan 2000.} *

