1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. cxd5 {This is White's most straightforward response, but I think we should be happy to face it.} Nxd5 $1 {Very often we will recapture this way, as Black has less space and wants to trade some pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 {The main move by far. Other moves will transpose to rather harmless lines:} ({A)} 10. Be2 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 is a harmless note in the 8.Be2 chapter. [/course/93560/21]}) ({B)} 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.O-O Nbd7 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Bxe7 Qxe7}) ({C)} 10. Rc1 Bb7 {brings us to StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Rc1 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 .}) 10... exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8e6] This is the main position for 8. cxd5. Compared to a normal QGD Exchange, Black's pawn is on b6, not c6, which changes a lot. Black cannot just play ...c6 and ...Bf5 for example, as the c6-pawn would be a serious weakness. If The bishop goes to b7, it would be very passive, and compared to other positions that we will see later, Black does not have the bishop pair to compensate for this. So the right plan is the active ...c5, combined with ...Be6! instead of the more passive ...Bb7.} 11. Rc1 {This is the main line. White hopes to create pressure down the c-file. White can hardly achieve anything without this. There are other moves, but they will generally transpose.} (11. Qb3 {does not have real independent significance.} Be6 12. Rc1 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes to the main lines.}) (11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc1 {transposes to 12.Bd3.}) (11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 {14.Rc1 transposes to 12.Be2} Nd7 {for 14...Qb7!? see Bertok-Fischer, Stockholm} 15. Rac1 {again transposes to 15.Be2.}) 11... Be6 $1 12. Qa4 ({Now} 12. Qa4 {with the idea} c5 13. Qa3 {, is the main line.}) ({White probes on the queenside and prepares to meet ...c5 with the pinning Qa3.} 12. Qb3 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes.}) 12... c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. Qa3 {[%cal Ga3e7] Capturing immediately makes little difference.} (13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa3 Rc8 {transposes.}) 13... Rc8 {Black has scored well over 50% from this position!} ({Instead} 13... Nd7 {is considered to be less accurate due to} 14. Bb5 {attacking the knight and thus increasing the pressure on the c5-pawn. Black still looks ok after} Rfc8 {but the immediate 13...Rc8 is certainly more flexible.}) 14. Bb5 $6 {This was played in a very famous Fischer-Spassky game that White won, but soon after it was shown to be inaccurate.} Qb7 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ya3e7] Black is already better here. The first point is that the pin is gone and ...c4 will leave White's bishop looking rather foolish. There is the matter of a pawn that is hanging, but as White has not yet castled, Black gets excellent play. The renowned game went} (14... a6 $6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O Ra7 $6 17. Be2 Nd7 18. Nd4 Qf8 19. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 20. e4 $1 d4 $6 21. f4 $16 {and the American scored a resounding victory in Fischer-Spassky, Reykjavik 1972.}) 15. dxc5 {There is little choice.} (15. O-O c4 $17 {is just good for Black - the queenside pawns will advance, gaining time by attacking White's wayward bishop, and eventually the queen.}) 15... bxc5 16. Be2 {White is essentially admitting his mistake.} Qb6 $15 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb8d7] I like this move, which simply covers the c5-pawn and keeps the tension. Black will have excellent play on the queenside.} (16... a5 {with the idea} 17. Rxc5 Rxc5 18. Qxc5 Qxb2 $15 {is also quite good.}) *

