e later, Black does not have the bishop pair to compensate for this. So the right plan is the active ...c5, combined with ...Be6! instead of the more passive ...Bb7.} 11. Rc1 {This is the main line. White hopes to create pressure down the c-file. White can hardly achieve anything without this. There are other moves, but they will generally transpose.} (11. Qb3 {does not have real independent significance.} Be6 12. Rc1 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes to the main lines.}) (11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc1 {transposes to 12.Bd3.}) (11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 {14.Rc1 transposes to 12.Be2} Nd7 {for 14...Qb7!? see Bertok-Fischer, Stockholm} 15. Rac1 {again transposes to 15.Be2.}) 11... Be6 $1 12. Qa4 ({Now} 12. Qa4 {with the idea} c5 13. Qa3 {, is the main line.}) ({White probes on the queenside and prepares to meet ...c5 with the pinning Qa3.} 12. Qb3 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes.}) 12... c5 13. Qa3 {[%cal Ga3e7] Capturing immediately makes little difference.} (13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa3 Rc8 {transposes.}) 13... Rc8 {Black has scored well over 50% from this position!} ({Instead} 13... Nd7 {is considered to be less accurate due to} 14. Bb5 {attacking the knight and thus increasing the pressure on the c5-pawn. Black still looks ok after} Rfc8 {but the immediate 13...Rc8 is certainly more flexible.}) 14. Bb5 $6 {This was played in a very famous Fischer-Spassky game that White won, but soon after it was shown to be inaccurate.} Qb7 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ya3e7] Black is already better here. The first point is that the pin is gone and ...c4 will leave White's bishop looking rather foolish. There is the matter of a pawn that is hanging, but as White has not yet castled, Black gets excellent play. The renowned game went} (14... a6 $6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O Ra7 $6 17. Be2 Nd7 18. Nd4 Qf8 19. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 20. e4 $1 d4 $6 21. f4 $16 {and the American scored a resounding victory in Fischer-Spassky, Reykjavik 1972.}) 15. dxc5 {There is little choice.} (15. O-O c4 $17 {is just good for Black - the queenside pawns will advance, gaining time by attacking White's wayward bishop (and queen).}) 15... bxc5 16. Rxc5 {White takes the bait. This is the only way to justify his play, but Black will get a strong initiative.} Rxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} 17. Qxc5 Na6 $1 {The key move. Without this, Black would just be clearly worse.} 18. Qc6 {White tries to bail out in the endgame.} Qxc6 19. Bxc6 Rb8 $1 {An important intermezzo!} ({The obvious} 19... Rc8 {allows} 20. Ba4 Rc1+ 21. Bd1 {Although Black can win back a pawn on the queenside, White will complete his development and be fine.}) 20. O-O ({White cannot play} 20. b3 $2 {because now} Rc8 $1 {indeed wins - the bishop cannot come back to block on d1 .}) 20... Rxb2 {[%csl Ra2,Rc6][%cal Ga6b4] Black has his pawn back and keeps up the pressure.} *

