nnot castle.} 19. Qa3 {The only move.} Qc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c1]} ({We are certainly not going to let White off the hook with} 19... Qxa3 20. bxa3 Rb8 21. O-O {=}) 20. Kd2 {[%cal Gh1c1] White hopes to play Rc1 when he could actually survive.} Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g2] Keep making threats!} ({If} 20... Rc8 $2 21. Nd4 {and Black's initiative is gone.}) 21. Rg1 ({No choice.} 21. Ne1 $2 d4 {is over.}) 21... d4 $1 {A great move! The position opens further and Black's bishop is ready to show its teeth.} 22. exd4 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gg4f4,Gb8b2,Ra3e3] Geller's suggestion from 1973 is best. Now ...Qf4+ is a big threat, as White will not have Qe3 due to .. .Rxb2+ Other moves should win too. For curious minds:} (22... Rc8 {Biyiasas-Winslow, San Francisco 1985}) (22... Bd5 {Kuzubov-Schroll, Plovdiv 2008}) 23. b3 {Now the white queen is cut off.} Qf4+ {[%mdl 32768]} 24. Kc2 Bf5+ 25. Kb2 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c2] Black is coming in. The position is winning, but I will give a couple more moves.} 26. Qe7 {The only hope for a mistake.} Rc2+ 27. Ka3 {Now there is only one winning move.} (27. Ka1 Rc1+ {is lights out.}) 27... Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b6]} 28. Re1 {The rook finally gets into the game!} Qb6 29. Re5 Be6 $1 {[%cal Gc2a2] Threatening ...Rxa2+ and ...Qxb3 mate!} 30. Z0 ({White can avoid this with} 30. Qe8+ Kh7 31. Qb5 {but after} Qd6+ 32. Rc5 {Black can just start eating pawns.} Rxf2) *

