1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. cxd5 {This is White's most straightforward response, but I think we should be happy to face it.} Nxd5 $1 {Very often we will recapture this way, as Black has less space and wants to trade some pieces.} 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 {The main move by far. Other moves will transpose to rather harmless lines:} ({A)} 10. Be2 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 is a harmless note in the 8.Be2 chapter. [/course/93560/21]}) ({B)} 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O Nd7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.O-O Nbd7 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Bxe7 Qxe7}) ({C)} 10. Rc1 Bb7 {brings us to StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Rc1 Bb7 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Bxe7 Qxe7 .}) 10... exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gc8e6] This is the main position for 8. cxd5. Compared to a normal QGD Exchange, Black's pawn is on b6, not c6, which changes a lot. Black cannot just play ...c6 and ...Bf5 for example, as the c6-pawn would be a serious weakness. If The bishop goes to b7, it would be very passive, and compared to other positions that we will see later, Black does not have the bishop pair to compensate for this. So the right plan is the active ...c5, combined with ...Be6! instead of the more passive ...Bb7.} 11. Rc1 {This is the main line. White hopes to create pressure down the c-file. White can hardly achieve anything without this. There are other moves, but they will generally transpose.} (11. Qb3 {does not have real independent significance.} Be6 12. Rc1 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes to the main lines.}) (11. Bd3 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rc1 {transposes to 12.Bd3.}) (11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa4 {14.Rc1 transposes to 12.Be2} Nd7 {for 14...Qb7!? see Bertok-Fischer, Stockholm} 15. Rac1 {again transposes to 15.Be2.}) 11... Be6 $1 12. Qa4 ({Now} 12. Qa4 {with the idea} c5 13. Qa3 {, is the main line.}) ({White probes on the queenside and prepares to meet ...c5 with the pinning Qa3.} 12. Qb3 c5 13. Qa3 {transposes.}) 12... c5 13. Qa3 {[%cal Ga3e7] Capturing immediately makes little difference.} (13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Qa3 Rc8 {transposes.}) 13... Rc8 {Black has scored well over 50% from this position!} ({Instead} 13... Nd7 {is considered to be less accurate due to} 14. Bb5 {attacking the knight and thus increasing the pressure on the c5-pawn. Black still looks ok after} Rfc8 {but the immediate 13...Rc8 is certainly more flexible.}) 14. Be2 {This modest move is White's safest choice, but Black has few troubles.} Kf8 $5 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black is spoiled for choice a bit. This unpins and prepares ...c4. This was the choice of none other than Garry Kasparov.} ({Unpinning with} 14... Qf8 $5 {is quite good. This avoids bringing the king near the center, but the queen looks more passive here.} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. O-O a5 {with ...Nd7 next is similar.}) (14... a5 $5 {is decent too. The black king stays put while the queen is ready to swing to the queenside. Perhaps the only downside is that it allows} 15. dxc5 {if 15.O-O Qa7!? 16.dxc5 bxc5} bxc5 16. Nd4 {even though this is not a big deal after} Nd7 {If} 17. Nxe6 fxe6 {is not bad for Black at all.}) 15. dxc5 (15. O-O c4 {is just good for Black. The queenside pawns roll.}) 15... bxc5 16. O-O a5 $1 ({Avoiding the annoyance of} 16... Nd7 17. Ba6) 17. Rc3 {White tries to stay active.} (17. Ne5 Nc6 18. Nxc6 Rxc6 {is a simple and easy position for Black. ...c4 is soon on the cards, as usual.}) (17. Rfd1 Nd7 {is also quite comfortable for Black.}) 17... Nd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. Rfc1 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge2b5,Gb5d7,Gc1c8] Now we have to watch out for both Nd4 and Bb5, removing the defender or our c5-pawn.} Rcb8 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gf8e7,Gb8b2] This unpins the c-pawn along the c-file and covers the b5-square. Black had good counterplay on the queenside in Winants-Kasparov, Bruxelles 1987.} *

