1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} dxc4 {This could be a nice shortcut as it can be played against both 8.Be2 and 8.Bd3, but I do not like it as much as the main lines.} ({We will take} 8... Bb7 {as the main line.}) 9. Bxc4 Bb7 10. O-O {[%csl Rd8] As often happens in the QGD, Black has problems finding a square for his queen.} (10. Qc2 $5 {as proposed by Khalifman in his old 'According to Kramnik' series, could also have some bite, but it has not caught on.}) 10... Nbd7 11. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1] White has the space, so it's much easier for him to connect his rooks.} Ne4 {Seeking exchanges.} 12. Nxe4 ({Life is much easier after} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Rac1 c5) 12... Bxe4 ({I do not like Black's position after} 12... Bxh4 13. Nc3 Bf6 {and now after} 14. Rad1 $5 {intending Rfe1, e4 White has great control of the center and Black remains cramped.}) 13. Bg3 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1] This looks nice for White.} Bd6 {[%cal Gd8e7] Now there is a square for the queen! Black's position is tenable, but not very inspiring. This could still serve as a solid backup however.} *

