1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4]} ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c6 {We will keep the tension with this flexible move.} (11... Nd7 12. Qb3 c6 {is likely to transpose}) 12. Re1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1] but 12.b4 tricks us, as both 12...c6 13.Qb3 and 12...c5 13.bxc5 bxc5 14.Rb1 Bc6 15.Bb5 are positions we look to avoid 11...Re8 12.Qb3 c6 13.Rfe1 Nd7 is legit though, and heads for our main line. 11...c5 is also totally fine, but a bit less interesting. This is covered as an alternative. The central plan.} (12. b4 {heads to the 11.b4 line.}) 12... Nd7 ({Instead} 12... Re8 13. Qb3 Nd7 {transposes.}) 13. Qb3 Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Both sides have just about completed development, and White just has to decide when to play e3-e4.} (13... Be7 {with the idea ...Nf6 is another way to play it.}) 14. e4 {This can be played immediately, but it is not dangerous if we react correctly.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] A good idea to remember. It works well here because White's rook is still on a1.} ({We must avoid} 14... dxe4 $2 15. Bc4 $1 {attacking f7 and planning Nxe4. This is White's big idea.}) 15. Nxd5 {There is not really any choice.} (15. dxc5 $2 Nxc5) (15. exd5 $2 cxd4 $17) (15. e5 $2 cxd4 16. exf6 Nc5 $17 {followed by ...dxc3 are all horrible for White.}) 15... Rxe4 $146 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd4c5,Gd7c5,Gd5f6,Gd8f6] The most ambitious. Black is very active and it is White who must work to equalize.} (15... cxd4 {is also quite good. White must scramble to equalize, but he will do so.} 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {The e4-pawn is falling so White goes after our d-pawn.} 17. Qa4 Nc5 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Nxd4 Rxe4 {Black clearly has no problems here. After} 20. Nb5 Bc6 {Timman-Spassky, Bugojno 1982 was agreed drawn.}) *

