1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4]} ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c6 {We will keep the tension with this flexible move.} (11... Nd7 12. Qb3 c6 {is likely to transpose}) 12. Re1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1] but 12.b4 tricks us, as both 12...c6 13.Qb3 and 12...c5 13.bxc5 bxc5 14.Rb1 Bc6 15.Bb5 are positions we look to avoid 11...Re8 12.Qb3 c6 13.Rfe1 Nd7 is legit though, and heads for our main line. 11...c5 is also totally fine, but a bit less interesting. This is covered as an alternative. The central plan.} (12. b4 {heads to the 11.b4 line.}) 12... Nd7 ({Instead} 12... Re8 13. Qb3 Nd7 {transposes.}) 13. Qb3 Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Both sides have just about completed development, and White just has to decide when to play e3-e4.} (13... Be7 {with the idea ...Nf6 is another way to play it.}) 14. Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White brings all of the pieces into play before breaking in the center.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6][%mdl 32768] A typical complex Tartakover middlegame. Black has the bishop pair and while they are not active, if the position opens up they may show their teeth. White still generally plays to break in the center, hoping that his central buildup will mean more than Black's potential.} 15. Bd3 {This is a bit cautious.} Ne6 16. Bb1 {[%cal Gb3c2] A rathor labored plan, which will not even threaten to mate us.} c5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gc5d4] Let's do it. If White does not capture, both ...c4 and ...cxd4 look like good options.} ({The prophylactic} 16... g6 {is good too, as} 17. e4 $6 {is well met with} c5 $1) 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qc2 g6 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Ga8c8,Gf6g7,Gd8e7,Gc5e4] We have an IQP, but our pieces are good. White's pieces on the other hand, look a bit awkward as he went searching for a phantom mate.} 19. Nd4 {Khalifman claimed that White was better here, but this is rather optimistic.} Rc8 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Gd8e7,Gc5e4,Gc8c2] Today's engines clearly prefer Black. His position is active and White lacks a good plan.} *

