1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4]} ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c6 {We will keep the tension with this flexible move.} (11... Nd7 12. Qb3 c6 {is likely to transpose}) 12. Re1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1] but 12.b4 tricks us, as both 12...c6 13.Qb3 and 12...c5 13.bxc5 bxc5 14.Rb1 Bc6 15.Bb5 are positions we look to avoid 11...Re8 12.Qb3 c6 13.Rfe1 Nd7 is legit though, and heads for our main line. 11...c5 is also totally fine, but a bit less interesting. This is covered as an alternative. The central plan.} (12. b4 {heads to the 11.b4 line.}) 12... Nd7 ({Instead} 12... Re8 13. Qb3 Nd7 {transposes.}) 13. Qb3 Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Both sides have just about completed development, and White just has to decide when to play e3-e4.} (13... Be7 {with the idea ...Nf6 is another way to play it.}) 14. Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White brings all of the pieces into play before breaking in the center.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] A typical complex Tartakover middlegame. Black has the bishop pair and while they are not active, if the position opens up they may show their teeth. White still generally plays to break in the center, hoping that his central buildup will mean more than Black's potential.} 15. Bf1 {This looks funny, but after g3 the bishop will find a more active role.} Ne6 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. g3 {[%cal Gb7f3] This was the idea, but it does weaken the long diagonal.} c5 $1 {No hesitation.} 17. dxc5 d4 $5 {[%cal Gb7f3]} ({Both} 17... Nxc5) ({and} 17... Bxc3 18. Qxc3 bxc5 {are viable alternatives. But this works, so let's do it. The pin on the d-file is temporary.}) 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. exd4 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Bxd4 $13 {[%cal Gd4f2,Gb7g2,Gd4c5] Look at those bishops! Black has full compensation for the pawn and White must be careful.} 21. cxb6 $2 {Too greedy.} Qf6 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf6f3] Black attacks f2 and threatens ...Qf3. This is very simple.} ({Technically} 21... Bxf2+ {is even stronger:} 22. Kxf2 Qf6+ 23. Ke2 Re8+ 24. Kd2 {when Black must find} Qg5+ $1 25. Kd1 Rd8+) 22. Qc2 {This covers f2 and control the e4-square so that White can block the diagonal. But it's not enough.} Qf3 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gf3h1]} 23. Ne4 (23. Re4 Rc8 $1 24. Bg2 Bxe4 {is a similar disaster for White.}) 23... Rc8 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rf2][%cal Rc2e4,Rc2f2,Gc8c2] White's queen is overloaded.} *

