ypical complex Tartakover middlegame. Black has the bishop pair and while they are not active, if the position opens up they may show their teeth. White still generally plays to break in the center, hoping that his central buildup will mean more than Black's potential.} 15. Bf1 {This looks funny, but after g3 the bishop will find a more active role.} Ne6 16. g3 {[%cal Gb7f3] This was the idea, but it does weaken the long diagonal.} c5 $1 {No hesitation.} 17. dxc5 d4 $5 {[%cal Gb7f3]} ({Both} 17... Nxc5) ({and} 17... Bxc3 18. Qxc3 bxc5 {are viable alternatives. But this works, so let's do it. The pin on the d-file is temporary.}) 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. exd4 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Bxd4 $13 {[%cal Gd4f2,Gb7g2,Gd4c5] Look at those bishops! Black has full compensation for the pawn and White must be careful.} 21. Rd1 {Pinning the bishop better than grabbing another pawn.} Qf6 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gf6f3][%mdl 32768]} 22. Rd2 {This and White's next are forced.} Qf3 23. Nd5 {White is surely relieved to trade queens.} Qxb3 ({Getting fancy with} 23... Bxf2+ 24. Rxf2 Qxd5 25. Qxd5 Bxd5 26. cxb6 axb6 {should be fine too, but let's keep the bishops.}) 24. axb3 Bxc5 {Black has his pawn back and is clearly at least ok here. White's centralized knight allow him to maintain some balance.} *

