1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4]} ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c6 {We will keep the tension with this flexible move.} (11... Nd7 12. Qb3 c6 {is likely to transpose}) 12. Re1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1] but 12.b4 tricks us, as both 12...c6 13.Qb3 and 12...c5 13.bxc5 bxc5 14.Rb1 Bc6 15.Bb5 are positions we look to avoid 11...Re8 12.Qb3 c6 13.Rfe1 Nd7 is legit though, and heads for our main line. 11...c5 is also totally fine, but a bit less interesting. This is covered as an alternative. The central plan.} (12. b4 {heads to the 11.b4 line.}) 12... Nd7 ({Instead} 12... Re8 13. Qb3 Nd7 {transposes.}) 13. Qb3 Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6] Both sides have just about completed development, and White just has to decide when to play e3-e4.} (13... Be7 {with the idea ...Nf6 is another way to play it.}) 14. Rad1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White brings all of the pieces into play before breaking in the center.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] A typical complex Tartakover middlegame. Black has the bishop pair and while they are not active, if the position opens up they may show their teeth. White still generally plays to break in the center, hoping that his central buildup will mean more than Black's potential.} 15. e4 g6 {[%cal Gf6g7][%mdl 32768] This closes the b1-h7 diagonal and gives the bishop a retreat.} ({Again we must avoid} 15... dxe4 $2 16. Bc4 $1 {hitting f7 and preparing Nxe4, when White's central initiative is too much.}) ({Black could play} 15... Ne6 16. e5 Be7 {instead, but I like having the bishop on g7 where it may put pressure on the e4-pawn.}) 16. e5 Bg7 {[%cal Gf8e6,Gd8e7,Ga8d8] If White does not come up with a plan, we will play ...Ne6, ...Qe7, ...Rad8 and eventually ...c5.} 17. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5] Looking to soften up our kingside.} Bc8 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5,Gc8g4,Gh6h5] The bishop emerges and controls important squares. Now Black may consider ...h5, as he can meet Ng5 with ...Ne6 and recapture with the bishop.} ({Note that Black should avoid} 17... h5 $6 18. Ng5 $1 Ne6 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 20. g3 $16 {as seen in Gaprindashvili-Maric, Novi Sad 1990. White can continue with f4-f5 with a strong attack. Black's rook is awkward on e6 here.}) 18. h5 g5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6] The position is unclear. White cannot set up real threats on the b1-h7 diagonal (it takes some time and h7 is covered anyway). Black has good squares for his pieces and may break with ... f6 at some point,} *

