1. d4 d5 {[%mdl 32768]} 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O {[%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Gf1e1,Ge3e4]} ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) {This was Khalifman's recommendation in the 'According to Kramnik' series. White's idea is to play Qb3, bring the rook the the center, and look to play the e3-e4 break.} 11... c5 {This is technically quite fine for Black, but it's a bit boring.} 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Qb3 Bc6 14. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd5] This can be met with:} Nd7 {Offering the d-pawn.} 15. Nxd5 Rb8 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qc3 Rxb2 18. Qxf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Gb2,Rf2][%cal Gf8b8,Gf6g4,Gf6e4] Black is active enough to offset his split queenside pawns. An almost identical position is reached in the line with 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6, but there White's rook is on f1, not d1. Here the rook is more active, but the f2-pawn is weakened.} *

