1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) 11... c6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is the combative choice. Instead} 11... c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Bb5 Qc7 {is a well-known theoretical line where White has tried just about every imaginable queen move. This line is drawish, but in general White can push a little bit with very little risk.}) 12. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge5] Black has tried various things here, but I like this move the best. Black covers the e5-square before committing anything else. Instead} (12... a5 {was the traditional main line, but after} 13. b5 c5 14. Ne5 {White has done very well. Now ...Nd7 is prevented because of Nc6! and White is also preparing Bf3 and sometimes Ng4. Black may be ok somehow, but he certainly walks a tightrope. The natural}) (12... Nd7 13. Qb3 a5 $6 {has also been often played, but then} 14. b5 {undermines the d5-pawn. Black has generally offered a pawn here with} a4 15. Nxa4 c5 {but I do not really buy it after the simple} 16. Nc3 {Finally there is}) (12... Qd6 {which guards the e5-square and hits the b4-pawn. But after} 13. Qb3 {White can bring his rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. b5 {White marches on, hoping to undermine the d5-pawn.} c5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb8d7] Black will be happy to push ...c4 with a protected passed pawn. So White goes for the hanging pawns.} 15. dxc5 bxc5 {[%csl Gb7,Rc3,Gf6][%cal Gf6a1,Gd5d4] Now Black's dark-squared bishop is especailly strong. White also has to always be wary of ...d4, opening up Black's other bishop.} 16. Rac1 {This was played twice in the Timman-Short match in 1993. Short won the match and the right to face Kasparov.} a4 $1 {[%cal Gd8a5]} ({In both of the match games Short played} 16... Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Nd7 {. He had a win and a draw, but our move is stronger.}) 17. Nxa4 ({The only way to test Black. Instead} 17. Qc2 Nd7 {and ...Nb6 secures everything and is great for Black.}) 17... c4 $1 18. Qc2 Qa5 {[%csl Ra2,Ra4]} 19. Nc3 {Natural, although now Black wins back the pawn with a good position.} Bxc3 {We part with our bishop to regain the pawn.} 20. Qxc3 Qxc3 21. Rxc3 Rxa2 22. Nd4 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Ge8a8,Gd7c5] White's knight looks nice but other factors are in Black's favor. First and foremost his rooks will be much more active than White's.} *

