1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) 11... c6 {This is the combative choice. Instead} (11... c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Bb5 Qc7 {is a well-known theoretical line where White has tried just about every imaginable queen move. This line is drawish, but in general White can push a little bit with very little risk.}) 12. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge5] Black has tried various things here, but I like this move the best. Black covers the e5-square before committing anything else. Instead} (12... a5 {was the traditional main line, but after} 13. b5 c5 14. Ne5 {White has done very well. Now ...Nd7 is prevented because of Nc6! and White is also preparing Bf3 and sometimes Ng4. Black may be ok somehow, but he certainly walks a tightrope. The natural}) (12... Nd7 13. Qb3 a5 $6 {has also been often played, but then} 14. b5 {undermines the d5-pawn. Black has generally offered a pawn here with} a4 15. Nxa4 c5 {but I do not really buy it after the simple} 16. Nc3 {Finally there is}) (12... Qd6 {which guards the e5-square and hits the b4-pawn. But after} 13. Qb3 {White can bring his rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. a3 {White keeps the tension on the queenside for now.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6b5,Gb6c4][%mdl 32768]} ({Develop. Black has also tried} 14... b5 {here (hoping to play ... Nd7-b6-c4), but White can switch plans with} 15. bxa5 Qxa5 16. Rfb1 {intending a4.}) 15. b5 {[%csl Rd5] Apparently White has had a change of heart, but Black's last move left the d5-pawn vulnerable. Or so it would appear...} (15. Rad1 axb4 16. axb4 b5 $1 {works well now - see Speelman-Lputian, Kropotkin 1995.}) 15... c5 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black must play this.} 16. Nxd5 (16. dxc5 $4 {makes no sense strategically, and it loses tactically after} Nxc5 17. Qc2 Rc8 {and the c3-knight is as good as gone.}) 16... Bxd4 $1 {[%cal Ge8e2] This key tactic justifies Black's play.} 17. Rad1 $6 {This looks critical and it was played by none other than Karpov, but it all works out well for Black.} Ne5 ({Throwing in} 17... a4 $146 {first is also quite good.} 18. Qa2 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxd5 20. Nc4 Qg5 21. g3 Rxe3 $1 {also leads to complications that favor Black.} 22. Rxd4 Rxe2 23. Qxe2 cxd4 24. Nxb6 Rb8) 18. Nxe5 ({The desperado} 18. Nxb6 {leads to simplifications that favor Black.} Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qxb6 21. exd4 cxd4 $15) (18. Nf4 {can me met with} Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qf6 $1) 18... Bxd5 19. Nc4 ({After} 19. Bc4 $2 Rxe5 20. exd4 Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Rd5 $17 {Black wins a pawn.}) 19... Qg5 $1 {[%csl Rg2]} 20. g3 Qf5 $1 {[%cal Gf5h3,Gf5e4]} 21. Rfe1 {Finally the d4-bishop is really threatened.} Qe4 $1 {[%csl Rg2,Rh1] Making a little threat.} 22. f3 Qxe3+ $1 {The only move, but a good one.} 23. Qxe3 (23. Nxe3 Bxb3 {is over.}) 23... Rxe3 24. Nxe3 Bxe3+ 25. Kf1 $2 {This was played by Karpov.} Rd8 $15 {[%csl Ra3,Rf1,Rf3][%cal Ge3d4,Gg8f8,Gd4b2]} ({Even stronger than} 25... Bd4 {when} 26. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 27. Rd1 Rc8 28. Rxd4 Rc5 29. f4 Kf8 30. Bd3 Ke7 {was drawn here in Karpov-Short, Amsterdam 1991. (Despite the material deficit, Black keeps some pressure. For example:)}) 26. Kg2 Bd4 27. Rc1 $1 Bb3 $1 (27... Bb2 28. Rc2 $1 Bxa3 29. Rd1 {is awkward.}) 28. Bc4 a4 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gd4f6,Gg7g5,Gd8d4] is annoying, as White will not want to capture and give Black a powerful passed b-pawn.} *

