s rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. bxa5 {Capturing is by far the most common choice for White.} Rxa5 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. a4 {This is an somewhat unusual structure in the QGD, but it is not uncommon in the Tartakover. White restrict ...b5 and hopes to combine pressure on the queenside with the possibility of an e3-e4 break.} ({Sometimes White starts with a rook move, but we'll just transpose after} 15. Rab1 Nd7 16. a4) ({or} 15. Rfe1 Nd7 16. a4) 15... Nd7 {We could look at some little deviations, but we'll stay consistent because White can vary the move order as described above. Black has various ideas here. Trading off the passive light-squared bishop with ...Ba6 is a common theme, sometimes combined with ...Qa8, which also puts some pressure along the a-file. The bishop may relocate to the more active d5-square.} ({I will mention though that in this exact position Black can play} 15... Bc8 $5 {intending ...Be6. The point is that} 16. Rfb1 {can be met with} Bf5 $1 {hitting the rook and giving us time to play ...Nd7.}) 16. Rfd1 {This move dissuades us from playing ...c5, but that was not our intention anyway.} Ba6 {[%cal Gd8a8,Ge8e6,Yf6d8,Yd8c7] Black should not have any problems here. In addition to the ideas outlined above, ...Re6 and ...Bd8-c7 are possible too.} *

