1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Be2 {An apparently modest move, this is very popular and is a serious try.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {This is White's idea - now that the bishop is committed to b7, White fixes the pawn structure.} (9. Rc1 {transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 {again transposes to 8.Rc1}) (9. cxd5 {is strangely timed.} Nxd5 {Black exchanges some pieces and achieves ...c5 effortlessly.} 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O {both 11.Rc1 and 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Rc1 transpose to 8.Rc1} Nxc3 12. bxc3 c5 {is easy for Black.}) 9... Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Here White usually plays} 11. b4 {, trying to cramp Black's queenside, but castling immediately is not without venom. In both cases we will play ...c6.}) 11... c6 {This is the combative choice. Instead} (11... c5 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 Bc6 14. O-O Nd7 15. Bb5 Qc7 {is a well-known theoretical line where White has tried just about every imaginable queen move. This line is drawish, but in general White can push a little bit with very little risk.}) 12. O-O Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge5] Black has tried various things here, but I like this move the best. Black covers the e5-square before committing anything else. Instead} (12... a5 {was the traditional main line, but after} 13. b5 c5 14. Ne5 {White has done very well. Now ...Nd7 is prevented because of Nc6! and White is also preparing Bf3 and sometimes Ng4. Black may be ok somehow, but he certainly walks a tightrope. The natural}) (12... Nd7 13. Qb3 a5 $6 {has also been often played, but then} 14. b5 {undermines the d5-pawn. Black has generally offered a pawn here with} a4 15. Nxa4 c5 {but I do not really buy it after the simple} 16. Nc3 {Finally there is}) (12... Qd6 {which guards the e5-square and hits the b4-pawn. But after} 13. Qb3 {White can bring his rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. bxa5 {Capturing is by far the most common choice for White.} Rxa5 15. a4 {This is an somewhat unusual structure in the QGD, but it is not uncommon in the Tartakover. White restrict ...b5 and hopes to combine pressure on the queenside with the possibility of an e3-e4 break. Sometimes White starts with a rook move, but we'll just transpose after} (15. Rab1 Nd7 16. a4 {or}) (15. Rfe1 Nd7 16. a4) 15... Nd7 {We could look at some little deviations, but we'll stay consistent because White can vary the move order as described above. Black has various ideas here. Trading off the passive light-squared bishop with ...Ba6 is a common theme, sometimes combined with ...Qa8, which also puts some pressure along the a-file. The bishop may relocate to the more active d5-square.} ({I will mention though that in this exact position Black can play} 15... Bc8 $5 {intending ...Be6. The point is that} 16. Rfb1 {can be met with} Bf5 $1 {hitting the rook and giving us time to play ...Nd7.}) 16. Rab1 Ba6 {[%mdl 32768]} (16... Qa8 {is fine too. Then} 17. Rfc1 Ba6 {will transpose.}) 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. Rfc1 Qa8 {[%cal Ge8e6,Gf6d8,Gd8c7] We've transposed to the last line.} *

