s rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. bxa5 {Capturing is by far the most common choice for White.} Rxa5 15. a4 {This is an somewhat unusual structure in the QGD, but it is not uncommon in the Tartakover. White restrict ...b5 and hopes to combine pressure on the queenside with the possibility of an e3-e4 break. Sometimes White starts with a rook move, but we'll just transpose after} (15. Rab1 Nd7 16. a4 {or}) (15. Rfe1 Nd7 16. a4) 15... Nd7 {We could look at some little deviations, but we'll stay consistent because White can vary the move order as described above. Black has various ideas here. Trading off the passive light-squared bishop with ...Ba6 is a common theme, sometimes combined with ...Qa8, which also puts some pressure along the a-file. The bishop may relocate to the more active d5-square.} ({I will mention though that in this exact position Black can play} 15... Bc8 $5 {intending ...Be6. The point is that} 16. Rfb1 {can be met with} Bf5 $1 {hitting the rook and giving us time to play ...Nd7.}) 16. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This looks the most dangerous to me. Black's queenside pawns are easy to cover, so White looks towards the center.} Ba6 {[%mdl 32768] We play this immediately to avoid White's possible e4 dxe4 Bc4 sequence.} ({Instead} 16... Qa8 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bc4 Rf8 19. Nxe4 c5 {also works out but it is needlessly complicated.}) 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. e4 dxe4 19. Nxe4 Re6 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5d5]} 20. Rad1 {This allows Black to implement his idea.} Ra5 {[%cal Ga5d5]} 21. d5 {We have to check this concrete move.} cxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Qxd5 {[%csl Rd7,Rd8][%cal Ge1d1,Ge4f6,Gd5d8] Now White is threatening to start taking things, starting with Nxf6+.} Be7 ({One of many moves to equalize.} 23... Qc8 {is another.}) 24. Rd1 {The pin looks annoying, but White's e4-knight is a bit loose too.} Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gd7f6]} 25. Qxd7 Qxd7 26. Rxd7 Rxe4 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ge7c5,Yd7d4,Yd7a7] It's time for White to think about holding the draw.} *

