s rooks to the center and play along the lines of what we saw in the 11.0-0 line, but with Black's queen on d6, the e3-e4 advance is even more effective.}) 13. Qb3 ({By far the main move. The only real alternative is} 13. Rc1 {which transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 13... a5 $1 {A thematic strike in the Tartakover! Black scores very well here. This is our main position for the 11.b4 line. Black scores over 50%! White has three ways to play - push, protect, or take.} 14. bxa5 {Capturing is by far the most common choice for White.} Rxa5 15. a4 {This is an somewhat unusual structure in the QGD, but it is not uncommon in the Tartakover. White restrict ...b5 and hopes to combine pressure on the queenside with the possibility of an e3-e4 break. Sometimes White starts with a rook move, but we'll just transpose after} (15. Rab1 Nd7 16. a4 {or}) (15. Rfe1 Nd7 16. a4) 15... Nd7 {We could look at some little deviations, but we'll stay consistent because White can vary the move order as described above. Black has various ideas here. Trading off the passive light-squared bishop with ...Ba6 is a common theme, sometimes combined with ...Qa8, which also puts some pressure along the a-file. The bishop may relocate to the more active d5-square.} ({I will mention though that in this exact position Black can play} 15... Bc8 $5 {intending ...Be6. The point is that} 16. Rfb1 {can be met with} Bf5 $1 {hitting the rook and giving us time to play ...Nd7.}) 16. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This looks the most dangerous to me. Black's queenside pawns are easy to cover, so White looks towards the center.} Ba6 {We play this immediately to avoid White's possible e4 dxe4 Bc4 sequence.} ({Instead} 16... Qa8 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bc4 Rf8 19. Nxe4 c5 {also works out but it is needlessly complicated.}) 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. e4 dxe4 19. Nxe4 Re6 $1 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5d5]} 20. Ra2 $5 {[%cal Ga2e2] A clever move, intending to double rooks on the e-file.} Ra5 {[%mdl 32768] Following the script.} ({Instead} 20... Be7 21. Rae2 Bf8 {was seen in Korobov-Grischuk, Zagreb 2021. Here} 22. Neg5 $5 {looks dangerous for Black.} hxg5 23. Rxe6 fxe6 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. h4 $1 gxh4 26. Re4 {Scary.}) 21. Rae2 Rd5 {[%cal Rb3f7] Let's follow the plan, as blocking the white queen's diagonal is a good idea.} ({Note that} 21... Be7 $2 {gets killed by} 22. Nd6) 22. Qc4 {[%csl Rc6]} Nf8 $1 23. Nxf6+ gxf6 $1 ({The pawns may look ugly, but the position is simplified enough that it will not matter. Black is well centralized and more exchanges are coming. After} 23... Rxf6 24. Re8 {White kept some pressure in Lputian-A.Petrosian, Yerevan 1995.}) 24. Rxe6 Nxe6 {[%csl Rd4] White has a weakness too.} 25. Qxc6 {[%cal Ge1e8,Re6d4] We cannot take the d4-pawn yet because of Re1-e8.} Kg7 {[%cal Ge6d4] Now the pawn falls and Black is fine.} *

