1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3] This natural move is the most common overall, but not by much. White intends to develop smoothly with O-O and Qe2, and then he will be free to deploy his rooks however he likes. Often White will play Bh4-g3 to avoid certain exchanges as well. Black can develop his minor pieces easily enough, but then there's the old question - what to do with the queen? Black needs to trade at least one set of minor pieces. This will be attempted with ...Ne4, or perhaps ...Nh5. Pawn exchanges in the center may help too (for example, if White plays cxd5 we react with ...Nxd5, as always). Black just has to be careful that in his eagerness to trade pieces, he does not give White a big lead in development, which may turn into a tangible initiative.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. Bxf6 {This plan seems more appropriate with White's light-squared bishop on e2, where it does not block the d-file.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black will generally play ...c5 here, as the d3-bishop blocks White's queen from putting any pressure on the d5-pawn.} 11. Qb3 $6 {This is not an unusual setup for White, but the timing is off and we can strike immediately.} (11. Rc1 c5 {transposes to 9.Rc1.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%cal Gc5c4] We will see this idea again in the 8.Qb3 line.} 12. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {This is the main line, I just find 12...d4 to be simpler.} 13. c6 $1 {It's wise to give back the pawn to stabilize the position.} (13. cxb6 $2 Nc5 14. Qc2 Nxd3+ 15. Qxd3 Qxb6 $17 {with the idea ...Ba6 (...d4 is always in the air too) is just good for Black.}) 13... Bxc6 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gd5d4] White has to watch out for ...Nc5 and ...d4.} 14. O-O ({The untried} 14. Nd4 $146 {is very solid for White and equalizes. It's a normal position, but this is one reason that I went for 12...d4 as our main move.}) 14... Nc5 15. Qc2 ({After} 15. Qd1 {both 15...Ne6 $15 intending ...d4 and} Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rc8 $15 {with ideas like ...Ne4 or ...Na4, are better for Black.}) 15... d4 {Black forces exchanges and a symmetrical structure.} 16. exd4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 {With a totally equal position.} *

