1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3] This natural move is the most common overall, but not by much. White intends to develop smoothly with O-O and Qe2, and then he will be free to deploy his rooks however he likes. Often White will play Bh4-g3 to avoid certain exchanges as well. Black can develop his minor pieces easily enough, but then there's the old question - what to do with the queen? Black needs to trade at least one set of minor pieces. This will be attempted with ...Ne4, or perhaps ...Nh5. Pawn exchanges in the center may help too (for example, if White plays cxd5 we react with ...Nxd5, as always). Black just has to be careful that in his eagerness to trade pieces, he does not give White a big lead in development, which may turn into a tangible initiative.} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. Bxf6 {This plan seems more appropriate with White's light-squared bishop on e2, where it does not block the d-file.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black will generally play ...c5 here, as the d3-bishop blocks White's queen from putting any pressure on the d5-pawn.} 11. O-O (11. Rc1 c5 {transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 11... c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. dxc5 (12. Rc1 {is much more common. Again this transposes to the 8.Rc1 line.}) 12... bxc5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8e8]} 13. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3b7,Gc3d5,Gb3d5] The only move to disturb Black.} Bc6 {[%cal Gc5c4] Now ...c4 is a threat.} 14. Be2 {[%cal Gf1d1] The bishop dodges the double attack and clears the d-file for a rook.} (14. Bb5 d4 15. Bxc6 {was agreed drawn in an old Benjamin-Seirawan game.} Nxc6 {leads to simplifications which are fine for Black.}) 14... Nd7 {[%cal Ga8b8]} ({This is certainly good enough, but} 14... a5 $146 {is an interesting idea too.}) 15. Rfd1 $2 {This mistake was played by none other than Lajos Portisch.} Rb8 16. Qc2 Qa5 {[%cal Gb8b2,Gf6c3] There's too much pressure on White's queenside.} 17. Nd2 ({If} 17. Rab1 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 {( 18.bxc3? Ba4 wins immediately).} Qxa2 {is a free pawn.}) 17... c4 $17 {[%cal Gb8b2,Gf6c3,Gd7c5] This cramps White further while keeping the threats.} ({Vaganian played} 17... Rxb2 {which is good, but not nearly as strong. After} 18. Qxb2 Bxc3 19. Nb3 $1 Bxb2 $6 {( 19...Qb4! was better).} 20. Nxa5 Ba4 21. Rab1 $1 {White was ok and even went on to win in Portisch-Vaganian, Saint John 1988.}) *

