1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3] This natural move is the most common overall, but not by much. White intends to develop smoothly with O-O and Qe2, and then he will be free to deploy his rooks however he likes. Often White will play Bh4-g3 to avoid certain exchanges as well. Black can develop his minor pieces easily enough, but then there's the old question - what to do with the queen? Black needs to trade at least one set of minor pieces. This will be attempted with ...Ne4, or perhaps ...Nh5. Pawn exchanges in the center may help too (for example, if White plays cxd5 we react with ...Nxd5, as always). Black just has to be careful that in his eagerness to trade pieces, he does not give White a big lead in development, which may turn into a tangible initiative.} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. Bxf6 {This plan seems more appropriate with White's light-squared bishop on e2, where it does not block the d-file.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black will generally play ...c5 here, as the d3-bishop blocks White's queen from putting any pressure on the d5-pawn.} 11. O-O (11. Rc1 c5 {transposes to 8.Rc1.}) 11... c5 12. dxc5 (12. Rc1 {is much more common. Again this transposes to the 8.Rc1 line.}) 12... bxc5 13. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3b7,Gc3d5,Gb3d5] The only move to disturb Black.} Bc6 {[%cal Gc5c4] Now ...c4 is a threat.} 14. Be2 {The bishop dodges the double attack and clears the d-file for a rook.} (14. Bb5 d4 15. Bxc6 {was agreed drawn in an old Benjamin-Seirawan game.} Nxc6 {leads to simplifications which are fine for Black.}) 14... Nd7 {[%cal Ga8b8]} ({This is certainly good enough, but} 14... a5 $146 {is an interesting idea too.}) 15. Nxd5 {This does not lead to anything for White, but at least he is not worse.} Rb8 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qc3 Rxb2 18. Qxf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Gb2,Rc5][%cal Gf6d7,Gf8b8,Gb2e2] Black has enough activity to compensate for the isolated c5-pawn. Black can always cover it with ...Nd7. The position is equal, but there's still play left.} *

