5 (We go for 12...c6 there) 12.bxc5 bxc5 . Here White's d3-bishop interferes with his control of d4.} Bc6 {This keeps some play in the position, but we have to make sure we do not get pulled into an unfamiliar (and unpleasant) line.} (13... cxd4 {is a straightforward way to equality, it's just a bit boring. We will consider it as an alternative.}) 14. O-O c4 $132 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gb8d7] This is untried, but looks ok to me. It's important that we gain a tempo. Black can follow up with ...Qa5 and ...Nd7 with a complicated game. If you do not like this, then 13...cxd4 is fine.} ({It's important to avoid} 14... Nd7 {when} 15. Bb5 $1 {suddenly transposes to the aforementioned line above - a line we want avoid.}) *

