 12...c6 there) 12.bxc5 bxc5 . Here White's d3-bishop interferes with his control of d4.} Bc6 {This keeps some play in the position, but we have to make sure we do not get pulled into an unfamiliar (and unpleasant) line.} 14. Bb5 $146 {Untried, but a tricky move.} a6 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Ba4 $5 (15. Bxc6 Nxc6 {is easy for Black. The d4-pawn is still pinned.}) 15... cxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxa4 17. Qxa4 {Now we have a funny trick.} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gf6c3,Ga8c8,Gc8c3] A remarkable move!} 18. Qxc6 ({Black's advantage is clear after} 18. Nxc6 $6 Bxc3+ 19. Ke2 Qf6) 18... Bxd4 19. exd4 Re8+ {[%cal Ga8c8]} 20. Ne2 $2 {It looks like Black overlooked something.} ({Hanging out in the center with} 20. Kd2 $2 {also loses quicky.} Qg5+ 21. Kc2 {or 21.Kd3 Qf5+} Rac8 22. Qa4 Re2+ $1 23. Kb3 Rxc3+ 24. Kxc3 Qd2+ 25. Kb3 a5 $3 {Covering the b4-square - this leads to a forced mate.}) ({White should seek equality with} 20. Kf1 Rc8 21. Qxd5 Rxc3 22. Qxd8 Rxd8 23. Rd1) 20... Qa5+ {Black has a winning attack. For example:} 21. Kf1 ({Or} 21. Kd1 Qxa2 22. Nc3 Qxf2 {and White won't last long.}) 21... Rac8 22. Qb6 Qd2 23. Qb2 Rc2 {And it's lights out.} *

