1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Rc1 c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. cxd5 {Again we welcome exchanges.} ({More testing is} 11. Qe2 {reaching a line from 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Bxe7 ({And here} 12. Bg3 {would transpose to 10.Bg3.}) 12... Qxe7 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] White's play looks harmless, but there is one interesting possibility to be aware of.} 14. e4 Bb7 15. b4 $5 {Quite surprising! White trades a bunch of pieces and then offers a pawn.} Rfc8 ({We could take the pawn, but} 15... cxb4 16. Rc7 Bc8 17. d5 {does give White interesting compensation. This line is so rare that I prefer to keep things simple.}) 16. dxc5 ({The most logical. White tries to get a better pawn structure. Black is active after} 16. bxc5 bxc5 17. Qb3 Nf6 $15) 16... bxc5 17. b5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] This position would be good for White if he could make a couple of extra moves.} a6 {This negates any chances for a white advantage.} 18. a4 axb5 19. axb5 Nb6 {[%csl Gb6] Black is at least ok here - he is better developed and the c5-pawn is at least as strong as White's b-pawn.} *

