1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 ({There is a little trick here but it's easy enough to avoid. White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with} 10. Qe2 {, is a more serious try for an edge.}) 10... c5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. Rc1 {This is uncommon, but it has scored well.} ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... cxd4 (11... Ne4 {is possible as well, but White has lots of options here. I prefer a clearer solution. Now White is best off going for an IQP.}) 12. Nxd4 {This is harmless at best.} Nc5 {[%cal Gc5d3]} 13. Be2 dxc4 14. Bxc4 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gf6e4] Intending ...b5 or ...Nfe4. An easy position for Black.} *

