1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 {White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with 10.Qe2, is a more serious try for an edge.} c5 ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. Rc1 {This is uncommon, but it has scored well.} ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... cxd4 (11... Ne4 {is possible as well, but White has lots of options here. I prefer a clearer solution. Now White is best off going for an IQP.}) 12. exd4 {This looks like a better try.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. Bxc4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf6h5,Ga7a6,Ge7b4,Gc8c4] Gaining a tempo. This is a typical position in the IQP. White's Rc1 is rarely the most dangerous plan (White is better off bringing his rooks to e1 and d1 quickly). Black can play ...Nh5 next to get the bishop, while ...a6 and ...Bb4 are typical ideas as well..} *

