1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 {White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with 10.Qe2, is a more serious try for an edge.} c5 ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. cxd5 ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Rc1 {A natural move, but not very dangerous. Black has scored very well here, and he even has a choice.} N7f6 {[%mdl 32768] Perhaps the simplest.} ({Another idea is} 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nf6 14. Qe2 Ne4 {but we do not have a happy square for the queen.}) ({Black can play} 12... cxd4 13. Nxd5 {13.exd4?! N7f6 $15 is ideal for Black} Bxd5 {After} 14. e4 $1 Bb7 15. Bc7 Qe8 16. Nxd4 {intending Bb5, it's rather tricky. Black is ok here, but he has to be careful, and it's unnecessary.}) 13. Qe2 cxd4 ({Again Black could play} 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Ne4) 14. Nxd5 ({After} 14. exd4 $6 Rc8 $15 {is another easy position for Black.}) ({And} 14. Nxd4 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Rc8 {intending ...Ne4 is also harmless.}) 14... Nxd5 ({After the obvious} 14... Bxd5 15. Nxd4 {gives White the initiative. The c6-square is weak, and} Rc8 $6 16. Rcd1 $1 {intending e4, is very uncomfortable.}) ({The engine's first choice is} 14... Qxd5 {but be aware that} 15. Rc7 {practically forces a repetition:} Bd8 16. Bc4 Qe4 17. Bd3) 15. Nxd4 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1] White intends Rfd1.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c1,Gd8a8] This looks safe enough. We can trade rooks and play ...Qa8. I always liked this kind of move!} *

