1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 {White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with 10.Qe2, is a more serious try for an edge.} c5 ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. cxd5 ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 {We welcome trades, but White's move order hides some venom.} Bxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. Rc1 Nf6 {The solid move.} ({Here} 13... cxd4 14. e4 $5 Bb7 15. Bc7 Qe8 16. Nxd4 {intending Bb5 is a tricky line that was mentioned earlier. There's no reason to bother with this.}) 14. dxc5 Bxc5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gf6e4,Gf6h5,Gd5f3,Gd8d3] We have various ideas here. Typical moves are ...Ne4 and ...Nh5, while ...Bxf3 may also be considered, as the White would have to recapture with the pawn.} 15. Ne5 {A tricky move.} Bb7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd8e7,Gf8d8] An important prophylactic move. Now we are ready for ...Qe7 and bringing the rooks to the center.} ({Black must avoid} 15... Ne4 $2 16. Bxe4 $1 Bxe4 17. Qa4 {hitting the e4-bishop and threatening the double attack Ne5-d7.}) *

