1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Bg3 ({There is a little trick here but it's easy enough to avoid. White is trying to avoid exchanges, or at least carry them out on his own terms. This move, along with} 10. Qe2 {, is a more serious try for an edge.}) 10... c5 ({One trick to avoid is} 10... Ne4 $2 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 f5 13. Nb5 $16 {and Black is in trouble.}) ({While after} 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 $14 {Black has the usual problems with his queen.}) 11. cxd5 ({Instead} 11. Qe2 {transposes to 10.Qe2.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qe2 cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Nxd4 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gc5d3] We simply hit the bishop and consider ...Ne4.} ({Another solid choice is} 14... Bf6 15. Rfd1 Bxd4 16. exd4 Nb8 $1 17. Rac1 Nc6 {as played in the high-level games Ivanchuk-Kasimdzhanov, Tripoli 2004 and Nakamura-So, Saint Louis 2015.}) 15. Bb5 {[%csl Gc6] Eyeing the c6-square.} (15. Bc4 Qd7 {followed by bringing the rooks into play looks fine for Black.}) 15... Bf6 16. Rfd1 a6 {Forcing matters.} 17. Bc6 Bxc6 18. Nxc6 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8b7] We will just play ...Qb7 next with easy equality.} *

