1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gh4g3]} Ne4 ({This is Black's main alternative to our choice,} 10... c5) 11. Bxe7 (11. Bg3 {scores well too. We can make some exchanges here, so I am more concerned with with the direct play of the main line.}) 11... Qxe7 12. cxd5 Nxc3 ({I also prefer White after} 12... exd5 13. Rac1 $14 {even though Black remains very solid here.}) 13. bxc3 Bxd5 ({This avoids blocking in our bishop.} 13... exd5 14. a4 $14 {also looks more pleasant for White.}) 14. e4 {White gains some time. Sometimes this isn't an issue, but here White has not spent any tempi on rook moves so he can initiate play in the center immediately.} Bb7 15. e5 {[%csl Rd7] Our d7-knight lacks scope.} c5 16. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2e4,Gd2c4] White is better here. We will see a similar position later where White spent a move on Rac1. The tempo makes a difference.} *

