1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gh4g3]} c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. cxd5 ({Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now} 11. Rfd1) ({and} 11. Bg3 {are clearly the main moves.}) {As is often the case, this is premature as it invites the exchanges that Black craves.} 11... Nxd5 12. Bg3 {White should play this to avoid becoming worse.} ({After} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Black has exchanged pieces and the rooks come to the d- and c-files with a very easy game.} 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. e4 Bb7 {is very different from the informational line. White's center is under pressure and we will have no problem activating our knight (probably on c5 ) .}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd5 ({A necessary capture. After} 13. Nxd4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nc5 $17 {White has no compensation for his worse structure.}) ({while} 13. exd4 N7f6 $15 {is a comfortable IQP for Black.}) 13... Bxd5 14. Nxd4 {We have transposed to 10.Bg3 #8, where we saw that both:} Nc5 ({and} 14... Bf6 {are possible.}) *

