1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gh4g3]} c5 11. Rac1 ({Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now} 11. Rfd1 {and}) (11. Bg3 {are clearly the main moves.}) {The rook is good here with open center but it's less critical in an IQP structure, where the rooks are best on e1 and d1.} 11... Ne4 $5 {[%mdl 32768] This keeps some life in the position.} ({From a theoretical view,} 11... cxd4 {is fine.} 12. exd4 {Even worse is 12.Nxd4 Ne5!} dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nh5 14. Bxe7 {after 14.Bg3 the c1-rook is somewhat misplaced because it does not support the d5-break.} Qxe7 15. d5 {After this forcing move it's hard for either side to avoid an immediate draw.} Nf4 $1 16. Qe3 Qf6 17. Ne4 Qf5 18. Ng3 Qf6 {when White should just repeat moves because} 19. dxe6 fxe6 {gives Black the initiative.}) 12. Bxe7 ({Instead} 12. Bg3 cxd4 13. exd4 Nxg3 14. hxg3 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Nf6 16. Rfd1 {leads to 11.Rfd1}) 12... Qxe7 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge4c3,Gd5c4] Black is ready to start exchanging everything.} 13. cxd5 ({If White plays something like} 13. Rfd1 {Black can start capturing.} Nxc3 {and then ...dxc4 to open up the b7-bishop. Then the rooks come to the center and Black has no problems.}) 13... Nxc3 (13... exd5 {is possible too, but I'd rather not block in the bishop.}) 14. bxc3 ({Trying to strengthen the center.} 14. Rxc3 Bxd5 15. e4 Bb7 {is similar to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 10.O-O Nbd7 10.Rc1 .}) 14... Bxd5 15. e4 Bb7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8,Gd7f6] Black is fine here with simple moves. White should not get too ambitious.} 16. e5 $6 {This does not work out well for White here.} Rfd8 $1 {[%csl Rc1] Compared to the informational line, White has spent a move on Rac1.} 17. Nd2 cxd4 18. cxd4 Nf8 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8d4,Ge7d7,Gd2b3,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] White has problems with the d4-pawn.} *

