1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gh4g3]} c5 11. Rad1 {[%csl Rd1]} ({Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now} 11. Rfd1 {and}) (11. Bg3 {are clearly the main moves.}) {Generally speaking, the wrong rook, unless White gets an IQP. If the center remains fluid, the rooks are better placed on d1 and c1.} 11... Ne4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({White's rook is perfectly placed after} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 {In the IQP. The d4-d5 break is supported, and the other rook can come to e1 . A concrete line is 13...Nh5 14.Bxe7 Qxe7 15.d5 $16 Nf4 16.Qe3 Qf6 17.Ne4 Qf5 18.Ng3 Qf6 19.dxe6! and the d7-knight is hanging.}) 12. Bg3 (12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {is similar to StartFENr2q1rk1/pb1nbpp1/1p2pn1p/2pp4/2PP3B/2NBPN2/PP2QPPP/R4RK1 w - c6 0 11EndFEN 11.Rfd1 Ne4 12.Bxe7 Qxe7 but White's rooks are better on d1 and c1 as there's little to do on the e-file.}) 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 {This looks safe, but there's not much compensation for the bishop pair.} Nf6 15. cxd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rd1,Rf1] In this symmetrical structure, it's clear that White would prefer to have his rooks at d1 and c1.} 16. Ndb5 Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Qc7 $15 {[%csl Gb7,Ge7] Black was a little better in Adly-Kramnik, Baku 2016, although White managed to hold after a long defense.} *

