1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gh4g3]} c5 {Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now 11.Rfd1 and 11.Bg3 are clearly the main moves.} 11. Rad1 {[%csl Rd1] Generally speaking, the wrong rook, unless White gets an IQP. If the center remains fluid, the rooks are better placed on d1 and c1.} Ne4 ({White's rook is perfectly placed after} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 {In the IQP. The d4-d5 break is supported, and the other rook can come to e1 . A concrete line is 13...Nh5 14.Bxe7 Qxe7 15.d5 $16 Nf4 16.Qe3 Qf6 17.Ne4 Qf5 18.Ng3 Qf6 19.dxe6! and the d7-knight is hanging.}) 12. Bg3 (12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {similar to 11.Rfd1 Ne4 12.Bxe7 Qxe7 but White's rooks are better on d1 and c1 as there's little to do on the e-file}) 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 cxd4 14. exd4 $5 {Accepting the IQP is logical, as the f1-rook can come to the half-open e-file.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Going right for the IQP.} 14... Nf6 $5 {is also possible, maintaining the tension a little longer.} 15. cxd5 {After 15.Ne5 Black can transpose to the main line by taking on c4 , but 15...Rc8 is even stronger, as White has trouble creating threats.} Nxd5 16. Qe4 g6 17. Ne5 {ignores the eye of the b7-bishop and threatens to take on g6 and leads to some complications. 17...Nxc3 18.Qxb7 Nxd1 19.Nc6 Qd6 20.Nxe7+ Kg7 21.Nxg6 Nxb2 22.Nxf8 Rxf8 23.Bc2 Qxd4 24.Qxa7 Rd8= is one possible line.}) 15. Bxc4 {[%cal Gd4d5] White is ready for the d4-d5 break, so Black prevents it.} Nf6 16. Ne5 {[%cal Bc4g8] Now Nxf7 is in the air.} Bb4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Re5f7,Ga8c8,Gb4c3,Gd8e7,Gc8c7] Black seeks further exchanges and 'makes some room' as he can defend along his second rank.} 17. Z0 (17. Nxf7 {does not work here:} Rxf7 18. Bxe6 {or 18.Qxe6 Qe8 $17 17...Qe8 $17}) *

