1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O {By far the main line.} Nbd7 {Black has a solid position, but lacks a good square for his queen - quite typical on the QGD in general. Exchanges will help, but White does not have to be so cooperative.} 10. Qe2 c5 11. Bg3 ({Increasing the tension. Captures will help us exchange pieces. Now} 11. Rfd1 {and}) (11. Bg3 {are clearly the main moves.}) {A bit of a prophylactic move. White wants to keep pieces on the board.} 11... cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Reversing the captures with} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 cxd4 {is valid and would transpose if White took with the pawn, but this White has an extra option with} 13. Nxd4) ({The main alternative is} 11... Ne4 12. cxd5 exd5 {, but I don't like this structure as much. After 12...Nxc3 13.bxc3 Bxd5 14.e4 is not a good version of this kind of structure for Black - the queen has no good square.} 13. Rad1 Qc8 {is a well-known idea of Nigel Short. Black intends ...Nf6 and ...Qe6.}) 12. Nxd4 $6 {This makes no sense here. White's pieces will get chased around.} Nc5 13. Bc2 {Otherwise we would eat that tasty bishop.} dxc4 14. Qxc4 Rc8 $15 {[%cal Gc5e4] Black has the initiative.} *

