1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 {A natural move, lining up with the black queen and keeping c1 open for the other rook.} Ne4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 $14) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bxe7 {Black certainly will not end up with the bishop pair now, but we are happy to have a good square for our queen.} Qxe7 13. cxd5 exd5 ({Now our bishop is blocked, but we keep good control of the center. Instead} 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bxd5 15. e4 Bb7 {is a typical response, but} 16. d5 $5 {works tactically and looks a bit better for White.}) 14. dxc5 Nxc3 $1 15. bxc3 Nxc5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd5][%cal Ga8c8,Gc5e4,Gc5a4] I prefer Black here. The c3-pawn is weaker than our d5-pawn (there's a little saying, 'bad bishops protect good pawns!'). We can bring a rook to the c-file and ...Na4 is in the air.} *

