1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 Ne4 ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 $14) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bg3 {Of course the bishop can be taken now, but if Black cannot find a square for his queen, he will not connect his rooks and the position could easily become uncomfortable.} Nxg3 ({An obvious move, but it's a bit hasty. We will focus on} 12... cxd4) 13. hxg3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Gd1]} ({White does not want to block the d1-rook. Black must be careful already. Black has no complaints after} 14. exd4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Nf6 {and the d5-square is well defended.}) 14... dxc4 $4 ({'Opening the position for the bishops' is the idea, but White is too well centralized. Black has to play the cautious} 14... Nf6 15. Rac1 {when one line goes} Bb4 16. cxd5 Bxc3 17. Rxc3 Qxd5 18. Nf3 Qa5 {and Black is close to equality.}) 15. Bxc4 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd4e6,Gd1d7,Gc4e6] Black is already lost. There is no good defense to Nxe6!} *

