1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 Ne4 ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 $14) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bg3 {Of course the bishop can be taken now, but if Black cannot find a square for his queen, he will not connect his rooks and the position could easily become uncomfortable.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] This looks like the best move order.} 13. Nxd4 {This is not nearly as dangerous as it was in the informational line.} Nxc3 $1 ({Let's split those pawns.} 13... Nxg3 $6 14. hxg3 {transposes to the informational line.}) 14. bxc3 Nc5 $1 ({Again we have to avoid} 14... dxc4 $4 15. Bxc4 {with Nxe6 looking very scary. After} Bd5 {we save the piece but not the game.} 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nf5 $1 Nf6 18. c4 {and White wins a very important pawn.}) 15. Bb1 {Keeping c2 open for the queen.} ({It looks more natural to play} 15. Bc2 {but then} Ba6 $17 {is quite strong.}) 15... Qd7 $146 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gb7a6,Gd7a4] I like this move. We still have ...Ba6 as a possibility, and we don't have to consider White responding to ...Ba6 with Nd4-c6 anymore. The queen may also jump to a4.} ({Note that} 15... Ba6 16. Qc2 {breaks the pin with tempo.}) 16. cxd5 Qxd5 17. f3 Rfd8 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb7a6,Ga8c8,Ge3e4,Gd5g5,Gd5h5] White has no real compensation for Black's better pawn structure.} *

