1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 Ne4 ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 $14) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bg3 {Of course the bishop can be taken now, but if Black cannot find a square for his queen, he will not connect his rooks and the position could easily become uncomfortable.} cxd4 {This looks like the best move order.} 13. exd4 Nxg3 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Now that the d-file is blocked, we are happy to eat the bishop. I prefer to play against the IQP than the structure that arises after} 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Nf6 {although this is objectively fine as well.}) 14. hxg3 dxc4 ({Black could also wait a move and play} 14... Nf6 {first.}) 15. Bxc4 Nf6 {This is a nice looking IQP for Black. We have the bishop pair and the d4-pawn is nicely blockaded.} 16. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5f7] Looking for tactics. We have seen this position before, but with White's rooks on f1 and d1. Our reaction is the same.} ({Instead} 16. Rac1 Bb4 17. Ne5 {transposes.}) 16... Bb4 {[%cal Gd8e7] This gives us some space for defense.} 17. Rac1 ({Just like before,} 17. Nxf7 {does not work now.} Rxf7 18. Bxe6 Qe8 {or 18.Qxe6 Qe8 In both cases Black is better.}) 17... Qe7 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] Black has no problems. We may give up the bishop pair, but we have fine development and a healthier structure.} *

