1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1e2,Ga1c1,Ge1g1,Gh4g3]} Bb7 ({This is 10 times more popular than} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 {which transposes to the informational line with} 10. Be2 {dxc4 .}) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 c5 11. Rfd1 Ne4 ({This is Black's main move. After either} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 $14) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14 {we have the typical issues finding a square for our queen. Note that the standard} Nh5 $6 {idea does not work well here because of} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. d5 $1 {Now White has the usual choice - exchange bishops, or retreat.}) 12. Bg3 {Of course the bishop can be taken now, but if Black cannot find a square for his queen, he will not connect his rooks and the position could easily become uncomfortable.} cxd4 {This looks like the best move order.} 13. Bxe4 $6 {This is bad, but it was played in an all-GM encounter so let's see how to react.} dxc3 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({White has what he wants after} 13... dxe4 $2 14. Nxd4 {with a better structure and better minor pieces.}) 14. cxd5 cxb2 15. Qxb2 Bf6 $1 {Forcing White to self-pin.} 16. Ne5 Qe8 $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge8e5] Sidestepping White's rook and increasing the pressure on the e5-knight.} ({Black is ok after} 16... exd5 17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Nxe5 $5 19. Rxd8 Nf3+ {but we can do better!}) 17. f4 {The only move.} ({In Miralles-Renet, Lyon 1990 White played} 17. Kh1 $2 {trying to sidestep a future ...Nxe5-f3 check. Now} Rd8 {intending to simply take on d5 , is winning. For example 18.dxe6 Nxe5 19.Bxb7 Nd3! and Black will win at least an exchange.}) 17... Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4]} 18. Bf3 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Rd8 $17 {[%csl Gc5,Rg3][%cal Gf6e5] White has maintained material equality, but he will soon be left with a terrible structure and the inferior minor piece.} *

