1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Rd1 {This is typical setup for White in the QGD - Qc2 + Rd1, but it's not dangerous here because Black has solved the development problem of his light-squared bishop.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({The immediate} 9... Ne4 {has proven to be satisfactory as well.}) 10. cxd5 {This has been played the most often, but it's not very good. Simple development is easy to meet though.} (10. Bd3 c5 $15 {is very comfortable for Black. His minor pieces are well placed if the center opens.}) (10. Be2 Ne4 {is also easy. Black gets his exchanges in, and again, why is White's queen on c2?! It's not that it's bad there, but it's not part of a particular plan, and Black is already ahead in development.}) 10... Nxd5 {Now White is faced with the usual choice - trade or retreat.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] This is fantastic for Black. he has a nice lead in development, and ...c5 is coming.} 13. e4 {White is still trying to get an advantage, but he is not well developed and this loosens up his pawn structure.} ({White cannot take the pawn with} 13. Qxc7 $4 {as after} Rfc8 14. Qf4 Bxf3 $1 15. Qxf3 Qb4+ {wins quickly.}) ({Perhaps} 13. Be2 {is relatively best, but} c5 $15 {is clearly comfortable for Black.}) 13... Bb7 14. Bd3 c5 {Of course we strike.} 15. O-O Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c2]} 16. Qe2 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 $17 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4,Re4][%cal Gf8d8]} 18. Z0 ({White's position is much worse than it may appear to be at first. Black's initiative is hard to contain.} 18. Rfe1 Nxd3 19. Qxd3 Rfd8 20. Qe2 $2 {20.a3 Qf6! 21.Qe3 Bxe4! 22.Qxe4 Rc4 wins a pawn} Qb4 21. a3 Qa4 22. f3 $2 {A strange blunder. However, 22.Nf3 Rxd1 23.Rxd1 Qxe4-+ is a good pawn with a better position.} Rxd4 {0-1 Degerman-Haba, Pula 1997.}) *

