1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Rd1 {This is typical setup for White in the QGD - Qc2 + Rd1, but it's not dangerous here because Black has solved the development problem of his light-squared bishop.} Nbd7 ({The immediate} 9... Ne4 {has proven to be satisfactory as well.}) 10. cxd5 {This has been played the most often, but it's not very good. Simple development is easy to meet though.} (10. Bd3 c5 $15 {is very comfortable for Black. His minor pieces are well placed if the center opens.}) (10. Be2 Ne4 {is also easy. Black gets his exchanges in, and again, why is White's queen on c2?! It's not that it's bad there, but it's not part of a particular plan, and Black is already ahead in development.}) 10... Nxd5 {White is faced with the usual choice - trade or retreat.} 11. Bg3 c5 12. dxc5 Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8c5] A maximalist approach.} (12... Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Qc8 $1 {is also very strong} 14. cxb6 Qxc3+ 15. bxc3 Nxb6 {gives Black more than enough for the pawn.}) (12... Nxc5 {is fine because} 13. e4 $2 {is well met with} Nb4 {but Black can do better.}) 13. e4 $2 {This is sharp, but bad.} (13. Nxd5 Bxd5 $17 {is great for Black too.} 14. e4 {can be met with} Bxc5 $1 {threatening ...Bb4+}) (13. cxb6 $2 Bb4 $17 {is disastrous.}) 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Rxc5 {White's structure is a wreck and he's behind in development.} 15. Ne5 {The only way to try to justify White's play.} Bf6 $1 ({This is even stronger than} 15... Nxe5 16. Rxd8 Rxd8 $13 {as played in Romanishin-Beliavsky, Moscow 1983. Black has great compensation, but he is not winning.}) 16. Nxd7 {Relatively best.} Bxc3+ {[%mdl 32768]} 17. Ke2 {Now Black only has one move to justify his sacrificial play, but it's winning.} Rc4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb7a6]} 18. Nxf8 {Let's check other moves too.} (18. f3 Ba6 $1 {is crushing.}) (18. Ne5 Rd4 $1 19. Rxd4 Qxd4 {with various ideas like ...Rc8 and ...Bxe4.}) (18. Nc5 {is clever, but we have the even more clever} Bd5 $1 19. exd5 exd5 {and the open e-file will be White's undoing.}) 18... Qg5 $17 {[%cal Gb7a6,Gb7e4] Black is down a rook and a knight, but White faces too many threats.} *

