1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh2h4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} ({White can also start with a pawn move - both} 11. h4 c5 12. O-O-O) ({and} 11. g4 c5 12. O-O-O {will transpose to the main lines.}) (11. Rd1 {is certainly playable, but it does not really fit into any particular scheme for White. Black can just continue with normal moves.}) (11. Be2 {is also rather vague. Compared to the line with 8.Be2, White has played Qc2 instead of the more useful b4 or O-O. A nice example of Black's play:} c5 12. Rd1 Nd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qf5 $6 g6 15. Qf4 Bg7 16. Rd2 Qf6 17. Qg3 Qe7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. a3 Nf6 20. Ne5 $6 cxd4 21. exd4 Ne4 22. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {was Feller-Grischuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Black has the bishop pair as usual, but now he has the better pawn structure too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center! Now White should really get going with his kingside demonstration, but he can also take on c5.} 12. Kb1 $2 {This is just too slow.} Nc6 13. dxc5 $2 {It appears that the d5-pawn is vulnerable now, but this makes matters worse.} Nb4 $1 14. Qb3 bxc5 15. a3 Bxc3 $1 16. Qxc3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Gb7e4] Black is winning. White's attack never even started and his own king is going to get shredded. A classic example:} 17. Z0 (17. exd4 Be4+ 18. Ka1 Nc2+ 19. Ka2 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Rc8 21. Qd2 Qb6 22. f3 Bd5+ 23. Kb1 Nxa3+ 24. Ka1 Rfd8 25. bxa3 Bb3 26. Rb1 Rxd4 {P.Benko-S.Reshevsky, 5th matchgame, New York 1960.}) *

