1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {[%cal Gh2h4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} ({White can also start with a pawn move - both} 11. h4 c5 12. O-O-O) ({and} 11. g4 c5 12. O-O-O {will transpose to the main lines.}) (11. Rd1 {is certainly playable, but it does not really fit into any particular scheme for White. Black can just continue with normal moves.}) (11. Be2 {is also rather vague. Compared to the line with 8.Be2, White has played Qc2 instead of the more useful b4 or O-O. A nice example of Black's play:} c5 12. Rd1 Nd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qf5 $6 g6 15. Qf4 Bg7 16. Rd2 Qf6 17. Qg3 Qe7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. a3 Nf6 20. Ne5 $6 cxd4 21. exd4 Ne4 22. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {was Feller-Grischuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Black has the bishop pair as usual, but now he has the better pawn structure too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center! Now White should really get going with his kingside demonstration, but he can also take on c5.} 12. Kb1 $2 {This is just too slow.} Nc6 13. h4 Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc8f5][%mdl 32768] Black intends ...Nb4 and ...Bf5.} 14. a3 cxd4 15. Nxd4 ({If} 15. exd4 Bg4 $17 {targets the d4-pawn - Black has completely taken over the initiative.}) 15... Nxd4 16. exd4 {Here the simplest is:} Bxh4 $17 {Black has an extra pawn and a good position.} ({I will mention that the engine is excited about the funny} 16... Rb8 $5 {intending to push the b-pawn.}) *

