, but he can also take on c5.} 12. dxc5 $6 {White switches his attention to the apparently vulnerable d5-pawn. This is the main alternative to the pawn advances, but it's not very good. It's been played a lot and was used successfully by a young Kasparov, so it's important to know how to react.} Bxc3 $1 ({A) Black must avoid} 12... bxc5 $6 13. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 14. Bc4) ({B) The traditional move is} 12... Nd7 {, and this is also good.} 13. c6 $1 {( 13.cxb6 Bxc3 14.bxc3 axb6 $17 ) ( 13.Nxd5 Nxc5 14.Bc4 b5! Kasparov-I.Zaitsev, Baku 1980.)} Bxc6 14. Nd4 Bb7 {both practice and the engines show that Black is a little better, but White is more solid here compared to 12...Bxc3!}) 13. Qxc3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gb6c5,Ga8c8] This is a highly thematic idea.} ({After} 13... bxc5 {White can grab the pawn with} 14. Qxc5 {.}) 14. c6 {Practically forced.} ({If} 14. Kb1 bxc5 $17 {Black's king is much safer.}) 14... Bxc6 15. Kb1 {It's best to leave the c-file. This position looks pretty solid for White, as the powerful f6-bishop is gone and White has d4 for his knight, but Black's initiative is still quite strong.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc6a4] threatening ...Ba4.} 16. Qd4 Nc5 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gc5e4]} 17. Bd3 {The e4-square is important.} Nxd3 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. Qxd3 d4 $146 {Setting the bishop free. We could stop here but let's go a little further.} (18... Qf6 {intending ...d4 next, is good too, but there's no reason to wait.}) 19. Qxd4 ({A)} 19. Nxd4 Bxg2 20. Rhg1 Qd5 $1 {leaves Black with a strong bishop. Already ...Be4 is a threat.}) ({B)} 19. exd4 Qf6 {pressures the f3-knight and plans ...Rfd8. 19...Bd5= $13 is good too. The bishop dominates.}) ({C)} 19. e4 $5 Qf6 {pins the knight to the f2-pawn and prepares ...Rfd8. ( 19...Qe7 20.Rhe1 Rfe8 21.e5 Rcd8 is also good.)} 20. Qxd4 $2 Qg6 {attacks the g2- and e4-pawns.}) 19... Qe7 {[%cal Gc6e4,Gf8d8,Gc8c2] Black has plenty of compensation here. His bishop is powerful and his king is safer.} *

