1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} ({White can also start with a pawn move - both} 11. h4 c5 12. O-O-O) ({and} 11. g4 c5 12. O-O-O {will transpose to the main lines.}) (11. Rd1 {is certainly playable, but it does not really fit into any particular scheme for White. Black can just continue with normal moves.}) (11. Be2 {is also rather vague. Compared to the line with 8.Be2, White has played Qc2 instead of the more useful b4 or O-O. A nice example of Black's play:} c5 12. Rd1 Nd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qf5 $6 g6 15. Qf4 Bg7 16. Rd2 Qf6 17. Qg3 Qe7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. a3 Nf6 20. Ne5 $6 cxd4 21. exd4 Ne4 22. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {was Feller-Grischuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Black has the bishop pair as usual, but now he has the better pawn structure too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center!} 12. h4 (12. g4 Nc6 13. h4 {transposes to the main lines. 13.dxc5? opening both long diagonals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 {This is necessary.} (14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. exd4 Bxh4 $17 {is a good pawn.}) 14... g6 {White should act quickly. This closes the b1-h7 diagonal. Black may also retreat with ...Bg7 with the idea of meeting g5 with ...h5 and h5 with ...g5, keeping the kingside closed. White should act quickly.} 15. h5 $6 {This is bad, but we have to check it.} g5 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Qf5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1d3] White has dreams of mate, but it's not so difficult to stop one threat. The attack on the d5-pawn can be ignored.} Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gf8h8,Gb7c8] Now we have ...Rh8 to defend, and ...Bc8 is a very serious idea.} ({In practice Black has gone for} 16... Nb4 {intending ...Bc8. This is also good. After} 17. Ne5 Bc8 18. Qf3 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Be6 {or the immediate 18...Be6 Black is fine. Our move is more ambitious.}) 17. Rg1 {[%csl Gg4] The best try. White moves off of the long diagonal and covers the g4-pawn.} Bc8 $5 {This looks best.} (17... Qc8 {and}) (17... Ne7 {are both fine too.}) 18. Qxd5 (18. Qc2 Be6 $17 {just leaves Black with the bishop pair and safer king.}) 18... Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Rd5,Rf3,Gf6][%cal Gb7f3,Ga8c8] Black has great compensation here.} *

