nals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 {This is necessary.} (14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. exd4 Bxh4 $17 {is a good pawn.}) 14... g6 {White should act quickly. This closes the b1-h7 diagonal. Black may also retreat with ...Bg7 with the idea of meeting g5 with ...h5 and h5 with ...g5, keeping the kingside closed. White should act quickly.} 15. h5 $6 {This is bad, but we have to check it.} g5 16. Qf5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1d3] White has dreams of mate, but it's not so difficult to stop one threat. The attack on the d5-pawn can be ignored.} Kg7 $1 {[%cal Gf8h8,Gb7c8] Now we have ...Rh8 to defend, and ...Bc8 is a very serious idea.} ({In practice Black has gone for} 16... Nb4 {intending ...Bc8. This is also good. After} 17. Ne5 Bc8 18. Qf3 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Be6 {or the immediate 18...Be6 Black is fine. Our move is more ambitious.}) 17. Nxd5 $2 {This loses to a shocking retort. Other failures are easier to deal with:} (17. Bd3 $2 Rh8 {leaves the white queen looking vulnerable.} 18. Nxd5 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 {is great for Black.}) (17. Qxd5 $2 Qxd5 $5 18. Nxd5 Na5 {wins material.}) (17. Ne5 $2 Nxd4 $1 18. Rxd4 Bc8 $1 {drives the queen away.} 19. Qf3 Bxe5 20. Rxd5 Bb7) 17... Nb4 $3 {[%mdl 32768] We have to know about this one.} 18. Nxb4 Qc8+ $1 {[%csl Rf3] Black is winning.} 19. Qxc8 Raxc8+ 20. Kb1 Bxf3 {And it's over.} *

