1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} ({White can also start with a pawn move - both} 11. h4 c5 12. O-O-O) ({and} 11. g4 c5 12. O-O-O {will transpose to the main lines.}) (11. Rd1 {is certainly playable, but it does not really fit into any particular scheme for White. Black can just continue with normal moves.}) (11. Be2 {is also rather vague. Compared to the line with 8.Be2, White has played Qc2 instead of the more useful b4 or O-O. A nice example of Black's play:} c5 12. Rd1 Nd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qf5 $6 g6 15. Qf4 Bg7 16. Rd2 Qf6 17. Qg3 Qe7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. a3 Nf6 20. Ne5 $6 cxd4 21. exd4 Ne4 22. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {was Feller-Grischuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Black has the bishop pair as usual, but now he has the better pawn structure too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center!} 12. h4 (12. g4 Nc6 13. h4 {transposes to the main lines. 13.dxc5? opening both long diagonals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Kb1 {A slow move, but one that is typical in all kinds of openings when White castles long.} ({The immediate} 17. a3 {can me met with} Qd6 {with the idea ...a6, ...b5.}) 17... Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc8f5] This is a thematic move which improves the bishop. Black threatens ...Bf5, as Bd3 would run into ...Nb4.} 18. a3 b5 $5 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga8b8] A clever computer move. Black declined to grab a pawn on the kingside a few moves ago, and now he offers one to open lines to the white king.} ({The immediate} 18... Bf5 {can be answered with} 19. Bd3 {.}) ({While} 18... Bg4 {is met with} 19. Be2 {.}) 19. Bxb5 {White may as well take, as lines will open up in any case.} Bf5 20. Bd3 Bg4 $1 21. Be2 Rb8 {[%csl Rb1,Rd4][%cal Gd8a5,Gf8c8] After some shuffling with the bishops, we can see that Black has good compensation. Both ...Qa5 and ...Rfc8 are coming.} *

