transposes to the main lines. 13.dxc5? opening both long diagonals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Rh4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gd1h1] This is a smart move. White lends some extra protection to the d4-pawn and hopes to eventually double rooks on the h-file. It's also useful to guard the g4- and f4-squares from Black's typical ideas ...Bc8-g4 and ... Qd6-f4.} Re8 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. Bh3 $6 {This has been seen in practice.} ({Of course} 18. Bd3 $2 {runs into} Nb4 {.}) ({Perhaps White should play something solid like} 18. Qd2 {in which case we can start our own play with} a6 {intending ...b5, with a sharp game ahead.}) 18... b5 $1 ({The immediate} 18... Bc8 $17 {also looks good.}) 19. Kb1 (19. Nxb5 Rb8 {with the idea ...Ba6 is already almost -3 according to Stockfish!}) 19... Bc8 ({Or} 19... Rb8 $17 {.}) 20. Bxc8 Rxc8 $17 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd8a5,Gc8c2] Black had a very strong attack in Cramling-Vaganian, Biel 1994.} *

