1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qc2 {Apparently a quiet move, but White usually has aggressive intentions.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Certainly the main continuation. White fixes the center in anticipation of a flank attack.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O-O {This is the big idea. With the center relatively fixed, White goes queenside and prepares a kingside pawn advance, counting on the 'hook' on h6 to open the position. White has scored rather well here, but today's engines prefer Black. The coming play is sharp, but Black is clearly holding his own. I have played this way myself with White, but honestly I always thought that while the idea was fun, it was a bit questionable objectively. Black has not done anything wrong, so there's no reason to expect that he should be in any trouble.} ({White can also start with a pawn move - both} 11. h4 c5 12. O-O-O) ({and} 11. g4 c5 12. O-O-O {will transpose to the main lines.}) (11. Rd1 {is certainly playable, but it does not really fit into any particular scheme for White. Black can just continue with normal moves.}) (11. Be2 {is also rather vague. Compared to the line with 8.Be2, White has played Qc2 instead of the more useful b4 or O-O. A nice example of Black's play:} c5 12. Rd1 Nd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Qf5 $6 g6 15. Qf4 Bg7 16. Rd2 Qf6 17. Qg3 Qe7 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. a3 Nf6 20. Ne5 $6 cxd4 21. exd4 Ne4 22. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {was Feller-Grischuk, Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. Black has the bishop pair as usual, but now he has the better pawn structure too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] Grunfeld style, with White's king of the queenside. Other moves have been tried, but this strikes me as being the most logical. Play in the center!} 12. h4 (12. g4 Nc6 13. h4 {transposes to the main lines. 13.dxc5? opening both long diagonals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4,Gf4h4] Sensible. White has designs on Qf4-h4 ideas.} Qd6 {[%csl Gf4][%mdl 32768] Preventing White's plan.} 18. Kb1 Rfe8 $5 {This is a useful move which is not too committal. We also give the e5-square some extra protection.} ({Black play could play} 18... a6 {but White can try} 19. Ne5 $5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Bxe5 {when White can regain the pawn with} 21. Nxd5 {or 21.Bg2 first.}) 19. Rh4 {And now we'll go for our typical plan when there's nothing urgent happening.} a6 20. Ka1 b5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb5b4,Ge8e4] We have an interesting game. The engines prefer Black. One idea to consider is ...b4 followed by ...Re4, when the d4-pawn will feel some pressure.} *

