nals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4,Gf4h4] Sensible. White has designs on Qf4-h4 ideas.} Qd6 {[%csl Gf4] Preventing White's plan.} 18. Bb5 $5 {This is not a bad idea. White's bishop does not do much, so he is prepared to exchange it off.} Rac8 19. Rh4 {This is a better try. Black must take some care.} a6 {[%mdl 32768]} 20. Bxc6 Bxc6 21. Ne5 {[%cal Gf2f4] White wants to play f4 with a bind.} Rfe8 ({The computer thinks that} 21... Bxe5 22. dxe5 Qxe5 {is ok, but this looks scary to me.}) 22. f4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd2h2,Gd1h1] Now White is ready to double, or triple, on the h-file.} ({We would also meet} 22. Rdh1 {with} Bd7 {.}) 22... Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7f5] This is the only move! We have to counterattack before it's too late.} 23. Rdh1 Bf5 24. Qh2 {[%cal Gh4h8] White is not being very subtle.} Kf8 {[%cal Gf8e7] We can safely evacuate. Here is a fun sample line:} 25. Rh7 {[%cal Gh7g7] This prevents us from running and threatens to Rxg7.} Qb4 $1 26. Rxg7 Rxc3+ $1 27. bxc3 Qxc3+ 28. Kd1 Qxd4+ {Black has a perpetual check. Note that White can never exchange queens, as we could then safely take the rook on g7 and be up a couple of pawns.} *

