nals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 {transposes to the main line.} g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4,Gf4h4] Sensible. White has designs on Qf4-h4 ideas.} Qd6 {[%csl Gf4] Preventing White's plan.} 18. Rh4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh4d4,Gf1d3,Gd1h1] This looks like the critical move. White gives the d4- extra protection and prepares his assault down the h-file.} Rac8 {This natural move has been played a couple of times, but I will make a different recommendation.} (18... Ne7 $2 {is too slow.} 19. Bd3 Bc8 20. Rdh1 Bf5 21. Ne5 {intending f4 and Qh2 is crushing, L. Perdomo - Pelikian, Sao Paulo 2015.}) 19. Kb1 {Vacating the c-file is obvious enough.} a6 20. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Ge1c2] This is a weird computer move. White prepares f4 and the knight heads for c2. This looks odd but it seems to work for White somehow.} ({Another potential issue is} 20. Bd3 Rc7 21. Ne5 $5 {Or 21.Rdh1 Re8 It's all complicated strategically. Unsurprisingly, both sides made mistakes in Bellon Lopez-Hellers, Sweden 2000, which ultimately ended in a draw.} Nxe5 22. dxe5 Qxe5 23. f4 $13 {looks a bit scary to me.}) 20... b5 21. Nc2 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4][%cal Gf1d3,Gd1h1] White covers some sensitive squares and prepares Bd3 and Rdh1.} b4 ({Unfortunately,} 21... Na5 $2 {runs into} 22. Nxb5 $1 {because our a5-knight is loose. We will see how we can avoid this issue by delaying ...Rac8.}) ({The natural} 21... Rfe8 $6 22. Bd3 $16 {does not help us much.}) 22. Na4 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf1d3,Gd1h1] I do not see a good way to continue here, while White's moves are easy to find.} *

