transposes to the main lines. 13.dxc5? opening both long diagonals is crazy. 13...Nb4 followed by ...bxc5 is totally winning for Black: -6 according to Stockfish!}) 12... Nc6 13. g4 cxd4 14. exd4 g6 {White should act quickly.} 15. g5 {This is the critical move.} hxg5 16. hxg5 Bg7 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ga8c8,Gf8e8,Yb7c8,Yc8f5] This has been played less than the pawn grab, but it's more ambitious, and much less scary! Black counts on his bishop pair. There are good squares for all of the pieces, and White's king is no safer than Black's.} 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4,Gf4h4] Sensible. White has designs on Qf4-h4 ideas.} Qd6 {Preventing White's plan.} 18. Rh4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gh4d4,Gf1d3,Gd1h1] This looks like the critical move. White gives the d4-pawn extra protection and prepares his assault down the h-file.} a6 $5 {[%mdl 32768] We will start with this flexible move.} 19. Bd3 ({Now if White plays that odd} 19. Ne1 $5 {we can similarly go} b5 20. Nc2 Na5 $5 {and because we refrained from ...Rac8, there is no} 21. Nxb5 $2 {trick because after} axb5 {our knight remains protected!}) 19... b5 20. Rdh1 Rfe8 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gb5b4,Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Ga8d8] With a sharp game. I think Black's play is easier.} *

