1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qb3 {This is a funny looking move. White waits for the bishop to go to b7 before fixing the center.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxf6 {White embarks on a familiar plan. If White does not do this, Black can play normally as there's no reason for White's queen to be on b3.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d5] The main line. White looks to discourage the ...c5 advance.} (11. Bd3 $6 {transposes to the line 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Qb3?!}) (11. Be2 c6 12. O-O Re8 {is likely to transpose to a line from 8.Be2. For example} 13. Rfe1 Nd7 {is a line that usually arises from 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.0-0}) 11... Re8 $1 {Black does not commit the c-pawn yet, preferring to line up his rook against White's uncastled king.} (11... c5 {is premature because of} 12. dxc5) ({After} 11... c6 12. Bd3 {White has his ideal setup in this structure - the bishop going to d3 in one move. He intends to castle and play for a quick e3-e4. Nevertheless, after 12...Na6 13.O-O the rare 13...c5!? still seems satisfactory for Black despite the lost tempo.}) 12. a3 $5 {This is a funny, but admittedly clever, waiting move. White does not want to bring the bishop to d3 just yet, as it can be vulnerable to a knight coming to c5, as we will see. The queen also gains an escape on a2. It's hard to believe that White can goof around with a pawn move where when he's still a couple of moves away from castling, but sometimes when playing White one can get away with a couple of small liberties.} c6 {This appear to be a bit compliant, but it's a practical way to deal with this rare sub-variation.} ({Instead} 12... c5 {is the most direct, and opening the position certainly looks logical.} 13. dxc5 Nd7 {The negative aspect is that there is no vulnerable white bishop on d3.} 14. cxb6 $5 {is greedy but there's no refutation.}) (12... Qd6 $5 {is a decent alternative however. After} 13. Bd3 c5 14. dxc5 Bxc3+ 15. Qxc3 bxc5 {followed by ...Nd7, Black has a normal position.}) 13. Bd3 Nd7 ({The computer suggests the comical} 13... c5 $5 14. dxc5 Nd7 {suggesting that 12.a3 is not so important when comparing the line to the main positions that arise after 12.Bd3 c5.}) 14. O-O g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Gf1e1] This was played by Kasparov with Black a few times. White has setup his pieces in the ideal way, but he did have to spend a tempo on a3. This is a normal Tartakover middlegame.} (14... Nf8 {is also possible, and likely to transpose.}) 15. e4 {Untried, but thematic and the engine's choice. Kasparov faced slower play in a few games.} ({Both} 15. Rfe1 Nf8 16. Bb1 Ne6 {Korchnoi - Kasparov, London 1983}) ({and} 15. Rd2 Nf8 16. Rc1 Ne6 {Piket - Kasparov, Wijk aan Zee 2001 lead to more maneuvering.}) ({Kramnik mistimed the central break with} 15. Bb1 Bg7 16. e4 $6 Ba6 $1 17. Rfe1 Bc4 {and Black activated his bishop nicely in Kramnik-Kasparov, Moscow 2001.}) 15... Nf8 16. e5 Bg7 {[%cal Gf8e6,Gb7c8,Gd8e7,Ga8d8] The position is a lot like some lines that arise in the 8.Be2 variation, but here White has the move a2-a3 for free. This should not make a tremendous difference.} *

