1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Qb3 {This is a funny looking move. White waits for the bishop to go to b7 before fixing the center.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {White embarks on a familiar plan. If White does not do this, Black can play normally as there's no reason for White's queen to be on b3.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d5] The main line. White looks to discourage the ...c5 advance.} (11. Bd3 $6 {transposes to the line 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Qb3?!}) (11. Be2 c6 12. O-O Re8 {is likely to transpose to a line from 8.Be2. For example} 13. Rfe1 Nd7 {is a line that usually arises from 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.0-0}) 11... Re8 $1 {Black does not commit the c-pawn yet, preferring to line up his rook against White's uncastled king.} (11... c5 {is premature because of} 12. dxc5) ({After} 11... c6 12. Bd3 {White has his ideal setup in this structure - the bishop going to d3 in one move. He intends to castle and play for a quick e3-e4. Nevertheless, after 12...Na6 13.O-O the rare 13...c5!? still seems satisfactory for Black despite the lost tempo.}) 12. Bd3 {White is still going for the ideal setup, but Black is very quick with counterplay here.} ({Instead} 12. Be2 c6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfe1 {transposes to the line 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.0-0}) 12... c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This thematic pawn sacrifice is completely sound.} 12... c6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rfe1 Nf8 15. e4 {is ideal for White, although the position is still complex after} Ne6 16. e5 Be7) (12... Nc6 $5 {intending ...Na5 and then ...c5, is another idea, but I prefer the immediate strike.}) 13. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] The point - the knight is coming to c5 no matter what.} 14. cxb6 $6 {This is too greedy, but it's a pawn, so we'll tackle this first. It's good to see how Black can develop his initiative.} Nc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b3,Gc5d3,Gb7a6]} ({Instead} 14... d4 {would be very strong, but White has} 15. Bb5 $1 {when Black has to find equality. It looks like best play leads to a draw:} a6 $1 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. O-O Bxf3 18. gxf3 Re5 19. Ne4 Rxe4 20. fxe4 Qg4+ {with perpetual check.}) 15. Qc2 Nxd3+ $1 ({This is both simpler and stronger than} 15... Qxb6 {when} 16. Be2 $1 {preserves the bishop.} d4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Bb7 19. Nf5 $132 {gave White his share of play in Kraai - Goldin, San Diego 2006.}) 16. Qxd3 $6 {This looks natural enough, but...} Qxb6 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb7a6] Now ...Ba6 is coming and Black is already winning.} 17. Nd4 {White hopes to block things up.} Ba6 18. Qd2 Bxd4 $1 {White falls apart.} 19. Qxd4 Qxb2 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8c8,Ga8b8]} ({White is playing down a rook and he cannot survive.} 19... Qxb2 20. Qd2 {20.Rd2 Qc1+ 21.Rd1 Qa3} Qa3 {and there are too many threats like...d4 and ...Rab8.}) *

