to see how Black can develop his initiative.} Nc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5b3,Gc5d3,Gb7a6]} ({Instead} 14... d4 {would be very strong, but White has} 15. Bb5 $1 {when Black has to find equality. It looks like best play leads to a draw:} a6 $1 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. O-O Bxf3 18. gxf3 Re5 19. Ne4 Rxe4 20. fxe4 Qg4+ {with perpetual check.}) 15. Qc2 Nxd3+ $1 ({This is both simpler and stronger than} 15... Qxb6 {when} 16. Be2 $1 {preserves the bishop.} d4 17. Nxd4 Bxg2 18. Rg1 Bb7 19. Nf5 $132 {gave White his share of play in Kraai - Goldin, San Diego 2006.}) 16. Qxd3 {This looks natural, but...} Qxb6 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb7a6] Black is already winning.} 17. O-O {White evacuates his king, but the tactics work for Black.} Ba6 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. Nxd5 ({It's safer to play} 18. Qd2 {but after} Bxf1 19. Rxf1 Rac8 {Black's pieces are very active and the exchange will count. White cannot grab the d5-pawn without dropping b2 , and Black can always take on c3 .}) 18... Bxd3 19. Nxb6 Bxf1 20. Nxa8 {Has White wiggled out?} Be2 {Nope. Black will end up ahead a piece. For example:} 21. Nc7 Rc8 22. Rc1 Bxf3 ({Or} 22... Bd8 {immediately.}) 23. gxf3 Bd8 {And Black wins.} *

