1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. cxd5 {This has been played a lot but it's quite harmless.} Nxd5 {Of course we are looking to exchange some pieces.} 10. Bg3 c5 {This is already nice for Black. White has spent a couple of moves (8.Rc1, 9. Bg3) rather than developing, so Black can play very directly.} 11. Bd3 cxd4 12. exd4 {[%csl Rc1,Rg3] This can hardly be critical, to say the least. Here various moves are possible of course. One interesting possibility is:} Ba6 $5 {Exchanging the bishops. Black has a good position.} ({Both} 12... Nc6) ({and} 12... Nd7 {are fine as well.}) *

