1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. cxd5 {This has been played a lot but it's quite harmless.} Nxd5 {Of course we are looking to exchange some pieces.} 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {transposes.}) 10... Qxe7 {[%mdl 32768] Black has exchanged a set of minor pieces, has a good square for his queen, and a lead in development. It's not surprising that he scores well here.} 11. Bd3 {This looks normal enough, but the bishop may prove to be vulnerable here.} c5 $1 {The most ambitious.} ({Of course} 11... Rc8 12. O-O c5 {is possible here as well.}) 12. Nxd5 (12. dxc5 Nd7 $1 13. cxb6 $6 Rfd8 $1 {is similar.}) 12... Bxd5 13. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] A recurring idea in the Tartakower. Black is ready to recapture on c5 with a nice position.} 14. cxb6 $6 {The only testing move, but it's too greedy.} Rfd8 $1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gd5f3,Gd7e5,Ga7b6] Black has fantastic compensation for the pawn.} *

