1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. cxd5 {This has been played a lot but it's quite harmless.} Nxd5 {Of course we are looking to exchange some pieces.} 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 {transposes.}) 10... Qxe7 {Black has exchanged a set of minor pieces, has a good square for his queen, and a lead in development. It's not surprising that he scores well here.} 11. Be2 (11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Be2 Rc8 {will transpose.}) 11... Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5][%mdl 32768] Black prepares the ...c5 break.} ({Unfortunately,} 11... Nd7 $2 {fails to} 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Rxc7) 12. O-O ({Or} 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. O-O c5 14. dxc5 Rxc5 {, transposing.}) 12... c5 {White has nothing better than to start chopping.} 13. dxc5 Rxc5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Rxc5 Qxc5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6] Now White is the one ahead in development, but Black is just a move away from complete equality.} 16. Qa4 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Ga4e8] The best try, as it hinders all of the moves Black wants to make.} Bc6 $1 {Black protects himself along the a4-e8 diagonal and White's mini-initiative melts away.} ({Watch out for} 16... Nc6 $4 17. e4 {trapping the bishop. Even the desperate} b5 18. Bxb5 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxb5 {loses immediately to} 20. Nd4 $1) 17. Qf4 Nd7 18. Qc7 {This little invasion is easy to meet.} Bxf3 19. Qxc5 Nxc5 20. Bxf3 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d2] It's equal, but 'trending' for Black.} *

