1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. Be2 dxc4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] Timing is everything. Although White's 9.Rc1 was useful, it did use a tempo and White will be one move slower getting a rook to the d-file if we compare it to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 dxc4 9.Bxc4 Bb7 10.O-O Nbd7 11.Qe2 with Rfd1 coming. I do not like 9...Nbd7 because after 10.cxd5 we cannot make the desired recapture with the knight because 10...Nxd5? 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Bxe7 Qxe7 loses a pawn to 13.Rxc7 .} 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. O-O c5 12. Qe2 {In this position White would rather have a rook on d1 than c1.} a6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5] We would love to get ...b5 in - we would grab some space and make some room for both our queen and our d7-knight.} 13. a4 {Definitely best, but we'll take this trade of a-pawn moves. We've covered the b5-square while White has weakened b4. The only downside is that our a6-pawn requires protection, so we can't play ...Rc8 just yet.} (13. Rfd1 b5 14. Bb3 {would leave us all kinds of nice options. The most ambitious is} c4 $5) 13... cxd4 {The most direct.} (13... Ne4 {looks ok too}) 14. exd4 {We have seen before that the IQP is less dangerous with a rook on c1. For one thing, d4-d5 is less dangerous.} Nh5 {Thematic, but allowing a repetition.} (14... Re8 $5 {avoids the draw. Black can play ...Nh5 next.}) 15. Bxe7 (15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Nf6 {controls the d5-square. This easy for Black.}) 15... Qxe7 16. d5 {The only testing move, but it leads to a forced draw.} Nf4 17. Qe3 Qf6 $1 18. Ne4 (18. dxe6 $2 fxe6 $17 {leaves White under too much pressure on f3 and g2.}) 18... Qf5 {We have to keep our knight protected.} 19. Ng3 (19. Nd6 $2 Qg4 $17 {threatens mate and wins the d5-pawn for nothing.}) 19... Qf6 20. Ne4 Qf5 {Both sides must acquiesce to the repetition.} *

