1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. Be2 dxc4 $1 {Timing is everything. Although White's 9.Rc1 was useful, it did use a tempo and White will be one move slower getting a rook to the d-file if we compare it to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 dxc4 9.Bxc4 Bb7 10.O-O Nbd7 11.Qe2 with Rfd1 coming. I do not like 9...Nbd7 because after 10.cxd5 we cannot make the desired recapture with the knight because 10...Nxd5? 11.Nxd5 Bxd5 12.Bxe7 Qxe7 loses a pawn to 13.Rxc7 .} 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. O-O c5 12. Qe2 {In this position White would rather have a rook on d1 than c1.} a6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5] We would love to get ...b5 in - we would grab some space and make some room for both our queen and our d7-knight.} 13. a4 {Definitely best, but we'll take this trade of a-pawn moves. We've covered the b5-square while White has weakened b4. The only downside is that our a6-pawn requires protection, so we can't play ...Rc8 just yet.} (13. Rfd1 b5 14. Bb3 {would leave us all kinds of nice options. The most ambitious is} c4 $5) 13... cxd4 {The most direct.} (13... Ne4 {looks ok too}) 14. Nxd4 {White hopes to make use of his rooks on the open central files, while Black has to solve the usual issues regarding his queen.} Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gf6e4] A good square for the knight, and we may simplify by bringing a knight to e4.} 15. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Qe8 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gf6e4,Gc5e4][%mdl 32768] Again this typical move with the open c- and d-files. It's especially good here with white pawn is on a4. It may look a little awkward because the f8-rook is stuck, but it's only a temporary inconvenience.} 16. Bg3 $1 {White will use the bishop to try to cause some problems. This move also sets a trap that could be easy to miss.} (16. f3 $2 Nxa4 {is a free pawn}) (16. b3 Nfe4 {trades pieces and gives Black a fine position.}) 16... Nfe4 $1 ({It looks like White overlooked that his pawn was attacked, but after} 16... Nxa4 $2 17. Ncb5 $1 {threatens to win an exchange with either Nc7 or Nd6, and after} axb5 18. Bxb5 {the black queen will not find a safe refuge.}) 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Bc7 $1 {[%csl Rb6]} ({Sharp play.} 18. Be5 Bf6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 {and ...Qe7, is easy equality.}) 18... Qxa4 {We have to go for it.} 19. Bxb6 Qb4 {Black must be careful here, as White is fully mobilized.} (19... Rfc8 $2 {was played in Popchev-Delchev, Sofia 1989. Here} 20. Nxe6 $1 {works out well for White.}) 20. Bc7 {The only square for the bishop, but it sets up a threat!} Bd8 $1 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gb4e7] We know we are happy to exchange these bishops, but this move importantly creates a retreat for our queen!} ({After} 20... Rfc8 $2 {White shows his teeth with} 21. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 22. Rc4 {and our poor queen is trapped!}) ({Black could play} 20... Bf6 {but after} 21. f3 {precision is required.} Rfc8 $1 {21...Nc5? 22.Ba2! threatens Rc4 and causes problems} 22. Nxe6 Bxb2 $13 {is messy, but} 23. Rb1 Nc3 24. Qxb2 Qxc4 {seems to hold everything together.}) 21. Be5 (21. Bg3 Nxg3 22. hxg3 Bf6 $15 {is just the bishop pair for nothing.}) (21. Bxd8 Rfxd8 {is just equal.}) 21... Bf6 {[%cal Gb4e7] This is fine for Black too. Note that White cannot repeat moves.} 22. Bc7 $6 Rfc8 $1 {[%cal Gb4e7] This works now that our queen can come back to e7.} 23. Nxe6 $6 {[%cal Gc4e6,Ge6g8,Ge6c8] Tempting, but it does not work out well for White.} Kh8 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Re6] White has trouble extricating his pieces.} ({The computer indicates that somehow} 23... a5 $5 {is good too}) *

