1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Now that Black has brought the bishop to b7, White fixes the pawn structure. We saw this in the main lines of 8.Be2.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. cxd5 exd5 {Now White can go in two completely different directions - he can continue to develop with 11.Bd3, hoping to be better placed to break with e3-e4 than he was in the lines with the bishop on e2; or he can play 11.b4, looking to restrain Black's queenside pawns. According the engines, Black can play 11...c5 against either move here. There is certain logic to that approach, as White is not castled yet. Indeed, it would be simpler to consider that approach, but I don't think Black is bound to it, and we will attempt to keep things a bit more complicated.} 11. Bd3 {According to Ivan Sokolov White's idea with this line is to force an exchange on d4 and obtain a position with the d-pawns fixed, and then rely upon the superiority of his d3-bishop to the one on b7. Sokolov says that 'if White's idea is well executed, he will have a small but lasting advantage'. Well, nowadays computers can help us neutralize just about anything, but we have some idea what we'll up against now.} ({Instead} 11. Be2 c6 12. O-O Re8 13. b4 {will bring us to the 11.b4 line.}) 11... c5 $1 ({After} 11... c6 {White doesn't have to bother with b4 now.} 12. O-O {and White will play e3-e4 at some point. It's not fatal for Black, but White has a better version of the StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.O-O line, as his bishop is already on d3.}) 12. O-O {Now we have a position that could have also arisen from StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Rc1 . Black has many reasonable moves here. This is always nice if you forget something!} Nd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8e8,Gg7g6,Gd7f8] Simplest.} ({One of our Tartakover heroes, Nigel Short, once tried} 12... Re8 {here. Then} 13. dxc5 {is the most challenging. If} bxc5 14. Qb3 $1) (12... Na6 $5 {is an interesting move. The idea is to bring the knight to c7 and e6 - often a nice centralization that pressures d4.}) (12... cxd4 {is common - 'satisfactory, but lacking complexity' - Short.} 13. Nxd4 {13.exd4 Nc6 14.Bb1 Re8 looks fine to me. This is the structure that 'is supposed to favors White' but not sure I believe it. After 15.Qd3 g6 I like the bishop pair.} Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Ne2 Qd6 {was Yermolinsky-Short, Tallinn/Parnu 1998. Fine for Black, but very solid for White.}) 13. Bb1 {White has tried this a few times, but it looks weird to me. I guess there's some hope to play Qd3-h7 checkmate.} Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Gg7g6] Black looks to play ...Nf8-e6. This is perhaps a more natural route than that is considered after 12...Na6. Yes, we have to move the rook to make this happen, but ...Re8 looks like a pretty good idea anyway.} *

