hat could have also arisen from StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Rc1 . Black has many reasonable moves here. This is always nice if you forget something!} Nd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8e8,Gg7g6,Gd7f8] Simplest.} ({One of our Tartakover heroes, Nigel Short, once tried} 12... Re8 {here. Then} 13. dxc5 {is the most challenging. If} bxc5 14. Qb3 $1) (12... Na6 $5 {is an interesting move. The idea is to bring the knight to c7 and e6 - often a nice centralization that pressures d4.}) (12... cxd4 {is common - 'satisfactory, but lacking complexity' - Short.} 13. Nxd4 {13.exd4 Nc6 14.Bb1 Re8 looks fine to me. This is the structure that 'is supposed to favors White' but not sure I believe it. After 15.Qd3 g6 I like the bishop pair.} Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Ne2 Qd6 {was Yermolinsky-Short, Tallinn/Parnu 1998. Fine for Black, but very solid for White.}) 13. Bf5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5] This is a typical idea which puts pressure on both the d5- and c5-pawns indirectly. The white queen's path to d5 is opened, and there is the possibility of capturing the d7-knight, which helps protect the c5-pawn.} g6 {[%mdl 32768] Asking the bishop a question.} ({I find} 13... cxd4 {to be too panicky. After} 14. exd4 $1 g6 15. Bh3 $14 {the d7-knight has no squares, and} Re8 $2 16. Nb5 $1 {would be a big problem.}) (13... Re8 {is a valid alternative, but I'd like to poke the bishop first.}) 14. Bh3 Bg7 {I like the bishop here. Out of the way and nice and snug.} 15. dxc5 Nxc5 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gc5e4] We have the IQP but an active position. White's bishop looks strange on h3. It may come back to g2, but that's a lot of moves to fianchetto a bishop!} *

