hat could have also arisen from StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 11.Rc1 . Black has many reasonable moves here. This is always nice if you forget something!} Nd7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf8e8,Gg7g6,Gd7f8] Simplest.} ({One of our Tartakover heroes, Nigel Short, once tried} 12... Re8 {here. Then} 13. dxc5 {is the most challenging. If} bxc5 14. Qb3 $1) (12... Na6 $5 {is an interesting move. The idea is to bring the knight to c7 and e6 - often a nice centralization that pressures d4.}) (12... cxd4 {is common - 'satisfactory, but lacking complexity' - Short.} 13. Nxd4 {13.exd4 Nc6 14.Bb1 Re8 looks fine to me. This is the structure that 'is supposed to favors White' but not sure I believe it. After 15.Qd3 g6 I like the bishop pair.} Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. Ne2 Qd6 {was Yermolinsky-Short, Tallinn/Parnu 1998. Fine for Black, but very solid for White.}) 13. Bf5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5] This is a typical idea which puts pressure on both the d5- and c5-pawns indirectly. The white queen's path to d5 is opened, and there is the possibility of capturing the d7-knight, which helps protect the c5-pawn.} g6 {Asking the bishop a question. I find} (13... cxd4 {to be too panicky. After} 14. exd4 g6 15. Bh3 $14 {The d7-knight has no squares, and} Re8 $2 16. Nb5 $1 {would be a big problem.}) (13... Re8 {is a valid alternative however.}) 14. Bxd7 {Consistent.} cxd4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] An important in-between move!} ({The hasty} 14... Qxd7 $2 {runs into} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Ne4 $1 {and Black is basically lost.}) 15. Bc6 $5 {This gains a tempo.} (15. Nxd4 Qxd7 {is similar.}) 15... Bxc6 16. Nxd4 Bb7 {[%cal Gf6g7,Ga8c8,Gf8e8] Knights vs. bishops! Play is about equal. An illustration of Black's possibilities can be seen after} 17. Z0 (17. Qf3 Bg7 18. Rfd1 Rc8 19. Nde2 Qe7 20. Qg4 $6 {was Sadorra-Friedel, Internet 2011. White is looking for some Nxd5 tricks based on some attacks on the c8-rook. Here} h5 $1 {is strong, as White's tricks do not work.} 21. Qa4 {21.Nxd5 Qd6 22.Qg5 Bxd5 23.Qxd5 Qxd5 24.Rxd5 Bxb2 $15 with a bishop and a queenside pawn majority Black is a little better and now a thematic push:} d4 $5 22. Nxd4 {22.exd4 a6! with the idea ...b5 gives good play} Qg5 23. g3 h4 {and Black's bishops and kingside pressure give him excellent compensation for the pawn.}) *

