1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Now that Black has brought the bishop to b7, White fixes the pawn structure. We saw this in the main lines of 8.Be2.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Now White can go in two completely different directions - he can continue to develop with} 11. Bd3 {, hoping to be better placed to break with e3-e4 than he was in the lines with the bishop on e2; or he can play}) (11. b4 {, looking to restrain Black's queenside pawns. According the engines, Black can play} c5 {against either move here. There is certain logic to that approach, as White is not castled yet. Indeed, it would be simpler to consider that approach, but I don't think Black is bound to it, and we will attempt to keep things a bit more complicated.}) 11... c6 {[%mdl 32768] With this move Black keeps the game interesting.} 12. Qb3 $6 {[%csl Re1,Rf1,Rh1] This does not work so well with 8.Rc1 and 11.b4. White needs to get his kingside developed!} a5 $1 {This is well-timed. It makes perfect sense to create some action while White is still a couple of moves away from getting castled.} 13. bxa5 Rxa5 {[%cal Gc1b1,Gb8d7,Gb7a6,Gf8e8] Black simply has a better version of this structure which we saw in the 8.Be2 chapter. White usually wants a rook on b1 to pressure the b6-pawn. Here that would cost a tempo.} *

