1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rc1 {This is a good, flexible move. It may transpose to other lines, but there are independent ideas as well.} Bb7 9. Bxf6 {Now that Black has brought the bishop to b7, White fixes the pawn structure. We saw this in the main lines of 8.Be2.} Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 ({Now White can go in two completely different directions - he can continue to develop with} 11. Bd3 {, hoping to be better placed to break with e3-e4 than he was in the lines with the bishop on e2; or he can play}) (11. b4 {, looking to restrain Black's queenside pawns. According the engines, Black can play} c5 {against either move here. There is certain logic to that approach, as White is not castled yet. Indeed, it would be simpler to consider that approach, but I don't think Black is bound to it, and we will attempt to keep things a bit more complicated.}) 11... c6 {With this move Black keeps the game interesting.} 12. Qb3 $6 {This does not work so well with 8.Rc1 and 11.b4. White needs to get his kingside developed!} a5 $1 {This is well-timed. It makes perfect sense to create some action while White is still a couple of moves away from getting castled.} 13. a3 axb4 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. axb4 Qd6 15. Be2 Be7 $1 {A typical regrouping.} 16. Rb1 ({A sad necessity.} 16. b5 Ra3 17. Qc2 {or 17.Qb2 Qb4-+} c5 {is ideal for Black. White has no pressure, and Black has his usual stuff, plus the active a3-rook.}) 16... Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gb6b5,Gb8d7,Gc8e6,Gd7b6] A good idea to remember. The bishop will go to f5 (or e6 if White brings his bishop to d3) and then ...Nd7, ...b5, and ...Nb6 would be a typical plan.} *

