ssary. Let's see why.} (15... g6 $2 {This blunder was actually played twice by 2400+ players. And one of them won!} 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. Na4 $1 {is winning for White.}) (15... Re8 $2 16. Na4 {is again big trouble.}) (15... Rb8 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Ne4 $1 {is quite annoying.}) 16. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4c6]} Rc8 {[%mdl 32768] Black self-pins, but the c6-square is covered. Let's see what might happen if White plays quietly.} ({In practice Black has always played the natural} 16... Nc5 {here.} 17. g3 g6 18. Bh3 Qd6 {and now White showed an interesting plan with} 19. Re1 h5 20. Re2 Rad8 21. Rd2 $14 {Van Wely-Bologan, Enghien-les-Bains 2001}) 17. g3 g6 18. Bh3 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 $2 {This is actually a blunder, although it's not so obvious why.} ({Better was} 19. exd4 {although after} Rc4 $132 {Black is just fine. He can create pressure on the c-file and d4-pawn. Black's next two moves will probably be ...Nf6 and ...Bc8.}) 19... Rc4 $1 20. Qd1 (20. Qd2 $2 d4 21. exd4 Ne5 $1 {exploits a sudden pin of the d4-pawn.}) 20... Ne5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb7h1,Ge5f3] Black has a huge initiative.} 21. Bg2 $2 {This looks natural.} d4 $1 22. Bxb7 ({Or} 22. exd4 Rxd4 $17) 22... dxc3 $17 {[%csl Gc3] The c3-pawn is very strong.} *

