1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Rb1 {[%cal Bb2b4] A highly artificial, but not completely stupid move.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768] We will allow White to carry out his 'clever' plan. Other moves are perfectly playable.} (8... Nbd7 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. b4 {is another example of White's plan.} c5 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. Bb5 Rb8 {has been shown to be quite viable for Black. There is also the Lasker-like}) (8... Ne4 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {White's rook now has a half open file - lined up against our b6-pawn. No big deal.} exd5 12. Bd3 c5 13. O-O Nd7) 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 {[%cal Gb1b4,Gb1b7] This is the point! Of course White could have this position with his f1-bishop developed too. So ...c5 is prevented, but that is usually not our intention in these structures anyway.} c6 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5] We are ready for the usual ...a5.} 12. Qb3 {This at least pretends to prevent ...a5.} ({Both} 12. Bd3 a5) ({and} 12. Be2 a5 {are normal. The position of the b1-rook is not bad, but it's not going to dissuade us from our usual plans.}) 12... Nd7 {[%cal Ga7a5]} ({As a matter of fact,} 12... a5 {is still quite playable if you want to mess with your opponent. If} 13. bxa5 b5 $1 14. a4 Qxa5 15. axb5 Rc8 $1 {when White may regret ignoring his kingside development. If} 16. bxc6 $6 Nxc6 {White is forced into} 17. Kd2 {This is not how I would play the QGD with White.} Be7 $13) 13. Be2 ({Similarly,} 13. Bd3 a5 14. b5 $2 c5 {is good for Black.}) 13... a5 14. b5 $2 {This is the tactical move, so we have to check it. White has not castled yet so it fails miserably.} (14. a3 $6 b5 $1 {is familiar, with the idea ...Nd7-b6-c4}) (14. bxa5 Rxa5 {is a normal position akin to the 8.Be2 lines.}) 14... c5 $17 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 15. Nxd5 $2 {Again, the move we have to check.} (15. dxc5 $2 Nxc5 {and ...Rc8 just wins for Black.}) (15. O-O {is relatively best, but} c4 $17 {is a typical good position for Black.}) 15... cxd4 {[%csl Gb7] White has no good answer.} 16. Z0 (16. Nxf6+ {relatively best.}) (16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. exd4 a4 $1 18. Qc4 Rc8 {wins the knight.}) (16. exd4 Bxd4 $1 17. Nxd4 Nc5 {will scoop up the d5-knight with a winning position. Qxf6 exd4 or 17.Nxd4 Bxg2 18.Rg1 Be4 with ...Nc5 coming. Rfe8 and White's position is disaster.}) *

