1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. Bxf6 {This move is legal. I guess the white player thinks that 7...b6 is such a big concession that he can give a tempo immediately. Ok, the move is not so bad, as we have seen White play this delayed capture countless times. But it's not really anything we have to devote much time too.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. cxd5 {This is White's idea - to get the fixed structure.} exd5 10. Qd2 {This is weird, but it's the only real independent course we should concern ourselves with. Other moves can be met with ...Be6, trying to 'punish' White''s move order, but I think it's simply more practical to play ...Bb7 and transpose to familiar positions.} (10. Rc1 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Rc1 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 , covered earlier.}) (10. Qb3 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Qb3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 .}) (10. Be2 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Be2 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 .}) (10. Bd3 Bb7 {is StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bpp1/1p2pn1p/3p4/2PP3B/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8EndFEN 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.Bxf6 Bxf6 10.cxd5 exd5 .}) (10. b4 $6 {is independent, but we can play} c5 {( 10...c6 is playable too of course).} 11. bxc5 bxc5 {intending ...c4, ...Be6, ...Qa5 and such.}) 10... Be6 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rg2g4,Ge6g4] White's Big Idea is to castle long if we are complacent, but we will not oblige. Ok here we do not want to play} (10... Bb7 11. O-O-O c5 12. g4 {and h4 next. This looks a lot like the 8.Qc2 line, but we saw there that the placement of the queen on c2 was a liability - not only is it on the c-file, but it is vulnerable to ...Nc6-b4. In that line White sometimes plays Qc2-d2 to help control the dark squares.}) 11. O-O-O $2 {This has never been tried, and rightfully so. Neutral moves can just be met with a quick ...c5.} ({For example} 11. Rd1 Qe7 {Black will just play ...Rd8 and ...c5 with a good position.} 12. g3 $6 c5 $1 13. dxc5 Rd8 $1 14. cxb6 {I am dumbfounded by the naïveté of White's play against such a strong classical attacking player like Geller. The confidence of youth I suppose.} d4 $1 15. Bg2 Nc6 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. exd4 Bh3+ 18. Kf1 Rxd4 {gave Black a strong attack in Psakhis - Geller, Yerevan 1981.}) 11... c5 {Black is already much better.} 12. dxc5 Bxc3 $1 13. Qxc3 Qe7 $17 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gb6c5] White would do well to survive twenty moves...} *

