1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 {The Tartakower! This is the backbone of our repertoire. It is a very reliable and dynamic system.} ({I believe it's more interesting than the Lasker with} 7... Ne4 {or the modern line with}) (7... Nbd7) 8. g4 $5 {Ok, points for creativity. Nowadays lunges from White's g-pawn are commonplace in all kinds of openings.} Nxg4 {[%mdl 32768] White cannot push the g-pawn any further if we take it! This is one of many reasonable choices.} ({First, a couple of moves that I do not like so much, as they seem to justify White's play.} 8... Bb7 {is the obvious move of course, but then} 9. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 10. h4 {is a familiar theme.}) ({Similarly,} 8... dxc4 9. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 10. h4 {seems to work out pretty well for White.}) ({The Lasker maneuver} 8... Ne4 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 {looks quite reasonable.}) ({Finally there is} 8... Nbd7 9. Rg1 {(Or 9.g5 Ne4! )} Bb7 10. g5 Ne4 $13) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nxd5 Qd6 12. Nc3 {So White has traded his g-pawn for our d-pawn. A good deal strategically for White, perhaps, but we are ahead in development in a semi-open position.} c5 {Surprised by 8.g4, my friend IM Dean Ippolito played} (12... Bb7 {here, and after} 13. Rg1 Nf6 14. Bg2 c5 {he had no problems against the soon to be World Junior and Ukrainian champion in Shtembuliak - Ippolito, Las Vegas 2019, but 14.Ne5! intending Ng4 is more challenging.}) 13. Rg1 Nf6 ({Some annotators considered this voluntary retreat to be inaccurate, but I think it's fine. Instead} 13... Nc6 {is also playable.} 14. d5 Ne7 15. Bc4 Ng6 $13 {was unclear in Potpara-Lekic, Belgrade 2014.}) 14. Bg2 (14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Qd4 Nbd7 {is level, but interesting enough.}) 14... Bg4 ({The natural} 14... Bb7 {looks playable too. Black has to watch for some Nh4 stuff.} 15. Nb5 Qe7 16. Nh4 Bxg2 17. Rxg2 g6 18. Qd3 {with a sacrifice looming on g6, although the engine says it's equal...}) 15. Qd2 $6 ({White should probably just head for the endgame after all with} 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Qd4 Nbd7 17. Qxc5 bxc5) 15... Nbd7 (15... Nc6 {is also good and could transpose after} 16. Ne5 Nxe5) 16. Ne5 ({There's not much choice.} 16. O-O-O Rad8 {just looks good for Black.}) 16... Nxe5 $1 {This is not forced, but I like it.} 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Bxa8 Rxa8 {Black has invested very little to keep White's king in the center.} 19. Rg3 {Forced.} Qf5 $13 {[%csl Rf3]} ({Leko played} 19... Ne4 {which looks good, but White has} 20. f4 $1 {which holds the balance. After} Nxd2 21. fxe5 Nf3+ 22. Kf2 Nxe5 23. Rag1 {was Grischuk-Leko, Moscow 2014. Here} Rd8 $1 {with the idea} 24. Rxg4 Rd2+ 25. Kf1 Nxg4 26. Rxg4 Rxb2 {or 26...Rxh2} 27. Rg2 Rb4 {would reach an ending with chances for both sides.}) ({After} 19... Qf5 $1 {White's f2-f3 is prevented and I like Black's chances.}) *

