1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1][%mdl 32768] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e4 $6 {[%csl Rd4] This looks aggressive, but it exposes the d4-pawn.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] This is one variation where the tempo saves on not castling can be put to good use, as White does not have time to castle long. White already has to be careful.} ({Instead} 8... O-O 9. Qd2 {gives White time to castle, adding protection to the d4-pawn.}) 9. d5 $6 {[%cal Gf6b2] This just exposes White's position further.} Ne5 10. Nxf6+ {Eliminating the bishop.} (10. Be2 $2 {was played in Romanishin - Geller, Tbilisi 1978.} Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Bxb2 12. Rb1 exd5 13. cxd5 Be5 $17 {just leaves Black a pawn up.}) 10... Qxf6 {[%cal Gf6b2] Now it is Black who is better developed, and White must lose more time.} 11. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Qe2 Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 exd5 14. cxd5 {Here many moves are possible.} Ke7 $15 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge7d6,Gc8d7] The black king heads to the secure d6-square, where it covers the only weakness on c7.} *

