 problems.}) 10... b6 $1 {This is still good, but White can stay within the bounds of near-equality.} 11. Qe4 $1 Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Ne5 {White needs to simplify to stay out of trouble.} Na5 ({Even} 12... O-O-O {!? is possible.} 13. Nxc6 Rd6 14. Nxa7+ Kb8 15. Qe5 Kxa7 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. O-O-O Rhd8 {wins back the pawn.}) 13. Qe3 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Nc6 $1 15. Be2 ({After} 15. Nxc6 $2 Bxc6 $17 {White is under serious pressure, with the d4- and g2-pawns under fire.}) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 {Now Black is spoiled for choice. Any sensible move is fine, but White is holding.} Qe7 $5 {This simple retreat is good and keeps pieces on the board. Practice has seen} (16... Qg5 17. Rxd8+ Rxd8 18. Qxg5 hxg5 {½-½ Eingorn - Barsov, France 2004. The active looking}) (16... Qg6 {is fine, but White is ok after} 17. Bf3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Qg5+ 19. Kc2 {Threatening mate on a8!} Kb8 20. Qe4) 17. Bf3 {Very natural, but probably not best.} (17. Rhe1 {is safe, as Black should not bother with} Bxg2 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rg1) 17... Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Kb8 {[%csl Rc1] I slightly prefer Black, as the white king and e5-pawn are both slightly exposed.} *

