1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qd2 {[%cal Ge2e4] A funny looking move. White is entertaining the idea of playing e2-e4.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768] Following the recipe.} (7... O-O 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 {would transpose to a position we avoided in the 7.e4 line. gives White time to castle, adding protection to the d4-pawn. would transpose to a position we avoided in the 7. e4 line.}) 8. e4 $6 ({Once again this is a bit risky as it weakens the dark squares. Better is} 8. e3 O-O {reaching a line we will consider from the move order 7.e3 0-0 8.Qd2}) 8... c5 $1 {No hesitation. White is teetering on the edge here.} ({That said,} 8... O-O {with the idea ...c5 next, is not bad.}) 9. e5 $6 (9. dxc5 $6 Nd7 {is also very easy for Black.}) 9... cxd4 {Black is doing well here. We'll check the most forcing line.} 10. exf6 dxc3 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. fxg7 Rg8 13. bxc3 Rxg7 {White has to spend some time figuring out how to regain the pawn.} *

