1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Qxc4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] The position actually resembles a Grunfeld, Russian Variation, but White's dark-squared bishop has been traded off. Black has some similar ideas here - taking advantage of the exposed white queen to play on the queenside aiming for ...b5 and ...c5.} 9. Ne4 {This has been play a couple of times, but it looks pointless to me.} Be7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gc7c5]} 10. Rc1 c6 {[%cal Bb8d7,Bd8a5] Intending a disruptive ...Qa5+} ({Colovic's} 10... Qd5 {is also fine}) *

