1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] The position actually resembles a Grunfeld, Russian Variation, but White's dark-squared bishop has been traded off. Black has some similar ideas here - taking advantage of the exposed white queen to play on the queenside aiming for ...b5 and ...c5.} 9. O-O-O $6 {Considering Black wants to play on the queenside, this just looks wrong - and it is.} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5,Gc7c5][%mdl 32768]} (9... a6 {is also possible, but Black may not have to bother with the prepatory move.}) 10. e4 (10. e3 {is a bit more solid, but it could be met in the same way with} Rb8) 10... Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc7c5] Black is going to play ....b5, pawn sac or not.} (10... c5 11. e5 Be7 12. dxc5 Qc7 {was also nice for Black in Krasenkow - Kovacs, Germany 2011.}) 11. Kb1 ({Even worse is} 11. a4 $2 a6) ({and} 11. Qa4 a6 {doesn't help White.}) 11... b5 $1 {With castling on opposite sides, the initiative is more likely to decide the game than a pawn.} 12. Nxb5 Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} (12... Ba6 {looks good too.}) 13. Qc2 ({No better is} 13. e5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nxe5) ({or} 13. Nc3 c5 14. dxc5 Qe7) 13... a6 14. Nc3 c5 $17 {[%csl Gb7,Gf6][%cal Gb8b1] Black has fantastic play for the pawn.} *

