1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] The position actually resembles a Grunfeld, Russian Variation, but White's dark-squared bishop has been traded off. Black has some similar ideas here - taking advantage of the exposed white queen to play on the queenside aiming for ...b5 and ...c5.} 9. e4 a6 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This looks a lot like the Grunfeld Defence, Hungarian Variation of the Russian Variation. Opening names are funny...} 10. e5 (10. O-O-O {?} b5 {looks like a miniature waiting to happen.}) 10... Be7 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc7c5]} 11. Qd3 $5 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3e4] White wants to play Qe4, Bd3, Qh7 checkmate.} (11. Qe2 {looks funny, but has the same effect.}) 11... c5 $1 {We play in the center of course.} 12. Qe4 cxd4 13. Bd3 g6 {We saw the threat!} 14. Nxd4 Qb6 $1 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc8d7,Gb8c6,Gb6b2,Gg8g7] Black's play should be faster here.} 15. O-O-O {Castling short is possible, but looks more consistent.} Bd7 16. h4 Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] White does not have time for h4-h5.} 17. Bc2 Nxd4 18. Rxd4 $2 (18. Qxd4 {is better, but} Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Bc6 {is a comfortable ending for Black.}) 18... Bc6 19. Qf4 (19. Qg4 h5 $1) 19... Rfd8 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf4h6,Gb6f2] Black is much better as White's attack has completely stalled. The engine already considers the position to be winning!} 20. Z0 ({Note that} 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Qxh6 Qxf2 {is just winning for Black, as} 22. Bxg6 fxg6 23. Qxg6+ Kf8 {is nothing.}) *

