1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] The position actually resembles a Grunfeld, Russian Variation, but White's dark-squared bishop has been traded off. Black has some similar ideas here - taking advantage of the exposed white queen to play on the queenside aiming for ...b5 and ...c5.} 9. g3 {This is an uncommon, but apparently logical try, as the finachetto is a safe development. Gelfand's shocking discovery essentially closed the book on this line though.} b5 $3 {[%mdl 32768] What a move, which shows how well Gelfand was prepared for the 2011 Candidates tournament. Black tosses a pawn in an unusual way to exploit his development lead and the power of the bishop pair.} 10. Nxb5 {No one has gone for this as it looks too risky for White. Declining the pawn with a move like} (10. Qb3 {does not help, as Black can still play} c5 $1 11. dxc5 Qa5 12. Bg2 Bb7) 10... Ba6 $1 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc7c5] Now ...c6 is a threat. The computer indicates} 11. Qa4 (11. Qb3 Nc6 $1 {Now the engines will show that the play is rather forcing. Colovic analyzed this too.}) 11... c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6,Ga6b7,Gf6b2]} 12. Bg2 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rb5]} 13. Na3 {The only move to stay alive!} cxd4 {[%cal Ga6b7]} (13... Nd7 {also looks decent. Black has good play.}) 14. Nd2 Bb7 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. O-O Bd5 {[%cal Bb8c6] Black is comfortable enough, and he has the bishop pair. It's no surprise that 9.g3 has basically disappeared from practice.} *

