1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries, most notably queen moves, which will meet by capturing on c4.} 7. Qc2 dxc4 {[%mdl 32768] Consistent and good.} ({White has actually done quite well after} 7... O-O 8. O-O-O {in practice, but I suspect that Black should be doing just fine here as well. In my database Black has tried nine different moves here, but not the top choice of my engine,} b5 $5) 8. e3 {This is really the only good move.} (8. e4 $2 {just drops the d4-pawn. while based on what we've seen, it's not difficult to discern that}) (8. O-O-O {?! is just reckless.} a6 {intending ...b5 is very good.}) (8. Ne4 {is safer, but} Be7 9. Qxc4 b6 {is similar to what we saw in the 7.Qb3 line, but now the e4-knight will be attacked very quickly.}) 8... c5 {Opening the position.} 9. dxc5 Qa5 ({Black always goes for this and it would be my choice, but I will note that} 9... O-O {transposes to the 7.e3 0-0 8.Qc2 dxc4 line, which is also fine for Black.}) 10. Bxc4 Qxc5 {Black has the bishop pair and White does not have much in return.} 11. Ne4 ({After} 11. Nd2 Be7 {avoids Ne4. Black will just castle and his queen can comfortably retreat to c7.}) 11... Qa5+ 12. Ke2 ({This connect the rooks and avoids retreating a knight. If} 12. Nfd2 Be7 {anyway.}) 12... Be7 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Gc8d7,Gb8c6,Ga7a6,Gb8d7,Gb7b5] Black is solid and has the bishop pair. White is well developed, so I think he can hold the balance but no more.} 13. Z0 (13. Qc3 {Heading for an endgame.}) ({Another high level game saw} 13. Rhc1 Bd7 14. Qc3 Qxc3 15. Rxc3 Nc6 16. a3 $6 f5 $1 17. Ned2 Bf6 18. Rc2 {was Wang Yue - Carlsen, Linares 2009. Here} Rc8 $1 19. Nb3 Ne5 {is very good for Black - bishop pair! Qxc3 Nxc3 a6 Rhd1 Nd7 Ne4 b5 Bb3 Bb7 Nd6+ Bxd6 Rxd6 Ke7 White eliminated Black's bishop pair, but the b7-bishop is quite strong and Black is doing well. See Vallejo Pons - Topalov, Linares 2005 for a nice example of how to play out these 'equal' endgames.}) *

