1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 8. cxd5 {White switches to a Carlsbad structure. This is not especially dangerous, but it's reasonable enough.} exd5 {[%csl Gc8,Gf6][%cal Gc7c6,Gc8e6,Gb8d7,Gf6e7,Ge7d6,Gd7b6] Strangely enough, the position is almost identical to a line of the Grunfeld: StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Nf3 Bg7 5.Bg5 Ne4 6.cxd5 Nxg5 7.Nxg5 e6 8.Nf3 exd5 9.e3 O-O . The only difference is that Black has a pawn on h6 instead of g6! Of course in the Grunfeld line they'll tell you it looks like a QGD... White has many moves here, but the positions are not exactly 'move by move' critical - an understanding of the structures is more important than remembering anything. Black enjoys the bishop pair, and he will typically develop with ...Be6 and ...Nd7, while rerouting the f6-bishop to d6 is also common. We will check a few moves to see some typical ideas. The most common is the minority attack with b4-b5.} 9. Qb3 {White sometimes places his queen here in the Tartakover. It's not clear what the queen is really achieving here. We don't have ...Be6 for now, but that's not such an issue, and of course White does not b4-b5 now.} c6 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7f8] We will relocate the knight soon. There is no forcing lines, so I will provide a nice example of play from a real QGD expert.} 12. Rad1 Nb6 13. h3 Be6 {[%cal Gf6e7,Ge7d6,Gd8d7] One idea is to bring the bishop to d6. Then ...Qd7 and White will have to watch out for ...Bxh3.} 14. Na4 Nxa4 15. Qxa4 Qd6 {Another typical move. Now White mistakenly plays for a minority attack.} 16. b4 b5 $5 17. Qc2 a5 $15 {Black is the one who took the initiative on the queenside in Martinovsky - Vaganian, New York 1997.} *

