nt than remembering anything. Black enjoys the bishop pair, and he will typically develop with ...Be6 and ...Nd7, while rerouting the f6-bishop to d6 is also common. We will check a few moves to see some typical ideas. The most common is the minority attack with b4-b5.} 9. b4 {This early advance, also seen in the Grunfeld line, is thematic but somewhat risky as White is underdeveloped.} c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Be2 ({The most common. The engine slightly prefers} 10. Bd3 {and it may be better somehow, but after} Be7 {it's going to be similar.}) 10... Be7 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5]} 11. a3 ({White cannot support} 11. b5 $2 cxb5 12. Nxb5 $2 {or 12.Bxb5? Bb4} Qa5+ {and ...a6 wins material.}) ({If} 11. Qb3 a5 $1 12. b5 a4 $1 {and ...Qa5+ is going to be disruptive.}) ({While} 11. Rb1 b5 $1 12. a4 $2 {is well met with} a5 $1) 11... b5 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5] This should look familiar by now.} 12. O-O a5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb8a6,Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] And again Black is the one with active prospects on the queenside.} *

