1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This funny looking move again. Maybe White wants to castle queenside? We can hope...} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({It's also possible to play} 9... c5 {immediately. After} 10. dxc5 Nd7 11. Ne4 Be7 12. c6 {I like the idea} Nf6 $5 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {and if} 14. cxb7 Bxb7 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 10. O-O-O $6 {We are learning that this is almost always bad!} c5 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5][%mdl 32768]} 11. h4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8b8,Gd8b6] An engine move which was mentioned by Colovic. Here's a sample line:} 12. Bxb5 Bb7 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxd8 Rfxd8 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Rd1 Rc8 {and Black's initiative persists in the endgame.} *

