1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Qd2 {This funny looking move again. Maybe White wants to castle queenside? We can hope...} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} ({It's also possible to play} 9... c5 {immediately. After} 10. dxc5 Nd7 11. Ne4 Be7 12. c6 {I like the idea} Nf6 $5 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {and if} 14. cxb7 Bxb7 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 10. O-O c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Rfd1 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1]} ({This certainly looks like the 'right rook'. If} 11. Rad1 {both} cxd4 {and 11...a6!? look fine.}) 11... cxd4 {Clarifying the position in the center.} 12. Nxd4 ({If} 12. exd4 Nb6 {followed by ...Bd7 is fine for Black.}) 12... Ne5 $146 {[%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f3] A new move in a well-known position. We hit the bishop and also cover the f3-square, as Be2-f3 is a typical idea for White.} ({Practice has seen} 12... Nb6 13. Be2 Bd7 14. Bf3 Rb8 {which should also equalize.} 15. Ne4 Bxd4 {This was played by Kasparov, but later he suggested 15...Nc4 with the idea ...Ne5. We are just taking a shortcut!} 16. Qxd4 Ba4 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Nc5 Rd2 {and although the b7-pawn is falling, Black had enough activity to hold in a game from the marathon match, Karpov - Kasparov, Moscow 1985.}) 13. Be2 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd8b6] I do not see any problems for Black. We can complete development with ...Rc8 and ...Qb6. We have the bishop pair, but White's pieces are well placed so it's still equal.} 14. Z0 ({If} 14. Ne4 {If White insists on bringing the bishop to f3, he must weaken his position with}) (14. f4 Ng6 $1 15. Bf3 $6 Qb6 {when I prefer Black. Be7 looks quite safe.}) *

