1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Qc2 {[%cal Ge1c1] This is fairly common. I have even played this move myself.} c5 ({In our repertoire, we will be consistent with} 8... dxc4 $5 {, but this is also quite good, and may transpose somewhere else.}) 9. O-O-O $2 {As is almost always the case, this should not really work.} ({Instead} 9. cxd5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 exd5 {is fine for Black.}) ({White should play} 9. dxc5 dxc4 {transposing to 8...dxc4}) 9... cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {It looks a bit like a Tartakover, but there Black plays ...b6, ...Bb7, and then often ...Bb7-c8!} 11. h4 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gf3g5]} Qc7 12. Kb1 Rd8 {[%csl Rd4] White is already in trouble.} 13. c5 b6 $17 {A disaster for White.} *

