1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Qc2 {[%cal Ge1c1] This is fairly common. I have even played this move myself.} dxc4 $5 ({We are being consistent here in meeting queen moves, but} 8... c5 {is also quite good, and may transpose. We will consider this as an informational line.}) 9. Bxc4 c5 10. dxc5 {Now we have a common position that often arises after 8....c5, as show in the informational line.} Nd7 $1 {This developing move is best, and it scores well.} (10... Qa5 {is slightly more common, but it's not as good.} 11. O-O Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qxc3 13. bxc3 Nd7 14. c6 bxc6 {is quite a dreary endgame for Black.} 15. Rab1 {was seen in Karpov-Kasparov, Moscow 1984. White won but 15.Rfd1 is even stronger.}) 11. c6 Ne5 $1 {I like this active move a lot.} (11... bxc6 {is ok too, and this is similar to the 8.Qb3 line, but here White's queen is a bit safer on c2.} 12. O-O Rb8 13. Rac1 c5 14. Rfd1 {and now the following game is a cautionary tale:} Qe7 $6 {This does not look like the right spot for the queen. a5 or c7 look like better choices.} 15. b3 Bb7 16. Ne4 Rfd8 17. Be2 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 $14 {and White had long lasting advantage in Anton Guijarro - Nakamura, Caleta 2017.}) 12. Nxe5 ({After} 12. Be2 Nxc6 {Black just has the bishop pair for nothing.}) 12... Bxe5 13. f4 Bf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Keeping this bishop is even more ambitious than} 13... bxc6 {with the idea} 14. fxe5 $6 Qh4+) 14. Ne4 ({Black would regain the pawn with no concessions after} 14. O-O Qb6 $1) 14... Bh4+ ({We could play} 14... Be7 {immediately, but why not soften things up.}) 15. g3 Be7 {[%csl Re3][%cal Rb7h1] White can grab the pawn, but his position looks very loose.} *

