1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 {After all the queen dances, we come to the main line, and probably the most challenging move.} c6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd5c4,Ge6e5,Gc6c5] This is by far Black's most common move. Black secures the center, and plans to complete development with ...Nd7, often followed by capturing on c4 and then going for ...e5 or ...c5.} ({We will be going for} 8... dxc4 {which is consistent with our repertoire, and a convenient shortcut.}) 9. Bd3 ({There is also} 9. h4 {intending g4, g5. This does not greatly concern me, but we are avoiding it with our move order nonetheless.}) 9... Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 {This is the main line, and it was seen in clashes between Kasparov and Karpov as well as other top GM's in the 1980's and 1990's.} ({Interestingly enough, the uncommon} 11... c5 {transposes to our repertoire, but with a move more for each side. Soon we will see some lines where we are combatting suggestions of Greek Grandmaster Ioannis Papaioannou, and he reaches the positions via this move order.}) 12. h3 {This little prophylactic move is the main line.} ({Papaioannou likes the endgame that arises after} 12. Ne4 exd4 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Qxd4 {We will see something similar, but with a symmetrical pawn structure, which denies White a kingside pawn majority.}) ({The advance} 12. d5 Nb6 13. b3 $5 {is also somewhat challenging for Black.}) 12... exd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bb3 Bf5 ({This is the most common.} 14... Re8 {is also popular, and may even be more accurate. Often the moves transpose. The position looks nice for Black at first, as he has the bishop pair and has developed rather easily, plus White has an isolated d-pawn. Practice has shown that White has some initiative though, as there is some pressure on the f7-pawn and Black has to watch out for Nf3-e5 all the time.}) 15. Re1 Re8 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gc1e1,Gd2f4,Gf3e5] White is very active so Black should seek further exchanges.} Qd7 18. Re1 {And now long analysis has uncovered Black's best move.} a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga8e8] There are actually deep variations where the pawn is hanging on a7! Some of the lines go to move 30 and beyond. Considering that 6.Bxf6 is not so common now, and these lines are so deep, it is more logical to go for a more economic solution, especially considering that 8...dxc4 seems totally sound.} *

