1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 {After all the queen dances, we come to the main line, and probably the most challenging move.} dxc4 $5 ({A bit of a revelation, as} 8... c6 {is by far the main move. There was a time when this immediate capture, just allowing Bxc4 in one move, would have been unheard of. But with today's engines, we can see that a lot of moves which apparently violate certain principles are quite playable. Considering that in the Queen's Gambit Accepted White takes on c4 in one move, we can see that it is not unreasonable to play this way. We will consider 8...c6 as an informational line, where I will show that both moves may even transpose!}) 9. Bxc4 ({White should not get fancy. Black is already better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6) 9... Nd7 {White almost always castles here, but there is one other line to consider.} 10. Ne4 {White is going for simplifications, and perhaps hoping to deter our ...c5 break.} c5 $1 ({Here} 10... Be7 {is a bit slow.} 11. O-O c5 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. Qxd5 {favors White.}) 11. Nxf6+ (11. d5 $2 {would hang the b2-pawn.}) 11... Qxf6 ({But not} 11... Nxf6 $2 12. dxc5 {when White's rook is conveniently backing up the c5-pawn.}) 12. Bb5 $5 {[%cal Gb5d7,Gc1c5] This move, which threatens to start taking everything, was not considered by Colovic. It's certainly more of a nuisance than castling.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] Not much choice.} 13. Qxd4 {Going for the endgame is much more consistent than 13.Nxd4?! when 13...e5! and ...Rd8 is very comfortable for Black.} Qxd4 14. Nxd4 {This is similar to the endgame that Papaioannou is aiming for (which we will see later). Here White has not castled and his bishop is on b5 instead of c4, while Black's knight is still on d7. Although it's a bit early to relax, I don't think Black should have any problems with accurate play.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd7f6,Ge6e5,Ga7a6,Gd7b6] This flexible move is a good start.} 15. Be2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge2f3,Ge1f2] Initiating Papaioannou's plan of f4, Bf3.} Nf6 16. f4 {[%cal Ge2f3]} ({The immediate} 16. Bf3 {could be met with} e5 {or 16...Rb8 immediately.}) 16... Nd5 {[%csl Re3,Rf4] An important move to cause a disturbance.} 17. Kf2 ({Of course not} 17. e4 $2 Nxf4 {White has saved time by playing Kf2 rather than 0-0 and Kf2, but there's other stuff happening now.}) 17... Nxf4 $1 {Winning a pawn, but it's really just an equalizing operation.} 18. exf4 Rxd4 19. Rhd1 {[%csl Gc1,Gd1,Ge2] Despite the simplification, White's development lead looks intimidating. We have to know the move here.} e5 $1 {[%csl Gc8] Returning the pawn allows us to complete our development comfortably.} (19... Rxd1 $2 20. Rxd1 $16 {is horrible.}) 20. fxe5 ({White can decline with} 20. Rxd4 exd4 21. Rc7 {but with the extra pawn we can just play} Be6 {hitting a2.}) 20... Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Be6 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ga8c8] And everything is fine.} *

