dy better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6) 9... Nd7 10. O-O {The most natural move.} c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Qe2 ({Now there is a big split. White can play classical with} 11. Qe2 {, intending Rd1 with quick development,}) ({or he can play} 11. Ne4 {, aiming for further simplifications.}) {This was the choice of none other than Kasparov, which of course gives the move a certain stamp of approval. 'The Boss' won a rather clean game, but maybe this is because he is Kasparov, and not because of any faultiness in Black's setup?!} 11... cxd4 {Black seeks clarity.} ({Kasparov faced} 11... a6 {This is a typical QGA-type move and it is not bad, but Black is lagging in development.} 12. Rfd1 cxd4 {Kasparov gave no comment to this move, but 12...b5 looks more consistent. I imagine everyone assumed that 13.dxc5!? would be very strong for White, but after 13...bxc4 14.c6 Qe7 15.cxd7 Bxd7 16.Qxc4 Rfc8 Black has a fair amount of play for the pawn, and the engines think it's equal.} 13. Nxd4 $1 {Here ...a6 does look too slow, as Black has trouble getting his pieces out.} Qe7 14. Ne4 Be5 15. Qh5 $1 {and Kasparov relentlessly kept up the pressure in Kasparov - Olafsson, Dubai 1986.}) 12. Nxd4 {This does not look dangerous here as White's rook is not on the d-file yet and Black did not spend this tempo on ...a6.} Nb6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd8e7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] This hits the c4-bishop. Black can continue with ...Bd7, ... Qe7, and centralizing the rooks.} *

