dy better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6) 9... Nd7 10. O-O {The most natural move.} c5 11. Qe2 ({Now there is a big split. White can play classical with} 11. Qe2 {, intending Rd1 with quick development,}) ({or he can play} 11. Ne4 {, aiming for further simplifications.}) {This was the choice of none other than Kasparov, which of course gives the move a certain stamp of approval. 'The Boss' won a rather clean game, but maybe this is because he is Kasparov, and not because of any faultiness in Black's setup?!} 11... cxd4 {Black seeks clarity.} ({Kasparov faced} 11... a6 {This is a typical QGA-type move and it is not bad, but Black is lagging in development.} 12. Rfd1 cxd4 {Kasparov gave no comment to this move, but 12...b5 looks more consistent. I imagine everyone assumed that 13.dxc5!? would be very strong for White, but after 13...bxc4 14.c6 Qe7 15.cxd7 Bxd7 16.Qxc4 Rfc8 Black has a fair amount of play for the pawn, and the engines think it's equal.} 13. Nxd4 $1 {Here ...a6 does look too slow, as Black has trouble getting his pieces out.} Qe7 14. Ne4 Be5 15. Qh5 $1 {and Kasparov relentlessly kept up the pressure in Kasparov - Olafsson, Dubai 1986.}) 12. exd4 Nb6 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5][%mdl 32768] Black must maintain some control over the d5-square.} 13. Bb3 {Not dangerous. The b1-h7 diagonal is more important.} {or the immediate 13.d5! are quite problematic.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] This is fine for Black. It's important to understand that the following pawn structure is satisfactory:} 14. Ne5 Bc6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 $132 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4] We have a well-known structure where the c6-pawn is no more weak than the target on d4.} *

