1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 {This will be our move order.} ({The alternative is} 5... O-O {which will generally transpose to the main lines after} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 {but there are some cases where we may delay castling, so this is more flexible with no downside as far as I can tell.}) 6. Bxf6 {White avoids the Tartakover. I have heard this referred to as the Petrosian Variation. The 9th World Champion played this way several times, and he was known to have an affinity for knights. White gives up the bishop pair, but speeds up development.} Bxf6 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg7a1] Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7. Now the main move by far is 7.e3, but there are some other tries. When we face White's queen moves (whether on move 6 or 7), we will take on c4 against all of them, which is not only an easy principal to remember, but objectively a strong approach. Black should take care in the center, especially on the light squares, while White must be careful on the dark squares. Essentially the f6-bishop in a fianchetto, it's just a bit more exposed on f6 than it would be on g7.} 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 {After all the queen dances, we come to the main line, and probably the most challenging move.} dxc4 ({A bit of a revelation, as} 8... c6 {is by far the main move. There was a time when this immediate capture, just allowing Bxc4 in one move, would have been unheard of. But with today's engines, we can see that a lot of moves which apparently violate certain principles are quite playable. Considering that in the Queen's Gambit Accepted White takes on c4 in one move, we can see that it is not unreasonable to play this way. We will consider 8...c6 as an informational line, where I will show that both moves may even transpose!}) 9. Bxc4 ({White should not get fancy. Black is already better after} 9. e4 $2 Nc6) 9... Nd7 10. O-O c5 11. Ne4 ({Now there is a big split. White can play classical with} 11. Qe2 {, intending Rd1 with quick development,}) ({or he can play} 11. Ne4 {, aiming for further simplifications.}) {White goes for simplifications. Usually this is welcomed by Black, and Colovic was not concerned here, but this line was recommended by Papaioannou (via a different move order considered in our informational line on 8...c6) in his course on modern-chess, so we must take it seriously.} 11... cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {[%cal Gc8d7]} 13. Nxd4 {This is quite harmless. Black has no weaknesses, and the typical problem in the QGD - the development of the c8-bishop - is easy to solve.} Qb6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] As played by Nakamura. Black will play ...Bd7 and bring the rooks to the center.} ({Colovic gives} 13... Bd7 {immediately, which is also fine, as the attack on the b7-pawn with} 14. Qb3 {can be met with} Qa5 15. Qxb7 Rab8) *

