1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 c5 {This is the old classical move, and it was what I hoped to recommend. I just couldn't do it...} ({In the course, we will go for} 6... b6 {which is consistent with our Tartakover repertoire.}) ({The other big line is} 6... Nbd7 {Then} 7. c5 {is considered critical, and there are some long sharp lines that follow} c6 8. h3 {8.h4 is similar. This is given by Shankland, although he does not examine the complications in any depth. White can also play 8.Bd3 b6 9.b4 a5 10.a3 Ba6 11.Bxa6 Rxa6 12.b5 when he is 'missing' the move h3. This looks like a small detail, but it can change things quite a bit in a few lines.} b6 9. b4 a5 10. a3 Ba6 {Now White can play slowly, or go for} 11. Bxa6 Rxa6 12. b5 cxb5 13. c6 Qc8 $1 14. c7 b4 15. Nb5 {Black has his share of chances after} a4 $1 {but this is a very tactical line where the balance can shift very quickly.}) 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. a3 Nc6 9. Qc2 Qa5 {This is the main position, which can be reached through various move orders.} 10. Rd1 $1 {After this move Black has some choice, but it all looks like suffering.} (10. O-O-O {was in vogue in the 1990's. Now we know that after} Be7 11. h4 a6 $1 {gives Black good counterplay and that} 12. g4 dxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {leads to complications that ultimately should lead to a draw.}) 10... Be7 {The old main line.} (10... Re8 11. Nd2 e5 12. Bg5 Nd4 $1 {is Nakamura's line. But even he is not playing it these days.} 13. Qb1 {White can also play 13.Qc1 Bf5 14.Bxf6 Nc2+ 15.Ke2 Nd4+ 16.Ke1 Nc2+ with a draw by repetition. We will see some lines that may end in a draw in our repertoire, but not so quickly.} Bf5 14. Bd3 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Ne4 {In this position White can try various captures and they are all a bit complicated. I think that Black is under some pressure here.}) (10... Rd8 {is another try, but again Black is looking to survive some complications and draw.}) 11. Be2 $1 {This simple move causes Black some trouble.} Ne4 ({Instead} 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nh5 {Black is worse after 12...e5 13.Bg3 Bg4 14.O-O as well.} 13. O-O Nxf4 14. exf4 {was the well-known game Kramnik-Carlsen, Dortmund 2009. Black is suffering here, as shown by both practice and modern engine analysis.}) 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. bxc3 {Shankland's choice. This is the most ambitious.} ({The exchange of queens is also pleasant for White.} 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3 exd5 15. Rxd5 Bxa3 16. Nd4 a5 {Black has been holding here in correspondence games, but after} 17. Rb5 {Black's task remains unpleasant. 16...Nxd4 17.exd4 also favored White in Carlsen-Nakamura, Saint Louis 2015.}) 13... exd5 14. O-O {White scores a very healthy 65% here. So while 6...c5 may remain viable theoretically, it is not a very practical choice unless you are trying to prove that Black can hold in a correspondence game.} *

