1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 6. Rc1 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {A typical move in the QGD. Here the rook combines with the f4-bishop to cast a glance at the c7-pawn. So Black's options are a bit limited, but White is also restricted - castling long is certainly no longer an option. There are also some positions where queens will be exchanged, and White will lose a tempo by playing Ra1-c1xd1.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet 6.Qc2 this way as well, so it will all be easier to remember.} ({First of all,} 6... b6 {is now less appealing.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. a3 $1 {saves the pawn, covers the b4-square, and renews the threat to c7 . After 9...c5 10.dxc5 give White a small but safe edge. Really White's sixth move is directed against the popular setups with ...Nbd7,}) ({as here} 6... Nbd7 7. cxd5 exd5 {is forced to not drop c7 , and then} 8. e3 $14 {is a 'clean' white edge.}) ({The immediate} 6... dxc4 $5 {is rather thematic.} 7. e4 {or 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Nc6!} b5 $1 8. Nxb5 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Ba6 {is possible, but it's needlessly complicated and I am not so sure Black will equalize here in any case.}) 7. dxc5 dxc4 {Again, simplicity. As mentioned before we do not mind the queen exchange.} ({The alternative} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 {is also quite playable. This usually arises from the 6...c5 line, but Black has avoided the most dangerous setup with Qc2 and Rd1.}) 8. Bd6 {White cannot realistically expect to hold onto the pawn.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 9. Bxe7 ({Instead} 9. e3 Nxc5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bxc4 b6 {is at least equal for Black -development is good, we have a square for the queen, and the rook will soon come to the open files.}) (9. Qd4 {could be tried, but White still lags in development.} Bxd6 10. cxd6 b5 $1 11. Nxb5 e5 12. Qxc4 Ba6 $1 {with great play is one possibility.}) 9... Qxe7 10. Qd6 Qxd6 $1 11. cxd6 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] Simply intending ...b5. It turns out that it is not so trivial for White to capture the c4-pawn, while the d6-pawn is easily blocked and more likely to be weak than strong.} 12. a4 (12. e4 b5 13. e5 $2 {loses the e-pawn after.} Ng4) 12... Rb8 13. a5 {The only move to be concerned about, but we have a good answer.} b5 $1 14. axb6 Ne8 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Gc4,Rd6][%cal Ge8d6,Gb8b6,Gd7b6,Gd6c4,Gb6c4] Black will win soon capture both of White's pawns.} *

