10. Bxc4 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3] A typical idea - this not only threatens to win the e4-pawn, it prepares to split White's queenside pawns.} 11. Bd6 ({If} 11. Bd3 {Black can either split the pawns with} Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Bd7) 11... Bxc3+ {or develop simply with 11...Nc6 12.O-O Bd7} 12. bxc3 Rd8 {[%cal Gf6e4] The e4-pawn is now attacked.} 13. O-O ({Connecting the rooks.} 13. e5 Ne4 $15 {hitting d6 and c3 looks good for Black.}) 13... Bd7 ({We cannot take -} 13... Nxe4 $4 14. Bxb8 {and we lose because of the back rank.}) 14. Rfe1 Bc6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb8d7,Ga8c8] White has the bishops, but Black has the better pawn structure and good squares for the pieces, Aronian-Radjabov, Porto Carras 2011.} *

