1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. Rc1 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {A typical move in the QGD. Here the rook combines with the f4-bishop to cast a glance at the c7-pawn. So Black's options are a bit limited, but White is also restricted - castling long is certainly no longer an option. There are also some positions where queens will be exchanged, and White will lose a tempo by playing Ra1-c1xd1.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet 6.Qc2 this way as well, so it will all be easier to remember.} ({First of all,} 6... b6 {is now less appealing.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. a3 $1 {saves the pawn, covers the b4-square, and renews the threat to c7 . After 9...c5 10.dxc5 give White a small but safe edge. Really White's sixth move is directed against the popular setups with ...Nbd7,}) ({as here} 6... Nbd7 7. cxd5 exd5 {is forced to not drop c7 , and then} 8. e3 $14 {is a 'clean' white edge.}) ({The immediate} 6... dxc4 $5 {is rather thematic.} 7. e4 {or 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Nc6!} b5 $1 8. Nxb5 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Ba6 {is possible, but it's needlessly complicated and I am not so sure Black will equalize here in any case.}) 7. dxc5 dxc4 {Again, simplicity. As mentioned before we do not mind the queen exchange.} ({The alternative} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 {is also quite playable. This usually arises from the 6...c5 line, but Black has avoided the most dangerous setup with Qc2 and Rd1.}) 8. e3 {White again allows the exchange of queens.} Qxd1+ {[%mdl 32768] And again we make White move the rook again.} 9. Rxd1 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc1d1]} Bxc5 10. Bxc4 (10. Bd6 {is playable, but it just costs time to trade pieces.} Bxd6 11. Rxd6 Bd7 $1 12. Bxc4 Rc8 {when Black has no weaknesses and can continue with ...Bc6, ...Nbd7, and ...Kf8-e7.}) 10... Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c3] Not the only move, but by splitting White's pawns, we not only avoid a dry position where White can play for a slight edge, we also create an imbalance a with good prospects for counterplay.} 11. O-O {White cannot avoid the coming structure.} ({If} 11. Rc1 Ne4) ({or} 11. Rd3 Ne4) 11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] The most ambitious. Black intends ...Ba6, so White should play purposefully.} (12... Bd7 13. Ne5 Rc8 {is also possible.}) 13. Bd6 ({The best choice. An example of White not taking care against Black's idea went} 13. Nd4 Ba6 $1 14. Nb5 Rc8 15. Bd3 {Melkumyan-Nakamura, chess.com blitz 2018, and now 15...Bxb5 16.Bxb5 Ne4 $17 wins a pawn. If 17.c4? a6}) 13... Re8 ({But not} 13... Rd8 $4 14. Bxb8 {and Black loses because of the back rank.}) 14. Bb5 $5 {This lures Black's bishop away from a6.} (14. Nd4 {is still well met with} Ba6 15. Nb5 Rc8) 14... Bd7 ({We do not want to be tangled up after} 14... Nbd7 $2) 15. Be2 Nc6 {This develops quickly, but 15...Bc6 also look okay.} 16. Rc1 Red8 {[%csl Rc3,Gd6,Ge2][%cal Gd7e8,Gf6e4] This was played in a couple of correspondence games. Black will play ...Be8 and perhaps ...Ne4. Note that we should not rush with ...Rac8 because of White's Ba6.} *

