tural and good, but} 10... Nfxd5 $5 11. Bd2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Qa4 $1 13. b3 Qa3 {also keeps some pressure on White.}) 11. Bd2 ({Not much choice, as} 11. Be5 $6 {runs into} Ng4) 11... Qxc5 12. e3 ({After} 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 {intending ...b6 and perhaps ...Ne4 is nice for Black - White is not developed.}) 12... Nxc3 ({This is simplest.} 12... b6 13. Nb5 {with the idea Rc1 is a bit annoying.}) (12... Rd8 {looks fine though.}) 13. Bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] Black is clearly fine in this symmetrical structure. His development lead makes his position even easier to play. I like the following line:} 14. Bd3 Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7f3,Gc5h5]} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gc5b4]} 17. Z0 ({We will trap the bishop if we can. A couple of possibilities:} 17. Bd3) ({or} 17. Be4 Qb4+ 18. Nd2 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxb2 $17 20. Qb4 {Rd2} Rfd8 $17 {with the idea of ...Rac8 or doubling rooks on the d-file. Bringing the queen to g4 could also cause White an immediate crisis.}) *

