1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. Qc2 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another typical QGD move if White insists on delaying e3. White does not commit his rook and maintains the options of castling queenside, but the queen is a bit exposed here and Black can often take advantage of this.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet this the same way as we did with 6.Rc1.} ({Once again,} 6... b6 {is inferior, this time because of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {the thematic move, but it doesn't work well here. 7...exd5 8.e3 $14 is a nice edge for White.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. e4 $1 {makes 6.Qc2 look quite clever. One point is that} Bb4+ {does not cause the trouble it seems to, as} 10. Kd1 $1 {is good for White - Black will waste a lot of time retreating his pieces.}) ({Black should also skip} 6... Nbd7 {because} 7. cxd5 {forces} exd5 8. e3 $14 {with another good exchange variation for White.}) ({Finally,} 6... dxc4 {can be met with} 7. e3 $1 {rather than 7.e4 Nc6!}) 7. dxc5 Na6 $1 {A good flexible move. We may recapture on c5, while ...Nb4 is also a possibility.} ({If} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Rd1 {we have been tricked into White's best line in the 6.e3 c5 complex.}) ({The less common} 7... Qa5 {is given by Ntirlis. This seems fine as well, but White has a lot of choice here and it can be a bit complicated after} 8. Nd2 $5 Qxc5 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. Bg5) 8. e3 {The safest choice. White needs to get developed.} Nxc5 {[%mdl 32768] This transposes to a line that is often reached via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 6 6EndFEN 6.e3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5 Nxc5 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. cxd5 {This is relatively safe, but it is White who must display some care.} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 $5 {[%cal Gd8a5] Accepting the IQP to accelerate development. Now ...Qa5+ is a genuine nuisance, so White has to further delay the development of his kingside.} (10... Qxd5 {is fine too, but we can be play for an imbalance.}) 11. Be5 {[%cal Ge5c3] A wise choice. Now the bishop can come back to c3 . We were hoping for 11.a3? Bd7! A typical reaction. We are intending ...Ba4, ...Rc8, and ...Bf6. White has problems.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gd8a5] Now we are looking to check again.} 12. a3 {White plays this now that the ...Bd7-a4 idea is not supported by Black's knight.} Bf5 ({Another way is} 12... Bg4 13. Be2 Rc8 14. Qd1 Bf6) 13. Bd3 Rc8 14. Qd1 Bf6 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gf8e8] Black has the IQP but an active position. If this does not appeal, then the dry 10...Qxd5 is safe enough.} *

