1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. Qc2 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another typical QGD move if White insists on delaying e3. White does not commit his rook and maintains the options of castling queenside, but the queen is a bit exposed here and Black can often take advantage of this.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet this the same way as we did with 6.Rc1.} ({Once again,} 6... b6 {is inferior, this time because of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {the thematic move, but it doesn't work well here. 7...exd5 8.e3 $14 is a nice edge for White.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. e4 $1 {makes 6.Qc2 look quite clever. One point is that} Bb4+ {does not cause the trouble it seems to, as} 10. Kd1 $1 {is good for White - Black will waste a lot of time retreating his pieces.}) ({Black should also skip} 6... Nbd7 {because} 7. cxd5 {forces} exd5 8. e3 $14 {with another good exchange variation for White.}) ({Finally,} 6... dxc4 {can be met with} 7. e3 $1 {rather than 7.e4 Nc6!}) 7. dxc5 Na6 $1 {A good flexible move. We may recapture on c5, while ...Nb4 is also a possibility.} ({If} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Rd1 {we have been tricked into White's best line in the 6.e3 c5 complex.}) ({The less common} 7... Qa5 {is given by Ntirlis. This seems fine as well, but White has a lot of choice here and it can be a bit complicated after} 8. Nd2 $5 Qxc5 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. Bg5) 8. e3 {The safest choice. White needs to get developed.} Nxc5 {This transposes to a line that is often reached via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 6 6EndFEN 6.e3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5 Nxc5 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. Rd1 $6 {[%cal Gd1c2,Ga1d1] This is White's favorite setup in the 6...c5 line, but there are big differences because Black has not wasted time with ...Be7xc5 and back to 77 again. Black's knight is on c5, not c6, and White has yet to play a3.} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc5e4][%mdl 32768]} 10. Nd2 {White already has to think about damage control.} ({If} 10. Be2 dxc4 {and ...Nce4 will break up White's pawn structure.}) ({and} 10. cxd5 {is well met by} Nxd5 $17 {pressures the c3-knight, and ...Bf6 is coming, not to mention ...Bd7 and a rook to the c-file. White is painfully behind in development. Colovic gave 10...exd5 as leading to equality, which is true, but taking with the knight is much stronger.}) 10... Bd7 $5 {[%cal Gc5a4,Ga8c8,Gd7a4] Intending to bring something to a4. White's queenside will come under pressure.} (10... Nfe4 {is fine, but} 11. Be5 {holds things together for White.}) 11. a3 {Some other possibilities:} (11. Be2 Na4 $1 12. Nxa4 Bxa4 13. b3 Bc6 14. O-O b5 $1 {Black has the initiative.}) (11. Be5 Ba4 $1 12. Nxa4 Nxa4 13. b3 Nb6 {with ...Rac8 coming, and continued pressure on White's position.}) 11... Ba4 $1 12. Nxa4 Qxa4 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga8c8,Gc5a4] White had problems with his queenside pawns in Jumabayev-Oparin, chess.com rapid 2022.} *

