1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. Qc2 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another typical QGD move if White insists on delaying e3. White does not commit his rook and maintains the options of castling queenside, but the queen is a bit exposed here and Black can often take advantage of this.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet this the same way as we did with 6.Rc1.} ({Once again,} 6... b6 {is inferior, this time because of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {the thematic move, but it doesn't work well here. 7...exd5 8.e3 $14 is a nice edge for White.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. e4 $1 {makes 6.Qc2 look quite clever. One point is that} Bb4+ {does not cause the trouble it seems to, as} 10. Kd1 $1 {is good for White - Black will waste a lot of time retreating his pieces.}) ({Black should also skip} 6... Nbd7 {because} 7. cxd5 {forces} exd5 8. e3 $14 {with another good exchange variation for White.}) ({Finally,} 6... dxc4 {can be met with} 7. e3 $1 {rather than 7.e4 Nc6!}) 7. dxc5 Na6 $1 {A good flexible move. We may recapture on c5, while ...Nb4 is also a possibility.} ({If} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Rd1 {we have been tricked into White's best line in the 6.e3 c5 complex.}) ({The less common} 7... Qa5 {is given by Ntirlis. This seems fine as well, but White has a lot of choice here and it can be a bit complicated after} 8. Nd2 $5 Qxc5 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. Bg5) 8. e3 {The safest choice. White needs to get developed.} Nxc5 {This transposes to a line that is often reached via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 6 6EndFEN 6.e3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5 Nxc5 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. O-O-O $2 {This has been played quite a bit, including games by strong players, but with today's engines we can quickly determine that this is a poor move.} Qa5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc8d7,Gf8c8][%mdl 32768] Black's pieces spring into action. White has no play on the kingside, so all he can do is try to fight in the center and on the queenside.} 10. Kb1 Bd7 11. Ne5 ({What else? After} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 {all of Black's pieces are ready for action, and the engine desperately gives up the exchange with} 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Rxd5 Be6 14. Bc4 Bxd5 15. Bxd5) 11... Ba4 $1 {A strong move which is difficult to meet.} 12. b3 {This meets a refutation.} Nfe4 {[%cal Ge4c3]} ({This is just crushing. In his QGD book, Pavlovic gives} 12... Bc6 13. f3 Ncd7 {as equal. In fact Black is much better here, but our move is even stronger.}) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. bxa4 ({There's no stopping us now. If} 14. Rc1 Nd2+ 15. Kb2 Bxb3 $1 {with the idea ...Ba3+ is a killer blow.}) 14... Nc3+ 15. Ka1 ({Or} 15. Kc1 Ba3+ {White will be forced to step into the crossfire with} 16. Kd2 {and then Black has an assortment of wins - the knight can take any of d1, a2, a4, while the engine suggests that playing} f6 $5 {is even stronger, and around -5.}) 15... Nxd1 16. Qxd1 dxc4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf8d8] With our rooks ready for action and ...Bf6 coming. White will not survive for long.} *

