 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. O-O-O $2 {This has been played quite a bit, including games by strong players, but with today's engines we can quickly determine that this is a poor move.} Qa5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc8d7,Gf8c8] Black's pieces spring into action. White has no play on the kingside, so all he can do is try to fight in the center and on the queenside.} 10. Kb1 Bd7 11. Ne5 ({What else? After} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 {all of Black's pieces are ready for action, and the engine desperately gives up the exchange with} 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Rxd5 Be6 14. Bc4 Bxd5 15. Bxd5) 11... Ba4 $1 {A strong move which is difficult to meet.} 12. Nxa4 Nxa4 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 $17 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Ga8c8] Black is just much better here and White may already be beyond salvation.} 14. Nc4 Qb5 {[%cal Gd5c3,Ga4c3,Gf8c8,Ga8c8] Threatening a fork on c3, while bringing a rook to c8 is also serious business.} ({Black played} 14... Qb4 $2 {which allowed White to hold on with} 15. Be5 {in Pelletier - Kramnik, Zurich 1999.}) ({Colovic gave} 14... Qa6 {in his course, keeping the possibility of ...b5 . This is also very strong.}) 15. Be5 {[%csl Gc3] Covering c3.} Nb4 16. Qb3 Nc5 {White's queen is bouncing around like a pinball.} 17. Na3 {This counterattack keeps White alive - for now.} Qa5 18. Qc4 a6 $17 {[%csl Rf1,Rh1][%cal Ga8c8,Gb7b5] Black's queenside initiative persists. White is in serious trouble.} *

