 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. Be2 {The only good move. Again, White needs to develop his pieces.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]} 11. a4 ({I like this line for Black a lot. White should really play} 11. a4 {to avoid being worse.}) {By restricting the b7-pawn, Black is limited to ...b6, and it's harder to find a comfortable square for the black queen. Harder, but not impossible!} 11... b6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Black has also done well with} 11... Qa5 12. O-O b6 {but I find the position of the queen on a5 to be a bit awkward.}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gf8d8,Gf8c8] Black is ready to play ...Rd8 and .. .Qc6, creating pressure on the long diagonal. White has been unable to present Black with any problems in practice. I will give a couple of lines though, as there are a couple of small pitfalls to avoid.} 14. Qe2 {This is the most common, but it allows Black to execute his plan.} (14. Ne5 {prevents ...Qc6, but Black can just play} Rd8) 14... Qc6 {[%cal Gb7g2,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] Black is ready to bring the rooks into play, and White must be wary of the long diagonal.} 15. Qf1 {[%csl Gg2] Covering the g2-pawn to free up the f3-knight.} Rfc8 $1 ({This is the right square.} 15... Rac8 16. Nd4 {forces the queen back to e8, blocking in the f8-rook.}) ({while} 15... Rfd8 16. Nd4 Qc8 {if 16...Qe8 17.Bc7 wins a pawn} 17. b4 Ncd7 18. Rac1 {is very uncomfortable for Black.}) 16. Ne5 Qe8 {[%cal Gc5d7,Gc8d8] Black coordinated his pieces and had nothing to worry about in Karjakin-Kramnik, Nice (blindfold) 2009.} *

