1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. Qc2 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another typical QGD move if White insists on delaying e3. White does not commit his rook and maintains the options of castling queenside, but the queen is a bit exposed here and Black can often take advantage of this.} 6... c5 $1 {We will meet this the same way as we did with 6.Rc1.} ({Once again,} 6... b6 {is inferior, this time because of} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 {the thematic move, but it doesn't work well here. 7...exd5 8.e3 $14 is a nice edge for White.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. e4 $1 {makes 6.Qc2 look quite clever. One point is that} Bb4+ {does not cause the trouble it seems to, as} 10. Kd1 $1 {is good for White - Black will waste a lot of time retreating his pieces.}) ({Black should also skip} 6... Nbd7 {because} 7. cxd5 {forces} exd5 8. e3 $14 {with another good exchange variation for White.}) ({Finally,} 6... dxc4 {can be met with} 7. e3 $1 {rather than 7.e4 Nc6!}) 7. dxc5 Na6 $1 {A good flexible move. We may recapture on c5, while ...Nb4 is also a possibility.} ({If} 7... Bxc5 8. e3 Nc6 9. a3 Qa5 10. Rd1 {we have been tricked into White's best line in the 6.e3 c5 complex.}) ({The less common} 7... Qa5 {is given by Ntirlis. This seems fine as well, but White has a lot of choice here and it can be a bit complicated after} 8. Nd2 $5 Qxc5 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 e5 11. Bg5) 8. e3 {The safest choice. White needs to get developed.} Nxc5 {This transposes to a line that is often reached via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 6 6EndFEN 6.e3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 c5 8.dxc5 Nxc5 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. Be2 {The only good move. Again, White needs to develop his pieces.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]} 11. a4 ({I like this line for Black a lot. White should really play} 11. a4 {to avoid being worse.}) 11... b6 ({Black has also done well with} 11... Qa5 12. O-O b6 {but I find the position of the queen on a5 to be a bit awkward.}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gf8d8,Gf8c8] Black is ready to play ... Rd8 and ...Qc6, creating pressure on the long diagonal. White has been unable to present Black with any problems in practice. I will give a couple of lines though, as there are a couple of small pitfalls to avoid.} 14. Rac1 ({This is less common than} 14. Qe2 {, but it's trickier.}) 14... Rd8 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Here we should avoid} 14... Qc6 15. Bf1 $1 {intending Ne5. If} Rfc8 16. Ne5 Qe8 17. Nc4 $16 {and Black cannot play 15...Rfd8 16.b4! when there's no solution to various tactical problems, for example 16...Nce4 17.Nxe4 Qxe4 18.Qc7!}) 15. Nd4 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb2b4,Gc2b3,Gb3e6] Now we must watch out for b4 with the idea Qb3, putting a lot of pressure on the e6-pawn.} (15. b4 Nce4 {is fine now.}) 15... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4] A key move. White's bishop controls important squares, so we give it a nudge.} (15... Nce4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Qb3 {is troublesome. Our queen is vulnerable, and we have to watch out for explosions on e6.}) (15... a5 {is possible, but I don't like giving up the b5-square forever.}) 16. b4 {This is no problem.} Nxf4 17. exf4 ({After} 17. bxc5 $2 Qxc5 {the c4-bishop is hanging, and} 18. Ne4 Qe5 {will see Black emerge a pawn up.}) 17... Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4] A counterattack on the d4-knight, while the c4-bishop is also rather loose. Black is doing well.} *

