 , but it's not considered to be a critical test.} 9. Be2 {The only good move. Again, White needs to develop his pieces.} dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]} 11. a4 ({I like this line for Black a lot. White should really play} 11. a4 {to avoid being worse.}) 11... b6 ({Black has also done well with} 11... Qa5 12. O-O b6 {but I find the position of the queen on a5 to be a bit awkward.}) 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qc8 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gf8d8,Gf8c8] Black is ready to play ...Rd8 and ...Qc6, creating pressure on the long diagonal. White has been unable to present Black with any problems in practice. I will give a couple of lines though, as there are a couple of small pitfalls to avoid.} 14. Rac1 ({This is less common than} 14. Qe2 {, but it's trickier.}) 14... Rd8 $1 ({Here we should avoid} 14... Qc6 15. Bf1 $1 {intending Ne5. If} Rfc8 16. Ne5 Qe8 17. Nc4 $16 {and Black cannot play 15...Rfd8 16.b4! when there's no solution to various tactical problems, for example 16...Nce4 17.Nxe4 Qxe4 18.Qc7!}) 15. Nd4 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gb2b4,Gc2b3,Gb3e6] Now we must watch out for b4 with the idea Qb3, putting a lot of pressure on the e6-pawn.} (15. b4 Nce4 {is fine now.}) 15... Nh5 $1 {A key move. White's bishop controls important squares, so we give it a nudge.} (15... Nce4 16. Nxe4 Bxe4 17. Qb3 {is troublesome. Our queen is vulnerable, and we have to watch out for explosions on e6.}) (15... a5 {is possible, but I don't like giving up the b5-square forever.}) 16. Be5 {This looks like a blunder at first, but White has a resource.} Nd7 {[%csl Rc4,Re5][%cal Gd7e5,Gc8c4][%mdl 32768] This attacks both of White's bishops.} 17. Nxe6 ({White can save the piece with} 17. Be2 Nxe5 18. Bxh5 {but Black is doing well with the bishop pair after} Qc5) 17... Nxe5 ({Black can also go into an endgame with} 17... Qxc4 18. Nxd8 Rxd8 {but after} 19. Nd5 $1 Bxd5 20. Qxc4 Bxc4 21. Bc7 Re8 22. Rxc4 {I prefer White's rook and pawn to Black's pair of knights.}) 18. Nxd8 Bxd8 19. Be2 Nf6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 20. Z0 ({White has a rook and pawn against two minor pieces, but we still have the bishop pair. White should probably head into an endgame with} 20. Nd5 Qxc2 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Rxc2 {with chances for both sides.}) *

