1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. a3 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another move delaying e3. Fortunately, we can go for 6...b6 here, as 6.a3 does not create any pressure down the c-file unlike the deviations we just examined.} 6... b6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({One point of White's move order is directed against the popular} 6... Nbd7 {line. Here} 7. Nb5 $1 {is annoying for Black as there is no check on b4.}) (6... dxc4 {was the recommendation of Ntirlis. This is fine, but both 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Bf6 and 7.e4 b5 8.Nxb5 Nxe4 9.Bxc4 lead to complications that are quite a bit to study for an uncommon line.}) ({I would like to recommend} 6... c5 {to be consistent with our responses against 6.Rc1 and 6.Qc2, but after} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {if 7...Bxc5 8.e3 we are getting tricked into the 6.e3 c5 line Now} 8. e3 {is not so dangerous. One attractive game went} Nd5 9. Bd6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Bxc4 Nc6 13. Ba6 Bxa6 14. Nxc6 Bf6 $3 {and Black took over in Esserman - Ippolito, Mesa 2009. The problem is 8.e4! when White is better.}) 7. cxd5 {A common reaction to ...b6 in the QGD as well as in the Queen's Indian when Black plays ...d5.} Nxd5 {Exchanging pieces. Just like in the Tartakover, we will almost always meet cxd5 in this way in the ...b6 lines.} 8. Nxd5 exd5 ({It's not easy for Black to prove compensation after} 8... Qxd5 9. Bxc7 {as there's no check on b4 .}) 9. g3 $5 ({An independent continuation. Instead} 9. e3 c5 {transposes to 7.e3.}) 9... c5 10. Bg2 ({White can fling in} 10. dxc5 bxc5 {first. It does not matter.}) 10... Be6 {As we also saw in the Tartakover, the bishop is well placed here instead of on b7 in certain structures.} 11. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb6b5] Now Black may consider ...c4, activating his queenside pawn majority.} 12. dxc5 bxc5 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ga7a5,Ga8a7,Ga7b7,Gc5c4] Black's pawns are secure, and he can put some pressure on the weakened b-file. In addition to ...Qb6, ...a5 and ...Ra7-b7 is a possibility, dodging the f4-bishop.} *

