1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. a3 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another move delaying e3. Fortunately, we can go for 6...b6 here, as 6.a3 does not create any pressure down the c-file unlike the deviations we just examined.} 6... b6 ({One point of White's move order is directed against the popular} 6... Nbd7 {line. Here} 7. Nb5 $1 {is annoying for Black as there is no check on b4.}) (6... dxc4 {was the recommendation of Ntirlis. This is fine, but both 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Bf6 and 7.e4 b5 8.Nxb5 Nxe4 9.Bxc4 lead to complications that are quite a bit to study for an uncommon line.}) ({I would like to recommend} 6... c5 {to be consistent with our responses against 6.Rc1 and 6.Qc2, but after} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {if 7...Bxc5 8.e3 we are getting tricked into the 6.e3 c5 line Now} 8. e3 {is not so dangerous. One attractive game went} Nd5 9. Bd6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Bxc4 Nc6 13. Ba6 Bxa6 14. Nxc6 Bf6 $3 {and Black took over in Esserman - Ippolito, Mesa 2009. The problem is 8.e4! when White is better.}) 7. e3 {White's most common move. This could also arise after 6.e3 b6 7.a3, but it is more often reached via 6. a3.} c5 $1 {Black strikes in the center, highlighting the slowness of White's last move.} ({If} 7... Ba6 8. Nb5 $5 {is an interesting try for White. We don't have the check on b4 , and have to deal with the c7-pawn.}) (7... Bb7 {is the obvious move.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Bxd5 {after 9...Qxd5 10.Bxc7 $16 we are missing our check on b4!} 10. Bd3 c5 11. dxc5 {forces} bxc5 {which is not so terrible, but I prefer the hanging pawns to this structure. Note that 11...Bxc5 12.Bxh7+! is winning for White.}) 8. dxc5 bxc5 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3][%cal Gd8b6][%mdl 32768] We have an 'almost' hanging pawn structure. White will lack the blocking move b2-b3.} 9. Be2 {A flexible move.} (9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 {transposes to 8.cxd5.}) 9... Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Ga2a3] Black has a healthy position. He has enough space, and a square for the queen. The move a2-a3 here has not helped White, as it slightly softens up the b-file.} *

