1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. a3 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another move delaying e3. Fortunately, we can go for 6...b6 here, as 6.a3 does not create any pressure down the c-file unlike the deviations we just examined.} 6... b6 ({One point of White's move order is directed against the popular} 6... Nbd7 {line. Here} 7. Nb5 $1 {is annoying for Black as there is no check on b4.}) (6... dxc4 {was the recommendation of Ntirlis. This is fine, but both 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Bf6 and 7.e4 b5 8.Nxb5 Nxe4 9.Bxc4 lead to complications that are quite a bit to study for an uncommon line.}) ({I would like to recommend} 6... c5 {to be consistent with our responses against 6.Rc1 and 6.Qc2, but after} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {if 7...Bxc5 8.e3 we are getting tricked into the 6.e3 c5 line Now} 8. e3 {is not so dangerous. One attractive game went} Nd5 9. Bd6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Bxc4 Nc6 13. Ba6 Bxa6 14. Nxc6 Bf6 $3 {and Black took over in Esserman - Ippolito, Mesa 2009. The problem is 8.e4! when White is better.}) 7. Qc2 {White is mixing and matching systems.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. cxd5 (8. e3 c5 9. dxc5 bxc5 {is similar to the 7.e3 line, but here White has committed to Qc2 rather early.}) 8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 10. e3 {White cannot really grab the c7-pawn.} (10. Bxc7 $4 Rc8 {pins and wins.}) (10. Qxc7 $2 Nd7 $1 {and with a rook coming to c8, Black's development lead is overwhelming.}) 10... Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5] We are ready for ...c5.} 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7] Developing with tempo, apparently.} c5 $1 {We can ignore it!} 12. Bxh7+ Kf8 {[%cal Gc5d4]} ({But not} 12... Kh8 $2 13. Ne5 $1) 13. dxc5 Nd7 $5 (13... Rxc5 {is also good, but this is even better.}) 14. Rd1 Qxc5 {[%cal Gg7g6]} 15. Z0 ({White can capture various things, but Black is so active that there's always enough compensation for a pawn. Some possibilities:} 15. O-O) ({If} 15. Rxd7 $2 Qa5+ {wins White's queen}) ({White can trade with} 15. Qxc5 Nxc5 16. Bc2 Bf6 17. Be5 Bxf3 $1 18. Bd6+ Ke8 19. gxf3 Bxb2 {regaining the pawn Qxc2 Bxc2 Rxc2 Rxd7 Bd5 and the active bishops give Black ample play.}) *

