1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. a3 ({Now} 6. e3 {is the top choice by an absolutely huge margin, but other moves have some point and we have to know how to react.}) {Another move delaying e3. Fortunately, we can go for 6...b6 here, as 6.a3 does not create any pressure down the c-file unlike the deviations we just examined.} 6... b6 ({One point of White's move order is directed against the popular} 6... Nbd7 {line. Here} 7. Nb5 $1 {is annoying for Black as there is no check on b4.}) (6... dxc4 {was the recommendation of Ntirlis. This is fine, but both 7.e3 Nd5 8.Bxc4 Nxf4 9.exf4 Bf6 and 7.e4 b5 8.Nxb5 Nxe4 9.Bxc4 lead to complications that are quite a bit to study for an uncommon line.}) ({I would like to recommend} 6... c5 {to be consistent with our responses against 6.Rc1 and 6.Qc2, but after} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {if 7...Bxc5 8.e3 we are getting tricked into the 6.e3 c5 line Now} 8. e3 {is not so dangerous. One attractive game went} Nd5 9. Bd6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Bxc4 Nc6 13. Ba6 Bxa6 14. Nxc6 Bf6 $3 {and Black took over in Esserman - Ippolito, Mesa 2009. The problem is 8.e4! when White is better.}) 7. Qc2 {White is mixing and matching systems.} Bb7 8. Rd1 {The sharpest choice. This has been played by some very strong players.} dxc4 $1 ({We should take up the challenge.} 8... Nbd7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. e3 $14 {is playable, but a typical white edge.}) 9. e4 ({White started this, so he has to play sharply.} 9. e3 $6 {is well met by} Nd5 $1 {If} 10. Bxc4 Nxf4 11. exf4 Bxf3 $1 {leaves White with an 'interesting pawn' structure.}) 9... b5 $1 {A typical idea. White can't take on b5 without dropping e4, so he has to play for compensation.} 10. h4 {The only good move. White must play for attacking chances. This position has occurred four times in my database, with Black choosing a different move each time! So it's not an easy choice, but any white player would have to be ready for quite a bit here.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5][%mdl 32768] We'll go with this move, but others are also quite playable.} (10... a6 {was ultimately successful in Vovk-Vajda, Malinska 2015, but I don't think Black needs to worry about the b5-pawn yet.}) (10... h6 {is not bad, but this can be played later. I think the critical line is} 11. Ng5 $1 Nh5 $1) (10... c5 $5 {is yet another option.} 11. dxc5 Nbd7 12. Ng5 {and now Black went for an interesting queen sacrifice with} e5 $5 13. Bxe5 Nxe5 14. Rxd8 Raxd8 15. b4 {Now, rather than 15...Nd3+ as played in Mamedyarov-Krysa, Caleta 2020 I think Black should have gone for} cxb3 16. Qxb3 a6 $13 {which is very interesting, with the computer spitting out a very useful 0.00.}) 11. Ng5 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (11. Nxb5 $2 Bxe4 12. Qxc4 c6 {followed by taking on f3 is again good for Black.}) 11... Nh5 $1 {This is a good idea, disrupting White's coordination.} 12. Bc1 (12. Be3 h6 {is similar.}) (12. e5 g6 $1 13. Be3 Ng7 $1 {with the idea ...Nf5 and ...c5 gives Black good chances.}) 12... h6 {We are not going to really win any material, but White has to be very accurate here.} 13. Nxb5 $1 (13. Nf3 $6 c5 $1 {takes over the initiative.}) (13. Be2 hxg5 14. Bxh5 $2 gxh4 {fails to impress. 14.hxg5 g6 15.Bxh5 gxh5 with ...Kg7 coming, looks insufficient for White.}) 13... hxg5 ({Despite opening the h-file, this is relatively safe and sound. Further complications arise after} 13... c5 $5 14. Bxc4 a6 15. Nc3 cxd4 16. Rxd4 Bc5 17. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. Rxd7 Qe8 {if you'd like to explore.}) 14. hxg5 Bxg5 $1 ({Instead} 14... g6 15. g4 Ng7 $2 {is too greedy.} 16. f4 $1 {with the idea Qh2 gives White a strong attack,}) 15. Rxh5 Bxc1 16. Qxc1 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] The dust is settling and chances are about equal, as Black is grabbing the e4-pawn and there's not any real danger on the h-file. This was Adhiban-Jakovenko, Batumi 2018.} *

