1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1] This is not so common, but it's a typical QGD move and it scores well.} Ba6 $1 {[%csl Rc4] Casual development leaves Black cramped, so we play this active move to get some exchanges in.} (7... Bb7 {is doubtless playable, but after} 8. Rd1 {it's not easy for Black. If} Nbd7 9. cxd5 {we must mind the c7-pawn, and} exd5 10. Bd3 {is a typical edge for White.}) (7... c5 {is better, and only slightly favouring White after} 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. Be2 {This is similar to the line with 6.a3 b6 7.e3, but here White has not burned a tempo on a3.}) 8. Ne5 {This covers the c4-pawn, but further delays White's development.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bxc4 (9. Nxc4 {has not been tried.} Qc8 $5 {looks like a good answer, planning ...c5 and possibily ...Rd8.}) 9... Bxc4 10. Nxc4 Nd5 $1 {Initiating further exchanges.} 11. Bg3 ({If} 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 Qxc5 {with ...Nd7 or ...Nc6 next, looks fine for Black.}) 11... Nxc3 ({I prefer trading right away, as} 11... c5 12. dxc5 Nxc3 {can be met with} 13. cxb6 $1 {threatening b6-b7.}) 12. Qxc3 Qd5 (12... Na6 {has also been played and looks fine.}) 13. O-O c5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Rac1 Nc6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8] Natural development.} ({This looks better than} 15... Na6 {when} 16. a3 {restricted the knight in Shishkin-Sahil, Alba Iulia 2019.}) 16. Nd6 Qxc3 17. Rxc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d5,Ge7f6,Gb4a2] Lots of trades and Black is clearly fine here.} *

