1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1] This is not so common, but it's a typical QGD move and it scores well.} Ba6 $1 {[%csl Rc4] Casual development leaves Black cramped, so we play this active move to get some exchanges in.} (7... Bb7 {is doubtless playable, but after} 8. Rd1 {it's not easy for Black. If} Nbd7 9. cxd5 {we must mind the c7-pawn, and} exd5 10. Bd3 {is a typical edge for White.}) (7... c5 {is better, and only slightly favouring White after} 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. Be2 {This is similar to the line with 6.a3 b6 7.e3, but here White has not burned a tempo on a3.}) 8. O-O-O $5 {Dubov's over the board inspiration. As he pointed out, the engine does not like it at first but it's not really worse for White.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Taking the pawn is the most ambitious.} 8... Bxc4 9. Bxc4 dxc4 10. Qe2 {regains the pawn.}) ({However} 8... Nc6 $5 {holding ground in the center and considering the idea ...Na5 is also interesting.}) 9. Ng5 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gh2h4,Gf4e5,Ye3e4,Yd4d5] White wants to mate us on h7! So Be5xf6 is a basic idea. White will play h4 to discourage us from eating the knight with ...h6xg5. We should also consider central play with e4 and d5.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] Backing up the f6-knight.} ({Let's avoid} 9... b5 10. d5 $1 {as our knight is tied to h7 .}) ({The stem game went} 9... Nc6 10. a3 g6 $1 11. h4 Bd6 $5 {instead 11...Nd5! 12.Nxd5 exd5 would be very sharp, as both sides have serious attacking chances!} 12. g3 $1 {supporting the f4-bishop and planning Bg2 gave White everything he wanted in Dubov-Svane, Batumi 2019.}) 10. h4 b5 {Now Dubov gives the following line:} 11. Nce4 Nxe4 {Stockfish suggests 11...g6 instead. It's all very sharp.} 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qc2 b4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 {Dubov ends here, saying equal. We could go a little further.} Qd5 (15... h6 {is the computer's choice. This is sharper.}) 16. Qxd5 Nxd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] We will get in ...c5 with equality.} *

