1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Rc1 {After 7.cxd5 and 7.Bd3, this is White's most popular move. The early development of the rook is common enough in various QGD lines, but here, combined with the bishop on f4, it takes specific aim at the c7-pawn.} ({We can compare what follows with the line} 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O a6 10. Qe2 b5 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Rfd1 $1) 7... Bb7 {[%mdl 32768] Not exactly a shocking move, but bringing the bishop to a6 is often played in our 6...b6 line. Now White can develop, play another waiting move, or initiate play in the center.} ({Here} 7... Ba6 {is well met with the strong} 8. Qa4 $16) ({The immediate} 7... c5 {is playable, although we are committing to having some hanging pawns.} 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. Be2 {I prefer to only go for this structure when White has played the weakening a2-a3.}) 8. Be2 {A natural move, but now Black can head for a typical setup where White's Rc1 is not the most critical test.} dxc4 $1 9. Bxc4 a6 10. O-O {As played in the analogous line with 7.Bd3 above.} ({If} 10. a4 c5 {and ...Nc6 gives Black a good position.}) 10... b5 11. Bd3 ({The correct square.} 11. Bb3 $6 c5 12. dxc5 Nbd7 {is already trending for Black. If} 13. c6 Bxc6 14. Ne2 Nc5 $15) 11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 c5 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc5d4] compared to the 7.Bd3 dxc4 8.Bxc4 Bb7 line, White has played Rc1 very early, when Rfd1 would be much more useful. It makes a huge difference!} 13. dxc5 {If White does not take he has to contend with ...cxd4, when White would have to accept an isolated pawn as Nxd4 runs into ...e5.} Nxc5 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gc5d3,Gb5b4,Gd8b6,Ga8c8,Gf8d8] White is not on the d-file yet, so Black is already fighting for the initiative and it is White who must be careful.} *

