1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Rc1 {After 7.cxd5 and 7.Bd3, this is White's most popular move. The early development of the rook is common enough in various QGD lines, but here, combined with the bishop on f4, it takes specific aim at the c7-pawn.} ({We can compare what follows with the line} 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bb7 9. O-O a6 10. Qe2 b5 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Rfd1 $1) 7... Bb7 {Not exactly a shocking move, but bringing the bishop to a6 is often played in our 6...b6 line. Now White can develop, play another waiting move, or initiate play in the center.} ({Here} 7... Ba6 {is well met with the strong} 8. Qa4 $16) ({The immediate} 7... c5 {is playable, although we are committing to having some hanging pawns.} 8. dxc5 bxc5 9. Be2 {I prefer to only go for this structure when White has played the weakening a2-a3.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] We can offer up the c7-pawn.} 9. Nxd5 ({If White politely declines with} 9. Bg3 {Black has no problems after} Nxc3 10. bxc3 Nd7 {or 9...c5 10.Nxd5 exd5}) 9... Qxd5 {[%cal Gd5a2,Ge7b4] We have threats too.} 10. a3 {Saving the a2-pawn and stopping ...Bb4+} Qa5+ $5 {This scores well. Ntirlis did not like it, which I can understand, but it's relatively easy and Black gets a position where he may outplay the opponent.} 11. Nd2 ({Black is fine after} 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 c5 13. dxc5 Rc8 $1) 11... c5 12. Rc3 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] The only challenge. Now Nc4 is a threat, so we will have to give up the bishop pair.} (12. dxc5 {can be met with} Bf6 $132) 12... Ba6 13. Nc4 Bxc4 14. Bxc4 b5 {Fighting for some space.} 15. Be2 Nd7 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gd7f6,Gd7b6] White has the bishop pair but the engines think Black is ok. After ...c4 and ...Nf6 or ...Nb6 Black can hope to use his queenside pawn majority. White has chances of course too.} *

