1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Be2 {Roiz recommended this move order in his modern-chess database. It does not mean much for us, as we will take on c4 in any case.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Bxc4 Ba6 {Going for the exchange of bishops is very typical in the 7...b6 line.} (8... Ba6 {is the most common move, and it has been played by some players you may have heard of: Carlsen, Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, and other 2750+ players. For some reason this was not considered by Roiz in his modern-chess database. White can either capture himself, or allow Black to capture.}) *

