1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {A popular move. This was Shankland's recommendation in his epic 1.d4 course.} dxc4 {This looks simplest, and has the added advantage that it gives us an answer to 7.Be2, which was met in the same way.} ({After the natural} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {if 9...Bxd5 , 10.Qc2 hits both the h7- and c7-pawns} 10. Bxc7 {looks insufficient for Black.}) ({However} 7... Ba6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {is not bad. Black always plays this, but Shankland only considered 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.O-O c5 12.e4 Qb7 13.d5 $16 which indeed favors White.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. O-O {if 10.Bxc7 Qa5+ 11.Ke2 Bxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Na6! is good for Black.} Rc8 $5 {intending ...c5.}) 8. Bxc4 Bb7 {This keeps pieces on the board and the play is more complicated, but I think White maintains chances for an edge.} (8... Ba6 {will be our repertoire choice.}) 9. O-O {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd1e2,Gf1d1,Ga1c1] As we've seen in many cases, White has a good square on e2 for his queen which allows his rooks to quickly come to the center, while Black cannot say the same.} a6 10. Qe2 b5 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] White has scored heavily here, although the engine claims near-equality for Black after:} Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c5] This looks like the best try.} (12... c5 {has been played many times, but} 13. dxc5 {looks very good for White.}) 13. Ne5 h6 $5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc7c5] One more preparation. I think that Black will get in ...c5 sooner or later!} ({The immediate} 13... c5 $2 {runs into} 14. dxc5 Rxc5 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qd3+) *

