1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {A popular move. This was Shankland's recommendation in his epic 1.d4 course.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768] This looks simplest, and has the added advantage that it gives us an answer to 7.Be2, which was met in the same way.} ({After the natural} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {if 9...Bxd5 , 10.Qc2 hits both the h7- and c7-pawns} 10. Bxc7 {looks insufficient for Black.}) ({However} 7... Ba6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {is not bad. Black always plays this, but Shankland only considered 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.O-O c5 12.e4 Qb7 13.d5 $16 which indeed favors White.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. O-O {if 10.Bxc7 Qa5+ 11.Ke2 Bxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Na6! is good for Black.} Rc8 $5 {intending ...c5.}) 8. Bxc4 Ba6 {Going for the exchange of bishops is very typical in the 7...b6 line.} (8... Ba6 {is the most common move, and it has been played by some players you may have heard of: Carlsen, Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, and other 2750+ players. For some reason this was not considered by Roiz in his modern-chess database. White can either capture himself, or allow Black to capture.}) 9. Qe2 {White prefers to avoid helping Black develop his knight, even if the a6-square is not always ideal.} (9. Qa4 $6 {could be met with} Bxc4 {, transposing, or with 9...Bb7 , arguing that White's queen has been lured to a silly square. As ...a6 will come next, Black has a pretty good case here.}) 9... Bxc4 ({Instead} 9... Qc8 {is also playable, but Black will have to take on c4 sooner or later. For example,} 10. O-O Bxc4 11. Qxc4 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 12.0-0.}) 10. Qxc4 c5 11. dxc5 ({Instead} 11. O-O {can be met with 11...Qc8, but this move order just gives Black extra options like} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qc8 13. Qxc8 Rxc8 14. Rac1 Nbd7 {Mamedyarov-Nakamura, Kolkata rapid 2018.}) 11... Bxc5 {With the symmetrical structure, Black has to be confident in neutralizing White's slight initiative.} (11... bxc5 {is playable as well, but I prefer not to split the pawns without good reason.}) 12. Rc1 {This is a bit tricky.} Nbd7 $1 ({Here} 12... Qc8 $6 {is mistimed, as it runs into} 13. b4 $1 Be7 14. Nd5 Qb7 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. O-O {$14}) 13. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge1g1,Gf1d1]} ({This has been tried a couple of times, but it doesn't bother us.} 13. O-O Qc8 {transposes to 12.0-0.}) 13... Bb4 $1 {We have seen this idea before; Black wants to either to split White's pawns, or to exchange more pieces.} 14. O-O Bxc3 15. Rxc3 Nd5 {[%cal Gd5f4,Ga8c8] Black will take the bishop with easy equality.} *

