ke} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qc8 13. Qxc8 Rxc8 14. Rac1 Nbd7 {Mamedyarov-Nakamura, Kolkata rapid 2018.}) 11... Bxc5 {With the symmetrical structure, Black has to be confident in neutralizing White's slight initiative.} (11... bxc5 {is playable as well, but I prefer not to split the pawns without good reason.}) 12. O-O Qc8 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8b7] I like this move. Black's queen heads for the cozy b7-square. I like this move. Black's queen heads for the cozy b7-square. transposes.} 13. Rac1 Nbd7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga7a6][%mdl 32768] Developing and preparing to bolster the queesnide with ...a6 and ...Qb7, connecting the rooks.} 14. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7] This looks like the only move that could possibly cause trouble.} Qa6 $1 ({Black must avoid} 14... Qb7 $2 15. b4 $1 Be7 16. Nfd4 {with the knight coming to c6, is a disaster.}) 15. Nc7 Qxc4 16. Rxc4 Rac8 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5] A simple improvement on a high level game.} (16... Rad8 {was Harikrishna-Karjakin, Jerusalem 2019. Here} 17. b4 $1 Be7 18. Nd4 {gives White pressure.}) ({After} 16... Rac8 $1 {one possible line is} 17. Rfc1 e5 $1 18. Nxe5 Rxc7 19. b4 $1 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Bxe3 $1 {with more pieces leaving the board and equality.}) *

