1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {A popular move. This was Shankland's recommendation in his epic 1.d4 course.} dxc4 {This looks simplest, and has the added advantage that it gives us an answer to 7.Be2, which was met in the same way.} ({After the natural} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {if 9...Bxd5 , 10.Qc2 hits both the h7- and c7-pawns} 10. Bxc7 {looks insufficient for Black.}) ({However} 7... Ba6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {is not bad. Black always plays this, but Shankland only considered 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.O-O c5 12.e4 Qb7 13.d5 $16 which indeed favors White.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. O-O {if 10.Bxc7 Qa5+ 11.Ke2 Bxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Na6! is good for Black.} Rc8 $5 {intending ...c5.}) 8. Bxc4 Ba6 {Going for the exchange of bishops is very typical in the 7...b6 line.} (8... Ba6 {is the most common move, and it has been played by some players you may have heard of: Carlsen, Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, and other 2750+ players. For some reason this was not considered by Roiz in his modern-chess database. White can either capture himself, or allow Black to capture.}) 9. Bxa6 {White prefers to trade himself.} Nxa6 {[%mdl 32768] White has three main tries now: 10.Qe2, 10.Qa4, and 10.0-0.} 10. Qe2 {Ntirlis gives this as his main line, and it's White best scoring move.} Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] A familiar idea. We protect the knight and the queen wants to go to b7.} 11. O-O {The obvious move.} ({Instead} 11. e4 c5 12. O-O {would transpose. Ntirlis points out that 12.d5? fails after 12...exd5 13.e5 Re8 $17}) 11... c5 ({Playing} 11... Qb7 {first is also possible. Then} 12. a3 $5 {or 12.e4 c5 equalizing without much difficulty.} c5 13. Nb5 {would transpose to 12.Nb5.}) 12. e4 (12. Rac1 {is common but it does not really bother us.} Qb7 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 {and Black has no problems.}) 12... Qb7 {Let's connect the rooks. This equalizes without much difficulty.} ({Black has also tried} 12... cxd4 {and while it seems ok, there is not reason to invite White's knight to d4 and then b5 so quickly. 13.Nxd4 Rd8 14.Rfd1 Qb7 15.Ndb5 White has a very slight initiative.}) 13. Rad1 Rad8 {[%cal Gc5d4,Gd8d7,Gf8d8,Ga6b4,Gb4c6] Black can take on d4, play ...Nb4, or double rooks on the d-file.} *

