1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {A popular move. This was Shankland's recommendation in his epic 1.d4 course.} dxc4 {This looks simplest, and has the added advantage that it gives us an answer to 7.Be2, which was met in the same way.} ({After the natural} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {if 9...Bxd5 , 10.Qc2 hits both the h7- and c7-pawns} 10. Bxc7 {looks insufficient for Black.}) ({However} 7... Ba6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {is not bad. Black always plays this, but Shankland only considered 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.O-O c5 12.e4 Qb7 13.d5 $16 which indeed favors White.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. O-O {if 10.Bxc7 Qa5+ 11.Ke2 Bxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Na6! is good for Black.} Rc8 $5 {intending ...c5.}) 8. Bxc4 Ba6 {Going for the exchange of bishops is very typical in the 7...b6 line.} (8... Ba6 {is the most common move, and it has been played by some players you may have heard of: Carlsen, Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, and other 2750+ players. For some reason this was not considered by Roiz in his modern-chess database. White can either capture himself, or allow Black to capture.}) 9. Bxa6 {White prefers to trade himself.} Nxa6 {White has three main tries now: 10.Qe2, 10.Qa4, and 10.0-0.} 10. Qa4 {This was Shankland's recommendation and we can see why - he used it to get a good position against Anand.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3][%mdl 32768] The trending choice for Black.} ({Anand went for} 10... Qc8 {which is playable.} 11. O-O c5 12. Rac1 Qb7 13. a3 {Here Anand played} Rfc8 {13...cxd4 14.exd4! also favors White. 13...Nc7 looks best, but I still prefer White slightly.} 14. Nb5 Nb8 15. dxc5 bxc5 {was Shankland-Anand, Wijk aan Zee 2019, when Sam points out that} 16. Nd6 Bxd6 17. Bxd6 {maintains a nice edge.}) 11. O-O Qe8 $5 {An engine move, but the idea is not uncommon.} ({The most popular response has been} 11... c5 {, but after} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Be5 $5 {White's rook comes to the center and taking on f6 may soon become annoying. Black looks a little disorganized.}) ({Instead} 11... Nbd5 {is not bad.} 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bg3 {was Esipenko-Fedoseev, Sochi 2018. Now} c5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 {intending ...Qe8, leaves Black very close to equality. Note that} 15. Rac1 {can be met with} Nxe3 $1) 12. Qxe8 Rfxe8 $1 ({Offering up the c7-pawn.} 12... Nxe8 {would be too passive.}) 13. Bxc7 Rec8 {[%cal Bc8c2] Black has typical compensation for the pawn.} 14. Be5 Nd3 $132 {[%cal Gd3b2,Gc8c3] Making use of the knight.} 15. Rab1 (15. Na4 {looks ugly. After} Rc2 {Black is very active.}) 15... Nxb2 {[%cal Gc8c3] And Black wins back the pawn.} *

