e2 {shows White's idea - he's gotten in useful moves without committing the queen yet.}) ({And if} 11... Qd7 12. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 13. Qxd7 Ncxd7 14. Rfd1 $146 {with ideas like Nb5 and g4!?, it seems to me Black is not out of the woods yet.}) 12. dxc5 {A typical simplification. Black should take some care.} ({Instead} 12. a3 {forces us where we want to go, and} Nbd5 {exchanges another set of minor pieces.}) ({The advance} 12. e4 {can be met with} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Be5 Rc8 {allowing us to retreat the knight to c6.}) 12... Bxc5 ({Let's not get too excited by} 12... Nd3 $2 {White has} 13. cxb6 Nxc1 $2 14. b7 $1) 13. Be5 Nfd5 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rd3] Maintaining the b4-knight for the moment for some nuisance value.} (13... Nd3 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rc2 $16 {is good for White.}) 14. a3 {White forces us to make the exchange rather than doing it himself.} (14. Qa4 Qe8 $1 {is a typical response.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Nd5 17. Rc2 ({Or} 17. Rcd3 f6 {and ...Rfc8.}) 17... Rfd8 {[%cal Gf7f6] I don't see any problems for Black.} 18. Z0 ({If} 18. Rcd2 {Black can play} Rdc8 {or 18...Be7}) *

