1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 {A popular move. This was Shankland's recommendation in his epic 1.d4 course.} dxc4 {This looks simplest, and has the added advantage that it gives us an answer to 7.Be2, which was met in the same way.} ({After the natural} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 {if 9...Bxd5 , 10.Qc2 hits both the h7- and c7-pawns} 10. Bxc7 {looks insufficient for Black.}) ({However} 7... Ba6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {is not bad. Black always plays this, but Shankland only considered 8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Nxd5 10.Nxd5 Qxd5 11.O-O c5 12.e4 Qb7 13.d5 $16 which indeed favors White.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. O-O {if 10.Bxc7 Qa5+ 11.Ke2 Bxd3+ 12.Qxd3 Na6! is good for Black.} Rc8 $5 {intending ...c5.}) 8. Bxc4 Ba6 {Going for the exchange of bishops is very typical in the 7...b6 line.} (8... Ba6 {is the most common move, and it has been played by some players you may have heard of: Carlsen, Caruana, Nakamura, Anand, and other 2750+ players. For some reason this was not considered by Roiz in his modern-chess database. White can either capture himself, or allow Black to capture.}) 9. Bxa6 {White prefers to trade himself.} Nxa6 {White has three main tries now: 10.Qe2, 10.Qa4, and 10.0-0.} 10. O-O {White remains flexible.} c5 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gc8b7,Gd8d7,Gd7b7]} 11. Rc1 $5 {Another flexible move. This is not common but it's the engine's top choice.} (11. Qe2 Qc8 {brings us back to the 10.Qe2 line.}) 11... Nb4 $5 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gb4c6,Gc5c4,Gb4d3,Ga8c8] Black looks to 'fix' his a6-knight in the most active way. There is the obvious ...Nbd5 as a possibility, and the knight may head back to c6. Even ...c4 and ...Nd3 is a possibility.} ({After} 11... Qc8 12. a3 Rd8 13. Qe2 {shows White's idea - he's gotten in useful moves without committing the queen yet.}) ({And if} 11... Qd7 12. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 13. Qxd7 Ncxd7 14. Rfd1 $146 {with ideas like Nb5 and g4!?, it seems to me Black is not out of the woods yet.}) 12. dxc5 {A typical simplification. Black should take some care.} ({Instead} 12. a3 {forces us where we want to go, and} Nbd5 {exchanges another set of minor pieces.}) ({The advance} 12. e4 {can be met with} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bc5 14. Be5 Rc8 {allowing us to retreat the knight to c6.}) 12... Bxc5 ({Let's not get too excited by} 12... Nd3 $2 {White has} 13. cxb6 Nxc1 $2 14. b7 $1) 13. Be5 Nfd5 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rd3] Maintaining the b4-knight for the moment for some nuisance value.} (13... Nd3 $2 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rc2 $16 {is good for White.}) 14. Nxd5 (14. Qa4 Qe8 $1 {is a typical response.}) 14... Qxd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. a3 Nd3 ({White is much better after} 15... Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Nd5 17. e4 {.}) 16. Rc2 Qe4 $1 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc5d6] With ...Rfd8 coming, Black is fine.} ({Black has to avoid} 16... Nxe5 $2 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Nxe5) ({After} 16... Qe4 17. Bg3 Rfd8 18. Qe2 Bd6 $1 {exchanges pieces and gives our knight an out on c5 or e5.}) *

