1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bxc7 {We will start with this move, as grabbing the pawn is both obvious and critical.} Bb4+ {First we create a little disruption in the white camp.} 10. Nd2 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Gf8c8,Gb4e1,Gd5g2] White is tied up and Black has a rather large lead in development. Black may bring the bishop to b7 or d7, depending on what follows. Either rook may come to c8.} ({Practice has show that this is more flexible than} 10... Bb7) ({While} 10... Ba6 {is well met by} 11. Bxb8 $16) 11. a3 {This is a natural move but it shows an advantage to Black's move order.} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3]} ({An untried idea which looks interesting is} 12... Bd7 $5 13. b4 {if 13.f3 Rac8 14.e4 Qxd4 15.Bd6 Qxd2+ 16.Kxd2 Nd4 is fine for Black} Rac8 14. Bg3 Ne7 {looks like decent compensation.}) 13. Qc3 {White avoids the fork, but the queen looks vulnerable on the c-file.} (13. Rb1 {is quite passive.} Bd7 $13 {with both ...Rfc8 and ...Nb3 in the air, Black should have plenty of play.}) 13... Bb7 {[%cal Gf8c8,Ga8c8]} (13... Bd7 {is also possible.}) 14. b4 Nb3 ({Black can already head for a draw with} 14... Rac8 15. bxa5 {and now} Rxc7 16. Qxc7 Qxa5+ 17. Kd1 Rc8 {will lead to a perpetual}) 15. Rb1 {The knight is trapped, but we have a resource.} Rfc8 16. Qxb3 ({Worse is} 16. Rxb3 Qd7 $17 {followed by ...Rxc7 and ...Rac8.}) 16... Qxb3 17. Rxb3 Rxc7 {[%cal Gc7c2,Gc7c1] Black has obvious compensation. White will be compelled to return the pawn.} 18. Kd2 Rac8 19. Bd3 {Necessary, but now we equalize the material.} Bxg2 {And Black has regained the pawn. It's equal.} *

