1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bxc7 {We will start with this move, as grabbing the pawn is both obvious and critical.} Bb4+ {First we create a little disruption in the white camp.} 10. Nd2 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Gf8c8] White is tied up and Black has a rather large lead in development. Black may bring the bishop to b7 or d7, depending on what follows. Either rook may come to c8.} ({Practice has show that this is more flexible than} 10... Bb7) ({While} 10... Ba6 {is well met by} 11. Bxb8 $16) 11. a3 {This is a natural move but it shows an advantage to Black's move order.} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3]} ({An untried idea which looks interesting is} 12... Bd7 $5 13. b4 {if 13.f3 Rac8 14.e4 Qxd4 15.Bd6 Qxd2+ 16.Kxd2 Nd4 is fine for Black} Rac8 14. Bg3 Ne7 {looks like decent compensation.}) 13. Qd3 {This looks critical. White avoids the fork and the queen is less vulnerable here.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7a4] This bishop has better prospects here than on the long diagonal.} ({After} 13... Bb7 14. f3 {it's not clear how to continue.}) 14. e4 {This is quite testing.} Qb3 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Qxb3 Nxb3 {[%cal Gb3a1,Gb3d4]} 16. Rd1 Rfc8 {[%cal Gc8c7,Gc8c2] Black has to stay active before White can consolidate.} 17. Bf4 Rc2 18. Rb1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gf4e3] White is ready to evict our rook and then he will cover the d4-pawn.} Rd8 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7e8,Gd7a4] A rather difficult but important move. We have to keep some pressure on the d4-pawn.} ({Unfortunately we cannot take the pawn:} 18... Nxd4 $2 19. Rd1) 19. Bd3 Rcc8 20. Ba6 ({Instead} 20. Be3 {allows us to quickly win back the pawn with} Ba4) 20... Rc2 {Now White can repeat moves or test us.} 21. O-O (21. Bd3 Rcc8 {repeats moves. If this brings you tears, you can check out 12...Bd7.}) 21... Ba4 $1 ({This looks more accurate than} 21... Nxd4 22. Rfd1 $14 {when there are still a lot of pieces on the board and White can hope to utilize his bishop pair.}) 22. Rfd1 Rxd4 23. Rxd4 Nxd4 {We are very active here.} 24. Z0 ({White can trade rooks:} 24. Rc1 Rxc1+ 25. Bxc1 {when the engine tells us we are fine with all kinds of moves, but the most forcing is} Bb5 {eliminating the bishop pair.} 26. Bxb5 Nxb5) *

