1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. a3 {[%csl Gb4,Rc7] White prevents ...Bb4+ and apparently renews the threat to the c7-pawn.} Ba6 $5 {[%mdl 32768] We can continue to leave the pawn to its fate.} (9... c5 {is also possible, and this was the recommendation of Ntirlis.} 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Rc1 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 {looks a little easier for White. After Ntirlis's} Na6 14. b4 $146 {freezes the knight and we don't have ...a5. After} Bb7 {White appears to be falling too far behind in development, but after} 15. Bd3 $1 Bxg2 16. Rg1 Bb7 17. Bh6 Bf6 18. Ke2 Kh8 19. Bf4 {Black is a bit tangled up, and the engine likes White's compensaiton.}) 10. Bxc7 $6 {This is not a good time to grab the pawn.} Bxf1 11. Rxf1 ({White cannot play} 11. Kxf1 $4 Qc4+ {winning the c7-bishop.}) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c6,Gf8c8] Black's play is very fast and White will have trouble evacuating his king from the center.} *

