1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bd3 {This is by far White's most popular move.} Qa5+ {Black's main choice.} ({A)} 9... c5 $6 10. Qc2 {hits our h7-pawn and threatens Be4.}) ({B)} 9... Bb4+ $6 {will waste more time than it gains.} 10. Ke2 $16) ({C)} 9... Ba6 {is reasonable, and we took a look at this via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 7EndFEN 7.Bd3 Ba6 8.cxd5 Nxd5 9.Nxd5 Qxd5 .}) {Now all three moves have been played frequently, and Black can play 10...Ba6 against all of them.} 10. Ke2 Ba6 $5 ({Here Black can also consider} 10... c5 {as given by Ntirlis. After} 11. Qd2 {Black can just exchange queens with equality. Note that with the king on e2, 11.Be4? loses to 11...Ba6+ 12.Bd3 c4}) 11. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b4] This not only avoids any ...Nb4 stuff, but b2-b4 is a possibility for White.} c5 {[%mdl 32768] This looks the most accurate to me, as White's next move is practically forced.} (11... Bxd3+ 12. Qxd3 c5 {should transpose, as White's best is still probably} 13. b4 {, although other moves would still be good for equality.}) 12. b4 $1 ({There's not much else, as the h1-rook has nothing to do, and} 12. Rc1 Nd7 {looks very good for Black, as his development is better and his king is safer.}) 12... Bxd3+ 13. Qxd3 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gh1a1]} Qa4 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7] A good square for the queen. Black is ready to complete his development and White's king position is still not ideal.} ({We cannot get greedy with} 13... cxb4 $6 14. axb4 Qxb4 $2 15. Rhb1) 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Rhc1 Nd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8] Black had no problems in Radjabov - Carlsen, Medias 2011.} *

