1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 ({For many decades this was just a secondary option for White next to} 5. Bg5 {, but Black's success with the Tartakover, Lasker, and Kramnik variations made life difficult for}) (5. Bg5 {fans, and}) (5. Bf4 {took over. Nowadays it seems clear that}) (5. Bf4 {is more challenging!}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 7. cxd5 {Finally we come to the most popular move. This is a common reaction against any setup with ...d5 and ...b6, be it a Queen's Gambit Declined or a Queen's Indian Defence.} Nxd5 $1 ({Preferable to} 7... exd5 {, as we know Black is happy to trade some pieces.}) 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 {The most active move, but it offers up a pawn.} (8... exd5 {is better than it was last move, as Black is happy to have exchanged knights.} 9. Bd3 c5 {is doubtless playable, but I prefer to only allow this structure if White has made some concession, as we saw in the 7.a3 line.}) 9. Bd3 {This is by far White's most popular move.} Qa5+ {Black's main choice.} ({A)} 9... c5 $6 10. Qc2 {hits our h7-pawn and threatens Be4.}) ({B)} 9... Bb4+ $6 {will waste more time than it gains.} 10. Ke2 $16) ({C)} 9... Ba6 {is reasonable, and we took a look at this via the move order StartFENrnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2PP1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 7EndFEN 7.Bd3 Ba6 8.cxd5 Nxd5 9.Nxd5 Qxd5 .}) {Now all three moves have been played frequently, and Black can play 10...Ba6 against all of them.} 10. Nd2 {White understandably does not want to move his king. Now White is ready to castle and then Nd2-c4 would be quite serious.} Ba6 $1 ({Here this is the only good move. If} 10... c5 $4 11. Be4 {and Black can resign.}) 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 (11... Qxa6 {has also been tried, but I prefer to develop, while protecting the c7-pawn helps too.}) 12. O-O c5 {Black is not experiencing any problems here.} 13. Be5 {This has been tried a few times and it's safe enough, but there aren't enough pieces around to cause Black's king any trouble. Neither} (13. Nc4 Qb5 {nor}) (13. Nb3 Qb5 {cause Black any problems.}) 13... f6 $5 {[%mdl 32768]} (13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 Rfd8 {is fine too.}) 14. Bg3 cxd4 15. Nb3 {White avoids an isolated pawn.} Qd5 (15... Qa4 {also looks fine.}) 16. Nxd4 e5 {Not the only move, but this suggestion of Ntirlis is the most forcing and gives Black easy equality.} 17. Nf5 Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 (18. Nxe7+ Kf7 19. Rfxd1 Kxe7 $15 {is nice for Black - White's bishop is out of play.}) 18... Bc5 (18... Rf7 {looks fine too.}) 19. Rd7 Rf7 {And White has nothing, for example:} 20. Rad1 Bf8 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ga6c5] intending ...Nc5.} *

