1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 ({This is a well-known move order finesse that was favored by both Karpov and Kasparov. The idea is to avoid the main lines with} 3... Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 {when White has long been held to be able to gain a plus.} Be7 {If Black insists on developing the c8-bishop with 5...c6 6.e3 Bf5 he has to be prepared to defend the dreary endgame which arises after 7.Qf3! Bg6 8.Bxf6 Qxf6 9.Qxf6 gxf6 It's very solid, but definitely not to everyone's taste.} 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7 {when both} 9. Nge2 {and 9.Nf3 Re8 10.O-O Nf8 11.h3} Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 {are considered to be pleasant for White. Nowadays these conclusions are being questioned, but the 3...Be7 move order has still etched its place in opening theory.}) 4. cxd5 {Going for an exchange variation is still a popular choice.} (4. Nf3 {is the most popular move. After} Nf6 {we will transpose to various main lines.}) 4... exd5 {The main point of Black's move order is that there is no Bg5, so White must commit something.} 5. Bf4 {This is by far the most popular move.} (5. Qc2 {will transpose to either 5.Bf4 or 5.Nf3 after} c6) (5. Nf3 {is less popular. After} Nf6 {it is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.}) 5... c6 6. e3 ({With} 6. Qc2 {White tries to prevent ...Bf5. After} Nf6 7. e3 {or 7.h3 g6! and ...Bf5 comes after all.} Nh5 $1 {corrals the White bishop. Then} 8. Be5 Nd7 9. Be2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 g6 11. Bxh5 gxh5 $132 {may look quite strange, but Black has good counterplay here with his bishop pair.}) 6... Bf5 {Now if White wants to get anything at all, he has to find a way to bother this bishop.} 7. g4 ({This is the most aggressive move.} 7. Nge2 {is the alternative.} Nd7 8. Ng3 Bg6 {will also be covered in depth.}) 7... Be6 $1 ({Worse is} 7... Bg6 8. h4 $1) 8. h4 {This space gaining move was very popular for a few years.} ({In the old days White sought to consolidate his space on the kingside with} 8. h3 {but over time Black found good counterplay with the counter-strikes ...g5! and ...h5!}) ({White has done well with} 8. Qb3 $5 {as played once by Kramnik, but it has not really caught on.}) 8... Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. g5 {One way to gain space.} ({The old way was with} 9. h5 {when Black cannot play ...h5, but there is another way.} Nh6 $1 {and here Black is ready to counter with ...f5 or ...g5.}) ({Nakamura played} 9. Bg3 {a few times, but it's not so dangerous.}) ({Yet again White can try} 9. Qb3 $5 {Like on move 8, this has not caught on, but it's more annoying here I think.}) 9... h6 $1 {Black cannot let White take over the world, and this is well timed. This is an interesting position where Black is holding his own.} *

