1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc8] This is much less popular than 5.Bf4. It's less flexible, and the tempo spent here means that Black can usually develop his c8-bishop more easily.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc8f5][%mdl 32768] It is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.} 6. Bf4 (6. Qc2 c6 {will transpose after} 7. Bf4 {(Or 7.Bg5 g6 )} g6 {to 6.Bf4 or 6.Bg5.}) 6... c6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Preparing ...Bf5. We pretty much always want to go ...c6 first, to avoid any problems with the d5- and b7-pawns.} ({For example} 6... Bf5 7. Qb3 {and we do not have ...Qb6 available.}) 7. e3 {This is not considered by Colovic, but it's been played a lot. It looks a bit naïve to just allow ...Bf5, but there are some ideas.} Bf5 {Black should play this before White prevents it with Bd3.} 8. Nh4 $5 {This is like many lines of the Slav - White allows Black's bishop to develop so he can harass it.} (8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 {is just basic equality, and similar to the 7.Qc2 line. There Black has ...g6 for free, for better or worse - probably neither.}) (8. h3 Nbd7 9. g4 {looks weird. White may grab the bishop pair, but the advance of the g4-pawn is double-edged. White could have played this more flexibly by going for the main lines. Both} Bg6 {and 9...Be4 look fine to me.}) 8... Bg4 $5 {A bit of disruption.} (8... Be6 9. Bd3 {is a small triumph for White. The h4-knight may go to f5 , or simply return to f3 .}) (8... Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 {is a bit cooperative, but Black can play ...Bd6 which should keep any white edge to a minimum.}) 9. Qc2 ({If} 9. f3 $2 Be6 $17 {leaves the h4-knight out to dry, and already ...Nh5 is a huge threat.}) (9. Be2 {trading bishops hardly looks dangerous. White could have done this with Bd3 instead of Nh4.} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Qd7 {covering the f5-square. Black can follow with ...Na6, or ...Qe6 and ...Nbd7.}) 9... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4] We have to continue to press.} (9... Nbd7 10. h3 Be6 11. Nf3 $14 {gave White everything he wanted in Maghsoodloo-Adams, Baden Baden 2022.}) 10. h3 $1 ({White does not want to give up the bishop pair too easily, while} 10. Nf5 $2 Nxf4 11. exf4 Bxf5 12. Qxf5 O-O {leaves White behind in development with a worse pawn structure.}) 10... Be6 (10... Bc8 $5 {is also possible, avoiding any potential f4-f5 issues.} 11. Nf3 Nxf4 12. exf4 Bd6 {should be level.}) 11. Nf3 Nxf4 12. exf4 {[%cal Rb8d7,Gf4f5] So we got the bishop, but have to watch for some f4-f5 stuff.} Bd6 {[%csl Rf4]} ({The immediate} 12... g6 {is similar.}) 13. g3 g6 ({I prefer this to} 13... Qf6 14. Bd3 g6 15. O-O-O Nd7 16. Ne5 {when Black seemed a bit cramped in Gukesh-Nepomniachtchi, Dusseldorf rapid 2023.}) 14. Bd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gh7h5] Black is quite flexible here. We may play ...h5, restricting White's kingside pawns, or ...Nb6. Castling long seems the most likely. Note that we do not have to fear the advance of White's f4-pawn.} 15. f5 $6 gxf5 16. Bxf5 $2 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3,Rf5][%cal Gf5e6,Gf7e6] This is quite troublesome for White.} *

