1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc8] This is much less popular than 5.Bf4. It's less flexible, and the tempo spent here means that Black can usually develop his c8-bishop more easily.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc8f5] It is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.} 6. Bf4 (6. Qc2 c6 {will transpose after} 7. Bf4 {(Or 7.Bg5 g6 )} g6 {to 6.Bf4 or 6.Bg5.}) 6... c6 {[%cal Gc8f5] Preparing ...Bf5. We pretty much always want to go ...c6 first, to avoid any problems with the d5- and b7-pawns.} ({For example} 6... Bf5 7. Qb3 {and we do not have ...Qb6 available.}) 7. Qc2 {This does not look dangerous, but it was tried by Carlsen in an important game. He lost though...} g6 {[%cal Gc8f5][%mdl 32768] I insist.} 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 ({White gets nowhere after} 9. Qb3 Qb6) ({while} 9. Qd2 Ne4 {simplifies and equalizes.}) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 ({Flexible, but} 10... O-O {must be fine too.}) 11. h4 {Carlsen's choice. It seems odd to play rather innocuously and then to suddenly try to stir something up.} (11. O-O O-O {would be standard, and equal.}) 11... a5 $5 {Aronian, perhaps being playful, responds with the opposite rook's pawn.} ({I can't imagine that} 11... O-O {is wrong, as White does not really have an attack.}) ({Colovic suggests} 11... Nb6 12. O-O-O Qd7 13. Ne5 Qe6 {and this looks fine too.}) 12. Kf1 ({If} 12. O-O-O a4 {Black's push looks quite justified.}) 12... O-O {[%cal Gf8e8] Black should play normally.} ({Aronian went for} 12... a4 {and won, but after} 13. a3 Qb6 $6 14. Qc2 {he had some issues with the a4-pawn in Carlsen-Aronian, Stavanger 2020.}) *

