1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc8] This is much less popular than 5.Bf4. It's less flexible, and the tempo spent here means that Black can usually develop his c8-bishop more easily.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc8f5] It is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.} 6. Bg5 c6 {[%cal Gc8f5][%mdl 32768] A standard position. With White's knight on f3 so early, It's not easy to prevent Black from developing his bishop.} 7. e3 {This is common but not dangerous at all. Sometimes it is played with a quick draw in mind, kind of like the Exchange Slav with 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bf4 Bf5 7.e3 e6 8.Bd3.} Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O {Equal, but there is still play, and either player can win. Black scores very well here, as often the white player is lower rated and unambitious. I'll show one example of ideal play for Black.} 11. Rab1 {Going for the minority attack.} a5 12. a3 Ne4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. b4 b5 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Ge4d6,Gd6c4] A well-known stratgic antidote. This was Nikolic - Kramnik, Monte Carlo 1998. A classic game for Black, where the c4-squares has been secured. We will see more of this plan in the Tartakover chapters.} *

