1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {[%csl Gc8] This is much less popular than 5.Bf4. It's less flexible, and the tempo spent here means that Black can usually develop his c8-bishop more easily.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc8f5] It is not easy to prevent Black from developing the c8-bishop.} 6. Bg5 c6 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 7. Qc2 {Preventing ...Bf5, but only for a moment.} g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5][%mdl 32768]} ({After} 7... O-O 8. e3 {Black will not get the c8-bishop out, and must revert to the older lines of the QGD where White can hope for an edge.}) 8. e4 {This is White's only attempt to 'make something happen'. Karpov defeated Yusupov once this way, but he never played it again. Nowadays it is well-known and not considered dangerous.} (8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {is very similar to 7.e3.}) 8... dxe4 {This looks like the best response.} ({Likely caught by surprise, Yusupov went for} 8... Nxe4 9. Bxe7 Kxe7 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4+ Be6 {which is still not bad. But after} 12. Bc4 {he erred with} Qa5+ $2 {12...Re8! would have been fine for Black.} 13. Kf1 Qf5 14. Qe3 Nd7 15. Re1 {which by now was rather uncomfortable for Black in Karpov-Yusupov, USSR (ch) 1988.}) 9. Bxf6 ({If} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Be6 $15 {Black has no issues at all and enjoys a superior pawn structure.}) 9... Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7 {Already the engines slightly prefer Black.} (10... Kf8 {is fine too.}) 11. Bc4 ({The best move order. If} 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. Bc4 {Black can simply transpose with} Bf5 {while 12...Rd8!? is a decent choice as well.}) 11... Bf5 {Forcing matters.} 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {[%cal Gh8e8,Gh8d8]} ({We could play} 12... Bxe7 {but the bishop is more active on f6 , and with the queens off the board, we should not face any problems with our king.}) 13. O-O {This calm move does not cause any problems at all.} (13. h3 {would be met with} h5) 13... Nd7 ({I like this move.} 13... Rd8 {is more common and also fine.}) 14. Rfe1+ Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd7b6,Gh8e8] We are ready to go to g7 to connect rooks.} 15. Ne5 $6 {Apparently White has newfound ambitions.} Bxe5 16. dxe5 Ke7 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh8d8,Gd7c5,Gb7b5,Gg6g5] Back to the center! The e5-pawn is not a strength. Black is already a bit better.} *

