Rh7 $1 {is crushing.}) (13... Nd7 {is very solid, and similar.} 14. h3 h5 15. Rhe1+ Kf8) 14. h3 h5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gb8d7]} 15. Rhe1 (15. Ne5 $4 {loses to} Bg5+) (15. d5 $6 {is tempting but premature.} Kg7 16. d6 {or 16.dxc6 Nxc6 $17} Nd7 $17) (15. Rhg1 {dreams of g2-g4, but Black has} h4 {and here I like having the rook on the h-file for the time being.}) 15... Kg7 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black is ready to complete his development.} 16. Ne4 {White seeks to eliminate of one Black's bishops.} Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] Black is clearly fine, and things are 'trending' his way. If White is tempted to eliminate his isolated pawn, he can easily get in more trouble.} 18. Z0 ({For example} 18. d5 $2 Nc5 19. Ree1 b5 $1 20. Bf1 cxd5 21. Rxd5 Rac8 22. Kb1 a6 $17 {and in this symmetrical structure, Black is much more active - just compare the activity of the bishops! Already ...Na4 looks very dangerous for White.}) *

