1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qc2 {[%cal Rc8f5]} Nf6 7. e3 ({White does not want to spend time on} 7. h3 {, but he can't have everything.}) 7... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4] A very important move. We cannot just let White play h3, Bd3, Nf3 with a secure edge.} 8. Be5 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} (8... f6 {is not fatal, but it is clearly weakening. Both} 9. Bg3 {and 9.Bxb8 Rxb8 10.Be2 are better for White.}) 9. Be2 {If White does not do this, Black will take on e5 and play ...g6, rerouting the knight to g7.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 {[%csl Rh5]} g6 {[%cal Gh5g7] No choice.} 11. Bxh5 gxh5 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Gf7f6] This may look ugly, but it's quite an interesting line for Black. The pawns are not as weak as they seem, and the bishop pair has a ton of potential. A quick ...f6 will open the position. White must try to make something of his slight development lead and in fact he will also generally seek to open things up with an e4 break. Both sides will have to make decisions regarding where to put their king...} 12. Nf3 {A natural move, but it's not so common and it scores poorly. The engine likes it at first, and it's not so trivial to meet despite its poor statistics.} f6 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. O-O {The only independent line.} ({Both} 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. e4 d4 15. O-O-O) ({And} 13. e4 d4 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. O-O-O {transpose to the 12.O-O-O line.}) 13... Bg4 ({Black tries to force the pace. This looks better than} 13... fxe5 14. Nxe5 O-O 15. e4 Bf6 16. f4 $14 {when White is well places in the center.}) 14. exf6 {White relieves the pressure on his center, but this is cooperative.} Bxf6 15. Nd4 O-O ({The immediate} 15... Qe7 {is possible as well.}) 16. h3 ({After} 16. f3 Bd7 {is similar, while the tactical 16...Qe7!? looks good as well.}) 16... Bd7 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gg8h8] The position has stabilized a bit. I prefer Black with those bishops.} *

