1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qc2 {[%cal Rc8f5]} Nf6 7. e3 ({White does not want to spend time on} 7. h3 {, but he can't have everything.}) 7... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f4] A very important move. We cannot just let White play h3, Bd3, Nf3 with a secure edge.} 8. Be5 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} (8... f6 {is not fatal, but it is clearly weakening. Both} 9. Bg3 {and 9.Bxb8 Rxb8 10.Be2 are better for White.}) 9. Be2 {If White does not do this, Black will take on e5 and play ...g6, rerouting the knight to g7.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 {[%csl Rh5]} g6 {[%cal Gh5g7] No choice.} 11. Bxh5 gxh5 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7][%cal Gf7f6] This may look ugly, but it's quite an interesting line for Black. The pawns are not as weak as they seem, and the bishop pair has a ton of potential. A quick ...f6 will open the position. White must try to make something of his slight development lead and in fact he will also generally seek to open things up with an e4 break. Both sides will have to make decisions regarding where to put their king...} 12. O-O-O {[%cal Gd1d8,Ge3e4] This is by far the main move. White brings his rook to the d-file, while getting his king to safety. But...the king may not be so safe on the queenside.} f6 13. e4 {This is White's only good move.} d4 14. exf6 {Another possibility.} Bxf6 15. Nf3 {This is the main line. It does allow the following pin though.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge8c8][%mdl 32768] We pin the knight and prepare to eventually castle long.} ({Black could also try} 15... O-O {!?} 16. Ne2 {(Or 16.e5?! Bxe5 17.Nxe5 Qg5+ )} c5 17. Qxc5 {and now} Qe8 $146 {hitting the e4-pawn and planning ...Bg4 or ...Bd7, with ...Rc8 coming. We avoid 17...Be6 18.Kb1 Rc8 19.Qa3 $16}) 16. e5 $5 {[%csl Re8] An uncommon move, but it certainly looks tempting with Black's king in the center.} Bxf3 17. exf6 {This is untried but has to be checked.} Bxd1 18. Re1+ $1 Kf7 19. Qxd1 Qxf6 ({After} 19... dxc3 $2 20. Qxh5+ Kxf6 21. Qf3+ {White's attack is winning.}) 20. Qxh5+ Qg6 ({This is safest. If} 20... Kg7 21. Qg4+ Kf8 22. Ne4 {White has compensation for the exchange, although the computer is all zeroes after} h5 {or 22...Qe5 .}) 21. Qf3+ Qf6 {White has nothing better than to repeat.} ({Black could play} 21... Kg8 {but after} 22. Nd5 {again gives White compensation - and again all zeroes.}) *

