1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Nge2 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gh2h4]} ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 {[%csl Gh4]} ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. Rc1 ({Now the main move is} 8. Ng3 {but White has a few other tries as well.}) {Maybe this is supposed to be a clever waiting move, but I don't get it. We certainly do not have to worry about White castling long now!} 8... h5 $5 {A sharp move which interferes with White's normal development scheme. I guess the big idea of 8.Rc1 is that after} (8... Ngf6 {White can play} 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. h4 {, but after} h5 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 g6 {is less dangerous for Black as White obviously cannot castle queenside now.}) (8... Nb6 {is a typical move for Black.} 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Nh5 {is a little inconvenient, but} Bxh5 11. Qxh5 Bd6 {still looks still solid}) (8... g5 $5 9. Bg3 h5 {is another way of introducing complications.}) 9. Ng3 Bg4 $1 10. f3 ({After} 10. Be2 g5 $17 {White will soon lose a piece.}) 10... Be6 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh5h4,Gg7g5,Ge7h4] White already has trouble with ...h4 and ...g5 causing problems.} *

