1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf4h2] This hardly looks dangerous. White could have played g4 on move seven after all.} Ngf6 {[%mdl 32768] Simplest.} (8... Bg6 9. Bh2 Ngf6 10. Nf4 O-O {looks fine too - again it's like the Slow Slav. Even}) (8... h6 {looks fine.}) 9. g4 Be4 $1 {We may as well be disruptive.} 10. Rg1 {After} (10. Nxe4 Nxe4 {both ...h5 and ...Bb4+ are there to annoy White.}) 10... Qb6 {This causes further disruption. Instead} (10... h6 11. Ng3 g5 12. Be5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 {is similar.}) 11. Qd2 h6 {[%cal Ge4h7,Gg7g5]} 12. Ng3 g5 $1 13. Be5 {One point of Black's move order can be seen after} (13. Ngxe4 $2 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 {when White loses his bishop because ...Bb4 is an even bigger threat.}) 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge8c8,Ge7b4] Black will pick up the e5-pawn, while White will probably regain it on e4. It's probably level, but Black's development seems more natural to me.} 15. Ncxe4 dxe4 16. O-O-O O-O-O {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge7b4] Black is not worse.} *

