1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. h4 $5 {It turns out that White can still play this move. White scores well here, as generally black players have struggled to find a good continuation.} Ngf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Of course we have to wonder what happens if we take the pawn.} 8... Bxh4 $6 9. Qb3 $1 Nb6 {(Instead 9...b6 runs into a typical shot: 10.Nxd5! cxd5 11.Rxh4 Qxh4 12.Qxd5 )} 10. a4 $1 Be7 11. a5 Nc4 12. e4 $1 {This is very disruptive. We cannot take on e4, and White intends exd5 and Nb5!}) ({The natural} 8... h5 {is well met by} 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Bd3 $1 {saving a tempo compared to a line we will see later where White plays Be2 and later Bd3.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Ngf6 {(More often Black has played 11...g6 12.e4 dxe4 13.Ngxe4↑ White is scoring heavily here.)} 12. Nf5 O-O 13. f3 {should be better for White (the engines are very excited), but it's still complex.}) 9. Ng3 Be6 ({Of course not} 9... Bg6 $2 10. h5) 10. Bd3 {This could be considered a triumph for White, he has taken control of the b1-h7 diagonal, but this h4 move is rather committal.} Nb6 {[%cal Ge7d6] We could castle too, but I'd rather let White make one more move to see what he's up to.} ({Colovic gives} 10... O-O 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Re8 {which is similar.}) 11. Qc2 ({If} 11. Nf5 {now, we have} Bxf5 12. Bxf5 Bd6 {eliminating White's bishop pair. If} 13. Bg5 h6 {.}) 11... O-O $146 ({A straightforward improvement. It's tempting to try to remain noncommittal with} 11... Bd6 {but after} 12. Nge2 $1 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 $14 {White's position was more flexible Zhou Jianchao-Bryant, Los Angeles 2022. Castling long is an option, but so is f3, g4, Kf2 with a nice space advantage.}) 12. Nf5 ({If} 12. O-O-O Rc8 $1 {and ...c5 next.}) 12... Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6f5,Gb4c3,Gb6c4,Gf6e4] This position looks very rich. We can take either knight and we have good squares for our knights on e4 and c4.} ({This is better than} 12... Bxf5 13. Bxf5 Bd6 14. Bg5 $1 h6 {because White can leave the bishop where it is and play} 15. O-O-O {!}) *

