1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. Ng3 {This is the main move by a very wide margin.} Bg6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Instead} 8... Be6 {is playable (threatening ...g5), but} 9. Nh5 {is a bit of a nuisance.}) 9. h4 ({Now} 9. Be2 {is by far the most common move, but we will check a couple of other things too.}) ({An obvious and aggressive move, but this time we can bite.} 9. Nh5 $2 {just loses now.} Qb6 {and because White's queen is tied to the h5-knight, his queenside falls apart.}) (9. Bd3 $2 {can also be dismissed.} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 g5 $17 {and White loses a piece.}) 9... Bxh4 ({As we've seen,} 9... h5 {allows} 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {which favors White.}) 10. Qb3 {This was tried in a couple of Holt-Tang games - two respective specialists in the line.} (10. Bd3 Bxg3 11. Bxg3 Ne7 {looks like a healthy pawn.}) (10. Nh5 Bf6 {is also very solid for Black.}) 10... Bxg3 $1 11. Bxg3 Qb6 ({Black went for} 11... Nb6 12. a4 a5 {in Holt-Tang, chess.com rapid 2019, but I don't like having our queenside frozen like this.}) 12. Qa3 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gb6d8] White has the bishop pair, but Black is very solid and has an extra pawn.} *

