1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. Ng3 {This is the main move by a very wide margin.} Bg6 ({Instead} 8... Be6 {is playable (threatening ...g5), but} 9. Nh5 {is a bit of a nuisance.}) 9. Rc1 ({Now} 9. Be2 {is by far the most common move, but we will check a couple of other things too.}) {Again this waiting move, and again it puts an end to any O-O-O ideas for White.} 9... h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4][%mdl 32768] This is very tempting.} ({Instead} 9... Ngf6 {will likely transpose to the 9.Be2 line after} 10. Be2 h5 11. h4) 10. h4 Bxh4 11. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7,Rh4][%cal Gb3b7] Often this is annoying because of the somewhat loose h4-bishop, but here we can trade it off.} Bxg3 12. Bxg3 Qb6 ({We need to avoid} 12... Nb6 13. a4 a5 {Normally this would just be compensation for White, as our whole queenside is paralyzed, but here White has the concrete} 14. Nb5 $1 cxb5 15. Bc7 {when even the creative} Rc8 $5 16. Bxd8 Rxc1+ 17. Kd2 Rc2+ {leaves us worse after} 18. Qxc2 $1 Bxc2 19. Bxb6 Bxa4 20. Bxa5 {when White is comfortably better despite the pawn deficit.}) 13. Qa3 Ne7 {This is similar to 9.h4, but here Black has been enticed into ...h5. White may have some compensation, but he has to prove it. If you do not like this, there's always 9...Ngf6.} *

