1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Nge2 ({This is a common alternative to} 7. g4 {White intends to bother the f5-bishop with Ng3 and often h4, as he does in the main lines of the Caro-Kann.}) 7... Nd7 ({This keeps an eye on the h4-square and is more flexible than} 7... Nf6 8. Ng3 Bg6 {if 8...Be6 9.Bd3 $14 takes control of the f5-square.} 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bd3 $1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 g6 12. O-O-O {$14 sees White developing very quickly.}) 8. Ng3 {This is the main move by a very wide margin.} Bg6 ({Instead} 8... Be6 {is playable (threatening ...g5), but} 9. Nh5 {is a bit of a nuisance.}) 9. Be2 {The main line.} Ngf6 {[%mdl 32768]} (9... Nb6 {preventing h2-h4 for the moment, was Colovic's choice. This should also equalize. A well-known high level game went} 10. Be5 $5 Nf6 11. h4 h6 12. h5 Bh7 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kh8 16. Nf5 Nc4 {when Black has decent play, despite White's eventual victory in Nakamura-Aronian, London 2011.}) (9... Qb6 $5 10. Qd2 h5 {was played a couple of times by Geller, and this also looks sufficient; the play is just a bit murky.}) 10. h4 {This must be critical.} ({Of course both sides can castle too.} 10. O-O O-O {with normal ideas like ... Re8 and ...Nb6. Black will generally meet f3 with ...c5.}) 10... h5 {So here we have a kind of 'tabiya' that can be reached in various ways. White has tried all kinds of semi-waiting moves here.} ({Instead} 10... h6 {is generally regarded as a concession, because} 11. h5 Bh7 12. Bd3 {gains the f5-square for White's knight.} Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O 14. Nf5 Re8 {is similar to Nakamura-Aronian mentioned above. Probably White is a little better, but it's not so clear. In practice White has gone for} 15. O-O-O {But 15.f3 looks more flexible to me, as the white king may be better on f2.}) 11. Bg5 {White is trying to secure his own h-pawn, while targeting Black's. This is well met with the surprising self-pin.} Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6g3,Gd8b6] Both ...Bxg3 and ... Qb6 may prove inconvenient for White.} 12. f4 $6 {This was played by a 2700+ player, albeit in a blitz game. It's just too weakening.} ({White cannot ignore us:} 12. Bd3 $2 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qb6 $17) (12. O-O {is not as bad, but after} Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qb6 $132 {I prefer Black.}) (12. Rh3 {is an unfortunate looking move.} Qb6 13. Qd2 O-O {$15 Portisch-Geller, Portoroz 1973. Silly rook.}) (12. Bf4 {could be wise. We could repeat, but 12...Nb6= is more ambitious.}) 12... Qb6 $1 13. Qd2 {Here Black castled queenside in a Navara-So blitz game. But there's a stronger move.} (13. Qb3 Qxb3 14. axb3 Bc2 {is also very good for Black.}) 13... Ne4 $146 14. Ngxe4 Bxe4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 $17 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gd6b4,Gf7f6] White is in big trouble.} *

