6,Yf8e8]} ({Covering the f5-square, but} 12... O-O 13. Nf5 Re8 {looks quite playable too. We've come across positions like this on our way here, but with Black a tempo down (here White lost a move with Be2-d3). We are very solid, and the h4-pawn could prove weak. If White goes for the typical f3, e4 plan, sometimes Black can play ...dxe4 and if White takes back with the pawn, we have ...Ng4. Black may also be able to ignore the central advance.}) 13. O-O-O (13. O-O O-O {intending ...Re8 and ... Nb6, hardly looks dangerous for Black.}) (13. Nge2 O-O {does not change much.}) (13. f3 {can also be met with} O-O) 13... O-O 14. Kb1 ({Similar play could result after} 14. f3 b5) 14... Re8 15. f3 b5 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4,Ga8c8,Gc6c5,Gd7b6,Gb6c4,Gd8a5] Black has various ways to proceed on the queenside, and his play looks easier to me.} ({We avoid the passive} 15... Nf8 $6 16. e4 Ne6 {16...dxe4 17.Ngxe4! Nd5 18.Be5 also looks dangerous.} 17. Be5 {gave White the initiative in Kasimdzhanov-Grabarczyk, Germany 2013.}) ({After} 15... b5 $1 16. e4 b4 17. Nce2 dxe4 18. Nxe4 {or 18.fxe4 Ng4} Rc8 {with the idea ...c5 and ...Qa5, Black has sufficient play.}) *

