1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 {This is White's main continuation. It may look rash, but White is keen on gaining space. Black should avoid:} Bg6 $6 8. h4 {White hunts the bishop, as he would in an Advance Caro-Kann.} Bxh4 $2 {Critical, but basically losing.} (8... h6 {allows} 9. h5 Bh7 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nf6 12. f3 {when White has more space and is very flexible. Ne2-g3-f5 is coming.}) (8... h5 {certainly stops the pawn, but} 9. g5 {cramps Black. The g8-knight can't move. After} Bd6 10. Nge2 {White keeps a nice edge.}) 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rh4] Black cannot defend with the queen as it's tied to the bishop.} b6 10. Rxh4 $1 {This is already +6!} Qxh4 11. Nxd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5c7,Gb3d5,Gd5a8] Splat! Black's position collapses. We always have to check for lines like this when considering the capture of the h-pawn.} *

