1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 {This is White's main continuation. It may look rash, but White is keen on gaining space.} Be6 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg7g5,Gb8d7][%mdl 32768] Black has been pushed back, but White's pawn advances also mean that there are ample opportunities to strike back, typically with ...h5 or ...g5, or both!} 8. Qb3 ({Now the most common move is still the space gaining} 8. h4) ({while the 'consolidating'} 8. h3 {is also popular.}) {This move is not played often, but it is a bit of a nuisance. Kramnik used it successfully against Wesley So.} 8... Qb6 {[%csl Rb7] Black can go for this normal move here. We will see that the addition of White's h4 and our ...Nd7 will change things however.} ({Another idea is} 8... b5 $5 {This 'ugly' move is coming up more in various lines of the QGD. The c6-pawn looks bad now, but it will be difficult to prevent Black from getting in ...c5. We should not fear playing with an IQP as it will hardly be the only weakness on the board in light of White's pawn advances.} 9. h3 Nd7 10. Nf3 Ngf6 {and Black will eventually play for ...c5.}) 9. f3 {The most flexible.} (9. g5 $6 {overextends.} Qxb3 10. axb3 h6 $1 {is already nice for Black.}) (9. h3 {has only seen in a couple of blitz games.} Qxb3 10. axb3 Nd7 {and Black will look to play the typical moves ...g5 or ...h5.}) 9... g5 $1 ({After} 9... Nd7 10. h4 $16 {we have transposed to the unpleasant StartFENrn1qk1nr/pp2bppp/2p1b3/3p4/3P1BP1/2N1P3/PP3P1P/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 8EndFEN 8.h4 Nd7 9.Qb3 Qb6?! 10.f3 We'll see this later.}) 10. Be5 {White should disturb Black's development.} (10. Bg3 h5 $15 {is already annoying for White.}) 10... f6 11. Bg3 Qxb3 ({Or} 11... h5 12. gxh5 Qxb3 13. axb3 {, transposing.}) 12. axb3 h5 13. gxh5 {[%csl Gf6] Black cannot play ...Nf6 now.} Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gh6f5,Gh6f7] The h5-pawn will not run away, and I think this is the best way for Black to coordinate his forces.} ({So played} 13... Rxh5 {which is in itself not so bad.} 14. Bd3 Kf7 {Questioned by Kramnik, this is also not so terrible. Kramnik suggested 14...f5 15.Nge2 Nd7 16.h4 Nf8 curling up into a ball.} 15. h4 f5 $6 {I think that this is the real mistake 15...Nd7 is better.} 16. Nh3 $1 {was Kramnik-So, Berlin 2018. Black's pawn structure is beginning to creak.}) 14. Bd3 Nf5 {[%csl Re3,Rg3][%cal Gh8h5,Gb8d7] Black looks ok to me. If 8.Qb3 catches on (and it has not over the last several years), I think this is Black's way forward.} *

