1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd1c2] White is satisfied with chasing off Black's bishop and now looks to consolidate his space advantage and develop normally with Bd3, Qc2, Nge2, O-O-O and so on.} (8. Bd3 {This will generally transpose to the 8.h3 line.} Nd7 9. h3 {and we are in the 8.h3 line. White can vary with a couple of questionable moves. 9.Qf3?! g5 10.Bg3 Ngf6 11.h3 h5 is already favoring Black. 9.Bf5?! is another strange move. 9...Bxf5 10.gxf5 Ngf6 Black develops normally.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5][%mdl 32768] We develop a piece and await White's next move. Black will not be idle - the thematic ...h5 and ...g5. strikes are the source of counterplay.} 9. Nf3 {This is considered to be inaccurate, as it's less flexible than the main move, 9.Bd3. It does limits Black's choice, but that's hardly an inconvenience.} g5 $1 ({Only this strike will work.} 9... h5 10. g5 $14 {gives White his space advantage.}) 10. Bh2 {White should at least leave the g-file open for his rook, as we shall see.} (10. Be5 $6 {makes no sense.} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 {or 11.dxe5 h5 $17} Bd6 $15 {Thanks for the bishop pair.}) (10. Bg3 {is hit with a typical} h5 $1 11. gxh5 Rxh5 12. Ne5 {or 12.Bg2 Ngf6} Ngf6 $15 {with a good position for Black.}) 10... h5 11. gxh5 Rxh5 12. Rg1 {[%csl Rg5,Rh3] Both sides have imperfect positions on the kingside.} Bf5 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gh5h8,Gd7f8,Gf8e6] We have unclear play that is rather typical of the line. Both side will likely castle queenside eventually.} ({More common is} 12... Rh8 {but then} 13. Qb3 {is rather annoying, as we have to keep an eye on our g5-pawn.} Nb6 14. a4 {creates typical problems we should avoid.}) *

