1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd1c2] White is satisfied with chasing off Black's bishop and now looks to consolidate his space advantage and develop normally with Bd3, Qc2, Nge2, O-O-O and so on.} (8. Bd3 {This will generally transpose to the 8.h3 line.} Nd7 9. h3 {and we are in the 8.h3 line. White can vary with a couple of questionable moves. 9.Qf3?! g5 10.Bg3 Ngf6 11.h3 h5 is already favoring Black. 9.Bf5?! is another strange move. 9...Bxf5 10.gxf5 Ngf6 Black develops normally.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] We develop a piece and await White's next move. Black will not be idle - the thematic ...h5 and ...g5. strikes are the source of counterplay.} 9. Bd3 {The main line. White can bring the knight to either f3 or e2 if we are idle, but we won't be. and we are in the 8.h3 line.} g5 $5 (9... h5 {is a big alternative, which was Colovic's choice. This is covered as an informational line. I decided to go with 9...g5, both for variety and because I slightly prefer it. It is also consistent with our answer to 9.Nf3.}) 10. Bh2 {This looks less natural than 10.Bg3. The main point is that it shields the h-file.} h5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. f3 (11. gxh5 {is less consistent.} Ngf6 12. Qc2 {instead 12.Be2 is well met with 12...Ne4!? 13.Nxe4 dxe4 $17} Rxh5 {and the bishop is worse on h2 because the h3-pawn is weak.}) 11... Ngf6 ({There is no great reason to release the tension, but} 11... hxg4 12. hxg4 Bd6 13. Qc2 Qf6 {intending ...O-O-O, looks fine too.}) ({Black can also consider} 11... Nb6 {with the idea ... Bd6.} 12. Qc2 Bd6) 12. Qc2 Nb6 $1 {The best way to develop. Black's queen needs a square.} 13. O-O-O Bd6 {[%cal Gh2b8] White's bishop is strong, so we want to neutralize this diagonal.} 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Ge8c8]} 15. Nge2 {The most natural move.} ({At first the engine wants to play the unnatural} 15. f4 gxf4 16. g5 Ng8 17. Qh2 {but it calms down after} O-O-O 18. Qxf4 Qxf4 19. exf4 Ne7) 15... O-O-O {The position is level, but still tense.} 16. Z0 ({Note that the tempting} 16. Nb5 $6 {is a shot in the dark.} Qe7 $1 17. Ng3 {not 17.Nxa7+? Kb8 and White loses the knight. He can't even take twice on c6 because ...Rc8 will get him in the end.} a6 18. Nc3 hxg4 19. hxg4 Bxg4 $1 {Black won a pawn and the game in El Debs-Ippolito, Arlington 2015.}) *

