1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd1c2] White is satisfied with chasing off Black's bishop and now looks to consolidate his space advantage and develop normally with Bd3, Qc2, Nge2, O-O-O and so on.} (8. Bd3 {This will generally transpose to the 8.h3 line.} Nd7 9. h3 {and we are in the 8.h3 line. White can vary with a couple of questionable moves. 9.Qf3?! g5 10.Bg3 Ngf6 11.h3 h5 is already favoring Black. 9.Bf5?! is another strange move. 9...Bxf5 10.gxf5 Ngf6 Black develops normally.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] We develop a piece and await White's next move. Black will not be idle - the thematic ...h5 and ...g5. strikes are the source of counterplay.} 9. Bd3 {The main line. White can bring the knight to either f3 or e2 if we are idle, but we won't be.} g5 $5 (9... h5 {is a big alternative, which was Colovic's choice. This is covered as an informational line. I decided to go with 9...g5, both for variety and because I slightly prefer it. It is also consistent with our answer to 9.Nf3.}) 10. Bg3 {The most natural move.} h5 {[%mdl 32768] Now White can either try to hold his ground on g4, or release the tension.} 11. f3 {White maintains the pawn on g4.} Ngf6 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh8h1,Gh5g4] My preference is this simple developing move, which threatens to keep taking on g4.} (11... hxg4 {is obvious enough, but after} 12. fxg4 Ngf6 {White has an extra option with} 13. Qf3) (11... Qb6 $5 {causes an immediate crisis of sorts.} 12. Qc2 hxg4 13. fxg4 Bxg4 14. Rh2 {may not be so simple for Black}) 12. Rh2 {while the computer is happy to offer a pawn with 12.Kf2!? Qxb2+ 13.Nge2 This strikes me as a weird way to play chess, but White does not have much choice!} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6] As usual, making some room and preparing ...Bd6.} 13. Qe2 {White does not want to give up the h2-b8 diagonal just yet. Other queen moves would also be met with ...Bd6.} (13. Nge2 $6 Bd6 {quickly gets awkward for White.}) 13... Bd6 14. Qf2 ({For} 14. Be5 $2 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Nfd7 $17 {see the game Krush-Bruzon, Buenos Aires 2003.}) 14... Bxg3 15. Qxg3 {Now Black can challenge the white queen to go into a level endgame.} Qb8 (15... Qe7 $5 {is also possible for a sharper game, but White's queen is well placed.}) 16. Qxb8+ Rxb8 {[%cal Gh5g4,Gh8h2] Black should have no problems here.} *

