1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd1c2] White is satisfied with chasing off Black's bishop and now looks to consolidate his space advantage and develop normally with Bd3, Qc2, Nge2, O-O-O and so on.} (8. Bd3 {This will generally transpose to the 8.h3 line.} Nd7 9. h3 {and we are in the 8.h3 line. White can vary with a couple of questionable moves. 9.Qf3?! g5 10.Bg3 Ngf6 11.h3 h5 is already favoring Black. 9.Bf5?! is another strange move. 9...Bxf5 10.gxf5 Ngf6 Black develops normally.}) 8... Nd7 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] We develop a piece and await White's next move. Black will not be idle - the thematic ...h5 and ...g5. strikes are the source of counterplay.} 9. Bd3 {The main line. White can bring the knight to either f3 or e2 if we are idle, but we won't be.} g5 $5 (9... h5 {is a big alternative, which was Colovic's choice. We will consider this as an informational line. I decided to go with 9...g5, both for variety and because I slightly prefer it. It is also consisitent with our (necessary) answer to 9. Nf3.}) 10. Bg3 h5 {Now White can either try to hold his ground on g4, or release the tension.} 11. gxh5 {White chooses to open the position. I think this is more critical.} Ngf6 12. Qc2 Nxh5 {[%cal Gh5g3][%mdl 32768] Somehow this obvious move is a novelty. We could take with the rook too, but why not hit the bishop?} (12... Rxh5 {can be met with} 13. O-O-O) (12... Qa5 13. O-O-O Ne4 {is similar to our main line, but there are differences. For example} 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Nge2 $1 Bxa2 16. Nxa2 Qxa2 17. Nc3 {and despite our little invasion, we do not have any real threats and d4-d5 is coming.}) 13. Bh2 Nhf6 {[%csl Rh3] We lost some time, but now ...Rxh3 will gain in strength.} 14. O-O-O ({If} 14. f3 Qa5 15. O-O-O {Black can follow suit with} O-O-O {or looks to create a further mess with 15...b5!?}) 14... Ne4 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Ge6a2,Gd8a5] It's useful to consider this 'impossible' move. White may win a pawn, but his position is loose and it will be difficult to develop without dropping the h3-pawn. This is all untried, so we'll consider a couple of possibilities.} 15. Bxe4 ({After} 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxa2 17. b3 $2 {hardly traps the bishop, as} Qa5 {threatens a killing ...Ba3+}) 15... dxe4 16. Nge2 {[%cal Gd4d5] I think White should develop. We have to watch out for d4-d5,} ({If} 16. Qxe4 Qa5 {and White has to watch out for ...Bf5.}) 16... Qa5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6a2] We cover d5 and hit the a2-pawn.} 17. a3 ({If White plays} 17. Kb1 {he will never be able to take on e4 with the knight. 17...Rxh3 $15}) 17... Rxh3 ({Ideally, Black would like to play} 17... f5 {but White has} 18. d5 $1 Bxd5 {or 18...cxd5?! 19.Nd4} 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. Kb1 {with the idea Nd4, and Black's position feels too loose.}) ({Black could try} 17... Qb6 {but White has decent compensation after} 18. Nxe4 $5 Bb3 19. Qd3 Bxd1 20. Rxd1 {as all of his pieces are aggressively placed in the center.}) 18. Nxe4 O-O-O {[%cal Gd8h8,Gd7b6] Black has the bishop pair and good squares for his pieces. White does have one very creative idea we have to check.} 19. d5 $5 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge6h3] This diverts the e6-bishop away from protecting the h3-rook.} Bxd5 20. Bc7 $1 {A funny trick.} Qxc7 21. Rxh3 Qe5 $132 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd7c5,Gc5b3,Gd5e6] White has won the exchange, but we have a pawn and the bishop pair and possibilities on both sides of the board.} *

