1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {[%mdl 32768] This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. Bg3 {White covers the h4-pawn while keeping his kingside pawns flexible with this rather innocent looking move. Nakamura has gone for this a few times.} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Ge7d6] The choice of Aronian and Caruana. Black prepares ...Bd6.} ({The natural} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 Nb6 11. Bd3 $14 {shows White's idea - it's difficult to contest White's space advantage on the kingside. Then} Nc4 12. Qe2 c5 $2 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. d5 $1 Nxd5 15. O-O-O {$16 saw White win rather easily in Nakamura - Bacrot, Elancourt 2013.}) 10. f3 {White has to cover the g4-pawn at some point.} Bd6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Gd6g3]} 12. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2f2] White is ready to meet 12...Qg3+ with 13.Qf2.} h5 $1 {It's useful to fix the structure.} ({Black could also play} 12... Ne7 13. Bd3 {if 13.h5 f5!} h5 14. g5 {transposing, but I find 12...h5! to be more forcing.}) 13. g5 Ne7 14. Bd3 {We have an interesting position where Black can castle on either side.} O-O {Caruana's choice, which I prefer. With the kingside blocked, Black's king should always be safe here.} ({Aronian went long with} 14... O-O-O 15. Nge2 Kb8 16. Kf2 g6 17. a4 a5 {was also satisfactory for Black in Nakamura-Aronian, Moscow 2011.}) 15. Nge2 ({The endgame arising after} 15. Qh2 {is fine for Black too.} Qxh2 16. Rxh2 Bf5) 15... Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c1] To deter White from castling long.} 16. Rd1 ({If} 16. O-O-O {?!} c5 17. dxc5 Rxc5 18. Kb1 Rfc8 {Black has clear play on the queenside, while it's not easy for White to do anything meaningful on the kingside.}) 16... g6 {[%cal Ge6f5,Gb6c4] Black secures the f5-square and I already prefer his position, as White's king will never be completely comfortable. This was Nakamura-Caruana, Baku 2014. Soon Nakamura played for e3-e4, but his position was too loose and he was fortunate to escape with a draw.} *

