1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 {This is the main move. Colovic calls it 'refuted', but I think that's a bit strong.} Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) {Now the old move is 9.h5, but eventually 9.g5 became the main line. There are a couple of other moves we have to be ready for.} 9. Qb3 $5 {This has only been played a few times. Like 8.Qb3, it is a little bit of a nuisance.} Nb6 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge7d6][%mdl 32768] This move is untried, but it looks the most solid to me. Black needs to make a little room for his pieces. Now the g4-pawn is hanging, while Black would also like to play ...Bd6 is he can.} ({Perhaps surprisingly,} 9... Qb6 $6 {does not work for Black. After} 10. f3 $16 {White's space advantage is too much to deal with. A couple of examples:} Ngf6 {after 10...f5 11.g5 Qxb3 12.axb3 Bb4 13.Kf2 $16 was Praggnanandhaa-Dushyant, Dubai 2022. Engines already consider this to be winning for White!} 11. h5 O-O 12. Bd3 Rfc8 13. Qc2 h6 14. g5 {and White's attack was already too strong in Lenderman-Tang, chess.com 2020. Just like in the 8.Qb3 line,}) (9... b5 {can be considered, but the addition of 8.h4 and 8...Nd7 changes things a bit.} 10. g5 $1 {The pawn was hanging, so it advances to hamper Black's development.} h6 {Black nibbles at the pawn structure.} 11. Nf3 Bg4 {and now both} 12. Bg2 {and 12.Nh2!? seem to allow White to maintain the initiative.}) 10. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7][%cal Ga4a5] This is always going to be the critical move when Black meets Qb3 with ...Nb6, and here it is no different.} ({White cannot play} 10. f3 $2 {here because of} Bxh4+) ({Gaining space with} 10. g5 {can be immediately challenged by} h6 {while 10...Bd6 looks fine too.} 11. Nf3 Bg4 12. Nh2 hxg5 13. hxg5 Bd6 $1) 10... a5 {[%csl Gb4,Rg4] This is necessary, but at least we have the b4-square now. We also renew the threat to the g4-pawn. None of this has been seen in practice, so we'll consider a couple of possibilities.} 11. g5 Bb4 ({We can't go} 11... Bd6 $2 12. Bxd6 {because our b6-knight is hanging.}) ({I'd rather avoid} 11... h6 12. Nf3 Bg4 13. Nh2) 12. Bd3 h6 $1 ({After the natural} 12... Ne7 13. Qc2 $1 Qd7 14. Be5 $16 {pressuring Black's kingside causes big problems.}) 13. Nf3 {A natural move.} ({If} 13. O-O-O hxg5 14. Bxg5 Qd7 {intending ...Ne7 and ...f6 at some point, looks unclear.}) 13... h5 $5 {Fixing the kingside.} 14. Ne5 ({If} 14. g6 f6 {and Black can develop normally.}) 14... g6 {[%cal Gg8e7] Black simply wants to play ...Ne7 and perhaps ...Bf5, while ...Nc4 is always in the air too.} 15. Nxg6 {We have to check this move.} fxg6 16. Be5 $1 {Only like this.} ({Worse is} 16. Bxg6+ $2 Kd7 17. Be5 Ne7 18. Bxh8 {and now Black can take either bishop!} Nxg6 $17 {or 18...Qxh8 $17}) 16... Rh7 17. Bxg6+ Rf7 18. Bxh5 Qd7 $13 {[%cal Ge6g4,Gb6c4,Ge6f5] With a messy position which the computer calls equal (of course!).} *

