1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. h5 {This is the older way of playing. White simply gains space.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf7f5][%mdl 32768] A very original idea which is considered standard now. Karpov played in against Kasparov in their 1985 match, and its value was upheld in many games by QGD experts Vaganian and Lputian.} ({After} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 $16 {Black is very cramped on the kingside.}) 10. Bxh6 $6 {White may be tempted to play this, but it's a clear mistake. The capture is not always bad however, so we always have to take it under consideration.} gxh6 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f5,Gd7b6,Gd8b6] The doubled h-pawns are hardly vulnerable here, and now White's kingside pawn moves look silly. He has weakened the dark squares and Black's play is very easy. We will simply castle here, and then ...f5 is a likely break. Black could also play ...Nb6 and ...Qd7 to annoy the g4-pawn, as f2-f3 will further weaken White's dark squares.} 11. Bd3 O-O ({Black does not really have to worry about the h7-pawn, but} 11... Nb6 {with the idea ...Qd7 is also good.}) 12. Qc2 Kh8 $5 13. Bxh7 ({White does not have to bite, but} 13. f3 $6 {would be met by} c5 $1 {when White's play looks totally incohesive.}) ({If} 13. O-O-O {Black could take on g4 or start a queenside operation with 13...b5!?}) 13... Nf6 {[%csl Rg4,Rh7]} 14. Bf5 Nxg4 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf5e6,Gf7e6,Ge7h4] White's space advantage is gone and Black's position looks much easier to play.} *

