1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. h5 {This is the older way of playing. White simply gains space.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf7f5] A very original idea which is considered standard now. Karpov played in against Kasparov in their 1985 match, and its value was upheld in many games by QGD experts Vaganian and Lputian.} ({After} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 $16 {Black is very cramped on the kingside.}) 10. Be2 {This is by far the main move. White protects the g4-pawn without further weakening his structure.} Nb6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf7f5][%mdl 32768] The main line. White has to figure out how to develop. He would rather not play f3, but the g4-pawn requires attention.} (10... f5 {is also possible.} 11. Bxh6 {Instead 11.gxf5 was played in Fier-Bacrot, Tbilisi 2017. Bacrot took with the bishop and won, but I think 11...Nxf5 $132 is stronger.} gxh6 12. gxf5 Bxf5 13. Bg4 $1 Bxg4 14. Qxg4 {when White has a small edge at best, but it's much less interesting for Black. We will see a similar, but improved version of this in our line.}) 11. Rc1 {A waiting move of sorts. This was Kasparov's choice when facing Karpov's 10...Nh6.} f5 $5 {This has only been played once, as far as I can tell, and it was in a correspondence game back in 2014. This is similar to 10.f3, but White's Be2 must be more useful.} ({Karpov reacted with} 11... Bd6 $6 {hoping to keep things simple, but after} 12. Nh3 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 {I think 13.exf4!? may be even stronger! 14...Bd7 14.Rg1 g5 15.hxg6 hxg6 16.Kd2! it was White who soon claimed the open h-file in Kasparov-Karpov, Mosow 1985.}) (11... Nc4 {is given by Kasparov, and this has been Black's main choice. I am deterred by} 12. Nh3 $5 {with the idea} Nxb2 13. Qb3 Nc4 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. Qxb7 {It's quite a mess, but I am not confident enough to recommend it.}) 12. Bxh6 ({This looks more critical than} 12. gxf5 Nxf5 $15 {with easy play for Black in Rawlings-Kratochvil, ICCF 2014.}) 12... gxh6 13. gxf5 Bxf5 14. Bg4 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ga1c1,Gd8d7] Compared to 10...f5 above, the addition of the moves Rc1 and ...Nb6 excludes White from castling long, and Black has an extra resource.} Rf8 $5 ({I prefer this to} 14... Qd7 15. Bxf5 Qxf5 16. Qf3 $1 {which looks very safe for White.}) 15. Bxf5 Rxf5 16. Qg4 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Ge8c8] This is it. Black is ready to castle long. His rooks will be active, and it's not clear what White will do with his king.} *

