for lack of space.}) 12. hxg6 {White really must take.} hxg6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf7f5] Black has clear counterplay and has done very well in practice.} 13. Be5 $5 {White is just trying to be a bit disruptive.} f6 {[%mdl 32768]} (13... Bf6 {is playable, but} 14. f3 {White allows White to consolidate his space advantage.}) 14. Nf4 $5 {[%cal Gf4g6]} ({The only testing move. After} 14. Bg3 g5 {Black has the usual play - he can pressure the g4-pawn and play for ...f5 .}) 14... Bf7 $5 {A calm move, as the e5-bishop is trapped anyway.} ({Black can also take the piece immediately with} 14... fxe5 15. Nxg6 Rh7 {but either capture on e5 gives White decent compensation. Worse is 15...Rg8?! 16.Nxe7 Qxe7 17.Rxh6 e4 was Mamedyarov-Nakamura, Tashkent 2014, when White could play 18.Kd2 $16}) 15. Qc2 {[%cal Gf4g6] The point of White's play.} fxe5 16. Nxg6 Bxg6 $1 {Black not only gives back the piece, he goes for a walk with his king.} (16... Rh7 $2 17. Nxe5 {is overwhelming for White.}) (16... Rg8 17. Nxe5 $1 {is also good for White - he has three pawns for the piece and the h6-knight is now a big problem.}) 17. Qxg6+ Kd7 18. Rxh6 (18. dxe5 Qf8 {holds onto the piece. It's still messy, but I'd take Black.}) 18... Rxh6 19. Qxh6 exd4 20. exd4 Qg8 $13 {[%cal Ge7g5,Ga8f8] I quite like Black here. White cannot castle long, and ...Bg5 and ...Rf8 are coming in any case, with a grip on the dark squares.} *

