1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. h5 {This is the older way of playing. White simply gains space.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf7f5] A very original idea which is considered standard now. Karpov played in against Kasparov in their 1985 match, and its value was upheld in many games by QGD experts Vaganian and Lputian.} ({After} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 $16 {Black is very cramped on the kingside.}) 10. Be2 {This is by far the main move. White protects the g4-pawn without further weakening his structure.} Nb6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf7f5] The main line. White has to figure out how to develop. He would rather not play f3, but the g4-pawn requires attention.} (10... f5 {is also possible.} 11. Bxh6 {Instead 11.gxf5 was played in Fier-Bacrot, Tbilisi 2017. Bacrot took with the bishop and won, but I think 11...Nxf5 $132 is stronger.} gxh6 12. gxf5 Bxf5 13. Bg4 $1 Bxg4 14. Qxg4 {when White has a small edge at best, but it's much less interesting for Black. We will see a similar, but improved version of this in our line.}) 11. Nh3 {White develops and supports g4-g5 if Black goes for ...f5. This is the main line.} g5 $1 ({Black cannot play} 11... f5 $2 12. g5 Nf7 13. Rg1 $16 {when he is really suffering for lack of space.}) 12. hxg6 {White really must take.} hxg6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf7f5] Black has clear counterplay and has done very well in practice.} 13. f3 $6 {This is the most common move, but it's not very good.} Bh4+ (13... g5 14. Bg3 f5 {is also decent, but the check is more disruptive.}) 14. Kd2 {This seems like a better try, as it's not like the king was great at home anyway, but I still like Black.} g5 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Bh2 (15. Be5 f6 16. Bh2 f5 {reaches the same position.}) 15... f5 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ge8c8,Gb6c4] The engine claims that White is close to equality, but with little margin of error. I think the position is going to be much easier to play as Black.} (15... Qe7 {with ...f5 to come is good too.}) *

