1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. g5 {[%csl Rg8] This move, which aims to hinder Black's development, is White's main continuation.} h6 {[%mdl 32768] Black should challenge White immediately.} 10. g6 {This pawn offer is the only way to justify White's play.} ({Instead} 10. Nf3 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bf5 {hardly causes Black any problems.}) 10... Ngf6 {Now White usually takes on f7.} (10... f5 $6 {worked out well in Lenderman-Caruana, Saint Louis 2016, but Black is very cramped after.} 11. h5 Ngf6 12. f3 $16) (10... fxg6 {is not common but looks fine. We will consider this later as an alternative.}) 11. Bd3 {This is much less common, as it appears to only serve to give Black more options. For us with will not really make any difference though.} O-O 12. gxf7+ Bxf7 {And we have reached our main line. White has avoided StartFENr2qk2r/pp1nbpp1/2p1bnPp/3p4/3P1B1P/2N1P3/PP3P2/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 11EndFEN 11.gxf7 Bxf7 12.Bd3 Nh5 , but we are not going for that anyway. Black can also play 12...Kh8 or 12...Rxf7 but I am not convinced that these are any better.} *

