1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. g5 {[%csl Rg8] This move, which aims to hinder Black's development, is White's main continuation.} h6 {Black should challenge White immediately.} 10. g6 {This pawn offer is the only way to justify White's play.} ({Instead} 10. Nf3 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bf5 {hardly causes Black any problems.}) 10... Ngf6 {Now White usually takes on f7.} (10... f5 $6 {worked out well in Lenderman-Caruana, Saint Louis 2016, but Black is very cramped after.} 11. h5 Ngf6 12. f3 $16) (10... fxg6 {is not common but looks fine. We will consider this later as an alternative.}) 11. gxf7+ Bxf7 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Bd3 O-O $5 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gf7h5] Certainly an obvious move, but it's not so common. We keep the options of both ...Nh5 and ...Bh5.} ({The most popular move is} 12... Nh5 {when} 13. Bh2 O-O 14. Qg4 Ndf6 15. Qg2 Be6 $13 {is a typical unclear position. I find castling to be more flexible, and it also avoids any move order issues Black may face after 11.Bd3.}) 13. Nge2 {This is untried and safer than some other moves, but now White's queen is not going to bother us. Black has various possibilities.} ({Alatortsev specialist GM Andrew Tang once faced} 13. Qb3 $2 {in a blitz game. Now} Nc5 $146 {is just crushing.} 14. dxc5 d4 {wins back the piece with a huge lead in development.}) ({After} 13. Nf3 $6 Bh5 {the pin is annoying and Black is ready to create counterplay with ...Bb4 and ...Qa5.}) 13... Bh5 ({We could also bother the bishop with} 13... Nh5 {or play 13...Rc8 intending to push some pawns on the queenside.}) 14. Qc2 Bb4 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf6e4,Gb4e1,Gh5d1] Black's play looks more natural. The bishops creates pressure and we can continue with ...Qe7 to connect the rooks.} *

