1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. g5 {[%csl Rg8] This move, which aims to hinder Black's development, is White's main continuation.} h6 {Black should challenge White immediately.} 10. g6 {This pawn offer is the only way to justify White's play.} ({Instead} 10. Nf3 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bf5 {hardly causes Black any problems.}) 10... Ngf6 {Now White usually takes on f7.} (10... f5 $6 {worked out well in Lenderman-Caruana, Saint Louis 2016, but Black is very cramped after.} 11. h5 Ngf6 12. f3 $16) (10... fxg6 {is not common but looks fine. We will consider this later as an alternative.}) 11. gxf7+ Bxf7 12. Bd3 O-O $5 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gf7h5] Certainly an obvious move, but it's not so common. We keep the options of both ...Nh5 and ...Bh5.} ({The most popular move is} 12... Nh5 {when} 13. Bh2 O-O 14. Qg4 Ndf6 15. Qg2 Be6 $13 {is a typical unclear position. I find castling to be more flexible, and it also avoids any move order issues Black may face after 11.Bd3.}) 13. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3g2,Gg1e2] This may look odd at first, but it's rather thematic and it's also the engine's first choice. White has made his bed so he brings his queen to the kingside.} Bh5 $146 {[%mdl 32768]} ({After} 13... Nh5 14. Nge2 $1 Nxf4 15. Nxf4 {White has a strong grip on the light squares and will castle long. This looks too dangerous for Black.}) 14. Qg2 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge1c1] With the queen settled in, White would like to play Nge2 and O-O-O. Surprisingly, Bxh6 (grabbing a pawn and threatening mate!) is often not such a threat, as White is already lagging in development.} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gf8f7,Ge7b4,Gd8a5] This move offers a pawn in multiple ways, but it is the only way to make use of Black's lead in development.} 15. Bxe4 $2 {The worst choice. It's not surprising as White is already a bit squishy on the light squares.} dxe4 16. Qxe4 ({Even worse is} 16. Bxh6 $2 Rf7 {when White cannot develop the g1-knight because of ...Bf3. Black is ready to play ...Qb6 with great play.}) ({White cannot get too greedy:} 16. Nxe4 $2 Qa5+ 17. Nc3 Rxf4 18. exf4 Ba3 {and White's position disintegrates.}) 16... Rf7 $17 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gd7f6,Gf6d5,Gd8a5,Gd8b6,Ge7b4] Black has more than enough compensation, and the engines consider Black to be much better. White is underdeveloped and creaking on the light squares.} 17. Z0 ({One possible line is} 17. Nge2 Nf6 18. Qg2 Bxe2 $5 19. Nxe2 Qa5+ 20. Kf1 Raf8 {intending ...Nd5.}) *

