1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 {[%mdl 32768]} 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move by far.} ({Colovic gives} 8... Bxh4 {and considers it a refutation. I don't want to debate this, but I will say that 8.h4 is still being played a lot, and black players are rarely grabbing the pawn. I am not aware of any theoretical problems with the pawn grab, but I imagine that players of the QGD simply do not find it to be practical - there is a lot of memorization and the position ultimately should probably end up in a draw. The line goes 9.Qb3 g5 10.Be5 f6 11.Bh2 Bxg4 when 12.Qxb7 should ultimately leads to a perpetual check (which is fine theoretically if you remember it all) while 12.Be2 (which I consider to be more critical) leads to an endgame where Black is a pawn up, but with a really bad pawn structure.}) 9. g5 {[%csl Rg8] This move, which aims to hinder Black's development, is White's main continuation.} h6 {Black should challenge White immediately.} 10. g6 {This pawn offer is the only way to justify White's play.} ({Instead} 10. Nf3 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bf5 {hardly causes Black any problems.}) 10... fxg6 {This is not played too often but I don't see any problems. There is one word of warning though.} 11. Bd3 Bf7 ({After the most common} 11... Nf8 {,} 12. Nf3 $2 {is a strange move. The obvious} Bg4 $1 {is quite annoying, and Black had very good counterplay in So-Akobian, Saint Louis 2017. But there is no reason to allow this pin. Instead 12.Qc2! looks good for White. Black can hold the pawn but he will be horribly cramped.}) 12. Qc2 (12. Nf3 Ngf6 {does not really help White. We will just castle.}) 12... Ngf6 13. Bxg6 O-O {[%cal Gf6h5,Ge7b4] This is similar to our main line, but White's queen is on c2 instead of g2.} *

