1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nbd2 {A flexible choice, although it puts less pressure on the center than 9.Nc3.} cxd4 10. exd4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] This is the main pawn structure for the lines with b3. Black should not rush to take on c4 to give White 'hanging pawns', but it's always in the air. Black controls the tension so he should maintain it - our next move will prevent c4-c5, and cxd5 will almost always just give White a bad isolated pawn position. maybe copy with} Nbd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rc4c5,Ga1c1] We copy White's knight position. One thing I like about this move is that White can't really achieve c4-c5 comfortably.} ({It's more common to play} 10... Nc6 {and this is Colovic's recommendation. Both moves are fine. I would just rather avoid lines like} 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rfd1 {and we'll have to watch for c4-c5. Now White has to decide how to arrange his heavy pieces.}) 11. Qe2 {White often play this, but it will generally transpose to 11.Rac1.} Rc8 12. Rad1 ({It's probably better to play} 12. Rac1 {.}) 12... Qc7 $5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc7f4,Gc7b8,Gb8a8,Gf8e8,Gf8d8,Gf6h5,Gh5f4] A flexible move which makes a lot of sense with no white rook on the c-file to bother us. We size up the f4-square, and may still bring the queen to a8.} ({Often we will go for} 12... Rc7 {with the idea of ...Qa8. But here the direct} 13. Ne5 dxc4 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 {justifies White's play a bit - after} Bd6 16. Qe2 {White's rooks will be well placed on e1 and d1 - we will see a position like this but with a rook on c1, in which case we have the pin ...Bf4 to annoy White.}) 13. Ne5 $6 ({We always have to check this move, but here it doesn't trouble us. If White makes a more neutral move like} 13. Rfe1 {we could make a quiet move, but I like the enterprising} Nh5 $5 14. g3 Nhf6 {when White has weakened the long diagonal.}) 13... dxc4 $1 {Perfect timing.} 14. Ndxc4 ({Accepting an isolated pawn. If} 14. bxc4 $6 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 $17 {is great for Black as White's pawn structure is wrecked.}) 14... Nd5 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gg7g6,Gd5f4,Gb6b5] Black is doing well. It's hardly an ideal IQP for White, as the b2-bishop is poorly placed.} *

