1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nbd2 {A flexible choice, although it puts less pressure on the center than 9.Nc3.} cxd4 10. exd4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] This is the main pawn structure for the lines with b3. Black should not rush to take on c4 to give White 'hanging pawns', but it's always in the air. Black controls the tension so he should maintain it - our next move will prevent c4-c5, and cxd5 will almost always just give White a bad isolated pawn position. maybe copy with} Nbd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rc4c5,Ga1c1] We copy White's knight position. One thing I like about this move is that White can't really achieve c4-c5 comfortably.} ({It's more common to play} 10... Nc6 {and this is Colovic's recommendation. Both moves are fine. I would just rather avoid lines like} 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rfd1 {and we'll have to watch for c4-c5. Now White has to decide how to arrange his heavy pieces.}) 11. Re1 {A normal move.} Rc8 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Rc1 Rc7 {[%cal Gd8a8] Preparing ...Qa8.} ({Another good move is} 12... Bb4 $5 13. a3 $6 {Instead White should play 13.Re3 which looks awkward but it's not so bad.} dxc4 {when ...Bxf3 will cause White problems.}) 13. Bb1 ({If} 13. Nf1 Qa8 {fits our scheme perfectly.}) ({The direct} 13. Ne5 {is not threatening with the rook on e1 . 13...dxc4 14.bxc4 Nxe5 15.Rxe5 Bd6 and ...Bf4 will be a bit annoying.}) 13... Qa8 $1 {[%cal Ga8g2]} 14. Ne5 Rd8 {Black's rooks are flexibly placed.} 15. Z0 ({One game continued} 15. a3 $6 dxc4 16. bxc4 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 {Now the tempting} Bxg2 18. d5 $1 {was not so clear in Benkovic-G.Szabo, Bucharest 2012. Stronger was 17...Ne8! intending ...Bf6, when Black is doing very well.}) *

