1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nbd2 {A flexible choice, although it puts less pressure on the center than 9.Nc3.} cxd4 10. exd4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] This is the main pawn structure for the lines with b3. Black should not rush to take on c4 to give White 'hanging pawns', but it's always in the air. Black controls the tension so he should maintain it - our next move will prevent c4-c5, and cxd5 will almost always just give White a bad isolated pawn position. maybe copy with} Nbd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Rc4c5,Ga1c1] We copy White's knight position. One thing I like about this move is that White can't really achieve c4-c5 comfortably.} ({It's more common to play} 10... Nc6 {and this is Colovic's recommendation. Both moves are fine. I would just rather avoid lines like} 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Qe2 Re8 13. Rfd1 {and we'll have to watch for c4-c5. Now White has to decide how to arrange his heavy pieces.}) 11. Rc1 {The most common. At least we don't have to worry about c4-c5.} Rc8 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Qe2 Rc7 {[%cal Gd8a8]} ({The same plan. There are other decent moves too like} 12... Re8 {,}) (12... Nh5 {,}) (12... g6 {.}) 13. Ne5 ({If} 13. Rfd1 Qa8 {play is similar to what we've seen before.}) 13... dxc4 {Usually White's Ne5 should be met this way, as with the hanging pawns White's will never want to recapture on e5 with a pawn.} ({Worse is} 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 {when White does not suffer with a poor structure.}) 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 ({The recapture} 15. dxe5 $2 Nd7 $17 {is pretty much always bad for White.}) 15... Bd6 {Black has some choice, but I like this move.} (15... Qd6 {is fine. White should probably play} 16. Qe2 {when we have to watch for d5 and Be5.}) ({If} 15... Rd7 16. Rfd1 Qa8 17. d5 {is another trick. We cannot play} exd5 $2 {because of} 18. Bf5 {.}) 16. Qe2 Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gf4c1,Gb7g2] Just to annoy White, as kicking the bishop with g3 will always be risky with the long diagonal open for Black's other bishop.} 17. Z0 ({An instructive sequence is seen in the following game:} 17. Rc2 b5 $1 18. c5 {(If 18.cxb5 Rxc2 19.Bxc2 Bxh2+ 20.Kxh2 Qc7+ 21.Kg1 Qxc2 $17 )} Nd5 $17 {was Galliamova-Koneru, Sochi 2015. If} 19. Bxb5 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Qh4+ 21. Kg1 Nf4 {gives Black a winning attack.}) *

