1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nc3 {The knight seems more active here, as it controls d5. However, White has less control over c4, which is sometimes a tender spot, and the f3-knight is less well protected. Sometimes these deficiencies are related, as we shall see.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. exd4 Nc6 {[%csl Gc3,Gc6][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] And again we copy! White develops his knight actively, so we do too. Now White is a bit more limited in choosing his heavy piece configurations.} (10... Nbd7 {is also playabe here of course.}) 11. Qe2 $6 {A common move, but it's a mistake!} Nb4 $1 {Black is already better.} 12. Bb1 {Preserving the bishop, but there are other problems.} (12. Rfd1 Nxd3 {is just good for Black. The b7-bishop will be very strong.} 13. Rxd3 {There are many good moves here, such as} Ne4 {, or even 13...Nh5!}) 12... dxc4 13. bxc4 Bxf3 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} 14. gxf3 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Ge2b2] Keeping the b2-bishop protected.} ({If} 14. Qxf3 {we can safely grab the d-pawn.} Qxd4 15. a3 Na6 $17 {.}) 14... Bd6 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4,Rf4][%cal Gg7g6,Gf6h5,Ga8c8,Gb4c6,Gd6f4] Black is very active and White must be very careful.} ({The pawn looks tasty, but} 14... Qxd4 $2 15. Ne4 Qd8 16. Rd1 {gives White a strong attack.}) ({Colovic gives} 14... Re8 {This is fine, but I don't see much need for this move.}) ({The immediate} 14... Nh5 {is also strong.}) ({After} 14... Bd6 {White can lose immediately after} 15. a3 Nh5 $1 {when ...Qh4 is crushing. We'll see this idea again.}) *

