1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nc3 {The knight seems more active here, as it controls d5. However, White has less control over c4, which is sometimes a tender spot, and the f3-knight is less well protected. Sometimes these deficiencies are related, as we shall see.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {[%csl Gc3,Gc6][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] And again we copy! White develops his knigh tactively, so we do too. Now White is a bit more limited in choosing his heavy piece configurations.} (10... Nbd7 {is also playabe here of course.}) 11. Re1 {This move is a 'signal' for us to play ...Nb4.} Nb4 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Instead} 11... Rc8 {is playable, but after} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Be4 {and d5 next, the position greatly simplifies, but Black will have to play precisely to equalize.}) 12. Bf1 Rc8 {This is like the main lines, and after:} 13. Rc1 {White does not want to give up the bishop.} (13. Be2 $6 {is wrong because after} dxc4 14. bxc4 $6 Bxf3 $1 {White's has to wreck his kingside structure to avoid dropping the c4-pawn.}) *

