1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nc3 {The knight seems more active here, as it controls d5. However, White has less control over c4, which is sometimes a tender spot, and the f3-knight is less well protected. Sometimes these deficiencies are related, as we shall see.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {[%csl Gc3,Gc6][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] And again we copy! White develops his knigh tactively, so we do too. Now White is a bit more limited in choosing his heavy piece configurations.} (10... Nbd7 {is also playabe here of course.}) 11. Rc1 Rc8 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Qe2 $6 {Again this natural move is bad, but it's been played a lot - by good players! Maybe we get lucky.. .} Nb4 $1 13. Bb1 dxc4 14. bxc4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5]} ({I think this is the most accurate, but} 15... Nh5 {is good too. If} 16. a3 $2 {better is 16.Qe4 g6 17.a3} Bd6 {was seen in Svidler-Kramnik, Amsterdam rapid 2019.}) 16. Ne4 (16. a3 Nh5 {is the same as Svidler - Kramnik.}) 16... Bf4 $17 {[%csl Rf3,Rf2] A great position for Black.} *

