1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. b3 ({White could start with} 5. Nbd2 {for example} O-O 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Bd3 ({That that the c4-pawn is covered by the b-pawn, White hurries to castle. This is the most common, but there's not really anything wrong with playing} 6. Bb2 {first.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {transposing.}) 6... b6 {This is consistent with our repertoire.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Bb2 c5 ({In this exact position, Black often plays} 8... Nbd7 {first, but we want to wait to see how White develops his pieces first.}) 9. Nc3 {The knight seems more active here, as it controls d5. However, White has less control over c4, which is sometimes a tender spot, and the f3-knight is less well protected. Sometimes these deficiencies are related, as we shall see.} cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 {[%csl Gc3,Gc6][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] And again we copy! White develops his knigh tactively, so we do too. Now White is a bit more limited in choosing his heavy piece configurations.} (10... Nbd7 {is also playabe here of course.}) 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Re1 {Our signal to play ... Nb4!} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd5c4,Gc8c4,Gb7f3][%mdl 32768]} ({Instead} 12... Re8 {runs into} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Be4 {and d5 again.}) ({Colovic suggests the rare} 12... g6 {After} 13. cxd5 {we have to play} exd5 {which is solid enough, but less interesting.}) ({Black can also play} 12... Na5 {to pressure the c4-pawn. If} 13. Ne5 Nc6 $1 {challenges White to make progress.}) 13. Bf1 {White does not want to give up the bishop.} (13. Be2 $6 {is wrong because after} dxc4 14. bxc4 $6 Bxf3 $1 {White's has to wreck his kingside structure to avoid dropping the c4-pawn.}) 13... Re8 {Now White can kick us back, or make his move.} (13... Ne4 $6 {has been played several times, but} 14. a3 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nc6 16. c5 $1 {is good for White.}) (13... Nc6 $5 {is not bad though, asking White if he has anything better than repeating moves.}) 14. Ne5 {Very direct. Some care is needed.} Nc6 {Simplest.} ({We could play} 14... Bf8 {but after} 15. a3 Nc6 16. cxd5 $1 {we have to be very careful.} Nxd5 $6 {better is 16...Nxe5 17.dxe5 Nxd5=} 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 $2 18. Bc4 {followed by Nxf7 is going to hurt.} Qd6 {if 18...Qd8 19.Nxf7 Kxf7 20.Qh5+} 19. Nxf7 Kxf7 20. d5 {and White is winning.}) 15. cxd5 Nxe5 $1 ({Again, we should avoid} 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 $2 17. Bc4 {when bad things await us.}) 16. dxe5 Nxd5 {Here everything is fine. I even prefer Black with the more compact pawn structure.} 17. Z0 ({A couple of examples:} 17. Qg4) ({Or} 17. Ne4 Bb4 $1 18. Re2 Nf4 19. Re3 Qxd1 20. Rxd1 Rc2 $17 {N.Zapata-Korneev, La Roda 2013.} 21. Nc3 Bxc3 {Rc5= Nucci-Cantelli, ICCF 2009.}) *

