1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White can choose this quiet continuation when he's not in the mood for a theoretical battle. Many books on the QGD do not even cover it.} Be7 {Black has all kinds of reasonable moves of course, but we will stick with the program and go ...Be7 and ...O-O. There are countless move orders, for White, but there are basically three different main setups White can choose from: 1. b3 with Nbd2 2. b3 with Nc3 3. without b3} 5. Nc3 O-O {[%mdl 32768]} 6. Bd3 {This is by far the most common move.} (6. b3 b6 {will reach lines we considered already.}) (6. cxd5 $6 exd5 {is just a bad version of this structure for White, as his c1-bishop is locked in for no reason. This does not need any special analysis - we will just play ...c6 and develop normally.}) 6... dxc4 {A logical move, as White has to spend another tempo moving the bishop.} ({Black can still play} 6... b6 7. O-O Bb7 {then} 8. cxd5 $5 exd5 9. b3 {is a line that normally arises from the Queen's Indian Defense. This is also fine for Black, but there is a lot more to learn than there is after our move 6...dxc4, which is objectively quite good.}) 7. Bxc4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc7c5,Gf1d3,Gd3c4] We have a position that's like a Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA), but White has lost a tempo, as he took an extra move to take on c4. We are not magically better yet however, as in the QGA Black usually plays quickly on the queenside, without rushing to play ...Be7 and ...O-O as we have here. Black is still comfortable however, and has scored well. White has a fundamental choice to make - allow ...b5 or prevent it with 8.a4.} ({Black can also play} 7... c5 8. O-O a6 {but this gives White an extra option with} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 {We will only allow this symmetrical structure when White has weakened himself with a2-a4.}) 8. a4 {[%csl Rb4] A typical move in both the QGD and the QGA. White restricts Black's queenside expansion, but weakens the b4-square in the process.} c5 {The main line, and I think this is the most challenging.} (8... b6 {is given by Colovic. This should be fine too.}) 9. O-O Nc6 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3c4] Now this really is like a QGA where White has lost a tempo, as Black's setup is common in the lines with a2-a4.} 10. dxc5 ({White can easily drift into an inferior IQP position. For example} 10. b3 $6 cxd4) ({If} 10. Qe2 $6 cxd4 11. exd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 {is a pretty safe pawn grab. Sometimes this works for White if he can play Nc3-b5, but here he cannot.}) 10... Bxc5 {We have total symmetry, except for the position of the a-pawns! This favors Black, and White has to be careful here despite having the move.} 11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5] A known setup in the QGA. White intends e4-e5 with attacking chances, so we should combat this plan. In fact Black is a tempo up on a known position from the QGA. After StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 e6 5.Bxc4 a6 6.a4 c5 7.O-O Nc6 8.Nc3 Be7 9.Qe2 O-O 10.dxc5 Bxc5 we have the same position, but with White to move! If 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 $15 the only imbalance is White's weakened queenside.} Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gf8d8] I like this flexible move.} ({Black can also play} 11... e5 {but then} 12. Ng5 {with pressure on f7 and Nge4 coming, looks easier for White.}) 12. e4 $6 {White's most common move. Sometimes it's difficult to put on the brakes when playing White.} ({Against slow moves like} 12. h3 {we can play} b6 {and ...Bb7, ... Rd8 with a good position.}) ({The engine suggests that White should already seek equality with} 12. Bd3 Rd8 13. Ne4 {although I am happy with Black after} Be7 {because of White's softened queenside.}) 12... Ng4 $1 ({Black is also doing well after} 12... Nd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 {, but we can set a good trap that a couple of decent players have fallen into!}) 13. g3 ({After} 13. h3 $4 Nd4 $1 {White can resign. Now Black has a few good moves here, but nothing is clear-cut.}) 13... Bd6 $15 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gb7b6,Gg4e5]} ({After the immediate} 13... Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bf4 {seems ok for White.}) ({The simple} 13... Bd7 {is good though, for example} 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Rfd1 Qc7 $15 {with ...Rd8 and ...Nge5 coming. White is a bit weak on the dark squares.}) ({With} 13... Bd6 $5 {we stop Bf4 and still may continue with ...Nge5 or ...b6. If} 14. h3 $6 Nge5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 {with ...Nd4 coming. White's position looks very loose.}) *

