1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 {[%mdl 32768]} 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 ({And this is the classical response. Black prepares to meet} 8. Qxc4 {with} b5 {, gaining time to play ...Bb7. There are some modern alternatives, such as: The ambitious 7...b5!? The quiet 7...b6!? And even the odd-looking 7...c6!? but we will stick with the classical response.}) ({White regains the pawn. This is rather obvious, but lately Catalan players have favored} 8. a4) 8... b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8d7,Ga8c8] In this line much revolves around Black's ability to get the freeing ...c5 advance in. If he cannot, he may be stuck with a backwards c-pawn. But if Black does achieve this advance, his pieces will quickly spring to life. White's queen is often vulnerable on the c-file as well.} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This is White's most straightforward concept in the 8.Qxc4 line. It may look kind of pointless at first, but White has a specific strategic idea in mind. He will capture on f6 to lure one of Black's minor pieces away from control of the critical c5-square, and then follow up with Nb1-d2-b3. Whether the idea works or not is another matter.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Now White almost universally captures on f6.} 11. Rd1 {This is a typical move in the Catalan, but there's not really time for this.} Rc8 $15 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc7c5] Black will achieve the ...c5 advance easily.} *

