1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5] In this line much revolves around Black's ability to get the freeing ...c5 advance in. If he cannot, he may be stuck with a backwards c-pawn.} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This is White's most straightforward concept in the 8.Qxc4 line. It may look kind of pointless at first, but White has a specific strategic idea in mind. He will capture on f6 to lure one of Black's minor pieces away from control of the critical c5-square, and then follow up with Nb1-d2-b3. Whether the idea works or not is another matter.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] Now White almost universally captures on f6.} 11. Nbd2 {This move is possible, but there's no advantage to delaying the capture on f6.} Rc8 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Nb3 ({This is just not really working for White. Better is} 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 {transposing to the main lines.}) 12... Be4 {This is a very common maneuver.} 13. Qc1 c5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc8c1]} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 $1 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Gf6b2] Taking advantage of White's poor move order.} 15. dxc5 ({If} 15. Nxc5 $4 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Bxd4 {wins for Black.}) 15... Qe7 {[%csl Rb2,Rc1,Ge4,Gf6][%cal Gd7c5] Black wins back the pawn with a clear advantage due to his more active pieces and bishop pair.} *

