1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5] In this line much revolves around Black's ability to get the freeing ...c5 advance in. If he cannot, he may be stuck with a backwards c-pawn.} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This is White's most straightforward concept in the 8.Qxc4 line. It may look kind of pointless at first, but White has a specific strategic idea in mind. He will capture on f6 to lure one of Black's minor pieces away from control of the critical c5-square, and then follow up with Nb1-d2-b3. Whether the idea works or not is another matter.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 11. Bxf6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7f6,Gd7f6,Ge7c5,Gd7c5] The only critical move. White pulls one of Black's pieces away from the c5-square.} Nxf6 {[%mdl 32768] This recapture make the most sense. The knight may move back to d7, or even to e4, as we shall see. Also opening the d-file for Black's queen will have certain implications.} 12. Nbd2 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd2b3] White prepares Nb3, hoping to lock down Black's ...c5 break. It does not really work though.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 13. Nb3 c5 {I like this direct move, trying to question the validity of White's concept.} ({There is a serious alternative in} 13... Be4 {which has been seen even more frequently in practice. Objectively this is also fine, but it seems less practical to me as White has more possibilities in this line.} 14. Qc3 Nd5 15. Qd2 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Rxc5 18. Rac1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Qa8 {is one possibility. Black is ok here, but it's all very safe for White.}) 14. Nxc5 $2 {White dreams of securing an extra pawn with b4, but this just loses.} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxd4 {[%csl Rc5] White can avoid the loss of a whole piece with:} 16. Nb3 {and now} Qxf2+ $1 {and ...Rxc2 is the most efficient.} *

