1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {[%cal Gc7c5] In this line much revolves around Black's ability to get the freeing ...c5 advance in. If he cannot, he may be stuck with a backwards c-pawn.} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This is White's most straightforward concept in the 8.Qxc4 line. It may look kind of pointless at first, but White has a specific strategic idea in mind. He will capture on f6 to lure one of Black's minor pieces away from control of the critical c5-square, and then follow up with Nb1-d2-b3. Whether the idea works or not is another matter.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 11. Bxf6 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge7f6,Gd7f6,Ge7c5,Gd7c5] The only critical move.} Nxf6 {This recapture make the most sense. The knight may move back to d7, or even to e4, as we shall see. Also opening the d-file for Black's queen will have certain implications.} 12. Nbd2 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd2b3] White prepares Nb3, hoping to lock down the c5-square. White is not able to get any advantage though.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 13. Nb3 c5 {I like this direct move, trying to question the validity of White's concept.} ({There is a serious alternative in} 13... Be4 {which has been seen even more frequently in practice. Objectively this is also fine, but it seems less practical to me as White has more possibilities in this line.} 14. Qc3 Nd5 15. Qd2 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Rxc5 18. Rac1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Qa8 {is one possibility. Black is ok here, but it's all very safe for White.}) 14. dxc5 {So White has taken a pawn. Black can regain the material rather easily, so White hope that while Black gathers the pawn, he may generate some 'Catalan pressure' in a simplified position.} Ne4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This active move is the modern solution.} (14... a5 $6 {is somewhat thematic and has been played a bit, but after} 15. a4 {I do not think Black's prospect have improved.}) (14... Bd5 {hints at ...Bxb3 to regain the pawn. This move is common, but White has scored well.} 15. Rfd1 Qc7 $6 {The main move in practice, but} 16. Nfd4 $1 {leaves White with a workable edge after} Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Rac1 {because} Rfc8 $2 {loses to} 21. Rxc5 Rxc5 22. Nxb5 $1 {exploiting Black's back rank weakness.}) (14... Be4 {is solid and scores well, but White can still play for a little something.} 15. Qc3 Bd5 {The point of the bishop shuffle is now ...Ne4 will gain a tempo.} 16. Rfd1 Ne4 17. Qe1 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Rxc5 19. Ne5 {White threatens Bxe4 and after Black deals with that, Nd3 will gain a tempo leaving White with a bit of pressure.}) (14... Rc7 $5 {is indicated by Stockfish and this could be worth exploring. Black intends the aesthetically pleasing ...Qa8. Black should be able to regain the pawn in short order with ...Nd7 and ...Rfc8.}) 15. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2e4] White rushes to simplify.} Nxc5 ({Black could even consider} 15... Bxc5 $5 16. Qd3 $1 Bxf2+ $1 17. Rxf2 Nxf2 18. Qxd8 Nh3+ $1 19. Bxh3 Rfxd8 $13 {with an unclear endgame.}) 16. Bxb7 Nxb7 17. Qd3 (17. Nc6 Qe8 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {is also fine for Black.}) 17... Qc7 {[%cal Gc7e5,Gf8d8] Black had easy development and a pleasant game in Glud-Hammer, Oslo 2007.} *

