dxc5 {So White has taken a pawn. Black can regain the material rather easily, so White hope that while Black gathers the pawn, he may generate some 'Catalan pressure' in a simplified position.} Ne4 $1 {This active move is the modern solution.} (14... a5 $6 {is somewhat thematic and has been played a bit, but after} 15. a4 {I do not think Black's prospect have improved.}) (14... Bd5 {hints at ...Bxb3 to regain the pawn. This move is common, but White has scored well.} 15. Rfd1 Qc7 $6 {The main move in practice, but} 16. Nfd4 $1 {leaves White with a workable edge after} Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Rac1 {because} Rfc8 $2 {loses to} 21. Rxc5 Rxc5 22. Nxb5 $1 {exploiting Black's back rank weakness.}) (14... Be4 {is solid and scores well, but White can still play for a little something.} 15. Qc3 Bd5 {The point of the bishop shuffle is now ...Ne4 will gain a tempo.} 16. Rfd1 Ne4 17. Qe1 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Rxc5 19. Ne5 {White threatens Bxe4 and after Black deals with that, Nd3 will gain a tempo leaving White with a bit of pressure.}) (14... Rc7 $5 {is indicated by Stockfish and this could be worth exploring. Black intends the aesthetically pleasing ...Qa8. Black should be able to regain the pawn in short order with ...Nd7 and ...Rfc8.}) 15. Rfd1 {Obvious and critical.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge4c5][%mdl 32768] Black simply wants to take on c5 with a good position. There is only one way to cause any trouble.} 16. Nfd4 $6 {This is not it.} Nxc5 17. Nxc5 ({Another game went} 17. Rac1 $6 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qb7+ 19. Kg1 Nxb3 20. Qxb3 Bf6 21. Nf3 Qe4 {with a great position for Black in Franciskovic-Repkova, Sibenik 2005.}) 17... Bxc5 18. Qb3 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qb6 $15 {Black had a slight initiative and went on to win in the game Nass-Kasimdzhanov, Nancy 2011.} *

