dxc5 {So White has taken a pawn. Black can regain the material rather easily, so White hope that while Black gathers the pawn, he may generate some 'Catalan pressure' in a simplified position.} Ne4 $1 {This active move is the modern solution.} (14... a5 $6 {is somewhat thematic and has been played a bit, but after} 15. a4 {I do not think Black's prospect have improved.}) (14... Bd5 {hints at ...Bxb3 to regain the pawn. This move is common, but White has scored well.} 15. Rfd1 Qc7 $6 {The main move in practice, but} 16. Nfd4 $1 {leaves White with a workable edge after} Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Rac1 {because} Rfc8 $2 {loses to} 21. Rxc5 Rxc5 22. Nxb5 $1 {exploiting Black's back rank weakness.}) (14... Be4 {is solid and scores well, but White can still play for a little something.} 15. Qc3 Bd5 {The point of the bishop shuffle is now ...Ne4 will gain a tempo.} 16. Rfd1 Ne4 17. Qe1 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Rxc5 19. Ne5 {White threatens Bxe4 and after Black deals with that, Nd3 will gain a tempo leaving White with a bit of pressure.}) (14... Rc7 $5 {is indicated by Stockfish and this could be worth exploring. Black intends the aesthetically pleasing ...Qa8. Black should be able to regain the pawn in short order with ...Nd7 and ...Rfc8.}) 15. Rfd1 {Obvious and critical.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge4c5] Black simply wants to take on c5 with a good position. There is only one way to cause any trouble.} 16. c6 $1 {A clever move, and the only way to cause any problems. Play becomes very forcing now, so every move is critical.} Qxc6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Not} 16... Bxc6 $2 17. Nfd4 {and White wins material.}) 17. Qxc6 Bxc6 18. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c6] Gaining a tempo. This was the point of 16.c6.} Bd5 {[%cal Gf8d8] The only move.} ({Black loses material after} 18... Bb7 $4 19. Rd7) ({as well as} 18... Ba8 $4 19. Nd7 {hitting our rook and threatening Nb6.}) {Black's position looks quite nice now, so White must continue to probe.} 19. Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gd7b6] Attacking the rook and also planning Nb6.} Rfe8 $1 ({An important move to remember! The natural} 19... Rfd8 $6 {is inaccurate because after} 20. Nb6 Rc2 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Nd4 $1 {Black is chased back and has a worse pawn structure. If} Rxb2 $2 {White has} 23. Nc6 Re8 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Nxe7+ {and White wins.}) 20. Nb6 Rc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2b2,Gc2e2] White is going to take on d5 and weaken Black's structure, so we must stay active.} 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Rxd5 ({Compared to the note at move 19, here} 22. Nd4 Rxb2 $17 {safely takes an important pawn.}) 22... Bf8 {Black even has some choice here, but this looks simplest. The back rank is secure now. The first game from this position saw two heavyweights.} (22... Bf6 {This looks the most active, but after} 23. Rc1 $1 Rxc1+ 24. Nxc1 Bxb2 25. Bxe4 Bxc1 26. Rd7 Kf8 27. Bc6 Re6 28. Rc7 {White kept a hint of pressure in Topalov-Anand, Nice 2008. Note that} Rxe2 $2 {fails after} 29. Rc8+ Ke7 30. Re8+ {skewering the rook.}) (22... Nf6 {is sufficient for equality, but more complicated.} 23. Rd2 {White holds onto the pawn for now.} Rxd2 24. Nxd2 Bb4 {Black will win back the pawn, but there's still some tricks because Black's back rank can be vulnerable.} 25. Nb3 Rxe2 26. Rb1 {It looks like White has nothing at all, but it is still a little bit tricky.} g6 $1 {Getting a little breathing room.} 27. Bb7 Re6 {and Black is fine. 27...a5!? is ok too, but more complicated.}) 23. Rb1 ({Twice White has tried} 23. Bxe4 Rxe4 {but Black wins back the pawn here, and in fact Black won both games.}) 23... Rxe2 24. Bf3 Rc2 {This is level, but not yet drawn. Both sides have active pieces.} *

