1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked (kind of, as we shall see), and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance.} ({The most obvious move is} 10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 $6 {is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went 12...Nd7 13.Rfd1 Bxf3?! 14.Bxf3 Rb8 15.e3 $16 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless, 12...Nc6!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. a3 $6 {White wants to prevent ...Nb4 for good, but he cannot completely ignore the attack on the d4-pawn.} Nxd4 $1 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Rd1 ({White can get the pawn back, but he must throw this move in first. White would lose immediately after} 14. Qxc7 $2 Qxb2 {.}) ({Or} 14. Bxc7 $2 Rac8 {.}) 14... Qc5 15. Qxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxc7 {It looks like White has secured near-equality, but Black has a big lead in development, and he is able to put it to use despite the limited material.} Ng4 $1 {White has serious problems.} 17. b4 {Relatively best.} ({White quickly loses material after} 17. e3 Bxe3 $17) ({Or} 17. Rf1 Rfc8 18. Bf4 Bd4 $17) 17... Bxf2 $1 {Black is threating ...Ne3+.} 18. Kf3 Rfc8 $1 {It's not so surprising that the tactics work for Black, as he is well ahead in development. We will end the trainable here, but I'll show a couple of possibilities from here:} 19. Z0 (19. Bf4 e5 $1 {Black attacks the bishop and prepares another tempo-gaining move.} 20. Kxg4 exf4 21. gxf4 Rc2 $17 {Black has a development lead, the better minor piece, and a better pawn structure.}) (19. Bd6 Ne3 $1 20. Rd2 {The rook does not have a good place to go.} ({Or} 20. Rh1 Nc4 {hitting the bishop on d6.}) 20... Bg1 $1 21. Bc5 g5 $1 22. Bxe3 g4+ {Black wins back the piece while keeping the development lead. If} 23. Kf4 Rc4+ {wins back the piece with a winning position.}) *

