1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked (kind of, as we shall see), and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance.} ({The most obvious move is} 10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 $6 {is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went 12...Nd7 13.Rfd1 Bxf3?! 14.Bxf3 Rb8 15.e3 $16 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless, 12...Nc6!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. Nbd2 {White develops normally, but again the d4-pawn is loose.} Nxd4 {[%mdl 32768] This is the simplest.} ({A) Here} 11... Nb4 $2 {allows} 12. Qxc7 {.}) ({B) Black has tried} 11... Rc8 {but} 12. Nb3 Nb4 13. Qd1 Be4 14. Ne5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {looks very slightly better for White.}) 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Nxe6 fxe6 ({Note that} 13... Qd5 $2 {does not work here!} 14. Nxc7 Qb7 15. Nxa8 Bxf1 16. Rxf1 {and White will emerge a pawn up.}) 14. Kxg2 c5 {[%csl Ga2,Ga6,Gb2,Gb5,Gc5,Ge6][%cal Gd8d5,Gd8e8,Gd8b6] Black's nice queenside majority compensates for the isolated e-pawn.} *

