1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked (kind of, as we shall see), and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance.} ({The most obvious move is} 10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 $6 {is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went 12...Nd7 13.Rfd1 Bxf3?! 14.Bxf3 Rb8 15.e3 $16 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless, 12...Nc6!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. Nc3 {This develops nicely, but now ...Nb4 can be played immediately because the c7-pawn is not hanging anymore.} Nb4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Here} 11... Nxd4 {is bad because of} 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Rfd1 $1 {with the idea Nxe6.}) 12. Qc1 Rc8 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 13. a3 (13. Rd1 {transposes to the 11.Rd1 line.}) 13... Nbd5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc7c5] Now if Black can play ...c5 he will just be better, so White needs to prevent it.} 14. b4 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga6a5] White has locked down the c5-square, but this advance grants new opportunities for counterplay. An eventual ...a5 will challenge White's queenside structure.} ({Similar play results from} 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. b4 a5 $132 {.}) 14... Nxf4 {Let's take the bishop.} ({Black can also play} 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Nd5 {intending ...a5}) 15. Qxf4 ({White just loses material after} 15. gxf4 $2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qxd4 {.}) 15... Nd5 $146 ({Exchanging with} 15... Bxf3 {is also not bad.} 16. Bxf3 c6 {was Ricardi-Leitao, Buenos Aires 2000. With ...a5 coming, the weakness of the c6- and b4-pawns even out.}) 16. Nxd5 (16. Qd2 a5 $1 {does not change much.}) 16... Bxd5 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gd5f3,Gd5c4,Gd5b7,Gc7c6] Black will play ...a5 in the next couple of moves. The d5-bishop may go to c4, retreat to b7, or perhaps take on f3 as in the example above.} *

