1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked (kind of, as we shall see), and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance.} ({The most obvious move is} 10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 $6 {is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went 12...Nd7 13.Rfd1 Bxf3?! 14.Bxf3 Rb8 15.e3 $16 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless, 12...Nc6!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. Rd1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd1d8] The main move. White protects the d4-pawn and tries to discourage ...c5.} Nb4 $1 12. Qc1 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1] This is the only good square, but if White loses control the queen is not well placed and the a1-rook may have trouble getting into the game.} ({White loses material after} 12. Qxc7 $2 Qxc7 13. Bxc7 Nc2) ({and} 12. Qd2 c5 {is too easy.}) 12... Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c1]} (12... Nbd5 {is also possible, but we may as well wait to see if White wants to spend a tempo kicking us away.}) 13. Nc3 {It is important to shield the c-file.} Nbd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is ready for ...c5. White can only aspire for something if he can hold off this advance.} ({If you want to get off the beaten track,} 13... Qe8 $5 {is an idea, getting off of the d-file to prepare ...c5.}) 14. Be3 {Ulf Andersson tried this a few times, but it's not dangerous, to say the least.} Nxe3 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This obvious move is uncommon, but today's engines show it to be straightforward.} (14... Qd6 {has been played a few times.}) 15. Qxe3 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5] I like this move. There's not stopping ...c5.} (15... c5 {is also fine, but a little more complicated after.} 16. dxc5 Qa5 17. Nd4 Bxg2 {Here} 18. Nb3 Bxc5 $5 {has been seen in a couple of games.} 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Nxa5 Ba8 21. Nb3 Rc7 {and Black is ok.}) ({I still I prefer} 15... Qe8 $1 {which is paradoxically simpler, yet more ambitious.}) 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 c5 {Black is doing great.} 18. d5 {This looks principled but doesn't cause us any problems.} Bd6 ({Taking right away with} 18... exd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Rxd5 Bf6 21. Rad1 c4 $132 {is fine too.}) 19. Nf3 ({Or} 19. dxe6 Qxe6 {.}) 19... exd5 20. Qxe8 Rfxe8 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5 Bf8 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc5][%cal Ge8e2] Black's queenside majority assures him of equal chances.} *

