1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] A very direct move. White simply hits the c7-pawn before Black is ready to play ...c5.} Nc6 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4] This is the theoretical antidote. The knight blocks the advance of the c7-pawn, but the d4-pawn is attacked (kind of, as we shall see), and often ...Nb4 will gain time and free the c-pawn to advance.} ({The most obvious move is} 10... Nd5 {which is considered to be naïve, although I don't believe that it's so bad. After} 11. Nc3 Nxf4 12. gxf4 {White has a nice grip in the center. Note that} c5 $6 {is bad after} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Ng5 {and wins. One very high level game went 12...Nd7 13.Rfd1 Bxf3?! 14.Bxf3 Rb8 15.e3 $16 and White was much better in Kramnik-Svidler, Linares 1998. The move ...b5 looks really out of place here. Nevertheless, 12...Nc6!? looks playable to me. In any case, the main line is quite comfortable for Black, so we don't really need an alternative.}) 11. Rd1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd1d8] The main move. White protects the d4-pawn and tries to discourage ...c5.} Nb4 $1 12. Qc1 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1] This is the only good square, but if White loses control the queen is not well placed and the a1-rook may have trouble getting into the game.} ({White loses material after} 12. Qxc7 $2 Qxc7 13. Bxc7 Nc2) ({and} 12. Qd2 c5 {is too easy.}) 12... Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c1]} (12... Nbd5 {is also possible, but we may as well wait to see if White wants to spend a tempo kicking us away.}) 13. Nc3 {It is important to shield the c-file.} Nbd5 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is ready for ...c5. White can only aspire for something if he can hold off this advance.} ({If you want to get off the beaten track,} 13... Qe8 $5 {is an idea, getting off of the d-file to prepare ...c5.}) 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 15. Be3 {The only move to hold up ...c5.} (15. Ne5 c5 {and}) (15. Bg5 c5 {transpose to 14.Ne5 and 15.Bg5, respectively, while}) (15. Be5 c5 16. dxc5 Rxc5 {with ...Qa6 coming, is comfortable for Black.}) 15... Ng4 ({Black has also had success with} 15... c6 {I guess the idea is to continue with ...Qb6, but I think White is a little more comfortable after} 16. Ne1 {intending Nd3.}) 16. Bg5 $5 {This is a little tricky.} f6 $1 {This looks a little bit ugly, but it gains time so we can reach our goals.} ({After} 16... Bxg5 17. Nxg5 {it becomes difficult to break with ...c5}) ({while} 16... Nf6 {can be met with} 17. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 18. Qc2 {intending e4 with some advantage.}) 17. Be3 c5 {[%mdl 32768]} (17... Nxe3 18. Qxe3 c5 19. dxc5 {amounts to the same thing.}) 18. dxc5 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Bxc5 20. Nd4 e5 {Now the play is forced.} 21. Bxd5+ Qxd5 22. Qb3 {The only move to save the piece.} Qxb3 23. Nxb3 Be7 {[%cal Gg8f7,Gf7e6,Gf8d8,Gc8c2,Gd1d7] This is equal, but there is still scope to outplay the opponent.} *

