1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5]} ({This is by far the most popular move, with well over 3000 games in my (filtered) database, compared to under 1000 for both} 10. Bg5 {and . I must say though, as a Catalan player myself, I never really cared for this line (I always preferred 8.a4 to 8.Qxc4). The Big Idea is to play the bishop to a5 to both attack and pin the c7-pawn, but I always found this to be rather artificial looking. Also, at least compared to}) (10. Bg5 {and}) (10. Bf4 {, Black has a great many choices here, and I think most of them are quite playable! We will focus on a modern solution, but one good thing about classical openings for Black is that it is easy to expand your lines, whether it be because of some small theoretical problem, or simply for variety's sake.}) 10... Be4 {This is the main move, but we will have a little twist. Here is a brief summary of some other lines:} (10... Nbd7 {is the only move I really do not like, as it really plays into White's hands.} 11. Ba5 Rc8 12. Nbd2 {with Nb3 in mind.}) (10... Nc6 11. e3 Nb4 12. Bxb4 Bxb4 13. a3 Bd6 14. Nbd2 {and White has both the e4- and b4-advances in hand.}) (10... Bd6 $5 {was Hammer's recommendation in his Chess24 course. This is a decent line, but White has about six different moves here to analyze, with different types of play...}) (10... Ra7 $5 {is a funny move, and this would be my second choice. The rook laterally supports the c7-pawn and there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Nc3 {This is the obvious looking move, but it does lose a pawn.} Bxf3 {This is a position where we should grab the pawn. There will be cases where we should not be greedy.} (12... Bd5 {is possible, but Black always has to be on the lookout for e4 and consider always Nxd5. After} 13. a4 {White keeps some pressure.}) (12... Bg6 {is similarly possible, but} 13. Ne5 $1 Qxd4 14. Bf4 {with the idea Rd1 gives White plenty of compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 {[%cal Gd4d8,Gd4b6]} 14. Be3 Qd8 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Rd1 Nbd7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} ({This is simple and solid. Various queen moves are fine too. Black could also play} 15... Nd5 {which should probably be met with} 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Bf4 {with the idea e4. Black remains up a pawn, but he will have to be careful.}) 16. Bxc6 {White should take while he still can.} Rc8 {[%cal Gb5b4] Now White really should give up the bishop pair.} 17. Bb7 $2 {This is bad, but we have to know why.} ({Better was} 17. Bxd7 Nxd7 {.}) 17... Rc7 18. Bb6 {In for a penny...} ({Instead} 18. Bxa6 b4 {loses a piece.}) 18... Nxb6 $1 {Forced, but strong.} 19. Rxd8 Bxd8 $17 {[%cal Gc7b7,Gb5b4] Black has only a rook and a knight for the queen, but he is winning back more material with the threats of ...Rxc7 and ...b4.} ({More natural is} 19... Rxd8 {but then White has the resource} 20. Bf3 b4 21. Qf4 $1 {hitting our rook. If} Rc4 22. Ne4 {White saves everything.}) 20. Bf3 $2 ({White is better off conceding the piece with} 20. Bxa6 b4 $17 {.}) 20... b4 21. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3b6] White hits the one loose piece, but:} Nc4 {[%cal Gc4e3,Gb4c3] Black gains back the tempo and wins material.} *

