there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Nc3 {This is the obvious looking move, but it does lose a pawn. Black should often consider ways to return the material, rather than desperately holding onto it.} Bxf3 {This is a position where we should grab the pawn. There will be cases where we should not be greedy.} (12... Bd5 {is possible, but Black always has to be on the lookout for e4 and consider always Nxd5. After} 13. a4 {White keeps some pressure.}) (12... Bg6 {is similarly possible, but} 13. Ne5 $1 Qxd4 14. Bf4 {with the idea Rd1 gives White plenty of compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {This is another way to play for compensation.} Qd8 $1 {Safest.} 15. a4 {[%cal Ga1a8,Gf3a8] The best try, as White has pressure on the a-file and long diagonal.} b4 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Ne4 {[%csl Rc5] In typical Catalan fashion, White tries to bear down on the c5-square.} Nd5 {Closing things up a bit.} 17. Bc5 Nd7 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc6c5]} ({I prefer this simple solution to} 18... Nxe7 19. Nc5 {but this is probably fine too:} Nxc5 20. Qxc5 a5 {and Black should be fine if he does not worry too much about this (extra) c-pawn.}) 19. Qxc6 {Or else White will just stay down a pawn.} Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5c6,Ge5f3] This trades off White's Catalan bishop. Black is fine.} *

