there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Bg5 {[%cal Bg5f6] The bishop is not getting to a5 now, so White reverts to a Bg5xf6 plan. This hardly threatens Black's concept though.} Nbd7 $146 {[%mdl 32768]} ({In practice Black grabbed the pawn with} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 {. This is probably fine too, although White maintains some pressure after} 14. a4 {.}) 13. Nbd2 (13. Rd1 {would transpose to 12.Rd1.}) 13... Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6c5,Ga8c8] As long as e2-e4 is not a threat, this is usually a good way of meeting Nb1-d2. With the knight on c3, it may take our bishop!} 14. Re1 {[%cal Ye2e4,Yc6c5] This has to be checked, but we are fast enough.} c5 $1 15. e4 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Re4][%cal Ga8c8,Ge4e5,Gf6d5,Gc8c1] Black has a very harmonious position.} *

