there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Bg5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gg5f6] With Ba5 prevented, White reverts to a Bg5 setup, where the thematic Bxf6 is always a possibility.} Nbd7 $146 ({In practice Black grabbed the pawn with} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 {. This is probably fine too, although White maintains some pressure after} 14. a4 {.}) 13. Nbd2 (13. Rd1 {would transpose to 12.Rd1.}) 13... Bd5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6c5,Ga8c8] As long as e2-e4 is not a threat, this is usually a good way of meeting Nb1-d2. With the knight on c3, it may take our bishop!} 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nb3 {This is consistent at least. We are not getting in ...c5 yet, but there is another typical way to react.} a5 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5a4,Gd5f3,Gd8d4,Ra2a4,Gb3c5][%mdl 32768] White cannot play a4 himself, so we get ready to torment the knight. Right now the threat is ...a4, and if Nc5 we can take on f3 and d4.} 16. Rd1 a4 17. Nc5 Ne4 {Not the only move, but the play is clear.} 18. Nd3 {White tries to keep control of the important squares.} ({Instead} 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 {is easy enough. Black will follow up with ...Qd5 and achieve the ...c5-break easily.}) 18... Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 19. Qe3 (19. a3 $2 {is too slow after} c5 $17 {with the initiative.}) 19... a3 $1 {A nice move which disrupts White's position. Play is unclear, but Black has the initiative.} ({Note that} 19... c5 {is not good:} 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21. Nf4 $16 {and the pin is quite annoying.}) 20. b4 ({This looks the most logical. If instead} 20. b3 $2 Nc3 $1 {and the knight, which can be supported with ...b4, is a monster.}) 20... Nc3 21. Rd2 ({Similar, but worse for White, is} 21. Re1 Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Bg5 23. Nf4 Nd5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 25. Qxa3 Bxf4 26. gxf4 Qf6 27. Qe3 Rc4) 21... Bxf3 $1 22. Bxf3 Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re3] Suddenly White's queen is feeling some heat!} 23. Nf4 Nd5 24. Bxd5 cxd5 {[%cal Yc8c1,Yg5d2] Black has all the positional trumps, so White grabs a pawn.} 25. Qxa3 Bxf4 26. gxf4 Rc4 {[%csl Rb4,Rd4,Rf4,Rg1][%cal Gd8f6] White has so many weak pawns that Black can hardly have any problems here.} *

