there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. a4 {This is a serious move, typical of the Catalan.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768] Let's develop.} ({This is certainly not a position where Black can grab the pawn.} 12... Bxf3 $2 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. axb5 {with pins everywhere.}) ({I would also avoid} 12... b4 {for reasons given in the Informational line.}) 13. Nc3 {White should maintain the tension.} ({After} 13. axb5 {both recaptures are fine. I like to capture towards the center myself, so let's say} axb5 {.}) 13... Bg6 {[%cal Ga8c8] With the knight on c3 I prefer this retreat. If ( 13...Bd5 14.Qc2 and the d5-bishop is uncomfortable.} 14. Ne5 {This move is always tempting, but it's usually too direct as the change in pawn structure is comfortable for Black.} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd8b8,Gf8d8,Gf8c8] Now neutral moves could be met with ...Qb8!? hitting the e5-pawn.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 {[%csl Gg6]} 19. Qc7 {White's mini-initiative will dry up quickly.} Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Ge8c8] Black wants to secure his e7-bishop and then look to the c-file, so White prevents this. The first high-level game with 11...c6 continued} 20. Z0 (20. Rc1 b4 {This gains some space and introduces the possibility of ...b3 and ...Bc2.} 21. Bf3 h6 {Luft.} 22. Kg2 b3 {This secures the c2-square for the g6-bishop. Black was fine in Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and he even developed a slight initiative later.}) *

