there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Be3 {This is similar to 12.Be3.} Rc8 14. Nc3 Bg6 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gb5b4,Gc6c5]} (14... Bd5 {is possible, especially with no e2-e4 on the horizon, but I prefer the 'Slav' retreat.}) 15. Ne5 {As usual, I am not worried about this move.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd5 17. a4 {This was played in Dominguez Perez-Kryvoruchko, Monzon 2016.} b4 $1 18. Ne4 c5 $1 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc5c4,Gg6e4,Gd5e3] Black is active and has his queenside pawn majority.} *

