1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5]} ({This is by far the most popular move, with well over 3000 games in my (filtered) database, compared to under 1000 for both} 10. Bg5 {and . I must say though, as a Catalan player myself, I never really cared for this line (I always preferred 8.a4 to 8.Qxc4). The Big Idea is to play the bishop to a5 to both attack and pin the c7-pawn, but I always found this to be rather artificial looking. Also, at least compared to}) (10. Bg5 {and}) (10. Bf4 {, Black has a great many choices here, and I think most of them are quite playable! We will focus on a modern solution, but one good thing about classical openings for Black is that it is easy to expand your lines, whether it be because of some small theoretical problem, or simply for variety's sake.}) 10... Be4 {This is the main move, but we will have a little twist. Here is a brief summary of some other lines:} (10... Nbd7 {is the only move I really do not like, as it really plays into White's hands.} 11. Ba5 Rc8 12. Nbd2 {with Nb3 in mind.}) (10... Nc6 11. e3 Nb4 12. Bxb4 Bxb4 13. a3 Bd6 14. Nbd2 {and White has both the e4- and b4-advances in hand.}) (10... Bd6 $5 {was Hammer's recommendation in his Chess24 course. This is a decent line, but White has about six different moves here to analyze, with different types of play...}) (10... Ra7 $5 {is a funny move, and this would be my second choice. The rook laterally supports the c7-pawn and there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Be3 {This is similar to 12.Be3.} Rc8 14. Nc3 Bg6 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Gf6d5,Gb5b4,Gc6c5,Ye4g6]} ({Following the usual script, but} 14... Bd5 {looks playable here too.}) 15. Ne5 {This is a bit safer than it usually is, but I almost always welcome this change in the pawn structure.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd5 17. Ne4 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6]} Bxe4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] The recurring idea.} 18. Bxe4 Qc7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc7e5,Gd5e3,Gc6c5] We unpin, tickle the e-pawn, and prepare the advance of the c-pawn.} 19. f4 (19. Bf4 Nxf4 20. Qxf4 c5 $15 {is similarly pleasant for Black.}) 19... Nxe3 20. Qxe3 c5 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc5][%cal Gc5c4,Ge7c5] My computer says it's equal, but I much prefer Black as his play is so straightforward on the queenside.} *

