there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] This makes room for the knight, and reintroduces the old Bg5xf6 plan, hoping to weaken our control of the c5-square.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5][%mdl 32768]} 14. Nbd2 Bd5 15. Nb3 $6 (15. Nb3 Qc7 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Rfd8 18. b4 {maybe 18.Rxd8+ Rxd8 19.a4 is a better try, but not too scary Rxd1+ Qxd1} a5 19. a3 {Rd8 Qe1} Be4 {Shankland-Radjabov, Wijk aan Zee 2019. Now White should take on f6 .}) {White cannot 'finesse' the move order.} 15... c5 $1 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 $1 {[%cal Gf6a1] Taking advantage of White's lapse.} 17. dxc5 (17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. dxc5 Qe7 {is similar, but White will lack the coming resource.}) 17... Qe7 {[%cal Gd7c5] Now Black is poised to win back the pawn with a nice advantage. White's best chance is to mix things up with an exchange sacrifice.} 18. Rxd5 $5 exd5 19. Bh3 Rxc5 $1 (19... Rc7 {is also feasible, but} 20. Bxd7 Qxd7 21. Nbd4 {with a strong c-pawn, would give White unnecessary chances.}) 20. Nxc5 Nxc5 {[%cal Ge7e2,Gc5a4,Gf6b2,Gf8e8] Black has an isolated pawn, but his pieces are very active and White is still a couple of moves away from getting his heavy pieces into play.} *

