there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Nc3 {Straightforward play.} Bg6 {[%mdl 32768] By now we have seen that this is often Black's best move.} ({Avrukh only considered} 13... Bd5 14. Qc2 b4 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {and here he gave} 16. Bf4 $14 {I am more discouraged by 16.Rdc1 $14 although in either case, Black remains quite solid and White only has a small edge.}) 14. Nh4 {Back when Gustafsson did his Chess24 course, this was the only move considered, but now it's is uncommon.} Bh5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gb5b4] Once again we can ignore the attack on the c6-pawn.} 15. a3 ({White gets in trouble after} 15. Bxc6 $2 Rc8 {with huge problems on the c-file.} 16. Bxd7 {does not help, as after} Nxd7 {, ...b4 remains a threat, as does ...Bxh4.}) ({White does not have time for} 15. Re1 $2 {guarding the e2-pawn, as after} Rc8 $17 {the ...c5 advance will come next, with great effect.}) 15... Rc8 {Now White is just in time...} 16. b4 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5] This holds down both of our pawn breaks on the queenside, for now at least.} Nd5 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge7h4,Gd5c3] We are threatening to trade on c3 and snatch the e2-pawn, while also hitting the knight on h4.} ({Note that we cannot play} 16... a5 $6 17. bxa5 Qxa5 $2 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Bb4 {winning material.}) 17. Nf3 ({We would meet} 17. Bf3 {in a similar way:} Bxf3 18. Nxf3 f5 {.}) 17... f5 $5 {[%cal Ge7d6,Ge7f6,Gd7b6,Gb6c4] The position is unclear. With ...c5 and ...a5 on hold, we can play for ...e5. Bringing a knight to c4 is another good idea - it's a nice outpost and it would support the ...a5 break.} *

