there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Nc3 Bg6 {By now we have seen that this is often Black's best move.} ({Avrukh only considered} 13... Bd5 14. Qc2 b4 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {and here he gave} 16. Bf4 $14 {I am more discouraged by 16.Rdc1 $14 although in either case, Black remains quite solid and White only has a small edge.}) 14. Bf4 {This is an active looking move, but there's not a dangerous followup.} Rc8 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd8b6,Gc6c5][%mdl 32768] Black will play ...Qb6 and ...c5 is undisturbed. And ...Nd5 is always a possibility to consider.} ({Note that the immediate} 14... Nd5 {is not good because of} 15. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 16. Qc6 $16 {and White will dominate the c-file.}) 15. Ne5 {At this point White needs to play this to avoid being worse.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 ({Perhaps} 16. Bxe5 {is safer, but after} Qb6 {Black will fight for the initiative with ...Rfd8 and ...c5. White's queen is misplaced.}) 16... Nd5 {This is similar to other positions.} 17. e4 $6 {This does not work out, despite the pin.} b4 $5 ({There is nothing wrong with the typical trick} 17... Nxc3 18. Qxc3 {if 18.Rxd8 Ne2+ 19.Kf1 Nxc1 20.Rxc8 Rxc8 21.Rxc1 c5 would be at least ok for Black.} Qc7 {when White's only move to hold the balance is the rather annoying} 19. Rd6 $5 {, but White is active here, so I prefer 17...b4!?}) 18. Nxd5 ({Black wins back the piece immediately after} 18. exd5 cxd5 $17) 18... cxd5 {The pressure on the d5-pawn looks like trouble, but White does not have a good square for his queen.} 19. Qe3 $6 (19. Qb1 $2 {walks into a pin from the g6-bishop.} Rc4 {steps up the pressure.}) (19. Qd2 {may be best, but Black is certainly ok after} Bxe4 {.}) 19... Bh5 $1 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh5d1] An important move! Black attacks the rook and suddenly threatens ...g5, trapping White's bishop. I cannot even find equality for White here.} *

