there are ideas like ...Qa8, ...Nbd7, ...Be4, and finally ...c5. Anand played this move quite a bit. There is a lot of subtle maneuvering with} 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 14. Qd1 {going on.}) 11. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc7c5] White has to keep an eye on the c5-square.} c6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc6c5,Ye4f3,Yd8d4] This unusual move happens to be the engine's top choice! It was quickly dismissed by Avrukh in his classic Catalan repertoire book for White, but he almost cryptically pointed out that he could be wrong! This little move first got serious attention in the game Giri-Kramnik, London 2014, and it was also featured in Jan Gustafsson's Chess24 course. The engine also considers 11... Nc6, as well as the unusual 11...Bd5, and even 11...h6 as 'equal' before even getting to the natural looking 11...Nbd7.} ({And then there's the most popular move} 11... Bb7 $5 {This line is fine, I think, but for starters White can repeat moves with} 12. Qc2 {.}) 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is a very natural move, as it's almost always useful to have some influence on the d-file. Moving the rook also avoids any ...Bd5-c4 attacks, so the e4 advance becomes more plausible.} Nbd7 ({Grabbing the pawn makes little sense here.} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 14. Be3 {with great compensation, as the black queen does not have a great square to go to and a2-a4 is coming.}) 13. Nc3 Bg6 {By now we have seen that this is often Black's best move.} ({Avrukh only considered} 13... Bd5 14. Qc2 b4 15. Nxd5 cxd5 {and here he gave} 16. Bf4 $14 {I am more discouraged by 16.Rdc1 $14 although in either case, Black remains quite solid and White only has a small edge.}) 14. a3 $5 {A clever move.} Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5][%mdl 32768]} ({Do not play} 14... c5 $2 {I made this big mistake in a blitz game, but I don't feel too badly as both Hammer and Harikrishna played it in serious tournament games!} 15. Be3 $1 {Black is not ready for the position to open up.} Rc8 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Ne5 $16 {the knight is heading to c6. Black is in big trouble.}) (14... Qb6 {is a playable alternative though.}) 15. b4 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gg6b1] This is a rare position where White achieves this advance when we are not well placed to play ...a5. White's queenside remains a bit contorted however, while Black's position looks pretty normal (although more like a Slav!).} (15. Nh4 {can be met with} Bh5 {as usual.}) 15... Nd5 {[%cal Ge7f6,Ge6e5,Gd7b6,Gd5b6,Gb6c4,Ga6a5,Gh7h6,Gf8e8]} ({Black has to change it up a little, as} 15... a5 $2 {does not work here. I discovered this in another blitz mishap. After} 16. bxa5 $1 {Black is not getting the pawn back. If} Qxa5 $2 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7 19. Bb4 {wins for White. So what is happening here? We cannot get in ...c5. We cannot get in ...a5. White cannot play e4 so easily though, and White's queenside play has left some soft spots, notably the c4-square. We can access this point easily with a knight via b6. Black could play for ...e5 at some point. This is unusual, but things have changed - for example our bishop is on g6, not buried on b7! White will still have to keep an eye out for ...a5 as well. There have not been many games here, but Black has scored over 50%, so that is encouraging.}) *

