1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... h6 {There was a time when I favored this direct move. There are a couple of little annoyances, but it still looks playable if you want to have a bit of a shortcut in hand.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rd1 ({More popular is} 12. Nc3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 {Now if Black heads for a common structure with} c6 14. e3 a5 {White can take advantage of his queen's active position with} 15. b4 $1 axb4 16. Qxb4 $14 {which is known to favor White slightly, as he keeps some pressure on Black's queenside. There is also the rare 13...Qxd4!? which, incidentally, is what Naranayan wanted to avoid for White in his Catalan course. After 14.Qxc7 Nc6 15.Qxb7 Na5 16.Qc7 Qd8 17.Qf4 Rb8 Black had compensation for the pawn in Mamedyarov-Wei Yi, Wijk aan Zee 2018. Still, Black is just trying to hold here, and in the game he did not manage to do so.}) 12... a5 13. Nc3 Bd5 (13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 15. b4 $14 {is like 13...c6 in the line given above.}) 14. Qd3 ({Note that} 14. Nxd5 $5 exd5 15. Qb3 {is also slightly annoying.}) 14... Bxf3 {Otherwise e2-e4 will come.} 15. Bxf3 c6 16. e3 {[%cal Yh2h4,Ya1c1] This is the line given by Narayanan.} ({White played the immediate} 16. h4 {and got some pressure in Papaioannou-Kasimdzhanov, Batumi 2018, although Black held.}) 16... Na6 {[%csl Gd1,Gd3][%cal Gf1d1] We have the typical structure. It seems like White is up a move or two as his queen and rook are already well placed, although ...Nb4 will gain a tempo.} 17. h4 $14 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gd3c4,Gd3e2] White has a slightly improved version of a typical kind of position we will see a lot of. So it's a slight edge, but still playable for Black.} *

