1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qc2 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... Be4 {The c2-square is a good spot for White's queen so we continue the chase.} 12. Qc1 {White's main choice. The queen is safe here and the d1-square is open for White's rook.} h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Now it's a choice where White wants to bring his queen's knight.} 14. Nbd2 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 {This is not usually an ideal square for the knight, but White has a specific idea in mind.} a5 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Qc3 $5 {[%cal Ga1d1,Ge2e4] This is the point. White wants to bring everything to the center before Black is properly organized.} ({Instead} 16. Rd1 {reaches a line covered under 14.Rd1. [/variation/22775242/#/14/w]}) ({While} 16. e3 {can just be met with the typical} c6 {or 16...Na6 first.}) 16... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4] The right route to the b4-square.} ({Clearly Black cannot play} 16... Na6 $2 17. Qxa5 $16) ({If} 16... c6 17. b4 $5 axb4 18. Qxb4 {is an idea we've come across. While not fatal, White does keep some pressure on our queenside.}) 17. Rad1 Nb4 18. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2b7]} c6 19. e4 {So White has aggressively gone for e4 instead of the more modest e3. This position has been seen a couple times in practice.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] A new idea, in typical Grunfeld style! Yes, I know that this is not a Grunfeld, but we do have that unopposed f6-bishop.} ({After} 19... Rc8 20. Ng4 {White developed pressure in the center in Adams-Harikrishna, Shenzhen 2017.}) ({Trading pieces with} 19... Bxe5 {is solid, but White's play certainly looked easier after} 20. dxe5 Qb6 21. Rd6 Na6 22. Rfd1 {in Giri-So, Nations Cup 2020.}) 20. dxc5 $2 Qc7 $17 {The pin is painful for White.} 21. f4 ({If} 21. Rd6 Na6 $1 {followed by taking on c5.}) 21... Rad8 {[%csl Re5,Rg2][%cal Gb4c6] Black will eventually take on e5 and can regain the pawn with ...Nc6. White's Catalan bishop has seen better days.} *

