tion/22775242/#/14/w]}) ({While} 16. e3 {can just be met with the typical} c6 {or 16...Na6 first.}) 16... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4] The right route to the b4-square.} ({Clearly Black cannot play} 16... Na6 $2 17. Qxa5 $16) ({If} 16... c6 17. b4 $5 axb4 18. Qxb4 {is an idea we've come across. While not fatal, White does keep some pressure on our queenside.}) 17. Rad1 Nb4 18. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2b7]} c6 19. e4 {So White has aggressively gone for e4 instead of the more modest e3. This position has been seen a couple times in practice.} c5 $1 {[%csl Gf6] A new idea, in typical Grunfeld style! Yes, I know that this is not a Grunfeld, but we do have that unopposed f6-bishop.} ({After} 19... Rc8 20. Ng4 {White developed pressure in the center in Adams-Harikrishna, Shenzhen 2017.}) ({Trading pieces with} 19... Bxe5 {is solid, but White's play certainly looked easier after} 20. dxe5 Qb6 21. Rd6 Na6 22. Rfd1 {in Giri-So, Nations Cup 2020.}) 20. d5 {This looks quite loosening, and indeed it can be exploited.} exd5 {[%mdl 32768]} 21. exd5 c4 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gb4d3,Gf6c3] A far from obvious move! The black knight will come to d3. White must be careful not to fall apart.} *

