 16...Nc6?! 17.Ne1! however.} ({We do not have any tricks after} 16... Bxd4 $2 17. Ne4 {with e3 next.}) ({or} 16... Qxd4 17. Ne4 {and our queenside will disintegrate. White has tried various things here.}) 17. Nc4 {The most popular move.} ({If} 17. Nb3 {The knight covers the c5-square here, but it does not do much else.} Na6 18. h4 {and Black can play} Qb6 {or 18...Nb4} 19. Qc4 Rfd8 20. Rd2 Qb4 $1 {White cannot really avoid the exchange of queens as the d4-pawn is under fire. The game Markus-Wojtaszek, Skopje 2015 was soon drawn.}) 17... Na6 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga6b4,Gd8c7][%mdl 32768]} ({Here} 17... Bxd4 $2 {does not work because of} 18. Qf4 $1 {if 18.e3? Qf6! does work for us} e5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 $16) 18. Qf4 ({After} 18. e4 $6 Bxd4 {is a good pawn grab. We can support the bishop with ... c5.}) ({If} 18. e3 {we have this} g6 $5 {idea again, intending to meet} 19. h4 {with} h5) 18... Nb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4d5]} 19. e3 Nd5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gg7g6] Black is fine here, as has been shown in practice. See the game Thybo-Leko, Porto Carras 2018.} *

