1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) {This retreat leads to a totally different kind of game. White's queen is more active here, but it is also a bit exposed, so the play can become quite sharp.} 11... c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. dxc5 {This has been played a lot but it is quite harmless.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5] We want to take on c5 with the knight.} 13. Nc3 (13. b4 $6 {is not a good idea. White's structure is unstable, and this is easily exploited with} a5 $15 {when Black easily regains the pawn while taking over the initiative.}) 13... Nxc5 14. Qe3 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ge3c5] Other moves do not make much sense, especially with the potential fork on b3. Now the positional threat of Bxf6 is easy enough to deal with.} Qa5 {[%cal Gd5c6] This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives.} ({The natural} 14... Rc8 {also looks fine.} 15. Rfd1 {or 15.Nxd5 Nxd5 16.Bxe7 Qxe7 17.Qa3 a5=} h6 {when Black does not have to fear the isolated pawn after} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxd5 exd5 {This is similar to 15.Bxf6.}) ({Even the rare} 14... Bxf3 $5 15. Bxf3 Qa5 {is very solid. White has the bishop pair, but Black's minor pieces are all good.}) 15. Qf4 {[%cal Gb2b4] White threatens b4, hoping that we do not notice.} Bxf3 $146 {We give White the bishop pair, but only temporarily.} ({In practice Black has favored} 15... Nb3 {but after} 16. Bxf6 $5 {instead of the more common 16.Rad1 Bc6=} Bxf6 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rad1 {looks a bit more pleasant for White.}) 16. Bxf3 ({Instead} 16. Qxf3 Nb3 {hits both the rook and the g5-bishop, and forces} 17. Bxf6 {anyway.}) 16... Nb3 17. Rad1 h6 {[%csl Rg5] White must concede the bishop pair.} 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 {The structure is symmetrical and it's totally equal. White must avoid pawn grabbing.} 19. Bxb7 $6 Rab8 {[%cal Gb8b2,Gf6g5,Gb8b4,Gb3d4,Gb3d2] Black has a strong initiative.} 20. Bg2 (20. Qf3 Nd4 21. Qg2 Qb6 {would recover the pawn while maintaining some pressure.}) 20... Bg5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Re4,Rf3][%cal Gb3d2] It's not so easy to find a square for the queen that does not lose material!} 21. Qg4 Rb4 {White's position is surprisingly difficult.} 22. Qh3 {White avoids potentially weakening pawn moves, but the queen looks silly here.} ({Instead} 22. e4 Bf6 {intending ...Nd4 or ...Nc5 is great for Black. White's whole queenside is a target.}) ({If} 22. f4 Bf6 {and Black similarly has great play.}) 22... Nd2 $1 23. Rfe1 Nc4 {[%csl Rb2]} 24. Ne4 Be7 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2,Rh3] Black is winning back the pawn and keeping his positional advantages.} *

