e on c5 with the knight.} 13. Nc3 (13. b4 $6 {is not a good idea. White's structure is unstable, and this is easily exploited with} a5 $15 {when Black easily regains the pawn while taking over the initiative.}) 13... Nxc5 14. Qe3 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ge3c5] Now the positional threat of Bxf6 is easy enough to deal with.} Qa5 {[%cal Gd5c6] This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives.} ({The natural} 14... Rc8 {also looks fine.} 15. Rfd1 {or 15.Nxd5 Nxd5 16.Bxe7 Qxe7 17.Qa3 a5=} h6 {when Black does not have to fear the isolated pawn after} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxd5 exd5 {This is similar to 15.Bxf6.}) ({Even the rare} 14... Bxf3 $5 15. Bxf3 Qa5 {is very solid. White has the bishop pair, but Black's minor pieces are all good.}) 15. Bxf6 {This is uncommon, but it has been tried a couple of times by Karpov.} Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Nxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gf6b2,Gc5e4,Ga5b4] We have an isolated pawn, but our pieces are very active.} 17. Qa3 Ne4 ({Instead} 17... Qb6 {was played in Karpov-Milos, Buenos Aires 2000. This is probably ok too but I prefer Gelfand's move.}) 18. Rad1 Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c2,Gc8c4] A mini-improvement. Black has enough counterplay - in fact I think his play is easier.} (18... Rfd8 {led to a quick draw in Karpov-Gelfand, Monte Carlo 2001.}) 19. Nd4 {[%csl Gc2]} Rc4 {[%cal Gc4d4,Gc4a4]} 20. Nb3 Qxa4 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3][%cal Gc4b4,Gf6b2] White's queenside is under some pressure, so Black is at least equal.} *

