1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. Nc3 Bc6 ({During Karpov's legendary Linares tournament victory he faced} 12... cxd4 {and got an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. dxc5 {This is not exactly a free pawn.} ({Instead} 14. Ne4 Bxd4 {just leads to simplifications and easy equality;}) ({while} 14. Rfd1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 {would bring us to the 14.Rfd1 line.}) 14... Nd7 15. Qc4 {This is the only move we have to really analyze, as the alternatives are simple.} ({If} 15. b4 Nxc5 $1 {and the c3-knight is loose.}) ({and} 15. Ne4 Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nxc5 {is very easy for Black.}) 15... Qe7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Ga6a5]} (15... Rc8 {looks fine too, with similar ideas.}) 16. b4 {Again, this the only move to force us to find a solution.} (16. Ne4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Nxc5 {is like 15.Ne4 above.}) 16... a5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5] This thematic move breaks up White's pawns and gives us an easy game.} 17. b5 $2 {This actually leads to a bad position for White.} Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Rac8 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4,Rc5][%cal Gc8c5] This is much stronger than simply recapturing the pawn. Everything is vulnerable on the c-file.} 19. c6 {What else?} bxc6 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 20. Bxc6 ({White has all kinds of problems after} 20. bxc6 Ne5 21. Qe4 {if 21.Qb5 Nxf3+ 22.exf3 Bxc3 is a piece.} Rxc6 {with a strong initiative.}) 20... Ne5 21. Qb3 Nxc6 22. bxc6 {Now taking on c6 is good, but there's even better!} Qb4 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rc3,Gf6][%cal Gf6a1]} 23. Ra3 {Forced.} Rxc6 24. Nb5 Qxb3 25. Rxb3 Rd8 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Gc6,Gd8,Gf6][%cal Gc6c4] Black is dominating.} *

