1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. Nc3 Bc6 ({During Karpov's legendary Linares tournament victory he faced} 12... cxd4 {and got an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. dxc5 {White allows his pawns to be broken up, but there is a specific idea in mind. Fortunately it's easy to neutralize.} Qxd3 {[%mdl 32768] I find this to be the most straightforward.} (13... Nbd7 $6 {does not work here} 14. b4 $1 a5 15. b5 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nxc5 17. Rfd1 {and White has a lot of pressure. If} Qb6 18. Be3) (13... Bxc5 {is a valid move though.} 14. Qc4 {or 14.Ne5 Bxg2 15.Kxg2 Qd4!?} Nbd7 15. b4 Be7 16. b5 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Ne5 {Anastasian-Nielsen, Istanbul 2003.}) 14. exd3 Bxc5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5] White hopes to play d5, when it will be Black with the bad pawn structure.} Bxf3 {Gustafsson's recommendation. The game Lalic-Eggleston, England 2014 was drawn here.} 17. dxc5 ({Black is quite ok after} 17. Bxf3 Bxd4 18. Bxb7 Ra7 $132 {with ...Nd7 and ...Rb8 coming. We've seen this kind of plan before.}) 17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 f5 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc3e4,Gf8c8] To stop any Ne4-d6 ideas.} 19. b4 Rc8 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5][%cal Ga6a5] Gustafsson goes this far, pointing out that with the threat of ...a5, Black is fine.} 20. a5 Nc6 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7,Gc8d8,Gc8c7] Black has no problems at all.} *

