an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga5g5,Gc5d4][%mdl 32768] The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} (13... cxd4 {is solid, and we will consider this as an alternative.}) 14. e4 $6 {Like 13.e4?!, this just does not fit with White's setup, which is based more on piece play than pawn advances.} cxd4 {[%cal Ga5g5]} 15. Qxd4 Bc5 16. Qc4 {Other queen moves could be met in the same way.} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc5f2,Gg4f2]} 17. Rf1 (17. Rd2 {may look more 'positive', but} Nd7 18. h3 Nge5 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Qe2 {is nice for Black after various moves,} Bb4 {being one of them.}) 17... Nd7 {[%csl Rb4,Rc4][%cal Gg4e5,Gd7e5,Gh7h6,Ga8c8,Gf8d8] Black is very comfortable, and his position is easy to play.} *

