1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. Nc3 Bc6 ({During Karpov's legendary Linares tournament victory he faced} 12... cxd4 {and got an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga5g5,Gc5d4] The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} 14. Qc4 {This is odd-looking, but it's a serious move.} cxd4 {[%cal Ga5g5,Gc6f3][%mdl 32768] A straightforward approach.} ({Instead} 14... Nbd7 {is also fine, but the critical line} 15. Ne5 $1 cxd4 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Ne4 Ne5 $1 {is rather complicated.}) 15. Bxf6 {A necessary exchange as the bishop was vulnerable.} Bxf6 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 (16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 {would transpose.}) 17. Rxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Nc6 19. Rd7 {It looks like White has his Catalan 'mini-edge' but we can neutralize any pressure with our next accurate move.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gc6a5,Gf8d8,Gb6b2,Gc6e5]} ({Not} 19... Ne5 20. Qc7 $16 {Now ...Ne5 is actually threatened, while ...Qxb2 and ...Na5 are also ideas.}) *

