an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga5g5,Gc5d4] The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} 14. Ne5 {Very direct.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 $5 {This is a natural enough move, although the play will become surprisingly complex.} ({Instead} 16... h6 {may be simpler, but it's less interesting.} 17. Bf4 {or 17.Bxf6 Bxf6 18.Qe4 Qc7} Nc6 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Qc4 c5 {has seen all draws.}) 17. b4 $5 {This does not have to be feared, but we need to know what to do.} Qc7 {[%mdl 32768]} (17... Rxd4 18. bxa5 Rb4 {also looks viable.}) 18. Qc4 Qxc4 ({We cannot take the piece here:} 18... Qxe5 $2 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 20. Bf4 {and Qc8 is going to hurt.}) 19. Rxd8+ (19. Nxc4 Nbd7 {with ... Rac8 coming does not look dangerous either.}) 19... Bxd8 20. Nxc4 Nbd7 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gh7h6,Gd8e7] Everything is under control.} *

