an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} Qa5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga5g5,Gc5d4] The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} 14. Ne5 {Very direct.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 $5 {This is a natural enough move, although the play will become surprisingly complex.} ({Instead} 16... h6 {may be simpler, but it's less interesting.} 17. Bf4 {or 17.Bxf6 Bxf6 18.Qe4 Qc7} Nc6 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Qc4 c5 {has seen all draws.}) 17. Qc4 $5 {[%csl Rb8] A piece sacrifice. We must take, as there is not a good way to develop now.} Qxe5 18. Rxd8+ Bxd8 19. Bf4 ({A necessity. The immediate} 19. Qc8 $2 Qc7 {just leaves us a piece up.}) 19... Qa5 20. Qc8 {[%cal Gc8g8,Gc8a8] This is the point of White's play. The queen ties down everything on our first rank.} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6c6] Threatening ...Qc6+} 21. f3 $1 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8][%cal Ga1d1] Now Rd1 is a huge threat.} e5 $5 {Various analysts have considered this to be bad, but it's not clear at all.} ({Black can also play} 21... g5 22. a5 $1 Nc6 $1 23. Qxa8 Qxb2 {as in the game Leko-Karjakin, Dortmund 2012.}) 22. Bxe5 Nc6 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 23. Qxa8 Nxe5 24. Rd1 Nc6 {[%cal Gg7g6] Black is ready to consolidate with ...g6.} ({The defenses are stretched too thin after} 24... Ned7 $2 25. Rxd7 Nxd7 26. Nd5 Qa5 27. b4 $1) 25. b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5] White must keep some momentum going.} g6 $1 ({Anyway. We must avoid} 25... Qxb4 {when} 26. Rxd8+ Nxd8 27. Qxd8+ Qf8 28. Qc7 {is highly unpleasant.}) 26. b5 axb5 27. axb5 Nd4 {[%cal Gd4e6]} 28. Na4 Qd6 {Everything is holding together, and there does not seem to be a way to make Black fall over.} 29. e3 $2 {It's important to know that this obvious move fails.} Nd5 $17 {[%cal Gd5e3] Black can make threats too!} 30. Kf2 Nxe3 $1 31. Kxe3 Qe5+ {[%cal Re3f2,Re5e2] White is in big trouble, for example:} 32. Kd3 Qxb5+ 33. Kxd4 Qd7+ {[%cal Gd7d1] and ...Qxd1} *

