1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. Nc3 Bc6 ({During Karpov's legendary Linares tournament victory he faced} 12... cxd4 {and got an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is fairly simple and safe alternative to our main line with} 13... Qa5) 14. Bxf6 {This uncommon move was the main concern of Gustafsson in his Chess24 course.} Bxf6 15. Nxd4 Bxg2 (15... Qa5 $146 {intending ...Rd8, is also possible.}) 16. Kxg2 Nc6 $1 ({I prefer this to the more common} 16... Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Nc6 {when despite the simplifications, White maintains some pressure with} 18. Qc5 $14 {or 18.Qxd8 Rfxd8 19.Ne4 eyeing the d6- and c5-squares.}) 17. Nxc6 Qxd3 18. Rxd3 bxc6 {[%csl Ga4,Gf6][%cal Gf8b8,Gb8b2,Gf6b2] Black has split queenside pawns, but I like the bishop here and there is counterplay on the b-file, courtesy of the move 8.a4.} *

