1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 ({This has been more popular than} 8. Qxc4 {in recent years. White discourages ...b5, which we saw allowed Black to immediately develop his problem c8-bishop with ...b5 and ...Bb7. The move of the a-pawn also gains some space, but it noticeably weakens the b4-square.}) 8... Bd7 {This move looks a little funny at first, but it is by far Black's top choice. The bishop gets to the long diagonal after all.} ({There are other moves too, like} 8... Nc6) ({and} 8... c5 {, but Black has trouble reaching equality in these lines.}) 9. Qxc4 {This is unsurprisingly the main line, but there are other moves too, which we will consider later.} Bc6 10. Bg5 ({This is the most popular move. We will consider} 10. Bf4 {and other moves in later chapters.}) 10... Bd5 11. Qd3 ({There are two main lines here:} 11. Qc2 {and}) (11. Qd3 {, which can lead to very different kinds of play.}) 11... c5 $1 ({I prefer to avoid continuing the chase with} 11... Be4 {because White can play} 12. Qe3 $1 {This looks awkward, but Bxf6 is a real threat here. After} Nbd7 13. Nc3 Bc6 {and now White's main (but not only) choice has been} 14. Qd3 {intending e2-e4. Black is still probably more or less ok after} Bb4 {but I prefer to play more directly.}) ({The typical} 11... h6 $6 {is totally mistimed.} 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. e4 Bc6 14. Nc3 {and White dominates the center.}) 12. Nc3 Bc6 ({During Karpov's legendary Linares tournament victory he faced} 12... cxd4 {and got an edge after} 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. h4 $1 {threatening Bxf6 and Ng5 in Karpov-Beliavsky, Linares 1994.}) 13. Rfd1 {The big move. White maintans the tension and focuses on the center.} cxd4 ({This is fairly simple and safe alternative to our main line with} 13... Qa5) 14. Nxd4 {This has been played in the most games, by far.} Bxg2 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Kxg2 ({Instead} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Kxg2 {transpose to the last line.}) 15... Nbd7 16. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3b7] White has done pretty well with this move, but I do not see any real problems for Black here.} ({Other moves are easier to deal with:} 16. f4 $6 Rc8 17. e4 h6) ({or} 16. e4 Bb4) 16... h6 $5 {A rare move. Black not only ignores the attack on the b7-pawn, but he appears to just lose a tempo.} ({Black has also tried} 16... Qb8 17. Bf4 Qe8) ({and} 16... Qb6 17. a5 Qa7 {but I find these queen wiggles to be awkward.}) ({The most common move is} 16... Rb8 17. Bxf6 $5 {the flashy 17.Nf5 leads to nothing after 17...exf5 18.Bxf6 Bxf6 19.Qxf5 Bxc3 20.bxc3 Qf6 21.Qxd7 Qxc3=} Bxf6 18. Ne4 Be7 {is almost the same thing as our main line, but after} 19. Nf5 $5 Rc8 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qa3 Qxa3 22. Rxa3 {the lack of ...h6 could lead to bank rank problems, and thus the computer sees chances for White in the endgame.}) 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 Be7 19. Nf5 Rc8 $1 {Black has used the extra tempo (by playing ...Rc8 in one move instead of ...Rb8-c8) on ...h6, which prove to be of some use.} ({Here} 19... exf5 $2 20. Qxf5 {just wins back the piece leaving White with a good extra pawn.}) 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qa3 Qxa3 22. Rxa3 {[%cal Gh7h6] So it's the same as the line above in the note to Black's 16th, but here we have that beautiful move ...h6 played.} Ne5 {[%cal Gc8c2,Ge5c4] No back rank stuff so Black should be fine here.} *

