1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Bc4c7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {[%mdl 32768] I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Nc3 {White allows the doubling of his f-pawns. This is a typical idea.} Bxf4 12. gxf4 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4] Having played this structure with White, I realize that despite the improved grip on the center, this setup is not without chances for Black, as the white king position is loosened up a bit.} a5 {[%csl Gb4] The typical setup, locking down the b4-square.} 13. e3 Na6 ({Instead} 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 {would be nice and simple, but White has the thematic} 15. b4 $14 {with some initiative on the queenside.}) 14. Kh1 {[%cal Gf1g1] White hopes to use the half-open g-file. Black is not so easily mated however.} Nb4 15. Rg1 ({Naranayan mentions} 15. Qe2 {in his Catalan course. Black can play various moves here.} Bxf3 {is typical.} 16. Bxf3 c6 17. Rg1 Qe7 {occurred in an Aronian-Nakamura blitz game.}) 15... Qe7 16. Ne5 Bxg2+ 17. Rxg2 g6 {Black is super solid here. See the model game Hedman-Abdusattorov, Dubai 2019.} *

