1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Nc3 {White allows the doubling of his f-pawns. This is a typical idea.} Bxf4 12. gxf4 {Having played this structure with White, I realize that despite the improved grip on the center, this setup is not without chances for Black, as the white king position is loosened up a bit.} a5 {[%csl Gb4] The typical setup, locking down the b4-square.} 13. e3 ({The immediate} 13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {does not really change anything after 14...Na6 or 14...c6, but} Nc6 $5 {or even 14...Ra6!? with the idea ...Rb6} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 {intending ...Qd6 and ...Rb8, is a possibility.}) 13... Na6 ({Instead} 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 {would be nice and simple, but White has the thematic} 15. b4 $14 {with some initiative on the queenside.}) 14. Ne5 Bxg2 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Kxg2 Nb4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8e7,Gg7g6] This is similar to the previous line. Black is very solid.} ({A high level game saw an instructive error:} 15... c6 16. h3 {White goes for Kh2 instead of Kh1.} Qb6 17. Qe2 c5 $6 {opens the position prematurely. After} 18. Rfd1 {Qe2-b5 was a constant worry for Black in the game Giri-Wang Hao, Yekaterinburg 2021.}) *

