1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Bg5 {White avoids the exchange of bishops.} Nbd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Nc3 h6 {Putting the question to the bishop.} 13. Bxf6 {This is almost always played. Instead of allowing the exchange of bishops earlier, White prefers to go for an imbalance.} (13. Bd2 {avoids exchanges, but this bishop has moved three times now just to land on the passive d2-square. Wesley So played this move a couple of times in rapid games.} Ne4 {was played in a So-Aronian game and 13...Qe7 was seen in So-Nakamura. Both games were eventually drawn. Here I'll propose something different. 13...a5 $146 I like this straightforward move, preventing a4-a5 and locking down the b4-square. Black has the useful ...h6 move in 'for free' and can continue with ...Qe7 and ... Bb4, or perhaps with ...Ne4.}) ({The strange} 13. Bc1 {was played once by Ding Liren. Certainly White is wasting a lot of time, so it should not be too dangerous for Black.} a5 14. b3 Qe7 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Ba3 $1 {Black managed to exchange bishops after all in Ding Liren-Mamedyarov, Berlin 2018. He then followed up with the typical ...Bxf3 and ...c6 with a comfortable position.}) 13... Nxf6 {White has a lot of choice here. Nothing is too scary, but there are quite a few types of positions that may arise, so we'll tackle them one by one.} 14. Nd2 {Exchanging bishops is not particularly dangerous.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 a5 {[%cal Gd6b4,Gc7c6] Not the only move, but it's thematic and good.} 16. Nde4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bb4 18. Rac1 c6 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf8d8] Very equal. The game Kuzubov-So, Kocaeli 2015 was soon drawn.} *

