 {was played once by Ding Liren. Certainly White is wasting a lot of time, so it should not be too dangerous for Black.} a5 14. b3 Qe7 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Ba3 $1 {Black managed to exchange bishops after all in Ding Liren-Mamedyarov, Berlin 2018. He then followed up with the typical ...Bxf3 and ...c6 with a comfortable position.}) 13... Nxf6 {White has a lot of choice here. Nothing is too scary, but there are quite a few types of positions that may arise, so we'll tackle them one by one.} 14. Rfe1 {Another way to prepare the e4 advance.} Bd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({I would rather avoid} 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 c6 16. a5 {but it's still not so bad to allow this.}) 15. Qd3 (15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Qb3 Rb8 {is easy.}) 15... Bxf3 $1 {Only now.} 16. Bxf3 c6 {[%cal Ga6a5] Planning ...a5 as usual.} 17. e3 ({Now} 17. a5 $2 {runs into} Bb4 $17 {, just like in the previous line.}) 17... a5 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gd8c7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] This is similar to main lines arising from 10.Bg5. Black looks fine here.} *

