1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Bg5 {White avoids the exchange of bishops.} Nbd7 12. Nc3 h6 {Putting the question to the bishop.} 13. Bxf6 {This is almost always played. Instead of allowing the exchange of bishops earlier, White prefers to go for an imbalance.} (13. Bd2 {avoids exchanges, but this bishop has moved three times now just to land on the passive d2-square. Wesley So played this move a couple of times in rapid games.} Ne4 {was played in a So-Aronian game and 13...Qe7 was seen in So-Nakamura. Both games were eventually drawn. Here I'll propose something different. 13...a5 $146 I like this straightforward move, preventing a4-a5 and locking down the b4-square. Black has the useful ...h6 move in 'for free' and can continue with ...Qe7 and ... Bb4, or perhaps with ...Ne4.}) ({The strange} 13. Bc1 {was played once by Ding Liren. Certainly White is wasting a lot of time, so it should not be too dangerous for Black.} a5 14. b3 Qe7 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Ba3 $1 {Black managed to exchange bishops after all in Ding Liren-Mamedyarov, Berlin 2018. He then followed up with the typical ...Bxf3 and ...c6 with a comfortable position.}) 13... Nxf6 {White has a lot of choice here. Nothing is too scary, but there are quite a few types of positions that may arise, so we'll tackle them one by one.} 14. a5 {White plays this while he can.} Qe7 {[%csl Ga8,Gb4,Gf8][%mdl 32768] A typical, flexible move which connects the rooks, helps to control b4 and supports potential ...c5 or . ..e5 breaks.} 15. Nd2 {White hopes his knights will be superior to Black's N+B.} (15. Rfd1 Rfd8 {maintains the status quo}) (15. Rfe1 Bb4 {keeps e2-e4 off the table.}) 15... Bxg2 {Simplest.} ({Aronian went for} 15... Bd5 {against Giri and drew, but after} 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Qxe2 19. Ne4 {White's position was easier to handle in Giri-Aronian, Wijk aan Zee 2014.}) 16. Kxg2 c5 $1 {Why not? This is the thematic break.} 17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Nce4 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Rac8 {[%cal Gc5a7] This has been seen in a couple of correspondence games. If White tries to 'pin' the bishop he can easily get into trouble.} 20. Rac1 $6 {[%cal Gc1c8]} b5 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc5b4] Now if White retreats, the a5-pawn will be a real weakness.} ({Even} 20... Bb4 21. Qxc8 Rxc8 22. Rxc8+ Kh7 $15 {intending ...f5 is nice for Black. The queen is good here and the a5-pawn is weak.}) 21. axb6 Qb7 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Re4][%cal Gf7f5,Gb7g2] Now ...f5 is a big threat.} 22. f3 {No choice, but Black has another tactic.} Be3 $1 23. Qxc8 Rxc8 24. Nd6 {White's moves are all forced.} Rxc1 (24... Qxb6 25. Rxc8+ Kh7 {is not bad, but going for a straightforward edge in the endgame is simpler and objectively stronger too.}) 25. Nxb7 Rc2 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rb6,Re2,Ge3] Black will regain the pawn with interest, and his bishop is stronger than the white knight.} *

