1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1f4] This was recommended by Avrukh in his second edition of his Grandmaster Repertoire book on the Catalan, so not surprisingly it became the most popular choice for White.} a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4][%mdl 32768] Following the typical script.} ({A solid yet rather passive alternative is} 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 {intending ...e5.}) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Bd2 {A change of heart?! The white queen looks funny on c1 now, but there is an idea.} Nb4 14. Qb1 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is the point. White has avoided exchanges and now he wants to play e2-e4 to cramp Black's minor pieces.} Nbd5 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd5c3] We will trade off the c3-knight to fight for the e4-square.} ({Aronian played} 14... Bxf3 $6 15. Bxf3 {against Ding Liren, but I don't want to make this exchange when it leaves White with both of his bishops.}) 15. Re1 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Be4 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gh7h6,Gc7c5,Gb7b5] Black is solid here. The engine wants to play ...h6 next, and perhaps ...c5 down the road. In the long-term Black has the potential to create an outside passed pawn.} *

