1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Qc1 {This was recommended by Avrukh in his second edition of his Grandmaster Repertoire book on the Catalan, so not surprisingly it became the most popular choice for White.} a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4] Following the typical script.} ({A solid yet rather passive alternative is} 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 {intending ...e5.}) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Bg5 ({Usually White prefers} 13. Rd1 {first, but this may transpose.}) 13... h6 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Bxf6 {This is an independent course, but not one which will frighten us.} ({Instead} 14. Bh4 Be7 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e4 Nb4 17. Rd1 {transposes to 13.Rd1}) 14... Qxf6 15. e4 e5 $1 {We do not want to allow White's e4-e5.} 16. dxe5 {This at least eliminates Black's bishop pair.} (16. d5 Bd7 $15 {is too easy. Black is very solid and has the bishop pair. The unopposed dark-squared bishop has a lot of potential.}) 16... Bxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ga6b4,Gf8d8,Yf2f4,Ye5c5] With good control of the dark squares, Black has no reason to complain here.} *

