1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Qc1 {This was recommended by Avrukh in his second edition of his Grandmaster Repertoire book on the Catalan, so not surprisingly it became the most popular choice for White.} a5 {Following the typical script.} ({A solid yet rather passive alternative is} 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 {intending ...e5.}) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Rd1 Nb4 14. Bg5 {Avrukh's recommendation is the most interesting try. Here 14...h6 is the move given in Avrukh's book (and we will indeed play this move), but later it was deemed that Black should break the pin first.} Be7 {Theory is fluid however, and now it seems to me that this 'finesse' is misguided. White has a very strong move here though.} 15. e4 $5 {A clever move. The pawn is poisoned.} ({Black's Big Idea was that after} 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e4 b6 17. Qf4 Rc8 {it was considered that Black was better off without the move ...h6. Here Black can consider ...g6 and ...Bg7 (no pawn hanging on h6), and a potential advance by White with h4, g4, g5 does not latch onto the 'hook' on h6.}) (15. h4 $5 {and}) (15. Qb1 $5 {are both interesting tries for White as well.}) 15... h6 {Black ends up playing this after all.} (15... Nxe4 $2 16. d5 $16 {causes Black serious problems.}) 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. h4 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gg3g4,Gg4g5] If we compare this to the main position after 17.e4, White now has the useful move h4 for free!} *

