1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7] Developing the bishop here changes things a lot. The bishop takes a look at the c7-pawn, thus preventing the typical move ...Bd5.} Bd6 {I like this best. Black has less space, so it's logical to seek exchanges.} ({The natural} 10... Nd5 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 $14 {and White will prepare e2-e4.}) ({A thematic idea is} 10... a5 11. Nc3 Na6 {when White has tried several different rook moves, and he scores well with all of them! With less space, Black really would welcome a trade of minor pieces.}) ({A popular alternative is} 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 Bd6 {and we can even transpose to some lines that can arise this way.}) 11. Qc1 {This was recommended by Avrukh in his second edition of his Grandmaster Repertoire book on the Catalan, so not surprisingly it became the most popular choice for White.} a5 {Following the typical script.} ({A solid yet rather passive alternative is} 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Re1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 c6 {intending ...e5.}) 12. Nc3 Na6 13. Rd1 Nb4 14. Bg5 {Avrukh's recommendation is the most interesting try.} h6 15. Bh4 ({An important point in White's play. The pin is maintained for the moment.} 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 {is no problem at all. If} 16. e4 e5 {.}) 15... Be7 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5] Now ...g5 is on.} ({Of course Black cannot play} 15... g5 $4 16. Nxg5) 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. e4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh2h4,Gg3g4,Gc1f4,Gg4g5] It was considered worse for Black to have the pawn on h6 here - he cannot play ...g6, and White's h4, g4-g5 could be dangerous. It seems that Black is ok here however, and in more than one way. As is often the case, White comes up with some ideas, but given enough time, Black will solve the problems.} Qe8 $5 {[%cal Ga8d8,Ge8a4] This is odd-looking, but Black intends ...Rd8 and this move has held firm in correspondence games.} 18. Bf1 $5 {[%cal Gf1b5] A funny move which has been seen in a few correspondence games. White wants to halve Black's bishop pair.} Rd8 {[%mdl 32768]} 19. Bb5 Bd7 $5 {Not the only move, but I like it. If the bishops are to be exchanged, it's on Black's terms.} 20. Qf4 (20. Bxd7 $6 Rxd7 $15 {helps us. The b4-knight is strong and Black can put some pressure on the d4-pawn.}) (20. Rb1 {is a weird move, but it avoids these ...Nc2 ideas.} c6 $1 {We bury our own bishop for now, but at least we keep it!} 21. Be2 c5 $132 {hits the freshly weakened a4-pawn.}) 20... Nc2 21. e5 $1 ({Remember the trick} 21. Rac1 Nxd4 $1) 21... Be7 ({We do not want any part of} 21... Nxa1 22. exf6) 22. Rac1 Nb4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd7b5] We have an interesting position where I like Black's prospects.} 23. Z0 ({If White plays} 23. Qe4 {with the idea d4-d5, Black can just play} Bxb5 $146 {I also like 23...c6 $146 intending ...c5 later} 24. axb5 {or 24.Nxb5 c6 25.Nc3 Nd5} c6 $132) *

