1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768] We continue with our plan.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5. White does best to capture this knight.} 12. e3 {This looks sensible, but Black can hold the pawn in a comfortable way now.} Na5 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc7c5,Yc7c6,Yb7b5] This protects the c4-pawn, eyes the b3-square, and prepares ...c5 or even ...c6 and ...b5.} 13. Ne4 {[%cal Gc1d2] There's nothing better.} Nd5 $146 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gd5b4]} ({After} 13... Nxe4 14. Bxe4 {the h7-pawn is attacked and White will play Bd2 next.}) 14. Nd2 ({Not} 14. Bd2 $2 Nb4 $17) 14... b5 {Justified ambition. I think that White has some, but not quite enough for the pawn.} ({Black can also call it a day with} 14... Nb4 15. Qc3 Nd5) 15. b3 {White has to play this to get any counterplay at all.} cxb3 16. Nxb3 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Qd7 $15 {[%cal Gc7c6] White has some compensation, but it's not really enough.} *

