1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. Bg5 {The future of White's bishop is unclear, so White looks for further exchanges, hoping that his apparently better pawn structure will give him some chances.} Rb8 {Now White has some choice.} 14. Bxf6 {White is eager to exchange pieces.} Bxf6 15. Ne4 Rb4 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd8b8][%mdl 32768] An active move which protects the c4-pawn and prepares ...Qb8.} 16. e3 (16. Nc5 {can be met with} Qa8 $5 {and if} 17. Nd7 $6 Rd8 18. Nxf6+ gxf6 $15 {Black's activity and extra pawn give him better chances despite the ugly looking pawns.}) 16... Qd5 $15 {[%cal Gf8b8] Black has a slight initiative.} 17. Rac1 (17. Nxf6+ gxf6 $15 {is nothing to be afraid of.}) (17. Nc5 Ra8 $1 {intending ...Be7, is also good for Black.}) 17... Rfb8 18. Nc5 a5 $1 {Saving the pawn. The knight fork does not work.} 19. Qe2 ({Instead} 19. Na6 Rxb2 20. Qxc4 Qf3 21. Rf1 R8b6 $15 {is similar.}) (19. Rb1 {is very passive and allows Black to keep the c4-pawn which cramps White.} R8b6 $17) 19... Be7 {[%csl Rc5]} 20. e4 Qd8 21. Na6 Rxb2 22. Qxc4 R8b6 $15 {Black was more active and still had an extra pawn in Illescas Cordoba-Beliavsky, Madrid 1998.} *

