1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White has had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. Bg5 {The future of White's bishop is unclear, so White looks for further exchanges, hoping that his apparently better pawn structure will give him some chances.} Rb8 {Now White has some choice.} 14. Rac1 h6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Forcing things. A move like} 14... a5 {would be fine too.}) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e3 {This was seen in Kramnik-Karjakin, Moscow 2011.} ({Note that} 16. Ne4 Rb4 17. Nc5 {should simply be met with} Qc8 {Here 17...Qa8 18.Nd7 Rd8 19.Nxf6+ gxf6 does not work out because of 20.Qd2! hitting our rook and the h6-pawn. Black is still ok after 20...c5! but it's all unnecessary.}) 16... c5 $1 {The most active.} ({Karjakin played the rather passive} 16... Qe7 17. Ne4 Rb4 18. Qe2 Rxa4 19. Rxc4 Rxc4 20. Qxc4 {with an edge for White in Kramnik-Karjakin, Moscow 2011.}) 17. dxc5 (17. d5 Qe7 {is no problem at all.}) 17... Qe8 {[%cal Ge8c6] A typical method.} 18. Ne4 Be5 $1 {A finesse. We want to bring the queen to c6.} ({If} 18... Bxb2 19. Rb1 Qc6 {White is active after 19...Be5 20.Rxb8 Qxb8 21.Qxc4 $14} 20. Rxb2 Rxb2 21. Qxb2 Qxe4 22. Rd4 {White regains the pawn with equality.}) 19. Qxc4 ({We can hope that White is tempted by} 19. f4 $2 Bxb2 20. Rb1 Qc6 $1 21. Rxb2 Rxb2 22. Qxb2 Qxe4 {as this totally different now because White's king position is too weak.}) 19... Bxb2 20. Rb1 Qc6 {[%cal Gb8b7,Gf8b8,Gb2e5] All of Black's pieces are good and he is at least equal.} *

