1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White has had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. Bg5 {The future of White's bishop is unclear, so White looks for further exchanges, hoping that his apparently better pawn structure will give him some chances.} Rb8 {Now White has some choice.} 14. e3 {This flexible move was not in Gustafsson's Chess24 repertoire, but it developed into the main line.} c5 $5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({A great idea from Wesley So. Black has also tried} 14... a5 {as well as other moves, and Black seems ok everywhere.}) 15. dxc5 {Taking a pawn while attacking Black's queen looks critical.} ({Instead} 15. d5 Nxd5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 Rb4 {intending ...Rfb8, must be fine for Black.}) 15... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8c6] This idea seems like old news for us now, but at the time this was not such a well-known idea.} 16. Rd4 {Going after the c-pawn.} ({It's probably safer to play} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne4 {which we considered via 14.Bxf6. After} Be5 $1 18. f4 f5 $1 {and it is White who has to be very accurate.}) 16... Nd7 $1 {It's good to keep the knight, as the light-squares around White's king are weak.} 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5] Black has good counterplay and his king is safer. See the fantastic game Xiong-So [/variation/33613582], Saint Louis 2017.} *

