1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White has had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. a5 {[%cal Ga1a4,Gc3a4,Gc2a4] White leaves his bishop alone for the moment and hopes to soon regain the sacrificed pawn.} Rb8 {[%mdl 32768] The most natural move, and it allows us to be consistent with our repones to 13.Bg5.} 14. Qa4 (14. Bg5 {transposes to StartFENr2q1rk1/2p1bppp/p1p1pn2/8/P1pP4/2N3P1/1PQ1PP1P/R1BR2K1 w - - 0 13EndFEN 13.Bg5 Rb8 14.a5 .}) 14... Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3,Gd8d5,Gb8b3] Black plays this to try to take over the light squares.} ({We will consider} 14... Rb4 {as an alternative - both moves are good.}) 15. Qxc6 $6 {This is tempting, but it allows Black to execute his idea perfectly.} (15. Bg5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qd5 $1 17. Bxf6 gxf6 {is just better for Black. The triped pawns are not vulnerable, and they control a lot of squares!}) 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qd5 $1 17. Qxc7 $6 {White grabs a pawn for his suffering, but it will not digest well.} ({Instead} 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. f3 Rb3 $15 {gives Black an easy advantage.}) 17... Ne4 18. Bd2 {This untried move is relatively best, but not good enough!} (18. Qf4 $2 Nxc3 19. Re1 Rfc8 {with a winning position in Sirosh-Kovalev, Puhajarve 2019.}) (18. Ra3 $2 Nd6 {threatens ...Nb5.} 19. Ra4 Rfc8 20. Qe7 Ne4 {was also winning for Black in B.Kogan-K.Burger, Reykjavik 1982}) 18... Rb2 19. Qf4 f5 $1 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gg7g5,Ge6e5,Ge4d2,Gd5d2,Gb2d2] The ideas ...g5 and ...e5 put a lot or pressure on White to avoid an immediate loss.} 20. Rab1 {The only move. At least it sets a small trap.} e5 ({the move order} 20... Rxb1 21. Rxb1 e5 {also works;}) ({but Black must avoid the X-ray} 20... Rfb8 $2 21. Qxb8+ $1) 21. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3d5] White has to pin the knight.} (21. Qe3 f4 {wins.}) 21... Rxb1 22. Rxb1 Qxa5 $17 {Black's knight dominates.} 23. Z0 ({If} 23. Be1) ({or} 23. Be3 Nxc3 {Qa2 and Black is dominating.}) *

