b8b3] Black plays this to try to take over the light squares.} ({We will consider} 14... Rb4 {as an alternative - both moves are good.}) 15. Na2 {Avoiding the exchange.} Be7 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Qxc4 ({If} 16. Nc3 {Black can repeat or play the alternative line with} Rb4) 16... Qd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5a5] Thematic.} 17. Qxd5 {It may look strange to undouble Black's pawns, but White has an idea in mind.} ({If} 17. Qxa6 Ra8 18. Qd3 Qxa5 {Black is better developed.}) 17... cxd5 18. b4 {[%csl Ra6,Rc7][%cal Gd1c1,Gc1c6] Now the Black c-pawn is backward and White also hopes to target the a6-pawn. But Black has resources.} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4d6]} ({Do not blunder!} 18... Bxb4 $4 19. Nxb4 Rxb4 20. Ba3 {and White wins.}) 19. Bf4 {This was seen in Atalik-Karavade, Veliko Gradiste 2018. Now Atalik indicates a strong plan for Black which we've come across before.} Nd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c4]} 20. Bxd6 ({If} 20. Rdc1 Nc4 21. Bxc7 Rb7 {Black will quickly win back the pawn:} 22. Bb6 {or 22.Bf4 g5! 23.Be3 f6 and ...Rfb8} Nxb6 23. axb6 Rxb6 $15) 20... Bxd6 21. Rdc1 Rb5 22. Rc6 Ra8 $17 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7,Ge7d7] Black's king will come to d7 and the b4-pawn will be the target.} *

