1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gd4d5] Again ignoring the c4-pawn. Black has to know what to do here.} Bxf3 $1 {This is very important! We've seen this exchange enough by now to not be so surprised, but here the idea is different.} ({After the natural developing move} 10... Nbd7 $2 {White executes his idea to perfection:} 11. e4 {Threatening to smother the bishop with d5.} b5 12. d5 exd5 {and now} 13. e5 {gives White a crushing position.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d4] This hits the d4-pawn and also prepares ...Na5.} 12. Bxc6 {This exchange is necessary.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc4,Gc6,Gc7][%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5] Ok, we have tripled pawns. We will see this again in the 7.Ne5 lines. White has had to exchange his kingside minor pieces however, and we do still have an extra pawn. Black will seek counterplay along the b-file and often with the ...c5 break. The exchanges have also left us with have good control of the light squares.} 13. a5 {[%cal Ga1a4,Gc3a4,Gc2a4] White leaves his bishop alone for the moment and hopes to soon regain the sacrificed pawn.} Rb8 {The most natural move, and it allows us to be consistent with our repones to 13.Bg5.} 14. Ra4 {This looks more natural to me than the queen move.} (14. Bg5 {transposes to 13.Bg5 Rb8 14.a5.}) 14... Rb4 {Holding onto the pawn for the moment.} 15. Na2 {White's best try.} ({After} 15. Bg5 $6 Qb8 $15 {Black immediately seizes the initiative.}) ({Instead} 15. Rxb4 {looks wrong.} Bxb4 {hits the a5-pawn and plans the typical ...Bxc3 and ...Qd5. After} 16. Bg5 Bxc3 {avoiding 16...Bxa5?! 17.Ne4!} 17. Qxc3 Qd5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 {Black is at least ok, for example} 19. Rc1 Rb8) 15... Rxa4 16. Qxa4 Qb8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gb8b3] The established response, but there are some other decent moves.} ({One that I like is} 16... h6 $5 {Black waits for White to take a pawn and then ...Qd5 comes. Stockfish even likes 16...h5!? haha!} 17. Qxc4 {or 17.Qxc6 Qd5 18.Qxc7 Bd8=} Qd5 18. Qxd5 cxd5) 17. Qxc4 ({If} 17. Nc3 $6 Qb3 {intending ...Bb4 is better for Black.}) 17... Qb7 $1 {[%cal Gf8b8]} ({Black avoids the obvious} 17... Qb5 18. Qxb5 $1 cxb5 19. Be3 Nd5 20. Rc1 $14 {intending Rc6, with some light pressure.}) 18. Bg5 {White pitches the b-pawn in order to complete his development.} Qxb2 {[%mdl 32768] May as well!} 19. Bxf6 {This looks like the best try, and sets a strategic trap.} ({After} 19. Nc3 {Aronian played} Nd5 20. Bxe7 Nxc3 21. Bxf8 Nxd1 22. Qxa6 Ne3 $1 {led to a perpetual check in Leko-Aronian, Istanbul 2012. And 19...Qb4 $146 is even stronger. After 20.Qxc6 Qxa5 $15 Black is still a pawn up after all.}) 19... gxf6 $1 {[%cal Gb2b5]} ({But not} 19... Bxf6 $2 20. Nb4 $16 {Black's pawns quickly start disappearing.}) 20. Nc3 Rb8 $5 {[%cal Gb8b3] This looks like a blunder, but it's not!} ({Instead} 20... Qb4 21. Qxc6 Qxa5 {is a safe choice.}) 21. Rb1 Rb4 $1 {Everything works out for Black.} 22. Qxc6 Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c6] The pin is very awkward for White.} 23. Rd1 ({After} 23. Rxb4 Bxb4 24. Qe8+ Kg7 {White starts losing pawns.}) 23... Rb3 24. Rd3 Bb4 {[%csl Rc3] Now White has to find a draw.} 25. Z0 (25. d5 $1 exd5 {25...Rxc3 26.Qe8+ Kg7 27.dxe6 Rxd3 28.Qxf7+ is also a draw.} 26. Qxa6 Rxc3 27. Qc8+ Bf8 28. Qg4+ Kh8 29. Qc8 Kg8 30. Qg4+ Kh8 31. Qc8 Kg8 {1/2-1/2 Matlakov-Shimanov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2012.}) *

