1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd4d5] This is a tricky line. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead plans to blast his way through the center. Play can become very sharp.} b5 {This is the most ambitious choice.} ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 {is quite solid, although White has scored well after} 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nxc4) 11. Bxf6 {[%cal Gd4d5] This is the point of this particular move order, and White has rarely tried anything else. The f6-knight is eliminate so White can try to get in a d4-d5 break.} ({The immediate} 11. Nc3 {should be met with} Nd5 $146 {which is both active and makes it difficult for White to regain the pawn.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. e4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 {with the idea ...Nb6.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Nc3 ({Again, the main move.} 12. Nbd2 {brings less pressure to the center. We just have to watch for Ng5 tricks by playing} g6 {when White is scraping to find compensation for the pawn}) 12... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8b5,Rd1d8] The key move. The queen steps off the d-file and lends some support to the b5-pawn. Now White has to decide how he wants to play in the center. The engine gives it all as 0.00.} ({Black must avoid} 12... Nd7 $2 13. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 14. Bxc6 $16) ({Another option is} 12... Qe7 {but} 13. e4 g6 14. d5 {knocks the bishop away from the b5-pawn.}) 13. e4 {Now if White plays for d4-d5, he will have the option to recapture on d5 with a pawn.} g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gc2h7] This gives the dark-squared bishop a little more room and blocks off the b1-h7 diagonal.} 14. d5 {Very direct.} Bb7 ({I prefer this to} 14... exd5 {which opens the e-file.} 15. exd5 Bb7 16. Re1 Qd8 17. Rad1 {was Giri-Navara, blitz 2020. This seems like an improved version for White.}) 15. e5 {White continues to advance before Black completes his development.} Bg7 16. Ng5 {The threat of dxe6 finally forces Black to capture on d5.} exd5 17. Nxd5 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Re5]} ({This moving, leaving c7 to fall, is forced. Instead} 17... Bxd5 18. Bxd5 c6 19. Bxf7+ $1 Rxf7 20. Nxf7 Kxf7 21. Qd2 $1 {gave Black big problems completing development. in Arvola-Sanal, Batumi 2019. Ra1-a3 is coming too.}) 18. Nxc7 ({White goes for it.} 18. axb5 {would transpose after} axb5 19. Nxc7 Qxe5) 18... Qxe5 {[%csl Rb2,Rc7,Rg5][%cal Gc6d4][%mdl 32768]} 19. axb5 {The only way to make a fight of it.} ({Instead} 19. Nxa8 Qxg5 $17 {is great for Black. If} 20. axb5 $2 Nd4) 19... axb5 20. Nxa8 ({Black also has enough counterplay after} 20. Rxa8 Bxa8 21. Nxa8 Nd4 $1 22. Qd2 Nb3 {when the b2-pawn will fall.}) 20... Qxg5 21. Nc7 {White has won the exchange but Black is very active and has good play. There are various moves here, but let's look at the most forcing line.} Nd4 ({Both} 21... Nb4 {and}) (21... Qe5 {are fine too.}) 22. Rxd4 {There's no choice as the white queen does not have a good square.} ({If} 22. Qd2 Qxd2 23. Rxd2 Bxg2 24. Kxg2 Nb3 {wins for Black,}) ({while} 22. Qb1 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Qe5 {embarrasses the white knight.}) 22... Bxg2 23. Qd2 $1 {A saving move.} Qxd2 24. Rxd2 {White is up the exchange but now we have a trick.} c3 $1 25. bxc3 Bxc3 {Lots of things are hanging but it's going to just be even.} 26. Z0 ({For example:} 26. Nxb5 Bxa1 27. Kxg2) *

