1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd4d5] This is a tricky line. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead plans to blast his way through the center. Play can become very sharp.} b5 {This is the most ambitious choice.} ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 {is quite solid, although White has scored well after} 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nxc4) 11. Bxf6 {[%cal Gd4d5] This is the point of this particular move order, and White has rarely tried anything else. The f6-knight is eliminate so White can try to get in a d4-d5 break.} ({The immediate} 11. Nc3 {should be met with} Nd5 $146 {which is both active and makes it difficult for White to regain the pawn.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. e4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 {with the idea ...Nb6.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Nc3 ({Again, the main move.} 12. Nbd2 {brings less pressure to the center. We just have to watch for Ng5 tricks by playing} g6 {when White is scraping to find compensation for the pawn}) 12... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8b5,Rd1d8] The key move. The queen steps off the d-file and lends some support to the b5-pawn. Now White has to decide how he wants to play in the center. The engine gives it all as 0.00.} ({Black must avoid} 12... Nd7 $2 13. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 14. Bxc6 $16) ({Another option is} 12... Qe7 {but} 13. e4 g6 14. d5 {knocks the bishop away from the b5-pawn.}) 13. e4 {Now if White plays for d4-d5, he will have the option to recapture on d5 with a pawn.} g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gc2h7] This gives the dark-squared bishop a little more room and blocks off the b1-h7 diagonal.} 14. h4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] This is a typical move. White does not try to force matters. White does have good central control, so he probes on the kingside a bit. It's also a bit of a waiting move.} Nd7 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge8b5][%mdl 32768] This lessens our control of the b5-pawn, but we have to develop!} 15. axb5 (15. d5 exd5 16. exd5 Bb7 17. axb5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 {transposes}) 15... axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. d5 exd5 18. exd5 Bb7 19. Nxb5 {[%csl Rb2,Rc4,Rc7,Rd5] So White wins back the pawn, but there's no reason for the first player to count on any advantage. Both sides have weak pawns and more simplifications will follow.} Qa5 {[%csl Gc7][%cal Ga5b5] Not the only move (the engine will indicate that many moves are fine), but this has been the choice in practice and it's active.} 20. Nc3 Nb6 {[%csl Rd5]} (20... Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Qxc3 22. bxc3 Nb6 {also led to a draw in Vitiugov-Navara, Linares 2018, but there's no reason to part with the bishop just yet.}) 21. d6 cxd6 22. Rxd6 Bxc3 {Now this just forces a draw. Another quick finish:} (22... Be7 23. Rd1 Bf6 24. Rd6 Be7 25. Rd1 Bf6 26. Rd6 Be7 {½-½ Mamedyarov-So, Stavanger 2018.}) 23. Qxc3 (23. bxc3 Na4 {does not change much.}) 23... Qxc3 24. bxc3 Na4 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] Both c-pawns will disappear and there's nothing left to play for. The game Oparin-Deac, Krasnaya Polyana 2021 was drawn in a few moves.} *

