wn sacrifice scores much better than 13.e4. It's not objectively superior, but it's tricky.} exd5 14. Nd4 $1 {The crux of White's play.} Qe5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] An important centralization!} ({Black must resist the urge to exchange pieces too quickly. After} 14... Bxd4 $6 15. Rxd4 {White has great compensation as the d5-pawn will fall and Black is still not getting developed. If} Nd7 $2 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Rd8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bc6 {with a deadly pin.}) 15. e4 $1 (15. Nxc6 $2 {is against the spirit of the line, which is based on hampering Black's development.} Nxc6 {intending ...Nb4 is good for Black. White can take on d5 but he'll still be down a pawn with a worse position. For example} 16. axb5 {or 16.Nxd5 Rad8 $17} axb5 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Nxd5 Rb8 $17) 15... dxe4 16. axb5 {This is kind of a 'bailout' move, but there is little danger for Black. All of the following moves are forced.} axb5 17. Nxc6 {Now this wins back the material, but it all settles down to equality.} Nxc6 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. Qxe4 Qxe4 20. Bxe4 Ra6 21. Z0 ({After} 21. Nxb5 {everything is disappearing. Any sensible move is fine here. Practice has seen} Ne5 22. Nxc7 Ra2 {as played in Wojtaszek - Giri, Shamkir 2018 and a few other games.}) *

