1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 {An interesting continuation. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead prepares to build up in the center.} Bc6 10. Bg5 $5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd4d5] This is a tricky line. White does not bother with the c4-pawn and instead plans to blast his way through the center. Play can become very sharp.} b5 {This is the most ambitious choice.} ({The natural} 10... Nbd7 {is quite solid, although White has scored well after} 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nxc4) 11. Bxf6 {[%cal Gd4d5] This is the point of this particular move order, and White has rarely tried anything else. The f6-knight is eliminate so White can try to get in a d4-d5 break.} ({The immediate} 11. Nc3 {should be met with} Nd5 $146 {which is both active and makes it difficult for White to regain the pawn.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. e4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd7 {with the idea ...Nb6.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Nc3 ({Again, the main move.} 12. Nbd2 {brings less pressure to the center. We just have to watch for Ng5 tricks by playing} g6 {when White is scraping to find compensation for the pawn}) 12... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8b5,Rd1d8] The key move. The queen steps off the d-file and lends some support to the b5-pawn. Now White has to decide how he wants to play in the center. The engine gives it all as 0.00.} ({Black must avoid} 12... Nd7 $2 13. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 14. Bxc6 $16) ({Another option is} 12... Qe7 {but} 13. e4 g6 14. d5 {knocks the bishop away from the b5-pawn.}) 13. d5 {This second pawn sacrifice scores much better than 13.e4. It's not objectively superior, but it's tricky.} exd5 14. Nd4 $1 {The crux of White's play.} Qe5 $1 {An important centralization!} ({Black must resist the urge to exchange pieces too quickly. After} 14... Bxd4 $6 15. Rxd4 {White has great compensation as the d5-pawn will fall and Black is still not getting developed. If} Nd7 $2 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bxd5 Rd8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bc6 {with a deadly pin.}) 15. e4 $1 (15. Nxc6 $2 {is against the spirit of the line, which is based on hampering Black's development.} Nxc6 {intending ...Nb4 is good for Black. White can take on d5 but he'll still be down a pawn with a worse position. For example} 16. axb5 {or 16.Nxd5 Rad8 $17} axb5 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Nxd5 Rb8 $17) 15... dxe4 16. Nxe4 {The critical move.} Bxe4 $5 {This leads to complications and will be our main line.} (16... Ra7 {is fairly safe. This will be considered as an alternative.}) 17. Bxe4 Ra7 {Now White can capture on either b5 or h7.} 18. Nf3 $5 {White could take on h7 immediately too. 18.Bxh7+ Kh8 19.Nf3 Qxb2 transposes.} Qxb2 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({An improvement over} 18... Qe7 $2 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Rd5 $1 {with the idea Rh5 After} g6 21. Re1 {White was winning in B.Jacobson-Khamrakulov, New York 2019. If} Qb4 22. Bxg6) 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5h5] Threatening Qh5.} g6 {Forced.} 21. Bxg6 $2 {Tempting, but this does not work.} fxg6 22. Qc5 ({After} 22. Qxg6 $2 c6 $1 {the a7-rook comes to life!}) 22... Bg7 ({Or} 22... Kg8) 23. Qxa7 Qf6 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Rf2,Rf3][%cal Gf8f2,Gb8c6] A strange position, but Black is winning. The pressure on the f-file combined with the queenside armada is decisive.} *

