1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. e4 $6 {[%csl Re4,Rg2] This is just wrong. The pawn is a target here, and it blocks the Catalan bishop.} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6b4][%mdl 32768] Black is ready to play ...b5, protecting the extra pawn, while ...Nb4 is a serious option as well. White is already much worse.} 10. e5 {White decides to regain the pawn.} ({Black is up a pretty good pawn after either} 10. Qxc4 $2 Nxe4 $17) ({Or} 10. Nc3 b5 $1 11. axb5 Nb4 12. Qe2 axb5) 10... Nd5 11. Qxc4 Na5 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc7c5,Gd5b4] Black is ahead in development and White has various weaknesses. The move a4 looks very out of place now.} (11... b5 $5 {is also possible.}) 12. Qc2 {At least this covers the b3-square.} c5 13. dxc5 Rc8 $17 {[%csl Rb3,Rb4][%cal Gc8c5,Gd5b4] White would do well to just survive the next few moves.} *

