1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Nc3 $6 {Another poor move.} ({If White wants to play directly in the center, it is better to do so with} 9. Rd1 Bc6 10. Nc3 {, as we saw earlier in this chapter.}) 9... Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gb7b5][%mdl 32768] Black can switch plans. It's hard for White to recover the pawn, and he is not developing an initiative in the same way as he does in the 9.Rd1 line.} ({This is stronger than} 9... Bc6 $6 {which 'forgives' White and allows him to play} 10. Rd1 {coming back to the 9.Rd1 line.}) 10. Rd1 ({After} 10. e4 b5 {Black comfortably holds the pawn and ...Nb4 is still coming.}) 10... Nb4 11. Qb1 Bc6 $17 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1,Rc1][%cal Gb7b5] Black has developed successfully - the same cannot be said for White! We could say that Black has the extra pawn, 'and the compensation'.} 12. Z0 ({Note that} 12. e4 $6 Nd3 {does not help White's situation.}) *

