1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Nbd2 {This is not terrible, but it's not very dangerous either.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Nxc4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] White has regained the pawn and avoided simplifications, but Black has control of the central light squares.} Be4 11. Qb3 ({White has also played} 11. Qd1 {moving the queen twice to go nowhere} Nc6 {heading for b4 while preparing ...Rc8 and ...c5, looks fine. I prefer this to 11...c5 12.dxc5 Bxc5 13.Nfe5}) 11... Nc6 {[%cal Ge4d5,Gb7b5,Gc6d4,Gc6b4] This move again.} ({But not the hasty} 11... c5 $6 12. Nb6 $1) 12. Be3 {This is how White has played in practice.} ({Of course not} 12. Qxb7 $2 Nxd4 {and Black wins.}) 12... Bd5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc6a5] This is not the only decent move, but it's very direct as ...Na5 is a threat.} 13. Qc3 {Moving out of the pin.} ({Exchanging pieces with} 13. Nfe5 Nxe5 14. Bxd5 exd5 15. Nxe5 Rb8 {is nothing.}) 13... Ne4 14. Qc1 (14. Qd3 $2 {was played in a game between strong players. Black inexplicably missed} Nb4 {when the c4-knight is in big trouble. If} 15. Qb1 {Black can play the desperado} Nxf2 $1 {before munching on c4.}) 14... Nb4 {[%csl Gb4,Gd5,Ge4][%cal Ga8c8,Gc7c5] All of Black's pieces are well place and I already prefer his position.} *

