1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Bg5 {This is likely to transpose elsewhere.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. e3 {An independent line, which I wouldn't even bother with if not for the fact that Wesley So befuddled Nakamura with it, albeit in a rapid game.} (10. Nbd2 $6 b5 {does not make much sense.}) (10. Qxc4 {transposes to StartFENrn1q1rk1/1ppbbppp/p3pn2/8/P1pP4/5NP1/1PQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 9EndFEN 9.Qxc4 Bc6 10.Bg5 .}) (10. Rd1 {is the most common move. This just reaches StartFENrn1q1rk1/1ppbbppp/p3pn2/8/P1pP4/5NP1/1PQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 9EndFEN 9.Rd1 Bc6 10.Bg5 .}) (10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Rd1 b5 {also reaches a line that arises from the StartFENrn1q1rk1/1ppbbppp/p3pn2/8/P1pP4/5NP1/1PQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 9EndFEN 9.Rd1 Bc6 10.Bg5 move order.}) 10... b5 $5 {Nakamura's choice is not the only move, but it's consisetent with our repertoire.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nc3 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8b5] The same idea we saw in the StartFENrn1q1rk1/1ppbbppp/p3pn2/8/P1pP4/5NP1/1PQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 9EndFEN 9.Rd1 Bc6 10.Bg5 line.} 13. Rfd1 {[%cal Ge2e3] This is like the sharp line with StartFENrn1q1rk1/1ppbbppp/p3pn2/8/P1pP4/5NP1/1PQ1PPBP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 9EndFEN 9.Rd1 Bc6 10.Bg5 b5 11.Bxf6 Bxf6 12.Nc3 b5 , but in effect White has mysteriously played 13.e3 instead of the more critical moves 13.e4 or 13.d5 .} g6 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7] Now Black is ready to develop. Please avoid the dirty (but thematic!)} ({trick} 13... Nd7 $2 14. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 15. Bxc6 {which indeed looks horrible, but I was still surprised to see the engine's near +5 assessment!}) 14. d5 $5 {This was played by So. It's the only move that is at all dangerous.} exd5 15. Nd4 ({Not} 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5 Nc6 $17) 15... Be5 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc6b7,Gb8d7,Gc7c6,Ge5c7] This odd looking move is suggested by the engine. Considering that White has played this somewhat passive e3 move, Black can take a moment to cover the c7-pawn, which is vulnerable to White's knight hops. Left undisturbed, we will play ...Bb7 and ...Nd7.} ({Instead} 15... Bb7 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. Ndxb5 {leaves both the c7- and d5-pawns hanging.}) ({Nakamura played} 15... Bxd4 $6 16. Rxd4 Nd7 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 {Now the rook is attacked and Bd5-c6 looks very annoying. Nakamura understandably tried to stay active with} Nc5 $2 {but it just does not work. better is 18...Rd8 19.axb5 axb5 when 20.Bc6= $13 is annoying but not fatal.} 19. Bxa8 Nb3 20. Rdd1 Nxa1 21. Rxa1 Qxa8 {and now the sting at the end with} 22. axb5 {was disastrous in So-Nakamura, lichess rapid 2020.}) ({After} 15... Be5 {the engine does not see any clear continuation for White} 16. h4 Bb7 {White cannot allow us to play ...c6, as it's two pawns.} 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Bxd5 c6 {and then ...Ra7 with an unclear position where we have an extra pawn.}) *

