1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Ne5 {This is an obvious move to make, especially if one is not particularly well-versed in the theory of the line. It's pretty easy to neutralize though - if you know how to play.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl Rd4] White has grabbed the bishop pair, but it's cost him some time. The d4-pawn is now under attack, so White's choices are limited.} 11. Bxc6 {Tempting perhaps, but White scores poorly.} bxc6 {If we compare this position with the one arising after 9.Rd1 Bc6 10.Nc3 Bxf3 11.Bxf3 Nc6 12.Bxc6 bxc6, we see that White is not only missing the moves Rd1 and Nc3! I suppose White could argue that Nb1-c3 interferes with recouping the c4-pawn, but it's still a couple of tempi and White has to work to equalize here.} 12. Qxc4 {White takes back the pawn, but he's clearly behind in development.} Qd5 $1 {Typical centralization.} 13. Na3 (13. Qxd5 cxd5 $17 {is similar.}) (13. Nd2 Rfb8 $15 {is also nice for Black. It's not easy for White to develop properly.}) 13... Rfb8 $15 {[%cal Gb8b4,Gb8b2] It's not easy for White to develop properly.} 14. Ra2 $6 {This is not very good, but it's difficult to offer good advice.} Rb4 15. Qxd5 cxd5 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Ga8b8] This was W.Shipman-Vigorito, Reno 2003. How I managed to almost lose a rook ending a pawn up is another story.} *

