1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Qc2 {This is White's main move by far, simply intending Qxc4.} ({The big alternative is} 7. Ne5) 7... a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Ne5 {This is an obvious move to make, especially if one is not particularly well-versed in the theory of the line. It's pretty easy to neutralize though - if you know how to play.} Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 {[%csl Rd4] White has grabbed the bishop pair, but it's cost him some time. The d4-pawn is now under attack, so White's choices are limited.} 11. e3 {[%cal Gc2c4] This is more ambitious. White secures his d-pawn and hopes to recover the c4-pawn and make use of the bishop pair. We can't be compliant.} Na5 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc7c5][%mdl 32768] The only good move. Black's only advantage is his lead in develoment, so we must cause some trouble.} 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} ({Black can hold onto the pawn after} 12. Na3 $6 Bxa3 13. Rxa3 Nd5 {with an active position. If} 14. Bd2 $6 Nb3) ({The mistimed} 12. Bd2 {leads to an awkward position after} Nb3 13. Ra2 {and then} c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qxc4 Rc8 {gave Black the initiative in Burmakin-Bruzon Batista, Ubeda 2001.}) 12... c5 $1 {Although White has the bishop pair, we must aim to open to position to use our development lead.} 13. Nxc4 {This no so common. It's not too bad if White follows up correctly, but it's still risky as Black's play flows easily.} cxd4 {[%cal Ga8c8] Threatening ...Rc8.} 14. Nxa5 Qxa5 15. Bxb7 (15. exd4 Nd5 {is easy for Black.}) 15... Rab8 16. Qc6 $2 {I faced this once in a blitz game online.} d3 $17 {[%cal Gd3d2] This pawn is serious!} 17. Rd1 ({If} 17. Qxa6 Qb4 {attacks the b7-bishop while threatening to win the other with ...d2.}) 17... Qh5 {[%csl Ra1,Rb7,Rc1][%cal Gh5d1,Gf6g4] We attack the rook and with ...Ng4 coming, Black has a winning attack. White's scattered pieces are not able to help defend.} *

