1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 {This is a popular and interesting line. White opens the diagonal of his Catalan bishop and prepares to recoup the pawn on c4.} Nc6 $1 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) {With this capture it is White who will often be a pawn ahead, but at the cost of giving up his favorite bishop.} 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {[%csl Gc8] An interesting position. Material is even for now, but White can win the c4-pawn if he is so inclined.} 11. Qa4 c5 ({Our repertoire move will be} 11... e5 $1 {but this is an alternative which has been seen a lot in practice.}) 12. Qa3 $5 {[%cal Ga3e7] This move was the recommendation in the popular book 'Wojo's Weapons' by Ippolito and Hilton. Pinning the c5-pawn is rather annoying and White scores quite well here. I think Black is ultimately ok, but 11...e5 is still theoretically preferable.} ({After the more common} 12. Qxc4 {Black can be quite happy after} cxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 {when practice has show that Black has full compensation.}) *

