1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 {This is a popular and interesting line. White opens the diagonal of his Catalan bishop and prepares to recoup the pawn on c4.} Nc6 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) {With this capture it is White who will often be a pawn ahead, but at the cost of giving up his favorite bishop.} 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {[%csl Gc8] An interesting position. Material is even for now, but White can win the c4-pawn if he is so inclined.} 11. Qa4 {White goes for the pawn.} e5 $1 {[%csl Gc8] Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 {[%cal Gc8h3,Ge5h5,Gf6g4]} 13. Qxc4 {Black is ahead in development, but White has a better pawn structure and an extra pawn. So Black must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1f4] Now 15.Bf2 is a threat. Black always has to watch out for this.} Bf5 (14... Bh3 {is also possible, but why not drive the queen to an awkward square first?}) (14... Nd5 $5 {was recommended by Jon Ludvig Hammer in his Chess24 course. Black prevents Bf4, and ...Nb4 is a possibility. This has hardly been played if you're looking to experiment or absolutely must avoid a repetition.}) 15. Qd2 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd2f4,Gd2g5] This locks in the bishop, but White plans for this to be a temporary problem, as Qf4 or Qg5 may come soon.} ({After} 15. Qc4 Be6 {White can repeat or go for Qd3 this time around. In turn, Black can play with 14...Bh3 or Hammer's 14...Nd5}) 15... Bh3 {This is the most forcing, and it sets a few traps based on White's weak back rank. Sometimes White will play f3 and Rf2, so we avoid that.} ({Black should avoid} 15... Rad8 $6 16. Qf4 $1) ({We checked} 15... Rfe8 {, simply attacking the e2-pawn, as an alternative.}) 16. Re1 ({This is universally played - the e-pawn needs protection.} 16. Rd1 Rfe8 {seizes the initiative.} 17. Nc3 Ne4 18. Qe3 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qh5 {and Black wins back the pawn while maintaining pressure.}) 16... Rad8 17. Qf4 $4 {This is a typical idea for White, but it does not work here!} Qxe2 $1 {[%cal Gd8d1] White will be mated.} *

