must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1f4] Now 15.Bf2 is a threat. Black always has to watch out for this.} Bf5 (14... Bh3 {is also possible, but why not drive the queen to an awkward square first?}) (14... Nd5 $5 {was recommended by Jon Ludvig Hammer in his Chess24 course. Black prevents Bf4, and ...Nb4 is a possibility. This has hardly been played if you're looking to experiment or absolutely must avoid a repetition.}) 15. Qd2 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd2f4,Gd2g5] This locks in the bishop, but White plans for this to be a temporary problem, as Qf4 or Qg5 may come soon.} ({After} 15. Qc4 Be6 {White can repeat or go for Qd3 this time around. In turn, Black can play with 14...Bh3 or Hammer's 14...Nd5}) 15... Bh3 {This is the most forcing, and it sets a few traps based on White's weak back rank. Sometimes White will play f3 and Rf2, so we avoid that.} ({Black should avoid} 15... Rad8 $6 16. Qf4 $1) ({We checked} 15... Rfe8 {, simply attacking the e2-pawn, as an alternative.}) 16. Re1 ({This is universally played - the e-pawn needs protection.} 16. Rd1 Rfe8 {seizes the initiative.} 17. Nc3 Ne4 18. Qe3 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qh5 {and Black wins back the pawn while maintaining pressure.}) 16... Rad8 17. Qc3 Qh5 {[%mdl 32768] We keep the queens on the board as we can often makes threats on the kingside.} 18. Be3 Rfe8 {[%cal Gf6d5] Black is fully mobilized.} 19. Nd2 ({White cannot offer a queen trade with} 19. Qc5 $2 {because we have} Qxe2 $1) 19... Nd5 20. Qc5 Bg4 {Simply attacking the e2-pawn.} 21. Nf3 {Now Black can win back the pawn.} Nxe3 22. Qxh5 Bxh5 23. fxe3 Rxe3 24. Rac1 Bxf3 25. exf3 Rxf3 26. Rxc7 g6 {[%cal Gd8d2] Black has no problems at all.} *

