wn. So Black must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1f4] Now 15.Bf2 is a threat. Black always has to watch out for this.} Bf5 (14... Bh3 {is also possible, but why not drive the queen to an awkward square first?}) (14... Nd5 $5 {was recommended by Jon Ludvig Hammer in his Chess24 course. Black prevents Bf4, and ...Nb4 is a possibility. This has hardly been played if you're looking to experiment or absolutely must avoid a repetition.}) 15. Qd2 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd2f4,Gd2g5] This locks in the bishop, but White plans for this to be a temporary problem, as Qf4 or Qg5 may come soon.} ({After} 15. Qc4 Be6 {White can repeat or go for Qd3 this time around. In turn, Black can play with 14...Bh3 or Hammer's 14...Nd5}) 15... Rfe8 {This is a good alternative, simply attacking the e2-pawn.} 16. Re1 ({If} 16. Nc3 Ne4 17. Nxe4 Qxe4 18. Re1 Bg4 {transposes.}) 16... Bg4 {[%csl Re2]} 17. Nc3 Ne4 18. Nxe4 ({Instead} 18. Qf4 Qxf4 19. Bxf4 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Bxe2 21. Bxc7 f6 $13 {should be easy to hold. Black is active and White's pawns are split.}) 18... Qxe4 19. Qc3 ({I faced} 19. Qf4 {is a blitz game once, and later noticed it had occurred in practice.} Bxe2 20. Qxe4 {During the blitz game I noticed 20.Qxc7 Qh1+! and mates!} Rxe4 21. Bf4 c6 22. Rac1 Bf3 {Jianchao Zhou - Hou Yifan, Xinghua Jiangsu 2011.}) 19... Bxe2 {White will ultimately win the c7-pawn, but this is 'normal' and nothing to worry about.} 20. Be3 Qf3 21. Rac1 a6 22. Bd4 Qg4 23. Be5 f6 24. Bxc7 Kh8 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh3] With such a weak king, White will have a lot of trouble using his extra pawn. In fact he had to be careful to hold in Kramnik-Leko, Dortmund 2010.} *

