1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black is ahead in development, but White has a better pawn structure and an extra pawn. So Black must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3e3] White looks to challenge Black's queen with Qe3. This looks more flexible than 14.Qc2 and is more popular.} Rad8 ({We should avoid} 14... Bf5 $2 {here because after} 15. Qe3 {we can't go to the desirable h5-square.}) 15. Qe3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf6g4] Now White's reply is forced.} 16. f3 Bc4 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e8] A key move!} ({After} 16... Rfe8 $6 17. Qg5 $1 {is annoying.} Qh3 18. Qc5 $1 {hits some pawns and the queen can always come back to f2 .}) ({The obvious} 16... Bh3 $6 {just does not work out well.} 17. Re1 $1 Rfe8 18. Qf2 $1 {covers everything nicely and White has scored tremendously here.}) 17. Nc3 (17. Qf2 Rfe8 18. Nc3 {would transpose.}) 17... Rfe8 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. g4 {This was only played once, and it was in a blitz game. Still, it was played Kramnik and Stockfish shows some initial enthusiasm.} Qg6 19. Qf2 ({Black is certainly ok after} 19. Qg5 Bxe2 20. Qxg6 hxg6) 19... Nd5 {We will see this idea repeatedly. Black seeks to remove White's knight in order to weaken the e2-pawn. Eliminating the knights also gives us a certain degree of safety, as the remaining opposite colored bishops will create a drawish tendency in the endgame.} (19... h5 20. g5 Nd5 {is likely to transpose.}) 20. Nxd5 Rxd5 21. Re1 h5 ({Another idea is} 21... f5 $5 22. g5 h6) 22. g5 f6 $5 ({Already Black head for a draw with} 22... Bxe2 $5 23. Rxe2 Rd1+ 24. Kg2 Rxe2 25. Qxe2 Rxc1 $1 {the point} 26. Rxc1 Qxg5+ 27. Kh3 Qxc1 28. Qe8+ Kh7 29. Qxf7 Qg5 30. Qxc7 Qf5+ 31. Kg2 Qg5+ 32. Kf2 Qd2+) 23. h4 fxg5 (23... Rde5 $6 24. e4 {was not so simple for Black in Kramnik-Nakamura, Paris blitz 2016, although he did go on to win.}) 24. hxg5 ({If} 24. Bxg5 Rd2 $132) 24... Rf5 $13 {Black is more active and has a safer king.} *

