1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black is ahead in development, but White has a better pawn structure and an extra pawn. So Black must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3e3] White looks to challenge Black's queen with Qe3. This looks more flexible than 14.Qc2 and is more popular.} Rad8 ({We should avoid} 14... Bf5 $2 {here because after} 15. Qe3 {we can't go to the desirable h5-square.}) 15. Qe3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf6g4] Now White's reply is forced.} 16. f3 Bc4 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e8] A key move!} ({After} 16... Rfe8 $6 17. Qg5 $1 {is annoying.} Qh3 18. Qc5 $1 {hits some pawns and the queen can always come back to f2 .}) ({The obvious} 16... Bh3 $6 {just does not work out well.} 17. Re1 $1 Rfe8 18. Qf2 $1 {covers everything nicely and White has scored tremendously here.}) 17. Nc3 Rfe8 18. Qg5 {White is willing to exchange queens to get an endgame with a structural edge. This is a typical motif for White, and therefore we should not always be so eager to regain the pawn.} Qh3 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf6d5][%mdl 32768] Keeping the queens on. We would like to play ...Nd5 next.} ({After} 18... Bxe2 19. Qxh5 Nxh5 20. Rf2 {White has what he wants.}) 19. Rf2 $6 {Apparently a nice, cozy move. White overprotects the e2-pawn, or at least he appears to!} (19. Bf4 $6 {is not very good, because after} Bxe2 {White cannot take the bishop.}) (19. Qh4 $6 {is taking the desire to exchange queens a bit too far. After} Qxh4 20. gxh4 Bxe2 {White can certainly forget about a structural advantage.}) 19... Bxe2 $1 {[%cal Gd8d1] This is actually not so bad for White if he reacts correctly. In practice he has not managed to do so!} 20. Be3 $2 Bxf3 $1 {Black's bishop continues its rampage!} 21. Rxf3 Ng4 {[%csl Re3,Rh2]} 22. Rf2 ({If} 22. Qh4 Qxh4 23. gxh4 Nxe3 {is simple. Black is up a pawn.}) 22... f6 $1 {[%cal Ge8e3] It's best to take on e3 with the rook to maintain all of the threats. Black soon won in Malakhov-Grischuk, Moscow blitz 2006.} ({Black cannot play} 22... Rxe3 $4 23. Qxd8+) ({while} 22... Nxe3 23. Re1 {allows White to fight on.}) *

