) 15. Qe3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf6g4] Now White's reply is forced.} 16. f3 Bc4 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e8] A key move!} ({After} 16... Rfe8 $6 17. Qg5 $1 {is annoying.} Qh3 18. Qc5 $1 {hits some pawns and the queen can always come back to f2 .}) ({The obvious} 16... Bh3 $6 {just does not work out well.} 17. Re1 $1 Rfe8 18. Qf2 $1 {covers everything nicely and White has scored tremendously here.}) 17. Nc3 Rfe8 18. Qg5 {White is willing to exchange queens to get an endgame with a structural edge. This is a typical motif for White, and therefore we should not always be so eager to regain the pawn.} Qh3 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf6d5] Keeping the queens on. We would like to play ...Nd5 next.} ({After} 18... Bxe2 19. Qxh5 Nxh5 20. Rf2 {White has what he wants.}) 19. Rf2 $6 {Apparently a nice, cozy move. White overprotects the e2-pawn, or at least he appears to!} (19. Bf4 $6 {is not very good, because after} Bxe2 {White cannot take the bishop.}) (19. Qh4 $6 {is taking the desire to exchange queens a bit too far. After} Qxh4 20. gxh4 Bxe2 {White can certainly forget about a structural advantage.}) 19... Bxe2 $1 {[%cal Gd8d1] This is actually not so bad for White if he reacts correctly. In practice he has not managed to do so!} 20. Qh4 {The safest choice.} Qxh4 {[%mdl 32768]} 21. gxh4 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc1g5]} Bc4 22. Bg5 Re6 {Material is level and both sides have split pawns.} *

