1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black is ahead in development, but White has a better pawn structure and an extra pawn. So Black must play actively! Typical ideas include ...Bh3 as well as ...Qh5 and ...Ng4. But first we will nudge the white queen from her active post.} ({Later we will also check} 13. Nc3) 13... Be6 14. Qd3 {[%cal Gd3e3] White looks to challenge Black's queen with Qe3. This looks more flexible than 14.Qc2 and is more popular.} Rad8 ({We should avoid} 14... Bf5 $2 {here because after} 15. Qe3 {we can't go to the desirable h5-square.}) 15. Qe3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf6g4] Now White's reply is forced.} 16. f3 Bc4 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e8] A key move!} ({After} 16... Rfe8 $6 17. Qg5 $1 {is annoying.} Qh3 18. Qc5 $1 {hits some pawns and the queen can always come back to f2 .}) ({The obvious} 16... Bh3 $6 {just does not work out well.} 17. Re1 $1 Rfe8 18. Qf2 $1 {covers everything nicely and White has scored tremendously here.}) 17. Nc3 Rfe8 18. Qg5 {White is willing to exchange queens to get an endgame with a structural edge. This is a typical motif for White, and therefore we should not always be so eager to regain the pawn.} Qh3 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf6d5] Keeping the queens on. We would like to play ...Nd5 next.} ({After} 18... Bxe2 19. Qxh5 Nxh5 20. Rf2 {White has what he wants.}) 19. Be3 {[%cal Ge3a7,Ga1d1] This is probably the safest move, even though the bishop looks a little wobbly here.} (19. Bf4 $6 {is not very good, because after} Bxe2 {White cannot take the bishop.}) (19. Qh4 $6 {is taking the desire to exchange queens a bit too far. After} Qxh4 20. gxh4 Bxe2 {White can certainly forget about a structural advantage.}) 19... Nd5 {[%mdl 32768] Following the script. We want to get rid of White's knight.} ({Worse is} 19... h6 $2 20. Qc5) ({Black can play the surprising} 19... Bxe2 $5 {with an unusual tactical idea.} 20. Nxe2 Rd5 {Black will load up on the e-file to regain the piece.} 21. Qf4 {not 21.Nf4? Qxf1+} Rde5 22. Bxa7 Rxe2 23. Bf2 Rxb2 24. a4 h5 {with counterplay was given by Kotronias ages ago. According to the engines, this still holds up, although that a-pawn concerns me a bit.}) 20. Bxa7 ({White at least snatches a pawn.} 20. Bd4 f6 21. Qc1 Nxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxe2 23. Rf2 a6 {presented no challenge to Black in Filippov-Grischuk, Tripoli (m/4-rapid) 2004.}) 20... Nxc3 21. bxc3 h6 {[%csl Ra2,Re2][%cal Gd8a8] This looks simplest to me. We may well take on e2, but we really just want to win the a-pawn.} ({Black should also be fine after} 21... Bxe2 22. Bd4 Rxd4 23. cxd4 Bxf1 24. Rxf1 h6 {as White's king position is too weak for him to get ambitious.}) ({After} 21... h6 {some possibilities:} 22. Qg4 {worse options are 22.Qf4?! Rxe2 23.Bf2 if 23.Rf2?! Qe6! Ba6!? 24.c4 Qd7↑ and 22.Qh4?! Qxh4 23.gxh4 Ra8 24.Bd4 Rxe2 25.a4 Ra2=} Qxg4 23. fxg4 Ra8 {when White a- and e-pawns are both likely to fall.}) *

