1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 {This is a popular and interesting line. White opens the diagonal of his Catalan bishop and prepares to recoup the pawn on c4.} Nc6 $1 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) {With this capture it is White who will often be a pawn ahead, but at the cost of giving up his favorite bishop.} 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {An interesting position. Material is even for now, but White can win the c4-pawn if he is so inclined.} 11. Qa4 {White goes for the pawn.} e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 {Grabbing the pawn. Later we will also check} 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gf1d1] Rather than grabbing the pawn, White focuses on development. If Black clings to the material, White's structural advatage may tell.} Ne4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] We have seen this strategic objective. Trade the knights!} ({White has done pretty well after} 13... Be6 14. Bf4 {with the idea of bringing a rook to the d-file.}) 14. Qb5 {White has played this a few times, but it should make little difference.} c5 $1 ({Worse is} 14... Qe6 15. Qd5 $1 Nxc3 16. Qxe6 Bxe6 17. bxc3 {which allows White to play 'for free' with his extra kingside pawn.}) 15. Qxc4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 {So White has induced Black's ... c5.} ({Giving up the e-pawn with} 16. Qxc3 Qxe2 17. Be3 Qh5 18. Bxc5 Re8 19. f3 Bb7 $13 {is normal long-term compensation for Black.}) 16... Be6 17. Qd3 Rad8 18. Qe3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gh5e2,Ge6c4] Black was fine in Radjabov - Aronian, Novi Sad 2016.} *

