1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 {This is a popular and interesting line. White opens the diagonal of his Catalan bishop and prepares to recoup the pawn on c4.} Nc6 $1 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) {With this capture it is White who will often be a pawn ahead, but at the cost of giving up his favorite bishop.} 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {An interesting position. Material is even for now, but White can win the c4-pawn if he is so inclined.} 11. Qa4 {White goes for the pawn.} e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 {Grabbing the pawn. Later we will also check} 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gf1d1] Rather than grabbing the pawn, White focuses on development. If Black clings to the material, White's structural advatage may tell.} Ne4 $1 {We have seen this strategic objective. Trade the knights!} ({White has done pretty well after} 13... Be6 14. Bf4 {with the idea of bringing a rook to the d-file.}) 14. Qxc4 {The main move.} Nxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. bxc3 ({If} 15. Qxc3 Qxe2 {White may pick up the c-pawn, but there will always be compensation with White's kingside so weak.}) 15... Be6 {Universally played, but the engine is equally happy with various other moves if you're feeling experimental.} (15... a5 {with the idea ...Ba6 is one idea.}) 16. Qd3 (16. Bf4 {was played by Wesley So a couple of times, but I imagine he was not in an ambitious mood.} Bxc4 {16...Qh5 looks fine too.} 17. Bxe5 Rfe8 18. Bxc7 Rxe2 {was played in both So-Nakamura and So-Aronian. In both cases the games were quickly drawn.}) 16... Rad8 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] This is the most natural, intending to centralize both rooks. The only downside is the a7-pawn is left alone.} ({The alternative} 16... Rfd8 {is also completely viable, for example} 17. Bf4 Rxd3 18. Bxe5 Rd2 19. e4 Bxa2 20. Bxc7 a5 $13 {when Black is not worse.}) 17. Bf4 ({After} 17. Qe3 {really any queen move will do! I would probably choose the consistent} Qh5 {but the engine is equally happy with 17...Qa5 and 17...Qb5}) 17... Qh5 {Here too other queen moves should be fine.} 18. Qa6 {[%csl Ra7,Rc7] We are already down a pawn and both c7 and a7 are attacked. But this is just a normal day at the office for us.} ({After} 18. Qe3 Rfe8 {Black vas various little threats like ...Bh3, ...Bg4, and ...Bc4.}) 18... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Re2] I like this move a lot. It is objectively sound, with the added benefit that White has various ways to go wrong.} ({In practice Black has almost always gone for} 18... Bc8 {which should also be good enough.}) 19. f3 $2 {What could be more natural? But this is bad.} Bh3 20. Rf2 (20. Rfd1 {is even worse.} Qc5+ {White cannot let our queen come into the f2-square.} 21. e3 Rfe8 $1 {White's king is too weak. The immediate threat is ...Rxd1+ and ...g5. It's already -4! Note that the immediate 21...g5? 22.Rxd8 Rxd8 allows the strong resource 23.Qf6!}) 20... Qc5 $1 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gc5g1,Gc5c3,Gh7h5,Gg7g5,Gd8d7,Gf8d8] White's queen is out of play and Black has all kinds of ways to develop an initiative.} *

