1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 {This is a popular and interesting line. White opens the diagonal of his Catalan bishop and prepares to recoup the pawn on c4.} Nc6 $1 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) {With this capture it is White who will often be a pawn ahead, but at the cost of giving up his favorite bishop.} 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {An interesting position. Material is even for now, but White can win the c4-pawn if he is so inclined.} 11. Qa4 {White goes for the pawn.} e5 $1 {Black frees the c8-bishop.} 12. dxe5 {White pretty much always plays this.} ({Instead} 12. Qxc4 $6 {is not a good move order. After} exd4 {the e2-pawn is vulnerable. For example} 13. Qxd4 Qxe2 14. Nc3 Qf3 {and White does not even enjoy an extra pawn to compensate the weakness of his vulnerable king.}) 12... Qxe5 {Grabbing the pawn. Later we will also check} 13. Nc3 {[%cal Gc1f4,Gf1d1] Rather than grabbing the pawn, White focuses on development. If Black clings to the material, White's structural advatage may tell.} Ne4 $1 {We have seen this strategic objective. Trade the knights!} ({White has done pretty well after} 13... Be6 14. Bf4 {with the idea of bringing a rook to the d-file.}) 14. Qxc4 {The main move.} Nxc3 15. bxc3 ({If} 15. Qxc3 Qxe2 {White may pick up the c-pawn, but there will always be compensation with White's kingside so weak.}) 15... Be6 {Universally played, but the engine is equally happy with various other moves if you're feeling experimental.} (15... a5 {with the idea ...Ba6 is one idea.}) 16. Qd3 (16. Bf4 {was played by Wesley So a couple of times, but I imagine he was not in an ambitious mood.} Bxc4 {16...Qh5 looks fine too.} 17. Bxe5 Rfe8 18. Bxc7 Rxe2 {was played in both So-Nakamura and So-Aronian. In both cases the games were quickly drawn.}) 16... Rad8 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] This is the most natural, intending to centralize both rooks. The only downside is the a7-pawn is left alone.} ({The alternative} 16... Rfd8 {is also completely viable, for example} 17. Bf4 Rxd3 18. Bxe5 Rd2 19. e4 Bxa2 20. Bxc7 a5 $13 {when Black is not worse.}) 17. Bf4 ({After} 17. Qe3 {really any queen move will do! I would probably choose the consistent} Qh5 {but the engine is equally happy with 17...Qa5 and 17...Qb5}) 17... Qh5 {Here too other queen moves should be fine.} 18. Qa6 {[%csl Ra7,Rc7] We are already down a pawn and both c7 and a7 are attacked. But this is just a normal day at the office for us.} ({After} 18. Qe3 Rfe8 {Black vas various little threats like ...Bh3, ...Bg4, and ...Bc4.}) 18... Bg4 $1 {[%csl Re2] I like this move a lot. It is objectively sound, with the added benefit that White has various ways to go wrong.} ({In practice Black has almost always gone for} 18... Bc8 {which should also be good enough.}) 19. Rfe1 Rfe8 {[%csl Re2]} 20. Bxc7 {As the attempts to retain the e2-pawn are problematic, White decides that he may as well have another pawn.} Rd7 {[%cal Gd7c7,Gd7e7][%mdl 32768] Hitting the bishop and preparing to double rooks on the e-file.} 21. Qa5 {Relatively best. White would be happy to get the queens off the board. We could trade and hold rather easily, but White's king is weaker, so there's no reason to let up the pressure.} Qh3 $5 22. f3 {White can finally play this move!} Rde7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e2,Gg4f3] This not only attacks the e2-pawn, it threatens to take on f3.} 23. Qd5 {The only move! But White has to find it...} ({Of course not} 23. fxg4 $2 Rxe2 {and mates.}) 23... Rxc7 (23... Bxf3 24. Qxf3 Rxc7 {is similar.}) 24. fxg4 Qxg4 $13 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3,Re2,Rg1] With a weak king and scattered pawns, Black has full compensation.} *

