1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qc2 {This was played a few times in the 1990's, with poor results. In 2013 Kramnik revived it against Carlsen. He got an advantage, but with the surprise element gone, he did not repeat 11.Qc2 again..} c5 ({We will focus on the sharper} 11... e5) 12. Qxc4 (12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qc6 {is kind of like the line with the modern line with 6.Nc3 dxc4 7.Ne5, but here White has committed to castling.}) (12. Rd1 {has been tried a few times, but it does not seem as dangerous here. After} cxd4 13. Rxd4 e5 14. Rxc4 Be6 {Black should have decent compensation.} 15. Rc7 Qd6 16. Rc6 Qe7 {repeating moves has happened in a couple of games.}) 12... cxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 $13 {Practice has show that Black has full compensation. For example:} 14. Qh4 h6 $5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Rc1g5] Preventing Bg5.} *

