1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qc2 {This was played a few times in the 1990's, with poor results. In 2013 Kramnik revived it against Carlsen. He got an advantage, but with the surprise element gone, he did not repeat 11.Qc2 again..} e5 $5 {The most interesting choice.} (11... c5 {is a good alternative which we took a look at as an informational line.}) 12. Rd1 ({An independent course.} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {transposes to 11.Qa4.}) 12... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7g2] Again, we will go for the most interesting line. Although this may seem to be an obvious move, this is not always the right square because if White can block the long diagonal comfortably with f2-f3, the bishop may not achieve much.} (12... Rb8 $6 13. Nc3 h6 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Rd4 Be6 17. Rad1 $14 {was Kramnik-Carlsen, London 2013. White is not up a pawn, but he is active and has a better pawn structure.}) (12... exd4 {has been the most popular.} 13. Rxd4 c5 $1 {instead 13...Be6 14.Nc3 has done very well for White.} 14. Rd1 {or 14.Rxc4 Ba6} Re8 15. Nc3 h6 {also seems quite viable.}) 13. Qxc4 {Natural enough, but now White will have to be careful to avoid immediate disaster.} ({If} 13. f3 $2 e4 {is a terrible for White.}) 13... Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7h3,Gf6g4,Gd7d1][%mdl 32768] Pinning the d5-pawn and threatening ...Qh3.} 14. d5 ({The only move. Again,} 14. f3 e4 $17 {ruins White's position.}) 14... Bxd5 15. Qh4 Qe6 16. Nc3 Bb7 {Black has the usual 'compensation', except here he is not even down a pawn!} *

