1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qc2 {This was played a few times in the 1990's, with poor results. In 2013 Kramnik revived it against Carlsen. He got an advantage, but with the surprise element gone, he did not repeat 11.Qc2 again..} e5 $5 {The most interesting choice.} (11... c5 {is a good alternative which we took a look at as an informational line.}) 12. Rd1 ({An independent course.} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {transposes to 11.Qa4.}) 12... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7g2] Again, we will go for the most interesting line. Although this may seem to be an obvious move, this is not always the right square because if White can block the long diagonal comfortably with f2-f3, the bishop may not achieve much.} (12... Rb8 $6 13. Nc3 h6 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 Qe7 16. Rd4 Be6 17. Rad1 $14 {was Kramnik-Carlsen, London 2013. White is not up a pawn, but he is active and has a better pawn structure.}) (12... exd4 {has been the most popular.} 13. Rxd4 c5 $1 {instead 13...Be6 14.Nc3 has done very well for White.} 14. Rd1 {or 14.Rxc4 Ba6} Re8 15. Nc3 h6 {also seems quite viable.}) 13. Nc3 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7h3,Ge5d4,Gf6g4] Black threatens not only yo take on d4, but to invade on h3.} ({Instead} 13... Qe6 $1 {is equivalent and after} 14. dxe5 Qh3 {we have transposed.}) ({I simply prefer} 13... Qd7 {because I find it more visually appealing, and White may be tempted into} 14. d5 $2) ({Black should avoid} 13... Rad8 $2 {because after} 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 $16 {White is developing quickly. He can block the long diagonal with f3 and his structural advantage counts for something.}) 14. dxe5 (14. d5 $2 {does not work because after} Nxd5 15. Nxd5 {or 15.e4 Nb4 $17} Bxd5 16. e4 Bxe4 $17 {Black is much better.}) 14... Qh3 {[%csl Rg2] This is the point of course.} 15. e4 (15. f3 $2 {does not stop} Ng4 {Then} 16. e4 Nxe5 {is just much better for Black.}) 15... Ng4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gg4e5]} 16. f4 {White has won a pawn (although not in the usual way) but Black has tremendous activity.} Rad8 {[%csl Re4,Rg2,Rh2] Returning the pawn is relatively safe.} ({This looks the most natural to me, but} 16... f5 $5 17. exf6 Rad8 {was successful in Stupak-Khruschiov, Cheliabinsk 2021. White has to be very careful here. It's not easy for him to complete development, and there's various tactics to look for on the light squares.}) 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Gd8d3,Gf7f5][%mdl 32768] Black has various threats, such as ...Rd3 and ...f5! So White chases away the black queen.} 18. Qg2 Qh6 {[%cal Gd8d1,Gb7e4,Gh6b6] We must retreat, as the pawn down endgame has no appeal. This move is not passive however. We are looking to swing the queen over to b6, and we still have the d-file.} 19. h3 Bxe4 {This is simplest I think.} (19... Qb6+ {also leads to a draw:} 20. Kf1 Bxe4 $1 21. Nxe4 {White should probably avoid 21.Qxe4 Qf2} Rd1+ 22. Ke2 Rxc1 $1 23. Rxc1 Qe3+ 24. Kd1 Qd3+ 25. Ke1 {or 25.Qd2? Ne3+ 26.Ke1 Qf1} Qe3+ 26. Qe2 Qxc1+ 27. Qd1 Qe3+ 28. Kf1 Nh2+ 29. Kg2 Qxe4+ 30. Kxh2 Qd3 {was Wang Yue-Wei Yi 2013.}) 20. Qxe4 ({Not} 20. Nxe4 $2 Rd1+) 20... Qb6+ 21. Be3 Nxe3 22. Na4 Qd4 (22... Qb4 {and similar queen moves also work after} 23. Qxe3 Qxa4) 23. Qxd4 Rxd4 {A level endgame, but there's still some play left.} *

