.. exd4 {has been the most popular.} 13. Rxd4 c5 $1 {instead 13...Be6 14.Nc3 has done very well for White.} 14. Rd1 {or 14.Rxc4 Ba6} Re8 15. Nc3 h6 {also seems quite viable.}) 13. Nc3 Qd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7h3,Ge5d4,Gf6g4] Black threatens not only yo take on d4, but to invade on h3.} ({Instead} 13... Qe6 $1 {is equivalent and after} 14. dxe5 Qh3 {we have transposed.}) ({I simply prefer} 13... Qd7 {because I find it more visually appealing, and White may be tempted into} 14. d5 $2) ({Black should avoid} 13... Rad8 $2 {because after} 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf4 $16 {White is developing quickly. He can block the long diagonal with f3 and his structural advantage counts for something.}) 14. dxe5 (14. d5 $2 {does not work because after} Nxd5 15. Nxd5 {or 15.e4 Nb4 $17} Bxd5 16. e4 Bxe4 $17 {Black is much better.}) 14... Qh3 {[%csl Rg2] This is the point of course.} 15. e4 (15. f3 $2 {does not stop} Ng4 {Then} 16. e4 Nxe5 {is just much better for Black.}) 15... Ng4 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gg4e5]} 16. f4 {White has won a pawn (although not in the usual way) but Black has tremendous activity.} Rad8 {[%csl Re4,Rg2,Rh2] Returning the pawn is relatively safe.} ({This looks the most natural to me, but} 16... f5 $5 17. exf6 Rad8 {was successful in Stupak-Khruschiov, Cheliabinsk 2021. White has to be very careful here. It's not easy for him to complete development, and there's various tactics to look for on the light squares.}) 17. Nd5 f5 $1 {A cool position where Black clearly has the initiative.} 18. Re1 {This has been seen in practice a couple of times.} Qh5 $146 {[%cal Gb7d5][%mdl 32768] A bit of a prophylactic move. Now Black is ready to take on d5.} ({After the immediate} 18... Bxd5 $6 19. exd5 Rxd5 20. Qg2 $1 {forces the exchange of queens, when White is beginning to consolidate and stands better.}) ({Two Svane-Beerdsen games saw the odd} 18... a5 {Both continued with} 19. a4 {instead 19.Qg2 Qxg2+ 20.Kxg2 fxe4 21.Ne3= is also possible} Rfe8 20. Ra3 {with each playing winning one!}) ({The engine suggests moving the other rook pawn with} 18... h5 $146 {If} 19. Qg2 Qxg2+ 20. Kxg2 fxe4 21. Ne3 Rd3 {seems to improve on 18...a5.}) 19. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga1a4,Ga1a2,Ga1a3] White may continue to push the a-pawn or play Ra3 - which we saw in the Svane-Beerdsen games.} Rd7 $132 {[%cal Gf8d8] Let's just double on the d-file. Black's position looks easier to play.} ({Instead} 19... fxe4 20. Ne3 {should be about equal.}) ({If Black plays} 19... Bxd5 20. exd5 Rxd5 21. Ra2 {is another weird computer move. If} Rfd8 22. b4 {is the idea. White increases the defense along the second rank.}) *

