1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Na3 $5 {Another Kramnik toy. He played this against both Anand and Adams.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d1] This is Black's main alternative to our repertoire move, 11...c5. This pressures the d4-pawn, but really it's trying to add weight to the ...c5 break.} 12. Qc2 $1 ({White abandons the pawn.} 12. Nxc4 $6 c5 {is just good for Black.}) 12... Ba6 {In turn, Black declines.} ({White has a structural edge after} 12... Rxd4 13. Nxc4 $14 {with b3 and Bb2 coming.}) ({The immediate} 12... c5 {is fine and will usually transpose, for example} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Nxc4 Ba6) 13. Nxc4 c5 $1 (13... Rxd4 $2 14. Ne5 {threatening a fork on c6 , is rather annoying.}) 14. dxc5 ({Now} 14. Ne5 $2 {fails to} Rac8 $17) 14... Qxc5 15. b3 Bxc4 16. Bb2 {[%cal Gc2c5] The main move, making use of the pin.} (16. Be3 Qh5 $132 {with the idea ...Ng4.}) (16. Qxc4 Qxc4 17. bxc4 Rdc8 {is pretty easy. Black often chooses this rook in order to keep a7-pawn covered.} 18. Be3 Rxc4 19. Rfc1 Ra4) (16. bxc4 Rdc8 $1 {Again, this rook.} 17. Bb2 Qxc4 18. Qxc4 Rxc4 19. Rac1 Rac8 20. Rxc4 Rxc4 21. Rc1 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 Nd5 {is a line given by Gustafsson.}) 16... Rac8 {Black plays this rook now as with the bishop committed to b2, there is no pressure on a7.} 17. Rac1 $5 {This is at least a little tricky.} (17. Rfc1 $4 Ng4 {hits f2 and plans ...Qh5.}) (17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Rfc1 {is more common but this is an easy draw.} Qe5 $1 19. bxc4 Rd4 {Black chases the c-pawn, and he is not afraid for Q vs 2R.}) 17... Qb4 {[%cal Gd8d2]} ({This sacs a pawn.} 17... Qa5 {is also considered to be satisfactory.}) 18. Bxf6 ({Or} 18. bxc4 Rd2 19. Bc3 Rxc2 20. Bxb4 R8xc4) 18... Ba6 $1 ({But not} 18... gxf6 19. bxc4 Rd2 20. Qb3 $16) 19. Bc3 Qb5 20. Rfe1 Bb7 21. Qb2 {This was Donchenko-Lei, 2019. Here:} f6 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7g2] Intending ...e5 looks simplest. I don't think Black should have any trouble here.} *

