1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Na3 $5 {Another Kramnik toy. He played this against both Anand and Adams.} c5 {[%mdl 32768] The most direct.} ({Black should avoid the familiar} 11... e5 $6 {here. After} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxc4 $14 {White has an extra pawn and has not wasted time with his queen.}) ({Then there is} 11... Rd8 {, which we considered as an informational line.}) 12. dxc5 (12. Nxc4 $2 Rd8 {is just good for Black.}) 12... Qxc5 13. Qc2 {[%csl Gc4] This is uncommon but it's not bad.} Bb7 $5 ({Black can also try to hold onto the pawn with} 13... Ba6 14. Qa4 Qc8 {but this looks awkward to me. and 14...Bb7 15.Qxc4 would transpose to the main line with an extra move for each side.}) 14. Nxc4 $2 {This looks normal but it loses material.} (14. Qxc4 {would transpose to the main line with an extra move for each side after} Qxc4 15. Nxc4 Ba6 16. b3 Rfc8) 14... Rfc8 {[%csl Rc4] Either rook will do.} 15. b3 Qd5 {No prizes for spotting the threat.} 16. f3 Qd4+ {[%csl Ra1,Rg1][%cal Gd4g1,Gd4a1] This is the point, but White is not resigning yet.} 17. e3 ({After} 17. Be3 $2 Rxc4 {White is indeed busted.}) 17... Qxa1 18. Bb2 Qxa2 19. Ra1 {So we got our queen trapped.} Qxa1+ 20. Bxa1 Bd5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Ga7a5] With two rooks for the queen and no targets for White, only Black can be better.} *

