1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Na3 $5 {Another Kramnik toy. He played this against both Anand and Adams.} c5 {The most direct.} ({Black should avoid the familiar} 11... e5 $6 {here. After} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxc4 $14 {White has an extra pawn and has not wasted time with his queen.}) ({Then there is} 11... Rd8 {, which we considered as an informational line.}) 12. dxc5 (12. Nxc4 $2 Rd8 {is just good for Black.}) 12... Qxc5 13. Be3 Qh5 {[%cal Gf6g4] Anand's original reaction, and this still looks best. Black has also tried clinging to the pawn.} (13... Qb4 {was Aronian-Nakamura, Saint Louis 2014}) (13... Qc6 {was Kramnik-Adams, Shamkir 2015. These moves are not so bad, but White did win both games...}) 14. f3 {This is necessary.} (14. Nxc4 $6 Ng4 15. h4 Ba6 16. b3 Nxe3 {forces the ugly} 17. fxe3 {when White is obviously worse despite the extra pawn. Of course not 17.Nxe3?? Bxe2}) 14... e5 $5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Ge5e4] We free our bishop and introduce the disruptive ...e4 as a possibility.} (14... c3 $5 {was Anand's original reaction. Black should always check this move if he is going to lose the pawn anyway.} 15. bxc3 Qa5 {15...e5 was suggested by Hammer has not caught on. Our 14...e5 is probably a better version.} 16. Qc1 {The more active 16.Qd6!? is trickier.} Ba6 $13 17. c4 Rac8 18. Bxa7 Bxc4 19. Nxc4 Qxa7+ 20. Qe3 Qa6 21. Ne5 Rc2 {was Kramnik-Anand 2014.}) 15. Bc5 {[%cal Ge2e4] White gains time to play e4 himself.} Re8 {[%cal Ge5e4][%mdl 32768]} 16. e4 {[%cal Ga3c4] White has prevented our ...e4 and is ready to round up the c4-pawn.} c3 $5 {By returning the pawn in this way, Black splits White's pawns.} ({The immediate} 16... Bh3 {also looks fine and may transpose.}) 17. bxc3 ({This is necessary. If} 17. b3 $2 Ba6 {intending ...Red8-d3, White might not capture our pawn so easily.}) 17... Bh3 $13 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge8c8] White's king is not comfortable and the queenside pawns are split, so the compensation should be long lasting. The engines already prefers Black.} 18. Rf2 (18. Re1 {makes less sense, as f3 is weak and a black rook is coming to the d-file.}) 18... Rec8 {[%csl Rc3,Rc5][%cal Gc8c3] Often this is the right rook to move. There is nothing to do on the e-file. This simple attack is not easy to meet.} 19. Be7 {White does not cling to the pawn.} (19. Bb4 {is of course met with} a5 {- another point of keeping the rook on a8 .}) 19... Rxc3 20. Nb5 ({The exchange} 20. Bxf6 gxf6 {does not change much. White's knight is poor.}) 20... Rc6 (20... Rc4 {should be fine too.}) 21. Rc1 $2 {A mistake, but White's position is not easy.} Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Rc8 23. Qe1 {Black has different ways to play here, but I like his choice in the game.} Ne8 $17 {[%csl Ge8,Rg1][%cal Gh5g6,Rb5a7,Gc8c7,Gg6e6] This was Cordts-Michiels, Ghent 2016. Black's position is much more fun. The queen can come back to g6 and perhaps move along the third rank. White's king faces constant dicomfort. I would comment that the e8-knight will surely find better pastures soon, but in the game Black won without moving the knight again!} *

