1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] This move is uncommon and it scores poorly, but it is not bad at all. It was recommended by Ipatov in his book Unconventional Approaches to Modern Chess.} cxb3 {[%mdl 32768] This is the most ambitious.} (11... Rd8 {is also good. It is probably less to learn, but leads to a lot of simplifications. We will check this as an informational line.}) 12. Ba3 {Of course, if this move worked, Black's last move would be a blunder. But White is actually wasting time.} b2 $1 13. Bxb2 Rd8 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga8b8,Ge6e5,Gc8b7] Black has even material and play typical of the 8.Bxc6 line.} *

