1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] This move is uncommon and it scores poorly, but it is not bad at all. It was recommended by Ipatov in his book Unconventional Approaches to Modern Chess.} cxb3 {This is the most ambitious.} (11... Rd8 {is also good. It is probably less to learn, but leads to a lot of simplifications. We will check this as an informational line.}) 12. axb3 {[%cal Gc1a3] This is very natural, but it has done poorly in practice.} Rd8 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd8d1][%mdl 32768] Now ...e5 will be a concern for White.} 13. Ba3 Qd7 {[%csl Rd4] Hitting the d4-pawn, but as we've seen, it's often not work taking it.} 14. Nc3 (14. e3 $2 {would obviously weaken the light squares even further.}) 14... Bb7 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd7c6,Gc6c3,Gc6g2] Now ...Qc6 is a big threat.} ({This is better than} 14... Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Rxd4 16. Bc5 {when White wins back the pawn with a slight edge.}) 15. f3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7h3] The position is suddenly difficult for White.} 16. dxe5 $2 {The only move played in practice, but it loses material.} Qh3 {[%cal Gd8d1]} 17. Qe1 (17. exf6 {is relatively best, but still bad.} Rxd1 18. Rfxd1 Qe6 $17 {Castiglione - Petrik, Slovakia 2014.}) 17... Ng4 $1 {A familiar idea.} 18. Rf2 Nxf2 19. Qxf2 Qe6 {[%csl Rb3,Re5] This was Babic-Galic, Osijek 2015. Black is up a good exchange.} *

