1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] This move is uncommon and it scores poorly, but it is not bad at all. It was recommended by Ipatov in his book Unconventional Approaches to Modern Chess.} cxb3 {This is the most ambitious.} (11... Rd8 {is also good. It is probably less to learn, but leads to a lot of simplifications. We will check this as an informational line.}) 12. axb3 {This has done poorly in practice.} Rd8 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 13. Ba3 Qd7 14. Nc3 (14. e3 $2 {would obviously weaken the light squares even further.}) 14... Bb7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c6] Now ...Qc6 is a big threat.} ({This is better than} 14... Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Rxd4 16. Bc5 {when White wins back the pawn with a slight edge.}) 15. f3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gd7h3]} 16. e4 {Untried, but the best chance for White.} Qc6 $5 {[%cal Gd8d4][%mdl 32768] Black wants to take on d4 with the rook.} ({After both} 16... exd4 17. Na4) ({and} 16... Qxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Rxd4 18. Na4 {White has decent compensation for the pawn.}) 17. Bc5 {This stops ...Rxd4 at least.} (17. Rc1 {does not help after} Qa6 $1 {hitting the bishop.}) 17... exd4 18. Bxd4 Rd7 {[%cal Ga8d8] Black intends to build up further on the d-file with good play.} *

