1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3] This move is uncommon and it scores poorly, but it is not bad at all. It was recommended by Ipatov in his book Unconventional Approaches to Modern Chess.} cxb3 {This is the most ambitious.} (11... Rd8 {is also good. It is probably less to learn, but leads to a lot of simplifications. We will check this as an informational line.}) 12. Qxb3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc1a3] The main line. White gets his queen off of the d-file.} Rd8 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Black has also done well with} 12... Qd7 13. Ba3 Rd8 {rather than 13...Re8 14.Rd1 Ba6 15.Nc3 Nd5 16.Rd2 Rab8 17.Qc2 Nxc3 18.Qxc3 $14 with an edge for White in Banusz-Nisipeanu, Austria 2018.} 14. Nc3 Ba6 {transposing to the next note.}) 13. Ba3 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8a6,Gd8d4] My preference. The d8-rook stays active, and ...e5 is a possibility.} (13... Qd7 14. Nc3 Ba6 {intending ...Nd5 should also be ok.}) 14. Rd1 Ba6 {We develop and attack the e2-pawn.} (14... e5 {is also possible. If} 15. dxe5 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 Bh3 $1 {with the idea} 17. exf6 $2 Qe4 18. f3 Qe3+ 19. Kh1 Qf2 20. Qg1 Qxe2 {and White is in trouble. White should play 15.d5 when 15...e4 is unclear.}) 15. Nc3 Nd5 {[%csl Re2] It's very typical in all of these 8.Bxc6 lines for Black to seek an exchange of knights. The slightly worse pawn structure is less troublesome without a blockading knight, and the opposite colored bishops will favor the side with the initiative - hopefully us - while also providing some drawing margin in the endgame.} 16. e4 ({After} 16. Nxd5 $2 exd5 {our pawn structure is optically worse, but our king is safer and our bishop is much more active - White's bishop has little to do.}) 16... Rab8 {We may as well gain a tempo.} ({Instead} 16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 {may favor White a bit, as the only real imbalance is the pawn structure.}) 17. Qc2 Nb4 ({Always played, but I think here} 17... Nxc3 {makes more sense as we gained ...Rb8 for free. After} 18. Qxc3 Qa4 {either ...e5 or ...f5 offer opportunities for counterplay.}) 18. Qc1 {This has not been played, but the computer indicates it as best - at first.} c5 $1 19. dxc5 Nd3 $132 {[%cal Ge8c6] White is not well coordinated and Black is very active.} 20. Qc2 ({If} 20. Qe3 Qc6 {with the idea ...Ne5-c4 looks good.}) 20... f6 $5 {[%cal Ge8h5]} ({I like this move, considering that} 20... Qc6 21. Qa4 {forces the queens off anyway.}) 21. Qa4 Qxa4 22. Nxa4 Rdc8 $13 {[%csl Ra3,Ra4][%cal Gd3e5,Gg7g5,Gg5g4,Ge5c4] Black remains down a pawn but White's position looks very awkward, especially as the minor pieces are on purely defensive duty. Our knight can hop around, and fixing White's pawns with ...g5-g4 is another idea.} *

