 Ba6 {We develop and attack the e2-pawn.} (14... e5 {is also possible. If} 15. dxe5 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 Bh3 $1 {with the idea} 17. exf6 $2 Qe4 18. f3 Qe3+ 19. Kh1 Qf2 20. Qg1 Qxe2 {and White is in trouble. White should play 15.d5 when 15...e4 is unclear.}) 15. Nc3 Nd5 {[%csl Re2] It's very typical in all of these 8.Bxc6 lines for Black to seek an exchange of knights. The slightly worse pawn structure is less troublesome without a blockading knight, and the opposite colored bishops will favor the side with the initiative - hopefully us - while also providing some drawing margin in the endgame.} 16. e4 ({After} 16. Nxd5 $2 exd5 {our pawn structure is optically worse, but our king is safer and our bishop is much more active - White's bishop has little to do.}) 16... Rab8 {We may as well gain a tempo.} ({Instead} 16... Nxc3 17. Qxc3 {may favor White a bit, as the only real imbalance is the pawn structure.}) 17. Qc2 Nb4 ({Always played, but I think here} 17... Nxc3 {makes more sense as we gained ...Rb8 for free. After} 18. Qxc3 Qa4 {either ...e5 or ...f5 offer opportunities for counterplay.}) 18. Bxb4 Rxb4 {[%mdl 32768]} 19. d5 {Ipatov gave this as unclear. Fair enough, but let's look a little more.} e5 {This fixes the structure which seems to help White, but the knight does not have a great square.} ({The engine also likes the non-committal} 19... h6 $5) 20. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gc1a3] White tries to improve the position of his queen.} Rc4 ({The immediate} 20... Rd6 {is also reasonable.} 21. Qe3 Qb8 22. Rab1 h6 {was unclear in Hilby-Brown, Las Vegas 2017.}) 21. Qa3 Rd6 {[%cal Gd6a6,Gd6f6,Gd6g6,Gd6h6] Black combines attack and defence.} 22. Rab1 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] Black has his weaknesses covered and creates counterplay on the kingside.} 23. Z0 (23. Rb4) ({Blocking with} 23. h4 {is possible, but White will have to watch out for ...g5 at some point.} Rb4 24. Qxb4 {h4↑ Black had good counterplay in Duda - Deac, Chennai 2022.}) *

