1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Bxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Nc3 {This is a relatively recent try. Perhaps it was inspired by White's success in the line with 6.Nc3 dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 bxc6 9.Nxc6 Qe8 10.Nxe7+ Qxe7, but here White has committed to castling, which he usually avoids in that line.} Rd8 {This is a solid way to play.} ({Black should avoid} 11... e5 $6 {here.} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Bf4 Qc5 14. Qd2 Bb7 15. Rad1 $16 {was Predke-Ganguly, Linares 2019. Black is not down a pawn, but his structure is worse and White has the initiative.}) ({Our repertoire move will be} 11... c5) 12. Qa4 {[%cal Ga4c4,Ga4c6]} Rxd4 {I think Black should take. This is obvious, but slightly unusual in these lines.} ({The little queen invasion after both} 12... c5 13. Qc6 $5) ({and} 12... a5 13. Qc6 $5 {is annoying.}) 13. Be3 e5 $1 {This justifies Black's play.} 14. Qc6 ({Taking the rook immediately amounts to the same thing, as after} 14. Bxd4 exd4 {White really needs to play} 15. Qc6 $1 Rb8 16. Nd5 {transposing.}) 14... Rb8 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. Nd5 {White has to force the pace or Black's compensation will be overwhelming.} Nxd5 17. Qxd5 c5 18. Qxc4 Bh3 {[%cal Gb8b2,Ge7e4,Gh3f1] Black has various threats, so White must return the exchange.} 19. b3 $1 (19. Rfe1 Qe4 20. f3 Qe3+ 21. Kh1 Qf2 {would be lights out, for example.}) 19... Bxf1 ({Now} 19... Qe4 {does not work:} 20. f3 Qe3+ 21. Rf2 $16) 20. Kxf1 {White is hoping that his better pawn structure gives him chances for an edge, but material is greatly reduced and Black can create enough counterplay to hold the balance.} Re8 21. Rc1 h5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gh5h4] Black has enough counterplay - the pressure against White's kingside and the e2-pawn balance out with the c5-weakness.} 22. Z0 (22. Qd3) (22. Rc2 $6 Qb7 $1 23. f3 h4 24. Kf2 $6 {was Schekachikhin-Agdelen, Vrnjacka Banja 2022. Here} Qd7 $17 {would have been very strong. g6} 25. gxh4 Qb7 {and the game Karjakin-Nepomniachtchi, Stavanger 2021 was soon drawn.}) *

