 on the f1-a6 diagonal.} 11. Qa4 {This appear to both the d-pawn and time, but we will see that White often considers the d4-pawn to be expendable.} Bb5 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. Qa5 {White should play actively.} (12. Qc2 $6 Qxd4 {does not look sufficient after} 13. Be3 Qe5 {Or 13.Bb2 Qc5}) 12... Qxd4 (12... c3 $6 13. Qxc3 Bxe2 14. Re1 {transposes to StartFENr2q1rk1/p1p2ppp/b1p1pn2/8/2pP4/P5P1/P3PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 11EndFEN 11.Qd2 c3?! which we'll come to later.}) 13. Be3 Qd6 {[%cal Gf6d5] Black is up two pawns and has sufficient resources to deal with White's bishops. We will play ...Nd5 after just about anything.} ({Note that after} 13... Qb2 $2 14. Bc5 {hitting the rook and intending a4, Black is in trouble.}) 14. a4 $6 Qa3 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ga3a5] This is a typical resource for Black.} *

