1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Nxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) ({This is almost as popular as} 8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 ({Moves other than} 9. Na3 {are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.}) {This is the main line. We get quite the unusual pawn structure.} 9... Bxa3 10. bxa3 {[%csl Ra2,Ra3,Rc4,Rc6,Rc7] Lovely, isn't it? The play is quite interesting. White has the bishop pair, but Black is often very active. We must always keep in mind the pawn break ...c5, and sometimes ...e5 as well.} Ba6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga6f1] Black protects his frontal c-pawn, which is an asset now. There is also latent pressure on the f1-a6 diagonal.} 11. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] A standard idea. White wants to play Ba3.} Qd6 {[%mdl 32768] So we stop it.} 12. Qd2 (12. Bf4 {gains a tempo, but it makes a4 looks like a waste of time. Black can just play} Qe7 {and if} 13. Bxc6 Rab8 {with the idea ...Nd5.}) 12... Rfb8 ({An independent course.} 12... Rab8 13. Qa5 Rb6 {transposes to 12...Rb6 in the main line, which we consider as an alternative.}) 13. Qa5 Rb6 $13 {[%cal Rc1a3,Gf6d5,Ga8b8,Gc4c3] The position has been seen in a couple of games. It's quite unclear - as is often the case in this line - but I like Black's chances. There is no Ba3, and we are ready to play ...Rab8 and go from there. One thing to know:} 14. e4 $2 {This looks good but we have a trick.} Nxe4 15. Bxe4 (15. Bf4 Qd5 {does not help White.}) 15... Qxd4 {[%cal Gd4e4,Gd4a1] Winning back the material.} 16. Z0 ({White can 'win the exchange' with} 16. Bxh7+) ({(Note that after} 16. Be3 Qxe4 17. Bxb6 axb6 {protects the a6-bishop.)}) {Kxh7 Be3} 16... Qd5 17. Qxd5 cxd5 {Bxb6 axb6 but then he can resign. :} *

