 on the f1-a6 diagonal.} 11. Bxc6 {Of course this is the most obvious move, but grabbing the pawn takes time, and the bishop will often have to retreat, taking more time.} Rb8 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gd8d6] Now ...Nd5 could be an issue for White, as his bishop will not have a smooth road home.} 12. Qa4 {The most common move.} Rb6 {[%cal Gd8d6,Gf6d5] Black has good play - he will go for ...Qd6 or ...Nd5.} 13. Bf3 {A prophylactic retreat, which also covers the e2-pawn.} Nd5 {[%mdl 32768] Black plays in the same way that we saw against 13.Bg2.} 14. Qa5 {White's main choice. The queen stays active.} c3 {[%cal Ga6f1]} (14... f5 $5 {intending ...Qd6 looks fine too.}) 15. Re1 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6d4,Gf6f3] Hitting the d4-pawn while preventing e2-e4. Again,} (15... f5 {is possible.}) 16. Qc5 {[%cal Ga3a4,Ga4a5] This looks like the best try. White wants to use his frontal a-pawn - a typical idea.} ({I am quite skeptical of} 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Qxc3 Rc6 $13 {as seen in Beliavsky-Geller, Moscow 1981.}) 16... Bb5 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb6c6] Black just wants to secure his position with ...a6 and ... Rc6, which would trap White's queen in a favorable way. One game saw Black try to trap the white queen. After} (16... Rb5 17. Qxa7 Rb6 18. a4 Bb7 $2 19. a5 Rb5 20. a4 Ra8 {he was 'successful', but} 21. Qxa8+ Bxa8 22. axb5 $16 {gave White a huge advantage in Pantsulaia-Magalashvili, Tbilisi 2009.}) 17. a4 $5 {White has to stop our plan somehow.} Bxa4 18. Ba3 Rfb8 $132 {[%cal Re2e4,Gf6f3] I prefer Black - active pieces and White still cannot play e4.} *

