1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Nxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) ({This is almost as popular as} 8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 ({Moves other than} 9. Na3 {are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.}) 9... Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] The modern treatment. It looks funny to block in the c1-bishop, but the queen is headed to a5. Although the move was not new, it was revived in 2016 and then interest in 8.Nxc6 heated up.} Rb8 {We grab the open file.} ({Black should avoid the rash} 11... c3 $6 12. Qxc3 Bxe2 13. Re1 Bb5 14. a4 $1 Bxa4 15. Qb4 Bb5 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 $16 {and White wins an exchange, as seen in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is eager to play Ba3.} c5 $5 {This tries to punish White for his unusual move order.} ({Black can also play the more obvious} 12... Qd6 {when} 13. Qa5 Rb6 {reaches our alternative line with 12...Rb6.}) 13. Qa5 Bb7 $1 {[%mdl 32768] Exchanging bishops weakens White's king position, and we have a clear lead in development.} 14. Bxb7 {Other moves are even worse:} (14. dxc5 $2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qd4 $17 {hits the a1-rook and ...Qe4+ is coming. For example} 16. Be3 Qe4+ 17. Kg1 Nd5 $17) (14. Qxc5 $2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qd5+ {gives Black a great endgame after} 16. Qxd5 exd5 {or 16.f3 Qxc5 17.dxc5 Nd5}) 14... Rxb7 15. Qxc5 Qd5 16. Ba3 Rd8 $15 {[%csl Gb7,Rd4,Gd8][%cal Gf6e4] Black's rooks are active and Black's nimble knight is superior to White's bishop.} *

