1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Nxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) ({This is almost as popular as} 8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 ({Moves other than} 9. Na3 {are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.}) 9... Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] The modern treatment. It looks funny to block in the c1-bishop, but the queen is headed to a5. Although the move was not new, it was revived in 2016 and then interest in 8.Nxc6 heated up.} Rb8 {We grab the open file.} ({Black should avoid the rash} 11... c3 $6 12. Qxc3 Bxe2 13. Re1 Bb5 14. a4 $1 Bxa4 15. Qb4 Bb5 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 $16 {and White wins an exchange, as seen in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 Rd8 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. e3 $6 {This looks like a solid move, but it is too slow.} c5 $1 {Surprising and strong!} (14... c3 {is good as well.} 15. Re1 c2 {although this is more complicated}) 15. Qxc5 Nd7 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Qa5 ({White queen gets trapped after} 16. Qxa7 $2 c6 {with ...Ra8 coming}) ({The invasion} 16. Qe7 $2 {does not work after} c3 {hitting White's rook and preparing ...c5 to open the floodgates for Black's pieces.}) 16... c5 $17 {[%csl Ra1,Gb8,Rc1,Gc4,Gd8][%cal Gd7c5] The c-pawns keep coming! The position is opening up and Black has a strong initiative.} *

