en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 Rd8 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Qc5 $6 {This runs into a familiar theme.} Nd7 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 15. Qxc6 Rb6 16. Qf3 Nf6 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gd8d4,Ga6b7] This control the light squares in the center. The d4-pawn is under attack and ...Bb7 is coming. White's queen is awkwardly placed.} ({This is even stronger than} 16... c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 $15) 17. Bg5 {Relatively best. Some bad choices:} (17. e3 c3) (17. Rd1 c5 $17) (17. Be3 Bb7 18. Qf4 Nd5 $17) 17... Rxd4 $1 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Qxf6 Qd8 $15 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd8d1] Material is even, but Black's strong c4-pawn and control of the d-file give him the advantage.} *

