en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 Rd8 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Rd1 $6 {This move has been fairly popular, but today's engines find a clever retort.} e5 $5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Ge5e4,Gd8d1][%mdl 32768] Black fights for the initiative with this surprising move.} ({Black has done well with} 14... c3 {and indeed it's fine, but after} 15. Qxc3 Bxe2 16. Re1 Qa6 17. Qxc6 {it's about equal and White does have the bishop pair as a long term asset.}) 15. Qxe5 {White cannot ignore the pawn.} Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gc4c3,Gd8e8] This is tricky, and White has to play very precisely just to survive.} ({I like this even better than} 15... Re8 16. Qc5 Rxe2 {which is quite good as well.}) 16. e3 $2 {This is losing. Black even has more than one good response.} Qg4 $1 ({Both} 16... c3) ({and} 16... Re8 {are strong as well.}) 17. f3 ({After} 17. Re1 Re8 {White's queen is trapped!} 18. h3 Qg6 {does not change anything.}) 17... Qg6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc4c3,Gd8e8,Gc3c2,Gb8b1] White's queen is in trouble and the c-pawn is a monster.} *

