en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} 14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Bc5 {This move was played by GM Vadim Malakhatko and he scored 3/3 with it! We should be happy to see it however.} Rd5 $1 {Only one of Malakhatko's opponents responded correctly with this move.} 16. Bxd5 $2 ({Better is} 16. Rfb1 Rxb1+ 17. Rxb1 h6 {and we have transposed to the main line with 15.Rfb1.}) 16... cxd5 {The engine already claims that Black is winning!} 17. Bxa7 {Eating a pawn.} (17. Rab1) ({(Or} 17. Rfb1 {)}) {(should be met with)} 17... Ra8 $1 {intending ...c6 and ...Nd7. Then ...e5 will come and the pawns can roll. Ra8} 18. Bc5 ({Or} 18. Bd4 Nd7 {and ...c5.}) 18... e5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gc4c3]} 19. Be7 {This only appears to be an annoyance.} Qe6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qxc7 {White has grabbed another pawn and weakened Black's kingside, but none of this is relevant.} Rc8 22. Qa7 c3 23. Rfe1 d4 {[%cal Ge6d6,Gf6f5,Ge5e4,Gd4d3,Gc3c2] Black prepared ...e4 and ...d3 and won soon in Sevian-Nakamura, chess.com 2022.} *

