en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 ({Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} 14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Rab1 Rxb1 {[%mdl 32768] With this move we simply transpose into the main line.} ({We will consider} 15... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 16. Rxb1 {And of course it's just the same position as it is after StartFEN1rq3k1/p1p2ppp/b1p1pn2/Q7/P1pr4/B5P1/P3PPBP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15EndFEN 15.Rfb1 Rxb1 16.Rxb1 .} h6 {Luft. We also to transport to this variation. [/variation/31307950/#/16/b]} *

