1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Nxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) ({This is almost as popular as} 8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 ({Moves other than} 9. Na3 {are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.}) 9... Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] The modern treatment. It looks funny to block in the c1-bishop, but the queen is headed to a5. Although the move was not new, it was revived in 2016 and then interest in 8.Nxc6 heated up.} Rb8 {We grab the open file.} ({Black should avoid the rash} 11... c3 $6 12. Qxc3 Bxe2 13. Re1 Bb5 14. a4 $1 Bxa4 15. Qb4 Bb5 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 $16 {and White wins an exchange, as seen in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 ({Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} 14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Rab1 Rb6 {[%mdl 32768] This could be played as an alternative if you want, but I am mainly showing it to illustrate why White has preferred 15.Rfb1.} ({With} 15... Rxb1 {we simply transpose into the main line after} 16. Rxb1 h6 {.}) 16. Bc5 Rd7 (16... Rd5 {is an attractive move, offering both rooks, but} 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Qc3 {intending to use both a-pawns to pry open a file for the rooks, favors White.}) 17. Rbd1 {[%csl Rf1] Here White's f1-rook is not doing anything, so White would rather have it on a1. This is the point of White using the f-rook on move 15.} ({Objectively, White should probably play} 17. Bxb6 {when either recapture is playable, and unclear.}) 17... Rd5 $1 {Now that White has left the b-file this improves things for Black.} (17... Nd5 {is also quite good.} 18. e4 Nf6 19. Rxd7 Nxd7 20. Bxb6 cxb6 21. Qc3 Nc5 $13) 18. Bxd5 cxd5 19. Bxb6 axb6 20. Qb4 (20. Qc3 c5 $1 {shows why White would like to have a rook on b1 to hit the b6-pawn.}) 20... Qf8 $1 {[%csl Gb6,Gc4,Gc7,Gd5,Ge6] Black is doing well despite the double exchange deficit.} *

