en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 ({Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} 14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Rfb1 {This is supposed to be rather clever compared to 15.Rab1, but ultimately it may not matter much.} Rxb1+ $5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is simplest, but} 15... Rb6 {is good as well. We'll consider it as an alternative line.}) 16. Rxb1 {[%cal Ga5a6,Gb1b8] Watch out for Qxa6!} h6 $5 {Luft.} 17. Bxc6 $6 {This would be ok, if not for one trick.} c3 $1 18. Qxc3 Rc4 {Leaving White no choice.} 19. Qf3 Qd8 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rc6][%cal Gf6d5,Gd8d2,Gd5c3] Black intends ...Nd5 cutting off the c6-bishop, while invading with ...Qd2 is another possibility. Despite the open position, White's a3-bishop can be ineffective as it strikes into the air.} 20. Z0 ({For example,} 20. Bb5 Bxb5 21. axb5 Qd2 {with a slight initiative.}) *

