1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Ne5 Nc6 {This is a surprising move if one is unfamiliar with it. Black voluntarily allows his structure to be compromised. We have seen in other lines that tripled c-pawns are not always so bad. The main point is that Black is developing quickly, especially considering that White has just moved his knight for a second time. Now White's choice is limited because his d4-pawn is under attack. Both captures on c6 lead to interesting play. The only real alternative is 7...c5 which is very solid but not very interesting. After} 8. Nxc6 ({dxc5 Qc7} 8. Nxc4 {Qxc5 Black can probably gradually equalize, but there are fewer opportunities for counterplay.}) ({This is almost as popular as} 8. Bxc6 {White is not looking to grab a pawn at the cost of his Catalan bishop. Instead he pins his hopes on the strength of this bishop and his apparently superior pawn structure.}) 8... bxc6 {Another line with triple isolated pawns. In exchange for this ugly structure, Black finds it relatively easy to be active.} 9. Na3 ({Moves other than} 9. Na3 {are not so common and are not very dangerous. Black's moves tend to be easy to find and active.}) 9... Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] The modern treatment. It looks funny to block in the c1-bishop, but the queen is headed to a5. Although the move was not new, it was revived in 2016 and then interest in 8.Nxc6 heated up.} Rb8 {We grab the open file.} ({Black should avoid the rash} 11... c3 $6 12. Qxc3 Bxe2 13. Re1 Bb5 14. a4 $1 Bxa4 15. Qb4 Bb5 16. a4 Ba6 17. Ba3 $16 {and White wins an exchange, as seen in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Qc8 {[%cal Gb8b5,Gf8d8,Ya6b5,Yc8a6] We protect the bishop and prepare ...Rd8, while ...Rb5 is also a possibility. Black may also consider ...Bb5 with the idea ... Qa6.} ({We will also consider} 12... Rb6 {as an alternative.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc1a3] White covers the b5-square and prepares Ba3.} Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d4] Hitting the d4-pawn.} (13... Rb6 $6 {is a normal looking move, but it's not right here.} 14. Ba3 {Interestingly enough, I faced} Rd8 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {is better for White.}) 14. Ba3 {The main line. White plays as actively as possible, offering up the d4-pawn as well. Black should bite.} Rxd4 ({Take! Interestingly enough, when playing White I faced} 14... Rb6 {a couple of times. Both} 15. Bc5 {and 15.e3 favor White.}) 15. Rfb1 ({This is supposed to be rather clever compared to} 15. Rab1 {, but ultimately it may not matter much. This is a very playable alternative.}) 15... Rb6 {[%mdl 32768]} (15... Rxb1+ {will be our main line.}) 16. Bc5 Rd7 $1 (16... Rd5 {is playable as well, although after} 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Bxb6 axb6 {White can retreat and then try to open things up with advances of the a-pawns.}) 17. Rd1 (17. Bxb6 cxb6 18. Qc3 {is untested, but it may be a better try.}) 17... Rd5 $1 {Black has a lot of choice here, but this is favored by today's engines, and they like Black.} (17... h6 $2 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Bxb6 cxb6 20. Qd2 $16 {was the stem game So-Nakamura, Sinquefield Cup 2016. Black is ok on material, but Rd1 is coming and White grabs the initiative.}) (17... Rb8 $6 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Bxa7 Ra8 20. Bd4 {was Howell - Adams, Douglas 2016. The bishop pair and passed a-pawn (pawns, actually) give White some advantage.}) (17... Nd5 $5 {worked out well in Jacobson - Ringoir, Charlotte 2018. It's unclear.}) (17... Rxd1+ {was suggested by Max Illingworth.} 18. Rxd1 Rb8 19. Bxa7 Ra8 20. Bd4 Bb5 $13 {is the idea.}) 18. Bxd5 ({It's not easy to find other constructive moves. If} 18. Rab1 Qb8 $5 {forces the pace.}) 18... cxd5 19. Bxb6 axb6 20. Qb4 {Keeping an eye on the b6-pawn.} ({With no rook on b1,} 20. Qc3 {could be met with} c5 $17 {followed by ...d4 and the pawns roll.}) 20... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gc7c5] Now White has only one way to even stay in the game!} 21. Qe7 {The queen is not doing much, but it's still a bit of a nuisance.} Nb8 $13 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb8c6,Gd5d4,Gc4c3] The knight comes to c6 and covers the a5-square, so White's rooks are held at bay. Black's position certainly looks like more fun!} *

