en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Rb6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gb6a6][%mdl 32768] This is a decent alternative which has been played frequently. Black protects his stuff and prepares ...Bb5 when a4 is off the table because of ...Ra6} 13. a4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc1a3] It's now or never.} ({If} 13. Rd1 $6 Bb5) 13... Qd6 {[%cal Rc1a3] Preventing Ba3. Now only a couple of moves are critical.} 14. e4 {This looks strong, but Black has a familiar exchange sacrifice.} (14. Rd1 $6 Nd5 {transposes to the line StartFEN1r1q1rk1/p1p2ppp/b1p1pn2/8/2pP4/P5P1/P2QPPBP/R1B2RK1 w - - 3 12EndFEN 12.Rd1 Rb6 13.a4 Qd6 14.Qa5?!}) (14. Bf4 Qe7 {intending ...Nd5 and ...Rfb8 is comfortable for Black.}) (14. Qc3 {walks into} Nd5 {Then} 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Ba3 Rfb8 {is about equal.}) 14... Qb4 $1 15. Qxb4 Rxb4 16. Ba3 Rxa4 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 $13 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gf6d7,Gd7b6] This is almost identical to the game Iliaguev-Caspi, Israel 2020.} *

