en in Lenderman-Tang, Philadelphia 2016.}) 12. Qa5 Rb6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Gb6a6] This is a decent alternative which has been played frequently. Black protects his stuff and prepares ...Bb5 when a4 is off the table because of ...Ra6} 13. a4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc1a3] It's now or never.} ({If} 13. Rd1 $6 Bb5) 13... Qd6 {[%cal Rc1a3] Preventing Ba3. Now only a couple of moves are critical.} 14. a3 $5 {[%cal Rd6b4] An unusual move that has done well. Mamedyarov used it to score a relatively easy win against So.} (14. Rd1 $6 Nd5 {transposes to the line 12.Rd1 Rb6 13.a4 Qd6 14.Qa5?!}) (14. Bf4 Qe7 {intending ...Nd5 and ...Rfb8 is comfortable for Black.}) (14. Qc3 {walks into} Nd5 {Then} 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Ba3 Rfb8 {is about equal.}) 14... Rd8 {[%mdl 32768]} ({So played} 14... Rfb8 15. e4 c3 $2 {A shocking misassessment. Black should have just moved the queen.} 16. e5 Qd8 17. exf6 Bxf1 18. Bxf1 c2 19. Ra2 {and White was winning in Mamedyarov-So, Riga 2019.}) 15. e4 $6 ({If} 15. Bf4 Qd7 {intending ... Nd5 and maybe ...Qc8. Then} 16. e4 c3 17. Rfc1 c2 $5 18. Rxc2 Bd3 {picks up the e4-pawn.}) 15... Ng4 $17 {[%cal Gd6d4] A funny engine novelty which is very strong. It's not easy to cover the d4-pawn.} (15... Qxd4 16. Be3 Qb2 17. Rfd1 $16 {is good for White.}) 16. Rd1 (16. Be3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 e5 {is strategic capitulation.}) 16... c5 {[%cal Gd8d1] White has serious problems!} 17. Z0 ({If} 17. h3 cxd4 18. hxg4 c5 {gives Black overwhelming compensation.}) *

