1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc4] We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. Qc2 {White regains the pawn this way, but does nothing to interfere with our development plans.} Bc6 10. Qxc4 {[%csl Gc6] So White regained the pawn and has the bishop pair. We have easy play though, and our c6-bishop essentially negated the Catalan bishop on g2.} Bd5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc7c5,Gb8c6] The choice of both Carlsen and So. Other moves are also possible, but I like this nudge of the white queen.} (10... Nbd7 {is more popular, but after} 11. Bf4 {we cannot move our bishop and it's needed to shield the c7-pawn. (We saw this idea in the chapter with 8.a4 Bd7 9.Qxc4 Bc6 10.Bf4.)}) 11. Qc3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c5][%mdl 32768] This is actually a novelty, but it's an obvious move.} (11... Nc6 {has been played too and should be fine, but I like the direct idea of preparing ...c5.}) 12. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] A typical move, but it won't discourage us.} c5 $1 13. dxc5 Rc8 14. Ba3 b6 {[%cal Gd7c5] Next we will play ...Nxc5 with a good position.} (14... Nxc5 {immediately is also possible, as} 15. Bxc5 $6 {can be met with} Ne4 {or 15...Nd7 .}) *

