1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc4] We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is in no hurry to regain the pawn, and instead rushes to play Ba3. This advance may also discourage ...b5 as well as ...Nbd7-b6, but the pawn could prove vulnerable to be vulnerable on a4. Carlsen tried this three times in 2022 - all in different time controls! He beat Giri in a classical game, lost to Nepo in rapid, and then beat Wang Hao in blitz. All of the games were interesting, but none were necessarily decided by the objective assessment of the opening.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Rc1 {This is uncommon and not dangerous, but I will show a cute way to deal with it.} Bd5 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Simply covering the pawn and preparing ...a6 and ...b5.} 12. Ne5 {White has to regain the pawn now or he won't get another chance.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nc6 $1 {We are not going for our usual triped pawns this time.} 14. Nxc6 Qd5+ $1 {Our clever point.} 15. Kg1 Qxc6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Again, White has no time to waste.} 16. Qc2 {This regains the pawn, but we are quick to create counterplay.} e5 $132 {[%csl Ra2,Ra4][%cal Ge8e2] Black is active so White must head for an endgame.} 17. Z0 (17. dxe5 Rxe5 18. Qxc4 Qxc4 19. Rxc4 {and here Black has some choice.} Ne8 $5 {is the most ambitious.} 20. e4 Rd8 {is level, but both sides have chances. 19...Rxe2 is also possible. 20.Rxc7 Rxa2 21.Be7 Rxa4 22.Bxf6 gxf6 23.Rxb7 a5 is obviously fine, but really just a draw as White can bring his f1-rook to the seventh rank.}) *

