1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc4] We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] White is in no hurry to regain the pawn, and instead rushes to play Ba3. This advance may also discourage ...b5 as well as ...Nbd7-b6, but the pawn could prove vulnerable to be vulnerable on a4. Carlsen tried this three times in 2022 - all in different time controls! He beat Giri in a classical game, lost to Nepo in rapid, and then beat Wang Hao in blitz. All of the games were interesting, but none were necessarily decided by the objective assessment of the opening.} Bc6 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gf1e1,Ge2e4] Carlsen's choice. This attacks the c4-pawn, connects the rooks, and also controls the e4-square so that Rfe1 and e4 is a possibility.} Nbd7 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gd7b6,Gc2c4][%mdl 32768]} 12. Rac1 {A patient move, simply increasing the influence on the c-file.} (12. Qxc4 {could be met with} Nb6 {, picking off the a4-pawn, but White may still go for this idea at some point.}) 12... Bd5 ({Giri played} 12... a6 {and this is also a good move. As ...b5 is a real threat, White has to go for} 13. Qxc4 Nb6 14. Qc3 Nxa4 15. Qb3 {Threatening Rxc6.} Qd5 16. Rxc6 $1 Qxc6 17. Ne5 Qb5 18. Qc2 {gave White a serious initiative in Carlsen-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2022, and Black was unable to handle the practical problems.}) 13. Rfe1 a5 $1 {[%csl Ra4] Wang Hao's choice in the blitz game. This freezes White's a-pawn not only to keep it as a target, but to stop it from bothering our knight should it land on b6.} (13... Rc8 $2 14. e4 Bc6 15. Nd2 c3 16. Nb1 $1 Nb6 17. a5 {was very good for White in Carlsen-Nepomniachtchi, chess24. com rapid 2022, although Carlsen later erred and lost.}) 14. Red1 {[%cal Gf3e5] White switches plans and goes to the d-file to prepare Ne5.} ({The immediate} 14. Ne5 {is bad:} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qd5+) ({If} 14. e4 Bc6 {...Nb6 is coming, so White is essentially forced into} 15. Qxc4 Bxe4 16. Qxc7 Bc6 17. Qxd8 Raxd8 {with a nice endgame for Black.}) ({Finally,} 14. h4 h6 $1 {does not change much.} 15. e4 Bc6 16. Ne5 $2 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 {was good for Black in Leenhouts-Michiels, Belgium 2022.}) 14... c6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5] A very ambitious move. Black simply wants to play ...b5-+} ({Black has a few reasonable moves here. Another one is} 14... Qc8 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 c6 19. Rd4 Nxe5 {with unclear play.}) 15. Ne5 b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4] This strong move is easier to find at home than it is in a blitz game!} ({Wang Hao went for simplifications with} 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nb6 17. e4 Nfd7 {but after} 18. Nxc4 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 {White's big space advantage gave him an edge in Carlsen-Wang Hao, Stavanger blitz 2022.}) 16. e4 {This wins a piece, but the black pawn armada will soon force White to part with his gains. (White can also take on c6:)} (16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Bxc6 b4 $1 {when the pawn wave will regain material, for example} 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. Qxc4 $1 bxa3 $13 {with two knights for a rook.}) 16... b4 17. exd5 ({White can retreat with} 17. Bb2 {but ...c3 can be played at any time.}) 17... cxd5 $1 18. Bb2 c3 $13 {Black has obvious compensation and White will certainly be compelled to return the piece. Let's check some lines:} 19. Z0 (19. Ba1 $2 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Nd7 $17) (19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Ba1 Rec8 $13) (19. Bxc3 Rc8 20. Qd2 bxc3 21. Rxc3 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Qb6 {and Black is doing well.}) *

