1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc4] We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. Ne5 {This has always been the main line of 7.Na3, and it's always been considered to be just fine for Black.} Bc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. f3 $2 {This just does not work, because Black has a trick.} Ba4 $1 {A nasty surprise. White is busted already.} 11. Qd2 ({Of course} 11. Qxa4 $2 Qxd4+ {is the point.}) 11... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4,Re5]} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 $17 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gf6d5,Gd5b6,Gf6d7,Gd7b6] Black is up a pawn with a better position.} *

