1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Na3 {A maximalist approach. White aims to recover the pawn. while developing a piece and But we can take this piece, and hold the pawn...} Bxa3 {We cannot let White regain the pawn with no concessions.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc4] We have an in interesting strategic situation. White has the bishop pair, but a pawn less and doubled a-pawns.} Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] A familiar strategy. We cannot fianchetto the bishop properly, so we look to bring the bishop to the long diagonal another way.} 9. Ne5 {This has always been the main line of 7.Na3, and it's always been considered to be just fine for Black.} Bc6 10. Nxc6 {White has to go for this, but it helps us develop.} Nxc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Bxc6 {Of course we have to consider this, but by now we have learned not to be afraid of such a structure.} (11. Rb1 Rb8 {does not change much.}) (11. e3 $6 {just looks like an inaccurate move order after} Nd5) 11... bxc6 {[%cal Gd8d5] With so many exchanges, this about as harmless as it gets with the tripled pawns. White should really continue to chop everything, as we are ready to play ...Qd5 and ...c5, and maybe ...Ne4.} 12. Bg5 h6 {This is nice and clean.} (12... Qd5 {allowing} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 {is also fine though.}) 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc6c5] We are ready to pressure the d4-pawn and break with ...c5.} 14. Rc1 c5 $1 {This either eliminates White's d-pawn, or uses it to shield our c7-pawn.} 15. Z0 ({For example} 15. dxc5) ({or} 15. Rxc4 cxd4 {Qb2!? Many other moves are fine too. Rxc4 Qxa2= with a certain symmetry, and equality, in Xiong-Radjabov, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019.}) *

