1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Nc3 {This is a very natural developing move, but it has never been popular. White may still seek to recover the pawn with typical moves like Qa4 or Ne5, so Black should be prepared to meet these ideas.} Nc6 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. e4 ({This discourages both of White's attempts to quickly recapture the pawn. Now White has choice to make. He can play the aggressive} 8. e4 {or the more restrained}) (8. e3 {.}) ({The most aggressive. Black must always consider the advance of the central pawns. This does block the Catalan bishop however, and the d4-pawn can be weak sometimes. White has done poorly in practice, but Magnus Carlsen recently wheeled this line out against Anish Giri. Other moves are easier to dismiss: A)} 8. Qa4 $2 Nxd4 {is another pawn.}) ({B)} 8. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 {(I prefer this to 8...Nxd4 9.Nxc4 )} 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Bf4 g5 {and again we'll grab a second pawn.}) 8... a6 {This simply prepares ...b5.} ({It's a tough choice between this and the} 8... Rb8 {, with similar ideas. After digging a bit, I preferred the pawn move against both 8.e4 and 8.e3.}) 9. d5 {This advance looks premature.} ({The hasty} 9. e5 $2 Nd5 $17 {does not help White's cause.}) ({We can meet} 9. a4 $6 {with a standard idea:} Na5 $1 {fixing on the b3-square and preparing ...c5, is also nice for Black.}) 9... exd5 10. exd5 Na5 $5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8f5,Gf8e8,Ge7d6] Black holds onto the pawn and can develop all of his pieces easily. The isolated d5-pawn is hardly an asset. White should already think about groveling for a draw.} ({Black is also quite ok after} 10... Nb4 11. Ne5 Bf5 12. a3 Nd3 13. Nxc4 {for example} Nxc1 14. Rxc1 Bd6) 11. Bd2 {Taking aim at the a5-knight, but letting go of the d5-pawn.} Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gf3e5] This hits the bishop and prepares Ne5.} Nc6 {This forces White into the following sequence where we are clearly playing for two results.} ({Black could also try} 13... Bf6 {when our queen will get bounced around after} 14. Ng5 {as we have to stay in touch with our knight. You can explore this if you'd like.}) 14. Ne5 Qc5 15. Bxc6 ({After} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 {the c-pawns are ugly, but two of them are extra!}) 15... bxc6 16. Bb4 $1 {A nice trick, but White is still just clinging to life.} Qxb4 17. Nxc6 Qxb2 18. Nxe7+ Kh8 19. Nxc8 Raxc8 $15 {[%csl Gc4,Gc7] We have two extra pawns. The engine says our edge is only slight. We may not win, but we certainly shouldn't lose!} *

