1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd1a4] This is a very natural developing move, but it has never been popular. White may still seek to recover the pawn with typical moves like Qa4 or Ne5, so Black should be prepared to meet these ideas.} Nc6 $1 8. e4 ({This discourages both of White's attempts to quickly recapture the pawn. Now White has choice to make. He can play the aggressive} 8. e4 {or the more restrained}) (8. e3 {.}) ({The most aggressive. Black must always consider the advance of the central pawns. This does block the Catalan bishop however, and the d4-pawn can be weak sometimes. White has done poorly in practice, but Magnus Carlsen recently wheeled this line out against Anish Giri. Other moves are easier to dismiss: A)} 8. Qa4 $2 Nxd4 {is another pawn.}) ({B)} 8. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 {(I prefer this to 8...Nxd4 9.Nxc4 )} 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Bf4 g5 {and again we'll grab a second pawn.}) 8... a6 {This simply prepares ...b5.} ({It's a tough choice between this and the} 8... Rb8 {, with similar ideas. After digging a bit, I preferred the pawn move against both 8.e4 and 8.e3.}) 9. Qe2 {This has traditionally been White's main choice, even though it leaves the d-pawn to it's fate.} ({A)} 9. e5 $2 Nd5 $17 {does not help White's cause.}) ({B)} 9. a4 $6 Na5 $1 {fixing on the b3-square and preparing ...c5, is also nice for Black.}) 9... b5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] I prefer protecting our extra pawn to grabbing another. After} (9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 $13 {our queen will be banished and White will play e4-e5 with a strong initiative.}) 10. Rd1 {[%cal Gd4d5] The threat of d5 is no joke.} Bb7 {This allows complications, but we should not fear them.} (10... Nb4 {is also a decent move.}) 11. d5 $1 {If White does not go for this, we have the useful moves ...Nb4 and ...Re8.} exd5 12. e5 $1 {[%csl Rd5] This is a very standard operation for White.} Re8 {[%cal Ge5f6,Ge7f6] And this is a standard response.} ({Instead} 12... Nd7 13. Nxd5 {is tremendous for White.}) ({Black could consider} 12... Nxe5 $5 13. Nxe5 Re8 {followed by ...c6. Here the clump of pawns is sturdy, but not yet mobile.}) 13. exf6 Bxf6 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gd5][%cal Ge8e2,Gd5d4] Black's pawn armada looks impressive.} 14. Be3 $1 {Now the d5-pawn is under fire, so Black has to advance.} d4 15. Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Gg2b7,Gd1d8] The following moves are forced.} Nxd4 16. Rxd4 $1 Bxd4 17. Bxb7 Rb8 $1 ({We should check out} 17... Bxe3 $6 {Interestingly enough, this move works out for Black if the moves 9.h4 and 9...h6 are inserted! We'll see why when we get to 9.h4.} 18. Bxa8 Ba7 $2 {Better, but still insufficient, is 18...Bxf2+ 19.Qxf2 Qxa8} 19. Be4 {White is able to hold onto the material.} b4 20. Rd1 Qf6 21. Nd5 Qe5 22. Nxb4 {White is winning here as Nc6 is coming and we cannot take the bishop because of back rank mate, but we will see a big difference with the moves of the h-pawns.}) 18. Bc6 ({If} 18. Rd1 Rxb7 19. Qf3 $1 {(The endgame clearly favors Black after 19.Rxd4 Qxd4! )} Rb6 20. Rxd4 Rd6 {is similar.}) 18... Re6 19. Rd1 Rxc6 20. Rxd4 Rd6 {Black is fine with a rook and two pawns vs. the bishop and knight.} *

