1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd1a4] This is a very natural developing move, but it has never been popular. White may still seek to recover the pawn with typical moves like Qa4 or Ne5, so Black should be prepared to meet these ideas.} Nc6 $1 8. e4 ({This discourages both of White's attempts to quickly recapture the pawn. Now White has choice to make. He can play the aggressive} 8. e4 {or the more restrained}) (8. e3 {.}) ({The most aggressive. Black must always consider the advance of the central pawns. This does block the Catalan bishop however, and the d4-pawn can be weak sometimes. White has done poorly in practice, but Magnus Carlsen recently wheeled this line out against Anish Giri. Other moves are easier to dismiss: A)} 8. Qa4 $2 Nxd4 {is another pawn.}) ({B)} 8. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 {(I prefer this to 8...Nxd4 9.Nxc4 )} 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Bf4 g5 {and again we'll grab a second pawn.}) 8... a6 {This simply prepares ...b5.} ({It's a tough choice between this and the} 8... Rb8 {, with similar ideas. After digging a bit, I preferred the pawn move against both 8.e4 and 8.e3.}) 9. h4 $5 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ge4e5] This was Carlsen's choice. A very deep idea! Serbian Grandmaster Alexandr Predke played this move twice in the 2022 World Rapid Championship. he lost both games, but not because of the opening. Apparently the world's strongest player took notice.} h6 {[%cal Rf3g5][%mdl 32768] After some though Giri chooses the most practical option.} ({Predke faced the natural} 9... b5 {in one of his games.} 10. e5 Nd5 11. Ng5 h6 12. Nh3 $1 {This looks rather artificial, but White has many attacking ideas, such as Qg4, Nf4, Be4, Bxh6} b4 $2 {This ignores the real threat.} 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Nf4 Be6 15. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 16. Qg4 {This was Predke-Yu Yangyi, Almaty rapid 2022. White threatens both Qxe6+ and Bxh6 and has a big advantage, although it's still complicated and Black went on to win.}) 10. Qe2 b5 11. Rd1 {[%csl Bh4,Bh6] So this is just like the 9.Qe2 line, but with the moves of the h-pawns thrown in.} Bb7 12. d5 {We have to check this of course.} exd5 13. e5 {[%csl Rd5]} Re8 ({Here too Black could consider} 13... Nxe5 $5) 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Be3 $1 {Now we will check the complications compared with the h-pawns moving.} d4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bxd4 18. Bxb7 Bxe3 $1 {This works now.} ({Here too,} 18... Rb8 {is possible and basically the same as it was with the h-pawns at home:} 19. Bc6 Re6 20. Rd1 Rxc6 21. Rxd4 Rd6 $13 {or Bd5 Rxe3! fxe3 Bxc3} 22. Rd1 $13 {Bf6 Bxf7+ Kxf7 Rxd8 Rxd8=}) 19. Bxa8 Ba7 $1 20. Be4 {This was winning for White with both h-pawns still at home.} b4 21. Rd1 Qf6 22. Nd5 $6 Qe5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Rg3][%cal Ge5e4,Ge5g3,Ra7g1] Here we have no back rank problems (9...h6!) and White's g3-pawn is under attack (because of 9.h4).} *

