line, but with the moves of the h-pawns thrown in. Black has the g5-square covered, but the pawn itself could be a target.} Bb7 12. d5 {We have to check this of course.} exd5 13. e5 Re8 ({Here too Black could consider} 13... Nxe5 $5) 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Be3 $1 {Now we will check the complications compared to the informational line with 9.Qe2 Bb7.} d4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxd4 Bxd4 18. Bxb7 Bxe3 $1 {This works now.} ({Here too,} 18... Rb8 {is possible and basically the same as it was with the h-pawns at home:} 19. Bc6 Re6 20. Rd1 Rxc6 21. Rxd4 Rd6 $13 {or Bd5 Rxe3! fxe3 Bxc3} 22. Rd1 $13 {Bf6 Bxf7+ Kxf7 Rxd8 Rxd8=}) 19. Bxa8 Ba7 $1 20. Be4 {This was winning for White with both h-pawns still at home.} b4 21. Na4 Qd4 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({We cannot go} 21... f5 $4 22. Qxc4+) 22. Re1 {Black has two pawns for the knight and could play a quiet move, with decent compensation, but there's a another way.} Rxe4 $5 (22... Re5 {and}) (22... g6 {are both ok too.}) 23. Qxe4 Qxf2+ 24. Kh1 Qxg3 {With compensation for a rook! The engines show that White should take some care, and that the games shold end with one player delivering perpetual check.} *

