o win.}) 10. Qe2 b5 11. Rd1 {[%csl Rg5,Rh6] So this is just like the 9.Qe2 line, but with the moves of the h-pawns thrown in. Black has the g5-square covered, but the pawn itself could be a target.} Bb7 12. Bf4 {Carlsen's choice.} Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gc6b4,Gc7c5][%mdl 32768] The engine move. Black wants to play ...Nb4 and ...c5. It's not easy to find anything for White.} ({Giri, surely caught off guard, played} 12... Re8 {which is also good.} 13. e5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. e6 Rf8 {was Carlsen-Giri, Stavanger 2023, while the computer likes 15...f6!?}) 13. Bh3 $5 {[%cal Gh3c8,Gd4d5] An interesting move where we have to know some stuff.} Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6b4] Dodging the h3-bishop and offering to return the pawn.} 14. Bxc7 $6 {This is not very good, but it's not easy to offer advice.} b4 $1 15. e5 ({After} 15. Na4 {Black has} Nxd4 $1) ({If White passively retreats with} 15. Nb1 {, Black completely takes over with} Rc8 16. Bf4 Na5 $1 {hitting the e4-pawn and preparing ...c3.}) 15... Nd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. e6 {If White does not play this, we will go ...Bc8! anyway.} Bc8 $15 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd5][%cal Gc8h3] White has regained the pawn, but I like Black because of the nice pawns pawns on the queenside. We are happy to exchange light squared bishops.} *

