1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd1a4]} Nc6 8. e3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd1e2,Gd1a4,Gf3d2] This is more restrained. White secures the d4-pawn and can look to regain the c4-pawn with Nd2, Qe2, or Qa4, depending on what Black does next. The downside is that it weakens the light squares and locks in the c1-bishop. Black will generally try to hold onto the pawn, but not with all his might. White will have to make some concession to regain it (moving his knight or queen around) and we can use this time to develop in a comfortable way.} a6 {[%mdl 32768] This is uncommon in this position, but it is as strong as the alternatives and consistent with our answer to 8.e4.} ({The alternative} 8... Rb8 {is similar, and more popular.}) ({A completely different idea is} 8... Bd6 {planning ...e5 next against pretty much anything. This has scored well in practice. All of these moves are quite playable.}) 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] White simply wants to take the pawn, but this is time consuming.} Na5 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf6d5,Ga8b8] I like this consistent approach.} ({This is simplest, but} 9... e5 $5 {is also quite good.} 10. Bxc6 exd4 11. exd4 bxc6 12. Nxc4 Re8 {Black has to be fine here with his bishop pair, and White's weakened kingside. It's still rather unclear though.}) 10. Qa4 {White hits the knight and prepare to regain the pawn.} c5 ({Black uses the time White spends regaining the pawn to strike in the center and complete development. I also found the amusing} 10... b6 $5 {hanging a rook! After} 11. Bxa8 Bd7 12. Qc2 Qxa8 {Black's compensation looks great, but White can fight back with} 13. b3 $1 {After} cxb3 14. axb3 Nc6 {is unclear, but I don't think that Black is so well coordinated.}) 11. Nxc4 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 b5 13. Qe2 Rb8 {[%cal Gc8b7] So we played both ...a6 and ...Rb8 after all. Black plays ...Bb7 next, and looks totally fine.} *

