1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] This is quite are, and rightfully so. It's almost an ideal move - White wants to regain the pawn, but he's not moving his queen around and it even develops a new piece. It just doesn't work...} b5 {This is basically forced, but it's good!} 8. a4 {[%csl Rd2] This is by far the most common move, and I've faced it in blitz few times. It's thematic, but probably just bad! White's d2-knight is misplaced.} c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Ne5 (9. e4 $2 {just doesn't give White anything. The d2-knight is silly. Choose your weapon:} Bb7 $17 {, 9...Na6 $17 , 9...a5 $17}) (9. axb5 $2 {removes White's option of a d4-d5 break.} cxb5 10. Ne5 {(Or 10.Ng5 Nd5 $17 ) .} Nd5 11. e4 Nb4 $17 {.}) 9... Nd5 {The only move, but Black is much better.} 10. e4 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4c6,Gb4d3] The knight is great here. It's untouchable and it gives the c6-pawn some extra protection.} ({After} 10... Nf6 11. d5 $13 {matters are not so clear.}) 11. d5 {There's not much else to try.} Qc7 $1 ({Worse is} 11... exd5 $6 12. exd5 {opening the diagonal of the Catalan bishop.}) ({The computer likes} 11... a5 $146 {with the idea} 12. dxc6 Ba6 $17) 12. Nxc6 $2 {This has been universally played.} ({It's better to try} 12. Ndf3 {but Black is still better after} cxd5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. axb5 a6 $1 {intending ...Bb7. Even if White wins the pawn back, he is not well coordinated and Black is developing smoothly.}) 12... N8xc6 13. dxc6 Ba6 $17 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2][%cal Gb4d3,Gb4c6,Gf8d8] Black is just a pawn up with a better position. There is no compensation because White's d2-knight is clogging everything up.} *

