1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] This is quite are, and rightfully so. It's almost an ideal move - White wants to regain the pawn, but he's not moving his queen around and it even develops a new piece. It just doesn't work...} b5 {This is basically forced, but it's good!} 8. a4 {[%csl Rd2] This is by far the most common move, and I've faced it in blitz few times. It's thematic, but probably just bad! White's d2-knight is misplaced.} c6 9. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b3] White wants to play b3 without allowing ...c3.} Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b4][%mdl 32768] This unconventional move is quite strong.} ({If} 9... Bb7 10. b3 $1 cxb3 11. Nxb3 $13 {gives White genuine compensation because our bishop is locked up.}) 10. b3 {White doesn't have anything better.} Nb4 11. Qb2 Ba6 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rb2,Rc1,Rd2] Black can simply hold onto the material because White's queenside is jumbled up.} ({Again,} 11... cxb3 $2 12. Nxb3 $13 {is the wrong idea.}) 12. Ne5 $2 {This is thematic, but bad.} ({There is no salvation though, for example} 12. bxc4 bxc4 {when Black has much more active pieces and the c4-pawn is a strength.}) ({Perhaps} 12. axb5 cxb5 13. Ne5 {is best, but} Rc8 $17 {is still a good extra pawn for Black.}) 12... Nfd5 $1 {[%cal Gc4c3] Threatening ...c3.} 13. bxc4 (13. Ne4 cxb3 $17 {is a good extra pawn.}) 13... bxc4 14. Nexc4 {White finally got his pawn back, but Black is fully mobilized.} c5 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rb2,Rc1,Rc4,Rd2][%cal Ge7f6,Rd4c5,Ga8b8] Everything is opening up. The engine has this at about -3.50!} *

