1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O ({By far the main move. We will also check} 6. Qc2 {and}) (6. Nc3 {.}) 6... dxc4 ({This is the classical setup. Black can also play the Closed Catalan with} 6... c6 {.}) 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] This is quite are, and rightfully so. It's almost an ideal move - White wants to regain the pawn, but he's not moving his queen around and it even develops a new piece. It just doesn't work...} b5 {This is basically forced, but it's good!} 8. b3 {This rare move may actually be the best try, but it still feels like White is grasping at straws.} c3 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is very natural, but} 8... cxb3 $5 {ensuring a pawn advantage, is good too. It's just (unnecessarily) complicated.} 9. Qxb3 a6 $5 10. a4 b4 11. Ne5 Qxd4 $5 12. Bxa8 Qxe5 $132 {is one possibility.}) 9. Nb1 b4 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3] White has to break up the pawns immediately.} 10. a3 Bb7 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. Qd3 {This regains the pawn. White is equal, which is an achievement in this line.} (12. Bg5 $2 {is too slow.} c5 13. Qd3 Nc6 $17 {was Anastasian-Granda Zuniga, New York 1998.}) 12... c5 {Simplest.} ({Black could play} 12... a5 13. Nxc3 Ba6 14. Qc2 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxe2 {but I think White has reasonable compensation here.}) 13. Nxc3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {Black has various moves here that are equal.} Nbd7 ({Note that} 15... e5 {does not win because of} 16. Na2 $1) ({After} 15... Nbd7 16. Nc6 Qb6 17. Nxb4 Qxb4 {is equal, and} 18. Ba3 {is met with} Qb7+ {.}) *

