1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nc3 {This move has always been around, but in 2018 Fabiano Caruana revived an uncommon interpretation of White's play against Hikaru Nakamura. This started a revolution of sorts, and White scored heavily. Nowadays it is one more main line to deal with, rather than a 'harmless sideline'.} dxc4 ({We will not be scared of of our normal plans. From White's perspective,} 6... c6 {has to be considered, with an early committal to Nc3 in a Closed Catalan.}) 7. Ne5 {The point of White's play. It looks similar to the StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 line, but the switch of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O for 6.Nc3 greatly changes things. This was not appreciated for a long time. 7.O-O transposes the to StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Nc3 line. 7.Qa4 a6 8.Qxc4 b5 leaves the c3-knight misplaced. Black will play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5 with an easy game.} Nc6 $1 {Perhaps this is what white players want to see, but I am stubborn.} ({Theoretically,} 7... c5 {holds up just fine, but after} 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White has played six (!) moves here with some success. Although Black is ok, he must play precisely while White is generally playing for two results.}) ({A curious idea is} 7... Qd6 {The queen may head to a6, while ...Rd8 is facilitated. It still looks a bit artificial to me, and you can look up the game Nisipeanu-Nakamura, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 for further discouragement.}) 8. Bxc6 ({The best move. Instead} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. O-O {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} c5 {This is the most common move, but White's good results have prompted Black to look at alternatives.} 12. dxc5 $1 {White would rather leave Black with an ugly c4-pawn than take it!} ({For a long time, focus was on} 12. Qxc4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 14. Qh4 Rb8 {when Black has good compensation. A well-known model game for Black went} 15. O-O Rb4 16. e4 h6 17. Re1 Rd8 18. f3 $6 Rd3 19. Kg2 Qb7 20. Re2 Bg4 $1 21. fxg4 Nxe4 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 {Markowski-Onischuk, Polanica Zdroj 1999}) 12... Qxc5 13. Be3 Qc7 {White's focus is his better structure, and his bishop is generally better too.} 14. O-O-O {White played this and won in the aforementioned game, Caruana-Nakamura, Saint Louis 2018.} ({Black's problems are magnified by the fat that both} 14. Rd1 {and}) (14. f3 $5 {intending Kf2, are also quite challenging.}) *

