/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. O-O {This has only been tried a few times. It looks logical of course but it becomes a bit more complicated for White to eat the c4-pawn.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] This is one of Black's main ideas in this line. The bishop wants to come to a6.} 13. Re1 ({Covering the e2-pawn. In practice Black has not found the best reaction here.} 13. Qxc4 {is still playable - we consider it via the move order StartFENr1b2rk1/p1p1qppp/4p3/3n4/Q1pP4/2N3P1/PP2PP1P/R1B1K2R w KQ - 2 12EndFEN 12.Qxc4 a5 13.O-O .}) 13... Nb4 $146 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc8b7,Gc8d7,Gf8d8,Gc7c5] I like this disruptive move, which most in the spirit of the position. Black shields the c4-pawn and prepares ...Bd7 chasing away the White queen.} (13... Qb4 {is a typical move, as we shall see. It just does not work well in this position.} 14. a3 $1 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 $16 {was Theodorou-Hakobyan, Saint Louis 2022. In a similar position we will see Black react with 14...Nxc3 but it does not work here because of 15.axb4 Nxa4 16.Rxa4 $16}) (13... Rd8 14. Qxc4 Qb4 15. Qxb4 Nxb4 16. Rd1 Nc2 {wins back the pawn, but after the precise} 17. Bg5 $1 f6 18. Rac1 $1 Nxd4 19. Be3 c5 20. Rd2 $14 {White kept an edge in Svane-Nisipeanu, Hamburg 2022.}) (13... Nb6 {is the initial recommendation of my engine. After} 14. Qc6 Qd6 15. Qxd6 cxd6 16. Bf4 {Black has to be careful, as} d5 $2 {just loses after} 17. Bd6 Re8 18. Nb5 {Instead 16...Rd8 is about equal, but I am still not too thrilled with the position.}) 14. a3 {White should force the pace, else Black can just play ...c5.} Bd7 ({I also considered the tricky} 14... Bb7 {If} 15. axb4 axb4 {White has to find} 16. Bg5 $1 {to survive. Unfortunately 15.Bd2! Bc6 16.Qd1 Nd5 17.e4 looks a little better for White.}) 15. Qd1 Nd5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gf7f5,Ga8b8] This looks equal to me. Black's c4-pawn is not easy to attack, and as usual Black does not mind having opposite colored bishops on the board.} 16. Z0 ({If} 16. e4 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Rab8 {already favors Black.}) ({White should settle for} 16. Bd2 f5 {with unclear play.}) *

