PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Nxd5 {It certainly looks questionable to open the e-file.} exd5 14. Qc5 {The sober move, but Black's game still looks easier.} Qe6 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gf8e8,Gc8a6,Ga5a4][%mdl 32768] Of course we avoid the exchange of queens.} 15. Be3 Ba6 {Now White can't castle without dropping the e2-pawn.} 16. Rc1 a4 (16... Rfb8 {looks good too.}) 17. Qc6 {Taking on c7 would be too much, as Black would take control of the c-file.} Qe4 18. O-O {White didn't have much choice at this point.} Bxe2 19. Rfe1 Bg4 20. Bd2 Qxd4 21. Bc3 Qc4 22. Qxc4 dxc4 {By now Black is up a pawn. It's still just level though, and the game Piorun-Van Foreest, Paris 2022 was soon drawn.} *

