PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. O-O {This is quite a serious move, even though it appears to drop the e2-pawn.} Ba6 14. Qa4 Nxc3 {The obvious move, but it's not so simple. Black can still play this way but it does not appeal to me.} 15. bxc3 {[%cal Gc1a3] White suddenly threatens Ba3 - this is the little trick.} Qe8 ({After} 15... Bxe2 16. Re1 {Gustafsson gave the following line in his Chess24 course:} Bf3 17. Ba3 Qe8 18. Qc2 Bb7 19. Rab1 {but not 19.Bxf8? Qc6} Qc6 20. Rxb7 $1 Qxb7 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Re5 {when White has the more pleasant position.}) 16. Qxe8 ({Black's compensation is clearer with queen on the board.} 16. Qc2 Qc6 $13) 16... Rfxe8 17. Re1 e5 {Black had some compensation in Niemann-Yankelevich, Belgrade 2021 and drew, but it still feels like White is playing for two results here.} *

