PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. O-O {This is quite a serious move, even though it appears to drop the e2-pawn.} Ba6 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Qa4 Rfd8 $5 {[%csl Rd4] As played by Nisipeanu. We renew the threat to take on c3 and e2, while the d4-pawn may also become a target.} (14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 {White suddenly threatens Ba3 - this is the little trick. Black can still play this way but it does not appeal to me. We will look at it as an informational line.}) (14... Rfb8 $5 {is a suggestion of Stockfish. It considers that Black can play slowly, for example} 15. Re1 h6 $5 {There's nothing forcing, but it's not easy for White to develop comfortably.}) 15. Re1 {Guarding e2.} ({After} 15. Nxd5 Rxd5 {the e2-pawn is under attack, and ...c5 will open things up. Black's compensation is not going anywhere.}) ({While the retreat} 15. Qc2 {can be met with} c5 {immediately, again with good compensation.}) 15... Qb4 $1 {An active and disruptive move, seeking to press matters while we still have a lead in development.} 16. Qxb4 {This is quite harmless.} Nxb4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb4c2]} 17. Rd1 Nc2 {We will win back the pawn, and maybe more!} 18. Rb1 Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4e2]} 19. Bf4 ({White cannot play} 19. Kf1 $2 {as} Nxe2 {can be played anyway.}) 19... Nxe2+ ({There is also} 19... c5 {as seen in Sapenov-Grebnev, Chelyabinsk 2022. This keeps pieces on the board, but we can also force equality.}) 20. Nxe2 Bxe2 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Bxc7 Rd5 {We have won back the pawn and it's just equal.} *

