mmediately, again with good compensation.}) 15... Qb4 $1 {An active and disruptive move, seeking to press matters while we still have a lead in development.} 16. a3 {Nisipeanu faced this move. It's the engine's first choice, but the Romanian GM had no problems neutralizing White's play.} Nxc3 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This leads to simplifications. We will get the pawn back, and then just need a couple of accurate moves to quell any white mini-initiative.} 17. axb4 ({Clearly} 17. Qxb4 $6 axb4 18. bxc3 bxc3 {is no good for White.}) 17... Nxa4 18. Rxa4 Rxd4 19. Rxa5 Rxb4 20. Bf4 Bb7 ({The computer actually prefers} 20... Rb5 21. Rxb5 Bxb5 22. Bxc7 f6 {and in fact this should be an easy draw, but we do not have to give up the pawn.}) 21. Rxa8+ ({Here the machines suggest} 21. Rd1 {but after} Rc8 {intending ...f6 I don't see any danger. Note that} 22. Bxc7 {is simply met with} Rxb2) 21... Bxa8 22. Bxc7 f6 $1 {[%csl Rb2]} ({Avoiding} 22... Rxb2 $4 23. Rd1 $1 {when Black can resign.}) ({After} 22... f6 $1 23. Rd1 Bd5 {White can even lose with} 24. Rd2 $2 Rc4 {, while} 25. Ba5 {Rxb2= was a dead draw in Bindrich-Nisipeanu, Magdeburg 2019.}) *

