1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nc3 {This move has always been around, but in 2018 Fabiano revived an uncommon interpretation of White's play against Hikaru Nakamura. This started a revolution of sorts, and White scored heavily. Nowadays it is one more main line to deal with, rather than a 'harmless sideline'.} dxc4 ({We will not be scared of of our normal plans. From White's perspective,} 6... c6 {has to be considered, with an early committal to Nc3 in a Closed Catalan.}) 7. Ne5 {The point of White's play. It looks similar to the StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 line, but the switch of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O for 6.Nc3 greatly changes things. This was not appreciated for a long time. 7.O-O transposes the to StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Nc3 line. 7.Qa4 a6 8.Qxc4 b5 leaves the c3-knight misplaced. Black will play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5 with an easy game.} Nc6 $1 {Perhaps this is what white players want to see, but I am stubborn.} ({Theoretically,} 7... c5 {holds up just fine, but after} 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White has played six (!) moves here with some success. Although Black is ok, he must play precisely while White is generally playing for two results.}) ({A curious idea is} 7... Qd6 {The queen may head to a6, while ...Rd8 is facilitated. It still looks a bit artificial to me, and you can look up the game Nisipeanu-Nakamura, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 for further discouragement.}) 8. Bxc6 ({The best move. Instead} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. O-O {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Bd2 {The most popular, the choice of the engines, and the most complicated.} Ba6 {[%mdl 32768]} 14. Qc5 $1 {The only challenging move.} ({Both} 14. Qb3 Rfb8 15. Qc2 c5) ({and} 14. Qa4 Rfb8 {hitting the b2-pawn and planning ...c5, give Black great play.}) 14... Qd7 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf8b8] Dodging the queen trade and planning ...Rfb8, activating everything. We still have a comfortable lead in development, and White's queen position is a bit sketchy.} ({In his Chess24 course, Jon Ludvig Hammer points out that Black should really be able to draw after} 14... Qxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 a4 {intending ...Bb5 and ...f6, but White can certainly play on for a long time, and there's no upside for us here.}) 15. Rc1 {I guess White is trying to 'pressure' us on the c-file, but I think White should have other priorities.} (15. O-O-O {? was played once, but this move is a disaster, and does not even merit a trainable line.} Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Bxe2 {regains the pawn, and Black's king is much safer than White's.} 17. Rde1 Qb5 $17 {was Ning Kaiyu-Xiao Yiyi, Xinghua 2020, and 17...Qd5! 18.Kb1 Bc4-+ looks even stronger.}) 15... Rfb8 {The most natural.} 16. b3 Nxc3 {Exchanging these knights is a standard plan.} 17. Rxc3 ({If} 17. Qxc3 a4 $132 {creates immediate counterplay.}) 17... Rb5 ({Forcing matters.} 17... a4 $5 {is possible here as well.}) 18. Qxc7 Qxd4 19. Be3 Qf6 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ga5a4] Keeping in touch with the shaky c3-rook.} ({Instead} 19... Qe4 $6 {allowed White to consolidate with} 20. O-O {and f3 in Oparin-Buhmann, Skopje 2019.}) 20. O-O Rd5 $1 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ga8c8,Gh7h6,Ga6e2,Gd5d8] A multipurpose move. The e2-pawn is now attacked, and Black secures his back rank so that ...Rc8 is a threat.} *

