y active and we start with hitting the b2-pawn.} 16. b3 {A natural move. It does not look important, but the c3-knight is less secure, while White's queen may get a bit stuck.} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] A nice move, preparing ...Rc6.} 17. Rc1 {Bringing some protection to the c3-knight.} Rc6 18. Qa3 {A critical position.} ({Again,} 18. Qxa5 $2 Qe8 {is too much to handle. This happened in Kardashevskiy-Petrov, Arandjelovac 2022.}) 18... Nb4 $5 {[%cal Gd7d4] White's queen is away from the action so Black begins tactical play.} (18... Nb6 $6 {is the only move seen as practice, but it allows White to consolidate his structural advantage.} 19. Ne4 {Even giving back the pawn with check is good. 19.Kf2!? Qxd4+ 20.Be3} Rxc1+ 20. Qxc1 Qxd4 21. Be3 $1 Qb4+ 22. Kf2 $16 {and White's structural advantage is important.}) ({I also investigated} 18... e5 $5 {, which looks similar to our main line.}) 19. Kf2 $5 {A clever move. White gives the pawn back with check in order to complete development.} Qxd4+ {[%mdl 32768]} 20. Be3 Qe5 {[%csl Rc3] Keeping pressure on the c3-knight.} 21. Qb2 ({Not} 21. Ne4 $4 Nc2 $1) 21... Nxa2 {This little trick is the simplest.} ({Also possible is} 21... Nd5 $5 22. Nd1 Qd6 {when Black should be active enough to compensation for White's better structure.}) 22. Qxa2 (22. Bf4 Qf6 {does not change much.}) 22... Rxc3 23. Rxc3 Qxc3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gh1c1] White will likely win back the pawn and we'll have total equality.} *

