y active and we start with hitting the b2-pawn.} 16. Rb1 {White protects the b-pawn without commiting his pawn structure.} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] The same idea as we saw before.} 17. Qxa5 {This was bad before, but it is much trickier here.} Qd8 $5 {[%cal Ga6e2][%mdl 32768] We have to be equally clever.} ({The response we saw before,} 17... Qe8 {, does not work here, as without a pawn on b3, the white queen has a way home:} 18. Qa4 $1 Rc6 19. Qd1 $16) 18. Qc5 ({If} 18. Nxd5 exd5 $13 {is the usual good compensation.}) 18... Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] Now we are back on track, threatening ...Rc6 when White's queen will be in some trouble.} 19. a4 $1 {[%cal Gc5a3] Creating a haven for the queen.} ({Again, we are not dissuaded by} 19. Nxd5 exd5 {when we suddenly threaten mate on e2.}) 19... Rab8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb6b2] We have a lot of pressure here.} 20. Z0 ({If} 20. Qa3 Rb3 {drives the queen into oblivion and we can open the position with ...c5.}) *

