PBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Bd2 {The most popular, the choice of the engines, and the most complicated.} Ba6 14. Qc5 $1 {The only challenging move.} ({Both} 14. Qb3 Rfb8 15. Qc2 c5) ({and} 14. Qa4 Rfb8 {hitting the b2-pawn and planning ...c5, give Black great play.}) 14... Qd7 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf8b8] Dodging the queen trade and planning ...Rfb8, activating everything. We still have a comfortable lead in development, and White's queen position is a bit sketchy.} ({In his Chess24 course, Jon Ludvig Hammer points out that Black should really be able to draw after} 14... Qxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 a4 {intending ...Bb5 and ...f6, but White can certainly play on for a long time, and there's no upside for us here.}) 15. f3 {[%cal Ge1f2] White tries to control some light squares and makes an escape for his king.} Rfb8 {Black is very active and we start with hitting the b2-pawn.} 16. Rb1 {White protects the b-pawn without commiting his pawn structure.} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] The same idea as we saw before.} 17. Kf2 {Castling would drop the e2-pawn, so White plays this way in order to connect the rooks.} Rc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. Qxa5 {Another pawn grab.} Qe8 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga6e2] This time we go back to this square.} ({Here} 18... Qd8 $2 19. Qa4 {hits our rook and gains time for an evacuation.}) 19. Nxd5 {Generally White would not want to do this, but here there is little choice.} exd5 {[%cal Ge8e2,Ga6e2]} 20. Rhe1 ({The only move really and the obvious choice, but I will mention that after} 20. Rhc1 Re6 $1 {is even stronger than taking on e2 with check.}) 20... Rc2 $5 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2,Rd2][%cal Ga6b5,Ga8a4] Black has a strong initiative for the two pawns, and will almost certainly win one of them back at least. For now there threat is ...Bb5 and ...Ra4, knocking White's queen away from his bishop.} ({If you'd like to regain a pawn immediately,} 20... Bc4 {is also good.}) *

