1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nc3 {This move has always been around, but in 2018 Fabiano revived an uncommon interpretation of White's play against Hikaru Nakamura. This started a revolution of sorts, and White scored heavily. Nowadays it is one more main line to deal with, rather than a 'harmless sideline'.} dxc4 ({We will not be scared of of our normal plans. From White's perspective,} 6... c6 {has to be considered, with an early committal to Nc3 in a Closed Catalan.}) 7. Ne5 {The point of White's play. It looks similar to the StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 line, but the switch of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O for 6.Nc3 greatly changes things. This was not appreciated for a long time. 7.O-O transposes the to StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Nc3 line. 7.Qa4 a6 8.Qxc4 b5 leaves the c3-knight misplaced. Black will play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, and ...c5 with an easy game.} Nc6 $1 {Perhaps this is what white players want to see, but I am stubborn.} ({Theoretically,} 7... c5 {holds up just fine, but after} 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 {White has played six (!) moves here with some success. Although Black is ok, he must play precisely while White is generally playing for two results.}) ({A curious idea is} 7... Qd6 {The queen may head to a6, while ...Rd8 is facilitated. It still looks a bit artificial to me, and you can look up the game Nisipeanu-Nakamura, Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 for further discouragement.}) 8. Bxc6 ({The best move. Instead} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. O-O {transposes to the line StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Nxc6 bxc6 9.Bxc6 Rb8 10.Nc3 , which is not dangerous.}) 8... bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 {So far, White is playing as he does in the main lines of StartFENrnbq1rk1/ppp1bppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 3 6EndFEN 6.O-O dxc4 7.Ne5 Nc6 8.Bxc6 , but here he has not castled, and Nc3 is on the board.} Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gd5][%cal Gd5b4] This is only the fourth most popular move, and the engine is initially skeptical, but we have seen that it is generally desirable to exchange knights in these opposite-colored bishop positions. In some cases the knight may even hop to b4 to start some trouble. Fighting for the initiative will be Black's focus, and the pawn deficit is generally of less importance.} (11... c5 {is by far the main move. We will look at this as an informational line.}) ({The other typical break is} 11... e5 {, but after} 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qxc4 {Black scores horribly.}) ({White has also scored heavily against} 11... Bb7 {with both} 12. O-O {and 12.f3}) 12. Qxc4 {Taking the pawn is the obvious choice.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6] Offering up another pawn. White should not be too greedy.} 13. Bd2 {The most popular, the choice of the engines, and the most complicated.} Ba6 14. Qc5 $1 {The only challenging move.} ({Both} 14. Qb3 Rfb8 15. Qc2 c5) ({and} 14. Qa4 Rfb8 {hitting the b2-pawn and planning ...c5, give Black great play.}) 14... Qd7 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf8b8] Dodging the queen trade and planning ...Rfb8, activating everything. We still have a comfortable lead in development, and White's queen position is a bit sketchy.} ({In his Chess24 course, Jon Ludvig Hammer points out that Black should really be able to draw after} 14... Qxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 a4 {intending ...Bb5 and ...f6, but White can certainly play on for a long time, and there's no upside for us here.}) 15. f3 {[%cal Ge1f2] White tries to control some light squares and makes an escape for his king.} Rfb8 {Black is very active and we start with hitting the b2-pawn.} 16. Rb1 {White protects the b-pawn without commiting his pawn structure.} Rb6 $1 {[%cal Gb6c6] The same idea as we saw before.} 17. Kf2 {Castling would drop the e2-pawn, so White plays this way in order to connect the rooks.} Rc6 18. Qa3 Rc4 {[%cal Gc4d4][%mdl 32768] With this move, we can 'prove' equality.} ({A more fighting choice is} 18... Nb6 $5 {attacking the d4-pawn and preparing ...Nc4. This was played in the game Goryachkina-Dubov, Sochi 2020, which awakened the word to 11...Nd5! We will look at this as an alternative.}) 19. Rhd1 ({White cannot consider} 19. e3 $2 {weakening the light squares. After} Nb4 {the knight looks at d2 and c3, while the pawn breaks ...e5 and ...c5 are both threatened.}) ({We cannot worry ourselves with} 19. Nxd5 exd5 $13 {with long lasting compensation.}) 19... Rxd4 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black has a good grip on the center. White should hurry to simplify.} 20. Be3 $1 Nxc3 {Again, we are proving the absolute soundness of our play.} ({Although White's king is not so bad after} 20... Nxe3 21. Kxe3 {Black can play this way to keep the game going. Both} e5 {and 21...Rd8 look ok.}) 21. Rxd4 ({Everything else loses big material. For example} 21. Bxd4 Nxd1+ 22. Rxd1 e5 $1) 21... Nxb1 22. Rxd7 Nxa3 23. bxa3 Bc4 {Simplest.} 24. Rxc7 Bxa2 {The smoke has cleared and we are left with a drawn endgame.} *

