1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%mdl 32768] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. cxd5 ({White has three ways to play here, but really only} 7. O-O {and}) (7. dxc5 {have any bite.}) {This is the meekest choice.} 7... cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 ({After} 8. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 $17 {Black already has a lead in development, and ...Nc6 and ...Rc8 are coming.}) 8... Nxd5 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd5b4] It may not look like much is happening, but with ...e5 and ...Nb5 in the air, already White is the one who has to be careful. White wants to prevent ...Nb4, but this costs White more time and slightly weakens the b3-square.} 9. a3 {[%csl Rb3,Gb4]} Bf6 {This simple attack on the knight is rather unpleasant for White.} 10. Nf3 ({After} 10. Nb3 $6 Bd7 {the possibility of ...Ba4 is quite annoying for White.}) 10... Bd7 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gd7b5]} ({This clears the c-file and is more flexible than} 10... Nc6 {.}) 11. O-O ({After} 11. e4 Qc8 $1 {is strong.}) 11... Bb5 $5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gd8c8,Gb8a6,Ga6c5] With ...Qc8 and ...Na6 coming, Black has some initiative.} *

