1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. cxd5 ({White has three ways to play here, but really only} 7. O-O {and}) (7. dxc5 {have any bite.}) {This is the meekest choice.} 7... cxd4 $1 8. Nxd4 ({After} 8. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 $17 {Black already has a lead in development, and ...Nc6 and ...Rc8 are coming.}) 8... Nxd5 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd5b4] It may not look like much is happening, but with ...e5 and ...Nb5 in the air, already White is the one who has to be careful.} 9. O-O Nb4 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5][%mdl 32768]} 10. Qc3 ({Other moves are similar. For example} 10. Qd2 e5 11. a3 N8c6 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 {and Black is at least equal.}) 10... e5 $1 11. Nb3 (11. Nf3 {would be met in the same way:} N8c6 12. a3 Nd4 $1) 11... N8c6 12. a3 Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e2]} ({This is the simplest, but} 12... Nd5 13. Qc2 Be6 14. Rd1 Rc8 {was also possible.}) 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qf3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gd8d7] Black's play is easier. The d4-pawn is cramping White.} *

