1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5c5,Gc5c2][%mdl 32768] We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Qc3 {White would like an endgame. This is White's best scoring move, but it's not very dangerous.} Qxc5 {The white queen is oddly placed on c3 , so we should avoid ( 8...Qxc3+?! 9.Nxc3 dxc4 10.Ne5 when White has a typically good Catalan endgame where it's not easy for Black to get his queenside developed properly.} 9. cxd5 Qxd5 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf8d8,Gb8c6,Ge6e5,Gd5h5] The most enterprising. Both sides have fiddled with the queen a bit, and both queens will have to move yet again. Black can develop quite normally now with ...Nc6 and perhaps ...e5 to free the c8-bishop, while ...Qh5 and ...Rd8 are possibilities as well.} ({The alternative} 9... Nxd5 10. Qxc5 Bxc5 {is much improved over the endgame above and probably equal, but White's play is easier and he scores well in practice.}) 10. O-O Nc6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge6e5,Gd5h5]} 11. Qd2 {The most common move in practice. White really wants that endgame!} (11. Bf4 {can be met with} Qh5 {but I like 11...Qb5! , hitting the e2-pawn, even more.}) 11... Rd8 $1 {Only on our terms.} ({If} 11... Qh5 12. Qg5 {is very insistent, although Black is fine here as well.}) 12. Qxd5 {White gets his endgame, but there is a cost.} Nxd5 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b6] Black is developing quickly. We can play either ...e5 or ...b6 to get our bishop out. Black is at least equal.} *

