1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5c5,Gc5c2] We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Bd2 {This is not very common, probably with good reason.} Qxc5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc5c2][%mdl 32768] There is already real pressure on the c4-pawn, so White must play rather passively.} 9. O-O $2 {This is not a typical offer of the c4-pawn.} b5 $1 ({This is much stronger than taking the pawn.} 9... Qxc4 $6 10. Qxc4 dxc4 11. Ne5 {is quite bad}) ({while} 9... dxc4 10. Na3 {also favors White.}) 10. b3 bxc4 11. Be3 (11. bxc4 Ba6 {wins the pawn quite cleanly.}) {This position was reached in Arun Prasad-Ippolito, Philadelphia 2008.} 11... Qa5 $1 {This is stronger than taking on b3.} 12. bxc4 Ba6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf8c8] ...Rc8 is coming and Black has a very active position.} 13. Z0 ({After} 13. cxd5 Rc8 {and ...Nxd5 Black has some initiative.}) *

