1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5c5,Gc5c2] We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Bd2 {This is not very common, probably with good reason.} Qxc5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc5c2] There is already real pressure on the c4-pawn, so White must play rather passively.} 9. Na3 {The only move really, but this is not an ideal square for the knight.} Nc6 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd5d4][%mdl 32768]} ({Guarding the b4-square while preparing to advance the d-pawn. This is much better than immediate} 9... d4 $6 10. b4 {when White's play is working.}) 10. cxd5 ({If} 10. O-O {?!} d4 $1 {Black has a nice space advantage and White's queenside pieces are all oddly placed.}) 10... Qxc2 {We'll go with this, as it's forcing. Everything is fine here really - Black could also recapture on d5 any which way, and it's all pretty equal.} 11. Nxc2 Nxd5 12. O-O Rd8 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8e6] White does not have any way to create pressure here, so we can get developed and it's just equal.} 13. Rfd1 (13. Ncd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bf6 {is also easy for Black.}) 13... e5 14. Ne3 Be6 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gf7f6,Ge5e4] Black is clearly fine as he's well developed and has a good amount of space.} ({Exchanging with} 14... Nxe3 15. Bxe3 Be6 {intending ...f5, is fine too.}) ({After} 14... Be6 {note that} 15. Nc4 $6 {does not 'increase the pressure', as} f6 {just leaves the c4-knight looking vulnerable.}) *

