1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5c5,Gc5c2] We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Nbd2 {White finally shows a little amibition. Daniil Yuffa is fond of this line and has scored well with it.} Qxc5 {[%cal Gc5c2][%mdl 32768]} 9. O-O {This is the most common move, but it's probably already an inaccuracy.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b5] Black prepares ...e5, while ...b5 is also a possibility.} 10. a3 ({It makes sense for White to throw this move in.} 10. b3 e5 {is similar, but White always has to watch for ...Nb4.}) 10... a5 11. b3 ({The 'trick'} 11. b4 $2 {does not work because} axb4 12. axb4 Nxb4 {hits the white queen.}) 11... e5 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gd5d4] Black is just better here, with more space and easier development.} 12. Z0 ({In practice White has tried to stem the tide with} 12. e4 {when both} d4 {and 12...dxc4 are nice for Black, depending on if you want a blocked position or not.}) *

