1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5c5,Gc5c2] We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Nbd2 {White finally shows a little amibition. Daniil Yuffa is fond of this line and has scored well with it.} Qxc5 {[%cal Gc5c2]} 9. a3 {White should play this immediately, as he can force b4.} b5 $5 {[%csl Rc4][%mdl 32768] Following Giri.} (9... a5 {is still playable. After} 10. b4 Qc7 11. b5 e5 {both sides have chances, but White's play against Black's center is certainly more dynamic than it was in the 9.O-O?! line.}) 10. b4 {Forced really, but this was White's idea anyway.} ({White is just worse after the passive} 10. b3 $2 bxc4 11. bxc4 Ba6 $17) 10... Qc7 11. c5 {[%csl Gc5] White has a nice protected passed pawn, but Black can quickly create counterplay.} a5 12. Bb2 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge6e5]} ({It's important to keep the tension. Instead} 12... axb4 $2 13. axb4 Rxa1+ 14. Bxa1 Nc6 15. Qb2 $16 {allowed White to keep control of everything in Yuffa-Buksa, Dubai 2023.}) 13. Nd4 ({After} 13. Qc3 e5 {both ...d4 and ...Nd5 are coming. White cannot play 14.Nxe5 axb4 (The immediate 14...d4? does not work because of 15.Qf3+-) 15.axb4 Rxa1+ 16.Bxa1 d4 and Black wins a piece.}) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 e5 15. Bb2 axb4 {Black should play this now, before White connects his rooks.} 16. axb4 Rxa1+ 17. Bxa1 d4 $1 {Another important move. If we do not play this now, White will go e2-e3.} 18. O-O Be6 $132 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gf8a8,Ga8a4] White has the passed pawn, but Black has space and his pieces are all good. With ...Nd5 and ...Ra8-a4 in the cards, It won't be so easy to protect the b4-pawn comfortably.} 19. Z0 ({After} 19. Qd3 Nd5 {prompted White to give up his important bishop with} 20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. e3 Qc6 $1 22. exd4 e4 23. Qe3 f5 {and Black had good attacking chances in Nepomniachtchi-Giri, Kolkata rapid 2019.}) *

