1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Nc3 {This is the main move. White brings the knight to its best square. This gives up the c4-pawn, but this is nothing new in the Catalan.} dxc4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({After} 8... Qxc5 $6 {White can finally take on d5 comfortably.}) 9. Nd2 $6 {White is too eager to recover the pawn.} Qxc5 ({Obvious and the universal choice, but I will point out that the engine is initially even more optimistic about} 9... Nc6 $146 10. Nxc4 Qxc5 11. b3 Qh5 {intending ...e5.}) 10. Na4 $2 {White always goes for this, but it looks like a clear mistake.} Qh5 $1 ({Short defeated Korchnoi quickly with} 10... Qa5 11. Qxc4 Bd7 12. Nc3 Rc8 $15 {in Korchnoi-Short, Luzern 1989, but our move is even stronger.}) 11. Nxc4 $2 {This looks natural, but White runs into big problems.} Bd7 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gf8c8,Gd7c6] A surprising move, after which the engines claim White is already busted!} 12. Bxb7 ({Let's see what happens if White grabs the pawn.} 12. O-O Nc6 {is already more than -2! The immediate threat is ...b5, while ...Rac8 and ...Nd4 are also very serious.}) 12... Bc6 $1 13. Bxc6 ({One point is that} 13. Bxa8 Bxh1 14. Bxh1 Qxh2 {is crushing. For example} 15. Bf3 Qg1+ 16. Kd2 Rd8+) 13... Nxc6 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc6d4,Ga8c8,Ge1g1,Gf6g4] Here Black is only down a pawn and the initiative is overwhelming.} *

