1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Nc3 {This is the main move. White brings the knight to its best square. This gives up the c4-pawn, but this is nothing new in the Catalan.} dxc4 ({After} 8... Qxc5 $6 {White can finally take on d5 comfortably.}) 9. O-O Qxc5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8d7,Gd7c6,Gf8d8]} ({An obvious move, but} 9... Nc6 {is more popular. This will often transpose after} 10. Bg5 Qxc5 {but I think taking on c5 immediately is more flexible.}) 10. Be3 Qh5 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Bg5 (11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nc6 {brings us back to the 10.Ne4 line.}) (11. h3 Bd7 {does not bother us, as we prepare ...Bc6 and our queen can always retreat to g6.}) 11... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} ({I like this move again, but surely} 11... Nc6 {is playable as well.}) 12. Rfd1 (12. h3 $6 {is just a waste of time.} Bc6 13. g4 Qg6 {and Black is at least ok.}) 12... Bc6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb8d7] Black is ready to develop harmoniously with ...Nbd7, and White has still not recovered the c4-pawn.} 13. Rd4 $5 {[%cal Gd4h4] White needs this creative move just to hold the balance.} (13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Ne4 {can be met with} Bxb2 $1 {when White has two pawns to recover.}) 13... Nbd7 ({Note that} 13... Bxf3 {does not win anything because White can throw in} 14. Bxf6) 14. Rh4 {Apparently aggressive, but White is just simplifying the position.} (14. Rxc4 Rac8 {is also fine for Black.}) 14... Qg6 15. Qxg6 hxg6 16. Rxc4 Rac8 {Black is harmoniously developed and has no problems.} *

