1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. dxc5 Qa5+ {We will stick with this classical line. Black will take on c5 and possibly create a pin on the c-file, taking advantage of the white queen on c2. The only downside is that White has a broad choice here.} ({Black can also play the sharp} 7... d4 $5 {gaining space.}) 8. Nc3 {This is the main move. White brings the knight to its best square. This gives up the c4-pawn, but this is nothing new in the Catalan.} dxc4 ({After} 8... Qxc5 $6 {White can finally take on d5 comfortably.}) 9. O-O Qxc5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8d7,Gd7c6,Gf8d8]} ({An obvious move, but} 9... Nc6 {is more popular. This will often transpose after} 10. Bg5 Qxc5 {but I think taking on c5 immediately is more flexible.}) 10. Bg5 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gc6b4,Gb7b5]} ({We will stick with the main line, but even here} 10... Bd7 $5 {looks quite satisfactory.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 $1 {is unexplored, and unclear.}) 11. Bxf6 {[%cal Gc3e4] This is consistent with 10.Bg5.} ({If} 11. Rfd1 Nb4 {it's still not clear how White can get this pawn back.} 12. Qa4 $4 {A terrible miscalculation.} Bd7 13. Rxd7 Nxd7 14. Qxd7 Bxg5 {and Black was already winning in Short-Bruzon Batista, Edmonton 2013.}) 11... gxf6 $5 ({Holding onto the bishop pair. This is more enterprising than the common} 11... Bxf6 {White has scored well after} 12. Ne4 {even though Black should gradually equalize with either} Qf5 {(my preference) or the more popular 12...Qe7}) 12. Rfd1 f5 {[%cal Gb7b5][%mdl 32768] Now Black is really ready for ...b5, so White should act quickly.} ({Here} 12... b5 {can be met with} 13. a4 {because White's rook creates some pressure on the a-file. It's still not so clear after} b4 14. Ne4 Qb6 15. Qxc4 Ba6 16. Qc1 Kg7 {but I prefer the text move.}) 13. e4 f4 $5 ({This has a certain appeal, but} 13... Bf6 {and}) (13... Rb8 {are both quite valid as well.}) 14. Qe2 ({After} 14. gxf4 Nb4 {the knight is coming to d3. Material is even, but the f4-pawn is weak and Black's queenside pawn majority is real.}) 14... Ne5 {This are other moves, but I like the clarity that this provides.} 15. Nxe5 (15. gxf4 $2 Nd3 {is clearly bad for White.}) 15... Qxe5 16. Qxc4 b6 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc8b7] White has his pawn back, but I prefer Black. the dark squared bishop is strong.} *

