g5.} ({If} 11. Rfd1 Nb4 {it's still not clear how White can get this pawn back.} 12. Qa4 $4 {A terrible miscalculation.} Bd7 13. Rxd7 Nxd7 14. Qxd7 Bxg5 {and Black was already winning in Short-Bruzon Batista, Edmonton 2013.}) 11... gxf6 $5 ({Holding onto the bishop pair. This is more enterprising than the common} 11... Bxf6 {White has scored well after} 12. Ne4 {even though Black should gradually equalize with either} Qf5 {(my preference) or the more popular 12...Qe7}) 12. Ne4 Qb5 {[%csl Gc4] Staying in touch with the c4-pawn.} 13. Rfd1 f5 ({German GM Daniel Fridman improves on the play of his wife six years earlier!} 13... e5 $6 14. Nc3 Qc5 15. Nh4 $1 Nd4 16. Qc1 {saw Black suffering in Lagno-Zatonskih, Rogaska Slatina 2011.}) 14. Nd6 ({After} 14. Nc3 Qc5 {we are actually back in the 11.Rfd1 line, with both sides having lost two tempi.}) 14... Qc5 ({Of course not} 14... Bxd6 $2 15. Rxd6 {when our king position is weakened and it's difficult to develop.}) 15. Qxc4 {An easy move to miss - it apparently drops a piece - but it's in fact the best try at this point.} Bxd6 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Qh4 {[%cal Gf3g5,Ga1c1] White threatens to regain the piece with Rac1, while Ng5 is even more serious.} Be7 {This saves the piece but leads to an immediate draw.} ({Black can play on with} 16... f6 {but I'm not sure it's worth the risk.} 17. Rac1 Qb4 18. Rc4 Qxb2 19. Rxd6 Qb1+ 20. Bf1 Qxa2 {Black is up two pawns, but clearly his king is shaky and White has pieces in play. White can still force a draw but it's more complicated:} 21. Ng5 fxg5 22. Qxg5+ Kh8 23. Qh6 Kg8 {and White has nothing better than to repeat moves. White can also try 21.e4 when apparently 21...Qa3 is absolutely the only move. It doesn't look worth it to me!}) 17. Ng5 Bxg5 18. Qxg5+ Kh8 {[%cal Gg5f6] White is down a whole piece so he must grab the perpetual.} *

