1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. O-O {The main line.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Nxd4 {Now Black has some choice in the direction of play.} Na6 $5 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ge6e5] This rare move looks like a good practical solution. It was played by Wei Yi against Carlsen, and also recommended by Hammer in his Chess24 course.} ({The main line is} 8... Nc6 {, but after} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {it's like a reversed Grünfeld. One discouraging possibility is} 10. Rd1 Ba6 11. b3 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd2 {intending a3 and b4. I prefer White here.}) ({Black can also play} 8... e5 9. Nf5 d4 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with a reversed Benoni of sorts. After} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd2 Nc6 {Black is totally fine, but White's play is straightforward starting with} 14. c5 {which scores a very healthy 65%. With 8...Na6 Black eyes ...Nb4 while maintaining the possibility of ...e5.}) 9. a3 $6 {This prevents ...Nb4, but it costs a tempo and weakens the b3-square. This may not seem relevant, but it could be...} dxc4 $1 (9... e5 $6 10. Nf5 d4 11. b4 {would totally justify White's ninth move.}) 10. Qxc4 ({After} 10. Rd1 Qc7 {it's not trivial for White to recover the pawn, while Black can easily develop his pieces with ...Rd8 and ...Bd7.}) 10... e5 $1 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc8e6,Ga6c5] With ...Be6 and ...Nc5 coming, White will get kicked around and his will have to watch for ...Nc5-b3.} *

