position that he was hoping for.}) 10. Qb3 {The most logical.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gc8e6] The point of Black's play. We are actually making room for ...Be6.} 11. Nf3 {[%csl Re5] This move has never played but it's important, and it was analysed by Hammer. Let take a look.} Qxd5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Black cannot save the pawn by advancing it.} 11... e4 12. Ng5) 12. Qxd5 ({Only grabbing the pawn is critical. If} 12. Nc3 {both} Qa5 {intending ...Be6 and 12...Qxb3 13.axb3 Nc6 are fine for Black.}) 12... Nfxd5 {[%cal Gb4c2] We do have the little threat of ...Nc2.} 13. Nxe5 $5 ({Only this move presents a challenge, but it all works out for Black.} 13. a3 $6 Nc2 14. Ra2 Be6 $15 {does not work for White.}) ({while} 13. Na3 f6 $15 {is a comfortable edge for Black.}) ({Black is also fine after} 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nc6) 13... Nc2 {Here we go...} 14. Bxd5 Nxa1 15. Be4 $1 {[%csl Gc2] White has to stop the knight from escaping.} Bh3 {Hammer's suggestion.} (15... Bf6 {also seems to work, but after} 16. f4 Bh3 {White can bring the rook to e1 or d1. It's better to limit the opponent's choices.}) 16. Re1 $2 {[%cal Ge7b4] The rook is vulnerable here.} Rae8 {(either rook really) is winning for Black, as ...Bb4, attacking both the e1-rook and the pieces on the e-file, is too big of a threat. For example:} 17. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Re4,Re5]} 18. f4 f6 19. Bd5+ Be6 {[%cal Ga1c2] The knight escapes and Black will keep his material advantage.} *

