1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. O-O {The main line.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Now Black has some choice in the direction of play.} Na6 $5 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ge6e5] This rare move looks like a good practical solution. It was played by Wei Yi against Carlsen, and also recommended by Hammer in his Chess24 course.} ({The main line is} 8... Nc6 {, but after} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {it's like a reversed Grünfeld. One discouraging possibility is} 10. Rd1 Ba6 11. b3 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd2 {intending a3 and b4. I prefer White here.}) ({Black can also play} 8... e5 9. Nf5 d4 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with a reversed Benoni of sorts. After} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd2 Nc6 {Black is totally fine, but White's play is straightforward starting with} 14. c5 {which scores a very healthy 65%. With 8...Na6 Black eyes ...Nb4 while maintaining the possibility of ...e5.}) 9. cxd5 Nb4 $1 ({After the compliant} 9... Nxd5 10. Rd1 {gives White the typical Catalan position that he was hoping for.}) 10. Qb3 {The most logical.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gc8e6] The point of Black's play. We are actually making room for ...Be6.} 11. Nf3 {[%csl Re5] This move has never played but it's important, and it was analysed by Hammer. Let take a look.} Qxd5 $1 ({Black cannot save the pawn by advancing it.} 11... e4 12. Ng5) 12. Qxd5 ({Only grabbing the pawn is critical. If} 12. Nc3 {both} Qa5 {intending ...Be6 and 12...Qxb3 13.axb3 Nc6 are fine for Black.}) 12... Nfxd5 {[%cal Gb4c2] We do have the little threat of ...Nc2.} 13. Nxe5 $5 ({Only this move presents a challenge, but it all works out for Black.} 13. a3 $6 Nc2 14. Ra2 Be6 $15 {does not work for White.}) ({while} 13. Na3 f6 $15 {is a comfortable edge for Black.}) ({Black is also fine after} 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nc6) 13... Nc2 {Here we go...} 14. Bxd5 Nxa1 15. Be4 $1 {[%csl Gc2] White has to stop the knight from escaping.} Bh3 {Hammer's suggestion.} (15... Bf6 {also seems to work, but after} 16. f4 Bh3 {White can bring the rook to e1 or d1. It's better to limit the opponent's choices.}) 16. Rd1 (16. Re1 $2 Rae8 {(either rook really) is winning for Black, as ...Bb4, attacking both the e1-rook and the pieces on the e-file, is too big of a threat. For example} 17. Nc3 Bb4 18. f4 f6 19. Bd5+ Be6) 16... Rad8 $1 ({Here} 16... Rae8 17. Bd3 $1 {is good for White, as our knight is not getting out.}) 17. Bd2 Bf6 {Not the only move, but this is the clearest.} 18. f4 ({The only move. If} 18. Nd3 {Black has to avoid the blunder} Nc2 $2 19. Nf4 $1) 18... Bxe5 {But after 18...Rfe8 it's going to be hard to round up the knight in the corner because if the knight ever leaves d3 (to cover the c2-square), then ...Bxb2 will come.} 19. fxe5 Rfe8 {[%cal Ge8e5]} 20. Bd3 {The most challenging.} Rxd3 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({This is necessary. If} 20... Rxe5 21. Bc3 $1 {followed by Na3 or Rc1, and our knight isn't getting out.}) 21. exd3 Rxe5 {Now we are finally ready to get our knight out.} ({We can escape with} 21... Nc2 {but White can then hold onto the pawn with} 22. Bc3 {Even so,} Ne3 23. Re1 Nd5 {probably provides Black with enough compensation. This could be played to avoid the draw. I don't think Black runs any great risks, but it is a pawn.}) 22. Na3 {The only critical move.} Re2 $1 {[%cal Ge2d2,Ge2g2] It's hard for White to do anything.} 23. Re1 $5 ({White cannot just queen the d-pawn.} 23. d4 f6 24. d5 Kf7 {With the text move White sets a very sneaky trap.}) 23... Rg2+ $1 ({White's big trap is} 23... Rxe1+ $2 24. Bxe1 Bf5 25. Kf2 $1 Bxd3 26. Ke3 $1 Bf5 27. Kd2 $1 {and Kc1, b3, Bc3 will finally catch the knight.}) 24. Kh1 {[%csl Re8]} f6 {Any move to avoid back rank mate will do.} 25. Rd1 Re2 {White can't make any progress.} *

