1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 {The Catalan! This is a very popular and serious choice. We will go for a very classical line. There is a lot to know, but it's interesting and common sense will help guide you in most lines if you forget something.} Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Qc2 {This is a tricky move which scores very well for White. I suspect this is more because black players are ill prepared, rather than any intrinsic superiority of the position itself.} c5 $1 {[%csl Rd4] One issue with 6.Qc2 is that it weakens to d4-square - as it does in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian - so it makes perfect sense to strike like this. One upside for Black is that there is more than one good way to play, depending on one's preferences.} ({One problem that Black faces is that unlike 6.O-O dxc4, here} 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 a6 {does not work as well because} 8. Bf4 {hits the c7-pawn and we cannot get back into our desired repertoire. For Closed Catalan players, this line does not cause any inconvenience because Black can simply play 6...c6, but of course this is not what we are looking for.}) 7. O-O {The main line.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Now Black has some choice in the direction of play.} Na6 $5 {[%cal Ga6b4,Ge6e5] This rare move looks like a good practical solution. It was played by Wei Yi against Carlsen, and also recommended by Hammer in his Chess24 course.} ({The main line is} 8... Nc6 {, but after} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 {it's like a reversed Grünfeld. One discouraging possibility is} 10. Rd1 Ba6 11. b3 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd2 {intending a3 and b4. I prefer White here.}) ({Black can also play} 8... e5 9. Nf5 d4 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with a reversed Benoni of sorts. After} 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Nd2 Nc6 {Black is totally fine, but White's play is straightforward starting with} 14. c5 {which scores a very healthy 65%. With 8...Na6 Black eyes ...Nb4 while maintaining the possibility of ...e5.}) 9. cxd5 Nb4 $1 ({After the compliant} 9... Nxd5 10. Rd1 {gives White the typical Catalan position that he was hoping for.}) 10. Qb3 {The most logical.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gc8e6] The point of Black's play. We are actually making room for ...Be6.} 11. Nb5 Nbxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. N1c3 {This was Carlsen's choice.} Be6 ({After} 12... Nxc3 $2 13. Nxc3 {White has a dream position, controlling the light squares and hindering Black's development.}) 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 (13... Nxd5 $2 14. Rd1 {wins for White.}) 14. Bxd5 Qxd5 15. Bg5 {The only real try for White is to try to control the light squares.} Qxb3 16. axb3 a6 17. Nc3 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ge2e4,Gc3d5] White's chances are based on getting the knight to d5, but the position has greatly simplified, and Black has enough resources to hold the balance. Even Carlsen could not extract anything from White's position.} h6 {Forcing White to execute his plan, which in a way highlights that it's not terribly dangerous.} (17... Rac8 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. Rxd8+ Bxd8 $1 20. Rd1 Kf8 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Rd7 Rb8 23. Kg2 Ke8 {was also good enough in Artemiev-Lysyj, Sochi 2016.}) 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nd5 ({If} 19. e4 Be7 20. Nd5 Bc5 {and the bishop comes to d4. The white knight looks nice, but it doesn't do much and the b2-pawn will require attention.}) 19... Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c2]} (19... e4 $5 {was also possible.}) 20. Rac1 e4 {[%cal Gf6b2]} 21. Z0 ({Black has activated his position and after} 21. Rc4 Rxc4 22. bxc4 Bxb2 23. Rb1 Ba3 24. Rxb7 Rc8 {Black was fine in Carlsen-Wei Yi, Wijk aan Zee 2018.}) *

