s hoping for.}) 10. Qb3 {The most logical.} e5 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gc8e6] The point of Black's play. We are actually making room for ...Be6.} 11. Nb5 Nbxd5 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Ge2e4] Pinning the knight certainly looks critical, but Black has enough resources, as we shall see.} Be6 13. e4 {White has little choice, as he is behind in development and the b5-knight is misplaced. We will also consider Hammer's suggestion} Nc7 $5 {This is a legit queen sacrifice which was suggested by Hammer.} 14. Rxd8 Rfxd8 15. Nxc7 {White can bail out with this move.} Bxb3 {[%mdl 32768]} 16. Nxa8 Rd1+ $5 {This is a winning attempt. Black will be down a piece though!} ({Simpler is} 16... Be6 {wins back the piece, as ...Rd1 is threatened.}) 17. Bf1 {This forces White to play accurately.} Bc4 ({If} 17... Rxc1 18. axb3 {White may be tied up, but he is up a whole piece. The computer says equality!?}) 18. Nd2 {Clearly forced.} Bxf1 19. Nxf1 Bc5 $5 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc5d4,Gf6e4] Black is down a whole piece, but White has to play accurately.} 20. Z0 ({In fact the only way to avoid problems is with the hard to find sequence} 20. Kg2 Nxe4 21. b4 Bd4 22. Ne3 {when Black even has a choice between} Bxe3 23. fxe3 f5 {and 22...Re1 23.Nc2 Re2 24.Nxd4 Rxf2+ 25.Kg1 exd4 in both cases, with some kind of dynamic balance.}) *

