1. Nf3 {Here we have White's most flexible first move. I have played it myself hundreds of times. White may transpose to mainstream 1.d4 openings, and English Opening, or maintain a Reti flavor. Black has to be aware and ready for all kinds of transpositions. We don't want to get tricked!} ({White can also start with} 1. c4 {when for this repertoire we will play} e6 {and 2...d5 against anything. There is also a great course on Chessable 1...c5 :)} 2. Nf3 {or 2.g3 d5 3.Bg2 Nf6 4.Nf3} d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {when} 6. b3 {reaches our main positions in the Neo-Catalan.}) 1... d5 {We will use this first move. There is nothing wrong with 1...Nf6 first though. 2.g3 d5 or 2.c4 e6 and we will be on track.} 2. c4 ({Another move order is} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 {5.d3 is the King's Indian Attack.} O-O 6. b3) 2... e6 ({This is what fits in our repertoire. I think that objectively,} 2... d4 {should be quite strong, but it leads to a totally different kind of game, has a lot of theory, and perhaps most importantly, does not help us if White plays 1.c4.}) 3. g3 {Of course if White plays d4 at any point in the next few moves, we will just be in a normal Catalan.} ({White could also start with} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2) ({Instead} 3. e3 {is the 'e3 Poison' which we will get to later.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {The Neo-Catalan. It looks like a quiet system, but it has a lot of venom. White is quite flexible, and he may take on d5 at any point or meet ...c5 with d4, in both cases opening the position. We have to be ready.} b6 {This fits well with our repertoire.} ({This is not the same as the Catalan.} 6... dxc4 7. bxc4 {just strengthens White's center and leaves us with a problematic c8-bishop.}) ({The immediate} 6... c5 {is well met with} 7. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {7...exd5 8.d4 is a Tarrasch QGD - not so easy for Black.} 8. Bb2 {with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White