1. Nf3 {Here we have White's most flexible first move. I have played it myself hundreds of times. White may transpose to mainstream 1.d4 openings, and English Opening, or maintain a Reti flavor. Black has to be aware and ready for all kinds of transpositions. We don't want to get tricked!} ({White can also start with} 1. c4 {when for this repertoire we will play} e6 {and 2...d5 against anything. There is also a great course on Chessable 1...c5 :)} 2. Nf3 {or 2.g3 d5 3.Bg2 Nf6 4.Nf3} d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {when} 6. b3 {reaches our main positions in the Neo-Catalan.}) 1... d5 {We will use this first move. There is nothing wrong with 1...Nf6 first though. 2.g3 d5 or 2.c4 e6 and we will be on track.} 2. c4 ({Another move order is} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 {5.d3 is the King's Indian Attack.} O-O 6. b3) 2... e6 ({This is what fits in our repertoire. I think that objectively,} 2... d4 {should be quite strong, but it leads to a totally different kind of game, has a lot of theory, and perhaps most importantly, does not help us if White plays 1.c4.}) 3. g3 {Of course if White plays d4 at any point in the next few moves, we will just be in a normal Catalan.} ({White could also start with} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2) ({Instead} 3. e3 {is the 'e3 Poison' which we will get to later.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {The Neo-Catalan. It looks like a quiet system, but it has a lot of venom. White is quite flexible, and he may take on d5 at any point or meet ...c5 with d4, in both cases opening the position. We have to be ready.} b6 {This fits well with our repertoire.} ({This is not the same as the Catalan.} 6... dxc4 7. bxc4 {just strengthens White's center and leaves us with a problematic c8-bishop.}) ({The immediate} 6... c5 {is well met with} 7. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {7...exd5 8.d4 is a Tarrasch QGD - not so easy for Black.} 8. Bb2 {with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6d5] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces (usually our knights), avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. cxd5 {We always have to consider this capture.} Nxd5 {We will take with a piece when there's no reason not to.} ({Certainly} 8... exd5 {is playable. After} 9. d4 {it's a Queen's Indian of some sort.}) 9. d4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd7c5] I like this smart move as White has to commit something. After ...c5 and dxc5, we would also like to recapture on c5 with the knight if possible.} ({I prefer this to} 9... c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nbd2 {with the idea a3, b4, and maybe Ne4. This looks nice for White.}) 10. Nbd2 {This has been played a lot, but it's slow and I don't think it's dangerous.} (10. Nc3 c5 {transposes to 9.Nc3}) (10. e4 N5f6 {pretty much forces} 11. e5 {when} Nd5 {and ...c5 is fine for Black.}) 10... c5 11. Nc4 b5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({We could just play something like} 11... Rc8 {but I like gaining space with this forcing move.}) 12. Nce5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 (13. dxe5 $2 Rc8 $17 {is just a bad structure for White, and we have a powerful queenside pawn majority.}) 13... f6 $1 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge6e5] A rare case of playing this way. Here it just works.} 14. Nd3 ({After} 14. Nf3 c4 $1 {the c-pawn is strong.}) 14... cxd4 15. Bxd4 e5 $132 {Black is taking space.} 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. Bxc5 {It looks like White has some pressure, but we have a resource here.} Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3d1,Gc3e2]} 18. Z0 ({One tactical point is that after} 18. Qxd8 {we do everything with check:} Nxe2+ 19. Kh1 Bxg2+ 20. Kxg2 Rfxd8 $17) ({White's best appears to be} 18. Qc2 Bxg2 19. Rfc1 $5 Bb7 $1 20. Qxc3 ({(If} 20. Bxf8 $2 Qd5 $1 21. f3 Rc8 {and ...e4 gives Black a huge attack.)}) 20... Rf7 {when the engine says is equal, but I prefer Black as his bishop looks very strong.}) *

