hite.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6d5] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces (usually our knights), avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. cxd5 {We always have to consider this capture.} Nxd5 {We will take with a piece when there's no reason not to.} ({Certainly} 8... exd5 {is playable. After} 9. d4 {it's a Queen's Indian of some sort.}) 9. d4 Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd7c5] I like this smart move as White has to commit something. After ...c5 and dxc5, we would also like to recapture on c5 with the knight if possible.} ({I prefer this to} 9... c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nbd2 {with the idea a3, b4, and maybe Ne4. This looks nice for White.}) 10. Re1 $5 {This has seen some high level action.} c5 (10... N5f6 11. Nc3 c5 12. e4 {is another viable move order.}) 11. e4 N5f6 12. Nc3 cxd4 13. Nxd4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gg2b7,Ge5f6] An important position. White threatens e5.} Bc5 ({Black can also play} 13... Ne5 {but I think 13...Bc5 is sounder.}) 14. Ndb5 {White is hoping to invade on d6.} Qe7 $146 {This looks like a blunder, but we have amazing resources.} ({Black should not encourage White to do what he wants to with} 14... a6 $6 15. Nd6 Bc6 {because White has} 16. Na4 $1 {and if} Bxa4 $2 17. e5 {wins for White.}) (14... Qb8 {is reasonable though.}) 15. e5 {[%csl Rb7,Rf6] It looks like we missed something, as everything is hanging now.} Rad8 $3 {[%mdl 32768] What a move!} 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Qe2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5] Black wins back the piece.} *

