1. Nf3 {Here we have White's most flexible first move. I have played it myself hundreds of times. White may transpose to mainstream 1.d4 openings, and English Opening, or maintain a Reti flavor. Black has to be aware and ready for all kinds of transpositions. We don't want to get tricked!} ({White can also start with} 1. c4 {when for this repertoire we will play} e6 {and 2...d5 against anything. There is also a great course on Chessable 1...c5 :)} 2. Nf3 {or 2.g3 d5 3.Bg2 Nf6 4.Nf3} d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {when} 6. b3 {reaches our main positions in the Neo-Catalan.}) 1... d5 {We will use this first move. There is nothing wrong with 1...Nf6 first though. 2.g3 d5 or 2.c4 e6 and we will be on track.} 2. c4 ({Another move order is} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 {5.d3 is the King's Indian Attack.} O-O 6. b3) 2... e6 ({This is what fits in our repertoire. I think that objectively,} 2... d4 {should be quite strong, but it leads to a totally different kind of game, has a lot of theory, and perhaps most importantly, does not help us if White plays 1.c4.}) 3. g3 {Of course if White plays d4 at any point in the next few moves, we will just be in a normal Catalan.} ({White could also start with} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2) ({Instead} 3. e3 {is the 'e3 Poison' which we will get to later.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {The Neo-Catalan. It looks like a quiet system, but it has a lot of venom. White is quite flexible, and he may take on d5 at any point or meet ...c5 with d4, in both cases opening the position. We have to be ready.} b6 {This fits well with our repertoire.} ({This is not the same as the Catalan.} 6... dxc4 7. bxc4 {just strengthens White's center and leaves us with a problematic c8-bishop.}) ({The immediate} 6... c5 {is well met with} 7. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {7...exd5 8.d4 is a Tarrasch QGD - not so easy for Black.} 8. Bb2 {with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6d5] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces (usually our knights), avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. e3 {This is the big tabiya.} c5 9. Qe2 ({Now we have another big split between} 9. Qe2 {and}) (9. Nc3 {.}) {This has been played a lot, but now we can develop normally.} 9... Nc6 $1 10. Nc3 {This is provocative.} d4 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({In practice Black has often gone for} 10... dxc4 {, reaching a structure which we generally avoid.}) ({or} 10... Rc8 {which is perfectly fine and may transpose to other positions.}) 11. exd4 ({After} 11. Na4 Rc8 {Black is at least equal. White's setup makes an odd impression.}) 11... Nxd4 {This is the simplest.} (11... cxd4 {is more ambitious.} 12. Nb5 d3 $1 {In the next line will see an even better version of this kind of position where White's f1-rook has gone to d1.}) 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 cxd4 (13... Qxd4 {is playable as well.}) 14. Nb5 Bc5 {[%csl Rb2,Rb5] Black has more space and White has to work hard to equalize.} 15. Z0 (15. b4 $2 d3 $1 16. Qf3 Bxb4 17. Nd4 Bc5 $17 {was Li Chao-Navara, Wijk aan Zee 2011.}) ({White should have played} 15. Qe5 $1 Nd7 16. Qc7 e5 {when the engine says White is near-equality, although I prefer Black as he has more space.}) *

