 scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6d5] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces (usually our knights), avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. e3 {This is the big tabiya.} c5 9. Qe2 ({Now we have another big split between} 9. Qe2 {and}) (9. Nc3 {.}) {This has been played a lot, but now we can develop normally.} 9... Nc6 $1 10. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] This is White's main choice.} Rc8 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Here} 10... Qd7 $6 11. d4 $1 {is a bit uncomfortable.}) ({The most common move is} 10... Qc7 {White scores almost 70%! Still, I do not see any problems. For example} 11. Nc3 Rad8 12. cxd5 {This operation should be critical.} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxd5 14. d4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Rd7 17. Rac1 Qb8 {and Black does not have any issues. If} 18. Qg4 g6) ({Black can play} 10... d4 {Here too. if} 11. exd4 cxd4 12. Ne5 Rc8 {and Black is fine. The d1-rook is misplaced.}) 11. Nc3 $2 {This poor move has been played several times.} d4 $17 {This is even stronger than it was in the last line.} 12. exd4 cxd4 13. Nb5 d3 $1 14. Qf1 Qd7 $1 {[%csl Ra1,Rd1,Gd3,Rf2][%cal Ge7c5,Gf6g4,Gf6e4] White's rook is misplaced on d1 - which also hurts his other rook. Black has a strong initiative.} *

