1. Nf3 {Here we have White's most flexible first move. I have played it myself hundreds of times. White may transpose to mainstream 1.d4 openings, and English Opening, or maintain a Reti flavor. Black has to be aware and ready for all kinds of transpositions. We don't want to get tricked!} ({White can also start with} 1. c4 {when for this repertoire we will play} e6 {and 2...d5 against anything. There is also a great course on Chessable 1...c5 :)} 2. Nf3 {or 2.g3 d5 3.Bg2 Nf6 4.Nf3} d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O {when} 6. b3 {reaches our main positions in the Neo-Catalan.}) 1... d5 {We will use this first move. There is nothing wrong with 1...Nf6 first though. 2.g3 d5 or 2.c4 e6 and we will be on track.} 2. c4 ({Another move order is} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. c4 {5.d3 is the King's Indian Attack.} O-O 6. b3) 2... e6 ({This is what fits in our repertoire. I think that objectively,} 2... d4 {should be quite strong, but it leads to a totally different kind of game, has a lot of theory, and perhaps most importantly, does not help us if White plays 1.c4.}) 3. g3 {Of course if White plays d4 at any point in the next few moves, we will just be in a normal Catalan.} ({White could also start with} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. g3 O-O 6. Bg2) ({Instead} 3. e3 {is the 'e3 Poison' which we will get to later.}) 3... Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 {The Neo-Catalan. It looks like a quiet system, but it has a lot of venom. White is quite flexible, and he may take on d5 at any point or meet ...c5 with d4, in both cases opening the position. We have to be ready.} b6 {This fits well with our repertoire.} ({This is not the same as the Catalan.} 6... dxc4 7. bxc4 {just strengthens White's center and leaves us with a problematic c8-bishop.}) ({The immediate} 6... c5 {is well met with} 7. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 {7...exd5 8.d4 is a Tarrasch QGD - not so easy for Black.} 8. Bb2 {with Nc3 and d4 coming in some order. This scores well for White.}) ({Objectively,} 6... d4 {maybe best, but White scores well after} 7. e3 c5 {with both Shankland's modern} 8. Ne5 $5 {and the traditional Reversed Benoni 8.exd4 cxd4 when the main move is 9.d3 but White has some other tries as well.}) 7. Bb2 {The main line.} Bb7 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gf6d5] In most of these lines we want to recapture on both d5 and c5 with pieces (usually our knights), avoiding isolated or hanging pawns, as White's g2-bishop is well placed to combat these structures.} 8. e3 {This is the big tabiya.} c5 9. Nc3 ({Now we have another big split between} 9. Qe2 {and}) (9. Nc3 {.}) {This line gave Black a lot of trouble for many years.} 9... Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gf8d8] It took Black a while to come up with this, but now it is well known. Black holds back with his b8-knight, and can often follow up with ...Rd8 and sometimes ...d4. White does not have the space advantage that is so prevalent in queen pawn openings, so he does not have more useful waiting moves than us.} ({We would like to play} 9... Nc6 $6 {but then} 10. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. d4 {gives White some initiative. Black has tried various things here, but with little success. I would like to recommend} Rad8 13. Ne5 Qxg2+ $5 14. Kxg2 Nxe5+ {as it looks like fun, but I don't really trust it.}) ({I also do not like} 9... Nbd7 10. Qe2 {when the knight is not well placed.}) ({Black's main continuation has been} 9... dxc4 10. bxc4 Nc6 {but after} 11. Qe2 {White has done well. He may play in the center with Rfd1 and d4, while there is also an interesting strategic plan with Ne1, f4, g4 gaining space on the kingside.}) 10. Qe2 (10. d3 Rd8 11. Qe2 {transposes.}) 10... Rd8 11. Rac1 (11. cxd5 Nxd5 {is fine for Black. White has to watch out for ...Ba6.}) (11. Rfd1 $6 {This natural move has been played a lot, but it's not very good.} d4 $1 12. exd4 cxd4 13. Nb5 d3 {White's rooks look foolish and Black has a strong initiative brewing.}) 11... Nc6 {[%cal Gd5d4][%mdl 32768] With a rook on c1 , White has a resource - we must avoid ( 11...d4? 12.exd4 cxd4 13.Nd5 $16} 12. d3 ({If} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Rxd5 {and White has to watch out for ...Ba6 again.}) 12... d4 {Now we can play this.} 13. exd4 Nxd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 ({White loses material after} 15. Nf5 $2 Bxf1 16. Nxe7+ Kf8) 15... Rxd4 {[%cal Gd4d7,Gc8c6,Ga8d8]} ({I prefer this recapture, but} 15... cxd4 {is also good.}) *

