1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will focus on Reti lines with e3 instead of g3. There was a whole book written on this approach with various move orders - 'e3 Poison' by GM Axel Smith. It's a tricky setup that is not without bite, so I think it's appropriate name.} ({Of course White could start with} 1. c4 {too.} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6) 1... d5 2. c4 ({And here} 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e3 {would be another move order.}) 2... e6 3. e3 ({And again White can play} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 {5.g3 O-O 6.Bg2 b6 is the Neo-Catalan chapter.}) 3... Nf6 {[%mdl 32768] We will pretty much play ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...O-O against anything. The timing of other moves such as ...c5 and ...b6 will vary a bit, depending on what White does.} 4. Nc3 {This move order can be tricky, but I've immunized us against it. We stick with the program.} Be7 {The alternatives are fine but lead to different types of positions.} (4... c5 5. d4 {is a whole new world with lots of possibilities.}) ({We can easily end up out of our repertoire after the tempting} 4... b6 {because while} 5. cxd5 exd5 {5...Nxd5 6.d4 Bb7 is also out of our repertoire.} 6. d4 Bb7 {is perfectly fine, it's a line of the Queen's Indian that we are not willing to transpose to - compare this to the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 5. b3 (5. d4 O-O {is the QGD with 4.e3.}) 5... O-O 6. Bb2 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 ({Instead} 7... Nxd5 {is definitely playable, but} 8. Qc2 $5 {is a serious setup. White has various attacking ideas connected with moves like h4 and Ng5. There are all kinds of move orders and a great many pitfalls, so I prefer to avoid it.}) 8. d4 Nc6 {Now we have transposed to the main lines of this chapter.} *

