1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will focus on Reti lines with e3 instead of g3. There was a whole book written on this approach with various move orders - 'e3 Poison' by GM Axel Smith. It's a tricky setup that is not without bite, so I think it's appropriate name.} ({Of course White could start with} 1. c4 {too.} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6) 1... d5 2. c4 ({And here} 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e3 {would be another move order.}) 2... e6 3. e3 ({And again White can play} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 {5.g3 O-O 6.Bg2 b6 is the Neo-Catalan chapter.}) 3... Nf6 {We will pretty much play ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...O-O against anything. The timing of other moves such as ...c5 and ...b6 will vary a bit, depending on what White does.} 4. b3 ({If White plays} 4. d4 {anytime in the next few moves, we'll just end up in the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 4... Be7 ({This is consistent with our whole repertoire. Another good setup, recommended by Gustafsson in his Chess24 course, is} 4... c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 {when Black will play ...Bd6 instead of ...Be7. This is perfectly sound, but it leaves us hanging against White's 4.Nc3 move order.}) 5. Bb2 O-O {This is the real starting point for this chapter. White's setup is not as harmless as it appears to be.} 6. Be2 {This is popular, and we cannot play in the same way as we do against 6.Nc3. But it's easily diffused, and Black has more than one way to easy equality.} (6. d4 {is yet again the QGD with 4.e3.}) (6. g3 {looks surprising, but it's not bad, and} b6 $1 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {brings us to the Neo-Catalan.}) 6... c5 7. O-O ({After} 7. cxd5 {we will play} Nxd5 $1 {7...exd5 8.O-O Nc6 9.d4 transposes to 8...exd5, which is what we are avoiding.}) 7... Nc6 {[%cal Gd5d4] Now Black is ready to play ...d4.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6][%mdl 32768] Here we can just go for the ...b6 plan. White has already castled so we don't have to worry about the attacking setups with Qc2, h4, Ng5 that we'll address later.} ({After} 8... exd5 9. d4 {White's knight is not yet on c3 , but he's castled instead. This changes things and White keeps an edge after 9...Ne4 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.Nc3 $14}) 9. Nc3 (9. d4 {also leads to dry equality:} cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b6 {or 11.Qxd4 Bf6=}) 9... Nxc3 {This is simplest.} (9... Bf6 {is also fine for Black.}) (9... b6 {is ok too, but Black has to be careful after} 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 {as the queen is a bit exposed.}) 10. Bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge7f6] Black will continue with ...Bb7 and ...Bf6. White has no initiative at all, so it's just equal.} *

