1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will focus on Reti lines with e3 instead of g3. There was a whole book written on this approach with various move orders - 'e3 Poison' by GM Axel Smith. It's a tricky setup that is not without bite, so I think it's appropriate name.} ({Of course White could start with} 1. c4 {too.} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6) 1... d5 2. c4 ({And here} 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e3 {would be another move order.}) 2... e6 3. e3 ({And again White can play} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 {5.g3 O-O 6.Bg2 b6 is the Neo-Catalan chapter.}) 3... Nf6 {We will pretty much play ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...O-O against anything. The timing of other moves such as ...c5 and ...b6 will vary a bit, depending on what White does.} 4. b3 ({If White plays} 4. d4 {anytime in the next few moves, we'll just end up in the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 4... Be7 ({This is consistent with our whole repertoire. Another good setup, recommended by Gustafsson in his Chess24 course, is} 4... c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 {when Black will play ...Bd6 instead of ...Be7. This is perfectly sound, but it leaves us hanging against White's 4.Nc3 move order.}) 5. Bb2 O-O {This is the real starting point for this chapter. White's setup is not as harmless as it appears to be.} 6. Nc3 (6. d4 {is yet again the QGD with 4.e3.}) (6. g3 b6 $1 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {brings us to the Neo-Catalan.}) 6... c5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4]} ({I would like to play} 6... b6 {but after} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 $6 {better is 7...exd5 but after 8.d4 we are in a line of the Queen's Indian that is sound but outside of our repertoire.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Qc2 c5 10. Bd3 $16 {White threatens both our h7-pawn and Be4.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb8c6][%mdl 32768]} ({Instead} 7... Nxd5 {is definitely playable, but} 8. Qc2 $5 {is a serious setup. White has various attacking ideas connected with moves like h4 and Ng5. There are all kinds of move orders and a great many pitfalls, so I prefer to avoid it.}) 8. d4 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gb2b3] We threatened to keep pushing our d-pawn, so this is necessary. Now we have a kind of Tarrasch QGD, which is not what we usually go looking for, but White has played a rather modest setup, and he is still a couple of moves away from getting castled.} Nc6 9. Bb5 {This looks more aggressive than 9.Be2, but two can play that game.} (9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Be2 {brings us back to 7.d4.}) 9... Bg4 $1 {The pin is annoying for White.} 10. dxc5 {This is too risky.} d4 $1 {Breaking things open while White's king is still in the center.} 11. exd4 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nxd4 13. Qd1 Nxb5 14. Nxb5 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e1,Ge8b5] A clever move.} 15. Qe2 {This is forced.} (15. Nc3 $2 Bxc5+ 16. Qe2 Rd8 {led to a miniature in Wild-Werle, Karlsruhe 2019.}) 15... Bxc5 $1 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $17 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ga8d8,Gf8e8] Black's initiative will persist into the endgame, if White makes it that far.} *

