1. Nf3 {In this chapter we will focus on Reti lines with e3 instead of g3. There was a whole book written on this approach with various move orders - 'e3 Poison' by GM Axel Smith. It's a tricky setup that is not without bite, so I think it's appropriate name.} ({Of course White could start with} 1. c4 {too.} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6) 1... d5 2. c4 ({And here} 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 e6 4. e3 {would be another move order.}) 2... e6 3. e3 ({And again White can play} 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 {5.g3 O-O 6.Bg2 b6 is the Neo-Catalan chapter.}) 3... Nf6 {We will pretty much play ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...O-O against anything. The timing of other moves such as ...c5 and ...b6 will vary a bit, depending on what White does.} 4. b3 ({If White plays} 4. d4 {anytime in the next few moves, we'll just end up in the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 4... Be7 ({This is consistent with our whole repertoire. Another good setup, recommended by Gustafsson in his Chess24 course, is} 4... c5 5. Bb2 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 {when Black will play ...Bd6 instead of ...Be7. This is perfectly sound, but it leaves us hanging against White's 4.Nc3 move order.}) 5. Bb2 O-O {This is the real starting point for this chapter. White's setup is not as harmless as it appears to be.} 6. Nc3 (6. d4 {is yet again the QGD with 4.e3.}) (6. g3 b6 $1 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O c5 {brings us to the Neo-Catalan.}) 6... c5 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4]} ({I would like to play} 6... b6 {but after} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 $6 {better is 7...exd5 but after 8.d4 we are in a line of the Queen's Indian that is sound but outside of our repertoire.} 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Qc2 c5 10. Bd3 $16 {White threatens both our h7-pawn and Be4.}) 7. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gb8c6]} ({Instead} 7... Nxd5 {is definitely playable, but} 8. Qc2 $5 {is a serious setup. White has various attacking ideas connected with moves like h4 and Ng5. There are all kinds of move orders and a great many pitfalls, so I prefer to avoid it.}) 8. d4 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gb2b3] We threatened to keep pushing our d-pawn, so this is necessary. Now we have a kind of Tarrasch QGD, which is not what we usually go looking for, but White has played a rather modest setup, and he is still a couple of moves away from getting castled.} Nc6 9. Be2 {The key position. Black has tried many things here, but often White gets a nagging advantage. We have to be accurate to generate enough counterplay.} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc8g4] Black maintains the tension and plays actively. The top players almost universally go for this, and with good reason.} (9... cxd4 {is premature.} 10. Nxd4 $14 {is quite pleasant for White. He will castle, play Rc1, Nxc6, Na4 and maintain a grip on the dark squares.}) (9... Bg4 $6 {looks logical, and it is Black's most common move. But it's not very good.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O $16 {Black can never achieve ...d4, and White has clear plans - Rc1, h3. Even though Black's position looks reasonable, White has scored close to 80% here.}) 10. O-O {White castles before conisdering the opening of the center.} Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%mdl 32768] Putting pressure on d4.} 11. Nxe4 {This looks strange, as it corrects Black's structure.} dxe4 12. Ne5 ({The d4-pawn is in trouble after} 12. Nd2 $2 Bf5 $17) 12... Bxe5 $1 {Other moves are playable too, but this is the most ambitious.} 13. dxe5 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d3,Gd8g5] An idea of Mikhalevski from 2017. The knight heads to d3. This has not been seen in practice, but I imagine that's just because White players are not rushing to play 11.Nxe4.} ({Instead} 13... Qg5 14. Qc2 $1 {(If 14.Qd5? Rd8 15.Qxe4 Rd2 16.Bd3 Qg6! wins for Black.)} Bf5 15. e6 $1 {is promising for White, as pointed out by Mikhalevski.}) 14. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1c5,Gf1d1]} ({Nothing else looks critical. If} 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 $15 {and we are coming into d3.}) 14... Qg5 {Aggressive.} ({Even the modest} 14... b6 {is playable.}) 15. Qc4 ({If} 15. f4 exf3 16. Rxf3 {White's pawns are split, but he threatens Qxc5 and e6 could still be annoying.} Qe7 {intending ...Be6 takes care of everything though.}) 15... Bf5 ({Following Mikhalevski. The immediate} 15... Qg6 {threatening ...Bh3, is also possible. After 16.Kh1? b6 $17 is a big problem for White. Better is} 16. f3 b6 17. Qxe4 Qxe4 18. fxe4 Ba6 {with an unclear endgame.}) 16. e6 $5 {[%csl Gb2]} ({This is a better try than} 16. f4 {as given by Mikhalevski. Then} Qg6 17. Qxc5 Nd3 18. Bxd3 exd3 $13 {gives Black more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) 16... Qg6 ({White is better after both} 16... fxe6 17. Qxc5 {and}) (16... Bxe6 17. Qxe4 {.}) 17. exf7+ Rxf7 $132 {[%cal Gf5h3,Gb4d3] Black has excellent counterplay here, and White should be careful.} *

