y. Now we have a kind of Tarrasch QGD, which is not what we usually go looking for, but White has played a rather modest setup, and he is still a couple of moves away from getting castled.} Nc6 9. Be2 {The key position. Black has tried many things here, but often White gets a nagging advantage. We have to be accurate to generate enough counterplay.} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc8g4] Black maintains the tension and plays actively. The top players almost universally go for this, and with good reason.} (9... cxd4 {is premature.} 10. Nxd4 $14 {is quite pleasant for White. He will castle, play Rc1, Nxc6, Na4 and maintain a grip on the dark squares.}) (9... Bg4 $6 {looks logical, and it is Black's most common move. But it's not very good.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O $16 {Black can never achieve ...d4, and White has clear plans - Rc1, h3. Even though Black's position looks reasonable, White has scored close to 80% here.}) 10. O-O Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rd4] Putting pressure on d4.} 11. Rc1 {A logical move, securing the c3-knight.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] We have to go in for simplifications.} ({We can't play} 11... Bg4 $2 12. dxc5 $16 {.}) 12. Nxe4 {White has to go for this.} ({Instead} 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. exd4 Bf5 $15 {is better for Black - White's b2-bishop is blocked in.}) 12... dxe4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 {White has to head for the endgame to have any hopes of achieving anything.} Qxd4 16. exd4 {[%cal Gc1c7]} Be6 ({Some care is needed. I prefer this to} 16... Rd8 {but both moves should hold without much difficulty.}) 17. Rc7 Rfd8 ({Black also held with} 17... Rfc8 {in Nakamura-Le Quang Liem, chess.com rapid 2019.}) ({After} 17... Rfd8 18. Rd1 {(Or 18.Rxb7 Rxd4 ) .} Rd7 19. Rxd7 Bxd7 {there's not much left for White. For example} 20. f3 exf3 21. Bxf3 Rb8 22. Rc1 Rc8) *

