1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. b3 {This is a good setup when Black has played ...c6, but here it neglects the center for too long.} c5 $1 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. Nbd2 Qc7 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge6e5] Black is already better. The queen bishop rarely should be in a fianchetto in the King's Indian.} 9. e4 ({White could also play a bad Benoni with} 9. c4 d4 $15) 9... d4 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b5] Black will play ...e5 and gradually attack on the queenside.} *

