1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nc3 {This is a normal enough move in the King's Indian.} c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. e4 Nc6 {This is like a reversed classical King's Indian, but we have modestly placed our pawn on e6.} 8. e5 {White continues like he does in the main lines.} ({It's amusing that after a more neutral move like} 8. h3 {the computer is very happy to play} d4 9. Ne2 e5 {when we have a Mar del Plata King's Indian down a tempo, and White has the extra move h3 . Despite the computer's favorable evaluation for us, I imagine white players would be happy enough here. I would prefer a modest setup with 8...b6 which looks comfortable for Black.}) 8... Nd7 9. Re1 {[%csl Rc3] So White's knight is on c3 instead of d2. It does not have much future on c3, but it does stop ... b5 for the moment.} Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga7a5,Gd8c7] Preparing ...b5. Black looks very comfortable here as his queenside play is easy. It's not clear how White can make progress on the kingside.} *

