1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Bf4 {This is kind of an odd move, but it can't be too bad.} c5 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. e4 Nc6 8. Ne5 {An independent continuation.} ({A funny transposition may arise after} 8. e5 Nd7 {White has to watch for ...g5 here.} 9. h4 {and now after the logical moves} b5 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Re1 Qc7 12. Nf1 Rfc8 {we are right back in the main lines!}) 8... Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Nd7 $1 10. Bf4 (10. Bc3 d4 11. Bd2 e5 {is similar.}) 10... d4 {Black goes for a normal King's Indian position.} 11. a4 e5 12. Bd2 b6 ({This looks simpler than} 12... Nb8 13. Na3 Nc6 {as played in Artemiev-Esipenko, Russian Championship 2020, but Black is fine here as well.}) 13. Na3 Rb8 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] The normal plan. Black prepares an advance on the queenside.} 14. f4 a6 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gb6b5,Gf4f5,Ge7g5,Gg3g4,Rh2h4,Ge7h4] Black has easy play. Note that White cannot just storm us on the kingside, as after f5 it's not easy to advance further, and we may also play the positionally desirable ... Bg5.} *

