1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. c4 $5 {This is actually a very tricky move. White may take on d5 and follow with d3-d4. Objectively Black is fine after White loses a tempo, but we may reach unfamiliar structures.} b6 $5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({If White is going to be clever, we will be too. Of course} 6... c5 {must be ok, but after} 7. cxd5 exd5 {or 7...Nxd5 8.d4!? with a Semi-Tarrasch where White is down a tempo. Black must be ok, but it's not as trivial as we'd expect.} 8. d4 Nc6 9. Nc3 {Now it's a Tarrasch where it's usually White's move. In effect, now we are 'White'. Oddly enough, this in a line I consider in my course on the Symmetrical English. The position is identical, but the color of the pieces has changed, so I examine the position from 'White's' side. Weird!}) 7. cxd5 exd5 $1 ({In similar positions in the Neo-Catalan, we play} 7... Nxd5 8. d4 {White loses a tempo, but he has also refrained from b3 and Bb2, so he is actually up a move in the fight for the center!} Bb7 9. Re1 $1 c5 10. e4 Nf6 11. Nc3 $14 {is nice for White.}) 8. Nc3 ({White can play} 8. d4 {immediately too.} Bb7 9. Nc3 c5 {will reach the same position.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bf4 ({Again} 9. d4 c5 10. Bf4 {transposes.}) 9... c5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd5d4]} 10. d4 {White cannot really do without this for long, or we will play ...d4 ourselves.} Nc6 11. Rc1 ({After} 11. dxc5 bxc5 {we will soon be ready for ...d4.}) 11... Ne4 $5 ({Black should avoid releasing the tension himself. After} 11... cxd4 $6 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc5 14. Qd3 Qe7 15. Bg5 {White had lasting pressure without having done anything special in Fedoseev-Mamedyarov, chess.com rapid 2023.}) 12. dxc5 (12. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 {and taking the d4-pawn favors Black.}) 12... Nxc3 13. Rxc3 bxc5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd5] The hanging pawns are pretty secure here.} 14. Qa4 Qb6 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gc3b3,Gb6a6,Gf8e8,Ga8d8] I like this simple move. Black will centralize the rooks, and we can meet Rb3 with ...Qa6. We have seen some similar positions in the Tartakover.} ({Black can also force matters with} 14... d4 15. Rcc1 Nb4 16. a3 Nd5 17. Bd2 Nb6 $132 {gave Black an active position in Usmanov-Zenzera, Kolomna 2014. White could also try the tricky 15.Nxd4!? but Black is ok after 15...Nxd4 White's point was that after 15...cxd4 there is 16.Rb3! 16.Bxb7 Nxe2+ 17.Kg2 Nxf4+ 18.Qxf4 Rb8=}) *

