1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 {The main line.} c5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4,Ga5a4]} ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. exd5 {This is not very common, but it's not bad. Black can recapture either way.} Nxd5 ({This is my preference, but Black can also play} 9... exd5 10. d4 {when Black will have to accept an isolated pawn, as} c4 11. Ne5 {gives White some initiative.}) 10. c4 {[%cal Gg2a8] This is very forcing, so it has to be checked.} (10. a4 b4 {transposes to 9.a4.}) 10... bxc4 11. dxc4 (11. Nxc4 Bb7 {is level. Both sides have an isolated pawn and some good squares. In my database, this has only been played once, and it was a game between two players local to me, in Foygel-Bryan, USA 1998.}) 11... Ndb4 {[%cal Gb4d3] Heading for d3.} (11... Nb6 {is ok too. If} 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxa8 Nd3 {wins back the exchange.}) 12. Ne5 {Without this, White would even be worse.} Bb7 13. a3 ({White should force matters.} 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bxc6 Nxc6 {is very comfortable for Black.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Bxb7 Nbd3 15. Bxa8 ({If} 15. Rxe5 {we could take the rook, but} Rb8 $1 {is even stronger.} 16. Re3 Rxb7 $15) 15... Nxe1 16. Qxe1 Nd3 {[%cal Gd3e1,Gd3c1,Gd8a8] Black wins back the piece with comfortable equality.} *

