1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 {The main line.} c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb5b4,Ga5a4]} ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. exd5 {This is not very common, but it's not bad. Black can recapture either way.} Nxd5 ({This is my preference, but Black can also play} 9... exd5 10. d4 {when Black will have to accept an isolated pawn, as} c4 11. Ne5 {gives White some initiative.}) 10. Ne4 {As played by Svidler against Karjakin, and later vs. Duda.} (10. a4 b4 {transposes to 9.a4.}) 10... Bb7 {[%mdl 32768] White has a normal open King's indian position while Black has easy development. With the black pawn on e6 instead of e5, Black does not have the usual space advantage associated with such a structure, but he also does not have a target on e5. The position is level, with plenty of play ahead.} 11. c3 Rc8 {Duda's choice.} ({Karjakin played the rather unnecessary} 11... a6 12. a4 b4 13. Bg5 $5 f6 14. Bd2 e5 15. Rc1 Rf7 {Black's position looks rather loose and Svidler struck with} 16. d4 bxc3 17. bxc3 cxd4 18. cxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Qb3 $1 {and Black had tactical problems in Svidler-Karjakin, Baku (m/1) 2015.}) 12. Bg5 {Svidler plays as he did against Karjakin.} h6 ({A modest move, which is certainly safer than} 12... f6) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Gf8d8] Black certainly looks fine here.} 14. d4 cxd4 15. cxd4 {Svidler was probably hoping the c5-square would mean something, but with the pressure on the d4-pawn it's not so easy to use it.} ({The isolated pawn position is comfortable for Black, but} 15. Nxd4 Rfd8 {is too.}) 15... Rfd8 16. Qe2 ({If} 16. Nc5 $2 Nxd4 $1 {wins a pawn.}) 16... a6 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd5b6,Gc6b4,Gc8c2] A small improvement. We secure the b5-pawn and can put pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nb6. Bringing a knight to b4 with the idea of ...Rc2 is another idea.} ({Black was also doing fine with} 16... Nb6 {and he went on to win in Svidler-Duda, chess24.com 2020.}) *

