1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. a4 {This is generally played to try to get an improved version of the 9.exd5 line, but it only has real effect if we recapture with the pawn, which is not our intention.} b4 10. e5 $6 {Playing in the traditional way makes less sense here, as White has weakened his queenside for no reason.} Nd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Nf1 Ba6 $1 {Black has saved a tempo on ...a5. We just don't need it here.} 12. Bf4 ({If} 12. h4 Qc7 13. Bf4 Rfc8 {Black is ready for ...Qd8 with a great position.}) 12... b3 $1 {A strong move which disrupts White greatly.} ({Black avoids the} 12... Qc7 13. Ne3 Rfc8 14. Nxd5 {trick, but if the coming sequence does not convince you, a move like 12...Qb6 or 12...Qa5 would be fine. Black still has the ...Rfc8, ...Qd8 plan.}) 13. c3 ({After} 13. cxb3 $2 Rb8 $17 {both the b- and d-pawns are very weak.}) 13... g5 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gg5g4] This does not often work, but this position is an exception.} 14. Nxg5 {Retreating the bishop will lose the e5-pawn.} Bxg5 15. Qg4 {[%cal Ga6d3] Usually this sequence is bad news for Black, but the weakened d3-pawn changes things.} h6 $1 ({An important detail. The immediate} 15... h5 {is less strong. After} 16. Qxh5 Bxf4 17. gxf4 Bxd3 {Black has to worry about a rook lift to e3 and h3.}) 16. h4 h5 $1 17. Qxg5+ ({Here} 17. Qxh5 Bxf4 18. gxf4 Bxd3 $17 {is good for Black - we can play ...Bh7 and ...Kh8. White does not have enough compensation for the piece.}) 17... Qxg5 18. hxg5 Bxd3 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2][%cal Gc5c4,Gd7c5,Gd3g6] Black's queenside space advantage gives him a big edge in the endgame.} *

