1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h2,Gf1e3,Gc1f4] White's best move. The knight may come to e3 or h2 and now the e5-pawn can be supported with Bf4.} Bb7 {[%mdl 32768] The modern interpretation. Now the normal move is 11.h4, but Kamil Plichta makes a good argument for White to change the move order. We checked the traditional move} (10... a5 {as an informational line.}) 11. Bf4 $5 Qb6 $5 {A little detour. Perhaps white players were keen to play 11.h4 to avoid 11...g5? but this just does not work, as 12.Nxg5! Bxg5 13.Qg4 definitely favors White. Our normal move would be 11...Qc7 This is what White is hoping for, because of the trick 12.Ne3 Rfc8?! 13.Nxd5! but I think 11...Qc7 is still playable! We'll consider this as an alternative.} 12. h4 Rfc8 13. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} h6 14. g4 $5 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gg4g5]} ({This is all pretty normal. Now} 14. N1h2 Qd8 {would transpose to the main lines which we'll see later. The only difference is that Black's queen went to b8 and d8 instead of c7 and b8.}) ({This is Plichta's recommendation. He calls Black's plan a little slow, but it's not any slower than with the black queen on c7...} 14. N1h2 Qd8 {transposes to the main lines with 11.h4.}) 14... Qd8 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8h7] Now ...Nf8-h7 would lock down the g5-square for the foreseeable future, so White's next move is practically forced.} 15. Qd2 {[%cal Gg4g5] Plichta stops here, and indeed g4-g5 will open things up a bit.} a5 16. g5 ({White should act immediately. As we'll see later,} 16. N1h2 Ra6 $1 {is quite nice for Black.}) 16... hxg5 17. Nxg5 {[%cal Gh5h6] Now h5-h6 will open things further. With so many pieces concentrated on the kingside, White won't worry about the pawn count.} Ndxe5 $5 {[%cal Ge7g5] We will see this tactic later as well. We are not winning a pawn, but meeting a flank attack with play in the center is supposed to be a good idea!} ({The engine contends that} 17... a4 18. h6 gxh6 {is equal, but White has too many attacking ideas to contend with, and I'm not a computer.}) 18. Nxe6 Qd6 $1 ({A calm move.} 18... fxe6 19. Bxe5 {favors White. This is unexplored territory, so we'll check a couple possibilities.}) 19. Ng5 Re8 {[%cal Ge7f6,Ga5a4,Gd5d4] We have an unusual position, but Black looks ok here. White has more space on the kingside, but with the center opened it won't be easy for him to attack and his own king position is compromised.} *

