1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 Bb7 ({We checked the traditional move} 10... a5 {as an informational line.}) 11. h4 {This is the main line. White has various attacking ideas on the kingside. We will seek our fortune on other parts of the board.} Qc7 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {[%cal Gc7d8]} 13. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6] The main plan for White. Black could allow h6, meeting it with ...g6, but there are three problems with this: 1. we give up the g5-square. 2. we always have to be wary of mate on g7. 3. we will have back rank problems forever.} h6 {[%csl Gh6]} 14. N1h2 {[%cal Gh2g4]} Qd8 $1 {[%mdl 32768] White can rev up for a sacrifice on h6, or play for g4-g5} 15. c3 {[%cal Gb5b4] This has been played a few times, including in one of the earliest games with Black's setup. Most white players play without this move, as it gives Black something to bite onto on the queenside.} ({Instead} 15. Ng4 Bf8 16. Qd2 a5 {is considered via 15.Qd2.}) 15... a5 16. Qd2 ({If} 16. a4 bxa4 $1 {opens lines. Black can follow with ...Nb6 and push the a-pawn.}) 16... d4 $1 {This is objectively best, and it allows us to follow the late Igor Bukavshin, who was an early pioneer of the ...Qc7, ...Rfc8, ...Qd8 idea.} (16... Nf8 {is also a legitimate plan. After} 17. a4 Ba6 $1 18. Ng4 Nh7 19. axb5 Bxb5 {immediate sacrifices on h6 do not work, and following} 20. Kh2 Bf8 {Black was doing well in Jakubiec-Meier, Germany 2019.}) 17. Ng4 ({If} 17. cxd4 cxd4 {with ...Nc5 and ...Nb4 coming, Black has a strong initiative.}) ({while} 17. c4 bxc4 18. dxc4 {is a structure we've considered. This occurred in Novik-Caletka, Pardubice 2019. Now} a4 {intending ...Na5 looks very good for Black.}) 17... dxc3 {Opening lines.} 18. bxc3 Bf8 $17 {[%cal Gb5b4]} 19. Z0 ({Black has to take some care of course but objectively he is much better. An early game in this line went} 19. Nfh2 Rab8 20. Be4 b4 21. cxb4 {was Andreikin-Bukavshin, Sochi 2015. Here} c4 $1 {intending ...Bb4, would have been very strong.}) *

