1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 {With this move White delays the fight in the center and plays a reversed King's Indian Defence, thus the nomenclature 'King's Indian Attack'.} ({Instead} 5. c4 O-O {and now} 6. b3 {is the Neo-Catalan. 6.d4 is the main line of the Catalan. 6.Qc2 is a peculiar move. After 6...c5 White has nothing better than 7.d4 when we have reached the 6.Qc2 Catalan.}) 5... O-O ({I prefer this move order to} 5... c5 6. e4 $5 {intending Qe2, which can even be followed with e5 and c4!?. If} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nxe4 9. Ne5 Nd6 10. Na3 $13 {White has good compensation for the pawn. Now 6.d3 is by far the main move, but we'll also check some rare alternatives.}) 6. Nbd2 c5 ({There are alternatives, such as} 6... b6) ({and Colovic's suggestion} 6... Nc6 {, but we will stick with Black's main setup.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. Re1 ({This is more accurate than} 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 Qc7 $1 {hitting the e5-pawn and forcing} 10. Qe2 b5 11. h4 a5 {which transposes to the line with 10.h4.}) 8... b5 ({Sometimes Black tries} 8... Qc7 {hoping to get White into the position mentioned on the last move, but} 9. c3 $5 {as given by Plichta, causes fresh problems. So we will stick to the main line.}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 Bb7 ({We checked the traditional move} 10... a5 {as an informational line.}) 11. h4 {This is the main line. White has various attacking ideas on the kingside. We will seek our fortune on other parts of the board.} Qc7 12. Bf4 Rfc8 {[%cal Gc7d8]} 13. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6] The main plan for White. Black could allow h6, meeting it with ...g6, but there are three problems with this: 1. we give up the g5-square. 2. we always have to be wary of mate on g7. 3. we will have back rank problems forever.} h6 {[%csl Gh6]} 14. N1h2 {[%cal Gh2g4]} Qd8 $1 {White can rev up for a sacrifice on h6, or play for g4-g5.} 15. Qd2 {This looks best, as it fits in with both of White's attacking ideas.} a5 ({We do not have to worry yet, so it's best to get the queenside play going. If} 15... Bf8 {we loosen control of the g5-square and after} 16. g4 {White gets in g5 next move.}) 16. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} Ra6 $1 ({A cool move, which surprisingly prevents White's advance tactically. Black is avoiding} 16... a4 17. g5 hxg5 18. Nxg5 Ncxe5 19. Nxe6 $1 {We saw a similar idea earlier in the 11.Bf4 line where this worked out ok for Black.}) 17. Re2 {[%cal Ga1e1] A sober strategic move. As the advance of the g-pawn doe snot work yet, but prepares to bring his las piece into play.} ({A young Gukesh played} 17. c3 {but we know this is usually not helpful to White. His opponent played the normal} a4 {and got a great position, while the computer loves 17...Rb6!? first, and only then shoving the pawns.}) 17... a4 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. a3 {This is often how White reacts to our advance (like we met h5 with ...h6). It's a tough choice as Black can open lines on the queenside easily now.} b4 {The queenside opens up and Black is much better.} 19. Z0 ({One game continued} 19. Rae1 bxa3 20. bxa3 Nd4 $1 {Opening more lines.} 21. Nxd4 cxd4 $17 {and the a3-pawn soon fell in Murzin-Toropov, Sochi 2019.}) *

