1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} ({In his Lifetime Repertoire, Liem Quang Le gives the unusual move order} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 $5 {This is directed against} c5 {because} 4. dxc5 $5 {creates unusual complications. Instead we would play 3...e6 4.Bf4 c5 5.e3 Bd6 when we are right back in our main repertoire.}) 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc7c5] This looks a bit passive, but it's consistent with our QGD approach, and it's a big main line. We avoid symmetry and intend to challenge the 'London bishop'.} ({Another move order is} 3... c5 {intending} 4. c3 e6 {but there is no reason for us to allow 4.dxc5!?}) 4. Nf3 ({The move orders do not affect us too much.} 4. c3 c5 {and}) (4. Nd2 c5 {should soon transpose.}) 4... c5 ({Another move order for Black, which was given by Sielecki in Keep it Simple for Black, is} 4... Bd6 {This has the benefit of avoiding certain lines like 4...c5 5.c3 Bd6 6.Bb5+, but} 5. Ne5 $5 {as given by Sahaj and Srinath, annoys me.} O-O {Here 5...c5?! 6.Bb5+ would force us to move our king.} 6. Nd2 c5 7. c3 {with the idea Ndf3 is not without bite. This setup gives White an iron grip on e5 and allows him to consider attacking ideas with h4-h5 or g4-g5. Sethumaran counters this with the rare} c4 $5 {We will see a similar plan in our repertoire, but with we will not rush to castle and present White with a clear target on the kingside.}) 5. c3 ({Another move order, advocated by Sahaj and Srinath in their Lifetime Repertoire on the London, is} 5. Nbd2 {keeping the option of c2-c4 in one go. We will cover this.}) 5... Nc6 {This is of course very natural and it's not surprising that it has always been the main line. I wanted to cover this, but I encountered problems...} ({Instead} 5... Bd6 {will be our move order.}) 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. Bg3 {A typical idea, as Black does not want to open the h-file for White's rook.} O-O 8. Bd3 ({White also has} 8. Bb5 {but I was less discouraged here.}) 8... b6 ({The main line.. There are alternatives, but I wasn't completely satisfied with any of them. One nice trap is seen after} 8... Qe7 {(playing for ...e5)} 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 $2 {Bad, but taking with the queen does not completely equalize either.} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4 $1 {and White has a winning attack.}) 9. e4 $1 {The critical test.} (9. Ne5 Bb7 10. f4 Ne7 $1 {gives Black nice counterplay.}) 9... Be7 $1 {Practice has shown this to be the best try.} (9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bb7 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Qa4 $1 {causes problems.}) 10. e5 Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g3] This line always seemed interesting to me, and it was even given by Boris Avrukh in his Grandmaster Repertoire book, Dealing with 1.d4 Sidelines.} ({Black is suffering after} 10... Nd7 11. h4 $1) 11. Ng5 $1 {This is the problem.} Bxg5 12. Qxh5 g6 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. h4 $13 {White has good attacking chances here. This line is recommended for White in the Lifetime Repertoires on the London by Liem Quang Le and by Sahaj and Srinath. The engines totally approve of this pawn sacrifice, and it just looked impractical to deal with White's attacking chances here.} *

