1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] A weird move. It's like White wishes he had played the Jobava system.} a6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gb7b5,Gb8d7,Gf8e7] I avoid this luxury in the actual Jobava line because StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bf4 a6 can be met with 4.e3 e6 5.g4!? Here White's knight is already on f3, so things are more stable. I also prefer to avoid 5...Be7 6.Nb5 Na6 This may be ok for Black, but unlike in our Jobava lines, we cannot kick the b5-knight with ...c6.} 6. Be2 {The most common.} (6. a3 {has been played several times, but I don't get it. We can just play} Nc6 {, 6...Nbd7 , or 6...b5}) (6. Ne5 {looks premature. Black can play} Nc6 {with similar play to our main line, while 6...Nfd7!? also looks quite good.}) (6. Bd3 {is rarely played. This bishop is more active here than it is on e2 , but 6...c4! 7.Be2 b5 gives Black a lot of space on the queenside while White lacks attacking chances. It looks about equal to me, but the engines like Black.}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Ne5 ({After} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bd3 Bd6 {we transpose to 6.dxc5, with both sides having lost a tempo.}) 8... O-O {We could take the knight, but we don't have to fear the coming exchange.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Na4 {[%csl Gc5] White is hoping to have some kind of grip, but it's nothing.} cxd4 11. exd4 a5 $5 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gf6d7,Gc8a6] We plan ...Ba6, and can fight for the e5- and c5-squares with ...Bd6 or ...Nd7.} *

