1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] A weird move. It's like White wishes he had played the Jobava system.} a6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gb7b5,Gb8d7,Gf8e7] I avoid this luxury in the actual Jobava line because StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 d5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Bf4 a6 can be met with 4.e3 e6 5.g4!? Here White's knight is already on f3, so things are more stable. I also prefer to avoid 5...Be7 6.Nb5 Na6 This may be ok for Black, but unlike in our Jobava lines, we cannot kick the b5-knight with ...c6.} 6. dxc5 {A strange move, allowing us to capture on c5 in one go.} Bxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Bd3 Nc6 8. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] White's only plan is e3-e4.} Bd6 $5 {A typical move against the London bishop.} ({Instead} 8... O-O 9. e4 d4 $6 {looks good, but after} 10. Ne2 {Black does not have control of the e5-square, so White may well play e5 himself.}) 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. e4 d4 11. e5 $5 (11. Ne2 e5 {is comfortable for Black.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxd4 {Black has various moves here.} (12. Nxe5 $6 dxc3 13. Nc4 Qc7 {just leads to a bad pawn structure for White.}) 12... Ke7 $5 {[%cal Gh8d8,Gd6d4] I like this funny move. With the king on a dark square, there are no discovered attacks and we really threaten to take the d4-knight. The king is not badly placed at all and we can develop with ...Rd8, ...Bd7, etc.} (12... O-O {and}) (12... Bd7 {are both fine too.}) *

