1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gc2c4] An interesting move order which was recommended by Sahaj and Srinath in their Lifetime Repertoire on the London. The main idea is that White may well play c3 instead of the typical c3.} Qb6 $5 {[%mdl 32768] This looks the simplest. Black prevents Bb5+ and hits the b-pawn, taking advantage of the fact that White cannot respond with Qb3. This move has been played by Ding Liren, Nakamura, Dominguez, Vidit, Shankland, and Tomashevsky, so it must be pretty good.} (5... Nc6 6. c3 {is the old main line which we are avoiding.}) (5... Bd6 {is our normal move. Then} 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 $5 {is the idea from Sahaj and Srinath. This is not the end of the world - Black has a normal position - but I think 5...Qb6 is easier.}) 6. c4 {This is rare, but it's been played a few times.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd2] Increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn. The d2-knight looks rather silly for this structure.} ({After} 6... cxd4 7. exd4 {Black has to worry about c4-c5. Then} dxc4 8. Nxc4 Bb4+ $6 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qd8 11. Qb4 {led to a quick white victory in Erigaisi-Xiong, FTX rapid 2022.}) ({After} 6... Nc6 $1 {I can hardly imagine Black facing any problems.} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bd3 $6 Qxb2 {as already a safe pawn grab in Berczes-Siddharth, Budapest 2022.}) *

