1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gc2c4] An interesting move order which was recommended by Sahaj and Srinath in their Lifetime Repertoire on the London. The main idea is that White may well play c3 instead of the typical c3.} Qb6 $5 {This looks the simplest. Black prevents Bb5+ and hits the b-pawn, taking advantage of the fact that White cannot respond with Qb3. This move has been played by Ding Liren, Nakamura, Dominguez, Vidit, Shankland, and Tomashevsky, so it must be pretty good.} (5... Nc6 6. c3 {is the old main line which we are avoiding.}) (5... Bd6 {is our normal move. Then} 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 $5 {is the idea from Sahaj and Srinath. This is not the end of the world - Black has a normal position - but I think 5...Qb6 is easier.}) 6. Rb1 Bd6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Black can also play} 6... cxd4 7. exd4 {Now we are on the 'wrong' side of Carlsbad structure.} Bd7 $1 {With the idea ...Bb5, trading bishops.}) ({Gledura, in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Queen's Gambit Accepted, likes the immediate} 6... Bd7 {often intending the same plan with ...cxd4 and ...Bb5. Both of these are legitimate ideas to consider for some variety.}) 7. dxc5 {White's main choice.} (7. Bxd6 Qxd6 {is harmless. This is similar to 5.c3 Bd6 6.Bxd6 Qxd6=.}) (7. Bg3 O-O 8. c3 Nbd7 {is like the main lines. Black could even drop the queen back to c7, when White's extra move Rb1 is useless at best, as castling long is not even an option.}) 7... Qxc5 8. b4 {Trying to make use of 6.Rb1.} Qc7 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. c4 O-O 11. Be2 ({If} 11. c5 Qc7 {Black can quickly chip away at the pawn structure with ...b6 and ...a5.}) 11... b6 ({The immediate} 11... a5 {is also possible.}) 12. O-O {This is given by Sahaj and Srinath.} a5 ({They point out the small trick} 12... Bb7 13. c5 {with the idea Qb3 and Rfc1. This is probably not too terrifying, but Black can avoid it nonetheless.}) 13. a3 (13. bxa5 Rxa5 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Rxb6 Ba6 {led to a quick draw in Sedlak-Nguyen, Muelheim 2022. The a2-pawn will fall.}) (13. b5 Bb7 14. cxd5 Qxd5 15. Nc4 Nbd7 {looks fine for Black as well.}) 13... axb4 {Opening the a-file helps Black.} 14. axb4 Bb7 ({Allowing the little trick, but we'll have an improved version. Both} 14... Nbd7 {and}) (14... Qe7 {look fine as well.}) 15. c5 bxc5 16. bxc5 Qe7 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gb7c6,Gb7a6,Gb8d7] Black can easily develop. The c5-pawn is not going anywhere and it could easily become a target.} *

