1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 {[%mdl 32768]} 6. dxc5 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {This makes Black spend another tempo with the bishop, but it concedes the center.} 6... Bxc5 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O h6 $5 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge6e5,Rf4g5,Gf6h5] This covers the g5-square. Black is totally fine here in various ways. We just have to consider White's e3-e4 break.} (9... Nh5 $2 {is not possible yet because of} 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+) (9... Re8 {is a good alternative.} 10. e4 e5 {and the pin is not dangerous.} 11. Bg5 d4) (9... Bd6 {is fine too, but a bit boring.}) 10. h3 ({If} 10. e4 Nh5 $1 {successfully nabs the bishop.}) 10... Re8 11. e4 e5 12. Bh2 {Now the easiest plan is to simplify.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 f6 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gc8e6] Black easily completes his development. Meanwhile White's London bishop is out of play.} *

