1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bxd6 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {This is harmless.} 6... Qxd6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Ge6e5,Gb7b6,Gc8a6][%mdl 32768] The queen is well placed on d6. Black will just castle and can play for ...e5.} 7. Ne5 {The only way to try to make anything of White's position is to set up a Stonewall with f4. The idea seems logical as White has traded his 'bad bishop' (although it was hardly bad on f4). The problem for White is that all of this takes time, and Black is ahead in development so White can't consolidate his center.} ({If White plays slowly with} 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Nbd7 {or 8...Nc6 and Black is ready to play ...e5 with a good game.}) 7... O-O 8. Nd2 Nfd7 $1 {Immediately challenging White in the center.} 9. f4 {This is consistent at least.} ({If} 9. Ndf3 Nc6) 9... f6 {White is not going to win the battle for e5.} 10. Nef3 ({After} 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 11. Bd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 e5 {Black is doing well.}) 10... Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc5d4] The ...e5 break is coming. Black may even exchange on d4 first to open the position further. White should be careful.} *

