1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bxd6 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {This is harmless.} 6... Qxd6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Ge6e5,Gb7b6,Gc8a6] The queen is well placed on d6. Black will just castle and can play for ...e5.} 7. Ne5 {The only way to try to make anything of White's position is to set up a Stonewall with f4. The idea seems logical as White has traded his 'bad bishop' (although it was hardly bad on f4). The problem for White is that all of this takes time, and Black is ahead in development so White can't consolidate his center.} ({If White plays slowly with} 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Nbd7 {or 8...Nc6 and Black is ready to play ...e5 with a good game.}) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6][%mdl 32768] A typical idea. Black intends ...Ba6. There's no reason White should have anything here.} ({Here we should avoid} 8... Nfd7 9. f4 f6 $2 10. Qh5 $1) 9. Qe2 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] And ...Ba6. We will see this idea in the next line too.} *

