1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Nbd2 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) ({White allows the exchange of bishops on f4, hoping the strengthening of his control of the e5-square will compensate for the doubled f-pawns. Black's simplest is to fall in line with White's plans.} 6. Bd3 {will lead to similar play after} Bxf4 7. exf4 Qc7 8. g3 b6) 6... Bxf4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({After} 6... Nc6 7. Bg3 {we have been tricked into the old classical line with .}) ({I also prefer to avoid} 6... O-O 7. Ne5 {intending Ndf3. We want to delay castling against this setup.}) 7. exf4 Qc7 {[%csl Rf4] Hitting the f4-pawn.} 8. g3 O-O 9. Bd3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6] We just want to exchange bishops. White can only delay this, but he can't stop it.} 10. Qe2 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gb6b5,Gb5b4,Gc5c4,Ga5a4] Further exchanges diminish White's attacking chances. The structure is still safe for White, so chances are equal. After the exchange of bishops, Black will likely play on the queenside with an eventual ...b5, maybe combined with ...c4.} *

