1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Ne5 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3]} ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {This early advance almost looks simplistic, but it can be dangerous.} 6... Qc7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({We are avoiding} 6... O-O 7. Nd2 Qc7 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. Ndf3 {With the center stable, White can consider playing h5-h5 or g4-g5. It's not so easy to create counterplay.}) 7. Nd2 Nc6 (7... Nbd7 {is also possible. Bringing the knight to c6 when possible looks more natural.}) 8. Bb5 {This is quite harmless, as Black does not mind trading some pieces.} O-O {Black is doing well here.} 9. Bxc6 {Without this White is already worse.} bxc6 ({9...Nh5 is good too. exd4} 9... Ne4 {with the idea ...f6 already favors Black.}) 10. O-O {Again White doesn't have a lot of options here.} (10. Qa4 $2 Nh5 $17) 10... Rb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ga7a5,Gc8a6,Gc5d4,Gc6c5] Black already has some initiative. The 'bad' bishop can come to a6. Exchanging pawns on d4 followed by ...c5 is another possibility.} *

