1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Ne5 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3]} ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {This can be a bit annoying as we want to avoid castling again White's Nd2-f3 setup. This early advance almost looks simplistic, but it can be dangerous.} 6... Qc7 ({We are avoiding} 6... O-O 7. Nd2 Qc7 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. Ndf3 {With the center stable, White can consider playing h5-h5 or g4-g5. It's not so easy to create counterplay.}) 7. Nd2 Nc6 (7... Nbd7 {is also possible. Bringing the knight to c6 when possible looks more natural.}) 8. Ndf3 cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({A reminder that we want to avoid} 8... O-O 9. Bd3 {when White may start pushing his kingside pawns.}) ({Other good moves are} 8... Nd7 {further challenging White in the center.}) ({And} 8... c4 {, preventing Bd3 and planning ...b5 and ...a5.}) 9. exd4 ({Black is better after} 9. cxd4 Nh5 $1) ({While} 9. Nxc6 Bxf4 10. Ncxd4 {gives Black a pleasant choice between} Bh6 $5 {And 10...Bd6 11.Nb5 Qb6 12.Nxd6+ Qxd6=}) 9... Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6] This prepares ...f6 and looks quite nice for Black.} *

