1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bb5+ ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {A logical move, as we have no choice.} 6... Nc6 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Bg3 {As is often the case, both sides only want to exchange the bishops on their own terms.} (7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Nbd2 O-O {is easy for Black.}) 7... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Ge4g3]} ({We do want to avoid} 7... O-O {not because it's bad, but we transpose to the 5...Nc6 line with 8.Bb5 . There are hundreds of games from this position, and there's no reason to get bogged down in the theory there when there's simpler ways.}) ({Exchanging with} 7... Bxg3 8. hxg3 Qb6 {is Sethumaran's solution, as there are targets on the b-file.}) 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 {[%cal Ge8g8] There's no reason that Black should have any problems here. Black gradually outplayed his opponent and won in Lye-Aleksandrov, Batumi 2018.} *

