1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bb5+ ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {A logical move, as we have no choice.} 6... Nc6 7. Qa4 {This is easily parried. The biggest concern is transposing to a line I prefer to avoid.} Bxf4 {[%mdl 32768] Simple.} (7... O-O {is sound, but after} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Bxd6 {(I am not concerned with 9.Qxc6?! Bxf4 10.exf4 Ne4! when Black has good play.)} Qxd6 {is a line that usually arises from StartFENr1bqk2r/pp3ppp/2nbpn2/1Bpp4/3P1B2/2P1PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QK2R w KQkq - 3 7EndFEN 7.Bxc6+ bxc6 8.Bxd6 Qxd6 9.Qa4 O-O . This is ok for Black, but it requires delicate handling. We'll check this out soon via the aforementioned move order.}) 8. exf4 (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. exf4 Qb6 {is similar.}) 8... Qb6 9. dxc5 (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O O-O {could transpose.}) 9... Qxc5 10. Nbd2 Bd7 11. O-O O-O {Black is totally fine here.} 12. Z0 ({A nice example of how to play this kind of position for Black can be seen in the following game:} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Qd4 Qe7 14. b4 c5 $1 15. bxc5 Rfc8 16. Nb3 a5 $1 {was Seirawan-Alburt, Jacksonville 1990. White allowed ...a4 and taking on c5. If} 17. a4 Ne4 {would win back the pawn as well.}) *

