1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bb5+ ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {A logical move, as we have no choice.} 6... Nc6 7. Ne5 {Very direct.} Qc7 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Qa4 ({After 8.Nxc6?! bxc6 9.Bxc6? Rb8 $17 White can't cover everything. bxc6} 8. Nxc6 {Qc7 Bxd6 Qxd6 Ne5} Rb8 $13 {hitting b2 and planning ...Ba6, also looks sufficient for Black.}) 8... O-O $5 {This pawn sacrifice is very tempting.} (8... Bd7 {is fine too.}) 9. Bxc6 ({After} 9. Nxc6 $6 Bxf4 $17 {everything is starting to fall apart for White.}) 9... bxc6 {[%cal Gf6h5]} ({An obvious move of course, but Sethuraman shows that} 9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nh5 $1 {also gives Black enough play.}) 10. Qxc6 {White is committed, and this is the only good move.} (10. O-O {?} Nh5 $17 {is a typical idea.}) (10. Nd3 $2 {is too slow.} Bxf4 11. Nxf4 cxd4 12. cxd4 c5 $17 {Azevedo-Matsuura, Florianopolis 2018.}) 10... Qb8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 11. Nd2 Qxb2 $5 {This is also playable, even though everything is hanging.} 12. Rb1 Qxc3 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc8a6]} (12... Qxa2 13. Qxa8 Ba6 14. Qxa7 Ne4 {is also possible. The computer says equal (of course).}) 13. O-O $1 (13. Qxd6 $2 Ne4 {is lights out.}) (13. Qxa8 $2 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Ba6 $1 {hits the white queen and gives Black a winning attack.}) 13... Bxe5 14. dxe5 Bd7 {The saving grace.} 15. Qb7 (15. Qc7 $2 Rfc8 16. Qd6 Rc6 17. Qe7 Re8 {wins material.}) 15... Rfb8 16. Qxb8+ Rxb8 17. Rxb8+ Ne8 $13 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gh7h6] It's very messy of course, but Black's play looks easier.} *

