1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. Ne5 {This is not as dangerous as it is in some other positions, because White has spent a tempo on Bf4-g3. This also means we don't have to worry about the advance of White's g-pawn!} ({Note that after} 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 {the tempi even out - Black played ...Qd8-c7xd6, but White played Bf4-g3xd6. So we are in the 6.Bxd6 line, with a tempo more for each side.}) 8... Nc6 {We force White to deal with the attack on e5.} ({This is more flexible than} 8... Nbd7 {as ...Nc6-e7 is an extra possibility.}) ({Another idea is} 8... c4 $5 {but as this can be played on the next move too, it makes sense to force White make a commitment first by challenging the e5-knight first.}) ({A totally different idea is} 8... b6 {planning a quick ...Ba6.}) 9. f4 {White goes for a Stonewall setup.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5][%mdl 32768] Fleixble. Black is a bit spoiled for choice.} (9... Ne4 {has been played a few times, and this looks fine too.}) (9... c4 $5 {could be played immediately. This prevents White's Bd3, but the bishop will not pose us much danger, so we will allow it so we can gain a tempo.}) (9... b6 {is normal, but as ...c4 is a good plan for Black, this would likely be a waste of time as we'll want to go ...b5 soon.}) 10. Bd3 c4 $5 ({Direct and strong. Another idea is} 10... Nf5 11. Bf2 Be7 {with the idea ... Nd6, clamping down on the e4-square.}) 11. Bc2 b5 {[%cal Gb5b4] Black has a lot of space on the queenside and his play is very straightforward.} 12. Z0 ({An instructive sequence is} 12. Bh4 Ne8 $1 {Preparing to kick White's knight with ...f6.} 13. Qh5 $6 g6 {The e7-knight gives Black's kingside extra protection.} 14. Qe2 f6 15. Nef3 b4 $17 {with the initiative in Kayumov-Vallejo Pons, Doha rapid 2016.}) *

