1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. dxc5 {This was Liem Quang Le's choice in his Lifetime repertoire on the London for White, and it scores better than the alternatives. Capturing now forces Black to recapture with the queen, but it does weaken White's perennial grip on the e5-square.} Qxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. e4 {This has been played a lot. White scores poorly but it's really just level.} (10. O-O {is not challenging at all, as Black effortlessly completes his development with} b6) 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 (11. Bxe4 {White is trying to be tricky as we cannot take.} Qc7 $1 {is good prophylactic move.} 12. Qe2 Nc5 {and Black is active.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxg3 {Opening the h-file is apparently a concession. White does not have real attacking chances though, and the pawn structure is still a bit compromised.} 13. hxg3 Nf6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rh7] White gains a tempo.} ({If} 14. Bc2 b6 {is very easy for Black.}) ({After} 14. Qe2 {I like} Rd8 {This has not been played before as far as I can tell. it makes perfect sense to prevent White from castling long though.}) 14... h6 ({This is stronger than} 14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 h6 16. O-O-O {when it's harder to develop and White has g4-g5 coming. Now White can castle either way.}) 15. O-O {This is safe, but not especially dangerous.} Bd7 $5 (15... Qc7 {preparing ...Bd7 is fine too.}) 16. Bxb7 Rab8 {We will win back the pawn one way or another.} 17. b4 ({If} 17. Be4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Rxb2 {.}) ({While} 17. Ba6 {is met with} Qb6 18. Bd3 Qxb2 {.}) 17... Qc7 18. Be4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxc3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gd7c6] The position is level.} *

