ve.} 12. Qe2 Nc5 {and Black is active.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxg3 {Opening the h-file is apparently a concession. White does not have real attacking chances though, and the pawn structure is still a bit compromised.} 13. hxg3 Nf6 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rh7] White gains a tempo.} ({If} 14. Bc2 b6 {is very easy for Black.}) ({After} 14. Qe2 {I like} Rd8 {This has not been played before as far as I can tell. it makes perfect sense to prevent White from castling long though.}) 14... h6 ({This is stronger than} 14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 h6 16. O-O-O {when it's harder to develop and White has g4-g5 coming. Now White can castle either way.}) 15. O-O-O Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8e6][%mdl 32768]} ({This avoids} 15... e5 16. Ng5 $5 {which is mildly annoying.}) 16. Rhe1 e5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc8g4] We already threaten to take on e4 - if White takes with the queen, he drops f2, while taking with the rook walks into a skewer.} 17. Z0 ({After} 17. Rd2 {Black can play} Rb8 {or 17...Qc7 to prepare to develop the bishop, or even or 17...a5!?}) *

