1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. dxc5 {This was Liem Quang Le's choice in his Lifetime repertoire on the London for White, and it scores better than the alternatives. Capturing now forces Black to recapture with the queen, but it does weaken White's perennial grip on the e5-square.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 {This was Le's choice, and it scores well. White may sharpen the fight by castling long. The sword cuts both ways though.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd7c5] This suggestion of Sethuraman looks like a great solution. I will try to expand on the lines a bit. Black attacks the b2-pawn and clears the way for ...Nc5.} ({Black can play} 10... e5 {although} 11. e4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 $1 {Requires care. White wants to avoids exchanges, as it's not so easy for Black to develop. I think Black is actually still ok after the rare} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qc6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Bxe5 {(Instead 15.O-O f6! is quite comfortable for Black).} Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Qa6 $1 17. Qe2 Qg6 $1 {but ultimately Black is just trying to hold an endgame, so we'll go for something else.}) 11. Bxd6 {This makes some sense, as Black has moved this queen a few times already.} Qxd6 {[%mdl 32768]} 12. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} e5 {Preventing e4-e5 and preparing ...Nc5. Again, White can choose where to castle.} (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf6 {looks reasonable too.}) 13. O-O {This is harmless.} Nc5 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gh5f4,Gc8g4] Black is already very comfortable.} 14. exd5 $2 {This doesn't work.} e4 {Black wins a piece.} 15. Nxe4 Ncxe4 16. Bxe4 Re8 17. Nd2 {And now the key point:} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Gf7f5,Gd6h2] threatening mate and ...f5.} *

