1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. dxc5 {This was Liem Quang Le's choice in his Lifetime repertoire on the London for White, and it scores better than the alternatives. Capturing now forces Black to recapture with the queen, but it does weaken White's perennial grip on the e5-square.} Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 {This was Le's choice, and it scores well. White may sharpen the fight by castling long. The sword cuts both ways though.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd7c5] This suggestion of Sethuraman looks like a great solution. I will try to expand on the lines a bit. Black attacks the b2-pawn and clears the way for ...Nc5.} ({Black can play} 10... e5 {although} 11. e4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 $1 {Requires care. White wants to avoids exchanges, as it's not so easy for Black to develop. I think Black is actually still ok after the rare} Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qc6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Bxe5 {(Instead 15.O-O f6! is quite comfortable for Black).} Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Qa6 $1 17. Qe2 Qg6 $1 {but ultimately Black is just trying to hold an endgame, so we'll go for something else.}) 11. O-O-O {This was Le's plan. To me, Black's king looks safer and it's easier for us to create play on the queenside. We already have an open c-file. The only problem is we are not fully developed.} Nc5 {[%mdl 32768] The most aggressive.} ({Black should avoid} 11... e5 $6 12. e4 {as we don't want a white knight coming to c4.}) ({The patient} 11... Re8 {looks ok though.}) 12. Bc2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gd1d6,Gg3d6] Now we have to watch out for Nc4 tricks.} Be7 $1 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gc8d7,Gd7b5,Gf8c8] A clever move. We may use this bishop in the play against White's king, while the g3-bishop cannot bother us. It even blocks the advance of White's g-pawn. Black's play looks much easier.} 13. Ne5 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3] We just want to shove the a-pawn.} 14. a4 {The engine's choice, but of course the pawn could easily be a weakness here. It's not easy to find ideas for White.} Qd8 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gd8e8] An idea from Sethuraman, which is immediately indicated by Stockfish. I'll show one interesting and critical line.} 15. e4 {[%cal Gd1d8] This looks logical - Black can create play against the white king, while White cannot do the same. So striking in the center makes sense before Black's attack gains momentum.} Qe8 $1 16. exd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc5a4] Now we are ready to take on a4.} 17. Nd3 {White hopes to use the open e-file to distract us.} Nxa4 $5 ({An interesting sacrifice. Both} 17... Ne6 $13 {and}) (17... Bd7 18. Nxc5 Bxc5 19. Qxe8 Rfxe8 {are possible as well.}) 18. Bxa4 Qxa4 19. Qxe7 Bf5 $13 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gf5b1,Ga4a1] This looks scary for the white king. The next move is forced.} 20. Nb1 Rfc8 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd5d4,Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Gc8c1,Gf5b1] Despite the extra piece, White is in for a tough defence.} *

