1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. Bd3 {This is White's most common choice. It does not strike me as being very dangerous though.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b6][%mdl 32768] Black can play ...e5 at will, or completely development with ...b6.} ({Black cannot play} 8... Nc6 $2 9. dxc5 $1 {stealing a pawn.}) 9. e4 $6 {This premature move has been played many times. White is behind in development and this leads to a worse pawn structure, with nothing to show for it.} cxd4 10. cxd4 (10. Nxd4 Bxg3 11. hxg3 Nc5 $17 {is also great for Black.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 (11. Rc1 Qb6 {does not really improve things.}) 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Nf6 {[%csl Rd4] Black is just better here as White does not have enough activity to compensate for the isolated d-pawn.} 13. Z0 ({A couple of possibilities:} 13. Bd3 Qa5+ 14. Ke2 Rd8 {was So-Carlsen, chess.com blitz 2017.}) (13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Bd3 b6 $1 {is also very good for Black.}) *

