1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {The London System. This use to be considered a solid, but somewhat lame way for White to play. Then some very strong players, Magnus Carlsen included, started to play it. Now it's not considered so harmless and it has a large body of theory. The danger for Black is not really running into some disaster (although it can happen!), but drifting into a prospectless position. This has happened to countless players when they did not take the opening seriously!} Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Bg3 ({This is our move order. White has a couple of minor tries like} 6. Bxd6 {and}) (6. dxc5 {, but there are four main ways White can play:}) (6. Nbd2 {will be met with} Bxf4 {with the idea ...b6, ...Ba6.}) (6. Ne5 {will be met with} Qc7 {, delaying ...O-O.}) (6. Bb5+ {will be met with} Nc6 {.}) (6. Bg3 {will be met with} O-O {and 7...Qc7.}) {Finally we come to the most popular move. White hopes to get into the main line with ...Nc6, but we will not oblige. While Black is a bit discouraged from exchanging bishops and opening the h-file for White, we do not have to worry about White shoving his kingside pawns up the board.} 6... O-O 7. Nbd2 ({Another move order is} 7. Bd3 Qc7 8. Nbd2) 7... Qc7 {This is very reliable system. In fact, it is so highly regarded that Sahaj and Srinath go to great measures to avoid it!} ({Again,} 7... Nc6 {is the classical system which we are avoiding because of} 8. Bd3 b6 9. e4 $1) 8. Bd3 {This is White's most common choice. It does not strike me as being very dangerous though.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b6] Black can play ...e5 at will, or completely development with ...b6.} ({Black cannot play} 8... Nc6 $2 9. dxc5 $1 {stealing a pawn.}) 9. O-O Bxg3 {[%mdl 32768] Now that White has castled, we double the pawns.} ({The immediate} 9... e5 {and}) (9... b6 {are both good too.}) 10. hxg3 e5 ({Again,} 10... b6 {is fine as well.}) 11. e4 {This is White's best chance for clean equality.} ({After} 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 {we have a similar position as we saw in the last few lines, but I welcome the change in White's kingside pawn structure as the g4-square may be useful for Black's pieces.}) 11... dxe4 {It's actually hard to mess up here! All captures lead to equality.} ({The center is meting away.} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 cxd4) ({or} 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 {and it's all equal.}) 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Nf6 14. Re1 ({After} 14. Bc2 {Black can continue exchanging pawns, or consider} e4 $5) 14... exd4 15. cxd4 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Rd8 {It's equal, but we can eat that bishop to create an imbalance.} 17. Z0 (17. Qb4 a5 18. Qb5 Nxe4 19. Rxe4 Be6 {was Rosner-Huschenbeth, Magdeburg 2019. Black eventually squeezed out a win.}) *

