1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd2 {A natural, but rather poor move. The engines already give Black an edge - and in more than one way! And it's only move four.} e6 ({Black can also play} 4... h6 5. Bh4 {and then} e6 {In most of the lines Black can throw in ...h6. We will avoid doing this on move four (just to be consistent), but it's rarely going to be a mistake.}) 5. e4 {White thinks it's a French.} (5. e3 {is rather passive. Both} c5 {and 5...a6!? are good. The latter avoids any Bb5+ stuff and prepares ...b5. The c3-knight is misplaced}) 5... dxe4 6. O-O-O {It still looks like some kind of French, but White is down a pawn. He can regain it, but it will cost some time.} h6 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. Bh4 a6 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7,Gc7c5] This is typical of some French lines with ...dxe4. Black wants to play on the queenside, especially as White's king resides there. This also reminds us of some QGD setups. How nice!} ({The engines also like} 7... c6 {with the idea ...Qa5.}) 8. Qe3 {[%cal Gc3e4]} b5 9. Nxe4 Bb7 10. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {White has his pawn back, but Black develops easily.} 11. Nf3 Be7 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gf6g4,Ge8g8,Gc7c5,Gd8a5] White has to watch for some ...Ng4 and ...Nd5 stuff. Black can just castle, and eventually look to play ... c5. It's an interesting position, and the engines give Black a slight edge.} *

