1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd2 {A natural, but rather poor move. The engines already give Black an edge - and in more than one way! And it's only move four.} e6 ({Black can also play} 4... h6 5. Bh4 {and then} e6 {In most of the lines Black can throw in ...h6. We will avoid doing this on move four (just to be consistent), but it's rarely going to be a mistake.}) 5. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is White's most common move, but it doesn't look very good. It just weakens the position too much, and Black is the one getting ther initiative.} c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] Black is already better.} 6. dxc5 (6. e3 {is very meek. Why is the pawn on f3?} Be7 $15 {with typical ideas like ...h6 and ..a6, ...b5.}) (6. e4 {transposes to the main line after} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bc5 8. Qd2) 6... Bxc5 ({Flinging in} 6... h6 {immediately is good too.}) 7. e4 h6 $1 {Well timed.} 8. Bxf6 {The only move to be concerned with. If this was problematic, it would be a good argument for playing ...h6 earlier, but Black is doing great. White is going to be suffering on the dark squares. A common theme whenever White plays f2-f3.} (8. Bh4 {walks into a typical tactic:} Nxe4) (8. Be3 dxe4 $17 {will leave White with a bad pawn structure.}) 8... Nxf6 9. exd5 {It looks like we will be taking on an isolated pawn. We may do so, but we do not have to take right away.} O-O $1 10. O-O-O ({After} 10. dxe6 $2 Qb6 $1 {Black's bishop is coming to e3. You'll hear it a lot in this chapter - White has problems on the dark squares.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 {[%csl Re3,Rf3][%cal Gd8b6,Gc8e6,Ga8c8] We still plan to play ...Qb6, threatening ...Be3. Then we can bring a rook to c8. White's pawn on f3 is ridiculous.} 12. Qxd5 $2 {White decides to have a pawn for his suffering.} Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ra2,Rc1][%cal Gc8e6,Ga8d8,Gf8d8,Gc5e3] At least he won't suffer for long. Black is just winning here.} *

