2e4] This is White's most common move, but it doesn't look very good. It just weakens the position too much, and Black is the one getting ther initiative.} c5 $1 {Black is already better.} 6. dxc5 (6. e3 {is very meek. Why is the pawn on f3?} Be7 $15 {with typical ideas like ...h6 and ..a6, ...b5.}) (6. e4 {transposes to the main line after} cxd4 7. Qxd4 Bc5 8. Qd2) 6... Bxc5 ({Flinging in} 6... h6 {immediately is good too.}) 7. e4 h6 $1 8. Bxf6 {The only move to be concerned with. If this was problematic, it would be a good argument for playing ...h6 earlier, but Black is doing great. White is going to be suffering on the dark squares. A common theme whenever White plays f2-f3.} (8. Bh4 {walks into a typical tactic:} Nxe4) (8. Be3 dxe4 $17 {leaves White with a bad pawn structure.}) 8... Nxf6 9. Bb5+ {This check is the reason some will play ...a6 early. Here it's no problem.} Bd7 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Even} 9... Kf8 {intending ...a6, is good.}) 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. exd5 {Again aiming to play against an isolated pawn.} O-O $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8] We have been denied the bishop pair, but our development is even faster now as our rooks are connected.} ({The immediate} 11... Rd8 {is also strong.}) 12. dxe6 $2 Qxe6+ 13. Qe2 {Blocking with a knight would be met the same way.} Be3 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8] What a bishop! White won't be able to castle anywhere. Black's rooks will just come to the center.} 14. Nd1 {Hoping to evict the intruder.} Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e3,Gd1e3] Another will take its place. White is totally busted.} 15. Z0 ({Note that} 15. c4 {can me met with} Nf4 $1 16. Qxe3 Nxg2+) *

