1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. e3 {This is solid, but passive.} e6 5. Qf3 $6 {Well, so much for solid. This was used by Nigel Short to beat a young upstart named Anish Giri.} c5 {Obvious enough.} 6. O-O-O ({Of course this was the point. Stockfish 16 is horrified and instead suggests} 6. Qd1 {:D}) 6... Be7 {Simple chess. It may be useful to be able to castle.} ({Anish played} 6... a6 {which is also decent, but White is developing quickly after all, so I want to do the same. Then} 7. Nge2 Qa5 8. Bxf6 Nxf6 9. g4 b5 10. g5 Nd7 11. Nf4 cxd4 12. Ncxd5 $1 {got very messy in Short-Giri, Amsterdam 2010. Black can improve here along the way, but so can White!}) 7. g4 ({This has been played a few times.} 7. Bb5 {has also been tried, but after} cxd4 8. exd4 a6 {with the half open c-file and ...b5 coming soon, Black is just better.}) 7... Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Gf6e4] Black's play is faster.} 8. Bxf6 {This is a common idea, especially in the Sicilian. White gifes up the bishop to prepare g4-g5 and a pawn storm. It's just very slow here.} Nxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({The most natural, but} 8... Bxf6 $5 {looks good too.}) 9. Kb1 ({This typical prophylactic move was played in a game. Note that} 9. g5 {should be met with} Nd7 $17 {when the g5-pawn is loose and Black is ready to play ...c4 and ...b5. Instead 9...Ne4 10.Nxe4 dxe4 11.Qxe4 Qxa2 is not so clear.}) 9... O-O $1 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb7b5] Black has various good moves, but this is the easiest.} ({The slow} 9... Bd7 {was played in Colovic-Perunovic, Kragujevac 2012. This sets up a little trick with} 10. g5 $2 Ne4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 $2 Bc6 $1 {but White can avoid this.}) ({The immediate} 9... c4 {is possible, as the complications arising after} 10. e4 b5 {favor Black. but there's no need.}) ({After} 9... O-O {we are ready to attack White's king.} 10. g5 Nd7 {with ...b5 coming, even as a pawn sacrifice. If we get nervous on the kingside, ...f5 is a good idea to fight for space.}) *

