1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. e3 {This is solid, but passive.} e6 5. Nf3 c5 {White has to play well to equalize.} ({Black can throw in} 5... h6 {but there's no hurry.}) ({Svidler likes} 5... a6 $5 {preparing ... c5. Later we'll see why, but it's not strictly necessary.}) 6. Bd3 {A natural square, but we can gain time. We don't really have to analyse} (6. dxc5 Bxc5 {as this just helps our development and we cna play normal moves.}) 6... c4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] This is often a good idea in these structures. Here it gains a tempo.} 7. Be2 Bb4 ({The most natural I think, but Benjamin Bok points out that} 7... b5 $5 {is quite good too.}) 8. O-O ({Worse is} 8. e4 $2 h6 $1 {when White will be forced to take on f6, which won't ease the pressure.}) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qa5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf6e4] Black is winning a pawn.} 10. Nd2 Qxc3 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b5] Black is very solid and won in Kotronias-Anand, Dubai 1986.} *

