{Black could also try the more complicated} 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 {This looks like a Burn French where Black is a tempo up. There are many possibilities. One is} Qa5+ $5 8. Bd2 Qb6 {with unclear play.}) 7. Bxf6 Nxf6 8. Bb5+ {This is what Svidler was avoiding - as White is equalizing, or at least close. We'll look a little further.} Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. exd5 ({Worse is} 10. e5 $6 Ne4) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] I would be happy enough with Black here. it's equal, but I like the bishop's potential.} *

