1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Nf3 {The most popular move overall, but one that has never been considered threatening. Even here White does not even score 45%.} e6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({We stick with the program. As usual, Black can throw in} 4... h6) (4... g6 {also makes sense, as White cannot double our pawns anymore, but that's a different story.}) 5. e4 ({Did we stumble into a French?} 5. e3 {simply brings us back to 4.e3.}) 5... h6 ({Instead} 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 {is indeed a Burn French.}) 6. Bxf6 {This is the safer choice - it doesn't lose a pawn! White has to count the little 'triumphs' in the Veresov.} Nxf6 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gf8b4,Gf8e7,Gd5e4] It's like a French, but we have the bishop pair already. If White plays quietly, we can take on e4 or increase the pressure with ...Bb4.} 7. e5 {Now it really looks like a French. White did get rid of his 'bad bishop', but often this bishop is important to help with the dark squares.} (7. Bd3 {can be met with} Bb4 {or simply 7...dxe4 8.Nxe4 Nxe4 9.Bxe4 c5=}) (7. Qe2 {is a weird move.} Be7 8. e5 $6 Nd7 9. O-O-O a6 10. h4 c5 11. g4 b5 $17 {Black is much faster and won a miniature in Yermolinsky-Kaidanov, New York 1993. Yermo is a great player, but here he experimented against the wrong opponent.}) 7... Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gc7c5] I think this is the simplest. Black has less space, so it's beneficial to trade another set of minor pieces.} ({Black can also play} 7... Nd7 {but the knight is not well placed here.} 8. Ne2 $1 {Everything else will be met with ...c5, when White looks worse.} c5 9. c3 Be7 {was fairly level in Vallejo Pons-Sargissian, Ohrid 2009. I feel like White got what he wanted here though - more space in an unclear position. I would prefer 9...cxd4 or 9...Nb8!? heading to c6 .}) 8. Nxe4 $2 {Quite a bad move, but there is one detail to consider.} ({White is also worse after} 8. Bd3 $2 Bb4 $1) ({Here} 8. Ne2 $2 {is not as good with Black's knight active on e4 . For example 8...c5 9.c3 Bd7 and Black has a great position.}) 8... dxe4 9. Ng1 {Ugly but there's not choice.} Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd7c6] This is great for Black, with ...c5 and ...Bc6 coming.} ({I prefer this to} 9... c5 {which allows} 10. Bb5+ {easing White's pain a bit.}) *

