1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Nf3 {The most popular move overall, but one that has never been considered threatening. Even here White does not even score 45%.} e6 ({We stick with the program. As usual, Black can throw in} 4... h6) (4... g6 {also makes sense, as White cannot double our pawns anymore, but that's a different story.}) 5. e4 ({Did we stumble into a French?} 5. e3 {simply brings us back to 4.e3.}) 5... h6 ({Instead} 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 {is indeed a Burn French.}) 6. Bh4 {This is in typical Veresov (reckless!) style.} g5 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({Winning a pawn.} 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 {is yet again a French.}) 7. Bg3 Nxe4 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({Freeing our f-pawn. Worse is} 7... dxe4 8. Nd2) 8. Nxe4 dxe4 {Now White has an unpleasant choice.} 9. Nd2 ({This looks passive and has been questioned, but it's probably just as good (or bad) as} 9. Ne5) 9... f5 $1 10. h4 {I don't think White has time for this.} f4 $1 11. Bh2 (11. Qh5+ Ke7 {transposes to 10.Qh5+.}) 11... Nf6 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gd8d4] White has no compensation for the pawn.} *

