back to 4.e3.}) 5... h6 ({Instead} 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 {is indeed a Burn French.}) 6. Bh4 {This is in typical Veresov (reckless!) style.} g5 $1 ({Winning a pawn.} 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 {is yet again a French.}) 7. Bg3 Nxe4 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({Freeing our f-pawn. Worse is} 7... dxe4 8. Nd2) 8. Nxe4 dxe4 {Now White has an unpleasant choice.} 9. Nd2 ({This looks passive and has been questioned, but it's probably just as good (or bad) as} 9. Ne5) 9... f5 $1 10. Qh5+ {This may look scary, and it is. For White.} Ke7 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gf5f4][%mdl 32768] An easy decision.} 11. h4 {Making a little room for the bishop.} ({The alternatives are even worse.} 11. f4 Nf6 {hits the queen and the d4-pawn.}) ({White can part with the bishop with} 11. Be5 {but after} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bg7 13. O-O-O Qe8 {Black will soon pick up the e5-pawn.}) 11... f4 ({This is better than} 11... Nf6 $6 12. Qe2) ({After} 11... f4 12. hxg5 {or 12.Bh2 Nf6 $17} fxg3 {White does not have anything resembling compensation. As is often the case, the lack of dark-square control is White's undoing. For example} 13. Nxe4 gxf2+ 14. Nxf2 Bg7 $17 {or 13.O-O-O Bg7 14.Nxe4 gxf2 $17}) *

