back to 4.e3.}) 5... h6 ({Instead} 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 {is indeed a Burn French.}) 6. Bh4 {This is in typical Veresov (reckless!) style.} g5 $1 ({Winning a pawn.} 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 {is yet again a French.}) 7. Bg3 Nxe4 {[%cal Gf7f5]} ({Freeing our f-pawn. Worse is} 7... dxe4 8. Nd2) 8. Nxe4 dxe4 {Now White has an unpleasant choice.} 9. Nd2 ({This looks passive and has been questioned, but it's probably just as good (or bad) as} 9. Ne5) 9... f5 $1 10. Bc4 {Relatively best.} Bd6 {[%mdl 32768] A new idea. This looks simpler than the alternatives.} ({I would avoid} 10... f4 {as} 11. Bxf4 $1 {is not so clear.} gxf4 12. Qh5+ Ke7 13. Nxe4 {One amusing line is} Nf6 $5 14. Nxf6 Kxf6 15. Qh4+ Kg7 16. Qxd8 Bb4+ 17. c3 Rxd8 18. cxb4 Rxd4) ({In practice Black has gone for} 10... Nf6 11. Be5 Bd6 12. Qe2 Bd7 {This is objectively pretty good, but White has some compensation as Black is rather cramped.} 13. O-O-O Qe7 14. f3 $1 exf3 15. Qxf3 O-O-O {when Black can meet} 16. Ba6 {with} c6 $1) 11. Bxd6 cxd6 12. Bxe6 Nf6 $15 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Ge8f8,Gf8g7]} 13. Z0 ({Black looks a bit better after} 13. Bxc8 Rxc8 {or}) (13. Bb3 Kf8 {as the center pawns are strong.}) *

