1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd3 {This move, which prepares queenside castling, has had some bouts of popularity. Like other sharper lines in the Veresov, the mighty engine is quick to cool down White's enthusiasm.} c5 {[%mdl 32768] We're four moves in and White must search for equality.} ({This is less common than} 4... h6 5. Bh4 c5 {but both moves score tremendously for Black.}) ({Our favorite} 4... e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. Nf3 {A change of heart? White decides to go solid.} c4 $1 {This move is almost always good in the Veresov when played with a gain of tempo. We gain space and begin action on the queenside, often gaining time against the awkward c3-knight.} ({More often Black has played} 5... cxd4 {which certainly looks logical, but} 6. Qxd4 {intending e4 favors White, despite the loss of tempo.}) 6. Qd2 b5 $146 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gf6e4,Gd8a5] Very ambitious.} ({In practice Black has gone for} 6... Qb6 {which is fine.}) ({I also like} 6... Ne4 $146 7. Nxe4 dxe4 {when White has to play} 8. Ng1) 7. Nxb5 {This is not very good, but we must prove the correctness of the concept.} (7. a3 Ne4 {is an improved version.} 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ng1 Bb7 $1 {with a great position.}) (7. Bf4 {hoping for} b4 8. Nb5 $1 {but even this is not clear after} Ne4 {followed by ...e5.}) 7... Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Gd8a5] 7...a6 $15 is simpler, maintaining the advantages of the position.} 8. Qc1 Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nxg5 $1 {Relatively best.} 10. Qxg5 ({If} 10. Nxg5 e5 $1 {looks scary for White. If} 11. e3 Bb4 12. Qd2 h6 $1 13. Nf3 Nf6 {and ...Ne4 is going to be killing.}) 10... e6 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Gf8b4,Gf8a3,Ga8b8] Simple. Black is down a pawn but everything else is great - ...Bb4 or ...Ba3 are coming, as well as ...Rb8. Have I mentioned that White often suffers on the dark squares in the Veresov?} *

