{remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. O-O-O {This has always been the main move. It's very risky.} c4 $1 {[%mdl 32768] We don't need a written invitation.} ({An untried idea is} 5... h6 $146 {with the idea} 6. Bh4 c4 $17 {with an even better version for Black, as} 7. Qg3 $2 {is not possible because of} g5) 6. Qf3 $2 {[%cal Gc3d5] If 6.Bxf6 c4! and 6.Bf4 cxd4 7.Qxd4 e6 8.e4 Bc5 looks good for Black too. White attacks the d5-pawn, but this is a poor square for the queen.} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga5a2,Ga5g5] The tactical idea is ...Ne4, while simply ...e6 and ...b5 is going to give Black an instant attack. Black already has a big advantage and White has yet to score from this position.} 7. Kb1 ({One game saw} 7. g4 {and now} Ne4 $1 {gives Black a winning position. For example} 8. Bd2 Nxd2 9. Rxd2 e6 {and ...b5 is coming.}) 7... e6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (7... Ne4 {is possible too, but this is simpler.}) 8. Bd2 ({If} 8. e4 $2 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 {and the g5-bishop is hanging, so White will remain down a pawn.}) ({And} 8. Bxf6 Nxf6 9. e4 b5 $1 10. exd5 Bb7 $1 {is horrendous for White.}) 8... Bb4 ({A natural move.} 8... Qa6 {is possible too.}) 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Rf3][%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5] Black's attack is automatic.} *

