1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd3 {This move, which prepares queenside castling, has had some bouts of popularity. Like other sharper lines in the Veresov, the mighty engine is quick to cool down White's enthusiasm.} c5 {We're four moves in and White must search for equality.} ({This is less common than} 4... h6 5. Bh4 c5 {but both moves score tremendously for Black.}) ({Our favorite} 4... e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. O-O-O {This has always been the main move. It's very risky.} c4 $1 {We don't need a written invitation.} ({An untried idea is} 5... h6 $146 {with the idea} 6. Bh4 c4 $17 {with an even better version for Black, as} 7. Qg3 $2 {is not possible because of} g5) 6. Qg3 {If 6.Bxf6 c4! and 6.Bf4 cxd4 7.Qxd4 e6 8.e4 Bc5 looks good for Black too.} Qa5 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. e4 ({Instead} 7. Kb1 b5 $1 8. e4 {transposes. The correspondence player Burmeister has played this many times with White, but without much success.}) 7... b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga5a2] We can already start attacking. Usually they say that a flank attack is well met with play in the center. here we are doing the opposite, but it works.} 8. Kb1 ({White is in trouble after both} 8. exd5 $2 b4) ({and} 8. e5 b4 9. exf6 gxf6 $17) 8... dxe4 (8... Nxe4 {is also possible.}) 9. Bxf6 exf6 $1 {This looks best.} ({After the natural} 9... Nxf6 {White has} 10. Qe5 a6 11. Bxc4 $1) ({Karjakin preferred} 9... gxf6 {Now} 10. Nxe4 Bb7 11. Nc5 Nxc5 12. dxc5 Rc8 13. Be2 $1 Qc7 {was the well-known game Nakamura-Karjakin, Baku 2014, which resulted in an important win for Black. However} 14. b4 $1 {would be very unclear. If} cxb3 15. Bxb5+ Bc6 16. Bxc6+ Qxc6 17. axb3 {and White is not worse.}) 10. Nxe4 Bb7 11. Be2 $5 ({A funny move. Instead} 11. d5 {was played in Burmeister-Lopes, ICCF email 2018. Now} f5 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13. Qxd6 O-O-O {! would have been very good for Black. The d5-pawn will probably not last very long.}) 11... Bxe4 12. Qe3 {The point.} f5 13. f3 {It looks like White is getting somewhere, but in correspondence play, it's easier to work it out.} Be7 $1 {White will regain the material, but we catch up in development.} 14. fxe4 O-O $1 15. e5 ({After} 15. exf5 {White is a pawn ahead, but Black will have the initiative. Both} Bd6 {and 15...Rfe8 look good.}) 15... Rab8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b6,Gb6a6] A cool move. Black wants to swing the rook to a6. White has a tough defense ahead in the game Burmeister-Sodomski, ICCF email 2018.} 16. Z0 ({Note that} 16. e6 $6 {does not really help White, as Black can just play} Nb6 $1 {heading to d5 or a4.}) *

