1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd3 {This move, which prepares queenside castling, has had some bouts of popularity. Like other sharper lines in the Veresov, the mighty engine is quick to cool down White's enthusiasm.} c5 {We're four moves in and White must search for equality.} ({This is less common than} 4... h6 5. Bh4 c5 {but both moves score tremendously for Black.}) ({Our favorite} 4... e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. Bxf6 {This sad move has been played several times.} Nxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 6. dxc5 e6 {[%cal Gf8c5] I have confidence that we will recover that pawn.} 7. O-O-O {I can't even consider this to be aggressive.} Bxc5 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge8g8]} 8. e4 {This at least sets a trap.} O-O $1 ({Easy. Black must avoid} 8... d4 $2 9. e5 $1 {and 10.Ne4}) 9. exd5 ({If} 9. e5 $2 Ng4 {wins for Black.}) 9... exd5 10. Nxd5 {We could trade everything and take on f2, but we can be more ambitious.} Be6 $17 {[%csl Gc5,Ge6,Rf2][%cal Ga8c8] Black's initiative easily outweighs White's extra pawn.} *

