{remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. Bxf6 {This sad move has been played several times.} Nxf6 6. dxc5 e6 {[%cal Gf8c5] I have confidence that we will recover that pawn.} 7. e4 {This has been played a few times, but it looks weird to me. White gives up his bishop, and moves his queen around to head into an endgame?} dxe4 {[%mdl 32768] Clearly best, but Black has not always played this way!} 8. Qxd8+ ({Probably the untried} 8. Nxe4 {is better, but} Qxd3 {will just leave Black with the bishop pair in the endgame.}) 8... Kxd8 9. O-O-O+ {More illusory aggression.} Kc7 {[%csl Rc5,Ge4][%cal Gf8c5] We have the bishop pair and White has to worry about ending up a pawn down.} ({The engine likes} 9... Ke7 {too, but of course it looks odd to block in our bishop.}) 10. f3 $1 {The best practical try.} ({Black will emerge a pawn up after} 10. Re1 Bxc5 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 Bxf2 {and there is no double attack with} 13. Rf4 $4 Be3+) ({If} 10. Nb5+ Kc6 11. Nd6 Bxd6 {and Black is better after either} 12. cxd6 Rd8 {or Rxd6+ Kxc5}) 10... Bxc5 ({Simplest. Instead} 10... exf3 11. Nb5+ Kc6 $6 12. Nxf3 {would be too dangerous.}) 11. Nxe4 ({White should trade knights. If} 11. fxe4 Ng4 $17) 11... Nxe4 ({A move like} 11... Be7 {would be good as well.}) 12. fxe4 Bd7 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Gd7][%cal Ga8d8,Gh8d8] Black has the bishop pair and a lasting advantage.} *

