e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. dxc5 {It looks strange to invite a knight to c5 to hit the queen, but White has a check on b5.} Nxc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5d3,Gd5d4] A simple, yet tremendous move. We hit the queen and also threaten ...d4, so White has little choice.} 6. Qb5+ Nfd7 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga7a6,Gh7h6,Gf7f6] A very rare move, but it is quickly indicated by the computer with the assessment  Indeed, White is in big trouble here. White's queen is rather short of squares, and other pieces are going to get kicked around as well.} 7. Nxd5 {White may at least have a pawn. This also gives his queen one more square on c4.} a6 $1 8. Qc4 ({If} 8. Qb4 f6 {followed by ...e6 will win material.}) 8... b5 $1 9. Qh4 (9. Qf4 Ne6 {gains more time.} 10. Qg3 Bb7 $17) 9... Bb7 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gh7h6,Gd8a5] It may not look like much is happening, but White would do well to survive for a few more moves. We'll look at a couple of lines.} 10. e4 {Perhaps the best try, but that's not saying much.} h6 {[%mdl 32768]} 11. Be3 {Other moves are similar.} e6 $5 {An easy route to a sizable advantage.} 12. Qxd8+ Rxd8 13. Nc3 b4 $17 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gb7e4] We will take on e4 next and have more space and a lead in development.} *

