1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. Qd3 {This move, which prepares queenside castling, has had some bouts of popularity. Like other sharper lines in the Veresov, the mighty engine is quick to cool down White's enthusiasm.} c5 $1 {We're four moves in and White must search for equality.} ({This is less common than} 4... h6 5. Bh4 c5 {but both moves score tremendously for Black.}) ({Our favorite} 4... e6 {remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. e4 {This is probably the best chance for White to equalize. That's not something we say often at move five.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] Forcing White to move the queen again. He can do so right away, or exchange on f6 first.} 6. Qxd4 e5 {And again. Surprisingly, White is ok here if he's careful.} 7. Qa4 $6 {This looks 'active' and it's the only move seen in practice, but White will be worse now.} d4 {Gaining space.} 8. Nd5 Be7 ({Simple, but the untried} 8... Bd6 $5 {looks good too.}) 9. Bxf6 ({After} 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 $15 {Black will just castle and play ...h6 and ...Nc5.}) 9... Bxf6 10. Bb5 O-O $1 {[%cal Gd7c5] We threatened ...Nc5, so White has to go for this. We don't have to worry about doubled pawns.} (10... a6 {is possible too, but it doesn't even threaten anything yet.}) 11. Bxd7 Bxd7 {White has to move the queen again!} 12. Nxf6+ {if White doesn't take now, we'll just play ...Bc6 or ...Rc8.} gxf6 13. Qa3 {This at least stops a disruptive ...Qa5+} Rc8 {[%csl Rg1,Rh1][%cal Gc8c2,Gf6f5,Gd7c6] Black has more space and a lead in development. Stockfish 16 already considers White to be busted - it's about -2.5!} *

