{remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. e4 cxd4 {Forcing White to move the queen again. He can do so right away, or exchange on f6 first. This will force White to move the queen again.} 6. Qxd4 e5 {And again. Surprisingly, White is ok here if he's careful.} 7. Qd2 $1 {This untried move may equalize!} Bb4 $5 {[%cal Gd5d4][%mdl 32768] The sharpest.} ({Black is certainly fine after} 7... d4 8. Nd5 Be7 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 {but at least White has avoided wasting more time with the queen.}) 8. exd5 ({Best. White is in trouble after both} 8. a3 $2 Qa5 $17) ({and} 8. Bxf6 $6 Nxf6 9. Bb5+ Kf8 $1 10. exd5 Qb6 $1) 8... O-O {[%cal Gh7h6,Gd8a5] Black just threatens to increase the pressure with ...Qa5, threatening ...Ne4. Even ...h6 is good.} 9. a3 {White has to deal with the pin.} Qa5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a1,Gf6e4]} ({Keeping the tension. We could also win back the pawn immediately with} 9... Bxc3 10. Qxc3 Nb6) 10. Nge2 {White gives the c3-knight more protection.} Ne4 ({We could also play} 10... Nxd5 {but it's not as strong as it looks. After} 11. Rd1 $1 Bxc3 12. Nxc3 Nxc3 {White has the clever} 13. Be7 $1 Re8 14. Bb4 $1 {although it's still pretty level.}) 11. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1a1] Now the rook is protected, so we have to start capturing.} Bxc3+ 12. Nxc3 Nxc3 13. Qd2 $1 ({Best.} 13. Bd2 {is too ambitious.} Qxd5 14. Bxc3 Nb6 $15 {when it's hard for White to develop because of the pressure on g2 .}) 13... Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5] White has the bishop pair, but we are very active and have better control of the center. I think Black's game is easier.} 14. Z0 ({Note that} 14. Be7 $6 {does not work so well here. After} Re8 15. Bb4 Qxd5 16. Bxc3 Bf5 {Black's development lead becomes alarming.}) *

