{remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. e4 cxd4 {Forcing White to move the queen again. He can do so right away, or exchange on f6 first.} 6. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop.} Nxf6 ({We can fling in} 6... dxe4 7. Qxd4 Nxf6 {transposing.}) 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd5 {is not very good. We have the bishop pair for nothing. Both} e5 {and 7...Nxd5 8.Qb5+ Bd7 9.Qxd5 Bc6 are good for Black.}) 7... dxe4 8. Bb5+ Bd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 9. O-O-O $6 {As is often the case, White's aggressive looking play falls flat.} Bxb5 10. Nxb5 ({We are simply a pawn up after} 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. Rxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nxb5 e6 $17 {if} 13. Nxa7 Bc5) 10... Qxd4 11. Rxd4 {[%cal Gb5c7] A little mate threat.} e5 $1 ({This is even better than} 11... Rc8 12. Nxa7 e5 {as played in one game.}) 12. Rc4 {Alternatives are no better:} (12. Nc7+ $6 Ke7 13. Nxa8 exd4 {is totally winning for Black.}) (12. Ra4 O-O-O {!} 13. Nxa7+ Kb8 {and ... Bc5 is coming.}) 12... Rd8 13. Nxa7 {Or else we're up a pawn for nothing.} g6 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rc1,Rc4,Rg1,Rh1][%cal Gf8h6,Ge8g8,Gf6g4] We threaten ...Bh6+, mating. White can stop this, but we'll be doing very well with our strong pawns. White's pieces on the queenside are not well placed. The sortie ...Ng4 could be very disruptive too.} *

