{remains quite playable here. Then} 5. e4 {is some kind of French with White's queen on d3.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 Be7 {should be a very satisfactory Burn French.}) 5. e4 cxd4 {Forcing White to move the queen again. He can do so right away, or exchange on f6 first.} 6. Bxf6 {White gives up the bishop.} Nxf6 ({We can fling in} 6... dxe4 7. Qxd4 Nxf6 {transposing.}) 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd5 {is not very good. We have the bishop pair for nothing. Both} e5 {and 7...Nxd5 8.Qb5+ Bd7 9.Qxd5 Bc6 are good for Black.}) 7... dxe4 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ {Safest.} Qxd7 {[%mdl 32768]} 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 (10... Nxd7 {is ok too, but the endgame is pleasant.}) 11. O-O-O+ Kc6 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ge7e5,Gf8d6,Gf8c5] Black is fine here. Our king is well placed for the endgame.} 12. Z0 ({White can win back the pawn with} 12. Re1 e5 13. Nxe4 {and now both} Nd5 {and 13...Nxe4 14.Rxe4 Bd6 are level, but there is still scope to outplay your opponent.}) *

