1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov. This was never considered to be too dangerous - a little tricky perhaps - but not objectively good. This holds true today, and Black scores very well. Today's engines confirm that Black is doing great. Simply put, the c3-knight is poorly placed as White cannot attack or defend in the center with c4 or c3. So White often plays for e2-e4, but it's not easy to achieve without the weakening move f2-f3.} ({Although it took a long time, nowadays it's considered that Jobava's} 3. Bf4 {is much more challenging. In this case White's c3-knight serves a purpose - to go to b5, hitting the c7-pawn.}) 3... Nbd7 {The main line. We avoid doubled pawns. We will typically play ...e6 and ...c5, often with ...a6 or ... h6 thrown in somewhere. Black has many playable moves.} ({Here} 3... e6 {may look consistent with our repertoire, but after} 4. e4 {we are suddenly in a Classical French! - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5. If this is part of your repertoire, go right ahead and play this way. Black has avoided the popular Steinitz Variation - 1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5.}) ({Shankland's suggestion} 3... Bf5 {and}) (3... c6 {are both very solid.}) ({Jones gives the King's Indian style} 3... g6) ({Finally there is the direct} 3... c5 {This, along with our line, are Black's best scoring setups. White has quite a few moves here. They range from bad to harmless. So we do not have much to worry about, and we certainly don't have to know everything in order to confidently face an uncommon and objectively weak line. There are some lines though where we should definitely know a few things.}) 4. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White intends to play e4. Of course this move takes away a square from White's g1-knight, and weakens the dark squares.} ({This is the traditional main line, but when it was found to be lacking, White tried to spice things up with another ugly move,} 4. Qd3 {, or else put on the brakes with the more solid}) (4. e3 {or}) (4. Nf3) 4... c6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8b6,Gd7a5,Ge7e5][%mdl 32768] This is very solid, but not without ambition. We will see that we are well prepared for White's central advance. We also solidify the d5-pawn, so we can strike with ...e5 if White sits around.} ({Black can also strike immediately with the typical} 4... c5 {or}) (4... h6 5. Bh4 {and then} c5) 5. e4 {I mean, this is the point, right?} ({After the rare} 5. Qd3 e5 {is great for Black.}) ({Sometimes White hesitates with} 5. Qd2 {when} h6 {when is a good answer. After both} 6. Bh4 e5 {and Bf4 Nh5! White is worse.}) 5... dxe4 6. fxe4 e5 $1 {Thematically striking on the dark squares. This position has been seen many times, with Black scoring a huge 65%. Today's engines confirm White's problems.} 7. Nf3 {This is not played often, but it's probably the lesser evil.} h6 $1 ({Good timing. We want the bishop to commit. After digging a bit, I believe White can equalize after} 7... exd4 8. Qxd4) 8. Bh4 ({The most natural.} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 $17 {is dark square heaven for Black.}) ({Instead} 8. Be3 {is not so terrible, but Black has easy play after} Bb4 {If} 9. dxe5 Ng4) 8... Qa5 $5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gf8b4] Breaking the pin and making threats.} ({I prefer this to often recommended} 8... Qb6 {After} 9. Qd2 exd4 10. Nxd4 Bb4 {and here Cuenca only gives} 11. O-O-O {but 11.a3!? and 11.Nf5!? look more dangerous, and quite unclear Probably the bold 10...Qxb2 is stronger, but of course it's rather messy. 11.Rb1 Qa3 and the engines do prefer Black, but not by much.}) 9. Qd2 {A natural move, but it doesn't slow us down.} Bb4 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 10. Bd3 O-O $1 11. Bxf6 ({What else?} 11. dxe5 Ng4 $15 {is easy for Black. (But now it looks like we overlooked something.)}) 11... Nxf6 $1 12. Nxe5 (12. dxe5 {is even worse.} Ng4 $17) 12... Rd8 $1 {White's center is under a lot of pressure. Dark squares!} 13. Nc4 ({This gains time at least. After the safe-looking} 13. Nf3 {Black has} c5 $1 {which is actually just winning after.} 14. dxc5 Nxe4 {or d5 c4!}) 13... Qh5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Gc6c5,Gb7b5] White remains under a lot of pressure.} 14. Z0 ({One possibility is} 14. e5 b5 $1 15. Ne3 c5 $1 {when White has to play accurately to survive.}) *

