][%cal Gd8b6,Gd7a5,Ge7e5] This is very solid, but not without ambition. We will see that we are well prepared for White's central advance. We also solidify the d5-pawn, so we can strike with ...e5 if White sits around.} ({Black can also strike immediately with the typical} 4... c5 {or}) (4... h6 5. Bh4 {and then} c5) 5. e4 {I mean, this is the point, right?} ({After the rare} 5. Qd3 e5 {is great for Black.}) ({Sometimes White hesitates with} 5. Qd2 {when} h6 {when is a good answer. After both} 6. Bh4 e5 {and Bf4 Nh5! White is worse.}) 5... dxe4 6. fxe4 e5 $1 {Thematically striking on the dark squares. This position has been seen many times, with Black scoring a huge 65%. Today's engines confirm White's problems.} 7. dxe5 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ga5e1,Ga5g5,Gf6e4][%mdl 32768] Threatening ...Nxe4 while preparing ...Nxe5 as well as ...Bb4. The loose bishop on g5 is the tactical justification. This position has been seen dozens of times. Perhaps there was a debate at some point, but today we know that Black is already better.} ({Black is not really worse after} 7... Nxe5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {, highlighting the benign nature of White's concept.}) 8. Qd2 ({Black simply has a better pawn structure after} 8. Bd2 $6 Nxe5) 8... Nxe5 $1 {A common theme in these lines is that we do not have to worry much about a damaged pawn structure. White's dark square weaknesses are much more important in the position.} 9. Bxf6 {The only consistent move.} ({After} 9. Nf3 Be6 {or}) (9. O-O-O Be6 {Black has the better structure and will continue with ...Bb4 or ...Be7 and ...O-O.}) 9... gxf6 $17 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8d8,Gh8g8,Gf8c5,Gh7h5,Gf8h6,Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Black is much better here. The king is fine in the center and there are plenty of ideas to develop an initiative. If White castles long, even ...b5-b4 is a serious idea.} *

