1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 {[%mdl 32768]} ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. e3 ({White should certainly go for the disruptive} 4. Nb5 {now to justify White's second and third moves.}) {This looks highly questionable.} 4... Bb4 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5,Gf6e4] This puts a lot of pressure on White. Black is already fighting for an advantage here and his score is close to 60%! It looks a bit like a Winawer French, but White does not have the space advantage or attacking chances that he'll find there.} 5. Nge2 ({Now the only sensible moves are} 5. Nge2 {to avoid doubled pawns, and}) (5. Bd3 {to get developed.}) ({This takes care of the c3-knight but it hinders White's development.} 5. a3 $6 {is rather compliant. After} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 {Black is better, with easy plans like ...Qa5 and ...Ne4, or ...b6 and ...Ba6.}) 5... O-O 6. a3 Be7 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc7c5] The time spent with the bishop achieved a goal - no Nb5 and White's development is congested.} (6... Bd6 {is fine too, but I'd rather avoid giving White a square on f4 for his e2-knight.}) 7. Ng1 {[%cal Gg1f3] I will give this as the main line, as it's been played by Carlsen, Sevian, and Niemann in fast time controls. And it's funny.} (7. Nb5 $6 {is pointless now, as Black can play} Ne8 $1 {with ... a6 and ...c5 coming.}) ({Other knight moves are met the same way-} 7. Ng3 c5 {or}) (7. Nc1 c5 {In both cases Black is very comfortable.}) 7... c5 8. Nf3 {This square does look better than g3 and c1, but White took three moves to get here.} Nc6 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gd8b6,Gf6h5] This is the simplest. With a slight development lead, Black looks at least equal to me.} (8... Nh5 {and}) (8... Ne4 {are sharper ideas.}) *

