1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. e3 ({White should certainly go for the disruptive} 4. Nb5 {now to justify White's second and third moves.}) {This looks highly questionable.} 4... Bb4 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5,Gf6e4] This puts a lot of pressure on White. Black is already fighting for an advantage here and his score is close to 60%! It looks a bit like a Winawer French, but White does not have the space advantage or attacking chances that he'll find there.} 5. Bd3 ({Now the only sensible moves are} 5. Nge2 {to avoid doubled pawns, and}) (5. Bd3 {to get developed.}) 5... c5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] Just like in the French.} 6. dxc5 ({After} 6. a3 $2 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5 $17 {White will find it rather difficult to avoid losing a pawn.}) 6... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} ({This is the most flexible move, but} 6... O-O {is good too.}) 7. Nf3 {This scores terribly, but it's not so bad. Black still has a pleasant choice.} Bxc3+ (7... Nxc5 {and}) (7... O-O {are possible as well, and they could all transpose.}) 8. bxc3 Nxc5 9. O-O O-O {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Gf6e4,Gb7b6] This looks very comfortable. Black wants to play ...b6 and ...Bb7, or he can bring a knight to e4 to pressure the c3-pawn.} 10. Bg5 {This looks like the best try, as the pin is a bit annoying.} Nce4 $5 ({The most direct. Black can also play} 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5) ({or simply} 10... b6) 11. Bxe4 ({After} 11. Bh4 Qc7 $1 {the knights cover each other nicely.}) 11... dxe4 12. Nd2 e5 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] We want to play ...Bf5 next, so White should take the pawn.} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxe4 Qc6 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Gc8e6] This was Zahour-Bultman, ICCF email 2013. Black has good compensation because of White's weak pawns.} (14... Qg6 {with the idea ...Bf5 looks good to.}) *

