1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. e3 ({White should certainly go for the disruptive} 4. Nb5 {now to justify White's second and third moves.}) {This looks highly questionable.} 4... Bb4 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5,Gf6e4] This puts a lot of pressure on White. Black is already fighting for an advantage here and his score is close to 60%! It looks a bit like a Winawer French, but White does not have the space advantage or attacking chances that he'll find there.} 5. Bd3 ({Now the only sensible moves are} 5. Nge2 {to avoid doubled pawns, and}) (5. Bd3 {to get developed.}) 5... c5 $1 {Just like in the French.} 6. dxc5 ({After} 6. a3 $2 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5 $17 {White will find it rather difficult to avoid losing a pawn.}) 6... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} ({This is the most flexible move, but} 6... O-O {is good too.}) 7. Nge2 {This avoids doubled pawns.} a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4][%mdl 32768] A clever move which threatens to play ...e5-e4, winning a piece. White's bishop will not be able to go to b5 now.} 8. O-O {This is untried. Probably because it loses a piece! It's still one of the engine's top choices though, which really just shows that White's position is not very good.} Bxc5 {I'll give the simple line which ensures Black of a good position. Shankland gave this as an alternate line.} ({Black can also grab the piece with} 8... e5 9. Bg5 e4 10. Nxd5 exd3 11. Qxd3 Bxc5 12. Rfd1 Be7 {Shankland gets this far and believes Black should win. Perhaps, but there are certainly practical problems. After} 13. Nxe7 Qxe7 14. Bf4 $1 {Black cannot castle because of Bd6. Stockfish 16 thinks it's close to equal.}) 9. e4 {This looks the most logical, but White is pushed back.} d4 10. Nb1 e5 11. Bc1 {Maybe the best move. Obviously rather sad.} (11. Bd2 {takes a square away from the b1-knight.}) (11. Bg3 Nh5 $15 {nabs the bishop - a common idea.}) (11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 $2 {runs into} g5 $1 13. Bg3 h5 $17 {grabbing a lot of space and of course White's king is not comfortable.}) 11... O-O $15 {[%csl Rb1,Rc1][%cal Gf8e8,Gd7f8] Black has more space despite our many pawn moves, White is somehow behind in development. Let's not forget that he developed the queenside minor pieces on moves 2 and 3, and now they are back home.} *

