1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. e3 ({White should certainly go for the disruptive} 4. Nb5 {now to justify White's second and third moves.}) {This looks highly questionable.} 4... Bb4 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5,Gf6e4] This puts a lot of pressure on White. Black is already fighting for an advantage here and his score is close to 60%! It looks a bit like a Winawer French, but White does not have the space advantage or attacking chances that he'll find there.} 5. Bd3 ({Now the only sensible moves are} 5. Nge2 {to avoid doubled pawns, and}) (5. Bd3 {to get developed.}) 5... c5 $1 {Just like in the French.} 6. dxc5 ({After} 6. a3 $2 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qa5 $17 {White will find it rather difficult to avoid losing a pawn.}) 6... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} ({This is the most flexible move, but} 6... O-O {is good too.}) 7. Nge2 {This avoids doubled pawns.} a6 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4] A clever move which threatens to play ...e5-e4, winning a piece. White's bishop will not be able to go to b5 now.} 8. Bg3 {This prophylactic move is relatively best.} Bxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} (8... e5 $2 {is bad because of} 9. Bf5 {just like what could have occurred in my game with Canty.}) (8... Nh5 {is possible, but I'd rather wait for White to castle.}) 9. O-O $6 ({Instead} 9. a3 {transposes to 8.a3.}) ({The modest} 9. h3 {may be best, but after} O-O {Black is at least equal, with ...b6 or ...b5 coming.}) 9... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g3,Ge8g8] Now that White won't have the h-file for his rook, Black happily grabs the bishop pair.} *

