1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. Nb5 {This is much more critical as it forces Black to misplace his knight.} Na6 {[%csl Ra6]} 5. e3 Be7 {I just want to get on with development. We can kick White's knight later.} ({The immediate} 5... c6 {is more popular.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Ga6b4,Gb4c6,Ga6b8,Gb8c6] Black's main plan is to kick the knight with ...c6, and then play ...c5. The a6-knight will often reroute to c6, via b4 or b8.} 7. Ne5 {This looks premature after Black's next move.} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gf7f6][%mdl 32768]} ({We can do this because we lead in development. White's idea was} 7... c6 8. Nc3 c5 9. Bxa6 bxa6 10. Nc6 {Black has actually scored well here, but White is better after} Qe8 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Qd4 $1) 8. f3 ({After} 8. Bd3 $6 f6 $1 9. Nf3 c6 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 c5 {...Qa5 and ...c4 are coming. Black is better.}) 8... Nf6 $5 {[%cal Gf6h5] Now ...Nh5 is an idea.} (8... Nd6 {is possible too.}) 9. g4 (9. Be2 Nh5 $1 {and we'll get the bishop and evict White's knight with ...f6.}) 9... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gf7f6,Gc7c6] ...f6 is coming, and so is ...c5. White's position looks shaky.} *

