1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. Nb5 {This is much more critical as it forces Black to misplace his knight.} Na6 {[%csl Ra6]} 5. e3 Be7 {I just want to get on with development. We can kick White's knight later.} ({The immediate} 5... c6 {is more popular.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Ga6b4,Gb4c6,Ga6b8,Gb8c6] Black's main plan is to kick the knight with ...c6, and then play ...c5. The a6-knight will often reroute to c6, via b4 or b8.} 7. h4 $5 {A thoroughly modern idea. In the London we avoided some similar stuff.} c6 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Nc3 c5 {White's center is not as stable as it is in the proper London with a pawn on c3 and knight on d2.} 9. Ne5 {This was played by Van Foreest, who is a great theoretician, but I don't trust it. It was a rapid game, and he probably wanted to get his opponent, also a tremendous theoretician, on his own.} Nb4 10. h5 h6 11. g4 Nd7 $1 {A standard idea, challenging White's knight.} ({Giri played} 11... Nh7 {here. Black was very solid in Van Foreest-Giri, Oslo 2022, but we can be more ambitious.}) ({Note that} 11... Ne4 {, a move often worth considering, does not work out well here.} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. dxc5 $1 Bxc5 14. Bg2 {when the e4-pawn is a problem. If} Qxd1+ $6 15. Rxd1 Nxc2+ 16. Ke2 {when the e4-pawn is still weak, and Black's minor pieces on the c-file also cause problems.}) ({After} 11... Nd7 $1 {it's rather telling that the engines suggest the humble retreat} 12. Nf3 {Now the simplest is} Nc6 {with the idea ...a6, ...b5. A sharper try is 12...cxd4 13.exd4 f5 $132}) *

