1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This Jobava version is more challenging than the older Veresov with 3.Bg5.} e6 ({A classical response which fits well with our repertoire. Other lines include the direct} 3... c5 {, the prophylactic}) (3... a6 {, and the fianchetto .}) 4. Nb5 {This is much more critical as it forces Black to misplace his knight.} Na6 {[%csl Ra6]} 5. e3 Be7 {I just want to get on with development. We can kick White's knight later.} ({The immediate} 5... c6 {is more popular.}) 6. Nf3 O-O {[%cal Gc7c6,Gc6c5,Ga6b4,Gb4c6,Ga6b8,Gb8c6] Black's main plan is to kick the knight with ...c6, and then play ...c5. The a6-knight will often reroute to c6, via b4 or b8.} 7. h4 $5 {A thoroughly modern idea. In the London we avoided some similar stuff.} c6 8. Nc3 c5 {White's center is not as stable as it is in the proper London with a pawn on c3 and knight on d2.} 9. h5 {Consistent.} h6 {[%mdl 32768] I'd rather the pawn not advance to h6.} 10. g4 $5 ({Instead} 10. Ne5 Nb4 {transposes back to 9.Ne5.}) 10... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gc5d4,Ge7b4,Gd8a5] An active move.} ({We want to avoid} 10... Nb4 11. g5 {opening lines.}) ({Grabbing the pawn with} 10... Nxg4 {is possible, when} 11. Rg1 {forces} f5 {Playable, but White has compensation.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rg4g5] A simple move really. White can't play g4-g5, so we just want to develop the bishop and cover the e4-pawn. We can reroute the a6-knight later.} ({Instead} 12... Nb4 13. c3 Nd5 14. Bg3 {was played in Matlakov-Azarov, Tornelo (internet rapid) 2021. The e4-pawn is vulnerable here.}) 13. Nc6 {A tempting move, perhaps but I am happy to see it.} Qe8 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gf8d8,Ga8d8,Gf7f6] The computer says equal, but I am happy with Black here. He has a safe king and easy play.} *

