1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {[%mdl 32768]} 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bh4 ({This is not as common as} 4. Bf4 {, but it's still been played a lot. It's highly questionable though, as the bishop is totally out of touch with the queenside, and it's often vulnerable here. It's already unlikely that White can even equalize.}) 4... c5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd8b6]} ({An additional problem with White's 4th move is that Black has decent are alternatives, such as} 4... h5 {(Shankland) and}) (4... Qd6 {(Gledura). We will stick to the classical line.}) 5. dxc5 {Giving up the center cannot be dangerous and Black equalizes easily. White avoids disaster though, which easily befalls him in the other lines.} Nc6 6. e3 g6 {This may be the only position in the entire course where we play ...g6 to fianchetto the king's bishop in the opening!} 7. Nbd2 Nxc5 8. Be2 (8. c3 Bg7 9. Be2 {is just a transposition.}) (8. Nb3 {can be met with} Ne4 {or 8...Bg7 9.Nxc5 Qa5+ 10.c3 Qxc5}) 8... Bg7 9. c3 O-O 10. O-O {The position is equal, but Black at least has more space.} a5 {[%cal Rb2b4,Ga5a4,Gh7h6,Gg6g5] A good move, preventing b4, while ...a4 is a possibility. White is very solid but it's not clear what he should be doing. One plan for Black would be to play ...h6 and ...g5, intending ...e5 and ...Be6.} *

