1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bh4 ({This is not as common as} 4. Bf4 {, but it's still been played a lot. It's highly questionable though, as the bishop is totally out of touch with the queenside, and it's often vulnerable here. It's already unlikely that White can even equalize.}) 4... c5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd8b6]} ({An additional problem with White's 4th move is that Black has decent are alternatives, such as} 4... h5 {(Shankland) and}) (4... Qd6 {(Gledura). We will stick to the classical line.}) 5. e3 Qb6 $1 {White cannot even muster a 30% score from this position in practice, but it's probably about equal with best play.} 6. Qc1 $2 {This is white's most common move in practice, but it's just bad.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} 7. exd4 g5 $1 {[%cal Gf8h6] These days this idea is well known, and it can be found all over Chessable.} ({The simple} 7... Nc6 $17 {is also very good.} 8. c3 {when Black can choose} Bf5 $17 {, 8...f6 $17 , 8...h5 $17}) 8. Nxg5 {This is poor, but White does not have good moves. Here we have to know the following tactical sequence.} (8. Bg3 {Declining does not help.} Bh6 $1 9. Ne5 Qxd4 $17) (8. Bxg5 {is met with some simple tactics.} Nxg5 9. Nxg5 Bh6 10. f4 Qxd4 $17) 8... Qh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6c1,Gh6h4,Gf7f6]} 9. Qf4 f6 10. Nh3 {It looks like White has held everything together.} Bxh3 $1 11. Qxh6 Bxh6 12. gxh3 {Now comes the sting.} Bc1 {[%csl Rb2] Black wins serious material.} *

