1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bh4 ({This is not as common as} 4. Bf4 {, but it's still been played a lot. It's highly questionable though, as the bishop is totally out of touch with the queenside, and it's often vulnerable here. It's already unlikely that White can even equalize.}) 4... c5 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd8b6]} ({An additional problem with White's 4th move is that Black has decent are alternatives, such as} 4... h5 {(Shankland) and}) (4... Qd6 {(Gledura). We will stick to the classical line.}) 5. e3 Qb6 $1 {White cannot even muster a 30% score from this position in practice, but it's probably about equal with best play.} 6. Nc3 {This is essentially the only move.} Qa5 {[%csl Rc3] The most ambitious.} ({White has an easier time after} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qa5 {if 7...Qb2 8.Kd2! is not so clear.} 8. Qd2) 7. Be2 {The safest.} Nxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} 8. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] A typical trick to avoid losing a pawn.} Nc6 (8... Bf5 {is possible too, but this is safer.}) 9. bxc3 ({The endgame arising after} 9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 e6 {looks equal.}) 9... e6 10. O-O c4 $5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gf8e7,Gc8d7] This was Grischuk-Hakobyan, chess.com rapid 2023. Black is super solid and can prepare to play on the queenside.} *

