1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. c3 {This is solid, but White is still struggling to reach equality.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} ({More accurate than} 5... Qb6 6. Qb3 {or}) (5... Nc6 6. e3) 6. cxd4 (6. Bxb8 {is a sad move to make.} Rxb8 7. Qxd4 e6 $1 {with the idea} 8. Qxa7 $2 Bd7) 6... Qb6 $1 ({Better than} 6... Nc6 7. Nc3) 7. Qb3 {This is relatively safe, but it gives Black a easy edge with no complications.} Qxb3 8. axb3 Nc6 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4]} 9. e3 e6 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gc6b4] We do not mind keeping the bishop inside the pawn chain, as White will have to exchange bishops in any case.} ({White now has two things to worry about, so this essentially gains a tempo over} 9... Nb4 10. Bb5+) 10. Bd3 ({This loses time, but White does not have much choice, as} 10. Nc3 $6 Bb4) ({and} 10. Bb5 $6 Bb4+ 11. Ke2 Bd7 {also favor Black.}) 10... Nb4 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 $15 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black has a slight edge with his better pawn structure.} *

