1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. c3 {This is solid, but White is still struggling to reach equality.} cxd4 ({More accurate than} 5... Qb6 6. Qb3 {or}) (5... Nc6 6. e3) 6. cxd4 (6. Bxb8 {is a sad move to make.} Rxb8 7. Qxd4 e6 $1 {with the idea} 8. Qxa7 $2 Bd7) 6... Qb6 $1 ({Better than} 6... Nc6 7. Nc3) 7. Qc1 {This demands more knowledge from Black.} Nc6 8. Nc3 Bf5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] A great move, maintaining the initiative. Black played this way in a couple of old correspondence games.} 9. Nxd5 ({If White declines with} 9. e3 e6 {he is back to 8.e3}) 9... Qa5+ 10. Nc3 e5 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4] The point of Black's play.} 11. Bd2 {White declines the second pawn.} Nxd2 12. Qxd2 O-O-O $5 {The sharpest try.} (12... exd4 {is also fine. After} 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Rd8 15. Qa4+ Qxa4 16. Nxa4 Rc8 $13 {Black has good compensation for the pawn. If} 17. Nc3 Ba3 $1) 13. e3 exd4 14. Nxd4 ({Worse is} 14. exd4 Bc5 $1) 14... Nxd4 15. exd4 Bc5 $1 16. d5 Rhe8+ {Every move gains time.} 17. Be2 Bg4 $1 18. O-O-O {No choice. Michael Prusikin analyzed this forcing sequence in his book, Countering the Queen's Gambit.} ({If} 18. f3 Bd7 {and then ...Be3 is coming.}) 18... Bxe2 19. Nxe2 Qxd2+ ({Simpler than} 19... Qxa2 20. Nc3) 20. Rxd2 Bxf2 $15 {[%csl Bf2] With a strong bishop and a better pawn structure, Black is a little better in the endgame.} *

