1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. c3 {This is solid, but White is still struggling to reach equality.} cxd4 ({More accurate than} 5... Qb6 6. Qb3 {or}) (5... Nc6 6. e3) 6. cxd4 (6. Bxb8 {is a sad move to make.} Rxb8 7. Qxd4 e6 $1 {with the idea} 8. Qxa7 $2 Bd7) 6... Qb6 $1 ({Better than} 6... Nc6 7. Nc3) 7. Qc1 {This demands more knowledge from Black.} Nc6 8. Nc3 Bf5 $1 {A great move, maintaining the initiative. Black played this way in a couple of old correspondence games.} 9. Nxd5 ({If White declines with} 9. e3 e6 {he is back to 8.e3}) 9... Qa5+ 10. Nc3 e5 $1 {The point of Black's play.} 11. dxe5 {This was played in a couple of the correspondence games.} Bb4 {[%mdl 32768]} (11... Nxc3 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. Bxc3 {transposes.}) 12. Bd2 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 ({If} 13. bxc3 Ba3 14. Qd1 Bb2 {wins an exchange.}) 13... Bxc3+ 14. Qxc3 $6 {This is how White played in the games.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Ga8c8] White has to play accurately just to survive.} 15. e4 Rc8 $1 16. Bc4 Nc2+ 17. Kd2 Qxc3+ 18. Kxc3 ({White could try} 18. bxc3 Nxa1 19. Bd5 {but Black remains up the exchange after} Be6) 18... Bxe4 $17 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc2a1] White is losing material.} *

