1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. e3 {The main line.} Qb6 ({The most ambitious. Both} 5... Nc6 {and}) (5... cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 {are fine for Black as well.}) 6. Qc1 {By far the most common move, but White has to walk a tightrope.} Nc6 {[%mdl 32768] It's best to maintain the tension. Black is playing for an advantage here.} (6... cxd4 7. exd4 Nc6 8. c3 {is fine too after} Bf5 {or 8...Bg4=}) 7. c3 ({Giving up the center with} 7. dxc5 {is obviously a concession.} Qxc5 8. Nbd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 f6 $15 {is a familiar story.}) 7... f6 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Ge7e5] Now ...g5 followed by ...h5 is a real threat, while White also has to be wary of ...e5.} (7... Bf5 {is simple enough, but we can play for more.}) 8. Nfd2 {An ugly move, but it's probably no worse than the more common 8.Nbd2.} e5 (8... g5 {does not have the desired effect after} 9. Nxe4) 9. Nxe4 {[%cal Gd5e4,Ge5f4] Black has the choice of which piece to take.} cxd4 $5 {Neither.} ({This is stronger than} 9... dxe4 $6 10. dxe5 {or}) (9... exf4 10. Nxc5) 10. cxd4 exf4 11. Nec3 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gf3d2,Gd2e4,Ge4c3] White's opening has consisted of taking a long road to bring his knight from g1 to c3.} fxe3 12. fxe3 ({After} 12. Qxe3+ $2 Kf7 {both the d4- and b2-pawns are hanging.}) 12... Be6 $15 {Black has the bishop pair and some lead in development.} *

