 after} 12. Bxd4 Bc5 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Qe3 {Black is merely comfortable - there is no knockout.}) 12. Nd2 $1 {In practice White has capitulated in most games, but this move keeps White alive. Of course this is not such a tremendous accomplishment with the white pieces in twelve moves.} Bxd4 {[%mdl 32768] This keeps the game going.} ({Black can also grab the pawn, but it all fizzles out soon.} 12... Nxd4 13. Nxe4 $1 {Worse is 13.cxd4? Bb4! followed by ...Bd7 and ...Rc8 with a strong initiative.} dxe4 14. cxd4 Bxd4 {Or 14...Bb4+ 15.Bd2 Qxd4 16.Bb5+ Kf8 17.a3! Bxd2+ 18.Qxd2 Qxd2+ 19.Kxd2= $13 and with a rook coming to c1, White is fine.} 15. Bxd4 Qxd4 16. Bb5+ Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 {The position is equal now. For example} 18. O-O {when Black should really just play} O-O {allowing} 19. Qc4+ {winning back the pawn.}) 13. cxd4 Bf5 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 14. Be2 $1 Rc8 ({There is nothing concrete after} 14... Nb4 15. O-O Rc8 16. Qd1) ({And if we take the pawn now with} 14... Nxd4 {White has} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 $1 Nc2+ 17. Qxc2 Bxc2 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Rc1) 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. O-O O-O {White has the bishops, but Black is active and White has to keep an eye on the d4- and b2-pawns. So, we do not win by force, but White has to avoid a lot of trouble and we have the option to steer the game to a draw in a couple of places.} *

