1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. e3 {The main line.} Qb6 ({The most ambitious. Both} 5... Nc6 {and}) (5... cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 {are fine for Black as well.}) 6. Nc3 {Shankland considers this to be dubious, but I think it may be White's best chance to equalize.} Qa5 {[%mdl 32768]} ({The most ambitious.} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qa5 8. Qd2 {is less convincing.}) 7. Be2 $2 {This is the only move that Shankland considers.} Nxc3 8. Qd2 ({The typical trick, but Black has a counter-trick. The engine rather sadly suggests} 8. bxc3 Qxc3+ 9. Kf1 Nc6 $17) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 ({Instead} 9. Nxd4 e5 $1 10. Bxe5 Bb4 {does not help.}) 9... e5 $1 10. Bxe5 Bb4 11. a3 Nc6 {White cannot regain the piece, so Black is winning.} *

