1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Torre Attack, in this form, is basically dubious. 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.Bg5 is more respectable.} Ne4 ({Part of me wanted to be 'consistent' and offer} 3... e6 {which is not as passive as it appears to be, especially considering pretty much all other courses all give . Black is often fighting for the advantage at an early stage of the game here though. There's a reason everyone recommends this move - there are not many openings where Black is scoring 55%+ in a position after just three moves! Nevertheless, I will give my own take here, and I hope I can offer more power to Black's cause.}) 4. Bf4 {This move is much more sound, although White still needs to be careful.} c5 5. e3 {The main line.} Qb6 ({The most ambitious. Both} 5... Nc6 {and}) (5... cxd4 6. exd4 Nc6 {are fine for Black as well.}) 6. Nc3 {Shankland considers this to be dubious, but I think it may be White's best chance to equalize.} Qa5 ({The most ambitious.} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qa5 8. Qd2 {is less convincing.}) 7. Bxb8 {A sad move, givng up the bishop that has already moved a couple of times for our undeveloped knight.} Nxc3 {[%mdl 32768]} (7... Rxb8 $5 8. Bb5+ Kd8 {is actually good for Black too.}) 8. Qd2 Rxb8 9. Qxc3 ({Black is also happy after} 9. bxc3 c4 $1) 9... Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 c4 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ge7e6,Gb7b5]} ({The most ambitious.} 10... e6 {is level.}) 11. e4 {Trying to break free.} e6 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3,Gc8,Gf8] With the bishop pair and a superior structure, Black has the better long-term prospects.} (11... dxe4 12. Nd2 {is not bad, but it's less clear.}) *

