1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {The Colle does not pose any particular problems for our repertoire.} e6 {The classical response.} ({In my Slav days I preferred to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain. Both} 3... Bf5 4. c4 c6 {and}) (3... Bg4 4. c4 c6 {transpose into the Slow Slav if White is so inclined. Time has taught me that these lines are not always so easy for Black - the ambitious bishop is often a target.}) ({Another big line is} 3... c5 {which may transpose into our repertoire, but then again, it may not.}) 4. Bd3 ({After} 4. c4 {we are immediately in the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 4... b6 $5 {I like this move a lot, and it's very consistent with our repertoire.} ({More often Black plays} 4... c5 {but then White has two completely different setups.} 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. O-O {is the 'real' Colle, which is essentially a Semi-Slav reversed. White often plays for e3-e4 here. Our move order clamps down on this idea.}) 5. O-O {A more popular setup is 5.b3 - often referred to as the Colle-Zukertort. This is a very old setup that looks like a reversed (gasp!) Tartakover.} Bb7 {[%csl Ge4] We have clamped down on the e4-square, so a passive move like 6.c3 makes little sense} 6. b3 (6. c4 Be7 {is again the QGD 4.e3 chapter, so we have a nice harmony here.}) (6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2 O-O {is just another move order.}) (6. Ne5 Be7 7. Nd2 O-O {will also transpose to the main setups after} 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gb8d7,Gd7e5]} ({Black has other moves like} 6... Bd6 {and . This fits into our scheme though. The bishop looks more modest here than it does on d6, but by developing in this way, we can avoid losing a tempo if we ever meet White's Nf3-e5 with ...Nxe5.}) 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 (8. c4 c5 {yet again reaches the QGD with 4.e3. Note that we have held back on the development on the b8-knight. You may remember from that chapter that we like to mimic White's b1-knight.}) 8... Nbd7 {[%csl Gd3,Ge7][%cal Gf3e5,Gf6e4] This is the main position. It's almost symmetrical. White's position looks more aggressive - his bishop is on d3 while our is on e7, and it's his turn. It's not enough to claim anything though, and remember we can play ...Nd7xe5 without losing a tempo to dxe5.} (8... c5 {is possible too, but there is no rush. Our move order will at least make White think about us using the c5-square for our knight.}) 9. Ne5 ({White does not really have a sensible plan other than this and} 9. c4 {, which again transposes to the QGD 4.e3 chapter. This is actually the most popular move in the position.}) 9... c5 {This is logical and it keeps some tension, but it is hardly the only decent move. The non-forcing nature of the play means that both sides have some flexibility while keeping equality within range.} ({Both} 9... Ne4 {and}) (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 {are fine as well.}) 10. Qe2 {This is playable of course, but it does not present any real danger.} Rc8 {Flexible, but I can't really argue with 10...Ne4 or 10...Qc7 It's a game.} 11. f4 Rc7 $5 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8d6,Gg7g6,Gd8c8] Black is very solid. We can play ...Qc8 to create pressure along the c-file. Then ...cxd4 and ...Ne4 may be possible. Another idea is ...Ne8-d6, where the knight covers a lot of squares. We may even play ...f5 with a 'double Stonewall'.} ({The idea we will see later,} 11... cxd4 12. exd4 Ne4 {would just lose a pawn here.}) *

