symmetrical. White's position looks more aggressive - his bishop is on d3 while our is on e7, and it's his turn. It's not enough to claim anything though, and remember we can play ...Nd7xe5 without losing a tempo to dxe5.} (8... c5 {is possible too, but there is no rush. Our move order will at least make White think about us using the c5-square for our knight.}) 9. Ne5 ({White does not really have a sensible plan other than this and} 9. c4 {, which again transposes to the QGD 4.e3 chapter. This is actually the most popular move in the position.}) 9... c5 {This is logical and it keeps some tension, but it is hardly the only decent move. The non-forcing nature of the play means that both sides have some flexibility while keeping equality within range.} ({Both} 9... Ne4 {and}) (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 {are fine as well.}) 10. Qf3 {[%cal Rf6e4,Gf3h3] This has been played quite a bit. White covers the e4-square for the moment, but in practice White has slid to h3 hoping we allow mate on h7.} cxd4 {[%mdl 32768] Opening things up a little.} ({Of course} 10... Rc8 {and}) (10... Qc7 {are playable too.}) 11. exd4 Rc8 12. Qh3 {White's play is rather direct.} Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ge4d2] We are not threatening to take on d2 yet, but ...f5 will shut down White's attacking ideas.} ({Black can play} 12... g6 {too, but I don't see any reason to weaken the long diagonal.}) 13. f3 ({After} 13. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 {we will win the c2-pawn.}) 13... Nef6 {[%csl Rf3] Simplest. White's pawn on f3 is in his way. We can't take on d2 because of mate, but ( 13...Ng5 14.Qg3 f5 is interesting.} 14. f4 Ne4 {[%cal Gf7f5] And back again. White's exotic queen play has brought him nothing. I prefer Black.} *

