1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {The Colle does not pose any particular problems for our repertoire.} e6 {The classical response.} ({In my Slav days I preferred to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain. Both} 3... Bf5 4. c4 c6 {and}) (3... Bg4 4. c4 c6 {transpose into the Slow Slav if White is so inclined. Time has taught me that these lines are not always so easy for Black - the ambitious bishop is often a target.}) ({Another big line is} 3... c5 {which may transpose into our repertoire, but then again, it may not.}) 4. Bd3 ({After} 4. c4 {we are immediately in the QGD 4.e3 chapter.}) 4... b6 $5 {I like this move a lot, and it's very consistent with our repertoire.} ({More often Black plays} 4... c5 {but then White has two completely different setups.} 5. c3 Nc6 6. Nbd2 Bd6 7. O-O {is the 'real' Colle, which is essentially a Semi-Slav reversed. White often plays for e3-e4 here. Our move order clamps down on this idea.}) 5. O-O {A more popular setup is 5.b3 - often referred to as the Colle-Zukertort. This is a very old setup that looks like a reversed (gasp!) Tartakover.} Bb7 {[%csl Ge4] We have clamped down on the e4-square, so a passive move like 6.c3 makes little sense} 6. b3 (6. c4 Be7 {is again the QGD 4.e3 chapter, so we have a nice harmony here.}) (6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2 O-O {is just another move order.}) (6. Ne5 Be7 7. Nd2 O-O {will also transpose to the main setups after} 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gb8d7,Gd7e5]} ({Black has other moves like} 6... Bd6 {and . This fits into our scheme though. The bishop looks more modest here than it does on d6, but by developing in this way, we can avoid losing a tempo if we ever meet White's Nf3-e5 with ...Nxe5.}) 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 (8. c4 c5 {yet again reaches the QGD with 4.e3. Note that we have held back on the development on the b8-knight. You may remember from that chapter that we like to mimic White's b1-knight.}) 8... Nbd7 {[%csl Gd3,Ge7][%cal Gf3e5,Gf6e4] This is the main position. It's almost symmetrical. White's position looks more aggressive - his bishop is on d3 while our is on e7, and it's his turn. It's not enough to claim anything though, and remember we can play ...Nd7xe5 without losing a tempo to dxe5.} (8... c5 {is possible too, but there is no rush. Our move order will at least make White think about us using the c5-square for our knight.}) 9. Ne5 ({White does not really have a sensible plan other than this and} 9. c4 {, which again transposes to the QGD 4.e3 chapter. This is actually the most popular move in the position.}) 9... c5 {This is logical and it keeps some tension, but it is hardly the only decent move. The non-forcing nature of the play means that both sides have some flexibility while keeping equality within range.} ({Both} 9... Ne4 {and}) (9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne4 {are fine as well.}) 10. f4 {[%csl Ge5] This Stonewall setup is White's main choice. It's consistent at least.} cxd4 $5 {[%mdl 32768] We are following Sam Shankland, which is usually a good idea.} ({More often Black plays the immediate} 10... Ne4 {but after} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Bc4 {scores well for White. Here ...cxd4 can always be met with Bxd4, keeping the bishop active, while ours is blocked by the pawn on e4.}) 11. exd4 (11. Bxd4 {is harmless.} Nc5 {and White's f4 move looks a bit odd.}) 11... Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gf7f5] Again, ...f5 is a productive idea.} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 {[%csl Ge4] Here is the difference - Black has a strong passed pawn.} 13. Bc4 Bd5 {This neutralizes White's bishop.} ({Black can also play} 13... Rc8 14. Qe2 Rc7 $5 {to create pressure on the c-file.} 15. a4 Qc8 16. Rf2 Nf6 17. Raf1 a6 {Black was doing well in Hamitevici-Korley, Copenhagen 2022. White has to watch out for ...b6 and ...Nd5.}) 14. Qe2 f5 $1 15. Rad1 Nxe5 $5 {The engine's suggestion. This could be tough to evaluate over the board, but we have the luxury of checking it in peace.} ({Sam played} 15... Qc7 {and still got a good position in R.Wang-Shankland, Edmonton 2014, but a later mistake led to an unfortunate loss.}) 16. dxe5 $6 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Qc8 $15 {[%csl Ge4] Black has both the strong e4-pawn and the better bishop.} *

