1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {[%mdl 32768] I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper (StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 ) .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Ge7e6] This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ...Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 (without hanging our queen), then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. c3 {This allows White to meet 4...Qb6 with 5.Qb3, but beyond that, there's not much to it.} (4. Nd2 {is odd move order which does not change much.} Qb6 {and the the usual ...Bf5, ...e6, etc.}) (4. Nc3 {is even more unusual. We know White's knight is not so well placed here.} Qb6 5. Rb1 Bf5 {and again, ...e6, etc.}) 4... Bf5 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gd8b6] Of course we can also meet Qb3 with ...Qb6.} 5. Nd2 Nd7 6. Ngf3 Ngf6 7. e3 e6 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gf8e7,Gd8b6,Gd1b3,Ge1g1,Ge8g8,Gf6e4] This is just equal. We'll play ...Be7 and castle, and then perhaps ...Ne4. At some point we may consider ...e5, especially if bishops get exchanged on e7, as then our queen would support this break.} *

