1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper (StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 ) .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Ge7e6] This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ...Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 (without hanging our queen), then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. e3 {This is common, but it essentially allows instant equality.} Qb6 {[%mdl 32768]} 5. Qc1 (5. b3 e5 $1 {is an even better version for Black, as 5.b3 weakens White's queenside.}) 5... e5 ({This 'forces' equality, but Black can play} 5... Bf5 {too. After} 6. Nf3 {we transpose to a position we'll discuss via the 4.Nf3 move order.}) 6. Nf3 ({The tactical point is} 6. dxe5 $4 Qb4+ {- one reason we flung in 2...h6.}) 6... exd4 {This is simplest, although admittedly rather dry.} ({Instead} 6... e4 {is more ambitious, but after} 7. Nfd2 {White will play c4, Nc3 with a kind of reversed French. I prefer White here.}) 7. exd4 Be7 ({Offering an exchange of bishops. The immediate} 7... Bf5 {looks fine too.}) 8. Bxe7 (8. Bg3 Bf5 {is equal. It would be hard for either side to cause problems.}) 8... Nxe7 9. Bd3 Bf5 {It makes sense to trade this bishop too.} 10. Bxf5 Nxf5 11. O-O ({White can also play safely with} 11. c3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 {Black could also play 12...Qc7 preventing Qf4, but it's not dangerous.} 13. Qf4 Ne7 14. Qd6 Qd8 {is like the main line.}) 11... O-O ({Black could also try} 11... Nxd4 $5 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Re1+ Kf8 {Some care is certainly needed, but we are up a pawn.}) 12. Qf4 {White's initiative is very temporary.} Ne7 13. Nbd2 Nd7 {Now the double attack is easily parried.} ({Black has also tried} 13... Ng6 14. Qf5 Na6 {but the black knights are both a little funny here.}) 14. Qd6 Qd8 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gd7f6] We'll play ...Ng6 and ...Nf6. It looks very equal.} *

