1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper (StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 ) .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Ge7e6] This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ...Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 (without hanging our queen), then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2][%mdl 32768]} 5. Nbd2 {This is not common, but it's safe.} Bf5 ({I prefer this to} 5... Qxb2 6. e4) 6. e3 e6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Gf8e7,Gf6e4] We can follow the normal scheme of development here: ...Nd7 and either ...Ngf6 or ...Be7. Here White's c4-c5 does not look so threatening, as White's d2-knight should be on c3 in such a structure.} ({Our b-pawn is not protected now, so we should avoid} 6... Qxb2 $6 7. Rb1 {We can take on a2 or c2, but White has good compensation.}) *

