1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper (StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 ) .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Ge7e6] This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ...Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 (without hanging our queen), then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 5. Qc1 {This is a natural move and it's quite common. The engines scream however, as it loses a pawn.} g5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] It's worth the trouble.} ({If you don't like the looks of this, there is nothing really wrong with} 5... Bf5 {either. After} 6. e3 e6 7. c4 Be7 {White can either help us develop with} 8. Bxe7 Nxe7 {or spend a tempo with 8.Bg3 After 8...Nf6 9.Nc3 Nbd7 ...Ne4 to exchange pieces will be a possibility. White may play c4-c5 at some point, but we can generally retreat to d8 (or c7 if White exchanged dark-squared bishops) and break with ...e5 or ...b6.}) 6. Bg3 g4 7. Ne5 Qxd4 {A center pawn is worth a small bit of trouble. White is slightly ahead in development, but it's difficult to make anything of it.} 8. c4 {[%cal Gc1c8] Looking to open the position. We do have to watch our bishop on c8 . 8.e3 Qc5 9.c4 Bg7 transposes.} Bg7 {[%csl Re5]} 9. e3 Qc5 10. Nd2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gh6h5]} 11. cxd5 ({White allows the exchange of queens. If} 11. Nd3 Qa5 {intending ...Ne4. If} 12. b4 Qd8 {and our extra pawn is quite healthy.}) 11... Qxc1+ {We can't take back with the pawn now.} 12. Rxc1 {[%cal Gc1c8]} Nxd5 {White is slightly more active for now, but I prefer the extra pawn.} 13. Z0 ({A correspondence game continued} 13. e4 Nb6 14. Be2 h5 15. Nd3 Na4 $1 16. Rc2 Na6 17. a3 Be6 $17 {when White had little to show for the pawn in Vasile-Boldysh, ICCF email 2009.}) *

