1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {A strange move, hitting at nothing. I have seen it called the Pseudo-Trompowsky and the Hodgson Attack.} h6 {I think this is the simplest way to respond to this rare line.} ({The most ambitious move is} 2... f6 {with the idea} 3. Bh4 $6 Nh6 $1) ({The simple} 2... Nf6 {is certainly possible. This is technically a Trompowsky proper (StartFENrnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1EndFEN 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 d5 ) .}) ({I would definitely avoid our customary} 2... e6 {however!}) 3. Bh4 ({I suppose White can play} 3. Bf4 Nf6 {with a London with the extra move ...h6. I think we can be pretty happy with that. No back rank mate.}) 3... c6 $1 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gc8f5,Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Ge7e6] This is a bit foreign to us, but it's quite straightforward. We will generally play ...Qb6, eyeing the b2-pawn. Once White deals with that, we can easily develop with ...e6 (without hanging our queen), then we can either offer an exchange of bishops with ...Be7, or develop with ...Nd7 and ...Ngf6, avoiding doubled pawns. Black has a pretty easy time here.} 4. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 5. b3 {White has avoided various little tactical ideas, but this softens up the queenside a bit.} Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gb8d7,Gf8e7][%mdl 32768] We just follow the development plan.} 6. e3 e6 7. Bd3 {White generally wants to eliminate our strong bishop.} (7. Be2 {is rather passive. We can play} Nd7 {and then either ...Be7 or ...Ngf6.}) 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Be7 ({Following Kramnik. Black could play} 8... Nd7 {first too. Now White can either exchange bishops, helping us develop, or keep the bishop, which costs a tempo.}) 9. Bxe7 Nxe7 10. c4 ({Instead} 10. O-O {could certainly transpose if we follow suit, but} c5 $5 {is possible as well.}) 10... Nd7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. O-O ({After} 12. c5 Qc7 {we will soon break with ...e5.}) 12... Qa6 $5 {[%cal Ga6d3,Gf8d8,Ga8c8,Gc6c5,Gd7b6] Pinning the c4-pawn. Black can then prepare ...c5, while with ...Nb6 at some point to put pressure on the c4-pawn is another idea.} 13. Z0 ({A well-known game at elite level went} 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 14. Rab1 b6 $5 15. Qf1 Rac8 16. Rd2 Nf6 17. Ne5 dxc4 18. Nxc4 Ned5 19. Rc2 $2 Nxc3 20. Rxc3 c5 $1 21. dxc5 b5 $1 22. Ne5 Ne4 {and Black won the exchange and the game in Morozevich-Kramnik, Astana 2001.}) *

