1. d4 d5 2. e4 $2 {This move loses a pawn. There is one little trap to be aware of though, and we should pay attention to our move orders.} dxe4 {[%mdl 32768]} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 ({I don't see how} 4. Bg5 Bf5 {changes White's fortunes.}) 4... exf3 ({Yum. The developing} 4... Bf5 {is a perfectly good alternative which has been recommended by some authors.}) 5. Qxf3 $2 {There have actually been many games where White lost a second pawn this way.} Qxd4 6. Be3 Qh4+ ({It seems useful to throw in this check, but the immediate} 6... Qg4 {is probably just as good.}) 7. g3 Qg4 {We are not really worried about White bringing his bishop to g2, and g2-g3 could be detrimental. The rook is exposed, for one thing. Also White's queen is denied access to the g3-square.} 8. Qf2 Qf5 (8... Bd7 $5 {intending ...Bc6 looks good too.}) 9. Qd2 {Down two pawns, White can't entertain the idea of exchanging queens.} e6 10. O-O-O {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd2d8] Watch out for mate!} Be7 {Whew! That was a close one.} 11. Nb5 {One more threat.} Na6 {Two pawns up. Just don't blunder.} *

