1. d4 d5 2. e4 $2 {This move loses a pawn. There is one little trap to be aware of though, and we should pay attention to our move orders.} dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 ({I don't see how} 4. Bg5 Bf5 {changes White's fortunes.}) 4... exf3 ({Yum. The developing} 4... Bf5 {is a perfectly good alternative which has been recommended by some authors.}) 5. Nxf3 Bf5 {[%mdl 32768]} (5... e6 {is possible, but passive.}) (5... g6 {is a good alternative though.}) 6. Ne5 c6 $1 ({This is definitely more accurate than} 6... e6 {when} 7. g4 {is not so clear.}) 7. Bc4 e6 8. g4 {Now this is bad, but white players have tried it.} Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gd7e5] Strongest.} (8... Bg6 {is a decent move too. If} 9. h4 Bb4 $1) 9. gxf5 {There's not a lot of choice.} Nxe5 ({Instead} 9... Qh4+ 10. Kf1 Nxe5 11. Be2 {transposes, but let's give White an opportunity to make further mistakes.}) 10. Be2 ({A very sad move to make. We were hoping for} 10. dxe5 Qh4+ {followed by ...Qxc4.}) 10... Qh4+ 11. Kf1 Qh3+ $1 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5] It's good to flick this move in.} 12. Ke1 Ned7 13. fxe6 ({Even worse is} 13. Bg4 $2 Qh4+ 14. Kf1 h5 {with ...Qh3+ and ...Qxf5 next.}) 13... Qxe6 $17 {Black is up a pawn and has a better position. White can't even castle.} *

