1. d4 d5 2. e4 $2 {This move loses a pawn. There is one little trap to be aware of though, and we should pay attention to our move orders.} dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3 ({I don't see how} 4. Bg5 Bf5 {changes White's fortunes.}) 4... exf3 ({Yum. The developing} 4... Bf5 {is a perfectly good alternative which has been recommended by some authors.}) 5. Nxf3 Bf5 (5... e6 {is possible, but passive.}) (5... g6 {is a good alternative though.}) 6. Ne5 c6 $1 ({This is definitely more accurate than} 6... e6 {when} 7. g4 {is not so clear.}) 7. Bc4 e6 8. O-O Bg6 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} ({The ONE THING we have to remember is not to play} 8... Nbd7 $2 9. Rxf5 $1 {when we are dying on f7. Now, however, we have a nice Caro-Kann type position - with an extra pawn.}) 9. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gd1f3] This is a silly move, but it's the only one we have to analyze at all.} (9. Bg5 {can be met with either} Be7 {or 9...Nbd7 White has no compensation.}) (9. Nxg6 {helps us too.} hxg6 $17 {with ...Bd6 coming. White will have to burn a tempo to deal with attacks on h2.}) 9... Nbd7 ({We could play} 9... Bd6 {too.}) 10. Nxg6 ({There's no time for} 10. g5 $2 Nxe5) 10... hxg6 11. g5 Nb6 $1 {Ok, I'll present a novelty, courtesy of my silicon friend.} ({Let's just avoid} 11... Nd5 $6 12. Qf3 {which is rather annoying.}) ({In practice Black has gone for} 11... Qc7 {If} 12. Bf4 Bd6 {After 12.Qe2 Nd5 White can win back the pawn with 13.Bxd5 cxd5 14.Nxd5 but Black is still a bit better after 14...Qc6}) 12. Bxe6 ({The best try. If} 12. Bb3 {we can comfortably play} Nfd5 {meeting} 13. Qf3 {with} Qc7 $17) 12... fxe6 13. gxf6 gxf6 14. Qg4 f5 $1 ({It looks like we have messed something up because} 14... Kf7 15. Bg5 Be7 16. Rxf6+ $1 Bxf6 17. Rf1 {looks dangerous, but we have a resource.}) 15. Qxg6+ Kd7 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Rg1,Rh2][%cal Gf8d6,Gd8g8,Gh8h4] We returned the pawn, but we have a great endgame coming after ...Bd6 and ...Qg8. The h2- and d4-pawns are weak. We may even lift a rook to h4 or g4.} *

