1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. Qb3 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Rd1 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e1] Black does not commit the c-pawn yet, preferring to line up his rook against White's uncastled king.} 12. Bd3 c5 $1 13. dxc5 Nd7 $1 {The point - the knight is coming to c5 no matter what.} 14. c6 $1 Bxc6 15. O-O Nc5 16. Qc2 Rc8 {This is a typical Tartakover position where both sides have their advantages. In the course, we stop here. Let's see how Kramnik handled the middlegame.} 17. Bh7+ {A minor disruption.} Kh8 18. Bf5 Ne6 $1 {[%cal Gc8c2,Gf6c3] A great square for the knight. Black is active and has the bishop pair. White's pressure against the d5-pawn doesn't really amount to anything as the c3-knight is a bit vulernable.} 19. Nd4 $6 (19. Qb3 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Qf6 21. Bg4 Bb7 22. Nd4 Ba6 23. Rfe1 Bc4 24. Qa3 Rc7 {was Gulko-Radashkovich, USSR 1971. Black won in 33 moves.}) 19... Nxd4 20. exd4 Rc7 $15 {Now Black has the bishop pair 'for nothing'.} 21. Qd3 g6 22. Bg4 (22. Bxg6 $2 {is totally unsound.} fxg6 23. Qxg6 Bg7) 22... h5 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gh6h5] A typical space-gaining operation.} 23. Bf3 Rce7 {[%cal Gh8g7,Gd8d6]} 24. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4] White would like to play h4 himself to stablize the kingside.} h4 $1 {Of course!} 25. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2h6]} Kg7 26. g4 $2 {This weakens the dark squares.} Re6 $1 {[%cal Gf6g5]} 27. h3 {Preparing f4 with} (27. Bg2 Qd6 $1 28. f4 {weakens a new square -} Re3 $17) 27... Bg5 28. Qc2 Qd6 {[%csl Rf4,Rg3,Rh2]} 29. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5] Hitting the d5-pawn, but Kramnik will not be denied.} Bd8 {[%cal Gd8c7] Less than 30 moves and White is busted!} 30. Bg2 ({Some other lines:} 30. Bxd5 $2 Qf4 {30...Bc7 31.f4 Re3-+ works too}) (30. Nxd5 Bxd5 31. Qxd5 {31.Bxd5 Bc7 32.f4 Re3-+} Qf4 32. Kg2 Bc7 33. Rh1 Rf6 $1 {Black's attack looks decisive. Already ...Re2! is a threat.} 34. Rde1 Rxe1 35. Rxe1 Qh2+ 36. Kf1 Qxh3+ 37. Ke2 Qh2) 30... Qf4 $1 (30... Bc7 {is good too, but why not prevent f4. White has no defense now.}) 31. Rc1 Bc7 32. Rfd1 Rf6 $1 33. Qc2 Re3 $1 {A great move, which can be discovered when you try to think about how to get the king when it's on f1.} (33... Qh2+ 34. Kf1 Re3 $1 {works too.}) 34. Kf1 ({If} 34. Qd2 Qh2+ 35. Kf1 Rg3 $1 36. f3 Rfxf3+ 37. Bxf3 Rg1#) 34... Rxc3 $1 ({The point is seen after} 34... Rxc3 35. bxc3 Bb5+ $1 {and if} 36. Ke1 Re6+) 0-1

