1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Be2 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 c6 12. O-O Re8 ({I think this is the most accurate, but moves like} 12... Nd7 {and}) (12... Qd6 {have been played too.}) 13. Rc1 Qd6 $1 {Timing is important.} ({A)} 13... a5 $6 14. b5 c5 15. Na4 $1 c4 16. Ne5 $1 {causes problems.}) ({B)} 13... Nd7 14. Qb3 a5 $6 {doesn't work here.} 15. b5 c5 16. Nxd5 Bxd4 17. Bc4 $16) 14. Qb3 Nd7 15. Rfd1 a5 $1 {Only now.} 16. b5 ({If} 16. a3 {it's a good time for} axb4 17. axb4 b5 {and ...Nb6-c4.}) ({We are also not worried about} 16. bxa5 Rxa5 17. a4 {when we have the usual assortment of ideas. I like} Bd8 $5 {heading for c7.}) 16... c5 {The course goes up to here. [/variation/20836207/#/12/b]} 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Qa3 Rad8 19. Nd4 {Brattain is a former student of mine, and I recall him telling me that he was prepared up to around here, based on a recommendation he saw somewhere. Black is totally fine, so he was cursing that he trusted whatever the source was...} Be5 $1 ({Much better than the cooperative} 19... Bxd4 20. exd4 Ne4 21. Qxd6 Nxd6 22. Bd3 {when White was indeed better in Zabotin-Demianjuk, Gagarin 2009.}) 20. h3 ({After} 20. g3 Qf6 {White can never really play Bf3, and} 21. Bf1 Bxd4 $1 22. exd4 {(If 22.Rxd4? Ne6 $17 and ...d4 is a typical idea.)} Ne4 23. Nxe4 dxe4 {and ...Bd5 looks comfortable for Black.}) 20... Qf6 21. Bf3 Ne4 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gg7g6,Gh6h5] It's about equal, but Black's position looks easier to play. He has the IQP but more 'improving moves' at his disposal.} 22. Qb3 g6 23. Na4 $2 {A step in the wrong direction.} (23. Nce2 {is more solid, even though it basically admits that the d5-pawn is not a problem for Black.} Nc5 24. Qb1 h5 {and I still prefer Black.}) 23... Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3] Suddenly White has tactical problems.} 24. Rd3 ({If} 24. Be2 {the bishop is vulnerable on the e-file.} Bxd4 25. Rxd4 Ne6 {and ...d4}) 24... Bxd4 25. Rxd4 ({I imagine White was counting on} 25. exd4 {but then} Nxh3+ $1 {snares a pawn. If} 26. gxh3 $2 Qg5+ {picks up the c1-rook.}) 25... Nxf3+ 26. gxf3 Qxf3 {Black has won a pawn. The b7-bishop does not look so good, but White's king is open.} 27. Rc7 Rc8 (27... Re5 $1 {is even stronger.} 28. Rxb7 Qxh3) 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 {[%cal Gc8c1]} 29. Qd1 Qf6 {Covering the b6-pawn.} (29... Qxh3 30. Nxb6 Rc5 {was good too.}) 30. Kg2 Re8 {The computer does not like this, preferring to keep ...Rc4 as a possibility.} 31. Qf3 Qd6 32. Qf4 (32. Qg3 {looks like a better try.}) 32... Qxf4 33. exf4 Re6 {There was probably some timed pressure.} (33... Re2 34. Nxb6 Rxa2) 34. Kg3 Kf8 35. Nc3 Ke7 36. Na4 Kd6 37. Rd2 Re4 38. Nxb6 Rb4 39. a4 d4 {Finally the bishop is free.} 40. Rc2 Rb3+ 41. Kh2 Rc3 42. Nc4+ Kc5 43. Ne3 Be4 0-1

