1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Qc2 dxc4 8. e3 c5 9. dxc5 Qa5 ({Black always goes for this and it would be my choice, but I will note that} 9... O-O {transposes to the 7.e3 0-0 8.Qc2 dxc4 line, which is also fine for Black.}) 10. Bxc4 Qxc5 {Black has the bishop pair and White does not have much in return.} 11. Ne4 ({After} 11. Nd2 Be7 {avoids Ne4. Black will just castle and his queen can comfortably retreat to c7.}) 11... Qa5+ 12. Ke2 ({This connect the rooks and avoids retreating a knight. If} 12. Nfd2 Be7) 12... Be7 {Black is solid and has the bishop pair. White is well developed, so I think he can hold the balance but no more.} 13. Qc3 $146 ({Another high level game saw} 13. Rhc1 Bd7 14. Qc3 Qxc3 15. Rxc3 Nc6 16. a3 $6 f5 $1 17. Ned2 Bf6 18. Rc2 {was Wang Yue-Carlsen, Linares 2009. Here} Rc8 $1 19. Nb3 Ne5 {is very good for Black - bishop pair!}) 13... Qxc3 14. Nxc3 a6 {The position is equal. White has temporary advantage in development, but black's position is out of weaknesses. Black's pair of bishops might become a potential source of worry for white in future.} 15. Rhd1 Nd7 16. Ne4 b5 17. Bb3 Bb7 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. Rxd6 Ke7 {White eliminated Black's bishop pair, but the b7-bishop is quite strong and Black is doing well. Of course it 'should' ultimately end in a draw, but Topalov shows that such endgame can still be won, even against a strong opponent.} 20. Rad1 ({An obvious move, but} 20. Rdd1 {is probably safer, so that White can contest the d-file}) 20... Rhd8 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga8c8,Gb7d5]} 21. R6d4 ({Another apparently active move, but} 21. R6d2 {was to be preferred.}) 21... Rac8 22. Ne1 {White is trying to neutralize the long diagonal, but the knight is poorly placed here.} a5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gb7a6,Ga5a4] Taking some space.} 23. f3 Rc7 24. e4 {This linits Black's bishop, but weakens the dark squares a little bit. Plus the white pawns are on the same color as Black's bishop.} Rdc8 {[%csl Gc7,Gc8][%cal Gc8c1]} 25. a3 g5 {[%cal Gd7e5] A typical move to fix White's pawns.} 26. Ke3 Ne5 27. R4d2 Ba6 28. Rd6 Ra7 {[%cal Gb5b4,Ga5a4,Ge5c4] White has to watch out for ...a4 and ...b4 and ...Nc4.} 29. R6d2 ({The active looking} 29. Rb6 {can be met with} Nd7 30. Rbd6 a4 31. Ba2 b4 $1 32. axb4 Ne5 {when both ...Rb8 and ...Bc4 are threats.}) 29... b4 $5 (29... a4 30. Ba2 Nc4+ 31. Bxc4 bxc4 {with the idea of doubling on the b-file was good too. White has to watch out for ...c3 as well.}) 30. axb4 Rb8 $1 31. Ra1 $2 ({Certainly} 31. Nc2 {keeping the b-file closed, is better.} a4 32. Bxa4 $1 {32.Ba2 Bc4! 33.Bb1 Bb3-+} Nc4+ 33. Kf2 Nxd2 34. Rxd2 {and White has two pawns for the exchange. They are only good defensively, but it's not going to be easy for Black to make significant progress.}) 31... Rxb4 {Now the pressure on the b-file is too much.} 32. Ra3 a4 33. Ba2 Bc4 34. Bb1 $6 ({Getting away from Black's knight with} 34. Kf2 {was a better try, but Black is still much better.}) 34... Bf1 {[%cal Ge5c4]} ({Not bad, but} 34... Rab7 {looks simpler. If} 35. Nd3 Nxd3 36. Bxd3 Bxd3 37. Rdxd3 Rxb2 38. Rxa4 Rxg2) 35. Ba2 Rab7 36. Nc2 $2 ({Again,} 36. Kf2 {was a better try.}) 36... Rxb2 37. Rxa4 Rc7 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 38. Kf2 ({If} 38. Ne1 Rc3+ {wins serious material.}) 38... Bb5 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Rc2] Black wins a whole piece.} 0-1

