1. d4 e6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 9. h5 {This is the older way of playing. White simply gains space.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf7f5] A very original idea which is considered standard now. Karpov played in against Kasparov in their 1985 match, and its value was upheld in many games by QGD experts Vaganian and Lputian.} ({After} 9... Ngf6 10. f3 $16 {Black is very cramped on the kingside.}) 10. Be2 {This is by far the main move. White protects the g4-pawn without further weakening his structure.} Nb6 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf7f5] The main line. White has to figure out how to develop. He would rather not play f3, but the g4-pawn requires attention.} (10... f5 $5 {is also possible.}) 11. Nh3 {White develops and supports g4-g5 if Black goes for ...f5. This is the main line.} g5 $1 ({Black cannot play} 11... f5 $2 12. g5 Nf7 13. Rg1 $16 {when he is really suffering for lack of space.}) 12. hxg6 {White really must take.} hxg6 {[%cal Gg6g5,Gf7f5] Black has clear counterplay and has done very well in practice.} 13. f3 $6 {This is the most common move, but it's not very good.} Bh4+ (13... g5 14. Bg3 f5 {is also decent, but the check is more disruptive.}) 14. Nf2 {White avoids moving his king, but this is passive.} g5 $1 15. Bh2 ({Instead} 15. Be5 f6 16. Bh2 Qe7 {is similar, with ...f6 for free.}) 15... Qe7 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gf7f5] I do not see any appeal to playing White's position. This game is a nice example of Black's play.} ({The immediate} 15... f5 {also looks good.} 16. Be5 Rg8 {with the idea ...Qe7, ...O-O-O.}) 16. Qc2 (16. e4 $6 {is premature.} dxe4 17. fxe4 Nc4 $17 {White's position was very loose in Turov - Vaganian, Aeroflot Open, Moscow 2002.}) 16... f5 $1 ({Black should avoid} 16... O-O-O {?!} 17. Nb5 $1) 17. Be5 (17. gxf5 Nxf5 {is a disaster for White.}) 17... Rf8 18. O-O-O (18. Rxh4 gxh4 19. Bf4) (18. gxf5 Nxf5 19. Qd2 g4 $17) 18... Nf7 (18... Bxf2 19. Rxh6 Bxe3+ 20. Kb1 O-O-O {?} 21. Nb5) 19. gxf5 $6 (19. Nd3 $2 fxg4 {( 19...Nc4-+ )} 20. fxg4 Nc4) (19. Rdf1 Nxe5 20. dxe5 fxg4 21. Nxg4 Bxg4 22. fxg4 Qxe5 23. Qg6+ Kd7 $17) 19... Bxf2 20. fxe6 Bxe3+ 21. Kb1 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Qxe6 23. Bf1 (23. Rh7 O-O-O 24. Nb5 Kb8) 23... g4 (23... Rxf3 $17) 24. fxg4 O-O-O 25. Rh5 Rf2 26. Qh7 Rdf8 27. Rf5 (27. Bh3 Kb8 $17 {Nc4}) 27... R2xf5 28. gxf5 Qxe5 29. f6 Bd4 30. Bh3+ Kb8 0-1

