1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bf4 Nc6 11. Nc3 Nb4 12. Qc1 Rc8 13. Rd1 Nbd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Be3 Ng4 16. Ne1 Bxg2 17. Nxg2 Qd5 18. h3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 c5 20. Nf4 Qf5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 $15 {All of this is in the course. Black is a little better - he has a slightly safer king and better minor piece in the long-term. This game was played a long time ago - 2008 -when Magnus was quite young, but still 2775! I like this game because it shows how quickly things can heat up in an apparently quiet position.} 22. Qd3 $6 ({After this Anand grabs hold of the initiative and doesn't let go. Better was} 22. Qf3 {when at least the f2-pawn is secure.}) 22... Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rb2]} 23. Qd2 {[%cal Gf4d3]} ({If} 23. b3 $2 e5 {and f2 is falling.}) 23... Rfd8 24. Qa5 $6 {Carlsen tries to stay active, but this quickly leads to a position beyond saving.} ({The passive} 24. Qe1 {was called for, even though Black can win the b2-pawn, by taking immediately or with} Bd4 {first.}) 24... e5 {[%csl Rf2]} ({Winning, although the engine slightly prefers trading rooks first:} 24... Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 e5 26. Nd3 Bb6 {with ...e4 coming. If} 27. Qb4 Rc4) 25. Rxd8+ ({Or} 25. Nd3 Bb6 26. Qe1 e4 {and then ...e3 and ...Qxb2.}) 25... Rxd8 26. Nd3 Bb6 {[%cal Ge5e4] Anand prefers a technical solution.} (26... Rxd3 {was also possible.} 27. exd3 Qxf2+ 28. Kh1 Qxg3 29. Qd8+ Bf8 {is winning as well.}) 27. Qc3 ({Or} 27. Qe1 e4 28. Nf4 e3 {and ...Qxb2, with an extra pawn and much better position.}) 27... Bd4 28. Qe1 e4 29. Nf4 Bxb2 $6 ({Throwing in} 29... e3 {to soften up White's king position would have been stronger.}) 30. Rd1 Be5 {Black is still up a good extra pawn. The rest is not relevant to our opening study, but it's worth playing through just to admire Anand's technique. he slowly takes over the board.} 31. Nd5 Qe6 32. Qa5 Rd6 33. Ne3 Rxd1+ 34. Nxd1 h6 35. Kg2 Qc6 36. Ne3 g6 37. Qb4 Kg7 38. Kh2 Bc3 39. Qe7 Bd4 40. Qb4 Qc5 41. Qd2 Bxe3 42. fxe3 b4 43. Kg2 a5 44. Kf2 a4 45. Qb2+ Kg8 46. Qd2 b3 47. axb3 axb3 48. Qd8+ Kg7 49. Qd2 Qb6 50. Qb2+ Qf6+ 0-1

