1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 Bd5 11. Qc2 Be4 12. Qc1 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rd1 a5 15. Nbd2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6 ({We cannot take:} 16... Bxd4 $2 17. Ne4) ({Or} 16... Qxd4 17. Ne4) 17. Nc4 Na6 (17... Bxd4 $2 {does not work here} 18. Qf4 $1 {( 18.e3? Qf6! does work for us).} e5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 $16 {There are many positions like this, where it's often considered that White is a tiny bit better. There are various permutation depending on where the pieces are. I think if Black is patient there should not be too many worries. We have to watch out for two things - White's h4-h4 followed by creating a battery on the b1-h7 diagonal; and a possible d4-d5 break. This game is not very exciting, but I like how Leko is very patient against a player who is about 200 points lower rated (but still very strong at almost 2500).}) 18. Qf4 ({After} 18. e4 $6 {,} Bxd4 {is a good pawn grab. We can support the bishop with ...c5.}) 18... Nb4 19. e3 Nd5 {In the course we stop here. [/variation/22775246/#/19/b]} 20. Qe4 (20. Qg4 g6 {and}) (20. Qd6 Qxd6 21. Nxd6 Be7 $1 {have both been seen in practice. If} 22. Nxb7 Rfb8 23. Nc5 Bxc5 24. dxc5 Rxb2 $15) 20... g6 {This is useful, as now Black can safely meet h4 with h5.} 21. Rac1 Qc7 22. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3e2,Ge2d3]} h5 {Avoiding White's h5, followed by Be2-d3.} 23. Qd3 Nb4 24. Qe4 Kg7 {Leko just makes little improving moves.} 25. Kg2 Rfe8 26. Rd2 Nd5 27. Qb1 Rad8 {[%cal Gf6d4,Gd8d4] White may play for e3-e4 at some point, so Black pays attention to White's d4-pawn. In the long term, Black may achieve ...e5 or ...c5.} 28. Rcd1 Rd7 29. Qe4 Red8 30. Rc2 Re7 31. Rcc1 Red7 32. Rh1 {Hinting that g3-g4 may be possible.} Rh8 {So Black tries to discourage it.} 33. Rhd1 Re7 34. Qb1 Nb4 35. Nd2 Rd7 36. Ne4 Be7 37. Nc5 Rdd8 38. Nd3 Qb6 {Note that Leko is not afraid of the exchange of knights, further reducing material and leaving just heavy pieces and opposite-colored bishops.} 39. Nxb4 Qxb4 40. Qc2 Rd7 41. Rd3 Rhd8 42. Rcd1 Qb6 43. b3 Qc7 44. Qc4 Bb4 45. Be2 Rd6 46. Rc1 Qe7 47. Rdd1 Qf6 {Not much has been happening, but the game goes on. White's next move is not technically a mistake, but practically it is, as he was not ready for Black's response.} 48. Qc2 c5 49. Qe4 {This stays within the drawing margin, but the coming pawn structure clearly only leaves Black with something to play for.} ({Thybo could have played} 49. dxc5 Rd2 50. Qc4 {(But not 50.Rxd2 Rxd2 51.Qc4 Qb2-+ because ...Rxe2 is coming and the c1-rook lacks protection).} Qb2 51. Kf1) 49... cxd4 50. Rxd4 Rxd4 51. exd4 Rxd4 52. Qxb7 {[%csl Ra4,Ga5,Rb3,Ge6,Gf7,Gg6,Gh5] Black's a-pawn holds back White's queenside, while Black has 4:3 on the kingside. So Black can keep pressing despite the near 0.00 engine assessment.} Rd2 53. Qf3 $2 ({Natural, but it loses a pawn. Even if this was not the case, it was actually better to keep queens on with} 53. Qe4) 53... Qxf3+ 54. Bxf3 Rb2 55. Bc6 $2 Rxb3 $2 {It's nice to take a pawn, but it's a bit irrelevant.} (55... Bd2 $1 {shifting the bishop first, was much stronger. For example} 56. Rf1 Be3 57. Bb5 Bb6 {White can hardly move and Black will push the e- and f-pawns.}) 56. Rc2 Bc3 57. Bb5 Bd4 58. Rd2 Bc5 {The play is one-sided, but White should hold. It's not easy to keep defending forever against a strong opponent though.} 59. Rc2 Be7 60. Rd2 (60. Rc7 {was worth considering, with possible counterplay against d7. It's not easy to safely get the setup with a black rook on the seventh rank and the bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal. Black had his chance on move 55.}) 60... Rc3 61. Rd3 Rc2 62. Re3 Bc5 63. Re2 Rc3 {Trading rooks would be a dead draw.} 64. Rd2 e5 {Finally some progress.} 65. Re2 Bd4 66. Rd2 Kf6 67. Re2 Ke6 68. Rd2 Kd5 69. Be8 Rc7 70. Bb5 e4 71. Re2 Ke5 72. Rd2 Rc3 73. Re2 $2 (73. Be8 {was called for.}) 73... f5 74. Be8 Kf6 75. Rd2 Bc5 76. Rb2 e3 $6 ({Leko looks to switch his attention to the g3-pawn, but it was better to play the instructive} 76... g5 $1 77. Bxh5 {( 77.hxg5+ Kxg5 and ...h4, followed by ...f4-f3).} gxh4 78. gxh4 f4 $17) 77. fxe3 $2 ({Falling in with Black's plans. Better was} 77. f4 $1 {when Black's e-pawn looks scary, but it's not going anywhere.}) 77... Rxe3 {[%csl Rg3]} 78. Bc6 Bd6 79. Bf3 Ra3 {[%csl Ra4,Rg3] The principle of two weaknesses. White can't hold both g3 and a4.} 80. Rd2 Ke6 (80... Be5 {was simpler.}) 81. Bd5+ (81. Rd4 $1 {and it's not over yet.}) 81... Kd7 82. Bf3 Rxa4 83. Rb2 Ke6 84. Re2+ Be5 85. Re3 Ra2+ 86. Be2 a4 87. Kf3 Kf6 88. Rd3 a3 {A nice technical game from Leko.} 0-1

