1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5 Bd5 11. Qd3 c5 $1 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. Rfd1 Qa5 {The most complicated. Black is willing to go into a tactical fight.} 14. dxc5 {This is quite harmless, and invites our next move.} Nbd7 15. e4 {I generally do not like this idea for White. We do have to deal with the e4-e5 advance now, but just about any move will avoid the threat!} Bxc5 {The most ambitious. Black has various threats, such as ...Ng4, and even ...Bxf2+ followed by ... Nc5xe4+.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 15... Nxc5 {either. This is also mentioned in the course.}) 16. Be3 Bxe3 {This is all right, but I'd prefer to bring a rook to d8 immediately} 17. Qxe3 Rfd8 18. Rd4 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gb2b4] Preparing to double rooks.} Ne5 ({Instead} 18... Ng4 {and}) (18... e5 $5 {were alternatives.}) 19. b4 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qe5 21. Rad1 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Rc8 ({Another idea is} 22... h5 $5 {supporting a possible ...Ng4, as well as ...h4.}) 23. Be2 h6 24. f4 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c3]} 25. b5 (25. Rc4 {could be met with} Qb8 {or 25...Nd7 with the idea 26.b5 Nb6 27.Rc5 Nd7 because 28.bxc6? Nxc5 29.Qxc5 Qxc6 30.Qxc6 Rxc6 is much better for Black.}) 25... Bxb5 ({This is simpler than} 25... axb5 {but this is ok too.} 26. axb5 Be8 27. e5 $5 Qxc3 28. Qxc3 Rxc3 29. Rd8 Kf8 30. exf6 gxf6) 26. Nxb5 $6 ({White should acquiesce to equality:} 26. axb5 Qxc3 27. Qxc3 Rxc3 28. bxa6 bxa6 29. Bxa6) 26... axb5 27. axb5 Qc2 $15 {With the safer king, Black is a bit better here.} 28. Qd3 Qc1+ 29. Kg2 Rc3 ({Tempting, but} 29... g6 $5 {making a little more room for the king was flexible.}) 30. Qd2 Qxd2 31. Rxd2 Nxe4 {Black has netted a pawn, but we will quickly see that it's of no use.} 32. Rd8+ Kh7 33. Bd3 {Leading to a drawn rook and pawn endgame.} f5 34. Bxe4 fxe4 35. Re8 Rb3 36. Rxe6 1/2-1/2

