1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 Bd6 11. Nc3 {White allows the doubling of his f-pawns. This is a typical idea.} Bxf4 12. gxf4 {Having played this structure with White, I realize that despite the improved grip on the center, this setup is not without chances for Black, as the white king position is loosened up a bit.} a5 {The typical setup, locking down the b4-square.} 13. e3 Na6 ({Instead} 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 c6 {would be nice and simple, but White has the typical move} 15. b4 $14 {with some initiative on the queenside.}) 14. Kh1 {This is a typical idea, hoping to use the half-open g-file. Black is not so easily mated however.} Nb4 15. Rg1 ({Naranayan mentions} 15. Qe2 {in his Catalan course. Black can play various moves here.} Bxf3 {is typical.} 16. Bxf3 c6 17. Rg1 Qe7 {occurred in an Aronian-Nakamura blitz game.}) 15... Qe7 16. Ne5 Bxg2+ 17. Rxg2 g6 {Black is super solid here. White may create chances on the kingside, but any demonstration there could rebound too.} 18. Rag1 Kh8 {Just in case White wants to make some sacs on g6.} 19. Rg5 Nbd5 {Back to the center.} 20. Nxd5 {Changing the central structure. White does not have to take, but Black can still bring a rook to the d-file and perhaps go for ...c5 at some point.} exd5 21. Qe2 Ne4 22. R5g4 Rg8 {More prophylaxis.} (22... Nd6 $5 {looks good. This is a typical great square for Black's knight in a Carlsbad structure. It also stops f4-f5.}) 23. f3 $6 {This weakens e3.} ({I think White should grab the chance to play} 23. f5 $1 {If Black does not take, White can soften up g6, and} gxf5 24. R4g2 $1 {should be pretty equal. Black's extra doubled pawn does not mean much, and everything else is quite level.}) 23... Nd6 {Black is happy to go here anyway.} 24. Qg2 Nf5 {[%csl Re3]} 25. Qh3 Rg7 ({White is playing for tricks. If} 25... Nxe3 26. Rh4 Rg7 27. Re1 {appears to cause a tactical problem, although even here} Nf5 28. Nxg6+ fxg6 29. Rxe7 Rxe7 {favors Black as his pieces will be much more active than White's.}) (25... c5 $1 {is strong though. If} 26. dxc5 Nxe3 $1 {with the idea} 27. Rh4 Rg7 28. Re1 d4) 26. Rg5 Rag8 {[%cal Gg7h7,Gg7g6,Gg8g6,Gf7f6] Black has found a funny arrangement to protect everything. Soon ...f6 will be threatened, and of course ...c5 is still a possibility.} 27. b3 ({A weird move, leaving the e3-pawn. After} 27. Re1 Qe6 $17 {Black is ready for ...f6. But not 27...f6? 28.Nxg6+ Rxg6 29.Rxg6 Rxg6 30.Qxf5}) 27... Qe6 $5 {[%cal Gf5d4] Good enough, as Black has ...f6, ..Nxe3, and now ...Nxd4 as threats.} (27... Nxe3 $1 {was possible here. If} 28. Re1 Qa3 $1 29. Rxe3 $2 Qc1+ {.}) 28. Rc1 {Ignoring everything, but there's not really a good answer.} f6 29. Nxg6+ Rxg6 30. Rxc7 Ng3+ $1 {Not the only winning move, but the nicest.} 31. Rxg3 (31. Qxg3 fxg5) 31... Qxh3 32. Rxh3 Rg1# 0-1

