1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 Bc6 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nc6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bg5 Rb8 14. e3 {This flexible move was not in Gustafsson's Chess24 repertoire, but it developed into the main line.} c5 $5 {A great idea from Wesley So.} ({Black has also tried} 14... a5 {as well as other moves, and Black seems ok everywhere.}) 15. dxc5 {Taking a pawn while attacking Black's queen looks critical.} ({Instead} 15. d5 Nxd5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 Rb4 {intending ... Rfb8, must be fine for Black.}) 15... Qe8 $1 16. Rd4 {Going after the c-pawn.} ({It's probably safer to play} 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Ne4 {which we considered via 14.Bxf6. After} Be5 $1 18. f4 f5 $1 {it is White who has to be very accurate.}) 16... Nd7 $1 {It's good to keep the knight, as the light-squares around White's king are weak.} 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gd7e5] Black has good counterplay and his king is safer.} 18. c6 ({After} 18. Rxc4 $2 Ne5 19. Re4 Qxc5 $17 {Black is much better, as the e4-rook is very awkward.} 20. Qe2 f5 21. Rh4 Qc6 22. e4 {was Tsai-Ippolito, Greensboro 2019. Now} h6 {intending ...Kh7! and ...g5! would have been very strong.}) 18... Ne5 19. Qe4 Qc5 20. Nd5 {[%csl Re5] Trying to disrupt Black's coordination.} Nd3 21. Nxc7 Nxf2 $1 {Breaking White's position.} 22. Kxf2 ({Played quickly, but} 22. Nxa6 {was a better try.} Qg5 $1 23. Qf3 $1 {( 23.Kxf2 Rxb2+ 24.Ke1 Rxh2 25.Qf3 Rh1+! 26.Qxh1 Qxe3+ 27.Kf1 Qxd4 $17 )} Rxb2 24. c7 Nh3+ $1 {( 24...Nd3 25.Rf1 $13 )} 25. Kh1 h6 $3 26. Rxc4 {( 26.Rf1 Qa5-+ 27.Qxf7+ Rxf7 28.c8=Q+ Kh7 is actually a forced mate.)} Rf2 $1 27. Qc6 {( 27.Qb7 Qxe3 28.c8=Q Rxc8 29.Rxc8+ Kh7-+ )} Qxe3 28. Rc2 Rc8 {.}) 22... Rxb2+ 23. Kf1 Qh5 {[%cal Gh5e2]} 24. Qg4 Qxh2 {[%cal Gh2f2]} 25. Qf3 {White has warded off mate, but now threats come from the other direction.} c3 $1 {[%cal Gc3c2,Gb2b1]} 26. Rc1 e5 $1 {This disruptive move is winning.} 27. Rh4 $2 {After this it's relatively easy, as Black's moves are forced.} ({Getting behind the c-pawn was a better try, but still losing. Black has to find his way though as it's rather complicated} 27. Rc4 Rfb8 $1 {(But not 27...Qd2 28.Rd1! )} 28. Nd5 {( 28.Nxa6 Qd2 29.R4xc3 and now Black must find ( 29.Rd1 Rb1 wins now). 29...e4! )} Rf2+ $1 29. Qxf2 Qh1+ 30. Qg1 {( 30.Ke2 Rb2+ )} Qxd5 31. R4xc3 Rb2 {and White cannot defend himself.}) 27... Qd2 28. Rd1 Rd8 $1 {A cool move, but perhaps not so difficult as there's not much else!} 29. Nd5 {Xiong goes into desperation mode. There is a trick for Black to avoid.} (29. Rxd2 Rdxd2 {and there's no stopping ...Rb1. If} 30. Kg1 Rb1+ 31. Qf1 c2) 29... Rxd5 30. Rd4 $1 Rxd4 (30... exd4 $4 31. c7 {would turn the tables!}) 31. exd4 Qxd1+ $1 {After 32.Qxd1 c2 and ...Rb1 next and it's over.} 0-1

