1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3]} (11. Qd2 {is a more normal move order.}) 11... Qd6 {[%cal Rc1a3] Preventing Ba3.} 12. Qd2 Rab8 13. Rd1 Rb6 {Black activates his forces while preventing White's Ba3.} 14. e4 {This is very natural. e4-e5 has to be addressed.} (14. Qa5 $6 {is mistimed.} Nd5 15. e4 Qb4 $1 16. Bd2 {16.Qxb4? Nxb4 17.Bf4 Nd3 18.Bxc7 Rb2 $17 Iturrizaga Bonelli-Dominguez Perez, Internet 2018} c3 17. Qxb4 Rxb4 18. Be1 Nb6 19. Bxc3 Rxa4 $15) 14... Qb4 $1 {An important resource. Black can afford to sac the exchange.} 15. Qxb4 Rxb4 16. Ba3 Rxa4 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 $13 {Black has two pawns for the exchange and White's rooks do not have any files to work with. Black can bring everything to the queenside. Even though Black has tripled pawns, they still have potential, and the c4-pawn is dangerous.} 18. Rdc1 Bb5 {[%cal Rb1b8] Shutting down the b-file} 19. Rc3 Ke7 20. a3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gc6c5] The knight heads for the queenside, and supports a break with ...c5.} 21. Bf3 c5 22. Bd1 Ra5 23. dxc5 Nxc5 24. f3 Nd3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ge7d6,Gd6c5,Gc5d4] The computer calls this equal, but with no play for the rooks, Black's position is easier to play.} 25. Be2 Kd6 26. Bxd3 $6 {White understandably grows impatient. It was better to wait with this capture.} cxd3 27. Kf2 c5 28. Ke3 c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd3] These pawns don't look so silly anymore!} 29. Rb1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Gb1b5] White is hoping to bail out by returning the exchange and eating the pawns.} Ba6 {Keeping the bishop and guarding the b7-square.} 30. Rb8 $6 ({It was better to wait with a move like} 30. h4 {If} Rb5 31. Rb4 $1 {and White has not lost control.}) 30... Rb5 31. Rxb5 $2 ({This leads to a lost position. Necessary was} 31. Rd8+ Ke7 32. Ra8 Rb7 {Black is still better, but at least White has an active rook.}) 31... Bxb5 {White was hoping for a blockade.} 32. Rc1 {If White sits, Black will bring the bishop to b3 or ( c2 . Here is a sample line: 32.h4 Kc5 33.Rc1 a5 34.Rc3 Ba4 35.h5 e5 36.f4 f6 and White will end up in zugzwang. he will eventually have to move his king, allowing ...Kd4; or his rook, allowing ...c3.} Kc5 33. Rb1 {White's idea is Kd2-c3.} a6 $1 ({If} 33... c3 $2 34. Rb3 c2 {or 34...Kc4 35.Rb4+} 35. Kd2 {and Black cannot make progress.}) 34. Rb2 ({Now the bishop is protected, so} 34. Kd2 {can be met with} Kd4) 34... e5 35. Rb1 g5 36. Rb2 (36. Rc1 a5 {will lead to a similar zugzwang described on move 32.}) 36... c3 37. Rb3 Kc4 38. Rb4+ Kc5 39. Rb3 c2 40. Kd2 h5 41. a4 Bc4 42. Rb8 g4 $1 43. Z0 ({Black will come in with the king. For example} 43. fxg4 hxg4 {(with the idea ...Kd4)} 44. Rd8 {and now the quickest win is} f5 $1 {creating another passed pawn.} 45. exf5 e4) 0-1

