1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. c4 dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2 Rb8 12. Qa5 Qc8 13. a4 Rd8 14. Ba3 Rxd4 15. Rfb1 Rxb1+ 16. Rxb1 h6 $5 {Black takes care of any back rank issues.} 17. Bc5 {This move is always played, but it's probably not very good.} ({In the course we also look at} 17. Bxc6 $6) ({and} 17. Qc5 {which is untried, but relatively best.}) 17... Rd5 18. e4 $6 {Tempting, but bad.} ({There is also} 18. Bxd5) ({and the better move,} 18. Qb4) 18... Rd3 {[%cal Gc4c3,Gf6d7]} 19. h3 {A weird move, but it seems there is not much for Whote to do.} (19. Bxa7 c3 {and the c-pawn just marches. If} 20. Rc1 c2 $1 21. Rxc2 $2 Rd1+ {which shows one reason for h2-h3.}) 19... c3 $1 20. Kh2 (20. Bf1 {does not help.} Nxe4 $1 21. Bxd3 Bxd3) (20. Rc1 {may be best.} c2 $1 21. Rxc2 Rd1+ 22. Kh2 Bd3 {and Black picks up the e4-pawn.}) 20... Nd7 21. Bxa7 ({It's not easy to just play two pawns down. If} 21. Be3 c5 $1 22. Bxc5 Ne5 $1 {Black has a strong initiative, and still is ahead in material.}) 21... c2 22. Rc1 Qb7 {[%cal Gb7a7,Gb7b2]} 23. Be3 Rxe3 $5 (23... Qb2 {is good enough too.} 24. Qxa6 Rxe3 25. Rxc2 Qxc2 26. fxe3 Ne5 {and the queen and knight are quite potent. The prophylactic ...h6 certainly has been useful!}) 24. fxe3 Bd3 25. Qc3 ({If} 25. Qd2 Qb2 26. a5 c5 27. a6 c4 {just in time to protect the bishop.} 28. a7 Qxa2 {and Black's knight will enter the fray.}) 25... Qb1 26. Rg1 ({If} 26. Qd2 {Black has some choice, but} Qb2 {reaching the previous note, is good enough.}) 26... Ne5 (26... Be2 $5 27. Qd2 Bd1 {is also possible. White could resign.}) 27. Qxe5 Qxg1+ 28. Kxg1 c1=Q+ 29. Kh2 Qc2 {[%cal Gd3f1] Both sides have a passed pawn, but White has problems with his king, and that makes the difference.} 30. Qf4 Qxa2 31. e5 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4,Ga2a4,Gc4c3,Gc3c2,Gc2c1] And White had enough.} 0-1

